<HEADLINE>
3 BODIES FOUND IN NYC TOWNHOUSE THAT BLEW UP; GAS LEAK SUSPECTED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs lede graf, 4th graf and headline to reflect finding of third
body; subs 6th graf to delete repetition of ages of victims) (ART ADV: Photo NYT17 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three bodies were recovered Wednesday from the rubble
of a Brooklyn townhouse that exploded on Tuesday night, and fire
investigators said that they strongly suspected the blast was
caused by a gas leak.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the main possibility,'' said Chief Fire Marshal Louis
F. Garcia, citing the nature of the damage, the absence of other
obvious causes and the accounts of neighbors who said they smelled
gas before the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not really looking at anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before noon Wednesday, firefighters discovered the body
of Leonard Walit, 72, buried under tons of rubble in the basement
of his townhouse at 420 State St. in Boerum Hill. Eight hours
later, firefighters discovered the body of his friend and neighbor,
Khay Cochran, 73, and, about three hours after that, found the body
of Walit's wife, Harriet, 66, a retired social worker.
</P>
<P>
   For friends and relatives and neighbors, it was a devastating
day _ a day in which hope faded to nothing and a stunned
neighborhood was left to confront the mystery of fate.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, Mrs. Walit had called Cochran complaining of
the smell of gas, neighbors said. Cochran, a close friend of the
Walits, went next door to help investigate. Minutes later, an
explosion obliterated the Walits' place and all but obliterated the
adjoining townhouse that Cochran shared at 418 State St. with his
longtime companion, Julian Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Yet miraculously, Jackson and another roommate, Francis Aguire,
escaped with barely a scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Fire Commissioner Thomas Von Essen, his white dress shirt coated
in black dust from a night of supervising several hundred
firefighters, said the explosion could have been touched off by
something as simple as someone turning on a light, or lighting a
match. The explosion _ so intense that it snuffed out all flames in
an instant _ appeared to have originated from the Walits' basement,
knocking out supported walls and allowing the upper floors to
collapse in a heap.
</P>
<P>
   ``The building just pancaked,'' said Philip J. Burns, a deputy
fire chief.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Investigators said it was far from clear whether the leak came
from a gas service line or from an appliance. The townhouse, they
said, had a gas stove, a gas boiler and a gas water heater, and a
spokesman for Keyspan Energy, the utility company, said that the
company's investigators had not identified any leaks coming from
its supply lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found zero evidence of natural gas leaking in the area,''
said Robert J. Mahoney, manager of media relations for Keyspan. He
cautioned, however, that because of the damage the company had not
been able to test the service lines leading directly into 420 and
418 State St.
</P>
<P>
   And although neighbors reported smelling gas before the
explosion, Mahoney said that the company's records of gas
complaints did not show any telephone calls from the neighborhood
on Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Yet more than a month ago, on June 5, a resident at 422 State
St. complained to Keyspan about a gas smell. The odor, the resident
reported, was strongest near a wall that adjoined 420 State St.
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney said that Keyspan workers promptly investigated the
complaint, performed extensive testing inside and outside 422 State
St., but failed to detect any leakage of gas. Given those results,
he said, there was no need to test 420 State St. or other
residences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went by the book,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunni Levinson, the person who made the complaint, said that
the Keyspan worker who responded told her that he, too, smelled
gas. ``It makes you wonder,'' she said. ``We smelled it, they
smelled it. When the gas man says he smells it, it has to come from
somewhere, and you have to find it.'' She added, however, that in
the weeks since she has not smelled gas.
</P>
</TEXT>
