<HEADLINE>
PAST, PRESENT OF EVOLUTION DEBATE COME TOGETHER IN KANSAS
PERFORMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE BEEM  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAWRENCE, Kan. _ H.L. Mencken must have been a prophet.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-five years ago this month, the caustic Baltimore Sun
columnist predicted that the dispute between creationists and
evolutionists, between traditionalists and modernists, wouldn't end
with the two-week trial of a Tennessee science teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Mencken was proved right Wednesday night, as about 1,300 people
filled the University of Kansas' Lied Center for a dramatic
presentation based on transcripts from the 1925 Scopes ``Monkey
Trial'' and a debate after the performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``People continue to be so divided on this issue,'' panelist
Edward Larson, author of a book on the Scopes trial, told the
audience. ``It's an important issue because of how we view
ourselves and our morality.''
</P>
<P>
   The Scopes re-enactment, presented by the People for the
American Way Foundation came 11 months after the Kansas Board of
Education voted to de-emphasize evolution in new science standards.
The standards are guidelines for what students will learn and be
tested on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tennessee was the battleground 75 years ago,'' said Ralph
Neas, foundation president. ``Kansas is today's ground zero in the
battle over evolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Actor Ed Asner, a native of Kansas City, Kan., portrayed William
Jennings Bryan, the well-known orator who prosecuted science
teacher John Scopes. James Cromwell, who starred in the movie
``Babe,'' played defense attorney Clarence Darrow. Also part of the
cast were actress Shirley Knight, a native of Mitchell, Kan., and
Harold Gould.
</P>
<P>
   The presentation coincided with a weeklong observance in Kansas
of the trial sponsored by the Mainstream Coalition, a political
watchdog group; Kansas Citizens for Science, formed after the state
board's vote; and several other groups.
</P>
<P>
   The August 1999 vote by the state board raised many of the same
issues as the Scopes trial.
</P>
<P>
   In 1925, Bryan argued that parents, not teachers, should decide
whether their children should learn scientific theories or anything
else that goes against the values they teach at home. The six board
members who voted for the standards made similar points, saying the
new standards allow local districts to decide what to teach.
</P>
<P>
   And Darrow, like the scientists and pro-evolution group that
arose after the state board's vote, charged that dismissing
evolution is just the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the next session you may ban books and newspapers...until
with flying banners and beating drums, we are marching backward to
the 16th century when bigots lighted torches to burn men who dared
to bring any intelligence and enlightenment and culture to the
human mind,'' intoned Cromwell during his performance as Darrow.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd Wednesday night also served as the courtroom audience,
responding with appropriate laughter, applause and hisses to
placards displayed near the stage.
</P>
<P>
   After the hour drama, a panel took the stage to discuss the
difference between theories of creationism and intelligent design,
which hold that a designer created the universe and everything in
it, and evolution, the theory that living things share common
ancestors but have evolved over time.
</P>
<P>
   Moderated by KU law professor Michael Davis, the panel included
Larson; Tom Willis of Cleveland, Mo., president of the Creation
Science Association for Mid-America; Eugenie Scott, director of the
National Center for Science Education in Berkeley, Calif.; John
Calvert of Lake Quivira, managing director of the Intelligent
Design Network; and Leonard Krishtalka, a KU evolutionary biologist
and curator of the school's Natural History Museum.
</P>
<P>
   During the 40-minute debate, Davis asked Willis, Scott, Calvert
and Krishtalka to describe why the debate over evolution still
rages. Scott and Krishtalka said it's because some people don't
understand exactly what evolution is and are uncomfortable with
what they do know about it.
</P>
<P>
   Willis and Calvert said their scientific evidence that a
designer created life isn't allowed into reputable scientific
circles.
</P>
<P>
   Krishtalka answered by saying that he believed creationism is
religion, and ``intelligent design is creationism in a cheap
suit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
