<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOOKAHEAD-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
NL shakedown begins before games resume
<TEXT>
<P>
   By CARLTON THOMPSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   The National League playoff picture took on a bit of a different
look Wednesday when the Cincinnati Reds all but conceded their
hopes of contention while the Atlanta Braves strengthened
themselves for the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati, just eight games behind first-place St. Louis in the
NL Central Division, traded away its top starting pitcher. Atlanta,
meanwhile, acquired a veteran starter with hopes of winning its
eighth straight NL East crown.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds traded lefthander Denny Neagle to the Yankees the day
after the All-Star Game, basically signaling the end of
Cincinnati's run for the division title this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you play for the Reds, that's pretty tough to swallow,''
Astros first baseman Jeff Bagwell said of Wednesday's deal. ``Don't
get me wrong. The Reds could still win it, because there's a long
way to go, and a lot can happen. But that's not exactly what you
like to see when you're coming back from the All-Star break. I'm
sure that deal doesn't make the Cardinals unhappy.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Braves, starting pitching has been the main reason
they have been so consistent over the past 10 years. And while
their 4.33 earned run average is good for second in the NL, it's
still significantly higher than what they're accustomed to.
</P>
<P>
   Although Andy Ashby, whom they acquired from the Phillies on
Wednesday, has struggled most of the season, he's certainly an
upgrade over Terry Mulholland and John Burkett _ the bottom two
starters in the Braves' rotation behind Greg Maddux, Tom Glavine
and Kevin Millwood.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves need Ashby to pitch like he did for the Padres in
1998 and '99 (when he was a combined 31-19) if they are going to
hold off the Mets in the NL East. The Ashby the Phillies saw this
season didn't look much like the one who was a picture of
consistency for San Diego. Ashby has a 5.68 ERA this season,
although he has allowed just three runs in his last 15 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ashby's ability and experience are very appealing to us, and
we believe he's shown signs of returning to his old form,'' Braves
general manager John Schuerholz said.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the Cardinals appear to have the best chance to
unseat the Braves as NL champs. While most contending teams are
looking for starting pitching, the Cardinals' rotation is so deep
that righthanders Matt Morris and Alan Benes, once highly touted,
have been relegated to relief work. Of course, that just makes the
Cardinals' bullpen that much better.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis arguably has the most dangerous lineup in the league
and is very sound defensively. The Cardinals should cruise to the
NL Central title, barring a rash of injuries to key players.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get too far behind this (Cardinals) club,'' Reds
first-base coach Dave Collins said. ``It isn't like you're chasing
chopped liver.''
</P>
<P>
   The best race figures to be in the NL West, where things are
still very much up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some team is going to win 20 of 25. You can count on it,'' San
Francisco manager Dusty Baker said. ``It might as well be us.''
</P>
<P>
   The defending champion Arizona Diamondbacks are a great team
every fifth day _ in other words, when Randy Johnson pitches _ but
just so-so the rest of the time. Take away Johnson's 14-2 record,
and the Diamondbacks are just two games over .500.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people are on the Colorado Rockies' bandwagon, and
rightfully so. They've made quite a turnaround under new manager
Buddy Bell, who has the club making a serious run at the playoffs
for the first time since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as the Rockies have improved, it's unlikely they'll
continue to stay in the race if they don't play better on the road.
Good teams typically play well away from home, and the Rockies
clearly didn't fall into that category during the first half. They
are 28-9 at Coors Field but just 17-31 on the road.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants finished the second half strong, and Baker always
seems to find a way to have them in the mix at the end of the
season. And don't discount the Los Angeles Dodgers, who on paper
look like the best team in the division.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of adversity hanging over us in the first half,''
Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``We've just got to put
together well-pitched games. That's going to be the key for us in
the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Dodgers and every other team that fashions itself as a
contender in the NL, it all begins today.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
