<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SORRY, THIS COLUMN IS OVERBOOKED
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Thirteen mini columns, each one soon to be a
major motion picture.
</P>
<P>
   -- The tourist rents a car, takes his family out for a drive
around San Francisco. Another car cuts him off, imagine that.
</P>
<P>
   Our tourist slams on his brakes, and out from under his seat
slides a handgun.
</P>
<P>
   If this is a new rental-car feature, it's a great idea on many
levels. One, as sloppy as airport security is these days, it's
still risky for the traveler to pack his or her own heat.
</P>
<P>
   -- Memo to Peter Harris, former toy-industry honcho hired as the
new boss of the 49ers: Some assembly may be required.
</P>
<P>
   Harris is ``simply fun to be around,'' says a 49er spokesman. So
is Robin Williams.
</P>
<P>
   -- Cheesy tourist trap or Bay eco-education center at Pier 45?
</P>
<P>
   Right now, I'd like to support ``A.'' San Francisco could use a
one-stop historical/cultural museum where tourists  &UR; and  &LR; locals
could absorb the big picture in one morning or afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But my faith in the ability of those Cleveland people to pull it
off without mind-boggling schlock: Zero.
</P>
<P>
   So it looks like I'm back to supporting Gavin Newsom's Plan B.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Jack Gallagher points out that Plan A would drive out
what there is now at Fisherman's Wharf's Pier 45: ``Fishermen!
Fish! Wharf!''
</P>
<P>
   -- Another way the city bites the hand that buys the Alcatraz
T-shirts and keeps the economy booming:
</P>
<P>
   Overbooking by the big hotels. Sometimes, it works. This week,
with a huge semiconductor convention in town, one hotel overbooked
by 100 rooms, another by 60, and, oops, all the usual no-shows
showed.
</P>
<P>
   One hotel blamed a computer snafu. So the victims were hoisted
by their own petard.
</P>
<P>
   Tempers flared, hotels scrambled to book guests in other full-up
hotels, and folks with legit reservations were exiled to San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we should open up the cell blocks at Alcatraz for victims
of overbook. A homeless shelter for screwed tourists.
</P>
<P>
   -- Chico has never recovered from the time Herb Caen reported
that Velveeta could be found in the gourmet section of the local
Safeway.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent issue of the Chico News &AMP; Review (spotted by Maxine
LeClerc), in a story on the great chefs of Chico, chef Robert
Allison of Christian Michaels' Ristorante says, ``There's a reason
why lamb and goat cheese go together, and it's not because they're
from the same animal.''
</P>
<P>
   -- What's San Francisco coming to when a local poet can't have a
smoke on the sidewalk without getting thrown in the can?
</P>
<P>
   Ron Sauer, a leading S.F. poet and translator, was busted for
smoking pot outside Specs bar on Saroyan Alley in North Beach last
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Sauer spent the night in jail (at least the jail wasn't
overbooked), went to court, charges were dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Specs, where Jack Kerouac drank and Janis Joplin got 86'd, is
still a hotbed of culture, home of poets and other endangered
species.
</P>
<P>
   What other bar has a Sunday figure-drawing session, with live
nude models? It's legit. No doodlers or finger-painters, please.
</P>
<P>
   -- The man who dropped rebar on cars driven by hookers'
customers _ the Bootybomber? _ got off easy, sure.
</P>
<P>
   But would it be fair for this clown to do hard time while so
many others involved in life-threatening criminal activity get the
old wink from the city?
</P>
<P>
   -- The Old Homeboy wonders if the Associated Press is pulling
the wool over our eyes. The story: A former Duke basketball player
says that while in high school he was given cash from a coach to
play summer-league ball.
</P>
<P>
   The coach who made the payoffs: Myron Piggie.
</P>
<P>
   And the story quoted a Duke executive vice president named
Tallman Trash III.
</P>
<P>
   Tallman trash? Homeboy says that's what you must listen to after
the 7-footer swats away your driving layup.
</P>
<P>
   -- Memo to 49ers' new boss: Forget the $700 million stadium. For
a couple thou you can build a new stadium from Leggo blocks.
</P>
<P>
   -- Today at the Gold Coast they dedicate the city's first
``Mo,'' a rest room named in honor of Florida attorney Morris
Engelberg, defender of the sacred honor of Joe DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   I hope it's a very large rest room, so Mo don't sue.
</P>
<P>
   -- We got your onomatopoeia right here, pal:
</P>
<P>
   On Stockton in Chinatown, Cuffs Corbett saw the Ching Ching Coin
Shop.
</P>
<P>
   -- Anonymous caller suggests, ``When you go on vacation, could
you please have the paper run the best-of-your-best columns, like
Ann Landers does when she's on vacation?''
</P>
<P>
   Bless your heart, sir, that's a great idea. But what will I do
for Tuesday?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
