<HEADER>
A0761 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GLF-GOLFCOL-COLUMN-LA     07-13 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFCOL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS ONE'S FOR MARTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Marty Tregnan finally got his day.
</P>
<P>
   And with it perhaps his fondest wish.
</P>
<P>
   Tregnan, the longtime public-golf advocate who campaigned until
his death in 1997 to keep the game accessible and affordable to all
segments of society, on Monday had his name and spirit linked to
unprecedented aid for golf's future.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion was the opening of the Tregnan Golf Academy at
Coolidge, the country's first municipal golf-training center
devoted to youth.
</P>
<P>
   Established for junior golfers, particularly from low-income
families, it is located in his beloved Griffith Park on the site of
the long-abandoned Coolidge par-3 course. The refurbished hilltop
facility sits a few long tee shots down Crystal Springs Drive from
the Wilson and Harding courses, where Tregnan served officially as
men's club president and unofficially but unmistakably as champion
of golf for the working class.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes he rubbed people the wrong way in his passion,
manifested often during his 40 years as an active and vocal member
of the Municipal Golf Association. But whether Tregnan was pushing
for greater opportunities for juniors, campaigning in City Council
to keep rates reasonable, or helping promote the creation of a golf
advisory board, no one who dealt with him could doubt his
dedication to keep public golf available to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan alluded to that at Monday's
dedication of the Tregnan academy, a state-of-the-art training
facility that includes three practice holes, a driving range,
chipping and putting greens, practice bunkers and a
1500-square-foot learning center with classroom space.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people here have helped make this happen,'' Riordan
told a turnout of nearly 300 at the 10-acre facility. ``But one in
particular is looking down on us in his curmudgeonly way, looking
down laughing. Marty? Have we done a good job? I think we have.''
</P>
<P>
   They have done that _ in three short years _ thanks to the
combined efforts of many, led by American Golf, the U.S. Golf
Association, the Griffith J. Griffith trust, the L.A. Junior
Chamber of Commerce Urban Youth Golf Program and the L.A.
Department of Recreation and Parks.
</P>
<P>
   American Golf made the biggest contribution, conducting a
$900,000 renovation of a Coolidge course that had been shut down
since 1982. The USGA has awarded $475,000 in two grants to the city
_ the most that organization has contributed to any project _ and
the Griffith trust has given $240,000.
</P>
<P>
   Those and other contributions _ acknowledged on bricks lining
the Tregnan entrance _ helped pave the way for the facility, which
will be staffed and maintained by Recreation and Parks. The Urban
Youth Golf Program will provide equipment and instruction, which
begins Saturday when the first Tregnan students start classes
designed to teach as much about sportsmanship and integrity as club
selection and course management.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is to serve 500 a year,'' said academy manager Randy
Kelly, who has nearly 350 registered for the first of two six-month
sessions. It can cost students as little as $25 a year for a
15-week instruction program that includes round-trip transportation
from neighborhood recreation centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has never really been tried to the extent that we're
doing it,'' Kelly said. ``We go out in vans and get the kids. We
make it accessible.''
</P>
<P>
   The five-step program, designed to prepare young golfers for the
next stage of junior opportunities on city and county courses,
emphasizes etiquette, dress code and safety along with care of the
course, the proper swing and handling of the club.
</P>
<P>
   All at a site Tregnan often said would be ideal for the purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marty would be thrilled,'' said Clare Darden, Tregnan's
sweetheart for 15 years before his sudden death at age 78 of heart
failure. ``He was always thinking the old Coolidge would be
perfect. Here it was, just lying there, not doing anyone any good.
This way, these kids are going to be ready to play when they're 14
on the big courses. So many kids aren't _ they really don't have
the chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Tregnan might be thrilled by more than just the new learning
center bearing his name. Boosted by the phenomenal popularity of
Tiger Woods, junior golf is booming throughout the inner city and
seemingly benefiting more each year from individuals and agencies
dedicated to that growth.
</P>
<P>
   Maggie Hathaway par-3, a county course in South Central Los
Angeles, is the introduction site in the Western States Golf
Association's 18-year-old program that advances juniors to
more-difficult county courses as skills improve. This year, the
Hathaway course is scheduled to become part of the national First
Tee program, which combines considerable pooled resources _
including those of the USGA, PGA, LPGA and World Golf Organization
_ to develop youth-training centers throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've sort of adopted the philosophy of Franklin Delano
Roosevelt that parks are very important to our community,'' said
Susan Henderson, director of the WSGA's Junior Golf Academy at
Hathaway.
</P>
<P>
   More than 400 children, aged 7-17, are now enrolled in the WSGA
program, which provides students with instruction and equipment for
$20 a year and which, like others, is feeling the impact of Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our program has had a good, healthy interest for a long
time,'' Henderson said, ``but certainly, after Tiger, interest has
doubled.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the same at the LPGA-founded Urban Youth Golf Program,
which provides equipment and instruction in nine-week sessions that
cost $20 a year for those who can get into the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a waiting list of about 300 now,'' said director John
Morrison, who has 600 in the program and ``we anticipate an
additional 500 in the next couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles city and county courses _ the next learning step for
children taught the game in the WSGA, Urban Youth and Tregnan
programs _ have reduced rates for juniors by half in recent years.
This year, July has been designated Junior Golfer Appreciation
Month at the 17 county courses, enabling juniors to play for $1 in
twilight time when accompanied by an adult or senior. County golf
operations administrator Steve Durand estimates 50 to 100 children
participate in junior programs at each county course _ 250 at
Maggie Hathaway.
</P>
<P>
   At city courses, director of golf operations Pete Frey says
junior golf programs, offering instruction and team play,
consistently average 2,500 youngsters a year with growth limited
only by lack of space.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't have too many kids,'' she said, ``because it would be
too crowded.''
</P>
<P>
   Tregnan might have had a real dilemma with that _ the concept of
too many juniors for public courses. But he would have loved
thinking up a solution _ much as he did in planting the seed for
the metamorphosis of Coolidge. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
