<HEADER>
A0762 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-SMOKE-DAVIS-SFCHRON &LR;      07-13 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOKE-DAVIS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN HEART ASSOCIATION AD BLASTS DAVIS OVER TOBACCO  SETTLEMENT
MONEY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ The American Heart Association blasted Gov. Gray
Davis in a full-page advertisement Wednesday, saying the governor
has hijacked the state's tobacco settlement money and put
Californians at risk.
</P>
<P>
   The association's full-page ad in the New York Times came as
Davis' office trumpeted new numbers showing that teen smoking in
California dropped from 10.7 percent in 1998 to 6.9 percent in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   While Davis' office attributed the drop to the state's tobacco
education campaign, the governor's critics say Davis is allowing
the program to become woefully underfunded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state gets $500 million a year from the tobacco
settlement, and no new dollars whatsoever are being put into the
state's tobacco prevention campaign,'' said Marc Burgat, spokesman
for the American Heart Association. ``The tobacco companies are in
the midst of a record year of spending on media and advertising,
while the state's funds remain static or are decreasing.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis' spokesman said the proof of the project is in the
results.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advocacy groups are doing their job in wanting more, but
California has done more than other states,'' spokesman Steve
Maviglio said. ``They are targeting California so other states will
follow. The bottom line is the results are there.''
</P>
<P>
   But one anti-tobacco advocate said the numbers will not stay
down if the Davis administration continues to ignore the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Davis administration has done absolutely nothing
meaningful on tobacco,'' said Stan Glantz, professor of medicine at
the University of California at San Francisco. ``There may be fewer
people smoking, but there are more than there should have been.''
</P>
<P>
   Glantz said the drop in smoking rates can be attributed to
Proposition 10, a 50-cent-per-pack tax on cigarettes approved by
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the height of arrogance for him to take credit,'' Glantz
said. ``It is down no thanks to anything the Davis administration
has done. There is no leadership from the administration on this
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Advertisements that Davis released with much fanfare soon after
he took office were produced under former Gov. Pete Wilson or by
other states.
</P>
<P>
   Davis did increase the state's advertising budget by $25 million
this year, but Burgat said that is simply not enough.
</P>
<P>
   Burgat cited a study by the federal Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention that said California should be spending $105 million
on anti-tobacco campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like a no-brainer,'' he said, adding that studies
show for every $1 spent on campaigns, the state saves $8 in future
health costs.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also vetoed a bill last year that would have directed the
state's share of the settlement to tobacco-related health programs,
saying there already is enough money in these programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the better policy to maintain flexibility in the use of
the tobacco settlement funds for other purposes as well. In the
event of unforeseen fiscal emergencies, it is critical for the
administration to have discretionary control of the uses of these
monies,'' Davis said in his veto message.
</P>
<P>
   The state has a $12 billion surplus this year.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement that states made with the tobacco industry,
California receives about $1 billion a year, with half going to
counties.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco has pledged to spend $1 million a year from its
share of the settlement money on tobacco control.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has put all of the state's tobacco money into health care,
increasing the number of children enrolled in the state's Healthy
Families program and supporting other initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' office also argues that there are two tobacco-related
funds that have been created by initiatives _ Propositions 99 and
10 _ that provide more than $400 million and almost $700 million,
respectively, for health and education.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1988's Proposition 99 added a tax to cigarettes to pay for
an anti-smoking campaign, the state has spent $1 billion, Davis
said in a statement announcing the smoking numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The California Department of Health study also showed that adult
smoking dropped to 18 percent from 18.4 percent, significantly
lower than the national average of 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The study shows smoking dropping across gender and ethnic lines
among youths age 12 to 17. Smoking among 16- and 17-year-olds fell
from 20 percent to 13.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Burgat said the numbers nationwide are going up the most
among 18- to 24-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   The state's survey also shows the numbers increasing in this age
group, although the governor's office declined to release those
numbers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
