<SLUG> BC-GALLERIA-THEZONE-RESEND-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG SHOPPERS GET OWN ZONE AT TRENDY GALLERIA
</HEADLINE>
 
(Original was garbled; this is first resend) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAM PARK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENDALE, Calif. _ Some new retailers at the trendy Glendale
Galleria are hoping to lure cash-flush Generation Y shoppers into
The Zone.
</P>
<P>
   It's a case of the kids speaking and the mall opening its
checkbook.
</P>
<P>
   The Zone concept was created with input from a focus group of
146 Southern California teens.
</P>
<P>
   They helped persuade the mall owners to spend $2.5 million
creating what officials say is the nation's first entertainment,
dining and shopping venue designed specifically for people 6 to 21.
</P>
<P>
   It will open Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The area will include a lounge with a message board,
out-of-the-ordinary vending machines and overhead television
screens that will show music videos, extreme sports footage and
messages from mall businesses, said Annette Bethers, senior
marketing director for the Galleria.
</P>
<P>
   Later, teens will be invited to bring videos of themselves and
their friends playing music, demonstrating other talents or
participating in extreme sports, she said.
</P>
<P>
   KIIS-FM will do frequent live broadcasts from the site, starting
with the grand opening set for 8 to 10 p.m. Friday, Bethers said.
</P>
<P>
   The Galleria's Gen Y shoppers, born between 1979 and 1994, spend
between $2,700 and $3,000 each per year, Bethers said.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide this age group numbers 60 million with purchasing
power of $90 billion to $150 billion annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came up with the concept more than a year ago,'' Bethers
said. ``We realized, upon doing some research on Generation Y's
numbers and buying power, that we had an opportunity to better
serve that customer in our mall and to begin building a loyalty
toward the center.''
</P>
<P>
   Galleria retailers that targeted Generation Y - such as Limited
Too, Hot Topic, Planet X and Quake - have been joined by more, mall
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers new to the mall are:
</P>
<P>
   No Fear - clothing for extreme sports.
</P>
<P>
   Van's - clothing, shoes, skateboards and accessories.
</P>
<P>
   Juxtapose - junior apparel plus a juice bar and music
headphones.
</P>
<P>
   Boarders - skateboards, snowboards, surfboards, apparel and
accessories.
</P>
<P>
   Premium - young junior apparel.
</P>
<P>
   Catwalk - junior apparel and shoes.
</P>
<P>
   The Glendale Galleria has a history of launching new retail
concepts, and that reputation attracts retailers and makes the mall
prominent in the diverse Los Angeles marketplace, Bethers said,.
</P>
<P>
   The first Disney, Synchrony watch and ESPN sports memorabilia
stores were launched at the Galleria, Bethers said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
