<HEADER>
A0764 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLA     07-13 1570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS FAIL AT LITTLE THINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Dodgers have power and pop, but
they don't manufacture runs and win the close games that
championship teams do. Their bullpen is solid, their ERA is fourth
in the league, but the starting pitching was a disappointment and
they've resorted to closing games by committee because Jeff Shaw
struggled.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers withstood injuries to Kevin Brown, Todd Hundley,
Kevin Elster and Adrian Beltre, a demanding schedule in the first
two months of the season and a fight at Wrigley Field in mid-May
that remains unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   But in order to be a playoff team, the Dodgers must do more than
hit the long ball at pivotal times. They must begin executing in
the finer points of the game if they're to make up the six-game
deficit they face in the National League West.
</P>
<P>
   And clearly, nobody is happy with the Dodgers standing in fourth
place at 44-42. If the Dodgers don't make a run at the playoffs,
discussions of who's on the hot seat will surely come.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least as far as contending, I don't think anybody would
disagree with the fact that we have the talent, but we have to get
it done,'' Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said. ``We worked
with (manager) Davey (Johnson) and brought in players we thought
would help us be a postseason team. There has been some
(adversity), but all that should be behind us in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players are talking about it. You have seven All-Stars and
a balanced lineup and we have tremendous make-up and the chemistry
on the team is outstanding. We have to do the little things.
Everybody has to turn it up a notch and it starts with me and Davey
and the coaching staff.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are roundly criticized by scouts for not being
fundamentally sound, either offensively or defensively.
</P>
<P>
   Scouts who follow the Dodgers on a semi-regular basis
continually say the players don't sacrifice for the betterment of
the team by hitting behind runners, laying down sacrifice bunts or
hitting cutoff men.
</P>
<P>
   What's more is the Dodgers are 6-17 in games in which they don't
hit a homer, and they lead the league by grounding into 80 double
plays. That's manifested in their 12-13 mark in one-run games and
7-9 record in two-run games.
</P>
<P>
   It's why Bob Daly, Dodgers managing general partner and CEO,
went to San Diego last week to talk to Johnson and tell him the
club needs to play with more enthusiasm and fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to have a philosophy and approach of, `How are we
going to score tonight if we don't hit the long ball?' '' Malone
said. ``We need to hit behind runners, get bunts down.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Dodgers survived some possible pitfalls in the
first half and are five games better off than they were a year ago,
a $90 million payroll is expected to yield more than a .512 winning
percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Blame can go to many areas, but the starting pitching, as
always, deserves a fair share. Right-hander Kevin Brown has been
even better this season, going 8-2 with a 2.38 ERA, but he's been
left alone for the last month by the rest of the starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Chan Ho Park is 9-6, but he hasn't won since June
18 and the organizational concerns of him getting unnerved in
crucial situations have returned. He was well on his way to an
All-Star bid with a five-game winning streak, but he's faltered
lately.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Darren Dreifort, called by Malone ``the key to the
second half,'' has regressed. He was 3-1 after a shutout of St.
Louis on May 12, but his only win since then came June 7. Dreifort
is 1-6 with a 7.03 ERA in his last 10 starts.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, an easy argument to make is that lefty Carlos Perez was
the Dodgers' third-best starter in the first half and went 4-4. And
for all the promise and potential of rookie right-hander Eric
Gagne, he's 1-5 with six no-decisions and opponents have scored
first in nine of his 12 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Because Dreifort, Gagne and Perez are a combined 9-16, the
Dodgers are trying to add a veteran starting pitcher before the
July 31 trading deadline. They were involved in talks about
Cincinnati's Denny Neagle and Philadelphia's Andy Ashby before both
were traded, and in both cases they were told they didn't have
enough in the prospect market to trade for either player.
Therefore, Neagle went to the Yankees and the Phillies traded Ashby
to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``The solutions aren't always external,'' Malone said.
``Everybody can say you want to win, but can you dig deep down and
make the sacrifices to win? It's how bad do we want to win, because
we have the talent. That's what people in the industry are telling
us.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dodgers position-by-position grades for the first half of the
season &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FIRST BASE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros is cleaning up in the fifth spot in the batting
order en route to career highs in home runs and RBI. His 25 homers
and 70 RBI are second on the club as teams pitch around Gary
Sheffield and Shawn Green to get to him. Defensively, his range is
limited, and that's a big part of the position as well. Grade: B &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SECOND BASE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark Grudzielanek's transition from shortstop to second has gone
smoothly, although a few ill-timed errors have allowed winning runs
to score. He hasn't been given many days off, mostly because of
Devon White's injury and F.P. Santangelo's mediocre offensive play.
Grade: B &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SHORTSTOP &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Elster started out with a bang with three homers at Pac
Bell Park, but the position hasn't produced offensively. Elster has
10 homers (one as a third baseman) and 21 RBI, and Cora is hitting
.254 with a homer and six RBI in 130 at-bats. Cora has brought
improved defense the last month. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THIRD BASE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the offseason distractions are showing now. Sure, Adrian
Beltre is 21 and in his second full season, but he's batting .251
with eight homers and 38 RBI. Worse, he's made 13 errors, many of
which were errant throws. When he missed three weeks with a
hamstring injury, Kevin Elster and Dave Hansen weren't upgrades. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CATCHER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The trio of Todd Hundley, Chad Kreuter and Paul LoDuca have 24
homers and 63 RBI, led by Hundley's resurgence. He's hitting .316
with 17 homers and 43 RBI heading into free agency. But some of the
disappointment of the starting pitchers can be attributed to the
catchers' play behind the plate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LEFT FIELD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield, All-Star. He's thrived with Green batting behind him,
has played through painful ankle injuries and is one of the leaders
in the clubhouse. Oh, and he's missed just two games and leads the
Dodgers in batting (.334), homers (27), RBI (71), walks (58) and
on-base percentage (.440) and is tied for the team lead with 64
runs score. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CENTER FIELD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   White's partially torn rotator cuff has thrown the Dodgers a
curve. The team's leadoff hitter and starting center fielder on
opening day went down with an injury May 2. Since then, Todd
Hollandsworth and Santangelo have platooned. Hollandsworth is
hitting .246 with a .323 on-base percentage and Santangelo is
batting .183 with a .310 on-base percentage. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RIGHT FIELD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Green has started all but one game but has slumped terribly in
the last month. His average has dropped to .294, he is fourth on
the team with 13 homers and has 59 RBI. Green, a Gold Glove winner
last season, has four errors, three more than a year ago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STARTING PITCHING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Brown missed three weeks but went 8-2 with a 2.38 ERA.
Chan Ho Park had nine wins by the middle of June, but he last won
June 18. That also happens to be the last time a starter other than
Brown won a game for the Dodgers. Carlos Perez last won May 20,
Darren Dreifort won June 7 and Eric Gagne has one win. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RELIEF PITCHING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Closer Jeff Shaw twice lost his closer's role, went on the
disabled list for the first time in his career and is 2-4 with an
8.00 ERA. He has 12 saves but has blown seven saves. But Mike
Fetters and Matt Herges have been Godsends, and after a rough
start, Onan Masaoka has pitched well as the only lefty. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BENCH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dave Hansen is the best pinch-hitter in baseball _ he has four
homers and nine RBI _ but he needs help. The big disappointment has
been Santangelo, a good clubhouse guy who's struggled to get any
rhythm. The bench was weakened when Geronimo Berroa, the
right-handed power source, broke his left foot. It forced the
Dodgers to deal utility infielder Jose Vizcaino. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MANAGER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Manager Davey Johnson has had to deal with suspensions, injuries
and the collapse of closer Jeff Shaw, and the Dodgers did fine for
the first 2 months. But the Dodgers lost 11 of 17 to end the first
half of the season at 44-42. Johnson has to figure out a way to get
Dreifort and Gagne and Green back on track. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FRONT OFFICE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New head man Bob Daly is discovering how tough talent evaluation
can be. He was instrumental in bringing Orel Hershiser back to the
Dodgers and now Hershiser is one of the top-paid consultants in the
game. The Gregg Olson signing is a nonfactor. F.P. Santangelo
hasn't performed well. However, clubhouse camaraderie is high and
the majority of the pieces are in place to compete for the division
title. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 0039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
