<HEADLINE>
HUNDLEY'S THUMB FEARED BROKEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Dodgers went nearly four weeks
without Todd Hundley in the lineup last month and the offense
suffered _ and they could be looking at more time with the
switch-hitting catcher out of their lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley is scheduled to undergo X-rays on his right thumb upon
his return to Los Angeles today. The Dodgers fear he has a hairline
fracture at the tip of his right thumb, and it's likely he won't be
ready to catch until after the three-game series with the Angels.
He's hitting .316 with 17 homers and 43 RBI, and has provided
protection and depth to the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to (physical therapist) Pat (Screnar), he's moving
it pretty good and the swelling has gone down,'' Dodgers manager
Davey Johnson said of Hundley's thumb. ``As far as throwing, we'll
have to see. The doctors said maybe by the weekend (Hundley could
play).''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley was injured Friday when he took a foul ball off the
thumb in Seattle. He was the designated hitter Saturday but was
scratched Sunday. He spent the All-Star break away from Los Angeles
because of a sick family member.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Hundley's ailing thumb and the absence of Chad
Kreuter, the Dodgers recalled Paul LoDuca from Triple-A
Albuquerque. LoDuca hit .346 with two homers and five RBI in nine
games last month and takes the place of Mike Metcalfe, sent back to
the minors Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   __ Devo's progression: For the first time since suffering a
partially torn left rotator cuff diving for a ball May 2, center
fielder Devon White faced live pitching. White batted from both
sides of the plate at the beginning of Wednesday's workout, did
some running in the outfield and shagged balls.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers officials believe White will be ready to go on a rehab
assignment in a week, and after he spends 10 days to two weeks
playing in the minor leagues, the club hopes White will be ready to
return.
</P>
<P>
   __ Shaw's back: The Dodgers plan to activate reliever Jeff Shaw
for tonight's game against the Angels. He's missed the past two
weeks with tendinitis in his right elbow, landing on the disabled
list for the first time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   However, Johnson doesn't plan on handing the closer's role back
to Shaw, who is 2-4 with an 8.00 ERA and has converted just 12 of
19 save chances. Instead, Johnson will look at matchups when it
comes to using Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably do like I did before,'' Johnson said. ``He came
back and threw pretty good, so we'll go from there.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Short hops: Dodgers second baseman Mark Grudzielanek, felled
by illness Friday in Seattle, was examined by Dr. Michael Mellman
because his condition has not improved. Johnson said it's unlikely
Grudzielanek will play tonight. . . . Gary Sheffield and Kevin
Brown were excused from the workout because they played in
Tuesday's All-Star Game. . . . The fines of coaches Rick Dempsey,
Glenn Hoffman and John Shelby were each reduced from $5,000 to
$3,000 for their part in the May 16 fight at Wrigley Field.
</P>
</TEXT>
