<HEADER>
A0768 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i BC-AIDS-MICROBICIDE-SFCH     07-13 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-MICROBICIDE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SPERMICIDE INCREASED HIV INFECTIONS  &HT;     By SABIN RUSSELL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURBAN, South Africa _ It was the worst of outcomes for a
clinical trial.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of protecting women against the AIDS virus, a
contraceptive gel being tested as a chemical shield against HIV
caused a higher rate of infection in the women who used it.
</P>
<P>
   The disastrous results, released Wednesday at the 13th
International AIDS Conference, have put an end to hopes that a
commonly used spermicide, nonoxynol-9, could be quickly put into
action as a ``microbicide,'' which could be applied before sex to
kill HIV.
</P>
<P>
   Underwritten by the United Nations, the carefully designed study
was set up in four countries in 1996 to settle the question of
whether nonoxynol-9 could become the first HIV microbicide _ a
dream AIDS prevention product sometimes called the ``chemical
condom.''
</P>
<P>
   But when researchers completed the study and examined their
data, they were shocked to discover that the women who used the gel
had a 52 percent higher infection rate. Fears that nonoxynol-9
would cause irritation and tiny tears in the vaginal wall, creating
a gateway for HIV, appeared to be well-founded.
</P>
<P>
   ``These results are a serious setback. I think this may be the
end of nonoxynol-9 as a microbicide,'' said Dr. Lut Van Damme, who
led the research effort from the Institute of Tropical Medicine in
Antwerp.
</P>
<P>
   The findings suggest that other clinical trials of the
microbicide may have to be halted for the participants' safety and
raise questions about promoting the product in family planning
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Experts are also worried about use of the chemical in sexual
lubricants. Gay men in the United States had been buying such
products in the belief that nonoxynol-9 might protect them from
HIV.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lynn Paxton, a microbicide expert at the federal Centers for
Disease Control in Atlanta, said that gay men should no longer use
lubricants with nonoxynol-9. ``I think we really need to get the
word out about this UNAIDS study,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   With prospects for an AIDS vaccine a distant dream, and
prevention education programs failing to stem Africa's soaring
infection rates, researchers have been searching for a microbicide
that would give women the means to protect themselves from the
virus. Hopes were riding high on nonoxynol-9 because it was already
on the market as a contraceptive and had a long-established track
record as a safe product.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Helen Rees, director of the South African equivalent of the
Food and Drug Administration, was bitterly disappointed. ``My
bottom line is that, if you are using nonoxynol-9 for HIV
prevention, you are wasting your money, and you may be wasting your
life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joseph Perriens, who has headed up UNAIDS efforts to develop
a microbicide program since 1993, and other microbicide experts
said they hoped the results of the test will not discourage
research in the field. In fact, they believe that the trial
findings add urgency to efforts under way to test other products
specifically designed to be HIV microbicides. None has received
marketing approval, but there are 34 candidate products in the
testing pipeline. The only products in advanced, large-scale trials
of the kind needed for regulatory approval, however, involve
nonoxynol-9.
</P>
<P>
   The UNAIDS trial used a product marketed under the trade name
Advantage-S by Columbia Laboratories, of Miami. The four-year trial
involved 990 prostitutes living in six cities, including Durban and
Johannesburg, South Africa; Hat Yai and Bangkok, Thailand; Cotonou,
Benin; and Abidjan, Cote D'Ivoire.
</P>
<P>
   Women were divided into two groups, one receiving packets
containing Advantage S, the other a vaginal moisturizer containing
no nonoxynol-9, to serve as a placebo. The women were given free
condoms and extensive counseling to use them every time. But they
were not told whether the gel they were using contained the
microbicide or was merely the placebo.
</P>
<P>
   When the results were unsealed in May, researchers were stunned
to find the infection rate for women using the microbicide was 15.5
percent; while the rate of infection among women using the placebo
was 10.2 percent. Further analysis showed that women using
Advantage S had 46 percent more vaginal lesions, small cuts or
sores that could have been caused by the gels.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Levine, research director for Columbia Laboratories, said
he felt the UNAIDS researchers were jumping the gun, basing their
conclusions of the first look at early data. He noted that some of
the prostitutes in the study used the product as much as 20 times a
day, far more than the four applications a day that was envisioned
as the typical usage rate for sex workers.
</P>
<P>
   Testing on prostitutes created a ``worst case scenario'' to
evaluate the product, said Levine. Further analysis of the data is
needed to find out whether the HIV infections were confined to the
heaviest users of the microbicide.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Padian, director of an international AIDS research program
at the University of California at San Francisco, had special
reasons to be disappointed. She was just about to launch a
nonoxynol-9 microbicide trial in Zimbabwe, involving about 1,200
women. Now, it is doubtful that trial will continue, until a new
microbicide candidate is found. ``I think the results of the
(UNAIDS) trial were pretty convincing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of nonoxynol-9 is already shifting attention to
alternative products now being tested. The three most promising are
a product called Pro 2000, under development by the New York-based
Population Council; another called ``buffer gel,'' which controls
the acidity of the vagina; and a chemical called dextrin sulfate,
which blocks the virus from penetrating cells.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
