<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0775 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-SCHOOL-REWARDS-SFCHRO     07-13 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-REWARDS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE BOARD OF EDUCATION ROLLS OUT MONETARY INCENTIVES
FOR  IMPROVED PERFORMANCE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By NANETTE ASIMOV 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Banking on the idea that people will do almost anything for
money _ even raise student test scores _ the California Board of
Education announced Wednesday that it will pay $150 per student to
schools that meet academic performance goals.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers in low-scoring schools that make great leaps forward
could earn as much as $25,000 each as a reward for their classroom
miracles.
</P>
<P>
   Even janitors can win big in California's new ``if you pay them,
they will learn'' system. They, along with school secretaries and
every other school employee, could receive at least some financial
bonus if schools make the grade.
</P>
<P>
   The rewards come from three pools of money totaling $677
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a win, win, win, win program for schools, teachers,
students and the community,'' said Doug Stone, spokesman for state
Superintendent Delaine Eastin, who Wednesday evening was still
ensconced in the board meeting where the awards were announced.
``Is it perfect? Absolutely not. But we're moving in the right
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   By agreeing on the rewards and the criteria for winning them,
California joins 14 states that have recently decided to use money
to encourage academic progress.
</P>
<P>
   California's rewards will be based on results from the Stanford
9 achievement test, due out Monday. More than 4 million students in
grades 2 to 11 took the multiple-choice exam in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   But it will be November before an announcement is made as to
which schools and teachers actually get the money, the 11-member
state board decided Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The reward system falls under the state's Public Schools
Accountability Act of 1999, a broad effort by state educators,
lawmakers and Gov. Gray Davis to jump-start student achievement.
California, which was once seen as an example of educational
progress in the nation, sank in the 1990s like the temperature on a
cold day.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians blamed a popular educational approach at the time
that generally ignored basic phonics, grammar lessons and strong
math standards. The late 1990s saw a return to such requirements.
</P>
<P>
   California's exam, now in its third year, emphasizes such
basics.
</P>
<P>
   ``What really matters in the state's new accountability system
for schools is whether students improve from one year to the
next,'' said Ann Bancroft, a spokeswoman for Davis' education
secretary, Sue Burr.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's action by the state board means that schools meeting
their annual goals for improvement will be rewarded for their focus
and achievement with significant new discretionary funds.''
</P>
<P>
   But the test being used to divvy up California's public
education dollars has been criticized by some, including a San
Francisco-based parent's group.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Alan Bonsteel, president of California Parents for
Educational Choice, contends that the Stanford 9 achievement test
should not dictate state spending because the test results reveal
very little about how students are actually doing in school.
</P>
<P>
   He has attacked the test for two main reasons: the widespread
availability of test questions, and disparities over the percentage
of eligible students who are tested.
</P>
<P>
   He argues that most of this year's test questions were repeated
from the previous two years and that old copies of the test are
easily obtained by teachers. He also insists that the state has
failed to audit what he calls the ``phony'' claims of individual
school districts about the number of eligible students taking the
test.
</P>
<P>
   Awards for schools will come from a $227 million pool and will
be known as the Governor's Performance Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Schools hoping to win $150 per pupil have to meet three
criteria:
</P>
<P>
   -- Test scores must rise by a specific amount from one year to
the next. Each year, the state's testing experts will assign a
numeric value to each school based on its scores. A value of 800 is
considered excellent. Schools must improve by 5 percent of the
difference between its own value and 800. (Schools that have
already achieved an 800 must improve by at least 1 point.)
</P>
<P>
   -- Each ethnic group within a school must also raise its scores,
but only by 80 percent of what the school as a whole must achieve.
</P>
<P>
   -- In elementary and middle schools, 95 percent of students
eligible to take the test must do so. In high schools, there has to
be a 90 percent participation rate.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Padia, a testing director at the state Department of
Education, said rates for high school students are more lenient for
a reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``The high school participation rate now is abysmally low,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to entice more teenagers to take the test, he said,
the board will slowly ratchet up the high school rate requirement,
possibly making it 92 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
   A second pool of money, $350 million, will be used to give a
bonus to every staff member at schools that win performance awards.
The actual amount going to each janitor, classroom aide, secretary,
teacher and principal is not yet known.
</P>
<P>
   The $350 million will be divided by the total number of
employees in each winning school. Half of the money will be divvied
up among employees and the other half will go into the budget of
each school's governing council.
</P>
<P>
   Schools that have no governing council ``might want to form
one,'' Padia said.
</P>
<P>
   The final pool of money, $100 million, will provide teachers
with bonuses of $5,000, $10,000, even $25,000 if their schools meet
a stringent set of requirements. The bonuses are only for teachers
who work in schools that score in the bottom half on the state
test.
</P>
<P>
   To win the bonus, a teacher's school, in addition to meeting all
criteria listed above, must improve by 10 percent, rather than the
5 percent required for schools overall. The school's test scores
must also have risen two years in a row, rather than just one.
</P>
<P>
   Among this group, 1,000 teachers at schools showing the most
gains will win $25,000. After that, 3,750 teachers will each win
$10,000, and 7,500 teachers will get the $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Padia estimates that about 60 percent of schools could win the
basic $150-per-pupil windfall. It is harder to estimate the other
groups, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not many schools will get the $25,000,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
