<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST MIGHT BE JUST AHEAD FOR ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Anaheim Angels finished the first half of
the season at 47-41, exceeding the expectations of many people.
They are in the AL West race, five games behind the first-place
Mariners and two games behind the A's, who lead the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no celebrating, no consumption of champagne during
the All-Star break. There was only pizza.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be pleased if we were in first place, but I wouldn't be
satisfied,'' manager Mike Scioscia said. ``It's like getting a
quarter of the way through a pizza. It tastes good, but you know
it's not the end.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's only the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia is in his rookie season as manager and is a candidate
for AL Manager of the Year. Second baseman Adam Kennedy and catcher
Bengie Molina are candidates for Rookie of the Year. Troy Glaus
made the All-Star team at age 23 and is halfway to 50 homers. Darin
Erstad, at age 26, leads the majors in hits.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the corps of young starting pitchers, without
whom the Angels would be looking down the barrel of another
disappointing season.
</P>
<P>
   At 26, Scott Schoeneweis is the oldest of a young and talented
group of pitchers that includes Jarrod Washburn (25), Brian Cooper
(25), Seth Etherton (23) and Ramon Ortiz (24).
</P>
<P>
   All five have spent time this season in the minors or on the
disabled list or both. But combined, they are 19-13. By comparison,
veterans Tim Belcher, Ken Hill and Kent Bottenfield are a combined
12-14.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher is on the disabled list and might not make it back. Hill
is always a pitch away from another trip to the DL. That leaves
Bottenfield as the Angels' only real candidate to be that veteran
pitcher needed to lead the staff in a pennant race.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is really looking for a starting pitcher who can
step up and be a consistent guy and go out every fifth day and
pitch into the seventh, eighth and ninth inning,'' Scioscia said.
``Certainly Bottenfield has the makeup of a guy who can do that. I
think you'll see other guys follow suit and that will allow this
club to reach its potential.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have hit 141 homers and are on their way to breaking
the club record of 192 set in 1996. But Scioscia says the offense
doesn't revolve around the long ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, there's still an upside from where we are now,''
he said. ``We're certainly not expecting more home runs, but we're
expecting to maximize run production better.''
</P>
<P>
   !dlim!Following is a first-half analysis with a look toward the
second half:
</P>
<P>
   --Manager _ In half a season, Scioscia has made the Angels
clubhouse the happiest place on earth. He commands respect, demands
hard work from his players and yet is approachable. With the help
of coaching staff, Scioscia is as prepared as any manager in the
game. Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   --First base _ Mo Vaughn finally has the opportunity to show the
organization what he can do when healthy. His .302 average, 23
homers and team-leading 68 RBI only tell half the story. Vaughn is
the clubhouse leader everybody expected him to be, having the
ability to pat a teammate on the back or kick him in the pants when
the situation calls for it. Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   --Second base _ Kennedy has shown flashes of offensive
excellence, highlighted by an eight-RBI game in Toronto in April.
However, like any rookie, Kennedy is still searching to find a
level of consistency. He has been shaky defensively but is
improving. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   --Shortstop _ Gary DiSarcina is out for the season with a
shoulder injury, and the Angels have used Benji Gil and Kevin
Stocker as fill-ins. Stocker, if healthy, will get most of the
starts in the second half. Gil got most of the first-half starts
and began slowly but has improved both offensively and defensively
in the past few weeks. Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   --Third base _ Glaus is hitting .293 with 25 homers and 60 RBI.
Except for a 1-for-29 slump late in the first half, he has been
consistent. A tired shoulder has contributed to a number of
throwing errors, but he is as good with the glove as any third
baseman in the league. Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   --Left field _ Erstad is batting .384 with 17 homers and 66 RBI,
and with 144 hits is on a pace for 265, which would break George
Sisler's major-league mark of 257. He is the club's MVP of the
first half. Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   --Center field _ Garret Anderson leads the club with 26 home
runs and is third on the club with 65 RBI. That's the upside. The
downside is Anderson, a career .300 hitter going into the season,
is hitting .246. He also needs to improve defensively by getting
better jumps on the ball off the bat. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   --Right field _ Tim Salmon is still the club's cleanup hitter,
but with 48 RBI, ranks fifth on the team. His 18 homers are fourth
on the team and his .265 average is considerably below his .291
lifetime average going into the season. Many observers believe
Salmon has lost a step defensively. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   --DH _ Scioscia has used the DH spot as a semi-day off for his
regulars, inserting primarily Scott Spiezio or Orlando Palmeiro
into the lineup. Palmeiro has been a solid on-base guy, hitting
.299. Spiezio provides occasional pop with eight homers and 25 RBI.
Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   --Starting pitching _ No starter has more than five victories,
but as a group they have kept the team in games enough to keep the
Angels in the race. Hill and Belcher have been hurt too much to
make significant contributions. Bottenfield has been inconsistent.
But the young pitchers have given the team reason to be optimistic
about the future. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   --Middle relief _ Al Levine, Shigetoshi Hasegawa and Mark
Petkovsek have been huge in bridging the game from the starters to
closer Troy Percival. Hasegawa's six wins lead the team. Levine has
an ERA of 3.19 serving as a starter, long man, set-up man and
closer (two saves). Petkovsek has bounced back from an illness to
pitch in 30 games, fourth most on the team. Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   --Closer _ Percival has saved 20 and blown five. He constantly
seems to be adjusting mechanics, but when he's right he's almost
unhittable. Still, the club could not have hoped for more
considering he is coming off shoulder surgery. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   --Bench _ Palmeiro and Spiezio have been valuable, as has backup
catcher Matt Walbeck. However, Edgard Clemente is struggling in his
role as a bench player, and overall Angels pinch-hitters are
batting only .158 with no homers and one RBI. Grade: C
</P>
