<SLUG> BC-BKO-SUMMER-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSS HASN'T FORGOTTEN HIS GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SEAN KEARNS  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Randy Moss caught a ball of a different
kind Wednesday. The 6-foot-4 Minnesota Vikings wide receiver
debuted in basketball's Summer Pro League with a solid showing at
the Pyramid.
</P>
<P>
   Moss scored 13 points in 18 minutes. His team, Pro Advantage,
beat KMPC 110-92.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict on his play: Don't punch that NBA ticket too
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got quick feet and is a good athlete,'' said Walter
Szczerbiak Sr., a former professional player and father of Wally
Szczerbiak of the Minnesota Timberwolves.
</P>
<P>
   The senior Szczerbiak also scouts for the professional leagues
in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could tell he didn't play college ball,'' Szczerbiak said
of Moss' game. ``He looked like a lot of good players playing in
the free-agent division.''
</P>
<P>
   That division includes players who were not invited to play in
the summer league by NBA teams. Most of the players have played
overseas, in the CBA or have been out of the game and are hoping to
catch someone's eye.
</P>
<P>
   Moss will be playing again today at 12:45 as part of the team
Passing Lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could tell he has basketball skills,'' said Don Sellers,
an assistant coach with the Trenton Shooting Stars in the
International Basketball League. Sellers will be coaching Moss
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's a guy that could make the transition successfully
into the minor leagues (of basketball),'' Sellers said. ``I don't
know if he could be an NBA player, but he could definitely be a
good minor-leaguer. I was impressed with his defense and his feel
for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss twice was West Virginia High School Basketball Player of
the Year at DuPont High in Rand, West Va., where he was a teammate
of Sacramento Kings guard Jason Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Kansas City Chiefs tight end Tony Gonzalez, another
summer-league participant, also is a long shot because he is an
undersized power forward at 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's undersized for what he does,'' said Rob Babcock of the
Minnesota Timberwolves.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, a two-sport athlete at Cal, scored 15 points on 4-of-6
shooting and a perfect 7 of 7 from the free-throw line. His team,
Nutriola, defeated Olimpia Milano 122-80.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez has about a week until he leaves for training camp with
the Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   __ Kobe's team in town: Kobe Bryant's team, Olimpia Milano,
began play on Wednesday with its loss to Nutriola. The team is
owned 50- percent by Bryant and his father, Joe Bryant, a former
NBA player.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Olimpia Milano faces the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   __ Of note: Seattle SuperSonics guard Shammond Williams
continues to play well. He had 23 points in a 109-82 win over the
Portland Trail Blazers. He's averaging 26 points over four games so
far. Point guard Kedrick Johnson had 22 points, eight rebounds and
seven assists against Olimpia Milano. Johnson played last season in
Australia . . . Dallas Maverick Dirk Nowitzki has also shown well,
scoring 29 in a loss to Golden State. He had 24 in his only other
game. Dallas draft pick Courtney Alexander is averaging 19.5 and
Etan Thomas is averaging 19 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
