   &UR; WORLD ONCE AGAIN DESCENDS ON SUMMIT SHANGRI-LA, CAMP DAVID &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INSIDE-CAMP-DAVID-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Camp David, once named Shangri-La, was a retreat
for President Franklin Delano Roosevelt from the stifling heat
which blankets Washington in the summer. Presidents ever since have
used it as a vacation home, a place to entertain guests and
occasionally _ as is the case this week with the
Barak-Arafat-Clinton summit _ to bring antagonists together to
talk. For the inhabitants of Thurmont, the nearest town to Camp
David, the flurry of activity on their doorstep is nothing new.
They seem more concerned with the local fire department's annual
carnival....By Andrew Marshall, The Independent &QL;
</P>
