<P>
   &UR; FROM THE INDEPENDENT OF LONDON: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CORRUPT HISTORY DOGS NEW PALESTINE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ARAFAT-WINNIE-POOH-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Like Winnie the Pooh, Yasser Arafat loves honey.
Some of his colleagues believe his daily intake of the stuff,
bought at some expense in Yemen and poured into his tea, is the
reason why he is still in action, travelling from country to
country, tirelessly pressing his cause. Indeed, despite being
troubled by Parkinson's disease, the Palestinian leader is still in
fairly good fettle. Alas, the same cannot be said of his
Palestinian state that may, or may not, now be approaching birth _
depending on the outcome of the tripartite summit in Camp David,
Md., which began Tuesday....By Phil Reeves, The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (800 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KILLING THE DEAD: HEZBOLLAH BLOWS UP COLLABORATORS' MEMORIAL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `TRAITOR'-TOMB-RAZED-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MARJAYOUN, SOUTH LEBANON _ Was this what victory was for? Was
this why the Hezbollah fighters lost their hundreds of ``martyrs''
in their 18-year conflict with Israel and its Lebanese militia
allies? To blow up a war memorial? It stood atop a hill within
sight of Israel, the foreign land whom the SLA men had been paid to
defend. Of course, they were collaborators, Lebanese working for
their country's enemy. Some of them were brutal, cruel men. But
most of the dead were blackmailed by the Israelis into joining the
militia, boy-soldiers whose brothers or fathers would have been
imprisoned if they had not served Israel's cause in Lebanon....By
Robert Fisk, The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (600 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PALESTINIAN FAMILIES DIVIDED BY NEW ISRAELI FENCE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPLIT-SISTERS-LEBANON-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AIT AL-SHAAB, SOUTH LEBANON _ The rocks were littered with old
Pepsi cans and empty water bottles and dead bushes but Haji Mariam
Badran scrambled towards the Israeli frontier wire with the help of
her stick. ``I talked to my sister Sheikha on the phone and she
promised to be here at 11:30,'' the old woman wheezed. ``We have
been here since 10:30. And now the Israelis told us to go away.''
Mariam Badran's story is as pitiful as it is tragic. On the very
day that Sheikha _ separated from her sister 52 years ago when the
Jewish Army attacked their village _ called from Israel to confirm
their meeting at the wire, the Israelis decided to call an end to
the family reunions over the frontier fence....By Robert Fisk, The
Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors...TIMELY for this week's Camp David
summit) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (725 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SOUTH LEBANON: THEY MADE A DESERT AND CALLED IT PEACE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `DANGER!'-MINES-LEBANON-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ABBASIYEH, SOUTH LEBANON _ The lost villages of southern Lebanon
are a disgrace. Some, like Ein Arab, have been used as a target
range for Israel's proxy ``South Lebanon Army'' militia. Others,
like Abbasiyeh, have no memorial. Just a single, slightly rusted
sign shows where the village once stood. ``Danger Mines!'' it says
in English, Hebrew and Arab. The Israelis have withdrawn _ up to a
point _ but the village is dead and the soil is now too dangerous
to tread on. So, what was liberation worth?....By Robert Fisk, The
Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,050 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AFRICAN AIDS BABIES ABANDONED AT CHURCH'S `DOOR OF HOPE' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DUMPED-AIDS-BABIES-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DURBAN _ The hatch slams shut, a bell rings and Raphael Kayamba
has the future of yet another anonymous individual on his hands. A
deacon at Berea Baptist Mission in Johannesburg, Kayamba deals with
the living, kicking proof of the South African AIDS crisis:
HIV-positive infants, abandoned at his church's ``door of
hope.''....By Alex Duval Smith, The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (TIMELY for this week's AIDS Conference, Durban, S.Africa) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (675 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLEVER TEXAS `COYOTE' PUTS NEW SPIN ON BORDER SMUGGLING &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `TOUR-DE-FRAUD'-MEXICO-INDPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ When border police in Texas stopped a team of
racing bicyclists in lycra jerseys and helmets it was the end of
the road for one of the most innovative ``coyotes'' _ people
smugglers on the Mexican frontier. The ``cyclists'' were all
undocumented Mexican migrants who had allegedly paid the smuggler
to take them across the border....By Jan McGirk, The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Texas, California) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (750 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DEFIANT SHEBAA FARMERS OF SOUTH LEBANON WON'T SURRENDER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `SHEBAA-FARMS'-FLAK-INDEPENDENT-800&AMP;ADD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SHEBAA, SOUTH LEBANON _ Like everything else in Lebanon, land is
about history. And in the case of the hot, jagged, grey rocks above
Shebaa, it's about occupation and war and annexation and a
half-century-old trail upon which Jews were once smuggled into
mandate Palestine. The ``Shebaa farms'' they call these walls of
stone and windswept trees and unkempt fields. And since they may
yet cause another war in southern Lebanon, it's wise to visit the
little village of Shebaa, where an old man remembers history with
the coldness of a book....By Robert Fisk, The Independent &QL;
</P>
