<DOCNO> NYT20000713.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 08:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0798 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      07-13 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    WHEN WHO AND WHAT AT WHY(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By E.J. MONTINI(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - It's not every day a man with a bloody shirt and a
question to ask walks into the combination gas station, grocery
store and post office Roberta Kornack manages in the town called
Why.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was shaking,'' Roberta says, ``this smallish, dark-haired
man. He was like a teddy bear. `It was terrible. I couldn't go on,'
he told us.''
</P>
<P>
   The man spoke with a foreign accent, French maybe. They offered
him a soft drink and got him to sit down.
</P>
<P>
   It was July 7, a Friday, just before noon. Employees of the Why
Not Travel store had already begun counting the cars whizzing by on
Arizona 85, heading for Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told us his name was Jon,'' Roberta says. ``He said he'd
left Phoenix that morning and was headed to Organ Pipe Cactus
National Monument. Up above Ajo, around Milepost 25, he was
following a green van. He said a rear tire blew out and the van
lost control, flipped and rolled, with one of the people inside
winding up on the road and others hurt inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon had a cellular telephone with him but didn't know he could
dial 911 for emergency assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stopped and tried to get others to stop so they could use
the phone to call for help, but they wouldn't stop,'' he told
Roberta. ``Why?''
</P>
<P>
   A Department of Public Safety officer arrived not long after the
accident. According to a report filed later, he remembered a
foreign man in the roadway helping to direct traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Jon told Roberta he had pulled one of the victims off the road.
That's how he got the blood on his shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got him to give the shirt to us so we could wash out the
blood for him,'' Roberta says. They used a hand cleaner and bleach.
</P>
<P>
   The man asked Roberta if everyone in this country is afraid to
help others when they are hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what to tell him,'' Roberta says. ``You'd end up
going into how everybody's in a hurry and how they might be afraid
to get involved because they might get sued. What do you say?''
</P>
<P>
   Tragedy generates questions. In this case, the ``who'' was
known. And the ``what.'' And ``where.'' Now, this confused man from
overseas was in a place called Why, and no one knew the answer.
</P>
<P>
   A DPS spokesman said there were four women in the van. They were
nurses, perhaps on their way to Rocky Point for the weekend. One of
them died at the scene. The others also were injured, but not
critically.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators don't believe a tire blew out on the van. They
suspect the driver may have drifted off the pavement, skidded on
the loose berm, then lost control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine seeing that happen right in front of you when you're
in a strange country,'' Roberta says.
</P>
<P>
   Jon seemed to calm down the longer he stayed in the Why Not
Travel store and cheered up considerably when they returned his
shirt to him, clean and white.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thanked us,'' Roberta says, ``but we didn't think to thank
him for being a good Samaritan. Or even find out his last name.''
Before he left, they did ask the man where he was headed, however.
</P>
<P>
   South, he told them. The desert for some is religious, a
cathedral done in reds and browns, its blue dome arching from
horizon to horizon. The man who'd witnessed the accident wanted to
be there more than ever, to wander among the organ pipes.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Montini at Ed.Montini(a)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-8978.
</P>
</TEXT>
