<SLUG> BC-STAB-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-STAB-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    20 TIMES? STABBING `ACCIDENT'(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BETH DEFALCO(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Mesa, ARIZ.)
</P>
<P>
   A Mesa teenager charged with stabbing a 7-year-old 20 times
first denied attacking the girl, then told detectives that he may
have accidentally stabbed her a few times while playing with a
steak knife, according to a police report released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After he initially denied attacking Emily Galbraith behind her
apartment complex on West 10th Place near Country Club Drive on
Monday afternoon, Michael Arvizo, 14, later admitted he
``accidentally stabbed Emily while he was throwing a knife in the
air,'' the report says.
</P>
<P>
   He contradicted that account later, telling officers that he
fell on top of Emily as they were climbing a wall and
``accidentally stabbed her then,'' the report says. Arvizo said he
stabbed Emily again as he was getting up from his fall and then
``got scared and deliberately stabbed her twice more.''
</P>
<P>
   Arvizo had been baby-sitting Emily and his sister, Heidi, the
victim's best friend, and had been walking the victim home at the
time of the attack, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The teen offered no motive for the attack, but Heidi told police
that her brother had smeared some nail polish remover on Emily's
head and that ``she got mad,'' the report says.
</P>
<P>
   Arvizo, who has been charged as an adult with a crime that
carries up to 24 years in prison, was interviewed almost
immediately after Emily was found unconscious in the parking lot at
her apartment complex.
</P>
<P>
   Emily was listed in fair condition Wednesday evening at Maricopa
Medical Center in Phoenix. Doctors are hopeful the little girl
won't need further reconstructive surgery. She lost 20 percent of
her blood and suffered deep cuts that just missed her heart and
other organs.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa paramedic Cori Garnell, one of the first rescuers to
arrive, told (beginitalic)The Republic (enditalic)on Wednesday that
Emily identified Arvizo as her attacker in a brief interview with
paramedics and police.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why Arvizo stabbed her, Emily simply replied, ``I
don't know,'' according to the police report.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how tough this little girl was,'' Garnell said.
``She was afraid to tell us her last name because she didn't want
to get in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   When police arrived Monday afternoon at the boy's home just
after the stabbing, Arvizo's mother, Diana McKinney, gave them
permission to enter, the report says.
</P>
<P>
   Police found a pair of water-soaked shoes in the bathroom,
noting the shower was ``wet like someone had recently took a
shower.'' They also saw what appeared to be ``blood in and around
the bathroom sink,'' the report states.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, police found a 6-inch steak knife between a storage
unit and the wall bordering the apartment complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``He deliberately denied the act and showed no remorse,'' Sgt.
Earle Lloyd, a Mesa police spokesman, told (beginitalic)The
Republic (enditalic)on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Arvizo was being held in lieu of a $97,350 bond Wednesday.
Although charged as an adult, he is housed at Maricopa County's
Madison Street Jail with other juveniles.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
