<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 08:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0802 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-SHARPE-AZR &LR;      07-13 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARPE-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-SHARPE-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    SHARPE DEPORTATION HEARING TODAY(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By JUDY VILLA(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Florence, ARIZ.) - Luis Sharpe remembers Cuba through the eyes
of a 6-year-old child: Spending time with his grandfather in
Havana; playing with new toys his grandfather showered on his
favorite grandson; climbing aboard the airplane that would take him
to U.S. soil and reunite him with his father.
</P>
<P>
   Bits and pieces of memories that have faded in the 34 years that
Sharpe has lived in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But Sharpe, who once lived a storied life as the marquee player
for the Arizona Cardinals, now is brushing up on everything Cuban
and facing the possibility that he could be deported to a country
he hasn't seen since he was 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I don't want to go back,'' the former offensive
lineman said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe spoke Wednesday from the Immigration and Naturalization
Service detention center in Florence, where he is being held.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would find a way to survive, but I'd be going into a place
that I don't know anything about,'' said Sharpe, wearing orange
detention pants and shirt and appearing to be relaxed and in good
health.
</P>
<P>
   A drug conviction earlier this year, Sharpe's second, landed him
in this predicament. Sharpe admits that parts of his past {ndash}
drug arrests, domestic violence, fights with police officers,
several failed rehabilitation attempts and two gunshots wounds
{ndash} are less than savory since he retired in 1994 because of a
knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   But he also maintains that he doesn't deserve to be banished
from the United States - and separated from his children - for the
rest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't think I'm worthy of being in this country
anymore,'' Sharpe said. ``But I have a lot to offer and I still do.
Because of all I've been through and gone through, I can be a help
to hurting, lost souls. I'm excited to do that again.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe seemed well on his way to getting his life back in order
18 months ago after he had successfully completed drug
rehabilitation and began volunteering at a Phoenix ministry. He had
rebuilt relationships with his five children and talked of becoming
a minister himself.
</P>
<P>
   But last year, after two months at Rhema Bible College in
Oklahoma, Sharpe returned for a visit and relapsed into drugs. He
was arrested in November and then again in January for possession
of cocaine and drug paraphernalia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I failed once again,'' Sharpe said. ``I serve a forgiving God,
and I thank him for his grace and his mercy.''
</P>
<P>
   But INS law isn't so forgiving. Any person who is not a U.S.
citizen is subject to deportation if he is convicted of a crime.
</P>
<P>
   And while actual deportations to Cuba are virtually
non-existent, about 600 Cuban citizens sit in detention centers
across the country because their home country will not take them
back, according to February statistics provided by the Florence
Immigrant and Refugee Rights Project. Some are released into the
community while they await word, maybe years down the road, that
Cuba will finally accept them, but others become what's called
``indefinite detainees,'' waiting out their time in detention
because they could pose a risk to society.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, six men returned to Cuban soil after they took
hostages in a Louisiana jail and demanded they be repatriated.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Ahr, an INS spokesman in Phoenix, said immigration
officials periodically submit a list of names they want to deport
and the Cuban government then decides which, if any, it'll take
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's done on a piecemeal basis, one at a time,'' Ahr said.
</P>
<P>
   Ahr could not discuss Sharpe's case. Sharpe, who said he had
planned to enter a rehabilitation program and resume his ministry
studies, was taken into INS custody last month after serving three
months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe, 40, is a legal resident of the United States, but he
never became a naturalized citizen even though his parents and
brother did. A sister was born in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just never took the time to do it,'' Sharpe said.
``Laziness, I guess. I just never went and did the paperwork. I
just never thought that I needed to, so I never did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost my shot. I can't blame anyone else, only myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe's first hearing on the deportation matter is today. It
could take months before it's resolved. Meanwhile, he serves
mandatory detention under INS law, working for a dollar a day in
the recreation yard.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe's attorney plans to challenge the mandatory detention law
in federal court, saying it's unfair and unconstitutional to detain
a man who is not violent, is not a threat to society and does not
pose a flight risk.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second time Sharpe has faced deportation to Cuba. In
1998, he was granted a one-time waiver because he had been a
longtime legal resident and was not considered an aggravated felon.
</P>
<P>
   If he is ordered deported, his only recourse will be to seek
political asylum, a withholding of the removal order or relief
under the Convention Against Torture.
</P>
<P>
   All involve proving that Sharpe would be persecuted or tortured
if he returned to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (beginitalic) (enditalic)Sharpe's attorney, Jose Peqalosa Jr.,
believes that would be the case. He believes Sharpe could be
persecuted for his socioeconomic status, his religious beliefs and
his political beliefs. Sharpe's grandfather, Ernesto
Caballero-Suarez, served as mayor of the small town of Jamaica
Yatero during the Batista regime, then was imprisoned and died
after current leader Fidel Castro took power.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe's father once worked at the Guantanamo Bay Naval Station
and chose to go to the United States in 1962 instead of remaining
loyal to Castro.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having been instilled with democratic values and being the
person that I am today, that transgresses Cuban law and Cuban
beliefs,'' Sharpe said, ``and that would, I think, subject me to
torture and persecution. Someone like me could be a threat to their
ideology.''
</P>
<P>
   Public sentiment, though, may not be with Sharpe the way it was
for Elian Gonzales, whose Miami relativesfought, then lost, a
seven-month battle to gain asylum for the boy. But for Sharpe,
``the stakes are higher,'' Peqalosa said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all as Americans have a heart,'' Sharpe said. ``We're all
interested in the well-being of all people, and any time you see a
person that would be persecuted or tortured, we all should care.''
</P>
<P>
   Returning to Cuba would mean that Sharpe would be virtually cut
out of the lives of his five children, because getting travel
documents to Cuba is very difficult. &UR; (beginitalic) (enditalic)He
would have no money. The only people he would know would be a
spattering of aunts, uncles and cousins to whom he's rarely spoken.
</P>
<P>
   He could never return to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   And though Sharpe is fluent in Spanish, he said that likely
wouldn't be enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I could communicate,'' he said. ``But could I function?
That's a different thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
