A0803 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN16-COX     07-13 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Bush breaks from GOP's racist past in NAACP speech
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was more chutzpah than healing in George W. Bush's speech
to the national convention of the NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   Credit the Republican presidential candidate with trying. No GOP
nominee-presumptive has bothered visiting the convention since 1988
when Bush's father addressed it. Four years ago, Bob Dole pointedly
snubbed an invitation, sourly dismissing it as an attempt by the
NAACP to set him up.
</P>
<P>
   Dole's gesture, carried out with more than ordinary political
histrionics, was surely meant to be read by the neo-Confederate,
``Fergit, Hell!'' wing of the GOP as extending the party's hoary
``Southern strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   The strategy was Richard Nixon's device for breaking the once
solidly Democratic South by co-opting Alabama Gov. George Wallace's
white-backlash politics _ ending busing for school desegregation
and so on _ without Wallace's overt racist posturing and
fulmination.
</P>
<P>
   That has complicated the challenge to Democratic presidential
candidates, but the GOP's silent pact with racism has now begun to
complicate the challenge to Republican candidates, too. The GOP
typically polls a distant second with the growing blocs of ethnic
voters, often the make-or-break difference in key states like
California.
</P>
<P>
   Bush conceded as much with his admission to the NAACP that the
party of Lincoln has not always carried the mantle of Lincoln. (You
could say. President Reagan opposed every piece of civil rights
legislation in its time. Republican members of Congress, with
honorable exceptions, have generally resisted relevant legislation.
The GOP is the main political engine for dismantling affirmative
action. The list goes on.)
</P>
<P>
   Bush himself bore a substantial burden to his NAACP appearance.
Though sporting a generally decent record on race, just three
months earlier he had stooped to racist fellow-traveling in South
Carolina, speaking at Bob Jones University, toxic for its ban of
interracial dating, and cravenly indulging the state's overhanging
ensign of racism, the Confederate battle flag, which even South
Carolina's own balky state legislators furled just weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if others in his party will follow, Bush has taken what
could be the first step in a long-term rehabilitation of the
relationship the between the GOP and African-American voters.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate's acknowledgement that racism remains active
should be a commonplace but was bold in a party that often pretends
the nation has achieved a magical post-racial colorblindness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of Jim Crow,'' Bush said, ``there's racial profiling
and redlining. Instead of 'separate but equal,' there's separate
but forgotten.'' Few in Republican leadership have admitted as much
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had little solid to offer the NAACP delegates and the
larger black community except a promise to enforce civil right laws
_ which ought to go without saying. But if just showing up doesn't
count for much these days, Bush's appearance, given the long
estrangement, at least counts as a start.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He is based in
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
