<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0855 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV16-C     07-13 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: HOW TO FUND A RICH UNCLE SAM
 &HT;    Moving in (k) commentary and (f) financial categories for
release
 &HT;    Sunday, July 16.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ News from the nation's entertainment capital that
Eastman Kodak will pay $75 million to put its name on the theater
where the Academy Awards are due to move raises the prospect that
we're missing a bet back here at what J. Edgar Hoover, once a
Hollywood icon, called the seat of government.
</P>
<P>
   After all, why shouldn't the taxpayers also profit from the
trend that brings in big bucks from corporate sponsors for naming
rights to just about anything that's nailed down?
</P>
<P>
   Politicians already help point the way. The Republican National
Convention will open July 31 in Philadelphia's First Union Center,
a hall named in honor of the nation's sixth largest banking firm,
with assets that rival the annual U.S. defense budget.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the GOP could find a way to earn some extra campaign
funds by having Gov. George W. Bush of Texas give First Union a
subtle plug when he claims his party's presidential nomination.
Bush could begin his acceptance speech by saying: ``First and
foremost, sound banking policies anchor the union.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, Vice President Al Gore could tell a
nationally televised Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles
that, as top dog, he would ``staple together centrist policies.''
That, course, would be a bow to the Staples Center, the host site,
and to the role office supplies play in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   There's already talk in Atlanta of putting a corporate tag on
that city's busy public airport. Wes Hasden, associate editor of
the Chattanooga Times, has suggested that Atlanta-based Home Depot
claim the prize. That way, the mass transit station at Hartsfield
International Airport could be called the Home Depot depot.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics might object to the idea of giving federal
facilities corporate names on the grounds that, thanks to a hot
economy, the government already expects to earn a $2 trillion
surplus over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   But like the Internet bubble that recently ruptured, such
projections are no sure thing. On the other hand, if things do work
out as planned, then the extra cash itself could earn some extra
cash as ``The Fortune 500 Surplus.''
</P>
<P>
   Along those lines, to help offset the rising costs of judicial
research, Chief Justice William Rehnquist could explore with Bill
Gates the notion of dispatching some of his corporate billions this
way. In return, a colorful Windows logo would be discreetly
embroidered onto the black robes of the nine jurists. For a few
billions more, the marble palace where they convene could be known
as the Microsoft Supreme National Business Court (MSNBC).
</P>
<P>
   As one of this city's prime tourist attractions, the White House
could no doubt also command top naming dollars from the business
community. Frequent mention in the press of the president's home
would only serve to enhance its naming value.
</P>
<P>
   A corporate consortium _ one that would surely include Kodak _
could be formed to help defray the expected large cost. Should any
antitrust concerns arise from such a collective approach, they
could be easily overcome at the MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 1010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
