weyded(at)nytimes.com.)
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILANTHROPY IS BECOMING A CLICK-AND-GIVE ENTERPRISE
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-GIVING _ Philanthropy has embraced the World Wide Web.
With a computer, a modem and a credit card, you can now give money
to Habitat for Humanity or any of the other 640,000 charities in
America, using allcharities.com. Type your ZIP code into an online
box at helping.org and you can learn when and where you can
volunteer in your community this weekend. With a few clicks at
guidestar.org you can peek at the American Red Cross' Form 990 tax
return and learn that Elizabeth Dole earned a $202,417 salary in
her last year as the charity's president. You can even buy eight
gourmet shrimp burgers at iGive.com for $17.95, with 15 percent of
your purchase _ in dollars, not burgers _ donated to Save the
Whales. Never before has so much information been so readily
available to donors. Never before has it been so easy to give money
and keep records for tax purposes. And never before have charities
_ which took in a record $190 billion in this country last year _
been so enthralled with the fund-raising potential of technology.
By Mark O'Keefe. With photos and a graphic. About 1,900 words
(``a'' and ``f'' categories).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 1020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000713.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0894 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-ONLINE-GIVING-NEWHOUS     07-13 2036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-GIVING-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILANTHROPY IS BECOMING A CLICK-AND-GIVE ENTERPRISE 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: Repeating for all needing. This article from
NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for Wednesday, July 12, is available as a
``separate-buy.'' For information about purchasing the article,
contact DEBRA WEYDERT of The New York Times Syndicate at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697; e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADV: With two photos, of Mary Kay Phelps (NNS1) and Tracey
Pettengill (NNS2), and a graphic listing Web addresses for online
giving. 
 By MARK O'KEEFE  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Philanthropy has begun to embrace the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   With a computer, a modem and a credit card, you can now give
money to any of the 640,000 charities in America, using
www.allCharities.com or any of more than a dozen similar Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Type your ZIP code into an online box at www.helping.org and you
can learn when and where you can volunteer in your community this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   With a few clicks at www.guidestar.org, you can peek at the
American Red Cross' Form 990 tax return and learn that Elizabeth
Dole earned a $202,417 salary in her last full year as the
charity's president.
</P>
<P>
   You can even buy eight gourmet shrimp burgers at www.iGive.com
for $17.95, with 15 percent of your purchase -- in dollars, not
burgers -- donated to Save the Whales (www.savethewhales.org) or
any other charity you choose. A fast-growing number of other
virtual charity malls also provide opportunities for do-gooder
shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Never before has so much information been so readily available
to donors. Never before has it been so easy to give money and keep
records for tax purposes. And never before have charities -- which
took in a record $190 billion in this country last year -- been so
enthralled with the fund-raising potential of technology.
</P>
<P>
   Since online donors are expected to demand more information and
accountability from charities, e-philanthropy -- though still in
its infancy -- has the potential to alter the character of the
nonprofit sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can find out a lot more about organizations with just a
few clicks of your mouse,'' said Mary Kay Phelps, senior director
of direct response fund raising for the American Red Cross
(www.redcross.org), the undisputed champion of e-philanthropy,
raising $2.8 million online in 1999. ``You can check their annual
reports. You can check how wisely they spend their money.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a Chronicle of Philanthropy survey of 252 of the
largest nonprofit organizations, the Red Cross' 1999 total was more
than four times the next highest amount raised online, $590,300, by
Catholic Relief Services of Baltimore (www.catholicrelief.org).
</P>
<P>
   For 1999, the $7 million online total for the 252 charities was
eight times what they raised online in 1998. But it was still less
than 1 percent of all the money they raised.
</P>
<P>
   One-third of the country's largest charities didn't do any fund
raising on the Internet in 1999. Alnisa Allgood, executive director
of San Francisco-based Nonprofit Tech (www.nonprofit-tech.org),
said that even in Silicon Valley, her unscientific estimate is that
only 5 percent of charities, most of them small, even have Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compared to the corporate world, the nonprofit world is way
behind,'' said Allgood. ``There's just a huge chasm.''
</P>
<P>
   That's changing.
</P>
<P>
   Nonprofit organizations of all sizes have scrambled to buy
computers and establish Web sites this year. And a suddenly
competitive number of Web-based charity portals -- doorways to
content in cyberspace -- have tried to strategically position
themselves as middlemen to cut their own slices of the fast-growing
philanthropic pie.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   For donors, as well as people not inclined to giving, the
Internet may reduce, but not eliminate, some of the most annoying
community fund-raising drives.
</P>
<P>
   Tired of the traditional raffles, candy sales and car washes in
which every parent, neighbor and relative is expected to
contribute, an increasing number of schools have turned to Web
sites such as www.Schoolpop.com, www.SchoolCash.com and
www.ShopforSchool.com that link to online retailers while giving a
percentage of purchases back to the schools.
</P>
<P>
   WAMU, a Washington, D.C., public radio station (www.wamu.org),
has foregone some of the usual on-air pitches that interrupt
favorite programs, replacing them with a highly promoted
``CyberMonday'' or ``CyberWednesday.'' Bheesham Sethi, the
station's director of institutional support, said about 35 percent
of revenues from one-week membership drives has come on cyber days,
and listeners love it, because it puts them in control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will Web fund raising be part of the charitable landscape?''
Sethi asked. ``Absolutely. Does that mean we'll do away with direct
mail and things like that? Absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   To expand, e-philanthropy must overcome several hurdles,
including donor concerns about privacy and security when giving
online. In addition, the Internal Revenue Service has raised
questions about whether charity gifts funneled through for-profit
portals are tax-deductible, especially if there's no written
agreement from the charity to accept such donations through a
middleman.
</P>
<P>
   The increasing investment in e-philanthropy banks on the yet
unproven assumption that Net-savvy donors' growing comfort with
buying and researching online will transfer to Internet giving.
</P>
<P>
   Gerardo Capiel is an example of how this progression would work.
As chief technology officer of Digital Impact of San Mateo, Calif.,
he finds the Internet his natural domain.
</P>
<P>
   Capiel read a newspaper article this year about flooding in
Mozambique and was stirred to help. The article listed a toll-free
number for Oxfam America, but when Capiel called, the number was
busy. Determined, Capiel turned to his computer and found the
charity online (www.oxfamamerica.org), where he gave his first
Internet donation.
</P>
<P>
   It was so easy that Capiel experimented at www.4charity.com, one
of at least 17 portals that help donors research charities and
process online gifts. Now Capiel does all his giving online,
enjoying the ability to ``drill deep'' for information and the
convenience of having a record of his charitable deductions.
</P>
<P>
   He chose the San Francisco-based 4charity.com because it doesn't
take a big cut of his gifts, as some portals do. Instead, it passes
100 percent to the charity (hoping to make the bulk of its revenues
by charging for work done on charities' own Web sites). For Capiel,
it didn't hurt that 4charity.com was founded by graduates of
Stanford University, his alma mater.
</P>
<P>
   When Capiel donates through the portal, his charities get his
name and e-mail address, something that might give some people
privacy worries, but not Capiel.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can run marketing campaigns to let me know what other
events they have going,'' he said. ``With that, I'll be able to
click from my e-mail to give them a donation. That will be great.''
</P>
<P>
   Capiel has seen for-profit businesses invest in the Internet for
a few years now. But it's as if the nonprofit sector collectively
awoke in 2000 to the potential of the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is year one,'' said Tracey Pettengill, 29, chief
executive officer of 4charity.com. ``We're in the protozoa stage of
development in the evolution of the Internet. But we're starting
something that will truly be revolutionary.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most dynamic possibilities of e-philanthropy --
interactivity between donor and charity -- could be its most
formidable hurdle.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the traditional philanthropic model centers on
what is known as ``the ask.'' Simply put, charities initiate and
donors respond.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet, however, creates a two-way street. For the medium
to work optimally, donors will become proactive, just as buyers of
e-commerce are.
</P>
<P>
   ``But with philanthropy, people aren't buying a stock or a
product,'' said John Walters, president of the Washington-based
Philanthropy Roundtable and a skeptic of e-philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survey after survey shows Americans practice what I call
`Trick or Treat' giving. You give to people and charities who ask
you. When it comes to reactive giving, the Internet is limited.
That's because donors simply don't start the search. They don't
say, `Who do I want to give to today?'''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Schmidt, founder and president of Virginia-based
Philanthropic Research, questions the viability of stand-alone
charity portals. What, after all, is going to drive donors to them?
</P>
<P>
   He sees more merit in making links to charity sites from online
media articles that pique interest in a problem, or from popular
financial service sites, where users are already thinking about
their money. The American Red Cross has found much of its success
by running banners requesting help on American Online and Yahoo!
</P>
<P>
   When Hurricane Floyd hit the East Coast in September 1999, more
than $574,000 was given online to the Red Cross, where the average
Internet contribution is $130, compared to $115 through other
methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true that you don't wake up in the morning saying, `I
have $1,000, where can I give it away?''' said Schmidt, whose
GuideStar display of charity tax returns and other information has
been hailed as a breakthrough in providing online accountability.
``But you do wake up in the morning and get engaged in life through
the Internet and say, `Aha.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The ahas are where the action is.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Gudrun Schindler had an ``aha'' one day in June while sitting at
her new Gateway Pentium III computer in her Elgin, Neb., farmhouse.
She clicked to the Web site of the World Pantheist Movement
(www.pantheism.net), as she often does. There she discovered a new
way to promote pantheism, which maintains the universe as a whole,
not a god, should be held in reverence.
</P>
<P>
   All she had to do was find and review Web sites, on any subject,
for a new online directory, Zeal, which gave 50 cents to a person's
favorite charity for every Web site accepted
(www.zeal.com/charity).
</P>
<P>
   The novel concept gives Zeal, a May start-up, inexpensive labor
for a task for which more established competitors have had to hire
staff. It also illustrates how the Internet can foster creative
ways for people to engage philanthropically.
</P>
<P>
   For Schindler, a teacher, the scheme provided a way to help a
cause she believes in, but has not been able to donate to because
of budget constraints. It became something of a fun addiction, she
said, to mine Web sites two to three hours at a time, watching the
pantheism tally steadily increase.
</P>
<P>
   In about 20 hours online, Schindler raised $326, joining 69
other pantheists pointing and clicking their way to a grand total
exceeding $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's been hard being out here in the middle of
nowhere,'' Schindler said. ``The Internet helps me connect, and
this made me feel like I was actually producing something.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as is the case with many e-philanthropy ideas, the future
is anything but clear. Zeal changed its policy on June 30, dropping
its charity contribution from 50 to 10 cents for each published
submission, while adding a $500 weekly bonus to a selected charity.
``Zealots'' whom Zeal has so carefully cultivated have been howling
in online discussion groups ever since.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Zeal senior marketing manager Daniel
Chamberlain said Zeal gave more than $10,000 to charities in May,
with nearly $40,000 expected to go out to more than 400 charities
later this summer. Chamberlain said he wanted to see the charity
drive ``continue indefinitely,'' perhaps with the help of sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Harrison, president of the World Pantheism Movement, is
tickled that the Internet may push donations to small charities
such as his. He calls it ``part of the magic money scene of the
Web.''
</P>
<P>
   But he hasn't seen any magic money yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in hope, with our fingers crossed, and will believe
itfully only when we see it,'' Harrison said. ``There is an element
of uncertainty here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 1033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
