   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HIV-POT (Durban, South Africa) _ The first U.S. study using
medical marijuana for people with HIV has found that smoking the
plant does not disrupt the effect of anti-retroviral drugs that
keep the virus in check. The results were announced Thursday at the
13th International AIDS Conference. By ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   EYE-SURGERY (San Francisco) _ Jim Beebe loved to read, play
poker, mow the lawn _ but he couldn't do those things anymore,
because of deteriorating vision. Now a new, experimental form of
eye surgery has restored much of his vision. The surgery involves
replacing the eye's deteriorating cornea with lab-grown cells from
a donor. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-ADOPTION (San Francisco) _ In a case an adoption expert
calls rare and dangerous, a California woman is accused of giving
her 10-year-old son to a stranger, a Florida man who had expressed
interest in adopting a boy in an Internet chat room. By DEMIAN
BULWA.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NY-SENATE (Albany, N.Y.) _ State Democrats rolled out their
third soft-money ad of the U.S. Senate campaign a new poll shows
Hillary Rodham Clinton and Rick Lazio remained deadlocked. The
campaign for Lazio, the four-term GOP congressman from Long Island,
predicted the ad war would ``backfire'' by failing to persuade
voters to support the Democratic First Lady. By LARA JAKES.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT(``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-SURVIVORS-CONTESTANTS (San Francisco) _ They came bearing
tales of eating insects, hunting lizards and diving in caves.
Others boasted of being natural leaders, black belts and mediators.
Someone ate a live goldfish. They are among the 100 people who
applied to become a ``Survivor,'' as in the CBS reality show that
pits strangers against each other in remote places. By RYAN KIM.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ROSEMARY (Albany, N.Y.) _ The soft, blue flowers of rosemary can
be used in punches, in salads or as garnish. The needlelike leaves
are flavorful in a variety of dishes, and the stems, stripped of
their leaves, can be used as skewers. This versatile herb also is
known for its medicinal traits, such as helping digestion. By LISA
STEVENS.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t' category)
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRALIA-REEF (Agincourt Reef, Australia) _ Cutting across the
Coral Sea aboard the sleek Quicksilver VIII catamaran, there is
little hint of the intrigue and grandeur hiding beneath the
surface. Then, soaring above the waves in a helicopter based at a
pontoon 90 minutes out from Port Douglas, a first clue: more shades
of blue than you ever imagined existed. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   With: AUSTRALIA-TIPS
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRALIA-RAIN-FOREST (Daintree River, Australia) _ Daintree
National Park is an area ``where the rain forest meets the reef.''
The area includes nearly 300 bird species, including the rare and
threatened 6-foot flightless Southern cassowary, as well as
marvelous multicolored butterflies, exotic flying foxes,
tree-hugging kangaroos and enough snakes to elicit shivers from
even the most ardent outdoorsman. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRALIA-TREEHOUSE (Port Douglas, Australia) _ In a land where
nature reigns supreme, what better way to spend the night than in a
treehouse? Especially when the treehouse and its surroundings are
the height of comfort. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRALIA-BIRDS (Port Douglas, Australia) _ Pause almost
anywhere in northern Queensland and, if you are patient, richly
decorated native birds will come your way. Near dusk, the
appropriately named rainbow lorikeet flaunts its colors even in
downtown Port Douglas. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRALIA-TROPICS (Cairns, Australia) _ It's your last day in
Tropical North Queensland, and there is so much yet to see and do:
a mountain railway; a butterfly sanctuary; an aerial tramway high
above the rain forest; an Aboriginal cultural center. What to do?
Everything, of course. Tour companies will combine all four
elements into a convenient package. Or you can take off on your
own. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-OFF-ROAD (Unated) _ Extreme rock crawling is the epitome of
off-road driving, something most four-wheelers can only dream
about. It takes special vehicles _ as well as special tires _ to
negotiate the courses that have been chosen for this four-wheeling
sport, and, unlike many sports, the courses are all natural. By G.
CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   FLY-FISHERMAN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Unlike other legends of fly
fishing in this state _ Lee Wulff, Harry Darbee, Walt Dette and
Fran Betters, to name a few _ Lloyd Bull was never one to court the
limelight. Consequently, like the river he's fished for more than a
half-century, Lloyd has kept a low profile and kept relatively
obscure considering the high level of his expertise, the company
he's traveled in, and his innovations and accomplishments. By FRED
LeBRUN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HINES-COLUMN (Washington) _ Think Trojan horse, the sack of
Rome, Maginot Line. As President Clinton ponders his next move on
the proposed national missile defense, he could profit from
considering Barbara Tuchman's book ``The March of Folly'' more
closely than the increasingly dubious data, analyses and excuses
from the Defense Department. This is no more so than a cockamamie
missile system that could end up costing Americans plenty of money.
By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Last week, the Colorado Board of
Education board approved a resolution that urges schools to display
the official motto of the United States of America: ``In God We
Trust.'' Here's a better idea: Completely wrap each school, from
roof to ground level, in ``In God We Trust,'' the way we now wrap
public buses in dot-com and Pepsi ads. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
