<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 11:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0909 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN16-CO     07-13 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Dealing with political protest
 &HT;    For release July 16, 2000.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps the networks have erred in shaving their coverage time
of the national political conventions this summer. There appears to
be a growing foreboding of protests and demonstrations that might
rival the ratings-high World Wrestling Federation TV performances.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia police have announced that the worst protesters
arrested at the Republican National Convention beginning July 31
will be sent for detention and processing to what is described as
the ``dungeon-like'' Holmesburg prison in Northeast Philadelphia.
It is a 99-year-old maximum security prison closed in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   I do not believe any announcement has been made regarding the
Democratic National Convention when it plays Los Angeles in August,
but sending unruly protesters to a Los Angeles Clippers basketball
game might be an equivalent
</P>
<P>
   All the gloom about this year's political conventions appears to
be evaporating. The party hacks still will be hacking away, but the
folks in the streets are promising to make things interesting. And
the cops are indicating they've got corresponding plans.
</P>
<P>
   There are ways of dealing with protesters and there are ways of
dealing with protesters.
</P>
<P>
   I like the way the late Miami Beach Police Chief Rocky Pomerance
handled matters at Republican conventions held there in 1968 and
1972. A burly, gregarious 300-pounder, Rocky let it be known that
he had a plan if any groups began marching on Miami Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Since all but two of the bridges leading to Miami Beach were
drawbridges, he said he would raise them to seal off the island.
</P>
<P>
   Another of his plans was to put unruly protesters on a bus,
drive them out to Andytown on the bug-infested edges of the Florida
Everglades and let them out, thus effectively removing them from
anywhere near the site of the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually that was kind of a psychological ploy, it was not a
plan at all,'' Pomerance admitted years later. (And quite possibly,
announcement of detention at Holmesburg also is a psychological
ploy.)
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Rocky's ploys weren't needed in 1968. The
convention that nominated Richard Nixon and Spiro Agnew was
relatively calm. It was the Democratic convention in Chicago
several weeks later that ran out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Rocky had another challenge in 1972, and it wasn't as well met.
Groups such as Yippies and Zippies, even Nazis and KKKers as well
as Vietnam veterans and Cuban exiles marching against communism
descended on Miami Beach for the Republican convention.
</P>
<P>
   Things got out of control when protesters began puncturing
delegate bus tires and physically confronting the delegates
themselves. Tear gas was chokingly plentiful and 800 were arrested
in a single night. There also was clubbing, but Pomerance _ to his
dying day _ insisted his police department clubbed no one. (There
were other agencies on the scene, including the Florida Highway
Patrol, a member of which created an opening for a cluster of
stitches in the head of one of the press photographers.)
</P>
<P>
   Through that unpleasant period, Pomerance nevertheless created a
moment of humor. In a pre-convention meeting with anti-war,
absurd-theater potentates Jerry Rubin and Abbie Hoffman, they
threatened to lead 10,000 naked protesters down Miami Beach's main
street, then over to the convention hall.
</P>
<P>
   According to Pomerance, he turned to Rubin and responded, ``If
you can get 10,000 people to walk naked down the asphalt on a hot
(August) day, I'll lead the parade.''
</P>
<P>
   The march never took place.
</P>
<P>
   A little creativity: Maybe that's what the Philly police need to
beguile potential protesters instead of packing them off to the old
dungeon-like joint. Put the baddest of the bad on a bus to, say,
Scranton (sorry, Scranton) or have them spend the winter at Valley
Forge as George Washington's troops (sorry, George).
</P>
<P>
   Even suggest a parade in the emperor's new clothes.
</P>
<P>
   That would give those TV cameras something to zoom in on _ and
restore the long-lost Nielson numbers for political conventions.
Anything might be better than listening to those drones at the
political podium.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
