<DOCNO> NYT20000713.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 12:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0930 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CHINA-IVILLAGE-$ADV17     07-13 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-IVILLAGE-$ADV17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INTERNET BECOMES WINDOW TO WORLD, BOON TO BUSINESS FOR RURAL
CHINESE VILLAGE
 &HT;    (850&AMP;ADDS)
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    EDs: For purposes of a locater map, Sangpocun is an hour outside
of Luoyang, which is about 425 miles south of Beijing.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    For Use Mon., July 17 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By JULIE CHAO 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANGPO VILLAGE, China _ Ding Yufeng is a fifth-grade dropout.
That does not make him unusual in this booming village in central
China.
</P>
<P>
   He is also a regular user of e-mail and the World Wide Web.
That, too, is not unusual here in Sangpo Village.
</P>
<P>
   Once a ``poor, backwards, uneducated'' speck in Henan province,
in the words of one local official, Sangpo is now a wired outpost.
Its 4,800 residents boast private cars, cellular phones, about 100
personal computers and a bustling Internet cafe.
</P>
<P>
   But Sangpo Village didn't get rich growing wheat and corn, which
is how most of surrounding Mengzhou County makes a living. Having
very little land, village leaders realized long ago the road to
wealth lay in private enterprise, not agriculture. So it decided to
capitalize on a traditional handicraft of its Muslim population _
sheepskin processing.
</P>
<P>
   In 20 years, the village has grown these backyard businesses
into a multi-million dollar niche market. It now processes 5
million sheepskins a year, almost half of China's total sheepskin
imports. Most come from Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Just outside Sangpo, the green fields along the side of the road
suddenly give way to row after row of short wooden tents, each with
a sheepskin on top laid out to dry. The streets inside the village
are also lined with drying sheepskins. Sangpo proudly calls itself
China's ``Fur City.''
</P>
<P>
   The finished products are exported to Turkey and Italy as
leather for shoes and handbags, to Russia as blankets and to the
United States as sheepskin carseat covers. The arrival of the
Internet two years ago has not only been a boon to business, it has
allowed bored youngsters a window to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet has shortened our distance with the rest of the
world,'' said Bai Huzhan, Sangpo's Communist vice-party secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Sangpo is an anomaly in China or a sign of things to
come remains to be seen. Some rural areas have started using the
Internet to post pricing and market information for farmers, but
the digital divide between rich and poor is still enormous, and
growing wider.
</P>
<P>
   More than 10 million people have gone on-line in this country of
1.25 billion, according to the latest official estimates. But less
than 1 percent of the population even has Internet access, as users
are heavily concentrated in the big cities.
</P>
<P>
   For now, officials in Mengzhou County _ where Sangpo Village
resides _ are happy for the tax revenue and jobs the village has
provided, but have yet to make any great efforts to wire the rest
of the county.
</P>
<P>
   Only 60 percent of households in Mengzhou County have
telephones. The largest town in the county has a couple of Internet
cafes, but few people can afford the fee of 3 yuan (US36 cents) an
hour.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the Sangpo Internet cafe, which charges 4 yuan
(US48 cents) an hour, is packed in the evenings, and home telephone
penetration is closer to 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Technology came quickly to Sangpo. In 1993, the only phone in
the village was at the government building. By 1994, it had 2,000
lines and today, it has more than 6,000. By 1998, Internet access
seemed like the natural next step. So village leaders convinced the
county to set up a computer training center.
</P>
<P>
   In Ding's home alone, there are five phone lines. Two of them
are dedicated to personal computers, which he says are in use at
least 12 hours a day _ if not 24 _ by the extended family of more
than 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two computers is not enough for the family,'' said his father,
Ding Cunzheng, who runs the family sheepskin processing business,
White Dragon Fur Factory.
</P>
<P>
   For years, White Dragon was a small enterprise making leather
jackets. But then the younger Ding, 23, discovered computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have any hobbies. I just fooled around and wasted my
time,'' says Ding, sitting in the factory office where he seems
oblivious to the clinging smell of animal hides. ``But when I
started learning computers, I found I could work at it all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon he was using search engines to find sheepskin suppliers and
eventually sent e-mails to hundreds of them introducing his
father's factory. He got few replies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our factory is too small,'' Ding said.
</P>
<P>
   But one business in Australia, where sheep outnumber humans, was
also small and looking for someone to buy its sheepskins. Before
long, another Internet match was made.
</P>
<P>
   White Dragon was able to cut out its middlemen and buy raw
materials directly from the Australian supplier. Its business
increased more than three-fold, and it now employs more than 40
workers, mostly from Shandong province.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   If anything, this is perhaps the dirty secret of Sangpo's
success. Cleaning, combing, cutting sheepskins is filthy work. It's
no work for rich villagers, especially those with two private cars
and 13 cell phones, as the Ding family has.
</P>
<P>
   Although the official population of the village is under 5,000,
the actual number of residents is closer to 11,000. The difference
being the laborers who've come from other towns and provinces for
jobs. They live in factory dorms and get paid by the piece, showing
that even Chinese villages take advantage of cheap Chinese labor.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   The prosperity of the village has made its residents rather
lazy, laments Bai, the vice-party secretary. Money came easily, and
loftier goals were viewed as unimportant.
</P>
<P>
   ``When villagers had nothing to do they would play mah-jong,''
he said. ``Kids wouldn't study; they'd just go out and spend
money.''
</P>
<P>
   But the arrival of the information superhighway made people
realize they needed to learn to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know if they don't study, they won't be able to grasp new
technology,'' Bai said.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Like many young people in Sangpo, Zhang Juan(CQ), 19, says her
favorite Web activity is chatting with her Net buddies from all
over the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the Web, I can see the outside world,'' Zhang said. ``We
chat about everything. If someone has something on their mind, they
can talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Her first time in a chatroom was nerve-wracking.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I was embarrassed to say I was from a village,'' she
says, taking a moment from a chat session in the Sangpo Internet
cafe.
</P>
<P>
   But she quickly gained confidence and made friends. Only
recently, she encountered a person from Hangzhou, a big city near
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   ``The person said, 'Well I have nothing to say to you, you live
in an isolated little village,''' she said. ``So I said, 'We're
much more developed here than where you are.'''
</P>
<P>
   (Julie Chao's E-mail address is: juliec(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://nong.net/default1.asp: Set up by China's Academy of
Agricultural Sciences and other companies as a comprehensive guide
to agricultural products and policies.
</P>
<P>
   www.junren.com/index.htm: Jiaozuo Junren Leather Co., one of
Sangpo's biggest factories.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
