<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors at publications outside the United States may find the
following stories from the New York Times News Service for  &UR; FRIDAY,
July 14, &LR;  of particular interest:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' news category)
</P>
<P>
   SRI-LANKA-CHILDSOLDIERS (United Nations) _ A rare inside look at
how Tamil rebels in Sri Lanka recruit children and use them as
soldiers has emerged in a report by a group of Tamil university
teachers in Sri Lanka _ some of whose members have been
assassinated. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S. (Beijing) _ The U.S. defense secretary and Chinese
leaders made hopeful pledges of cooperation and friendship Thursday
despite evidence of deep rifts over key military policies and dark
Chinese suspicions about U.S. intentions in Asia. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   (An early version of this story will move by 3 p.m. EDT.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Washington) _ Developments in the peace talks at
Camp David. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-BANKS (Mexico City) _ Developments in the bank-bailout
scandal. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BRIEFS (Undated) _ World news in brief.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNITED STATES &LR;  _ General
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-NAACP (Baltimore) _ President Clinton is scheduled
Thursday to address the convention of the National Association for
the Advancement of Colored People. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA-POLICE (Philadelphia) _ A news helicopter
videotaped the beating and kicking of a wounded black man after a
car chase and shootout with police. The taped confrontation,
broadcast around the nation, comes at the worst possible time for
the police department on the eve of the Democratic National
Convention. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   IND-BABY-ELEPHANT (Indianapolis) _ Indianapolis had a scientific
breakthrough in March with the birth of Amali, the first African
elephant in the world born after artificial insemination. And to
prove the pregnancy was not a fluke, another African elephant, also
impregnated artificially, is due to give birth next month. By Carl
H. Lavin.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-DRUG-TRIAL (New York) _ Sentencing is scheduled
Thursday for the U.S. Army officer who once oversaw the
government's antidrug wars in Colombia and who pleaded guilty to
failing to report that he knew that his wife had been laundering
the profits of her drug smuggling. By Alan Feuer.
</P>
<P>
   NY-TAXIS-CREDITCARDS (New York) _ Taxi riders in New York will
soon be able to pay by credit card. By Edward Wong.
</P>
<P>
   NY-TRIBE-LAND (Southampton, N.Y.) _ A group of young people from
the Shinnecock tribe are now talking aggressively about seeking
claim to the 3,600 acres of prime Southampton real estate that
includes three golf courses _ including the renowned Shinnecock
Hills that will host the U.S. Open in 2004 _ and the Southampton
campus of Long Island University. By Charlie LeDuff.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-INFANTS (Durban, South Africa) _ Infants born to women
who received an anti-AIDS drug at delivery receive some protection
against HIV and the protection persists for up to a year,
scientists report here. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNITED STATES &LR;  _ Washington
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `w' category)
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The House will vote Thursday on
the Foreign Operations Bill, which contains language that restricts
family planning organizations from performing abortions or lobbying
abortion issues overseas. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `f' news category)
</P>
<P>
   WORLDCOM-SPRINT (Undated) _ Sprint and WorldCom, two of the
United State's largest long-distance carriers, called off merger
plans Thursday and opened the gates for takeover overtures by both
foreign and domestic telecommunications giants. Deutsche Telekom of
Germany, Europe's largest telephone company, has been mentioned as
the main party interested in Sprint. Other potential suitors are
Nippon Telegraph and Telephone of Japan and BellSouth of Atlanta.
By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   (An early version of this story, by Daniel J. Wakin, will move
by 3 p.m. EDT.)
</P>
<P>
   AIRBUS-NEW-JET (Toulouse, France) _ Airbus Industrie is getting
closer to production of a gigantic double-decker jumbo jet, known
as the A3XX, for use on long distance routes like those between
Asia and Europe or the United States. There are a number of
obstacles, and it is not clear whether Airbus can get enough orders
to make the project ultimately profitable. But the potential
rewards are huge. For one, the A3XX would challenge the long,
lucrative dominance of Boeing's 747. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   DIAGEO-GENERAL-MILLS (Undated) _ Diageo, the British food and
liquor giant, and General Mills, the No.2 maker of cereals in the
U.S., confirm that they are in talks over a possible merger of
Diageo's Pillsbury food unit with General Mills. By Andrew Ross
Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-SOGO (Tokyo) _ On the aftermath of the Sogo department
store company's financial collapse with debts in excess of $17
billion. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `e' news category or as indicated)
</P>
<P>
   BROTHERS-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ None of the five senses
feels safe from assault in the Maly Theater's robust two-part
production of ``Brothers and Sisters,'' adapted from a trilogy
known as ``The Prysalins,'' by the Russian novelist Fyodor Abramov,
and part of the Lincoln Center Summer Festival 2000. By Ben
Brantley.
</P>
<P>
   YORUBA-AMERICAS-ART (New York) _ ``Beads, Body and Soul: Art and
Light in the Yoruba Universe,'' at the Museum for African Art in
SoHo and the Studio Museum in Harlem, is as opulent as it is
edifying, and follows the migration of one people's beading
tradition _ and the religious beliefs it reflects _ from Africa to
various parts of the Americas. By Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   CARRACCI-BAROQUE-ART (New York) _ Over the past 30 years, the
Metropolitan Museum has assembled a splendid collection of work by
the Carracci: four paintings _ three acquired in the last six years
_ 17 drawings and a slew of prints. A selection from these holdings
is on display in ``The Birth of Baroque: Carracci at the
Metropolitan.'' By Grace Glueck.
</P>
<P>
   NY-KRUGER-RETROSPECTIVE (New York) _ Barbara Kruger's
retrospective, which has landed at the Whitney from the Museum of
Contemporary Art in Los Angeles, represents a career whose concerns
were fixed in the 1970s and early '80s, along with the arguments
about it. By Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   NABOKOV-BUTTERFLY-SEARCH (Undated) _ While Vladimir Nabokov was
writing in the 1940s, he also studied the anatomy of butterflies at
the Museum of Comparative Zoology at Harvard. On June 2, 1950, he
visited the Pine Bush in upstate New York for the first time to
look for Karner blues, a butterfly that he had identified and name
from old specimens but had never seen in the wild. Fifty years
later _ to the day _ we followed in his footsteps. By Margaret
Mittelbach and Michael Crewdson.
</P>
