<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVOLUTION IN THE INTERNET CHAT ROOM 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   If you're having trouble finding
stimulating, intellectual conversation in Internet ``chat rooms,''
it could be because you're talking to a chimp.
<TEXT>
<P>
   At least that's the theory postulated by Weekly World News, the
New York Times of supermarket tabloids. (Motto: All the Bigfoot
news that's fit to print.)
</P>
<P>
   I personally try to stay away from Internet chat rooms because
my brain cells are winking out fast enough without them. Spend five
minutes in one of these rooms and you may lose the ability to spell
or form complete sentences, which may account for their appeal with
young people.
</P>
<P>
   What follows is a brief but verbatim transcript _ with the names
changed _ of the typed conversation that took place in an America
Online chat room early last week. The subject was Britney Spears,
who is a pop singer or perhaps a new doll from Mattel; it was
impossible to tell from the conversation:
</P>
<P>
   AngieJo1222: yo yo what up?
</P>
<P>
   RYC33: nothin
</P>
<P>
   Americagrrl09: what are yall up 2
</P>
<P>
   BassNoFool88: Wazup
</P>
<P>
   TicsNTacs667: Britney Spears is FKAE, cheap and plastic
</P>
<P>
   AngieJo1222: ?
</P>
<P>
   Americagrrl09: nothin
</P>
<P>
   AngieJo1222: me i dumo?
</P>
<P>
   Casey91121: boys are dumb
</P>
<P>
   AngieJo1222: im a cheerleader
</P>
<P>
   I do not mean to single these people out. You will find
conversations operating on the same protozoan level in just about
any chat room you care to visit. The only difference is that the
one I chose to quote is less obscene than most.
</P>
<P>
   But back to the chimps. According to Weekly World News, animal
experts in the United States, Canada and Europe have been working
with chimpanzees and have taught them how to distinguish words on a
computer screen and type in short responses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internet expert'' George Leriger said the chimps can't type
long, complex sentences but they can respond with yes, no and other
simple phrases.
</P>
<P>
   Leriger does not say so specifically, but I would have to think
the list of ``other simple phrases'' would include ``wazup?'' ``me
i dumo'' and ``im a cheerleader.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which adds a whole new dynamic to the Internet chat
scene, particularly for people seeking romantic encounters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems impossible that `yes' and `no' responses and an
occasional show of affection could be enough to make a person on
the other end of he computer think they've found a love interest,''
Leriger said. ``But we have looked at transcripts from the chimps'
computers and it's clear that has happened quite a few times.''
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I don't see anything wrong with this. If young
people want to chat with a chimp on the Internet, that's fine with
me. It's probably more intellectually stimulating than other things
they could be doing, such as watching TV or listening to their CDs.
</P>
<P>
   What effect this is having on the chimps, on the other hand, is
hard to say. Some people might consider it cruel to put a chimp in
a chat room with a bunch of hormonally gorged 14-year-olds, but I
would presume the chimp would have enough sense to log off if
things got too weird.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, you never know. Some cheerleaders can be pretty cute.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
