<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEVER, NEVER TAKE APART YOUR OWN PROJECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wait'll the garage is built. Then we'll have room enough to
store a century of packrat stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe, but isn't there a law out there that says, if there
is space available, it will be overfilled, instantly?
</P>
<P>
   At least the garage is coming soon, with room even for the car,
and to store all the stuff that was taken out of the toolhouse that
had to be torn down to make way for the garage.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, all that stuff is now flooding the basement, the
house, and the yard. We are not hoping for rain.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the toolhouse had to go. It was a nice building that I
built in August 1972, during the Fischer-Spaasky chess match.
</P>
<P>
   My wife called it the toolhouse of the August moon. That was
nice, and it could have been called Walden because it was the exact
size and shape as Thoreau's famous hut at Walden Pond.
</P>
<P>
   It would have cost $500 to tear down and haul away. (Thoreau's
hut was, what, $6.98? As I contemplated that with tears rolling
down my cheeks, John, my son-in-law, came up with a brilliant idea:
Why not take it down and put it up somewhere else in the yard?
It'll be a piece of cake for the handyman, and save a buck, too.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the toolhouse was taken apart and is in pieces in the
yard, ready for reassembly.
</P>
<P>
   But it was no piece of cake. And here is the lesson for today:
Never, never take apart something that you put together. Being an
amateur, you will have overbuilt it, using half again as many
nails, using galvanized nails where they were not necessary (they
hold like crazy, and are equally difficult to pull), and glopping
up the roof with way too much roof cement.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing wrong with all this overbuilding, except when
you take it down. Misery, misery. Roofing cement is great stuff;
once applied, it never comes off. Well, hardly ever.
</P>
<P>
   First, the roof had to go. One does not save asphalt roofing
shingles, but we did save the sheathing plywood and rafters. All
with the help of David, my husky son. It could not have been done
without him.
</P>
<P>
   If you ever watched a crew scraping off roof shingles, you can
understand the problem. It is hard work, but with a certain amount
of luck and a lot of elbow grease, they come off in great sections,
not individually.
</P>
<P>
   Usually you can use a square-bladed shovel to rip off the
shingles. I found the perfect tool for this. It is called the MUTT,
which stands for Mighty Useful Tough Tool. It looks like a
long-handled ice cutter, but with a much heavier blade, and a sharp
one, too. It is no longer sharp, but it served well to rip off
those shingles, hitting a few dozen nails in the effort. It will
also handle ice, tiles, and roots with aplomb, with a strong back
behind it.
</P>
<P>
   It may be available in lumber stores.It was made by Dick Davis
of Pasadena, Calif., but a number I had listed for him has been
disconnected. Alas.
</P>
<P>
   Other useful tools in our project (and they are readily
available) were a flatbar (a short, wide, flat prying tool), a
ripping hammer, one or more pinch bars, (a 2-foot prying tool with
a wedge at one end and a hook at the other).
</P>
<P>
   And, a really heavy crowbar. Get one that weighs maybe 20 pounds
or more (about the weight of a Civil War musket). About 6 feet
long, it makes a great prying tool as well as a sledgehammer of
sorts. You can really batter off plywood sheets with this, without
wrecking the plywood.
</P>
<P>
   Getting everything down to the four walls was easy. Separating
the walls was not. The plan was to leave the walls with the
sheathing and shingles intact, and move them elsewhere for
reassembly someday. Finally, they were separated.
</P>
<P>
   We sort of thought that the walls, just 10 to 12 feet long and 6
feet high, would be heavy, but wow, not that heavy. Whew.
</P>
<P>
   But somehow, with one end on a wheelbarrow and the other in the
strong, capable hands of David, we pushed and grunted all four
walls, one at a time, to the new site, awaiting reassembly.
</P>
<P>
   All right, bring on the garage makers!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
