<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0992 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-BORDERS-COLUMN0714-CO     07-13 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN0714-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Here's some advice: Never bet on relatives in a horse race
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSSIER CITY, La. _ My cousins are having a rough day on the
ponies. I keep laying money on their nags to no avail, so that by
the seventh race I'm down $185.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know if the Bourque brothers, Coby and Cody, are really
my cousins, though they share my mother's maiden name. (Actually, I
don't know for sure if they're even brothers, though the odds are
good given the similarity of their first names and the fact they're
both riding horses here in Louisiana.) If kin, they're the Cajun
branch of the family, descendants of the group that had the good
sense to migrate south from Canada. My mother's side of the family
left Canada also but only made it as far as New Hampshire and
Massachusetts. My mother has lived in East Texas for more than 30
years but still considers herself a Yankee here only temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I like to think of these two jockeys riding the nags in
the July Louisiana sun as shirt-tail kin and given that Bourque
(pronounced Burke up north and Bork in Louisiana) isn't a terribly
common name, there's the possibility. My mother firmly believes
that anyone even mildly famous with this surname is related,
including an NHL player and other minor luminaries.
</P>
<P>
   There is a physical resemblance in that all Bourques are
potential jockey material, myself included _ if I shrunk about 3
inches and lost 50 pounds. I had a great-uncle named Alexander who
was a midget and ran a bicycle shop in Canada, or so the story
goes. My 93-year-old grandmother was four-feet-11 before old age
stooped her, and now she's about the length of a Big Bertha driver.
</P>
<P>
   My wife has gone off with her daughter deep into Arcadia for a
beauty pageant, so I talk a couple of friends into heading to
Louisiana Downs to donate some money to the Edwin Edwards defense
fund. We are lucky enough to be seated next to an acquaintance of
my friends, who hails from Timpson, owns racehorses and has three
racing today. Jerry Bob Nix and his wife, Kay, are congenial table
neighbors and graciously take us down to tour the winner's circle
before his first race. They introduce us to their trainer and to
the jockey _ not one of the Bourques _ who is riding their horses
today.
</P>
<P>
   We stand in the winner's circle as that race's entries come
strolling by, magnificent beasts prancing nervously. I stand well
back so as not to cause a stampede with a false move.
</P>
<P>
   The jockey is, well, a small fellow, friendly and mud-spattered.
I also get to shake hands with the guy who plays the bugle to call
horses to the gate, which I've always thought is a way-cool job.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Bob's first horse is named Alkahaulit. Sound it out. One
of this horse's relatives was named Beer Belly Bob. I'm not making
this up.
</P>
<P>
   This is Alkahaulit's first race, and he's a 35-1 longshot. Jerry
Bob gives the jockey some advice, which mainly consists of making
sure the horse heads out the gate in the right direction and
doesn't get hurt. I go in to make a bet, and the owner gives me
some advice: ``I wouldn't be betting real heavily on that one. It's
his first race, and there's no telling what he'll do.''
</P>
<P>
   I heed the advice and put a modest $6 on Alkahaulit across the
board, meaning if he finishes in the top three I'm in the money. He
finishes next-to-last, but Jerry Bob is satisfied, says the horse
will win a race before the season is over. I have no reason to
dispute this.
</P>
<P>
   His second horse is a near-favorite, and I put a 10-spot on him.
He takes the lead heading into the stretch but fades and ends up
third, which pays a modest profit.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Bourques are killing me in the other races. I bet
a trifecta and forget to box it. (Horse lingo: A trifecta is when
you predict the top three finishers. You can pay extra and box it,
which means it doesn't matter what order they finish in, as long as
you've picked the right three horses.) I picked the right three
horses, but not in the right order. Near as I could figure, this
mental error meant I lost out on winning about $400 on one race.
</P>
<P>
   Finally I give up on the cousins. Blood may be thicker than
water, but this was getting expensive. l start betting randomly,
making my picks on the color of the horses, their names and other
random trivia. On the eighth race I hit a longshot exacta (picking
the top two finishers) and win $217 on a $10 bet. I lose a bit more
in the last two races but walk out just a sawbuck or so lighter
than when I walked in.
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad price to pay for meeting a real-live horse owner, a
jockey and the bugle player all in one day.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. E-mail: gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
