</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATALYTIC-CONVERTERS0714-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    50 ways to kill your catalytic converter
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Do you ever get a song in your head that plays over
and over until you think it's going to drive you nuts? This week's
miscellaneous unscheduled manufacturers maintenance item, or MUMMI,
has been rattling around in my brain with a slightly different
twist to the words.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got your dead skunk in the middle of the road ... stinkin'
to high heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Only instead if ``skunk'' I've been thinking ``cat.'' I'm not
talking about our feline friends, I'm thinking about a catalytic
converter, known in the industry as a cat.
</P>
<P>
   Automotive cats don't stink when they die, but they can emit an
odor that will rival the rottenest egg before their demise. Not all
cats will produce this sulfurous warning symptom.
</P>
<P>
   There are almost as many ways to kill a cat as Paul Simon's ``50
Ways to Leave Your Lover.'' Oh good, now I can start thinking of a
new song.
</P>
<P>
   Catalytic converters began establishing their dubious reputation
from the moment they made their debut on most passenger vehicles in
the mid-1970s. The American motoring public, seduced by the '60s
muscle-car mentality of bigger and faster, was not prepared to pay
the price for Detroit's years of decadence.
</P>
<P>
   Vehicle manufacturers scrambled for ways to make their engines
pollute less. Engine performance was sacrificed to many of these
infant pollution control devices, which were countered with
widespread disabling or destruction of those components.
</P>
<P>
   The catalytic converter _ an unobtrusive mufflerlike gizmo _
usually remained intact until its overwhelming noxious odor and
floor-mat-melting, grass-fire starting qualities elevated it to the
most hated smog parts list.
</P>
<P>
   Although today's cats seldom melt carpets or start fires, their
reputation stays with them. Consequently, they have been misused,
abused or, at best, ignored, only getting attention when either the
vehicle won't get out of its own way or it fails an emissions test.
Unfortunately, many cats are simply replaced without regard to the
reason they failed in the first place. They rarely die of their own
accord. Something kills them.
</P>
<P>
   The inside of a catalytic converter is a delicate network of
honeycomb passages coated with a thin plating of platinum and
palladium to reduce hydrocarbons and carbon monoxide emissions and
rhodium to reduce nitrous oxides. The total surface ``exhaust gas
contact'' area supposedly is about the size of three football
fields, give or take a few feet.
</P>
<P>
   When a properly running engine's exhaust passes through the cat,
a chemical reaction occurs, and almost all of the exhaust emissions
are converted to harmless carbon dioxide and water. If the engine
is malfunctioning or the ``service engine soon'' light is on, cat
murder is being committed.
</P>
<P>
   One of the top ways to kill your cat is with poison. In the old
days, leaded fuel was the leading cat poison, but that is not an
issue anymore unless you drive your vehicle in a foreign country
that still uses lead in gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   Other cat (and oxygen sensor) poisons are silicone and engine
oil. Silicone is a lubricant used in antifreeze and some aerosol
sprays and can also be found in some ``form-a-gasket'' products.
</P>
<P>
   It can be introduced into the exhaust system several ways. The
most common is an internal coolant leak, usually resulting from
damage done to an overheated engine, including a ``blown'' head
gasket, cracked head or block. Silicone lubricant spray and gasket
goo fumes are sucked into the engine via the air intake.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
