<DOCNO> NYT20000713.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0994 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN0714-CO     07-13 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN0714-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A challenge in Dallas
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Rosa Meraz de Montoya, stuffing envelopes in an East
Dallas campaign office, cares about the 5th District congressional
election more than the average volunteer. She wants her only
daughter to go to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's my princess,'' said Montoya, who also has three boys.
</P>
<P>
   Dallasite Regina Montoya Coggins, 46, a graduate of Wellesley
and Harvard Law School, is running a surprisingly well-financed
campaign to unseat two-term Republican Pete Sessions.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of two Texas seats Democrats hope to recapture this
year. The other is the 14th District, stretching from Austin to the
Gulf Coast, where Loy Sneary of Bay City is trying again to unseat
Republican Ron Paul of Surfside.
</P>
<P>
   The 5th includes normally Republican-leaning Lake Highlands in
Dallas County and stretches south and east through
Democratic-leaning territory 180 miles to Bryan.
</P>
<P>
   While Sessions enjoyed a large lead in name identification in
May, it is too soon to predict what will happen on Election Day,
after each candidate has spent close to $1 million on TV and direct
mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the 5th is an extraordinary opportunity for us,''
said Democrat Martin Frost, who has represented the adjoining 24th
District for 11 terms. If the Democrats shift just six seats,
they'll regain control of the U.S. House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Montoya Coggins ``is running a very good campaign,'' Frost said.
The wife of U.S. Attorney Paul Coggins has already raised more than
$1 million and is still bringing it in.
</P>
<P>
   Sessions, 45, a Waco native with a degree from Southwestern
University, is the son of former FBI director and current federal
Judge William Sessions. His brief record is one of the most
conservative in the House.
</P>
<P>
   After 16 years with Southwestern Bell, Sessions quit to run
against 12-year incumbent John Bryant in 1994. Sessions lost, with
47 percent. But when Bryant ran for the U.S. Senate in 1996,
Sessions got 53 percent against Democrat John Pouland.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Sessions received almost 56 percent while outspending
Victor Morales, who was also the 1996 Democratic nominee for the
U.S. Senate, by a 7-1 ratio. Democrats John Sharp for lieutenant
governor and Paul Hobby for comptroller narrowly carried the
district in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Montoya Coggins is well-connected. She has been on corporate
boards, the board of the Dallas Chamber of Commerce, a partner in
the politically connected Akin, Gump law firm, and has a long
string of civic activities, including a recent stint as national
president of Girls Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at a list of people supporting me, it is a who's
who of the business community,'' said Montoya Coggins, who also
served as Bill Clinton's director of the Office of
Intergovernmental Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   She says she's a moderate against a right-wing Republican who
voted ``yes'' on overriding President Clinton's veto of so-called
partial-birth abortions and ``no'' on things such as spending
federal money for after-school programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pete Sessions is out of touch with his district,'' says
Montoya Coggins, who supports abortion rights and lists education
and a prescription-drug payment program under Medicare as principal
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Sessions' campaign manager, businessman Gary Griffith, concedes
Montoya Coggins has shown powerful fund-raising ability. But
Sessions, a member of the money-attracting Banking and Financial
Services Committee, will be at least as well-financed, Griffith
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're actively engaged in organizing for a campaign this
fall,'' Griffith said, ``and I think Pete Sessions is taking this
race as seriously as any he's ever run.''
</P>
<P>
   Pouland says Montoya Coggins will enjoy a 20-year base in Lake
Highlands that he didn't have.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she gets 35 percent there, she'll win,'' Pouland said. ``I
think she'll win the race by about 2 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
