<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0996 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-ROAD-MANNERS0714-COX     07-13 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROAD-MANNERS0714-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Better manners might come in blink of a light
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One of my greatest pleasures is driving an automobile.
For some people, it's golf, for others it's tennis, but for me, a
great vehicle and the open road say it all. Ah, the open road.
Around here, that is only a fading memory.
</P>
<P>
   I hate Atlanta traffic and the ever-increasing congestion, but I
can live with it. The thing that drives me to distraction is the
decline in driving skills on our roadways. There seem to be no
rules, no regulations and a total lack of courtesy on the part of
most drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps I am overly optimistic to expect any better, based on
the absence of realistic driving training. When is it going to dawn
on our society that next to violence, the No. 1 weapon of death is
a moving vehicle? If we can't enlist our civic leaders to address
the growing problem, it falls upon the rest of us to address it if
by no other means than our personal behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, I was traveling south on I-85. I was in the left lane,
but I was moving more quickly than the cars to my right. I also am
a driver who constantly watches her mirrors. Knowing what is behind
you as well as beside you is as important as knowing what is in
front of you.
</P>
<P>
   So you can imagine my shock when in my rearview mirror, I saw
what appeared to be the roof of a car behind me. Fifteen seconds
earlier, my backside was totally clear.
</P>
<P>
   I was driving my husband's compact truck, which has a low ride
level. The black roof of the vehicle in my mirror was as close as a
NASCAR racer in full draft mode.
</P>
<P>
   It was what I considered to be a completely unacceptable
situation. No, I didn't ``brake check'' the guy behind me. People
who do that are putting themselves in danger. But I didn't move
over. Why? Because the car behind me had already shown poor
judgment by his position, which made it a dangerous move for me to
change lanes.
</P>
<P>
   I had no idea what his next move might be. The safest thing to
do was to maintain my position until I was sure that I had ample
room to move to the right.
</P>
<P>
   I activated my turn signal and waited. A mile or so later, when
the driver finally dropped back enough for me to see the front of
his new black Corvette, I safely made my lane change.
</P>
<P>
   He sped past me only to draft the next vehicle he encountered.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing an opening in the traffic, the guy darted right across
five lanes of traffic in one swift maneuver at what appeared to be
a speed close to 100 mph.
</P>
<P>
   There must be a better way. Europeans have a much saner approach
to the passing dilemma. They simply blink their headlights.
Europeans don't take the blinking of headlights as a personal
assault; it is simply their automotive way of saying, ``Excuse me,
could I please get by?''
</P>
<P>
   As I see it, it would be a welcome addition to Atlanta drivers'
concept of Southern road hospitality.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
