<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMICS-MOVIES0714-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   How to keep the SUPER in superheroes
</P>
<P>
   By Dave Larsen and Randy Palmer
</P>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Movies based on comic books have produced some
super-duper box-office hits, but few have successfully translated
the often complex characters and intricate story lines of these
cartoon sagas to the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Given the troubling cinematic fates of such costumed
crime-fighters as ``Batman'' and ``Superman,'' comics fans are
holding their collective breath for today's opening of ``''X-Men.''
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from the top-selling Marvel series about genetic mutants
with superhuman powers, the highly anticipated film is directed by
Bryan Singer, whose credits include Oscar-winning indie ``The Usual
Suspects.'' The cast includes Patrick Stewart, Ian McKellen, Hugh
Jackman, Anna Paquin, James Marsden, Famke Janssen and Halle Berry.
</P>
<P>
   With a host of additional superhero adventures on the horizon,
including ``Spider-Man'' and ``The Fantastic Four,'' we offer a
dozen do's and don'ts of comic-book movies.
</P>
<P>
   DO start with a compelling story, such as ``''X-Men'''s
allegorical tale of mutant heroes. The genetically sup-
</P>
<P>
   erior outcasts have human flaws, and fight to protect a world
that fears and hates them.
</P>
<P>
   DON'T expect flashy visuals to compensate for a weak script. As
``Spawn'' creator Todd McFarlane told Entertainment Weekly
magazine: ``Though some of the special effects were nice, we could
have made some of the characters a little meatier instead of
relying on big explosions.''
</P>
<P>
   DO outfit your superheroes in sculpted leather and rubber
costumes, as in ``X-Men'' and ``''Batman.'' Grown men in brightly
colored Spandex doesn't play well on the big screen.
</P>
<P>
   DON'T put nipples on said leather and rubber costumes, as
director Joel Schumacher did with ``Batman &AMP; Robin.'' Save the
fetish wear for the privacy of the Batcave.
</P>
<P>
   DO justice to the material. ``Comic-book people tend to be
obsessed with respectability,'' Frank Miller said in Premiere
magazine. Miller's graphic novel, ``The Dark Knight Returns,''
influenced the bleak tone of Tim Burton's ``Batman,'' the best film
of the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``X-Men'' takes itself seriously, drawing parallels between
mutant persecution and the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   DON'T go camp, as Schumacher did with the pun-drenched ``Batman
&AMP; Robin.'' Superhero spoofs also have been box-office kryptonite.
``Mystery Men'' was funny, but it failed to find an audience.
``Blankman'' was a dud and ``The Meteor Man'' fizzled.
</P>
<P>
   DO establish a set of rules and adhere to them. ``X-Men''
defines each characters' powers and uses the limits of those
abilities to advance the story.
</P>
<P>
   DON'T alter the characters' powers to service the plot. When
Superman moves at the speed of light near the end of ``Superman
II,'' audiences shouldn't be asking why he didn't do that sooner.
</P>
<P>
   DO consider offbeat and lesser-known comics. ``Men in Black,''
based on an obscure Marvel title, grossed $250 million _ just $1
million shy of ``Batman'''s box-office take. Other such adaptations
include ``Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles,'' ``Mystery Men,'' ``The
Mask,'' ``Blade'' and ``The Crow.''
</P>
<P>
   DON'T assume that any character in a cape _ or other such
superhero apparel _ will leap to the top of the box-office chart.
``Tank Girl'' tanked. ``Howard the Duck'' laid a huge egg. ``The
Phantom'' didn't stand a ghost of a chance.
</P>
<P>
   DO hire an actor who can portray a superhero's inner conflict,
regardless of his or her physical relation to the comic book
character. Michael Keaton's ``Batman'' is a prime example, along
with ``X-Men'''s Hugh Jackman (Wolverine) and Anna Paquin (Rogue).
Intense but slightly built Tobey Maguire is director Sam Raimi's
top pick to play Peter Parker in his upcoming ``Spider-Man'' movie.
</P>
<P>
   DON'T hire muscle-bound thespians with limited range just
because they fill out the costume, as was the case with Dolph
Lundgren's ``The Punisher,'' Shaquille O'Neal's ``Steel'' and
Sylvester Stallone's ``Judge Dredd.''
</P>
<P>
   DO stay true to the characters, rather than allowing them to
become star vehicles. ``X-Men'''s little-known cast members blend
into their roles, enhancing the film's believability.
</P>
<P>
   DON'T tailor established roles to suit big stars hired for their
box-office appeal. Arnold Schwarzenegger spouted far too many of
his trademark one-liners as Mr. Freeze in ``Batman &AMP; Robin,''
earning a deserved cold-shoulder from audiences.
</P>
<P>
   DO have colorful, charismatic villains, such as Jack Nicholson's
Joker and Jim Carrey's Riddler.
</P>
<P>
   DON'T let them upstage the hero, like Nicholson's Joker and
Carrey's Riddler. Also, don't overcrowd your hero with countless
foes, as in ``Batman Returns,'' ``Batman Forever'' and ``Batman &AMP;
Robin.'' There's only so much screen time to go around.
</P>
<P>
   DO give the hero a well-developed love interest. The Man of
Steel reversed time to save his beloved Lois Lane in ``Superman.''
``X-Men'' establishes a love triangle among Wolverine, Jean Grey
and Cyclops, as well as unrequited romance between Rogue and
Wolverine.
</P>
<P>
   DON'T insert a love interest simply because she's
well-developed, so to speak, as was the case with ``Batman
Forever'''s Nicole Kidman and ``Swamp Thing'''s Adrienne Barbeau.
</P>
<P>
   DO spend your budget on essentials such as costumes, sets and
special effects. ``X-Men'' eschewed big-star salaries by using a
cast of relative unknowns, putting its $75 million budget on the
screen. ``The Crow'' derived strong, stylish production values from
a meager $6 million budget.
</P>
<P>
   DON'T blow your entire budget on big stars and splashy set
pieces, as in the later ``Batman'' movies. Schwarzenegger's
$20-million salary could have paid for a few realistic-looking
icicles, at the very least. Conversely, don't stretch your small
budget too thin. ``Spawn's'' anthropomorphic cape was terrific, but
the computer-generated scenes in hell looked like a Nintendo game.
Roger Corman's cheapie version of ``The Fantastic Four `` was never
released.
</P>
<P>
   DO hire Danny Elfman to compose your musical score. The former
Oingo Boingo frontman has written the dark, witty and romantic
orchestrations for numerous comic book movies, including
``Batman,'' ``Dick Tracy,'' ``Darkman,'' ``Batman Returns'' and
``Men in Black.''
</P>
<P>
   DON'T disrupt the mood with jarring musical interludes by
Prince, as in ``Batman,'' simply because a hot pop star sells
soundtrack albums.
</P>
<P>
   DO remember that there's a character under the costume.
``Spawn'' emphasized the vengeful hero's outfit at the expense of
the tortured soul inside the mask and cape.
</P>
<P>
   DON'T skimp on the costumes _ unless it's ``X-Men'' villain
Mystique, played by supermodel Rebecca Romijn-Stamos. In her case,
blue body paint does just fine.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
