</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE STILL ISN'T UP TO SPEED ON THIS NASCAR STUFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I had this dream, see. I dreamt I had entered a world in which
more than 100,000 people were speaking a language I did not
understand. These people had come to this specific gathering place
to take part in a spiritual ritual, and every one of them had
experiences and a complete frame of reference totally foreign to
me.
</P>
<P>
   On second thought, that was no dream. That was me at New
Hampshire International Speedway at Loudon, N.H., last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The phrase ``parallel universe'' has never had more personal
meaning. Something was going on that had great meaning to these
people, who didn't seem to mind the necessity of rising before the
sun was up in order to negotiate their way to a track that can
accommodate 100,000-plus people and which is ultimately accessible
only by New Hampshire Route 106, a two-lane highway (plus breakdown
lanes).
</P>
<P>
   They had come to see 43 skilled drivers steer their assorted
Chevys, Pontiacs, and Fords for 300 laps around the 1.058-mile
oval. In that sense, they did not get what they paid for, the race
being shortened by rain to 273 laps.
</P>
<P>
   But that is quite clearly not the whole point. They had also
come to celebrate a culture. A NASCAR race is more than just the
race. The competition is a lure, but it is not just the
competition. In the minds and hearts of the True Believers, NASCAR
is a unique fan experience in which the connection between
participant and viewer is quite real. These people seemed to be
bonded, both fan to fan and fan to driver.
</P>
<P>
   It seems to me that in order to participate, you need to love
your car. I mean really love your car. I don't. Never have, never
will. To me, a car is a large portable radio that costs me far too
much money to maintain. It is a nuisance that invariably lets me
down when I most need it. At best, I have an adversarial
relationship with my car. So perhaps I could never, ever become a
NASCAR person. It just isn't in me.
</P>
<P>
   I could never enjoy myself the way, for example, Rick Demelis
did.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Demelis had no problems leaving his house at 5 a.m. and
returning home at 11 p.m. He didn't mind the $170-per-person outlay
for tickets and entrance to the Du Pont tent, where he could
partake of food and drink all day while enjoying the race on his
own terms. He was, in fact, thrilled to have the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``These tickets are hard to get your hands on,'' he confides.
</P>
<P>
   It makes sense that Rick Demelis would be a NASCAR fan. He is
the owner and operator of A.J.'s Exxon in Hingham. He used to race
Modifieds himself. I know he knows cars because he has been largely
responsible for keeping my own large portable radios on the road
for the past 20 years. For him, last Sunday was a very satisfactory
day, rain-shortened race or no rain-shortened race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't upset by it,'' he says. ``I've been going up there
for six years, and that's the first time it's rained. It happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, he would have loved to see what would have happened if the
race had been resumed after it rained for the second time. Like
everyone else in attendance, he knew that, for the second year in a
row, Tony Stewart had a fuel crisis, and that, absent the
raindrops, things might have turned out differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good race is one that's competitive right to the end,'' he
says. ``That could have been a great race. Those last 27 laps could
have been the most exciting part of the entire race.''
</P>
<P>
   But he's a big boy, and he knows it's caveat emptor with the
weather. Anyway, that's why he opted for the tent. He is a
hard-working man, and he wanted the full experience of a great day
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love the whole experience,'' he explains. ``Getting
there. The tailgating. It's like a football game. The tents. The
thousands of people walking around with the different T-shirts. The
colors.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's all over and above the race itself, which Demelis, as
a car guy, finds endlessly fascinating. ``It's not like going to
New England Dragway and it's a matter of putting the pedal to the
metal and whoever's the fastest wins. There is so much strategy. In
the car itself you've got the motor, the tires, the fuel, and the
driver to evaluate.''
</P>
<P>
   Does it not go without saying that Rick Demelis was one of the
thousands who rented a scanner in order to check out the
interaction between the crew and the driver? ``It's a very big
thing,'' he says. ``When does the pit crew tell him to come in?
What are they talking about?''
</P>
<P>
   A Winston Cup race is extremely fan-friendly. Information access
is immediate. Drivers are interviewed during the rain delay.
Everything is done to make everyone feel welcome. And that includes
the press.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball, basketball, football, and hockey could take lessons.
NHIS public relations director Fred Neergaard introduced me to
Brian VanDercook, the PR representative of the Hass-Carter K Mart
team, whose driver is Jimmy Spencer, and he, in turn, took me to
their ``Holler,'' or transport vehicle, where driver Ricky Simmons
gave me a complete tour, showing me every possible aspect of the
enterprise. At one point I guiltily took notes, as if I had any
remote idea what Mr. Simmons was talking about. At any rate, it was
all above and beyond the call of any PR duties I've ever
experienced.
</P>
<P>
   There are reasons why this sport has grown from an offshoot of
backwoods Southern evade-the-revenuers mountain racing to its
current status as the best-attended and fastest-growing sport in
America. And Rick Demelis says it's not all about being a car
lover, either, citing Diana Demelis as Exhibit A.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took my wife for the first time last year,'' he says. ``She
doesn't like anything. Now she's got to be at my side at any race.
Believe me, if my wife gets into it, anybody can get into it. My
wife gets into nothing. But she wants to go back to these races.
And my brother-in-law took his girlfriend this time. She turns
around and says, `Can you get me tickets for September?' ''
</P>
<P>
   I saw it with my own eyes, and I know the phenomenon is real. I
still think it helps substantially if you love your car. All I know
is that after five laps, I was thinking, ``Please, God, make them
go faster. Please don't tell me there are 295 laps to go.''
</P>
<P>
   So to Fred, Brian, Ricky, Rick, and the brothers Bahre, who own
the track, I regretfully say, sorry. I just don't get it. But it's
pretty evident you don't need me.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail at
ryan(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
