<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOWNCAR-REVIEW0714-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Imposing Town Car offers classic luxury
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A truly massive vehicle and one that's
ultra-sophisticated in some ways, the 2000 Lincoln Town Car also is
as retro as the 2001 Chrysler PT cruiser or any other vehicle
harkening to the good ol' days of cheap fuel and big-engined luxury
cars.
</P>
<P>
   That's because it has a 4.6-liter V-8 engine driving the rear
wheels, making it among the last of its kind. The Town Car,
available commercially in base ($38,630), signature ($40,630) and
Cartier ($43,330) versions, has a cushy and exceptionally quiet
ride with enough space for six adults.
</P>
<P>
   As an everyday car, the Town Car has few equals when it comes to
comfort. Cadillac and Lexus are the only other manufacturers
regarded as challengers, and while the DeVille and GS 400 are more
sophisticated, they lose out in the space race.
</P>
<P>
   From its massive chrome grille to huge taillamp assemblies, the
Town Car stretches 18 feet and has a curb weight of more than 4,000
pounds. The only available drivetrain is Ford's workhorse 4.6-liter
V-8, which is tuned to a robust 220 horsepower, and a four-speed
automatic transmission. Despite the power and weight, the Town Car
pulls to 60 mph in less than 10 seconds and delivers 18 mpg in town
and 25 on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   Rear visibility isn't great, and the side vision suffers because
of the Town Car's massive pillars, but the straight-ahead and
in-town ride is very gentle. The power steering's about as soft as
the ride, but the power anti-lock disc brakes produce fast stops,
accompanied by gentle nose dive.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few cars that comes with a real clock, the Town Car
pampers driver and passenger with monstrous, overstuffed reclining
seats. Even the seat backs can be heated, and the front seats are
eight-way power-adjustable, so getting comfortable is hardly a
problem. The seats automatically slide back to facilitate
entry/exit, and the travel is so great that many drivers will have
to lean forward to put the key in.
</P>
<P>
   Even the center consoles are king-size, quite suitable for
playing board games, using a laptop or for paperwork. There's
plenty of storage: Deep door boxes are lidded, and the deep trunk
has more than 20 cubic feet of space.
</P>
<P>
   But unobtrusively transporting people, not things, is what the
Town Car is designed to do, and for those who believe that the
proper way to go is with rear-wheel drive, the superbly assembled
and finished Town Car is a tradition that just won't totally give
in to 21st century trends.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
