u e BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-13 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVE COLUMNIST'S PENALTY SPURS WIDE DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even as The Boston Globe and columnist Jeff Jacoby both say his
suspension was not connected to his conservative politics, Jacoby's
fate became a raging ideological battleground this week.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, citing ``serious journalistic misconduct,'' the
Globe suspended Jacoby for four months without pay for writing a
July 3 column on the signers of the Declaration of Independence
that was based on other accounts without alerting readers to those
sources. Factored into the punishment was his practice of
circulating his column early without Globe permission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Globe badly overreacted,'' Jacoby said Wednesday.
``I don't think I deserve to lose my income for four months for an
oversight.'' Acknowledging the Globe's standards, he added that ``I
have very high journalistic standards too . . . My hope at this
point is to be back in my office writing a column.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, the heated media debate over Jacoby's suspension
surfaced everywhere from the editorial pages of The Wall Street
Journal to a story by media critic Howard Kurtz of the Washington
Post to the Globe newsroom. (Business writer Hiawatha Bray is
circulating a petition among Globe staffers asking publisher
Richard H. Gilman to reconsider Jacoby's suspension.)
</P>
<P>
   And as ideological allies rallied around him, the discussion
quickly began to focus on whether Jacoby paid a price for being the
conservative columnist on a liberal editorial page.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision had nothing to do with ideology or with Jeff's
religion'' or any other, random issue such as ``whether he's an
easy edit or a hard edit or whether he's popular or not,'' said
editorial page editor Renee Loth. ``The decision is about
standards. Readers deserve to know that the material that appears
underneath someone's byline in The Boston Globe is his material.
That really seems to me to befundamental.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the allegations that he is the victim of his
conservative politics, Jacoby says flatly: ``I haven't seen any
evidence to think that this about ideology.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in a July 11 Wall Street Journal column critical of the the
suspension, James Taranto wrote that `Mr. Jacoby happens to be the
Globe's only conservative columnist and some conservatives now
accuse the paper of singling him out on ideological grounds.'' In a
July 11 story, Kurtz noted that Jacoby was ``an unabashed
conservative on a famously liberal op-ed page'' and cited several
journalists' concerns about a connection between Jacoby's politics
and his fate.
</P>
<P>
   In a July 11 letter to the Boston Globe, radio talk host David
Brudnoy broached the subject cautiously, writing that ``the Boston
Globe is well-armed with columnists who provide a liberal take on
the news . . . The Globe speaks endlessly and forcefully of
`diversity.' That is precisely what Jacoby has provided on the
Globe's op-ed page.''
</P>
<P>
   Others were blunter. JewishWorldReview.com
(www.jewishworldreview.com) editor-in-chief Binyamin L. Jolkovsky
had this explanation for the suspension: ``In the past, Jeff had
the audacity to question frequently and with eloquence, what is
more and more becoming the accepted norm in this era of moral
revisionism. His views are conservative and based upon his value
system as a Sabbath observant Jew.'' Commentator David Horowitz
wrote that Jacoby had been rendered an ``unperson by his leftwing
bosses at the Globe.''
</P>
<P>
   Globe ombudsman Jack Thomas says he's gotten hundreds of calls
and more than 1,000 e-mails since Jacoby's suspension. But he says
more than 90 percent of those e-mails originate from states outside
the Globe's circulation area and are ``steeped in right-wing
rhetoric that denounces the Globe as Marxist lefties engaged in a
McCarthy-like purge.''
</P>
<P>
   In the debate, there are a few dispassionate opinions. Bob
Steele, director of the ethics program at the Poynter Center for
Media Studies, says that without knowing ``all the pieces of the
puzzle, for me . . . or anyone from afar to give a meaningful
interpretation (of Jacoby's case) is impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Media analyst Tom Rosenstiel says, ``as an observer from a
distance away, it's a little murky what the crime is because they
didn't use the word plagiarism. . . . The important thing in these
cases is (for the Globe) to make clear to the staff and the public
what their standards are. What you say in these cases is as
important as what you do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While Harvard decides whether to name Freedom Forum senior vice
president Robert Giles as curator of the Nieman Foundation, the
lobbying continues. Trying to counter unions who have argued that
Giles's role during the Detroit newspaper strike _ when he was
editor and publisher of The Detroit News _ should disqualify him
from the post, top officers of the American Society of Newspaper
Editors recently weighed in.
</P>
<P>
   Austin-American Statesman editor Richard Oppel; Tim McGuire,
editor of the Minneapolis Star Tribune; Diane McFarlin, publisher
of the Sarasota Herald-Tribune; and Peter Bhatia, executive editor
of The (Portland) Oregonian, signed a letter to Harvard President
Neil Rudenstine supportive of Giles.
</P>
<P>
   And as the Nieman watch continues, there is speculation that
Harvard may ultimately bypass Giles, choose a temporary curator and
reopen the search in earnest next year. Insider gossip suggests
that should the search be restarted, another possible candidate
might emerge: former Wall Street Journal staffer and PBS Democracy
Project Director Ellen Hume.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Mark Jurkowitz covers the media for The Boston Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
