<HEADER>
A1006 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBO-ALCANTARA-BOS &LR;      07-13 1386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALCANTARA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALCANTRA'S MISDEEDS BRING SCORN, BUT NO EXPLANATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Izzy Alcantara was styling, commemorating his three-run homer
with a slow-motion, hot-dog jaunt around the bases.
</P>
<P>
   The opposing pitcher took offense. The next time Alcantara came
to the plate, the pitcher buzzed him, sending him reeling backward.
</P>
<P>
   It was the summer of 1998. Alcantara was an upward-bound slugger
for the Double A Reading (Pa.) Phillies. He responded by pointing
his bat at Mark Guerra, the Binghamton Mets pitcher, and heading
for the mound, according to published reports and eyewitness
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets catcher, Pedro Grifol, intervened, whereupon Alcantara
launched a left jab and, in return, got whacked in the head with
the catcher's mask.
</P>
<P>
   For his antics, Alcantara was suspended for three games and
fined $300.
</P>
<P>
   And that isolated incident, according to several of his former
managers and other baseball personnel, represented Alcantara's
worst contribution to professional sports _ until he seized his
spot in Red Sox infamy July 1 by all but quitting on the basepaths
and in the field in a game against the Chicago White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   In the days since his afternoon of notoriety, Alcantara has
silently endured the backlash: his teammates' scorn, his manager's
refusal to play him, and a seething fandom's incessant call for his
pillorying.
</P>
<P>
   Meet the Bill Buckner of the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   But ask managers who policed Alcantara before he arrived last
month on Jimy Williams's doorstep and none can recall the Dominican
power hitter displaying such poisonous behavior. No blatant
loafing. No watching lazy fly balls fall at his feet, as he did in
Chicago. No punching out of work in the middle of a rundown, as he
also did, to his team's shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never did that with me,'' said Al LeBoeuf, who managed
Alcantara at Reading in 1998 and now is a coach for the Clearwater
Phillies in the Florida State League. ``I never, ever had a problem
with him. He was always on time, always worked hard and played
hard, and, as a manager, that's all you can ask for.''
</P>
<P>
   Alcantara's fiasco began in the third inning of a 7-2 loss when
his lackluster reaction to a routine single to right by Ray Durham
allowed White Sox catcher Mark Johnson to score from first. One
batter later, Alcantara's lackadaisical effort turned Jose
Valentin's single into a double, allowing another run to score.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth inning, he was charged with an error when he
scooped up Chris Singleton's single, then dropped it as he prepared
to throw, allowing Singleton to reach second.
</P>
<P>
   Alcantara extended the nightmare in the eighth inning when,
rather than advance on a wild pitch, he ambled off second base, got
caught in a rundown, and made no effort to escape. As a result, he
prevented Jeff Frye from advancing from first.
</P>
<P>
   Elected to the Double A All-Star team last year and to the
International League squad this year before he was summoned by the
Red Sox June 25, Alcantara was known throughout his eight-year
minor league career as a defensive liability, a slugger many teams
would covet if they could find a safe spot for him in the field.
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, the Red Sox should have known when they signed
Alcantara that they would use the journeyman minor-leaguer in the
field at their peril. He had struggled at every defensive position
he has played: third base, first, and the outfield. But his
shortcomings apparently were not for lack of dedication.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other guys are better defensive players than him,'' said
Pawtucket manager Gary Jones. ``He's an offensive player. But he
worked on his defense when he was here. He went out every day and
took fly balls and worked hard and tried to be a better player, and
I did see improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he had no reason to criticize Alcantara's work ethic
or effort. ``I don't know what happened up there,'' Jones said,
referring to the Chicago disaster. ``All I'm saying is that he
played hard every day and I never had a problem with his work
habits.''
</P>
<P>
   Same story in Trenton, N.J., where Alcantara hit 20 homers in 77
games for Boston's Double AA affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may not be the best defensive player of all time,
certainly. But he was anything but a loafer,'' said Andy Freed, the
team's radio announcer. ``He was awesome for us and everyone knew
he was better than the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Which begs the question, what in the name of Jimmy Piersall was
Alcantara thinking that fateful afternoon in Chicago?
</P>
<P>
   A farmer's son from the coastal town of Bani in the Dominican
Republic, Alcantara has yet to publicly explain his lapses in his
sixth game as a major leaguer.
</P>
<P>
   Alcantara was signed by Montreal, when Duquette was general
manager there, in 1992. Tampa Bay picked him up in 1997 after
Montreal left him off their 40-man roster, but Duquette got him
back in 1998 as a minor league free agent when Tampa Bay left him
unprotected.
</P>
<P>
   He had endured a long journey to the bigs, playing more than
3,000 minor league games, riding countless overnight bus trips, and
sleeping in cut-rate motels from South Florida to northern Vermont.
At 27, he is older than Nomar Garciaparra, Trot Nixon, and Derek
Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   So why risk it all by failing to hustle?
</P>
<P>
   Asked in the clubhouse Sunday for an interview, Alcantara said,
``No hablo ingles.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is not true, because he has spoken English to reporters
for many publications. When it was suggested to him that he must
know enough English to converse, he tersely replied, ``Thank you,''
as if to say, ``No comment.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Alcantara has become a pariah and only general manager Dan
Duquette has publicly uttered a word in his defense. Despite
Williams's refusal to play Alcantara since the rookie shrank from
responsbility in the ``City of Big Shoulders,'' Duquette has said
he will not jettison Alcantara for ``one bad day.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette believes the Red Sox need Alcantara's bat. After
struggling for years to hit breaking balls, Alcantara was whaling
Triple A pitching and leading the International League in home runs
(22) and RBI (63) before he was told after a game in Louisville
last month to awaken the next day at 4 a.m. and report to Toronto
to play that night for the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Alcantara homered in his first three at-bats for Pawtucket last
year in his Triple A debut. He was on pace this year to hit 47
homers for Pawtucket and he showed a hint of big league batting
talent in his six-game run before his benching: .375, with a homer
and three runs scored, in 16 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   But didn't the 1998 incident suggest he was a showboat, a
potentially disruptive force?
</P>
<P>
   ``He did (showboat),'' LeBoeuf said. ``But in the minors you
have guys who hit four or five home runs all year and stand there
watching them. He didn't do anything out of the ordinary,
especially for a guy with his kind of power.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette insists Alcantara is going to play for the Red Sox. But
that may hinge on what Williams believes the definition of ``is''
is.
</P>
<P>
   Asked last weekend about Alcantara's status, the manager said,
``Any player in that locker room has a chance to play. They're all
major league players.''
</P>
<P>
   But Williams has not spoken a word on Alcantara's behalf since
he described the team's performance that day in Chicago as
``U-G-L-Y.'' The manager has allowed Alcantara to do little more
than take batting practice, which even backfired last weekend when
his line drive struck rehabbing pitcher Bret Saberhagen in the
buttocks, cutting short the pitcher's throwing session.
</P>
<P>
   Williams also has shown Alcantara none of the benevolence he has
afforded other players, like Ed Sprague, whom the manager patted on
the back Sunday before a sell-out Fenway crowd after Sprague was
booed repeatedly in lowering his Red Sox batting average to .118.
</P>
<P>
   As Alcantara left the clubhouse Sunday for the All-Star break,
Bernard Gilkey momentarily clutched his shoulder and Carl Everett
tapped him on the arm as if to wish him well. But no one said
goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   And baseball people who knew Alcantara before he took the field
that day in Chicago continue to ponder the mystery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why he would do that at the major league level,'' LeBoeuf
said, ``I just don't know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
