<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEE DEE QUEASY OVER TALL SHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dee Dee is feeling even more lightheaded than usual due to the
recent outbreak of Tall Ships Fever. Our all-purpose advice
columnist hasn't succumbed to the epidemic; however, she has been
overwhelmed by questions from the legions of afflicted. Some of
these sufferers are in desperate straits, to toss off a
nauticalism, so Dee Dee feels an obligation to address their issues
without delay. Fire when ready.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dear Dee Dee: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What is the origin of the term ``Tall Ships''? _ Inquisitive,
Howling Point, ME
</P>
<P>
   The phrase had its popular origin in John Masefield's poem ``Sea
Fever,'' which begins with the haunting stanza ``I must go down to
the sea again, to the lonely sea and the sky, / And all I ask is a
Sail Boston 2000 T-shirt and matching cap and a bottle of SPF 25
sunblock /And a ticket on a Tall Ships harbor cruise to get by.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dear Dee Dee: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I heard a television commentator say that this Tall Ships
extravaganza is a ``once-in-a-lifetime event.'' If I recall
correctly, and I think I do, we were told the same thing when the
Tall Ships first visited Boston in 1976, and again, repeatedly,
when similar flotillas entered local waters in 1980, 1986, and
1992. How many more times must I brace myself to hear the same
nonsense? _ Fed Up, Flotsam, MA
</P>
<P>
   As a Tall Ships survivor you must know by now that there will
never be an end to the blather surrounding these events, so Dee Dee
advises you to remain braced, permanently.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dear Dee Dee: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since I suffer from an extreme fear of cliches and superlatives,
my philologist has advised me to avoid the Tall Ships at all costs.
This seems an extreme measure, especially since I have been looking
forward to kicking up my heels while the fleet is in. What do you
think? _ Frisky, Bloater Beach, CT
</P>
<P>
   Far be it from Dee Dee to question a medical specialist, or
whatever he or she is, but this advice is unsound. By all means see
the Tall Ships, and frolic with those who sail them. But try to
avoid hearing or reading about them in the news media, since that
is where you're most likely to encounter the language you fear,
words such as ``magnificent,'' ``awesome,'' ``breathtaking,''
``legendary,'' ``larger-than-life,'' etc. Dee Dee apologizes if
this language has frightened you. Try to think of it as aversion
therapy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dear Dee Dee: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How tall does a ship have to be to qualify as a Tall Ship? My
ship, Hyperbole, measures 28 feet 6 inches from the base of her
hull to the top of her mast. Could she be called a Tall Ship? _
Hopeful, Styx River, RI
</P>
<P>
   One might as well ask, along with Irving Berlin: How deep is the
ocean? How high is the sky? How many times a day do I think of you?
How many roses are sprinkled with dew? Dee Dee's getting a little
carried away, but you get the point. Tallness is a personal matter,
between you and your ship. If you think of her as tall, she will
be.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dear Dee Dee: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Why are Tall Ships referred to as ``she''? Is this an example of
seagoing sexism? _ Stymied, Shagbark, NH
</P>
<P>
   Dee Dee's dog-eared copy of ``The Bias-Free Word-Finder'' says
this ``outdated, unnecessary, and unacceptable'' custom dates back
to ancient times, when ships were named for goddesses, under whose
protection they sailed. But Dee Dee thinks there's a more obvious
explanation: Most ships are female.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
