<HEADER>
A1008 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-RETAIL-TALBOTS-ART-BO     07-13 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETAIL-TALBOTS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 AFTER '97 MISSTEP, TALBOTS AGAIN IS A CLASSIC SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; HINGHAM, Mass. _ Three years ago, a half a century after it
first began selling classically styled women's clothing from a
17th-century colonial-frame home here, The Talbots Inc. seemed to
disastrously veer away from its traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1947, sensible wardrobes from Talbots have found favor
with women between 35 and 55. But looking to broaden its appeal to
include women in their late 20s and early 30s, Talbots began
flirting with trendier styles and shorter hemlines in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a marketing flop. Not only did new styles fail to
win over younger customers, but they also alienated women who had
been intensely loyal to Talbots for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took the pendulum and swung it all the way out,'' says
Arnold B. Zetcher, Talbots chairman, president, and chief
executive. ``And that was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Today 1997 is ancient history, and Talbots now may be one of the
hottest apparel retailers in the business. (That's hot by the
standards of Wall Street and not necessarily hot by the fashion
standards of Paris and New York.)
</P>
<P>
   Check out the chain's nearly 700 stores, and it's clear that
Talbots has returned to its classic roots.
</P>
<P>
   Page through some of the roughly 57 million catalogs that
Talbots mails out in a year, and aggressively fashion-forward
clothing is nowhere in evidence. Instead there is page after page
of tasteful twin sets, blazers, and capri pants, only sometimes in
larger sizes and in a wider range of colors.
</P>
<P>
   Such styles have wowed both consumers and investors.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, at a time when many other publicly traded retailers are
reporting ho-hum sales and watching their stock prices languish,
</P>
<P>
   nearly everything seems to be going right for Talbots _ even the
performance of its new Web site at www.Talbots.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been profitable since day one,'' Zetcher says.
</P>
<P>
   For fiscal 1999, Talbots sales rose 13 percent to $1.29 billion.
Profits rose 59 percent to $58.5 million. For its most recent
quarter, profits were up 69 percent to $32.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   What's driving profits at Talbots? CIBC World Markets analyst
Dorothy Lakner offers one explanation: ``Their customers are
willing to pay full price.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not the case for all retailers. Many of their customers
won't buy an item unless it's marked down. That's great for the
consumer, but it cuts into profits.
</P>
<P>
   There may be another reason Talbots customers are willing to pay
full price. At many department stores, shopping for clothes can be
a time-consuming hassle, analysts say. Talbots, in contrast, can
offer customers one-stop convenience, a place where a wardrobe or
an outfit can quickly be assembled and accessorized, retail
analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Other specialty chains can offer similar convenience, but
Talbots is the only specialty chain that focuses on classic
clothing, says Harry A. Ikenson, senior analyst at Chase H&AMP;Q.
</P>
<P>
   Zetcher has his own theory for why his customers are willing to
pay full price: Classic clothes don't go out of style. A Talbots
wardrobe is ``like an investment,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   For a retailer, full prices at retail translate into healthy
profits, and healthy profits translate into strong stock
performance. On the New York Stock Exchange, Talbots shares have
risen about 60 percent in the last 12 months, closing Wednesday at
$59.5625, down 6.25 cents. During the same period, many publicly
traded retailers have seen their stock shares fall.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to capitalize on its momentum, Talbots recently unveiled
a plan to open more than 400 stores by the end of 2005. That would
bring the chain's store total to more than 1,100 and projected
annual sales to more than $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the rebound is a response to the disaster of 1997,
which happened because past successes were taken for granted and
the chain stopped paying close attention to its best customers.
</P>
<P>
   To reverse the downward slide, Zetcher initiated several
changes, adopting a team approach to the design and styling of
future merchandise. So customer feedback would have more weight,
store managers were given a voice in the design process, something
they hadn't had before. In addition, the financial department was
brought in to help plan inventory levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The combination of the merchandise being right on and the
inventory being kept at the appropriate level'' is a big part of
the Talbots comeback story, Zetcher says.
</P>
<P>
   Such fixes won back the traditional customers who had cut back
on their purchases at Talbots in 1997. But there was still the
challenge of bringing in new customers.
</P>
<P>
   This time, instead of courting younger women, Talbots decided to
focus on capturing a far larger percentage of the women between 35
and 55 and converting them into Talbots customers.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Zetcher launched Talbots Woman, a larger-size line,
and he hired Boston ad agency Arnold Communications to launch a
brand campaign that included the chain's first TV ads.
</P>
<P>
   With the theme of ``Talbots _ It's a classic,'' Arnold ads
portray Talbots customers as ``contemporary, successful, and
fun-loving'' and the antithesis of the Martha Stewart devotee, says
Francis J. Kelly III, Arnold's chief marketing officer.
</P>
<P>
   Women in the ads are ``not all throwing dinner parties with
crystal and silverware,'' he says. ``They don't spend their whole
day trying to look good.''
</P>
<P>
   For Talbots, early signs of a turnaround began to appear in
mid-1998, and the turnaround has gained momentum ever since.
</P>
<P>
   In three of the last four quarters, Talbots has alerted Wall
Street to adjust profit targets upward, according to First Call
Corp., a Thomson Financial company.
</P>
<P>
   How much higher can Talbots share price climb? That's a good
question. Six of the 13 analysts who follow Talbots have a hold
rating on the stock, according to First Call.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Talbots is moving ahead with the retail Web site it
launched in November and recently touted with ads that feature
cartoon character Jane Jetson.
</P>
<P>
   Early results hint that Talbots.com may achieve what the
youthful fashions of 1997 couldn't do _ bring Talbots new
customers. On a monthly basis, 25 to 40 percent of shoppers at the
Web site are new to Talbots, Zetcher says.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the big question for Talbots is whether it can
sustain its impressive sales momentum. If Talbots keeps listening
to its customers, some retail analysts don't see any reason why the
chain's momentum can't continue to build.
</P>
<P>
   Zetcher vows not to become complacent. Referring to the troubles
Talbots encountered when it pursued younger customers with younger
fashions three years ago, he says: ``I don't think 1997 can happen
again. But we know success is not owed us or due us. We have to
continue to earn it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
