<HEADLINE>
BUSH AND GORE: A CHOICE, NOT JUST AN ECHO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There isn't much evidence that Wall Street is paying attention
yet to the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, corporate earnings and summer vacations are
higher priorities. But once the conventions are over, money
managers will focus on the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Sinai thinks they should.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the candidates are saying is immensely significant for
Wall Street,'' said Sinai, chief economist at Primark Decision
Economics. On a host of issues, the two candidates offer Wall
Street a choice, not an echo.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush supports the partial privatization of Social
Security; Al Gore doesn't. Bush wants the private sector to lead
the way on prescription drugs for Medicare; Gore wants a bigger
role for the government. Bush wants big tax cuts; Gore wants
medium-size ones. Bush is likely to rein in the Justice
Department's aggressive antitrust policies; Gore is apt to leave
them in place.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast between the two candidates has grown sharper in the
past few weeks as Gore has stepped us his populist rhetoric. For
much of his career, Gore has stressed his free-market credentials,
his support for high technology, and his track record on reducing
the deficit.
</P>
<P>
   But in a recent speech before the American Federation of
Teachers, Gore sounded more like William Jennings Bryan. ``We know
our opponents in this election are on the side of the powerful, not
the people,'' he said. ``They have powerful interests lined up
against us like the big oil companies, like the HMOs and the
polluters.''
</P>
<P>
   In a series of speeches, Gore has accused the ``high-profit''
drug companies of ``gouging'' consumers.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of talk may go over well in some quarters, but not on
Wall Street, where high profits are a good thing and the prefered
language for ``gouging'' is ``charging a premium price for a
premium product.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Goodman, senior economic adviser for Putnam Investments,
said that what Wall Street will be focusing on is quite basic.
``Money managers want to know what will affect the ability of
corporations to generate profits,'' he said. ``It is very cold and
pragmatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many on Wall Street, Goodman, a conservative on economic
matters, prefers the market-oriented philosophy of the Republicans
to the more ``redistributionist'' policies of the Democrats. And at
the moment, he doesn't see much to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why. According to Goodman, there are four possible
outcomes to the November elections:
</P>
<P>
   A Republican president and a Republican Congress; a Republican
president with Democrats holding at least one house of Congress; a
Democratic president with Republicans holding at least one house of
Congress; and, finally, a Democratic president and a Democratic
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In Goodman's view, the first three options should all be fine
with Wall Street. He points out that stocks did well in the Reagan
years and in the Clinton years, when divided government was the
rule in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The only scenario he worries about is a Democratic sweep. ``The
probability of that seems very low,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Perna has a somewhat different take on the election. An
economic consultant in Connecticut, Perna thinks the ideal outcome
for Wall Street would be a split decision _ Congress controlled by
one party and the White House by another. Perna has coined a term
for that condition: ``flexible gridlock.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What ends up happening is that the pendulum doesn't swing as
much,'' he said. ``Some things get done, and you avoid the dangers
of excesses.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the excesses to be feared would be too much fiscal
stimulus from either Republican tax cuts or Democratic spending
programs. Either one, argues Perna, could end up putting upward
pressure on interest rates by pumping money into an already hot
economy.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Wall Street is calm. That could be because Bush appears
to be in the catbird seat. He is ahead in all the opinion polls.
According to Barron's, a recent survey of institutional investors
conducted by one Wall Street firm showed 75 percent of those polled
expected a Bush victory.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers may explain why Gore's attacks on oil companies
and drug companies have had no obvious impact on stock prices in
either sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Gore comes on after the convention, you may see some
concern in the market,'' said Mark Zandi, chief economist at RFA
Dismal Sciences, a Pennsylvania forecasting firm. By contrast, if
Bush looks as though he is headed for victory, there could be a
preelection rally, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   It is fashionable these days to say that government doesn't
matter anymore. The truth is that it does _ even on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Syre (617-929-2918) and Charles Stein (617-929-2922) can
also be reached by e-mail at boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
