<HEADLINE>
VENTURE-BACKED IPOS STILL SHOWING SOME LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bucking all forecasts, the IPO market for venture-backed
start-ups still had a pulse in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-four venture-backed companies made it through the gate
nationally last quarter, raising $4.3 billion in initial public
offerings, even as a grim stock market dealt death blows to
teetering dot-coms in April and May.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the volume marked a decline from the euphoric first
quarter, when 77 companies went public and raised $8.5 billion,
according to Venture Economics, a Boston research firm that tracks
such data. But it wasn't so far below the activity of a year ago,
when 70 IPO deals raised $5.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Observed Paul Ferri, a general partner with Matrix Partners, a
Waltham, Mass. venture firm, ``The very high-quality deals get done
in any market. What all this market turmoil has done was flush out
the junkier companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Venture money was behind about half of the total 104 companies
that went public in the quarter. All told, companies raised $24.69
billion in IPOs, the second-biggest quarter ever, thanks largely to
AT&AMP;T's $10 billion wireless offering.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two years, IPOs have fueled the technology boom, as
venture capitalists who finance young companies were able to reap
fast returns on their investments _ sometimes in as little as a
year or two, compared to four to six years in the past.
</P>
<P>
   April's market drop brought with it a glum sense that the party
was over. Venture partners started talking about the need to pump
additional money into portfolio companies that would have to stay
private longer than planned. Some start-ups were warned to get
thriftier with their cash. Others were dumped entirely.
</P>
<P>
   A new sense of caution showed up in the roster of venture-backed
companies that did manage to go public. Only 12 Internet companies
hit the market, down from 29 in the prior quarter.
</P>
<P>
   California, led by Silicon Valley, scored the largest number of
IPOs, claiming 21 of the 54 offerings in the quarter. Massachusetts
was a distant second, with three deals.
</P>
<P>
   Several local deals were pulled after the Nasdaq plunged 25
percent in one week in early April. They included Furniture.com and
Internet consulting firm Zefer Corp., which recently refiled to go
public. Other start-ups had to seek buyers and scrap their plans to
go public.
</P>
<P>
   But the three Boston-area deals that went public have been
stunning successes, especially given the market's rocky treatment
of many tech stocks this year.
</P>
<P>
   Backers Matrix and Charles River Ventures watched Sonus Networks
Inc., a Westford supplier of networking software and equipment,
soar 782 percent since its IPO on May 24.
</P>
<P>
   Storage Networks Inc. of Waltham _ backed by Greylock Management
Corp. and Sigma Partners _ has jumped 327 percent since it went
public June 29. And, Praecis Pharmaceuticals Inc., a Cambridge
company financed in part by Highland Capital Partners, has gained
273 percent since its April 26 offering.
</P>
<P>
   Matrix's Ferri recalls with some awe that many deals of the
quarter were priced at levels below what the companies had hoped.
In the case of Sonus, he said, ``We did it above the filing
range.''
</P>
<P>
   Continuing stability in the IPO market will affect how freely
venture capitalists invest in new companies _ and whether they are
able to raise new funds, said Jesse Reyes, a vice president with
Venture Economics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 1353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
