<HEADLINE>
EVEN ON LIVE-ACTION SITE, `BIG BROTHER' IS A SNORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cast of ``Big Brother'' is in the discovery phase of its
great adventure, which is sort of like the ``Getting to Know You''
scene in ``The King and I.'' But without the orchestra, the cute
kids, and the froufrou hoop skirt, it's hard to sustain interest in
the taped CBS show or the ``live'' Web site. This group could
really use a big splashy production number, some ol' razzle-dazzle
as they unpack those metal suitcases and settle into those little
bunks.
</P>
<P>
   But no. So far the Web site, which promises unedited footage and
includes a parental advisory, has been as tame as the show's
television debut. Immediately after the show ended Wednesday night,
the Web site was overwhelmed with traffic as folks raced to their
computers to watch the preliminary howdy-dos. Just as one ``house
guest'' was about to reveal her secret recipe for chocolate-chip
cookies, the site crashed. Oh, the suspense.
</P>
<P>
   By now, the folks at America Online, which is handling the Web
component, seem to have worked out the kinks in the site
(www.bigbrother2000.com). But they haven't been able to generate
much tension or drama, unless of course, you're interested in
watching strangers eat and sleep. So far, the best thing about the
Web site is that it doesn't feature the wooden commentary of
co-hosts Julie Chen and Ian O'Malley. Just a thought: Do viewers
get a chance to vote the hosts off the show before they start
eliminating the house guests?
</P>
<P>
   But back to the Web site. Frankly, I never understood the
fascination with the JenniCam or the coffee pot cam or other Web
sites that chronicle the minutiae of everyday existence. Certainly,
there's nothing particularly riveting about www.dotcomguy.com, the
site started by a rather dull fellow in Texas who vowed to
sequester himself away from the world and survive off the Internet.
He just sits around and buys stuff.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, there is something seductive about the concept
of bigbrother2000.com. After all, it provides an opportunity for
self-respecting intellectuals who would never _ never! _ take part
in such a stunt: We get to make fun of the folks on the show and
dish about their outfits, their hairdos, their temperaments, and,
with any luck, their mating habits.
</P>
<P>
   But by late last week the only clucking going on in Big
Brotherville was happening in the chicken coop, as the residents
learned how to feed and water the hens. Most of the action was
mundane getting-to-know-you stuff as the residents made breakfast
and small talk. There was some sort of minor crisis over the lack
of an electric shaver, but other than that, everyone seemed to be
getting along swimmingly. But hey, who knows what will happen when
they have to change the chemicals in the pool?
</P>
<P>
   For now, tuning into the Big Brother site is a bit like watching
corn grow, which, by the way, is a popular online activity (see
www.iowafarmer.com/corncam/corn.html). The residents are making
nice: No one has asked Jordan to elaborate about her career as an
exotic dancer, and no one has challenged beauty queen Jamie to a
duel of wits. And the only hint of creepiness occurred when a
disembodied voice instructed the residents to change the batteries
in their microphones, reminding us that Big Brother is watching
them as we watch ``Big Brother.'' Orwellian, it's not. But things
may heat up. Apparently Jordan is trying to convince everyone to
perform a Big Brother rap. We may get that production number, after
all, and who knows what kind of costumes the former exotic dancer
will design.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Nielsen/Net Ratings released figures for the top
live-action and animated Web sites. At the top of the list? None
other than www.joecartoon.com, the home of animated games like the
Frog in the Blender and Shoot the Singer. The mom-and-pop site beat
out corporate ventures like atomfilms.com and Warner Bros.'
entertaindom.com.
</P>
<P>
   So who is the mastermind behind these sick games for geeks? That
would be Joe Shields, who will be happy to tell you about himself
if you give him a minute to go fetch a beer.
</P>
<P>
   So who are you, Joe? The short version: ``I'm a big, fat,
beer-drinkin', fishin' cartoonist,'' says Shields, 39.
</P>
<P>
   The ``log cabin'' version: ``I'm one of those guys who drew on
his desk in high school,'' he says, explaining how he grew up in
Michigan, learned screen-printing in Gloucester, Mass., got an arts
degree from Montserrat College of Art in Beverly, and later
returned to Michigan for a short-lived career in auto parts. He
then worked as a T-shirt designer and put a few of his designs up
on the Web in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   His work mixes the adorable and the macabre: Let's say it's an
acquired taste. ``Someone said I was a cross between Stephen King
and Gary Larson,'' he notes. It was that comparison that inspired
him to create the famous frog animation, which he posted on his Web
site in April 1999. Suddenly, the obscure fishin' and drinkin'
cartoonist wasn't so obscure anymore; at the height of the frog
frenzy, his site generated 700,000 hits a day.
</P>
<P>
   The site now makes a comfortable profit (``We do very well'')
for Shields and his Webmaster, who goes by the nickname Russ the
Barbarian. The secret? ``There was no business plan, no target
audience, no market stategy, no nuthin' _ just me feeling free,''
explains Shields, who says he has turned down offers from film and
television producers but hopes to get a film deal within the next
six months.
</P>
<P>
   So much for ``Big Brother'' and other Hollywood attempts to make
a buck off entertainment online. ``You have dot-coms out there with
all kinds of venture capital and committees and business plans, and
then there's one guy out there all by himself,'' says Shields, who
doesn't suffer from insecurity. His motto: ``If Joe thinks it's
funny, it is. If you don't, you're stupid.'' Consider your options.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 1354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
