<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 E-MAILING OVER THE BOUNDING MAIN: NAVY GOES HIGH-TECH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's Sunday night, and a queue of impatient sailors forms
outside a brightly lit room aboard the USS McFaul. It's not the
chow line; the main evening meal is over and the late-night
``midrats'' snack is some hours away. Nor are they waiting for
permission to enjoy a night on the town; the McFaul is cruising at
18 knots, heading eastward into the Atlantic from New York.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the men and women of the destroyer McFaul are lined up
waiting to check their e-mail. There was a time when sailors would
be out of touch with home for weeks or months. The youngsters
aboard McFaul will never know such a world. These days, the Navy
depends on an intricate system of global communications that
ensures that a ship is never out of touch. Neither are its sailors.
</P>
<P>
   ``E-mail is the stuff around here right now,'' says Garlon
Payton, a fireman aboard the McFaul.
</P>
<P>
   Payton knew nothing about e-mail when he joined the Navy three
years ago. Neither did his father and sister, who live in
Charleston, S.C. Today, they're all hooked up; father and sister
each have America Online accounts, and like every member of the
McFaul crew, Payton has his own e-mail address. Whether he's tied
to the dock at the McFaul's home port of Norfolk, Va., or cruising
the Mediterranean, Payton and his shipmates are never very far from
home.
</P>
<P>
   Providing e-mail access for its 320-person crew is a trivial
matter for the McFaul, a floating showpiece of advanced technology.
Named for a US Navy SEAL commando killed during the 1989 invasion
of Panama, the McFaul was commissioned in 1998 and still hasn't
lost its new-warship smell. It's one of the most advanced surface
ships in the fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of old-fashioned boilers or diesels, its propellers are
driven by four jet engines similar to those used on DC-10
airliners. As a result, the 9,000-ton ship accelerates dramatically
under full power, and at its top speed of about 30 knots, or 35
miles per hour, the McFaul kicks up a wake like a speedboat.
</P>
<P>
   The superstructure is covered in spongy plastics to make the
ship harder to spot on radar. Meanwhile its own radar detects every
ship and aircraft for miles in all directions, though the Navy
won't say exactly how many miles.
</P>
<P>
   The ship seems lightly armed with a single five-inch naval gun.
But then there are ominous gray doors, fore and aft, flush with the
deck so a visitor can sit on them. Each of the doors can be loaded
with a Tomahawk cruise missile or a Standard anti-aircraft missile
There are also anti-submarine missiles and six torpedoes, and room
to park a sub-hunting helicopter on a pad in the rear.
</P>
<P>
   The McFaul can go someplace fast, and do a lot of damage when it
gets there. But the Navy believes that its ships will become
dramatically more effective when they can share information, in a
process that Navy spokesman Lt. Cmdr. Randy Britton calls
``network-centric warfare.''
</P>
<P>
   The combined data stream from dozens of warships and planes can
be blended into a three-dimensional ``battlespace.'' Commanders are
transformed into information managers, analyzing the battlespace
and dispatching those assets which are best suited to cope with
particular tasks.
</P>
<P>
   ``With targeting information from one ship,'' Britton said,
``you could actually launch a weapon from another ship.''
</P>
<P>
   The Navy has launched a program called Information Technology
for the 21st Century, or IT21, which aims to achieve this kind of
seamless coordination. Today, many ships have a patchwork of
computer and communications systems, but when the work is done,
every warship will use standardized software, data formats, and
communications systems. Not only will information be accessible
from any ship in the fleet, but the significance of the information
will be clear to any experienced officer.
</P>
<P>
   The IT21 program began in 1997. ``We started with the command
ships and the carriers,'' said Lt. Flex Plexico, spokesman for the
US Pacific Fleet. By the end of last year, nearly all of the Navy's
ships had at least some features of the new systems, including
e-mail and limited World Wide Web access. Plexico says the IT21
system will be installed Navy-wide by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits of IT21 extend beyond the battlespace.
</P>
<P>
   ``IT21 is about war-fighting,'' said Plexico. ``It's also about
administration . . . and quality of life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Navy can save time and money by using efficient computer
networks to plan maintenance and order supplies. And sailors
scattered around the globe will be able to contact families and
friends without even having to pay for a postcard.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail goes out from standard PCs running Microsoft Corp.'s
Windows NT operating system, and Microsoft's Outlook e-mail
program. The e-mail computers are connected to the ship's
unclassified data network, used to link administrative computers
throughout the vessel. Secret information is handled over a secure
network that never comes in contact with the Internet-connected
system.
</P>
<P>
   Sailors get no access to Internet chat rooms, instant messaging
services, or the Usenet system of bulletin boards. Web access on
the ship is quite limited. Sailors can check out CNN, the ESPN
sports site, and a few others. But the ship uses software to block
out all Web sites that haven't been officially approved. That cuts
down on porn-site viewing, of course, but also prevents access to
thousands of innocuous and valuable Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the McFaul isn't the best place in the world to do
Web-surfing. It's connected through the ship's Inmarsat satellite
telephone system. This system provides just 64 kilobits per second
of data bandwidth, and half of that is reserved for voice traffic.
So all Internet users on the ship must share a mere 32-kilobit
pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   That's actually pretty fast compared to some of the satellite
systems used for military communications. Critical traffic often
goes over radio links that can handle just 2,400 bits per second.
Slow as this is, it's enough to let ships exchange vital tactical
information. If more speed is needed in a combat situation, the
McFaul can commandeer the Inmarsat bandwidth as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy isn't immune to computer vandals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had a couple of virus incidents, very limited in
scope,'' said Warrant Officer Stephen Fowler. For example, the
McFaul received an unwelcome visit from the Melissa computer virus
during its global rampage last year.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa was designed specifically to attack computers running
Microsoft software. In addition, Microsoft products have a
reputation for unexpected breakdowns, including the notorious
``Blue Screen of Death'' crash that forces the user to restart the
machine. Such a malfunction left the cruiser USS Yorktown dead in
the water for three hours in 1997, when Windows NT-based engine
room computers crashed during a test.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was caused by entry of bad data, not a bug in NT
itself. But Microsoft critics say that in a well-designed operating
system, incorrect data should not cause a crash. In any case, the
failure demonstrated that in a warship, the software for critical
ship systems has to be absolutely reliable.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the weapons, navigation, and engineering systems on
McFaul and other ships rely on specially designed, highly reliable
software, not off-the-shelf products from Microsoft or other
vendors. In warfare, said Lt. Cmdr. Britton, ``if you get the Blue
Screen of Death, it really is the Blue Screen of Death.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Navy continues to experiment with civilian gadgets as
well. For instance, it's begun issuing Palm Pilot handheld
computers to officers as replacements for their traditional paper
``wheelbooks.'' If it works out, it's possible that every sailor in
the fleet will be similarly equipped.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to make the sailors more productive, because there
are likely to be fewer of them. In recent years, the Navy has found
it difficult to recruit new sailors and retain its veterans.
</P>
<P>
   One of the young men lined up to send e-mail, 20-year-old
Machinery Repairman Peter Chiu, has been with the McFaul since it
was commissioned. Chiu gets out in another month, and he can hardly
wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's been around here since commissioning,'' he said,
``and they're all ready to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   The Navy's working hard to bolster recruiting, even hiring
controversial filmmaker Spike Lee to make TV commercials for the
service. But it's also planning a new generation of highly
automated warships that simply won't require as many sailors. The
next generation of destroyers, due to set sail by decade's end,
will be as capable as the McFaul, but will be operated by just 95
sailors. If it works, it'll save the Navy millions in personnel
expenses. And there'll be shorter lines outside the e-mail rooms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
