<HEADLINE>
TEEN GETS MICROSOFT'S RESPECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SANDY COLEMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Joel Lamousnery didn't get his first computer until
three years ago _ but he hasn't wasted any time learning to use it.
</P>
<P>
   The recent Dorchester High graduate has passed several Microsoft
exams on the first attempt _ a feat many adults fail, according to
Microsoft officials.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the 17-year-old has passed three of six Microsoft
Certified Systems Engineer exams, which measure technical
proficiency and expertise. Many technology companies require them
as hiring criteria, but they are designed for experienced
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a student to pass of his age and experience level shows
dedication and commitment on his part,'' said Anthony Salcito,
Microsoft director of education for the East region. ``They are
difficult tests. They aren't easy to pass on the first try.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider a sample question:
</P>
<P>
   You have just installed a NE2000 Ethernet network adapter card
in a workstation with the following configuration: IRQ(EQ)3,
I/O(EQ)300h, MEM(EQ)CC000. What type of problem could result from
this installation?
</P>
<P>
   A. A potential IRQ conflict with COM1
</P>
<P>
   B. No problem, the PC is configured correctly.
</P>
<P>
   C. A potential IRQ conflict with COM2
</P>
<P>
   D. A potential IRQ conflict with the floppy drive
</P>
<P>
   The answer is C.
</P>
<P>
   Lamousnery will be in elite company if he passes all the exams.
To date, only 268,000 people nationwide have earned the credential.
</P>
<P>
   It is ``a big deal that carries a lot of weight in the IT
world,'' said Marie Smith, a manager at Bell Atlantic's technical
support division, where Lamousnery is interning this summer. Smith
knows of managers who have taken courses to prepare for the exams _
but shied away from taking them in the end.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Lamousnery the secret of his success on the exams, and he
shrugs it off with ``maybe I got lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   He took the exams, he says, to prepare for his career. He will
attend Northeastern University in the fall to study management
information systems. His goal: to oversee an information technology
company.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare for the exams, Lamousnery took courses through
TechBoston, a Boston public schools program that trains high school
students to get certified in several computer fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very proud of Joel,'' said Mary Skipper, TechBoston
director. ``He's the epitome of what we want TechBoston students to
be. . . . He's the active student in his learning. We're feeding
him stuff, but he's taking it and learning on his own.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamousnery asked his father years ago to buy him a computer, but
he can't recall exactly what he wanted to use it for. Initially, he
used it to research and write papers for school, then to manage a
life brimming with after-school activities that included mentoring
middle school students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to use it like a very important tool to do all the
stuff I have to do in my life, and I wanted to learn it more,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lamousnery's passion also led him to build his own computer,
piece by piece, ordering parts over the Internet from eight
companies and paying for it with money he earned working as a
grocery store cashier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted something faster,'' he said. It cost him about $900
and took him about an hour to put together.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
