<DOCNO> NYT20000713.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1018 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-13 1719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY HARRY HAS SPECIAL POWERS _ OVER US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Let's face it,'' says educational consultant Jim Trelease,
whose career is devoted to getting children to read. `` `Harry
Potter' is the best thing to happen to children's books since the
invention of the paperback.''
</P>
<P>
   What is it about ``Harry Potter,'' anyway?
</P>
<P>
   Since ``Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire,'' the fourth book
in the series by J. K. Rowling, debuted Saturday, children have
been spotted reading in some of the darndest places, from the
bleachers of a Little League game to the line outside an ice cream
shop. At a family anniversary party in Weston, Mass. Sunday, four
10-, 11-, and 12-year-olds were walking around with heads stuck in
the 734-page tome.
</P>
<P>
   So what has Rowling tapped into that no other author of
children's literature ever has managed to do, landing two of her
books on the New York Times's Best Seller List simultaneously?
</P>
<P>
   Trelease's theory is that they are page-turners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many books written for kids in recent years have been
issue-driven, about topics adults think kids should be reading,''
says Trelease, of Springfield, Mass. and author of ``The Read-Aloud
Handbook, 4th Edition'' (Penguin). ``These books are exciting. You
can't wait to know what happens next.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough, but Andy Barza, a ninth-grader at Beaver Country
Day School in Boston's Chestnut Hill section, gets to the nub of it
perhaps better than any adult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry has powers every kid wishes he could have,'' he says.
``What kid doesn't want to be in control of his life as well as the
world around him?''
</P>
<P>
   Put another way, Rowling writes about issues that most children
spend a lot of time thinking about, even if they can't or don't
talk about them, and she does it without hitting them over the
head. She grabs readers almost immediately by making Harry an
orphan and a scapegoat, someone treated by his aunt and uncle
``like a dog that had rolled in something smelly.''
</P>
<P>
   Killing off parents is a familiar refrain in good children's
literature because it makes the children the main doers, says
internationally known language-arts educator Lucy Calkins. As an
orphan who goes to boarding school and whose foster parents are
glad to see him go, Harry gets a double whammy. That alone
translates to enormous control. That he has magical powers on top
of that makes Harry even more delicious.
</P>
<P>
   Rowling is onto some big themes here, the universal childhood
fears of desertion, rejection, and inadequacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``As scary as it is for them, all kids fear they will be
abandoned,'' says children's literature specialist Masha Rudman, a
professor at the University of Massachusetts at Amherst. ``They
think about losing their parents, being isolated, and not being
able to survive. Harry offers reassurance that they could.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes of his own doing, sometimes not, Harry frequently gets
into frightening dilemmas, and because Rowling is so clever, we
can't be sure he'll survive unscathed. Therein lies another
strength of the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``He fails on occasion, but it doesn't kill him,'' says Rudman.
``Since fear of failing in all sorts of ways is another big issue
in childhood, he gives us hope that even when we fail, there is
still a chance for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowling also creates personalities children can identify with,
says reading specialist Julie Wood of Harvard's Graduate School of
Education. ``Every child knows an overachiever, a strict but
affectionate mistress, a bully,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The variety of characters is one reason 10-year-old Conor
Detwiler is a big fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This book isn't just about Harry,'' he says. ``There are other
people talking, so you hear people your age, no matter what your
age is, and you can wonder, `Well, would I do that?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Rudman speculates that Conor isn't the only reader framing
questions like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rowling's characters constantly battle with the give-and-take
between good and evil, and so do children,'' she says. ``In the
book, you don't know which direction things will go in, to the dark
side or the light side, the evil or the good, and that's often how
children feel: as if there's a war going on within them and the
outcome is a mystery, right down to the minute they act.''
</P>
<P>
   For Wood, it's more than the universality of Harry's struggles
that make the books work.
</P>
<P>
   ``They cut across social class and economics. They aren't full
of middle-class affluence the way `Babysitters Club' and other
series are,'' she says. ``Harry lives under the staircase (in his
uncle's home). He's impoverished, economically and emotionally.''
</P>
<P>
   As cofounder of the Literacy Institute at the Neighborhood House
Charter School in Boston's Dorchester neighborhood, Wood has seen
``Harry Potter'' serve as an entry into reading for kids who
previously didn't like to read. One 12-year-old boy was so excited
by the books that he got involved in a Web publishing project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a breakthrough for him,'' says Wood, who urges parents
and teachers of nonreaders to find ways to put Harry into the hands
of children, especially those from low-income backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the ``Goblet of Fire'' has been surrounded by so
much marketing hoopla that, depending on your point of view, it was
either brilliant or manipulative, Wood says in one way, at least,
the July date is a gift from the publisher: Children who don't read
over the summer typically lose some of the reading and writing
skills they gained in the previous academic year. The more they
read, and better yet, the more we engage with them about what they
read, the less likely they will fall victim to what educators call
the summer reading lag.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reading is not just eyes over the print. The more thinking and
talking you do with your child between the pages of a book, the
better,'' says Calkins, director of the Reading &AMP; Writing Project
at Teachers College at Columbia University. Her newest book, ``The
Art of Teaching Reading'' (Addison Wesley Longman) is due out next
month.
</P>
<P>
   Whether your child is reading the first ``Harry Potter'' or the
fourth, here are some suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   --Read aloud to him/her. For children who are old enough to
understand it but might not read it themselves, you become a magic
carpet, taking them beyond their ability, says Calkins. Expect a
child who can read for himself to tell you at some point, ``I can't
wait for you.'' Even for him, our involvement is helpful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every book has a song,'' says Calkins. ``You helped him feel
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood says reading aloud expands a child's background knowledge:
``There's great vocabulary in these books, but some kids will read
through words they don't understand. Reading aloud, you can pause:
`What a great word/phrase! Do you know what that means?' ''
</P>
<P>
   --Read along with your child. ``It's a draw to a child to have
you loving the same book,'' says Calkins. Because ``Harry Potter''
is chock full of nuance and foreshadowing, it lends itself to
exclamations such as, ``My gosh, did you realize what that
meant?!'' and to conversations not only about the content but also
about the writing.
</P>
<P>
   --Ask questions. The book could lead a child to form negative
opinions about foster parents (they're all cruel) and rich families
(they're all bad). Rudman recommends asking questions to help a
child argue with the author: How realistic is Harry's foster
family? What is it that makes Ron's family so wonderful? Other
topics to explore: How much did the characters change from the last
book? How good are Harry's decisions? After all, he often succumbs
to temptation even when he knows he shouldn't. Ask a young reader,
``Do you agree with all the decisions Harry makes?'' and an older
one: ``What's the difference between making a good decision and
writing a good story?''
</P>
<P>
   --Alter your child's identity. If your son has always hated
reading, instead of seeing this as a one-time event (``At least
you're reading a book.''), act as if it will continue, says
Calkins: ``What a reader you are! Here you are at 11, entering a
whole new phase of your life!''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps what educators like most about Rowlings's series is what
Calkins calls the Harry Potter phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a perfect illustration of how social reading is for
kids,'' she says. ``Just like kids want to cut their hair the same
as peers, or dress the same, they want to read books that are the
talk of the town. They like to be part of what's in. That the
hottest thing around is a book, well, how fantastic is that?''
</P>
<P>
   Conor Detwiler says ``Harry Potter'' is never boring.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to pay attention to every detail because you know
sooner or later it will be important,'' he says. ``I talk to all my
friends about `Harry Potter.' I don't know anyone who doesn't read
them if they can.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIPS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL; 
--Reading specialists do not recommend ``Harry Potter'' for
children under 7, even if you read it to them. The relationships
among the characters are developmentally beyond them, as is the
line between reality and fantasy. (When the first book came out,
even author J.K. Rowling said her 6-year-old was too young for
it.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
--A child who reads ``Harry Potter'' at 8 or 9 may well enjoy it
again at 12 or 13 because she's at a different developmental stage
and will get something different out of it. &QL; 
 &QL; 
--Readers who like the ``Harry Potter'' series may also like the
Redwall series by Brian Jacques, the Narnia series by C. S. Lewis,
or books by Virginia Hamilton or Philip Pullman. &QL; 
 &QL; 
--Help your child avoid the summer reading lag by making reading
and writing part of summer activities. Some ideas: a summer journal
or diary, an e-mail relationship, a photo essay of a trip, a
library reading program, a kids' publishing project on the
Internet. For other ideas, check out the America Reads Challenge
Web site: www.ed.gov/americareads/summer.html
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ Babies whose fathers are involved during the
first eight weeks of life manage stress better during their school
years, according to studies cited in ``Father Facts, 3d edition,''
published by the National Fatherhood Initiative.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Barbara F. Meltz's e-mail adress is meltz(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
