<HEADLINE>
DO SUNBLOCK FILMS FOR WINDOWS REALLY WORK? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C.   HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. We're moving into a steel-beamed condo soon. The windows are
double pane and rated highly for wind resistance. My concern is
about UV rays from the sun, fading carpet, and furniture. I have
heard of a film that can be applied to block the rays. Are such
films effective, and how well do they hold up under washing?
</P>
<P>
   RUBY ANN PRITCHETT, Virginia Beach, Va.
</P>
<P>
   A. If your double-paned windows have Low E glass, they are
already UV resistant, and nothing more need be done. Low E glass
increases the window's insulating value and tends to reflect heat
and cold, and it helps filter out UV rays. To find out, check with
the manufacturer of the windows or the contractor.
</P>
<P>
   If the windows do not have Low E Glass, you can have them tinted
or coated. Find a company that does this in the Yellow Pages under
``glass coating and tinting.'' Properly done, these coatings should
last through many washings. They are professionally installed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. We are renovating a 20-year-old, U-shaped ranch and would
like to add ridge vents when we redo the roof. We have four gable
vents now, with an attic fan in one of the vents, and soffit vents
all around. Do we keep the gable vents when we add ridge vents?
Also, the soffit vents, which are 12-inch rectangles every 6 to 8
feet, are rusted and bad looking, and my husband wants to replace
them with continuous vent strips. Would this work?
</P>
<P>
   MADELINE and AlAN ARON, Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   A. What you suggest doing is the best thing you can do for your
attic ventilation and for the house. The ridge vent on all ridges
is state of the art, and the continuous 2-inch-wide vent strips in
the soffits will complete the ventilating scheme. Those rectangular
soffit vents are OK except for the rusting, but are way too far
apart to be effective.
</P>
<P>
   It is generally recommended that when ridge and soffit vents are
installed, the gable vents should be closed, because open, they
will interfere with the efficiency of the ridge and soffit vents. I
agree.
</P>
<P>
   You can get rid of the attic fan, unless it is used as a whole
house fan, drawing air from outdoors into the first floor and out
the attic vent. If it is a whole house fan, you can leave it in
place and use it as needed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. We are considering changing our screened-in porch to a
sunroom, with good windows and screens, but we are afraid we would
be creating a hothouse. We don't want to get into heating and air
conditioning. What considerations should be keep in mind?
</P>
<P>
   MARY SONNER, Zionsville, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   A. Your idea of converting the porch into a sunroom is a good
one, particularly if it's on the sunny side of the house. The idea
of a sunroom is to bring sun and heat into the room and into the
house in winter.
</P>
<P>
   In summer, shading and ventilation are important to keep the
room from getting superheated. Also, keeping it separate from the
house, that is, closing it off with an insulated door in summer, is
equally important.
</P>
<P>
   Venting can be done by keeping the windows open for
cross-ventilation, and shading the windows as well. Because heat
rises, it might be a good idea to put in some louvered vents above
the windows. These, of course, should be closed in winter, but in
summer will allow any heated air to escape more readily than
through lower windows.
</P>
<P>
   Shading can be done with window quilts, if you can get them in
the Midwest, sold in specialty home shops. These are most
expensive, but room-darkening shades will be helpful. Outside
awnings also will do a lot toward shading the sunroom.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My son bought a 1930s Tudor-style house in Beverly. Roll
roofing was used to make the siding look like stucco. It is dirty
and weathered, and he'd liked to paint it, but the painters said
asphalt cannot be painted. Is that so? If so, what can he do?
</P>
<P>
   FRANK SHEA, Marblehead, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It ain't necessarily so. There are paints designed to cover
asphalt, but if you cannot find such a paint, consider painting the
siding with Reroof, a special, rubberized coating normally for
apshalt roof shingles. It's made by Masters Choice of Jamestown,
N.Y., 800-766-7622.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Have you ever heard of vinyl shingles, instead of the
standard vinyl siding (horizontal clapboards)? Are they any good,
or better than the siding?
</P>
<P>
   BRIAN McMAHON, Dorchester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, we have heard of them, and have seen them at home shows.
They are different from the standard siding, but they are still
vinyl and, in my opinion, not worth putting on your house. If you
can't opt for wood, consider fiber-cement siding that comes in
clapboards and shingles. While it is an artificial siding, I think
fiber-cement is the best of the non-wood siding. Call 888-542-7343.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail him
at hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
