<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1020 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-BUSH-CATHOLICS-BOS &LR;      07-13 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CATHOLICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINAL GIVES BUSH A RANGE OF CATHOLIC ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For weeks, Cardinal Bernard F. Law prepared for a
private sessionhe'd requested with George W. Bush. But when,
without public notice, the two met last week in San Diego, the
archbishop of Boston raised the issue of abortion only briefly.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, according to two others who sat in on the meeting, Law
used most of his 90 minutes with Bush urging him to take the bold
step of supporting universal health care coverage, a policy goal
more popular with liberal Democrats than conservative Republicans
and even more sweeping and costly than the plan proposed by Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   As Bush nears a decision on a vice presidential candidate, he is
carefully considering the importance of the Catholic vote and the
church's antiabortion view. An early favorite for the vice
presidency, Governor Thomas Ridge of Pennsylvania, is under attack
by some Republicans because he is a Catholic who favors abortion
rights. As a result, some Bush associates who once backed Ridge are
now looking closely at prospects such as Governor Frank Keating of
Oklahoma, who is Catholic and opposes abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   But as Law's session with Bush demonstrates, the idea that
Catholics are focused solely or even mostly on abortion may be
simplistic. No one doubts Law's fervent opposition to abortion,
which is in accord with the teachings of his church. But less
noticed is the Catholic hierarchy's support for expanded health
care and anti-poverty programs. In addition, the church opposes the
death penalty, which Bush favors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Catholics are a complicated question,'' said James Guth,
professor of political science at South Carolina's Furman
University. ``They differ on a lot of things, and the one issue
that binds them is anti-Catholicism.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush stirred sensitivities to anti-Catholicism last February
when he spoke at Bob Jones University, whose leaders had referred
to Catholicism as a cult. Since that appearance in South Carolina,
Bush has been trying to make amends with Catholic voters, assuring
them he has no bias and is seriously considering a Catholic running
mate.
</P>
<P>
   It is by no means certain that Bush will pick a Catholic, but it
is clear that religious affiliation is a concern for the Texas
governor. Catholics make up about 25 percent to 30 percent of the
electorate and a sizable portion swing between the two main
political parties. They are especially numerous in the upper
Midwest, where the Bush campaign believes the election will be
decided.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is under pressure regarding the abortion issue. Some
Catholic leaders recently told the Bush campaign they would be
personally offended if Bush picked Ridge, according to a top Bush
associate, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They basically said, `Don't stick a finger in the eye of the
Catholic Church. If you want to put a prochoice running mate on
your ticket, pick someone from another religion. Don't embarrass
us,' '' said the Bush associate, who now thinks Keating would be a
good choice because the Oklahoma governor, like Bush, opposes
abortion except in cases of rape, incest or when the life of the
mother is endangered
</P>
<P>
   Catholics used to be considered reliable Democrats. John F.
Kennedy captured about 80 percent of the Catholic vote in 1960,
according to Guth. In 1996, the Clinton-Gore ticket won about 54
percent of the Catholic vote, and played a key role in the election
outcome, Guth said. Current polls show that Bush and Gore would
roughly split the Catholic vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Catholics usually end up on the winning side,'' Guth said,
noting that Catholics are just as split on the abortion issue as
the general public.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond L. Flynn, the former Boston mayor and former US
ambassador to the Vatican, said both the Democratic and Republican
parties are ``out of touch'' with Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abortion is one issue, certainly an important one,'' said
Flynn, president of Catholic Alliance, which encourages voter
participation and which Flynn said has 15,000 members. ``But there
are other issues, social and economic justice, that are the
cornerstone of the Catholic faith. The media focus on abortion.''
Flynn said the candidates should court his brand of Catholicism:
``pro-life, pro- family and pro-poor.''
</P>
<P>
   Law's meeting with Bush echoed that theme, and the cardinal was
specific about the need for the Republican Party to embrace
universal health coverage. Law has requested a similar meeting with
Gore, but the cardinal's associates said no session has been
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Law currently is on a retreat and thus would not respond to
interview requests, according to his office.
</P>
<P>
   Law, who requested the meeting weeks ago, met with Bush July 5
at the San Diego Marriott. Two other participants, officials of the
Catholic Health Association, provided an account of the five-person
session. The fifth person was one of the cardinal's aides, while
Bush brought no one from his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Law and the Catholic health officials began by telling Bush the
effort by Congress to balance the budget has been too harsh,
leading to a $100 billion, five-year reduction in federal
assistance to hospitals, many run by Catholic organizations. The
Catholic leaders then presented Bush a written proposal that calls
for providing basic health insurance to the 45 million uninsured
Americans, with an estimated cost of $1,800 to $2,000 per person.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has proposed a variety of federal tax credits and other
programs to help pay for health insurance. Gore has proposed
providing health insurance to all children and says his ultimate
goal is universal coverage. The proposal from Law for universal
coverage is most similar to the plan offered by Bill Bradley during
the Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not make any commitment to Law's proposal, according to
one of the participants, Dr. Michael F. Collins, president of the
Caritas Christi Health Care System of Boston and vice-chairperson
of the Catholic Health Association of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said Law did not mention the vice-presidential selection
and made only a brief comment about abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cardinal made a statement during the meeting that he felt
a commitment to a just health care system was a pro-life message,''
Collins said. ``That was the only reference.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reverend Michael D. Place, president of the Catholic Health
Association and another participant at the meeting, stressed they
were not playing down abortion, but rather they were trying to
expand the meaning of ``pro-life'' to include health care for
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is far to say he shares our concerns'' about health
coverage, Place said of Bush. ``He did not go on to agree with our
strategies.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal Law and the others handed Bush could be viewed as
tying the antiabortion position and universal health care together.
``Human life is sacred and each person has inherent dignity,'' the
document said. ``There is a human right to basic and compassionate
quality health care, regardless of age, income, illness, or
condition of life, and a morally responsible society has an
obligation to provide it.''
</P>
<P>
   Keith Fournier, a co-founder and chaplain of the Catholic
Alliance, said the proposal for universal coverage is an emerging
focus of Catholic leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life goes from conception to natural death,'' Fournier said.
``Of course we oppose abortion. It is a barometer issue. But there
are many more issues. How we do we treat people across their lives?
There is concern for the poor. Either party is mistaken if they
think they can just get the Catholic vote by pandering.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
