<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1028 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-BIG-BROTHER-BOS &LR;      07-13 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BIG-BROTHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BIG BROTHER' IS BUSY SPYING, BUT WHO'S WATCHING? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At some point during the first week of ``Big Brother'' _ was it
when schleppy George donned the Lulu wig and William taught him the
funky chicken, or was it when cartoon-haired Brittany sobbed over
an ailing hen? _ I did feel a little unnerved.
</P>
<P>
   No, it wasn't because TV voyeurism is pulling up the stakes of
civilization and threatening to turn us all into
dignity-and-privacy-starved Pagongs. And it wasn't because most of
the nation has yet to get hooked on this hugely hyped TV
experiment, whose ratings have been mostly down since last
Wednesday's off-putting primer episode. It was because I was
getting bored and distracted, hungry for some ``reality'' action,
wondering if I could rustle up a tape of the late ``Melrose
Place,'' another soap opera series with a pool conveniently
provided for the baring of flesh. Now, there was some dish on a
platter.
</P>
<P>
   So far, and that's an important qualification, watching ``Big
Brother'' is only slightly more exciting than watching a drugstore
surveillance tape. One week in, CBS's five-nights-a-week series
remains slow, self-conscious, and visually sterile. It is notably
short on its genre's most important ingredients: conflict,
alliance, flesh, and human nature on a binge. Those are what give
us the material to judge the cast members _ and our judgment and
debates are what float shows like this and ``Survivor'' (Richard
sucks!). To be fair, reality melodrama can be a slow-blooming
phenomenon; it takes time for hatred, dissent, contempt, and sexual
tension to grow. But in the meantime, we're left with full-frontal
images of cast members brushing their teeth, a game of poolside
footsie, and 10 characters who have yet to let themselves go.
</P>
<P>
   Once they do, ``Big Brother'' may catch fire. Tuesday night's
episode revealed what the show could become, as some of the _ what
do you call them? detainees? _ began to grate on one another's
nerves. William once again proved to be incendiary, going head-on
with Brittany about her limited view of race in America. He failed
to articulate his criticism, and she was too defensive to help him;
but emotions ran high, with the 25-year-old nose-ringed virgin
sobbing that her best black friend is not token.
</P>
<P>
   The show may gain more momentum as the housemates choose two
candidates for banishment. (Viewers will then vote by phone, and
next Thursday the loser will be kicked out.) This rejection process
will surely raise the house temperature, as well as viewers'
interest; it's what gives ``Survivor'' such water-cooler intensity.
It brings out ``The Lottery'' in us all.
</P>
<P>
   William, of course, is the most likely to be booted, though I'd
hate to see him go. He's openly provocative, trying to make fools
of the group by falsifying a ``Big Brother'' challenge, rolling his
eyes about the sick-chicken crisis, and yet he's oddly sympathetic
as a fish out of water. He has kept ``Big Brother'' from imploding,
particularly as other housemates withhold their controversial data.
Jordan, for instance, keeps quiet about her exotic-dancing job,
even when the conversation begs for disclosure. And Jamie has
whispered to only a sacred few that she is, in fact, currently Miss
Washington USA.
</P>
<P>
   The second nominee for rejection? Despite his cancer history
(where did that get poor Sonja on ``Survivor''?), and despite his
braveness about having lost a leg, Eddie may be annoying the group
with his macho, Rocky-like ways. He can be narcissistic, believing
Jordan's critique of models was somehow aimed at him and his model
girlfriend, and he's too businesslike, wearing a T-shirt that reads
``Potential Millionaire.'' Also on the short list: George, the
suburban dad who wants to be loved a little too much. He's not as
funny as he thinks he is. And Curtis: Say something, dude.
</P>
<P>
   But it's hard to muster passion about the impending ``Big
Brother'' eviction at this point. Right now, ``Big Brother'' is
what Henry James labeled certain fat 19th-century novels: a loose,
baggy monster. It's filled with dead air _ conversational pauses,
sluggish camera zooms, and mundane tasks as filler. With five
episodes a week, and not much time to edit, the editors leave their
footage ragged and shapeless. Real-time postmodern art? Perhaps.
But the fast-paced episodes of ``The Real World'' and ``Survivor''
are just about poetry compared to ``Big Brother.'' They are
carefully distilled from days of shooting and made dense with
drama. You feel the editors working to create a story to engage you
(at the expense of documentary accuracy, of course). Watching ``Big
Brother,'' you feel abandoned by the man behind the curtain, left
to the eternal rigors of 24/7 2000.
</P>
<P>
   It also doesn't help that the packaging of ``Big Brother'' is so
very blah. The introductory graphics are cheesy, in a
computer-generated, local-newscast kind of way, and the generic New
Age-y soundtrack is no better. The voice of Big Brother, which
introduces segments with lines like ``Racial tensions heat up in
the kitchen,'' is vacant and humorless. And if the dazzlingly
playful ``Real World'' homes are eye candy, then the ``Big
Brother'' house is the opposite of eye candy; it's visual Novocain.
</P>
<P>
   Who designed this joint _ Samuel Beckett? Is it manufactured to
drive the inhabitants insane?
</P>
<P>
   Dare we hope so?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
