<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BROTHERS-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ None of the five senses
feels safe from assault in the Maly Theater's robust two-part
production of ``Brothers and Sisters,'' adapted from a trilogy
known as ``The Prysalins,'' by the Russian novelist Fyodor Abramov,
and part of the Lincoln Center Summer Festival 2000. By Ben
Brantley.
</P>
<P>
   NY-KRUGER-RETROSPECTIVE (New York) _ Barbara Kruger's
retrospective, which has landed at the Whitney from the Museum of
Contemporary Art in Los Angeles, represents a career whose concerns
were fixed in the 1970s and early '80s, along with the arguments
about it. By Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   YORUBA-AMERICAS-ART (New York) _ ``Beads, Body and Soul: Art and
Light in the Yoruba Universe,'' at the Museum for African Art in
SoHo and the Studio Museum in Harlem, is as opulent as it is
edifying, and follows the migration of one people's beading
tradition _ and the religious beliefs it reflects _ from Africa to
various parts of the Americas. By Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   CARRACCI-BAROQUE-ART (New York) _ Over the past 30 years, the
Metropolitan Museum has assembled a splendid collection of work by
the Carracci: four paintings _ three acquired in the last six years
_ 17 drawings and a slew of prints. A selection from these holdings
is on display in ``The Birth of Baroque: Carracci at the
Metropolitan.'' By Grace Glueck.
</P>
<P>
   NABOKOV-BUTTERFLY-SEARCH (Undated) _ While Vladimir Nabokov was
writing in the 1940s, he also studied the anatomy of butterflies at
the Museum of Comparative Zoology at Harvard. On June 2, 1950, he
visited the Pine Bush in upstate New York for the first time to
look for Karner blues, a butterfly that he had identified and name
from old specimens but had never seen in the wild. Fifty years
later _ to the day _ we followed in his footsteps. By Margaret
Mittelbach and Michael Crewdson.
</P>
