<HEADER>
A1042 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-AUTOS-SUV-COMPETITION     07-13 1367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-SUV-COMPETITION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTO INDUSTRY RETHINKING THE FUTURE OF SUVS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESA, Ariz. _ America's marriage with sport utility vehicles has
always been a love-hate relationship.
</P>
<P>
   We love them for their utility, the sense of security they give
to occupants, and what they say about our active lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
   We hate them for their gas-guzzling and environmentally harmful
ways, their tendency to tip over, the threat to occupants of
smaller vehicles, and what they say about our selfish lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
   At General Motors' Desert Proving Grounds in Mesa, college teams
from 15 engineering schools around the country worked recently, in
a program called FutureTruck, to help save the marriage. Each team
was given a new Chevrolet Suburban, modest financial backing, and
free expert advice. Their mission: Build the SUV of the future.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge came as SUVs and pickups (classified, along with
vans, by the government as trucks) approach a regulatory and
consumer crossroads _ over safety questions, the reality of
escalating gasoline prices, and stricter government rules on
emissions and gasoline mileage _ even as their sales numbers
continue to rise.
</P>
<P>
   Automotive News projects that this year 9,138,184 trucks will be
built in North America, and 8,172,244 cars. By 2004, that gap will
widen from 9,692,789 to 7,492,446.
</P>
<P>
   It is a situation, says Shelley Launey, director of the Clean
Cities Program for the US Department of Energy, that could put both
the FutureTruck participants and their experimental vehicles at the
heart of efforts to build a cleaner, more efficient fleet of
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Already manufacturers recognize the conflict between consumers'
hearts and consciences. Ford Motor Co. recently acknowledged in
presenting its corporate annual report that its SUVs need to be
cleaner and safer.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Toyota had announced, even as it unveiled the latest in
what will be a fleet of five SUV models, that it needs to become
``greener'' in its offerings.
</P>
<P>
   And before that, Dodge announced that its popular Durango will
be offered with a 6-cylinder, hybrid gasoline-electric engine that
is cleaner, gets better mileage, and is stronger than its current
V-8.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks of testing the Suburbans at the Desert Proving Grounds
showed that GM and the students _ along with Dodge and its Durango
SUV _ are riding what could become a wave of hybrids that use
electric motors to boost the efforts of smaller gasoline engines.
It exploits technology that is already being introduced in cars
from Toyota, Honda, Ford, and GM.
</P>
<P>
   Students, engineers, and industry officials all agreed that the
lineup of rebuilt Suburbans at the Desert Proving Grounds was
symbolic of where America stands today in its efforts to build
cleaner, more efficient vehicles. Of the 15, there were no solely
electric SUVs; 14 of them were some variation of the hybrid, and
the one fuel cell vehicle (a technology believed to be 10-20 years
away) was lacking a major component: the fuel cell.
</P>
<P>
   The fuel cell _ with liquid hydrogen as its key element _
generates electricity by combining hydrogen and oxygen atoms in a
reaction with only two byproducts: water vapor and heat. But it
remains prohibitively expensive _ as much as $1 million for a
single cell today.
</P>
<P>
   In hybrids, electric motors work in conjunction with regular
gasoline engines, sometimes powering the vehicle themselves on
short trips or at times working to boost the power of the gas
engine that would be smaller than typically used. When the vehicle
is running on the gas engine, braking causes the electric motor to
work as a generator, charging the car's batteries for future use.
</P>
<P>
   Honda's Insight and Toyota's Prius, two small cars powered by
hybrid engines, are selling well in the United States, and both
will probably become the basis for hybrid models of more standard
autos. Honda will offer its popular Civic model in the United
States as a hybrid beginning in 2002. GM and Ford have displayed
high-mileage prototypes of hybrid sedans.
</P>
<P>
   But considering that trucks now outsell cars in the United
States, and that they tend to consume far more fuel than their
smaller counterparts, specialists say that modest gains in fuel
efficiency in the truck fleet would be more beneficial than strides
in smaller vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, even as gasoline prices soared this spring and summer,
there was no noticeable effect on the sales of trucks and SUVs.
Those in the industry, from Ron Zarella, president of General
Motors-North America, to Don Madden, a local Ford dealer, say that
SUVs continue to sell because people who can afford to drop $40,000
to $50,000 for a vehicle aren't fazed by spending a few hundred
dollars more per year for gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   But reform is surely on the way. Half of the participants in
this year's and subsequent FutureTruck competitions will end up
with jobs in the auto industry, said Launey of the Department of
Energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll bring with them the interest in and understanding of
advanced vehicle technology that includes an appreciation of fuel
economy and reduced emissions,'' Launey said.
</P>
<P>
   And with the fuel cell concept appearing ``like it's a long time
before it's going to be competitive,'' she added, ``any program
where maintaining the power and utility of the vehicle is the goal,
you almost have to be hybrid.''
</P>
<P>
   So the students from colleges and universities in the United
States and Canada came to FutureTruck _ sponsored by GM, the
Department of Energy and Yahoo.com _ with hybrids.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Institute of Technology kept the stock 5.3-liter V-8
Vortec engine that came in the Suburban, burned reformulated
gasoline and aided it with a high-torque electric motor to help cut
gasoline consumption during heavy tasks.
</P>
<P>
   The University of California at Davis powered its Suburban with
a 1.9-liter Saturn engine and aided it with an electric motor that
kicked in to help with acceleration and towing.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Maryland went with a 3.8-liter 6-cylinder
engine that ran on ethanol and was boosted by an electric motor.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Wisconsin replaced the Suburban's steel frame
with an aluminum frame to save weight.
</P>
<P>
   And West Virginia University coupled a 4.2-liter turbocharged
diesel engine with an electric motor and managed a powerful 260
horsepower.
</P>
<P>
   The schools competed in safety, performance, towing ability,
greenhouse emissions, fuel economy, and consumer acceptability. No
one offered radical safety solutions _ though advances in this area
are already coming from manufacturers in the form of SUVs and
trucks with lower impact rails to prevent them from climbing over
smaller vehicles in crashes. In addition, manufacturers are
planning a host of SUVs that more closely resemble the
old-fashioned station wagon with big but safer lower stances.
</P>
<P>
   But the potential for gasoline mileage and environmental
improvements presented by the students was impressive, judges said.
</P>
<P>
   West Virginia, whose Suburban reduced greenhouse emissions 23
percent, was the overall winner.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Tech truck won the towing competition, a grueling
test through 112-degree heat across the arid landscape, even as it
saved gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   And the UC-Davis SUV, which can run on strictly electric power
while in the city, managed 18.7 miles per gallon, nearly a 20
percent increase over stock Suburban performance.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers must still be convinced that hybrid powerplants can
perform much like standard engines _ and Honda's Insight is
apparently doing just that as sales have persuaded the manufacturer
to boost its 2000 production for the United States from 4,000 to
6,500 and expand the hybrid concept to the Civic.
</P>
<P>
   So the marketplace and the SUV experimenters appear to be moving
in the same direction: more efficient and more environmentally
friendly hybrid power.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't have electric until we have the fuel cell, and right
now nobody's got it,'' said Luciano Martin, the technical adviser
for the team from Montreal's Concordia University. ``Right now,
hybrid is what we've got.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
