<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ROSEMARY: A PERFECT DINNER COMPANION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LISA STEVENS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Rosemary, long the symbol of remembrance, love
and death, was used in ancient Greece and Rome in weddings and
funerals to signify enduring affection.
</P>
<P>
   Greek students wore rosemary in their hair to help their memory
during exams. Wreaths containing rosemary were also worn during
festivals. The herb was often called for in magic spells. People
also used to place sprigs of rosemary under their pillows to ward
off nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   It is fitting that the dense, evergreen, aromatic herb, which
grows wild along the Mediterranean coast, is derived from the Latin
meaning ``dew of the sea.'' Use rosemary's soft, blue flowers to
float in punches, in salads or as garnish. The needlelike leaves
are flavorful in a variety of dishes, and the stems, stripped of
their leaves, can be used as skewers.
</P>
<P>
   Rosemary is also known for its medicinal traits. The herb fights
bacteria, can be used as an astringent, aids digestion and
stimulates circulation. It also is good for headaches and high
blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The herb's historical significance is associated with the Virgin
Mary, according to Arabella Boxer and Philippa Back, authors of
``The Herb Book,'' (Peerage Books, 1985). ``The flowers are
believed to have taken their color from her blue cloak when she
threw it over a rosemary bush to dry,'' the authors write. Another
legend claims the flowers received their color when Mary, fleeing
to Egypt, placed her blue cloak over a rosemary bush.
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT: Rosemary
</P>
<P>
   WHAT: A pungent evergreen herb that is a member of the mint
family.
</P>
<P>
   FORMS: Fresh, dried
</P>
<P>
   LOOK FOR: Thin, dark-green needlelike leaves that are aromatic
with a woodsy perfume.
</P>
<P>
   STORE: Fresh sprigs in a plastic bag in the refrigerator for
several days. Store dried rosemary in an airtight container in a
cool, dark place for up to six months.
</P>
<P>
   USE IN: Lamb, chicken, pork and fish dishes, egg dishes,
tomato-based sauces, breads, vegetables, pizza, potato gratins,
apple jelly.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   SKEWERS OF LAMP WITH HERBS
</P>
<P>
   (Adapted from ``The Herb Book'' by Arabella Boxer and Philippa
Back (Peerage Books, 1985)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   1/2 leg of lamb, boned
</P>
<P>
   1/2 medium onion, sliced thinly
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, crushed
</P>
<P>
   6 sprigs lemon thyme
</P>
<P>
   6 sprigs marjoram
</P>
<P>
   3 sprigs lovage
</P>
<P>
   3 sprigs rosemary
</P>
<P>
   3 sprigs parsley
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup red wine
</P>
<P>
   Cut the meat into 1 1/2-inch cubes and place them in a bowl. Add
onion and garlic to the meat. Chop all of the herbs and add to the
meat. Stir in the wine and oil. Marinate for 4 to 6 hours or
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Thread the meat loosely onto skewers. Preheat grill. Over medium
heat, place kebabs on grill rack over heat. Grill 12 to 16 minutes,
turning once halfway through grilling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
