<HEADLINE>
IT'S OFFICIAL: THE THUNDERBIRD RETURNS IN '02 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is the buzzing afterglow that automobile designers and
manufacturers dream about. They unveil a new model at an auto show
and the reaction is electric.
</P>
<P>
   Build it, the public demands. The buzz lingers; the demand is
unending. What's a manufacturer to do? Curiously, however, the
latest buzz vehicles have been, rather than something totally new,
a step back in time. Hence, Volkswagen's New Beetle and Chrysler's
PT Cruiser. See them in a parking space near you.
</P>
<P>
   What's next, readers have asked me.
</P>
<P>
   I give you the Ford Thunderbird, another retro intro, unveiled
as a concept car at the 1999 Detroit International Auto Show. There
has been a constant buzz about the T-Bird ever since. And now it is
official: Ford will build a two-seat Thunderbird beginning next
year and sell it for the 2002 model year.
</P>
<P>
   Like the New Beetle, like the PT Cruiser, it is not really a
retro car. It is purely evocative and that is plenty.
</P>
<P>
   Think back to those mid-1950s Thunderbirds, before Ford lost its
way and made them bigger and uglier down the decades.
</P>
<P>
   Ford itself acknowledges the history of the T-Bird to be one of
``glory years, dark days'' but now proclaims a triumphant return.
Thankfully, with its mesh grille, rounded and subtle lines, and
seating for just two, Ford is giving us the best of what the T-Bird
once was. It is reaching back through the decades, through designs
called ``square,'' ``projectile,'' ``jet aircraft,'' and
``luxury,'' through variations that included four doors and
horrific, bulging noses, to give us the car they dreamed up in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   This was in 1954 _ for the '55 model year. The goal, in upbeat,
postwar America was a two-passenger, canvas-topped sports car. They
wanted it under 3,000 pounds, V-8 powered, and capable of topping
100 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Ford delivered a car just over 3,000 pounds with a 102-inch
wheelbase and overall length of 175 inches. It sat just 52 inches
high and was powered by a 292-cubic-inch V8. Price? $3,000-$4,000.
</P>
<P>
   When it came time to name the car, there was some debate.
Imagine if any of these suggestions had been adopted: Beaver, Hep
Cat, Arcturus, or El Tigre. Would we be panting today over the
reintroduction of the Hep Cat?
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, the new Thunderbird draws its lines not from any of
the abominations of the 1970s and '80s, but instead from the '50s
with a dash of the 1961 model tossed in.
</P>
<P>
   The two-seater was a huge success. But Ford, for some reason,
had to tinker with it. The changes for 1956 were fine _ better
cabin ventilation, more trunk space created by moving the spare
tire outside above the rear bumper. Even the portholes in the rear
of the hardtop roof had a certain class to them. But by 1957, the
two-seater was dead. Killed by a bad case of big and ugly. For the
next four decades, we got four-seaters, long roofs, fender skirts,
sharp sculpted lines that looked more Lincoln Continental than
sports car, and those deeply-browed twin headlights. The brows
looked like George Chuvalo after Muhammad Ali pounded on him.
</P>
<P>
   By 1958, the wheelbase had grown to 113 inches and the car was
nearly three feet longer than the original. It also weighed nearly
two tons. The T-Bird retained this ``square'' look until 1961 when
the ``projectile'' look _ with cleaner body lines and sharply
creased where hood met grille _ was introduced. This was a better
looking car, but by the mid-'60s square was back and the ugly
plunge continued.
</P>
<P>
   By 1970, the T-Bird had hit the wall. It got a long hood that
ended in an extruded aluminum grille, called a ``poke-thru-nose.''
The designer of this 4,551-pound behemoth should have been poked in
the nose. By 1997, the T-Bird was, mercifully, dead.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's coming back. New platform, new power, new technology.
More on that in a later column. For now, let's just enjoy the
new/old lines. We're gonna party like it's 1955.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
