<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANS AM'S THE EPITOME OF RETRO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Dude!''
</P>
<P>
   These days, that passes for a sentence, as when the 16-year-old
pumping gas takes one look at the 2000 Pontiac Firebird Trans Am
convertible, with Ram Air, that you are driving and makes the
exclamation.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: That's one boss car.
</P>
<P>
   I'd had some doubts the first time I climbed into this car. At a
time when ``retro'' is in _ Beetles, PT Cruisers, throw-back
convertible sports cars _ the Trans Am doesn't have to don the
retro mantle. It's always been retro and I felt, well, kind of old
driving it.
</P>
<P>
   The kid looked at the Trans Am's snout and saw snorting power. I
looked at it and saw _ Tori Spelling.
</P>
<P>
   I'll grant you, the car does not lack muscle, bold styling, or
raw sound _ all things I like. It's just that it is rooted in the
muscular past. Call it the anti-Porsche: From the driver's seat,
its front fenders disappear from view while the center of the hood
bulges like a popped bicep.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the Mustang and the Camaro, the Trans Am still roams
the Pony Car range. Pontiac bills it as a muscle car with modern
control.
</P>
<P>
   Flick the traction control system on and off in various
situations and you'll see what they mean.
</P>
<P>
   The Trans Am, fresh air introduced into its 5.7-liter pushrod
V-8 via gaping hood snout and through the air cleaner, is a
320-horsepower charger that delivered a remarkable 20 miles per
gallon in a week of driving.
</P>
<P>
   And where many performance cars today seem to suck themselves to
the ground and pin you down in your seat at acceleration, the Trans
Am romps like a racehorse.
</P>
<P>
   Its nose lifts, it snorts, and it throws you back in the saddle.
</P>
<P>
   Straight ahead on the highway, it bursts past other vehicles
and, with or without traction control, changes lanes smoothly.
Cornering on lesser roads, or accelerating (OK, stomping it) from a
standing start, however, can show you both sides of this beast.
</P>
<P>
   Without traction control, stomped starts generate immediate
oversteer (as in the north end of the horse tries to pass the south
end of the horse). With the control on, you still sense this effect
but it fixes itself.
</P>
<P>
   Without traction control and entering a corner as you should at
speed _ that is, with a slight tap of the brakes to set the weight
on your forward, steering wheels _ you find yourself plowing into
the turn and now you are in the world of understeer. Again,
traction control doesn't eliminate the sensation that this is about
to happen, but it does fix it.
</P>
<P>
   The four-speed automatic transmission made its upshifts before I
would like in some instances and if I were to buy this car, I'd go
with the optional 6-speed manual.
</P>
<P>
   The Trans Am is not a small car so you are throwing around a bit
of bulk at high speed when you push it. I was surprised when I
passed a Grand Am on the highway and realized my car was bigger.
</P>
<P>
   Handling this bulk requires beefy suspension and the Trans Am
has got that. Up front there are coil springs of gas-charged shocks
and stabilizer bars. The rear has a rear axle with torque arm,
trailing arm, track bar, coil springs, and stabilizer bar.
</P>
<P>
   It made for a very stiff _ jarring on bumpy roads _ ride and
could not prevent a feeling of torsional twist in corners. In fact,
there was a strange sense of weight shifting to the rear and the
front end floating. You could get into trouble with this car.
</P>
<P>
   The brakes were also not the quickest I have encountered and
larger discs _ over a foot in diameter _ would help here.
</P>
<P>
   All this said, the Trans Am does carry a certain panache for a
particular segment of the population _ either young drivers or
older types still living hot-rod dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Car and Driver magazine has a category for cars such as this:
LAF.
</P>
<P>
   That's loud, affordable, fast.
</P>
<P>
   Face it, the car bulges just sitting there. Muscle car in full
flex.
</P>
<P>
   Pop-up headlights, distinct side moldings running down the side,
that Tori Spelling nose.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, it has a distinct ``Star Wars''/performance persona. The
bucket seats _ front and rear _ are deep and supportive. Good
legroom up front, OK headroom. The rear seats don't have great
legroom, but lay you down nicely with their low posture.
</P>
<P>
   The gauges on the dash can disappear with certain steering wheel
settings, though the rumble of the engine pretty much tells you
what you are up to. Cabin noise is subdued _ you want to hear that
engine burbling, and you do. You don't want to hear wind whistling
through the gaps in a convertible top, and you don't. It's
remarkably quiet, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   I particularly didn't like the odd lump that eats up much of the
floor on the passenger's side up front. Trunk space is adequate
(you certainly could not take four on vacation in this rig), but
thankfully, the rear seat folds down, so you could travel as a
pair.
</P>
<P>
   I understand what this car is _ an enduring throwback _ and
respect its power and twitchiness. Makes me want to climb into a
Camaro and Mustang, just to compare Ponies.
</P>
<P>
   Nice Touch
</P>
<P>
   --The ease with which the roof goes up and down. Even with
manual clips above the windshield, it's only a 20-second job.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyances
</P>
<P>
   --The outside mirrors. Way too small, especially given the
C-pillar blocked view caused by so much canvas roof.
</P>
<P>
   --The dash vents. Circles that don't rotate. It takes an awkward
dual-twist of fins to redirect air.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE NUMBERS
</P>
