A1056 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-WOODY-ALLEN-VIDEO-LAD     07-13 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODY-ALLEN-VIDEO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LITTLE `STARDUST' ON DVD
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Video Column) 
By ROB LOWMAN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call it plain-wrap Woody.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, ``The Woody Allen Collection,'' eight of the
filmmaker's works, arrived in stores on DVD and video. Starting
with his 1971 film, ``Bananas,'' the collection covers Allen's '70s
period, ending with the 1980 film ``Stardust Memories.''
</P>
<P>
   And, except for ``Annie Hall,'' this is the first time the other
seven titles are on DVD. But don't expect a lot of extras on DVD _
unless you count the original trailers. When Allen was in Los
Angeles a few months ago to promote his latest film, ``Small Time
Crooks,'' he flatly stated he wasn't interested in going back and
examining his films _ no sense second- guessing himself. He wanted
them to stand on their own; there would be no director's commentary
or deleted scenes included on the video discs.
</P>
<P>
   So how do they stack up? As Allen noted, his early films were
basically a series of gags strung together. Three of the films in
the collection _ ``Bananas,'' ``Everything You Always Wanted to
Know About Sex but Were Afraid to Ask'' and ``Sleepers,'' to some
extent _ fall into that category. But the humor, for the most part,
is enough to sustain the films. True, some of the jokes are dated,
but having the late outspoken sportscaster Howard Cossell playing
himself in ``Bananas'' _ first doing play-by-play of a banana
republic revolution and then of the wedding of Fielding Mellish
(Allen), the film's nebbish hero _ is comic genius. Likewise, there
are scenes in ``Sex'' (remember Gene Wilder's infatuation with a
female sheep?) and ``Sleeper'' that are as funny today as they were
then.
</P>
<P>
   His 1975 film ``Love and Death,'' his parody of Russian
literature (think ``War and Peace''), was the first time that Allen
integrated his comedy brilliance into a more cohesive, cinematic
work. While there are references to everyone from Tolstoy to the
Marx Brothers to filmmakers Sergei Eisenstein and Ingmar Bergman,
this handsomely shot film illustrates Allen's growth as a
filmmaker.
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, blossomed in ``Annie Hall,'' the 1977 romantic
comedy that won four Oscars, including best picture, best actress
(Diane Keaton) and Allen as best director. In retrospect, the
romantic comedy is a bit overrated, in retrospect (the inclusion of
some slapstick scenes seems somewhat out of place _ almost as if
Allen needed to fall back on reliable shtick), but it's his first
truly mature work.
</P>
<P>
   Allen followed up the success of ``Annie'' with ``Interiors,'' a
drama. If Allen disappointed his fans by abandoning comedy for
Bergman-like angst, he nevertheless made one of the best films
about family in the last 25 years. And as in the case of most of
his films, Allen coaxed outstanding performances from his cast,
this time the magnificent Geraldine Page.
</P>
<P>
   The 1979 ``Manhattan'' is perhaps Allen's best dramedy. The
gorgeously shot black-and-white film (with a George Gershwin score)
is a bittersweet ode to life. The theme of an older man with with a
teen-age girl, though, is bound to be disturbing in light of
Allen's own scandal involving his now wife, who was Mia Farrow's
adopted daughter. If you can divorce yourself from the ``reality,''
it's a fine film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stardust Memories,'' also shot in black-and-white, is a film
that has grown in stature over the years. Another mature work (this
one with a Fellini-esque quality), it points the way to much of
Allen's later films, like ``Bullets Over Broadway'' and ``Purple
Rose of Cairo,'' that examine life in terms of art.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, Allen's right _ the films do stand on their
own. &QL; 
--- The ``Woody Allen Collection'' is priced at $99.98 for VHS and
$134.98 on DVD. Each title is available individually for $14.95 and
$19.98 on DVD. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
