<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1057 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-13 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CLINTON'S OWN MARCH OF FOLLY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CRAGG HINES  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Think Trojan horse, the sack of Rome, Maginot Line.
</P>
<P>
   As President Clinton ponders his next move on the proposed
national missile defense, he could profit from considering Barbara
Tuchman's ``The March of Folly'' more closely than the increasingly
dubious data, analyses and excuses from the Defense Department.
</P>
<P>
   For reasons having more to do with short-term political
expediency than long-term national security, Clinton still seems
likely to go forward with the latest demented progeny of Ronald
Reagan's Star Wars fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton should unexpectedly pull the plug, great; maybe he
will tell us what took him so long.
</P>
<P>
   The president has a list of high-minded criteria he says he'll
use in judging whether to go forward with the project. And when he
announces his formal decision later this year, he may claim it's
only to keep the program alive into the next administration.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming Clinton acts before the presidential election, his
decision will in large part be intended to provide protection for
Al Gore from facing a ``missile gap'' attack from George W. Bush.
The presumptive Republican nominee, like many Republicans in
Congress, already supports a more expansive anti-missile system
than would be provided by the program currently in the works. Bush
also should add Tuchman to his limited reading list.
</P>
<P>
   In her 1984 ``Folly'' book, Tuchman looked back at a long string
of self-defeating (and self-deluding?) political decisions
stretching from Troy to Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``A phenomenon noticeable throughout history regardless of place
or period is the pursuit by government of policies contrary to
their interests,'' Tuchman began. ``Why do holders of high office
so often act contrary to the way reason points and enlightened
self-interest suggests? Why does intelligent mental process seem so
often not to function?''
</P>
<P>
   That certainly seems to be the case in Clinton's drive, to date,
to keep the missile defense program alive. It was thrust upon him
by the Republican-controlled Congress, but that does not mean he
has had to embrace it so warmly.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to use improved technology to produce a super-fast,
super-accurate weapon that can hurtle through space and knock out
incoming intercontinental ballistic missiles. These missiles could
be the mad work of, say, North Korea, Iran or Iraq - the once and
probably future ``rogue states.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. technology had better be significantly improved, because in
the roughly two decades that the Pentagon has salivated over
similar systems, more than two-thirds of the tests have failed. The
dud shot last weekend was only the latest misfire, and the most
recent problem wasn't something really high tech. The ``kill
vehicle,'' which we now know looks like a cross between a fire
hydrant and the corner mail box, didn't even separate from the
booster rocket.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more pressing questions that the latest tests leave
unanswered is: How can the system distinguish between a real
missile and the dozens of decoys that probably would be launched at
the same time. Pentagon tests on the point appear to have been
dumbed down to meaninglessness.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be a unilateral disarmer or a shill for
Russian President Vladimir Putin to think this program is cuckoo
and that the project should be renamed the Pentagon Job Protection
and Defense Contractors Bonanza Act. Fifty Nobel winners, almost
half of them physics laureates, have written to Clinton asking him
to reject the program, saying: ``The system would offer little
protection and would do grave harm to this nation's core security
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   The program also throws a lot of money at a single threat -
missiles - without doing anything about an equally serious
terrorist proposition, say a thimbleful of a deadly bacterial agent
being driven across the border.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-missile system is one of those government projects that
if you have to ask the price, you really can't afford it. Sixty
billion is a rough opening bid. Last weekend's failed test alone
cost $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   You could probably take the tens _ if not hundreds _ of billions
of dollars that would be spent before this thing became operational
and buy off every bureaucrat and secret agent in Pyongyang, Tehran
and Baghdad for the next 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   Then they could call the Pentagon collect far enough in advance
of a missile attack so we could get the Israeli air force to go
bomb the launch site.
</P>
<P>
   Farcical? No more so than the cockamamie national missile
defense system you may be about to pay for.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 1422EDT &QL; 
