<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1061 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-13 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COLORADO'S GODLY IDEA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Just when you think public schools are going to
hell in a handbasket, along comes the Colorado State Board of
Education to show us the way to salvation.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in a 5-1 vote, the board approved a resolution that
urges Colorado schools to display the official motto of the United
States of America.
</P>
<P>
   No, that is not ``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire?''
</P>
<P>
   It's ``In God We Trust.''
</P>
<P>
   First engraved upon our money in 1864 _ as a nose-thumb to all
those European nations with portraits of kings and queens on their
currency _ ``In God We Trust'' became the national motto in 1956
under President Dwight Eisenhower.
</P>
<P>
   To some folks it might seem that the practical effects of Ike's
move have been minimal. How many times a day are YOU inspired to do
something (or not) because you remember ``In God We Trust''?
</P>
<P>
   Clair Orr is not some folks.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Colorado education board, Orr sponsored the
motto resolution. To him, ``In God We Trust'' is as powerful and
worthy of display as any document from the founding fathers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our nation has lost its way on the road to virtue and moral
character,'' Orr said of his resolution. ``We have a moral
obligation to educate our children in the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Four other board members (all Republicans like Orr) agreed. The
only dissenter: Gully Stanford, a Denver Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   The way Stanford sees it, the number of ingredients in America's
melting pot continues to increase. Thus, it seems pushy,
narrow-minded and kind of asking for it to jam the Judeo-Christian
God down every American's throat.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Lynn, a United Church of Christ minister and the executive
director of Americans United for Separation of Church and State,
agrees with Stanford. He called the Colorado board's decision an
attempt to ``meddle in the religious lives of young children.''
</P>
<P>
   Thank heavens Clair Orr and the majority of the board pay Lynn
no mind. They saw an urgent need among public school students and
they responded.
</P>
<P>
   After all, ``In God We Trust'' is stamped on every piece of
paper currency in sight, right? Money is the most ubiquitous and
cross-cultural public forum we have.
</P>
<P>
   If kids are not connecting the acquisition of an Old Navy
T-shirt or boxed collector's set of Tupac CDs to our
Judeo-Christian God, then we must try harder to help them. As Orr
said, we've got a moral obligation.
</P>
<P>
   So, what's say we all take the Colorado board's resolution and
run with it?
</P>
<P>
   Let's not just encourage public schools to display a banner or
sign, let's chisel ``In God We Trust'' above every entrance to
every grammar, middle and high school and every state-supported
university in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, we could completely wrap each school, from roof to
ground level, in ``In God We Trust,'' the way we now wrap public
buses in dot-com and Pepsi ads.
</P>
<P>
   Next, the kids themselves could become walking billboards that
point the way back to the Road to Virtue and Moral Character.
</P>
<P>
   They already perform a similar function for dozens of shoe and
clothing manufacturers. Why not employ one of the Republican
Party's most sacred rituals _ the public/private partnership _ and
get corporate sponsorship for all kinds of national-motto jackets,
shirts, vests, caps and sneakers?
</P>
<P>
   Can't you just see a hall full of 14-year-olds wearing
sweatshirts emblazoned with, ``In God (and Tommy Hilfiger) We
Trust''?
</P>
<P>
   To get kids really into our Judeo-Christian God, each school
district could hold national motto drives. Students, teachers and
parents could compete to see which school could slap ``In God We
Trust'' on the most surfaces. The winners would display a special
congressional banner that proclaims:
</P>
<P>
   ``We're No. 1 in Trusting God!''
</P>
<P>
   As for kids and parents who don't subscribe to the
Judeo-Christian God _ the millions of Americans who are Muslims,
Buddhists, Hindus, nature worshippers, secular humanists and
atheists _ well, that's their tough luck.
</P>
<P>
   When you've gotten so lost on the Road to Virtue and Moral
Character that you believe the posting of a national motto can
actually bring you back, you can't afford such luxuries as freedom
of (or from) religion for all Americans.
</P>
<P>
   And that, according to the Colorado State Board of Education, is
``the truth'' we must teach our children.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
