<HEADER>
A1071 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-AUSTRALIA-REEF-HNS &LR;      07-13 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTRALIA-REEF-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BARRIER REEF-UNDERWATER WORLD UNLIKE ANY OTHER  
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HARRY SHATTUCK  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AGINCOURT REEF, Australia _ Cutting across the Coral Sea aboard
the sleek Quicksilver VIII catamaran, there is little hint of the
intrigue and grandeur hiding beneath the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Then, soaring above the waves in a helicopter based at a pontoon
90 minutes out from Port Douglas, a first clue: more shades of blue
than you ever imagined existed.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the pontoon, plunge beneath the surface, snorkeling or
scuba diving or in a semisubmersible vessel with picture windows,
and enter an underwater world unlike any other: living coral in
brilliant orange and yellow and red and blue; jagged cliffs and
rocky boulders, one amazing formation after another; blue-spotted
trout and green-and-red parrotfish and their kinfolk swimming past
by the thousands, unperturbed by human intruders.
</P>
<P>
   This is the wonder of the Great Barrier Reef, Earth's largest
living organism and most diverse environment.
</P>
<P>
   Defining a lagoon 15-150 miles wide on Australia's eastern
coast, the Great Barrier Reef encompasses almost 3,000 reefs and
900 islands and stretches for 1,250 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Some elements were formed as long ago as 18 million years, but
most of what visitors see today has developed much more recently.
Indeed, the Reef is constantly changing and building, with coral
formed by billions of small, primitive marine animals (or polyps)
that die and let new polyps grow on their skeletons.
</P>
<P>
   While the coral lives only beneath the water's surface, debris
can form small sandbanks that tides sweep together. These provide
refuge for sea birds, which deposit plant seeds (attached to their
feathers or in droppings). This allows the development of
vegetation and, over time, the emergence of a coral island.
</P>
<P>
   This magnificent system is now home to an estimated 400 types of
hard and soft coral; 1,500 species of fish; 4,000 types of
mollusks, including colorful clams and snails; 350 types of sea
urchins, starfish, sea cucumbers and other echinoderms; and
thousands of species of crustaceans, worms and sponges.
</P>
<P>
   It also welcomes hundreds of thousands of humans each year,
requiring concentrated efforts to protect the reef and its
admirers.
</P>
<P>
   Access is easy.
</P>
<P>
   Some continental (noncoral) islands now boast resorts; in the
Whitsundays well to the south, Hayman Island is regarded as one of
the world's most luxurious vacation retreats, combining reef
exploration with gourmet cuisine, fine wines, idyllic swimming
pools and other pampering.
</P>
<P>
   A few true coral cays welcome overnight guests, most notably
Green Island.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise ships ply reef waters on multiday excursions; Captain
Cook Cruises' 168-passenger Reef Endeavor operates leisurely
itineraries from Cairns that last as long as a week.
</P>
<P>
   But for those with limited time and money, day trips by boat
provide a good introduction and memories to last a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   A huge advantage, too, of lodging on the mainland, especially in
Tropical North Queensland, is that so many other natural wonders
merit exploration.
</P>
<P>
   Port Douglas and Cairns make ideal gateways because of the
reef's proximity to this part of the coast and because the
combination of warm water and sunlight allows maximum coral growth
just beneath the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Quicksilver, the region's principal reef tour-boat operator, and
acclaimed for its high-quality product, offers daily excursions to
Low Isles, on the reef's inner fringe about eight miles offshore,
and to Agincourt Reef, 45 miles from Port Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   At Agincourt, the continental shelf rests at depths of only
60-90 feet, in water so clear that visibility averages 50 feet.
Nearby, the ocean floor drops to depths of almost 2,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Voyages to Agincourt Reef aboard the 440-seat Quicksilver VIII
(or a smaller companion catamaran) begin at 8 a.m. from Cairns or
10 a.m. from Port Douglas' Marina Mirage, within walking distance
of downtown. Bus transportation from area hotels is included in the
price, about $85.
</P>
<P>
   (All prices mentioned are in U.S. dollars.)
</P>
<P>
   During the 90-minute ride, marine biologists give background on
the reef, its environmental concerns and reef safety. (Don't stand
on or bump coral; don't harass animals.) Snorkeling lessons are
offered at the reef.
</P>
<P>
   The pontoon _ one of two used here by Quicksilver _ is
remarkable for its practicality. Swimmers and snorkelers depart
from a submerged platform; an underwater observatory allows viewing
of coral and fish; and semisubs depart every 15 minutes. All are
included in the tour price.
</P>
<P>
   A two-minute boat ride takes guests to a floating helicopter pad
from which air excursions depart every 15 minutes. The flights
provide perspective on how the brownish living coral and breaking
surf combine with other factors to create such marvelous blue-green
colors. (Cost is about $65; bookings must be made in
advance.)Organized diving tours (about $40) take place on the edge
of the continental shelf; operators choose from among 20 sites
depending on the day's weather and visibility. Equipment is
provided.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who prefer not to get wet can enjoy the Reef
immensely.
</P>
<P>
   Viewed from the semisub, the underwater landscape is as
bewildering as it is beautiful, dotted with caves and tunnels,
cliffs and shelves, full of contrasts in color and substance. Coral
appears less like animals than like plants clinging to rocks, even
a floral garden. Fish dart in every direction. And don't take those
sluggish sea cucumbers for granted, Quicksilver biologists caution:
They are the ``vacuum cleaners'' of the Reef.
</P>
<P>
   The smaller fish are striking in shape, color and ability. Some
change color when threatened. If a male angelfish dies, biologists
say, its female partner can change sex. Parrotfish are said to
begin life as dark-colored females, complete at least one
reproduction season, then become brightly colored males.
</P>
<P>
   Red-and-blue damselfish, 2 inches in length, share the sea with
900-pound grouper, sharks, six species of marine turtles, dudongs
(also known as sea cows, with whalelike bodies as long as 9 feet)
and, in winter, humpback whales.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors are cautioned against feeding fish, but organized
feedings are conducted twice during the 3 1/2-hour stay at the
pontoon, letting everyone see large schools up close.
</P>
<P>
   Human feeding is scheduled as well; a buffet lunch is included
in the tour price.
</P>
<P>
   Quicksilver's 10 marine biologists, employed in the company's
Reef biosearch division, monitor the area daily to ensure its
protection and preservation. Among recent projects, they have
studied the effects of mainland nutrient runoff on water quality,
the progress of corals around tourist platform sites, the effects
of sunscreen on corals, and the growth rate of 200 giant clams near
Agincourt Reef.
</P>
<P>
   The catamaran arrives back in Port Douglas at about 4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   If, even then, the Reef remains a mystery of sorts, don't feel
alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the environmental subtleties still are not fully
understood,'' one biologist says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 1430EDT &QL; 
