<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1072 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-AUSTRALIA-TIPS-HNS &LR;      07-13 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTRALIA-TIPS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TIPS ON VACATIONING IN TROPICAL AUSTRALIA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HARRY SHATTUCK  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are tips for planning a vacation to Australia's Tropical
North Queensland and the Great Barrier Reef.
</P>
<P>
   Advance Planning: An important firststep in planning a visit to
Queensland - or any other Australian state _ is to request a
vacation planner kit from the Australian Tourist Commission. Call
800-369-6863.
</P>
<P>
   Or access www.australia.com on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Other comprehensive online sites include
www.destinationqueensland.com (the official site of Tourism
Queensland), www.great-barrier-reef.com, www.cairns.aust.com and
www.portdouglas.com.
</P>
<P>
   Packages: A tour packager can help in two ways: (1) combining as
many or as few elements of a trip as the traveler desires; and (2)
supplying discounted air service and lodging. We used Austravel, an
experienced firm. Call 800-633-3404. Qantas Vacations also offers
packages to Queensland that include most of the attractions
mentioned in this section. Call 800-532-6717 or access
www.qantasvacations.com.
</P>
<P>
   Travel agents work closely with these and other tour companies
and can provide brochures and other information.
</P>
<P>
   When to go: Queensland's climate is ideal year-round assuming
heat and humidity aren't a bother. Seasons are reversed in
Australia; our summer is their winter. Many travelers may want to
combine a trip with the 2000 Sydney Olympics scheduled Sept.
15-Oct. 1. For information about remaining Olympics tickets or
packages, call Cartan Tours, the designated U.S. distributor, at
800-841-1994. Or access www.cartan.com.
</P>
<P>
   Documentation: A valid U.S. passport and an Australian visa are
required. A visa costs nothing and is produced electronically, so
you don't have to carry a document. A travel agent or tour packager
can handle details. The visa is valid for up to three months in
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: The Australian dollar has been trading at about $1
Australian to $1.65 U.S. (making Australia a remarkable value for
Americans this year). All prices listed here are in U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Getting around: Car rental firms familiar to Americans have
offices in Cairns and Port Douglas. Prices are reasonable, and a
travel agent or tour packager can make reservations. One caution:
Driving is on the left side of the road. Most day-tour operators
offer hotel pickup service.
</P>
<P>
   Major attractions: The Rainforest Habitat Wildlife Sanctuary is
on Port Douglas Road about three miles south of town. Hours are 8
a.m.-5 p.m. daily.
</P>
<P>
   Admission is about $9.75 (half-price for children). A daily
``breakfast with the birds'' includes entry costs, and staff
members introduce several of the most unusual birds. The cost is
$18.25 (half for children). Access
www.radisson-resorts.com.au/rhab1.html for more information.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian Butterfly Sanctuary is at 8 Rob Veivers Drive in
Kuranda. Hours are 9:45 a.m.-3 p.m. daily. Admission is about $6.50
(half for children). Access www.australianbutter-flies.com.
</P>
<P>
   Skyrail operates from 8 a.m.-5 p.m. daily (except Christmas Day)
between Kuranda and Cairns. The one-way cost is about $16.50 (half
for children). Access www.skyrail.com.au.
</P>
<P>
   The Cairns-Kuranda Scenic Rail operates daily. One-way tickets
cost about $14. Travel agents or tour packagers can make
arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   The Tjapukai Aboriginal Cultural Park is on Kamerunga Road at
Carovonica Lakes, about a 15-minute drive from Cairns and adjacent
to the Skyrail terminal. It's open daily, with shows beginning at
9:15 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   and continuing until 4:40 p.m. Prices start at about $14.50
(half for children). Access www.tjapukai.com.au.
</P>
<P>
   One-hour walking tours conducted by KuKu-Yalanji guides in
Mossman Gorge National Park can be booked in advance. Tours are at
10:30 a.m., 11:30 a.m., 1 p.m. and 2:30 p.m. Monday-Friday. Access
www.internetnorth.com.au/yalanji. E-mail
yalanji(at)internorth.com.au.
</P>
<P>
   Tours: Quicksilver is the area's leading day-tour operator to
the Great Barrier Reef. Round-trip catamaran trips depart Cairns at
8 a.m. and Port Douglas at 10 a.m. Costs range from $82 to $90 and
include morning and afternoon tea, lunch, snorkeling equipment,
swimming at a pristine reef and semisubmersible coral viewing. Reef
tours by helicopter cost extra. Reservations are essential. Access
www.quicksilver-crui-ses.com.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail quicksilver(at)quicksilver-cruises.com. Call
011-61-7-4099-5455.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Cook Cruises offers three-, four- and seven-day
excursions aboard the 168-passenger Reef Endeavor from Cairns to
remote parts of the reef. A travel agent can provide details about
itineraries and costs. Access www.captcookcrus.com.au.
</P>
<P>
   Downunder Tours, headquartered in Cairns, is recommended for day
tours to Kuranda and other attractions. A travel agent or tour
packager can make arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Coral Coaches offers day tours into the Daintree rain forest and
other packages that include area attractions and multiday
excursions. The company also offers scheduled point-to-point bus
service. A travel agent can provide information.
</P>
<P>
   Most Daintree River boat tours areheadquartered at makeshift
stands near the ferry terminal. Several advertise in local
publications. Bruce Belcher's one-hour tour costs about $9 (half
for children); his covered vessel seats up to 20 people.
</P>
<P>
   Additional resources: Lonely Planet, which publishes one of the
most in-depth series of guidebooks, is based in Australia, so it's
no surprise that Queensland (Lonely Planet, $24.95) is a
comprehensive account.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the same series and also recommended is the third
edition of Islands of Australia's Great Barrier Reef (Lonely
Planet, $14.95) by Hugh Finlay.
</P>
<P>
   The Maverick Guide to the Barrier Reef (Pelican, $14.95), by Len
Rutledge, offers historical, geological and practical insight.
</P>
</TEXT>
