<SLUG> BC-AUSTRALIA-RAIN-FOREST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RAIN FOREST MEETS THE REEF IN TROPICAL QUEENSLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HARRY SHATTUCK  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAINTREE RIVER, Australia _ Cap'n Bruce silences the motor and
maneuvers his small boat ever so slowly and ever so quietly toward
the Daintree River bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, over there. At the edge of the water. Know what that
is?''
</P>
<P>
   In an instant, every eye is fixed on a mysterious object - long,
thin, brown, menacing.
</P>
<P>
   It's ...
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a log-odile,'' Cap'n Bruce says. ``They're all over this
part of the river.''
</P>
<P>
   A log-odile?
</P>
<P>
   ``Think about it, mate,'' Cap'n Bruce says, his voice booming
with laughter. ``Don't bother staring any longer, though. It won't
be moving anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, let's go meet Gummy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gummy, holding court just around the bend, is not a log-odile.
``He's the largest and oldest croc we see around here,'' says Bruce
Belcher, aka Cap'n Bruce.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call him Gummy because he's lost his teeth through all the
battles he's had with the other males,'' Belcher continues. ``Most
crocs aren't territorial. But Gummy protects his place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, he gets his choice of all the girls in the river,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Genetically, female crocodiles aren't attracted to an inferior
male.''
</P>
<P>
   Gummy lives within Daintree National Park along Australia's
upper northeast coast, an area known as Tropical North Queensland,
``where the rain forest meets the reef.''
</P>
<P>
   His neighbors include almost 300 bird species, including the
rare and threatened 6-foot flightless Southern cassowary, as well
as marvelous multicolored butterflies, exotic flying foxes that
hang from ceilings, tree-hugging kangaroos and enough snakes to
elicit shivers from even the most ardent outdoorsman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got lizards that stand 6 feet tall,'' one Aussie boasts.
``But don't worry. If they're bothered, they usually head up a
tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``They look for the highest spot. Of course, if that's you ...''
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans, eager to explore the Great Barrier Reef just
offshore, bypass this remote region. Don't make that mistake. By
all means visit the Reef - it's one of the world's natural wonders
- but save time for Cap'n Bruce, Gummy and the Daintree rain
forest, too.
</P>
<P>
   And prepare to be mesmerized.
</P>
<P>
   A brief orientation: Queensland, Australia's second-largest
state, stretches 1,250 miles along the continent's eastern
seaboard. The southern extreme, near Brisbane, is famed for its
Gold Coast, where glitzy hotels and condominiums overlook the
Pacific Ocean. But to the north, the topography and ambience are
studies in contrast.
</P>
<P>
   Most visitors to northern Queensland arrive in Cairns, a city of
100,000, an international airport and no riveting personality.
Thirty miles up the Captain Cook Highway hugging the Coral Sea,
Port Douglas is more compact, more fun-loving - care for a trim at
the Severed Ear barbershop? - and an ideal gateway for day trips to
the Reef or rain forest.
</P>
<P>
   Rent a car in Port Douglas, then follow signs to Mossman and
Daintree Village, a drive that can take 45 minutes or all day,
depending on how well you resist temptations to pause en route.
</P>
<P>
   Nearing Daintree Village, a choice:
</P>
<P>
   If time permits _ and a deep spirit of adventure takes over _
ferry across the river into the heart of Daintree and Cape
Tribulation national parks, part of a nearly 500-square-mile Wet
Tropics World Heritage Area.
</P>
<P>
   A living museum for animals and plants, this vast rain forest
protects 25 rare or endangered vertebrate species, and its canopy
includes giant palms that have stood for 3,000 years. More than
3,000 plant species have been identified here, including the
highest concentration of primitive flowering plants in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Tread carefully since not all roads are paved. Or consider a
tour, which can provide perspective and identify some of the
world's most colorful wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   On a tight schedule? Back near the ferry dock, a handful of
small-boat operators conduct wildlife tours several times daily.
Although they cover only a tiny portion of a river that meanders
for 85 miles from the Pacific, even a one-hour excursion can
provide rich insight.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher relishes pointing out native birds. ``Over there, that's
a great egret,'' he says. ``And in the distance, that's a
yellow-spotted honeyeater.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're coming up on a black-necked stork; it's the only species
of stork in Australia.'' Belcher points to a striking iridescent
black-and-white bird also known as a jabiru.
</P>
<P>
   Most passengers are looking for crocodiles. ``This is one of
their favorite nesting grounds,'' Belcher says. ``We have about 70
adult crocs in this part of the river. And lots of baby crocs.''
</P>
<P>
   Gummy, perhaps 20 feet long, sunbathes half out of the water and
seems unbothered by visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a marine park, we're not allowed to feed the crocodiles,''
Belcher says. ``And because we don't feed him, Gummy has had no
influence from humans. But we give him about 10 meters distance -
not for our safety but for his peace of mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Caution is essential, though. ``During winters, a croc is like
licorice in a refrigerator; he can't move,'' Belcher says. ``But
summertime increases the appetite. He's hungrier and more active.
The accidents involving people happen in summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Gummy is left in peace, at least until another tour boat
arrives. The next stop is Daintree Village, identified by signs as
``the end of the road.''
</P>
<P>
   The entrance to the Daintree Village Restaurant and Coffee Shop
_ ``famous for its pan-fried barramundi and homemade scones since
1986,'' a sign proclaims _ is temporarily blocked by dozens of
peacocks flaunting their brightly colored feathers as they parade
in the town's only street.
</P>
<P>
   ``The peacocks live all around here,'' says restaurant owner
Bill Kromhout, who moved to Daintree Village from the Netherlands
and owns the eatery. ``They just take over the town whenever they
please. We've got about 100 people here, too, when we can find
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Visions of Gummy preclude ordering a Croc Burger, one of the
house specialties. And a combo of pancakes and prawns _ well,
enough said. But the pan-fried barramundi (a locally caught fish),
chips, salad and Aussie beer represent a feast for $8. The peacock
show is free.
</P>
<P>
   On your way back to Port Douglas, a recommended midpoint stop is
Mossman Gorge National Park, home to the KuKu Yalanji, indigenous
inhabitants known here as the rain forest people and custodians of
the forest.
</P>
<P>
   This is a perfect afternoon escape, a place to swim and picnic
or to enjoy walks in the bush, rendered more accessible by tracks
and a suspension bridge. The KuKu Yalanji lead tours, too, telling
about native plants and their practical uses, identifying birds and
other wildlife, and adding perspective to a captivating day.
</P>
<P>
   This is the only place in Australia where the rain forest grows
all the way to the coast. The canopy is so thick that when rain is
pouring above, only a mist penetrates the forest.
</P>
<P>
   Rest for a spell. Keep your eyes peeled for a tree kangaroo. But
don't worry: There isn't a log-odile in sight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
