<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LUXURY LODGING IN A TREEHOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HARRY SHATTUCK  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT DOUGLAS, Australia _ In a land where nature reigns supreme,
what better way to spend the night than in a treehouse? Especially
when the treehouse and its surroundings are the height of comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Kewarra Beach Resort and Thala Beach Lodge, sister properties
just off scenic Captain Cook Highway between Cairns and Port
Douglas, provide idyllic retreats after a day of active
exploration.
</P>
<P>
   With his eco-resorts, Queenslander Robert Prettejohn meshes
local character and style with modern creature comforts in settings
so lush that guests may be tempted not to venture beyond them.
</P>
<P>
   Thala, a 15-minute drive south of Port Douglas, spreads over 145
acres of bush rising sharply from the Coral Sea. Its main lodge is
built on poles reaching into the forest canopy, with views
extending over the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Bungalows with private balconies are placed high in the canopy,
at various levels of the steep hill (shuttle service is available).
Designs incorporate natural materials and finishes to harmonize
with the environment.
</P>
<P>
   The rustic exterior gives little inkling that within the
bungalows are spacious bedrooms with air conditioning, ceiling
fans, color televisions and minibars and a bathroom with separate
tubs and showers.
</P>
<P>
   Kewarra, 20 minutes north of Cairns, occupies flatter land and
hugs the beach on the site of a former sugar-cane field; it is
better suited for travelers with limited mobility.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty acres of gardens are beautifully landscaped, and the
resort provides listings of the 180 species of birds and the many
butterflies and plants on the property.
</P>
<P>
   Sleeping accommodations are known as mouds, Western Torres
Straight Islanders' dialect for house. Many of these bungalows are
built on poles; all are well-furnished.
</P>
<P>
   Lobby and dining areas at both resorts have ceilings but leave
sides open to the breeze and ocean air.
</P>
<P>
   Cuisine is hardly routine treehouse fare.
</P>
<P>
   At Thala, breakfast options during a visit included a starter of
half a dozen oysters accompanied by a glass of champagne, followed
by smoked salmon eggs Benedict and topped off by a bowl of
strawberries.
</P>
<P>
   Dinner entrees at the lodge's Osprey's Restaurant, which exudes
romance, included Tasmanian salmon pan-seared in sesame sauce. It
was rivaled only by Kewarra Beach'sSpanish mackerel on zucchini
noodles with a minted lemon marmalade.
</P>
<P>
   Only Kewarra touted Mississippi Mud Cake, topped with a Mandarin
syrup and hazelnut praline.
</P>
<P>
   Both resorts are members of the exclusive Small Luxury Hotels of
the World chain.
</P>
<P>
   Rates for a bungalow at Kewarra Beach start at about $60 per
person, based on double occupancy, and include airport transfers;
costs increase to about $131 per person for a two-room suite.
Double-occupancy rates at Thala Beach Lodge start at about $80 per
person. All rates vary by season and type of accommodation.
</P>
<P>
   A travel agent can make reservations. For more information,
access www.thalabeach.com.au, www.kewarrabeach.com.au or
www.slh.comon the Internet. Call Thala Beach Lodge at
011-61-7-4098-5700. Call Kewarra Beach Resort at
011-61-7-4057-6666. Write to either resort at P.O. Box 199,
Smithfield, Queensland, Australia 4878.
</P>
<P>
   Other highly regarded eco-resorts in the area clude Silly Oaks
(north of Port Douglas), Daintree Eco Lodge (near the river
and(known for its program of physical and mental therapies) and
Coconut Beach Rain Forest Resort and Ferntree Rain Forest Resort
(both on Cape Tribulation).
</P>
<P>
   Northern Queensland also offers standard hotels and motels,
including many chains familiar to Americans. A travel agent or tour
packager can provide details.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
