<SLUG> BC-AUSTRALIA-BIRDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     EXOTIC BIRDS ABOUND IN HABITAT PARK 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HARRY SHATTUCK  
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT DOUGLAS, Australia _ The shop owner can't hide her
amusement when an American visitor points to a photograph in a
nature book.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do I go to see this beautiful rainbow lorikeet?'' the
stranger asks. ``Are they only found deep in the rain forest?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where've you been, mate?'' the merchant guffaws. ``Just look
around. Those rainbow lorikeets are more common than dishwater.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, a convoy of lorikeets _ brilliant orange, yellow,
blue, green, red _ alights in a nearby tree. Maybe 100 lorikeets.
No, maybe 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Pause almost anywhere in northern Queensland and, if you are
patient, richly decorated native birds will come your way. Near
dusk, the appropriately named rainbow lorikeet flaunts its colors
even in downtown Port Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   But by some estimates, only about one-third of Australia's
estimated 800 bird species are commonly sighted on organized
bird-watching tours. Most are found only in specific habitats; many
are rare or endangered.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason even dedicated bird-watchers relish a visit to
the Rainforest Habitat Wildlife Sanctuary just outside Port
Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 species live and fly freely within a canopied
rain-forest aviary designed to mirror a natural environment. Maps
and illustrated spotters' guides help with identification.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most captivating residents is a bird that doesn't fly
at all: the endangered Southern cassowary, which can reach a height
of 6 feet and is among the world's largest birds.
</P>
<P>
   Sturdily built but with tiny wings, the Southern cassowary is
notable for the red-and-blue color patterns on its head and neck
and also on wattles that hang from its neck, and for a hornlike
casque on its head that is used for protection.
</P>
<P>
   The cassowary, found only in far North Queensland and in New
Guinea rain forests, is related to the emu but is shorter, stockier
and heavier.
</P>
<P>
   Both are members of a flightless group known as ratites, which
includes New Zealand kiwis, South American rheas and ostriches.
Flightless birds are believed to have lived in Australia for 35
million years.
</P>
<P>
   While the Rainforest Habitat's cassowaries merely move about in
water or on land, other birds provide a spectacular show of sights
and sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Australian king parrots, eclectus parrots, Eastern and crimson
rosellas, sacred kingfishers, fruit doves, galahs and yellow
orioles _ all colorful and dazzling _ maneuver almost to within the
grasp of wide-eyed visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Employees and seasoned bird-watchers eagerly provide lessons,
too _ about the eclectus parrot, for instance: The male glitters in
green, while the female's head is a bright red that yields to blue
and brown on the body.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Australia's parrot group (including cockatoos) totals 52
species, 43 of which are found nowhere else. Many are represented
here.
</P>
<P>
   Also popular is the fabled laughing kookaburra, a member of the
kingfisher family.
</P>
<P>
   Birds aren't the only attraction. Other residents include gray
and red kangaroos, wallabies, koalas, bandicoots, fresh- and
saltwater crocodiles and spectacled flying foxes _ dubbed masked
rain-forest raiders as they hang from the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Rainbow lorikeets? Yes, they're here, too. But then they're as
common as dishwater.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
