</P>
<P>
   TELECOM _WorldCom and Sprint have formally ended the deal that
would have led to a massive merger, bowing to regulators'
objections. The move does not signal the end of industry
consolidation. In fact, it frees both companies to negotiate with
others _ and there are talks going on. (Ebbers, in fact, hinted --
or joked -- that Deutsche Telekom ought to speak with him.) What
kind of deals are now likely? What is BellSouth looking at? And who
might be looking at BellSouth? Overview and analysis, in addition
to today's news. (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TIMEWARNER-GA _ A Georgia Appeals court has upheld a $530
million verdict against Time Warner and other former owners of Six
Flags over Georgia. The park's new owner sued them in 1998 for
delaying the opening of the ``Batman'' ride and other
mismanagement. Time Warner says it will appeal but is taking a $50
million 2Q charge. (Kempner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
