<DOCNO> NYT20000713.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1105 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-SURVIVORS-CONTESTA     07-13 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURVIVORS-CONTESTANTS-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; CANDIDATES AUDITION FOR THE `SURVIVOR' TV SHOW &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By RYAN KIM &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   6c.2000 San Francisco Examiner &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ They came bearing tales of eating insects,
hunting lizards and diving in caves. Others boasted of being
natural leaders, black belts and mediators. Someone ate a live
goldfish.
</P>
<P>
   For the more than 100 people who turned out at the Marina Green
Wednesday, the goal was simple: become a ``Survivor,'' as in the
CBS reality show that pits strangers against each other in remote
places.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what it's like to push my body, and I know I wouldn't
give up,'' said Josh Rogers, a 25-year-old personal trainer from
Los Gatos.
</P>
<P>
   KPIX-TV's ``Evening Magazine'' hosted tryouts for the show,
which consisted of filling out an application and making a
three-minute audition tape. Another audition will be held July 20
at an undisclosed location.
</P>
<P>
   Contestants can also download an application from www.cbs.com
and send in their own audition tape.
</P>
<P>
   CBS will eventually pick 16 contestants to vie for $1 million
while competing against each other for seven weeks somewhere in
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The current top-rated show, filmed in the South China Sea, has
featured contestants on two competing teams eating bugs and rats.
At the end of each episode, members vote off one of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the hopefuls strode up like confident warriors trying
to get a spot in the ultimate showcase for their skills. There were
a few freaks _ one group arrived in leather masks and whips _ but
most of the aspirants spared the theatrics.
</P>
<P>
   One exception was Devin Kochis, a 32-year-old UC-Berkeley police
officer who passed up a sergeants exam to try out Wednesday. Armed
with a tiki torch, Kochis tore off his shirt and revealed the word
``survivor'' written across his chest and stomach. ``Why would I
make the best survivor?'' asked Kochis, with a deadly serious
stare. ``Because I've got survivor written all over me.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, as he stood in front of a camera recording his
audition tape, Kochis backed up his bravado by swallowing a gold
fish. ``It didn't taste like anything, but it was a big fish,'' he
said later.
</P>
<P>
   As the contestants stared into the cameras recording their
auditions, they all insisted they were the epitome of survivors.
Whatever life has thrown at them, they had all managed to come out
on top.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of my ability to survive; I'm in great shape for my
age,'' said 67-year-old Pat McAlonan, a recreational cave diver
from San Rafael.
</P>
<P>
   As if addressing such a topic would force them to break from the
rugged adventurist persona each came with, hardly anyone
acknowledged the monetary payoff. Even fewer talked of the fame
that would accompany an appearance on the popular show.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them insisted they were in it for the experience and
challenge of the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in it for the adventure,'' said Jennifer Downey, a
26-year-old environmental scientist from Noe Valley, Calif. ``It
sounds so exciting; it's a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   And to that end, the candidates said they were prepared to do
just about anything to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll do anything, get naked, whatever,'' said Damien Schot, 24
of San Bruno, Calif. ``If I have to dance around like a chicken,
I'll do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Schot said he was not afraid of eating rats, either. He's
already dined on crickets, snails and meal worms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've even eaten a moth on a dare,'' he said proudly, as only
someone who's eaten bugs can.
</P>
<P>
   There are limits, of course, to what people will do.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to roll around naked with an ugly, fat man, I don't
think I could do that,'' said Jonathan Critcher, a 28-year-old
member of the Coast Guard from Richmond, Calif. ``Other than that,
there's nothing I couldn't do.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as important as the physical stamina and ruggedness
involved in ``Survivor,'' the show requires a balance of
Machiavellian scheming and selfless benevolence. Go too far one
way, and you get booted off the show.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tender balance that all Wednesday's contestants believed
they had down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be the mediator,'' said Downey. ``I'm usually in the
middle, the team player.''
</P>
<P>
   But Downey was not sure that would fly on the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a lot of enemies,'' she said thoughtfully.
``Maybe that's too boring, and people will kick me off.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE - OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The largest concern for some of the people was not how far they
would advance; everyone seemed to think they were winning material.
But the chance of being selected made some contemplate what they'd
have to leave behind.
</P>
<P>
   Besides her husband and her pets, Downey was concerned about
getting her daily fix of Starbuck's coffee. Schot said he was
worried about something a little stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a party guy,'' said Schot. ``If I get on the show, you'll
see me microbrewing, trying to make moonshine.''
</P>
<P>
   The auditions plodded on with many of the contestants struggling
to fill their three minutes of camera time. Afterward, they got
back into their cars and returned to their lives, quietly
contemplating a momentary escape from the routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a neat concept,'' said Critcher, the Coast Guard
member. ``Maybe it's a step toward fame for other people, but I
just want to see if I can do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 1455EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
