<DOCNO> NYT20000713.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1106 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-NY-SENATE-HNS &LR;      07-13 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DEMOCRATS UNLEASH NEW AD ATTACKING LAZIO 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LARA JAKES  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ New York Democrats have rolled out their third
soft-money ad of the U.S. Senate campaign as a new poll showed
Democratic candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton and Republican
challenger Rick Lazio running neck and neck.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign for Lazio, the four-term representative from Long
Island, predicted the ad war against him would ``backfire'' by
failing to persuade voters to support the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   A poll by Quinnipiac University showed Clinton and Lazio tied at
45 percent in a survey of 1,086 registered state voters taken July
5-10. The poll, with a margin of error of 3 percentage points,
found that upstate New York remains the race's battleground, with
Lazio leading in the traditionally conservative region by 47-41
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Upstate is also where the Democratic Party's new ad will run
through next week. It hammers Lazio for voting against a bill
guaranteeing prescription drug coverage under Medicare. The
30-second ad features Frank and Ann Mormile, an Albany couple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between her and I we take a total of about 34 pills a day,''
Frank Mormile says in the ad. ``At the age of 72, I went back to
work to help pay for the medication that I need. Where I should be
enjoying my life, which they call our golden years, forget those
words _ it's not our golden years any longer.''
</P>
<P>
   An announcer says: ``Rick Lazio voted against guaranteed
prescription coverage under Medicare. Bowing to the drug companies,
Lazio backed a plan that would leave millions without affordable
coverage. Tell Lazio: Next time, vote for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad brings the state Democratic Party's spending to nearly $1
million in ``issue'' or so-called ``soft-money'' ads that are legal
but largely unregulated. While they don't specifically endorse
Clinton, the subtle message behind the advertising is that voters
should support the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's campaign did not deny his voting record but responded
that Clinton and the Democratic Party had only ``succeeded in
increasing Mrs. Clinton's negative ratings.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Quinnipiac poll, 40 percent of voters surveyed had an
``unfavorable'' impression of Clinton, compared to 13 percent for
Lazio. Thirty-four percent of those surveyed gave Clinton a
``favorable'' rating to 31 percent for Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillary Clinton's campaign of search, distort and destroy has
backfired as New York voters prove they're smart enough to see past
her deceptions,'' said Lazio campaign manager Bill Dal Col. The
poll, he said, ``suggests that New Yorkers have come to realize
that they cannot trust Hillary Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is overwhelmingly favored in New York City, 61-30
percent; Lazio holds a healthy edge in the New York City suburbs,
59-33 percent, and a small lead of 47-41 percent among white women,
a voting bloc that nearly always backs statewide winners. Clinton,
however, remains strong among Jewish voters, 54-34 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
