<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1108 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-U.S.-590&AMP;ADD-NY     07-13 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND CHINA VOW FRIENDSHIP DESPITE CONTINUED RIFTS ON MILITARY
POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The U.S. defense secretary and Chinese leaders made
hopeful pledges of cooperation and friendship Thursday, despite
evidence of deep rifts over key military policies and dark Chinese
suspicions about U.S. intentions in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Two days of high-level meetings began and ended with smiles and
handshakes, a sign of how strongly both sides want to avoid open,
dangerous antagonism.
</P>
<P>
   But officials were also struggling with potentially explosive
disputes including U.S. plans for missile defenses and continued
arms sales to Taiwan, and U.S. charges that China recently helped
Pakistan develop ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials endured a new humiliation after Israel said
Wednesday that it was reneging on a $250 million deal, five years
in the making, to sell Beijing an advanced airborne radar system.
Israel canceled the sale under heavy pressure from the United
States, which fears the system could be used to track fighter
planes in a battle over the Taiwan strait _ the most likely scene
of direct Chinese-American conflict.
</P>
<P>
   In a 90-minute meeting Thursday afternoon, President Jiang Zemin
brought up the canceled sale, U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen
said. ``It was certainly of concern to China,'' Cohen told
reporters, but he said the tone of the meetings was generally
positive.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen met nearly every top political and military leader and
spoke to military officers at the National Defense University. As
he greeted Cohen Thursday, China's top soldier, Zhang Wannian, vice
chairman of the Central Military Commission, stressed ``how
important it is for China and the United States to have a healthy
and stable relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials from both sides said they were pleased that military
visits and talks, suspended after the United States bombed the
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade last year, had been largely restored.
</P>
<P>
   But Cohen could offer the Chinese no convincing answers to
concerns about proposed missile defenses and arms sales to Taiwan.
And it was also clear that China had not effectively countered U.S.
charges that it has aided the development of ballistic missiles in
Pakistan and Iran, possibly violating pledges.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate news conference Thursday, China's chief arms
control official, Sha Zukang, said that his country had on three
occasions, most recently in a joint statement by Jiang and Clinton
in 1998, pledged not to help either India or Pakistan develop
missiles capable of carrying nuclear warheads. He scoffed at
reported U.S. intelligence agency findings that China has provided
just such technical aid to Pakistan, its strategic ally, within the
last 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen on Thursday afternoon would only say of the missile
charges that ``these issues are still under discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   Sha repeated China's vehement warnings that it sees the proposed
U.S. missile defense as negating China's small nuclear forces.
China also opposes the U.S.-Japanese program to develop regional
missile defenses, which could be used to shield Taiwan. China
considers Taiwan a part of the nation that must eventually return
to it, if not by peaceful means then by war.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to military officers Thursday morning at the
National Defense University north of Beijing, Cohen described the
U.S. military presence in Asia as a benign, stabilizing factor
rather than, as many Chinese believe, one intended to hem in an
increasingly confident and powerful China.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Noting the U.S. military's strong presence in South Korea and
Japan, its close ties with Australia, Thailand and increasingly the
Philippines, and its pledge to help Taiwan defend itself, Cohen
said: ``The truth is that this region is safer, more secure and
more stable because of the United States. And that peace and
stability has benefited every nation, including China.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there are calls in China for the United States to
vacate Asia,'' Cohen added, departing from his prepared text. ``But
I ask you, who will fill the vacuum?''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen complained that the Chinese press often unfairly
characterizes the United States as out to dominate the world, and
working against China.
</P>
<P>
   His military audience listened intently and applauded. During a
brief, relaxed question period, in an apparently unscripted
outburst, the wife of a Chinese officer won loud applause when she
said the U.S. press maligns China on human rights and that the
United States could promote peace by halting arms sales to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   But the generally polite reception belied a growing suspicion
here about U.S. intentions. The military journals and newspapers
that are studied by these officers, the cream of the People's
Liberation Army, describe U.S. policy in ever-more sinister terms.
</P>
<P>
   A recent article in the Liberation Army Daily, on the proposed
national missile defense, was headlined ``Sixty Billion Dollars to
Crush China.'' The U.S. military is routinely described as
encircling China and arming Taiwan to diminish China's power.
</P>
<P>
   The visiting Americans saw an editorial in Thursday morning's
China Daily, the official English-language newspaper, titled ``U.S.
a Threat to World Peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The editorial, translated from the overseas edition of the
People's Daily, said the United States is causing a global arms
race by seeking military supremacy, and that the U.S. alliance with
Japan _ the core of the United State's Asia policy _ ``constitutes
a threat to regional stability.''
</P>
<P>
   The editorial charged that U.S. military spending last year _
$276 billion _ was 2.5 times the total spending of Russia, Britain,
France, Germany, Japan and China combined and that the United
States is now seeking military control of outer space.
</P>
<P>
   And it said the United States is most responsible for the global
spread of missile technologies because by working with Japan to
develop missile defenses it had provoked other countries to seek
better missiles of their own.
</P>
<P>
   China does not like to admit its dependence on foreign purchases
for advanced weapons, and Thursday, despite anger and dismay over
the canceled Israeli sale, the public response was subdued.
</P>
<P>
   At a regular foreign ministry news conference, spokesman Zhu
Bangzao obliquely criticized the United States for its role, saying
that ``no country has the right to interfere with the bilateral
cooperation between China and other countries.'' He also implicitly
criticized Israel, saying that ``agreements and understandings
reached between states should be observed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
