<HEADER>
A1132 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-KIDS-FOOD14-COX     07-13 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-FOOD14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FREE MEALS STOP IN SUMMER FOR MOST POOR CHILDREN
 &HT;    With KIDS-FOOD-DATA.
 &HT;    Eds: Inserts for Cox states are at end of story.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nearly four-fifths of the poor children who receive
federally subsidized meals during the school year don't get them
during their summer vacation, the Food Research and Action Center
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last summer, only 3.2 million of the 14.9 million low-income
children who received free or reduced-price breakfasts or lunches
during the school year were served by the summer nutrition
programs,'' said Lynn Parker, director of FRAC.
</P>
<P>
   The nonpartisan Washington-based center is known for its
meticulous research. It is funded by foundations and by unions and
companies in the food industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, states and communities are falling far short of
taking full advantage of available resources, and many needy
children are missing the meals and vital nutrients they need during
the summer just as much as they do the rest of the year,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The study, called ``Hunger Doesn't Take a Vacation,'' is based
on state reports on participation in two federally subsidized
programs the summer portion of the national school lunch program
and the summer food service program, which is used at youth
programs sponsored by local governments or nonprofit groups.
</P>
<P>
   Participation rates vary enormously by state, the researchers
found.
</P>
<P>
   At the top, the number of children reported as served in the
summer dropped to only 68 percent of school-year levels in the
District of Columbia, 44 percent in Nevada, 43 percent in
California, 35 percent in New Mexico and 34 percent in Delaware.
Federal auditors are rechecking the figures in the district, but no
serious questions have been raised about the validity of the
numbers from the top states.
</P>
<P>
   At the bottom, the number fell in the summer to 3 percent of
school-year levels in Alaska, 5 percent in Wyoming, 7 percent in
Oklahoma and Iowa, and 8 percent in Oklahoma and Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   At Mathematica(cq) Policy Research, Inc., an employee-owned
research firm in Princeton, N.J., senior economist Anne Gordon
said, ``Given welfare reform and the fact that the food-stamp rolls
are dropping, there is a concern about whether kids are getting the
nutrition they need in the summer, but we really don't understand
what leads to this low participation.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the firm, which recently received a contract from the
U.S. Department of Agriculture to find out the reasons, expects to
report on its results by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, we don't even know if they're getting less food
in the summer time, or if families somehow pick up the slack,''
Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   The FRAC report did not give reasons for the low participation
rates. In interviews, staff members said that their personal
experience indicates:
</P>
<P>
   _ Some sponsors of summer programs for children don't realize
how much they could save by using federal money for meals.
</P>
<P>
   _ It can cost a lot to transport meals from central kitchens in
schools to scattered educational or recreational sites, especially
in rural areas. It can also cost extra to transport children from
scattered sites to a school cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   Schools that serve meals to summer-school students receive the
same federal reimbursements as during the regular school year.
Other nonprofit sponsors of summer nutrition programs receive $2.18
per lunch, $1.25 per breakfast and 50 cents per snack, as well as
administrative fees of up to 22.75 cents per lunch, 12.5 cents per
breakfast and 6.25 cents per snack.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, participation doubled after the state hired
Project Bread, an anti-hunger group, to send people across the
state to encourage school systems and community groups to start
serving summer meals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because times are good, we got some extra money from the state
legislature for outreach,'' said dietitian Barbara Ruhs(cq), who
works on child nutrition programs in the Massachusetts Department
of Eduction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, it's as simple as explaining the program to a small
district's food service director, or informing parents that the
programs are available through devices like commercials and
posters, including ads on the subway,'' Ruhs said.
</P>
<P>
   However, she said, some children don't come because their
parents won't let them walk through bad neighborhoods during the
summer, when there are no crossing guards.
</P>
<P>
   And some sponsors can't afford to feed poor parents who bring
their children, since the federal money can't be used to feed
anyone older than 18.
</P>
<P>
   ON the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Food Research and Action Center, www.frac.org
</P>
<P>
   Summer Food Service Program,
fns1.usda.gov/cnd/SummerOld/AboutSFSP/faqs.htm
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is AndyM(at)Coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
