<HEADLINE>
WIRELESS WEB STEPS BACK TO GO FORWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Remember how crude the World Wide Web used to be? Or maybe
you're one of the millions who never logged on until companies like
Yahoo and America Online had begun to civilize the Internet. Maybe
you missed out on the primitive delights of the Web's Heroic Age.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky you; here comes another chance. The clumsy, klutzy
amateur-hour experience of the early Internet lives on in today's
wireless Web. I've spent a month now using the Web browser on a
Sprint PCS phone. For a relative old-timer like me, it's a chance
to relive the frustrations of a simpler, more innocent time. For
the newbies,.ir's an opportunity to retrace the wagon-ruts of the
pioneers.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the wireless Web experience can never match the
backwardness of the old days. In 1994, there was scarcely anything
online escept for dry academic papers, crude pornography, and the
occasional set of baby pictures. Today, at least, there's stuff
worth looking at _ news headlines, weather reports, movie listings,
e-mail, all available through a pocket-size cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   But even in the early '90s, one did one's Web surfing on a
reasonably fast desktop computer, with a nice color monitor and a
full-size keyboard. Wireless Web devices boast slow processors,
tiny monochrome screens, and a keyboard that looks like the
touchpad of a phone, because that's what it is.
</P>
<P>
   Just as in the early days of the Web, a host of corporate touts
insist that life without wireless Web access will scarcely be worth
living. The world's leading computer and telecommunications
companies are designing phones and palmtop computers to deliver the
Web to your pocket, and major online companies are converting their
bloated, colorful sites into leaner wireless formats.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, history seems to be repeating itself. It took years
for the Internet to become a mass medium. For all the hoopla,
consumers are so far giving wireless Internet service ``a good
leaving-alone.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the word from Europe. Portable phones are far more
popular there than in the United States, and so wireless Web
companies have concentrated their efforts on this market. To little
avail, according to a study released last month by Deutsche
Telecom, which found that the average European with a wireless Web
phone used it to go online just once a week. And among Deutsche
Telecom's own cellular customers, just 1 percent used their phones
for surfing.
</P>
<P>
   It must be a European thing. Wireless Web phones are huge in
Japan; the government there says 10 million people are using them.
As for me, I've developed quite a liking for my borrowed Sprint
wireless Web phone. It's plainly awful for casual Web surfing;
indeed, most ordinary Web sites won't even display on the phone.
Sites must first be converted into a suitable format; the most
popular of these is called the Wireless Access Protocol, or WAP.
</P>
<P>
   WAP-ready sites have stripped out the pretty colors and other
useless fripperies, leaving you with the site's useful information
in plain monochrome text. In some ways, this makes a WAP site
simpler to understand than an ordinary Web page.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, it's not easy typing in commands by using a
telephone keypad. I found myself using the phone for only the
simplest online tasks, like visiting America Online and skimming
the news headlines, or checking my e-mail at Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   I never got around to buying anything with my phone, but I could
have. Amazon.com, for example, has a WAP-enabled site where you can
log in and buy that Harry Potter book.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody'll ever use one of these things for casual surfing.
Instead, says Ben Linder, vice president of Phone.com Inc., maker
of WAP browsing software, wireless Web phones are designed for the
``surgical extraction of information'' _ quick snippets of
know-how, delivered on demand wherever you are.
</P>
<P>
   But where's the money in it? Barry Parr, director of consumer
e-commerce research at International Data Corp., says the wireless
Web is a technology in search of a business model. ``I don't think
people are going to be buying a lot of stuff with these gadgets,''
he says. Besides, the device screens are too small for ads that
might make a WAP site profitable. And Parr notes that companies
like Sprint charge cell-phone prices for wireless Web access,
instead of a flat-rate plan.
</P>
<P>
   Perfectly good arguments, every one of them. And the naysayers
who scoffed at the founders of Yahoo and America Online had
arguments every bit as good. You know the saying _ history repeats
itself, the first time in color, the second time in black and
white.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hiawatha Bray is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached
by e-mail at bray(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 1520EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000713.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1139 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-HIV-POT-HNS &LR;      07-13 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIV-POT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STUDY POINTS TO APPARENT BENEFITS OF MARIJUANA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Filed in ``l'' and ``i'' categories)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURBAN, South Africa _ Smoking marijuana does not disrupt the
effect of anti-retroviral drugs that keep the AIDS virus in check,
according to a study released Thursday at an international
conference on the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the marijuana study are the first to be released
from research conducted at San Francisco General Hospital into the
use of marijuana by people infected with the human immunodeficiency
virus, or HIV. Given the scarcity of data about the possible
medical uses of marijuana, the results have been eagerly awaited by
advocates in this heavily debated issue.
</P>
<P>
   It took four years for Donald Abrams, a professor at the
University of California at San Francisco, to jump through hurdles
erected by the federal government to get the research under way,
and in the process he was restricted to focusing on marijuana's
safety rather than its effectiveness. The 67 people who
participated in the study were kept in the hospital during the
25-day study period.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact of the matter is that any good clinician with his
eyes and ears open has known for a long time that cannabis is very
useful in the treatment of the AIDS reduction syndrome and does not
harm patients,'' said Dr. Lester Greenspoon, professor of
psychiatry at Harvard University and author of ``Marijuana: the
Forbidden Medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspoon said that when marijuana is allowed to be used for
medicinal purposes, ``it will be seen as one of the least toxic
drugs.'' He added that Abrams' research has `` put the seal of
approval on a new drug.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers were especially keen to study people on drug regimes
that contain protease inhibitors, because the key ingredient in
marijuana is metabolized by the same system in the liver as those
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The participants, nearly all men, were divided into three
groups, with one set smoking marijuana, another taking a Food and
Drug Administration-approved pill containing the main ingredient in
marijuana, and a third taking a placebo, or harmless pill.
</P>
<P>
   In all groups, tests showed that the level of virus in the blood
dropped or remained undetectable by current tests. But those taking
marijuana either by smoking or in a pill form saw their level drop
slightly more than those on the placebo.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, researchers found that those using the pill or
smoking marijuana gained an average of 2.2 kilograms, compared to
.6 kilograms in the placebo group. Marijuana was first used widely
by people with AIDS to combat the nausea and extreme weight loss
that comes with the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams called the lower viral levels in the marijuana patients
intriguing, but said it was not statistically significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is that there is no statistical difference
between the three groups,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we've demonstrated the safety in a population as
vulnerable as people with HIV, I think it paves the way for doing
studies of efficacy,'' Abrams said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Abrams, an oncologist, said he hopes to soon begin
studying the use of smoked marijuana for cancer patients to see if
it can control nausea and pain, including the nerve-based pain that
is often beyond the reach of opiate painkillers like morphine.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams said he expects to release more results from the study
soon, including marijuana's effect on appetite, testosterone levels
and body composition.
</P>
<P>
   Results of the study were released at the 13th International
AIDS Conference in Durban.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS, the acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is an affliction
in which HIV weakens the immune system, subjecting the body to
serious infection. AIDS is most often spread through sexual
contact, sharing contaminated needles and infected blood products.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
