<SLUG> BC-WORLDCOM-SPRINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINT AND WORLDCOM CALL OFF MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., Kan.)  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By DANIEL J. WAKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sprint and WorldCom, two of the United State's largest
long-distance carriers, called off merger plans Thursday and opened
the gates for takeover overtures by both foreign and domestic
telecommunications giants.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was widely expected after U.S. and European
regulators had expressed opposition to the merger.
</P>
<P>
   A formal end to the proposed $115 billion merger means suitors
can begin official approaches. Part of the companies' original
merger agreement barred any formal contacts with other potential
partners.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom of Germany, Europe's largest telephone company,
has been mentioned as the main party interested in Sprint, and
executives of the German company have said it made informal
approaches in the last two weeks. Other potential suitors are
Nippon Telegraph and Telephone of Japan and BellSouth of Atlanta.
Sprint is particularly attractive because it owns a wireless
telephone network as well as its fixed-line business.
</P>
<P>
   Both businesses are desirable to foreign companies as footholds
in the world's largest telecommunications market.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department opposed the Sprint-WorldCom merger on the
grounds that it would have left too few long-distance options for
Americans and would have led to higher prices for less service.
European regulators were concerned that it would reduce competition
for Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   In statements Thursday, both companies repeated their opposition
to those views.
</P>
<P>
   ``The set of conditions ultimately demanded by the U.S.
Department of Justice would compromise the customer and financial
benefits of the merger,'' they said in a joint statement.
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom's president and chief executive, Bernard Ebbers, said a
policy of quashing such deals ``ultimately will reduce innovation
and choice, and raise the cost of telephone services for
residential customers, particularly those in rural America.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprint, based in Westwood, Kan., suggested that a court fight of
the Justice Department decision might yield results, but that the
time required for such lengthy litigation was not worth it.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department sued late last month to block the merger,
and the companies withdrew their application from the European
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   After AT&AMP;T, WorldCom, based in Clinton, Miss., is the United
State's second-largest long-distance company, followed by Sprint.
</P>
</TEXT>
