<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1170 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-13 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `BIG BROTHER' IS A BORE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ CBS's so-called ``reality'' show ``Big Brother,'' a
tasteless stinkeroo, is supposed to run through September if it
isn't canceled. Help!
</P>
<P>
   If this is reality, give me fiction.
</P>
<P>
   So far ``Brother'' isn't worth the bother.
</P>
<P>
   Why did CBS think that millions of Americans would get hooked on
watching shallow, inarticulate young people do nothing? If we are
going to be peeping Toms, we want to be entertained, amused or _
heaven forbid _ educated. But this is simply boring.
</P>
<P>
   The show debuted before 22 million curious folks on July 5,
helped by its position following the popular ``Survivor,'' which
has topped the ratings chart with an average of 21 million viewers
every week since it was launched six shows ago. By the end of the
first half-hour of ``Brother,'' however, 1.5 million voters had
turned it off. Not an auspicious beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the ``Brother'' audience has ranged from 11 million
to 6 million. This is not good enough to sustain a show that is
scheduled to air five days a week for two more months.
</P>
<P>
   True, it is a bigger audience than the 3.5 million book-lovers
who snapped up ``Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire'' last
weekend. Television is a powerful medium, after all.
</P>
<P>
   But the show was touted as a blockbuster, pioneering a new form
of entertainment that would transform our viewing habits forever by
showing us real people having real experiences.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble with this silly show about 10 strangers sealed in a
house full of cameras and microphones is that so far none of the
stars has had anything to say. The charm of the show is supposed to
be that it is unscripted. But without a play book, the thing
wanders aimlessly.
</P>
<P>
   For example, fussing over an injured chicken was the excitement
one night. Another night a mild, incoherent flirtation was what
passed for passion.
</P>
<P>
   I tried to count the number of times the young folks said ``you
know'' and ``like'' in their sentences but lost track. This does
not make for riveting dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, ``Survivor'' actually resembles high adventure. It
is stagey and hokey, as is ``Brother.'' But things do happen. The
participants compete in tests of athletic skill while engaging in a
lot of muttered backbiting and maneuvering against one another. And
they have identifiable personalities to like or dislike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brother'' may yet improve, but I doubt it. There's not enough
there, there.
</P>
<P>
   Something good would come of this, however, if it were to dampen
network enthusiasm for other so-called reality shows. A horror is
apparently in the works that would feature a woman shackled to four
men for a week, after which she picks the one she likes best. Ugh!
As a locked-together quintet, how do they manage bathroom
maneuvers? Eating? Sleeping? Spare us, please.
</P>
<P>
   This is supposed to be an improvement on sitcoms, which could
certainly stand a great deal of improving. And it is nice to be
free of a canned-laughter sound track. But the assumption that we
are all mindless snoops is too much.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to see how ``reality'' is going to make it
unless the people and situations are interesting.
</P>
<P>
   The dirty little secret is that real life is often drab,
composed not of grand schemes but of repetitive little chores. Not
everyone dines at the White House, outwits the boss or rescues a
child from a river.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' works because the characters revel in the attention
they are getting, the setting is exotic, the tasks are uncommon and
the tension of kicking off one person per show builds nicely.
``Brother,'' by contrast, sits there stupidly, staring back at us.
In terms of action, a cockroach has more to offer.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the ``Brother'' folks have been speculating about how
much money they will lose if the series is canceled. This may
motivate some of them to stir up trouble or instigate a hot romance
to get the ratings moving in future segments. But viewers can sense
when they are conned. Such artifice could well send more of them
fleeing.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind ``Brother'' was to do something fresh during the
summer doldrums when many people are at the beach and ignoring all
those TV re-runs. And the two major party conventions, featuring
nominees and platforms fixed in advance, are not likely to help in
the thrill department.
</P>
<P>
   But fresh is not necessarily better. That is the unhappy message
of ``Big Brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its bad taste, it is not a comment on declining American
morality or slipping cultural standards. The public has more sense
than the producers, and people are voting against this show with
their channel clickers. The show is only a comment on the bad
judgment of those who control TV programming today.
</P>
<P>
   Give it up, guys. Don't wait until September. Try replicating
``Bonanza'' and ``Matlock'' instead.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 1610EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000713.0118 </DOCNO>
