<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1172 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HOMEVIDEO-NYT &LR;      07-13 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER M. NICHOLS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   STRETCHING A DVD PACKAGE
</P>
<P>
   At its annual meeting in Las Vegas last week, the video business
acknowledged DVD _ a format that some in the industry have had
their reservations about _ as its most positive development. It
doesn't take a convention to gauge the rise of the disc and its
player, about 10 million of which could be in use by early next
year. On the release horizon, hundreds of films wait to join the
current DVD inventory of about 6,500 movie and music titles.
</P>
<P>
   In true more-is-more spirit, the biggest and the splashiest of
them _ usually meaning the ones with the most special effects _ are
so jammed with extra features that they threaten to spill right off
the disc. DVD makers used to revel in all the room they had, but
now they wonder how to get everything onto two-disc editions or the
new ``18'' (for gigabytes) dual-layered, two-sided discs.
</P>
<P>
   Like the old laser discs, 18s will have to be flipped, something
early DVD developers said should not happen. They also take longer
to replicate, which can help delay special editions and in some
cases force studios to issue one disc that is light on extras at
the time the videocassette appears and another one later with all
the features added. ``You have to be very careful consumers know
another edition is coming along,'' said Jonathan Gaines of Acoustic
Visions, a Los Angeles company that helps produce discs for the
movie studios.
</P>
<P>
   One habitual space-grabber, as it was on laser disc, is
``Terminator 2: Judgment Day,'' the Arnold Schwarzenegger vehicle
directed by James Cameron. Action-movie buffs always seem to be up
for still more ``T2,'' as it's called by grateful distributors, and
next month a DVD 18 edition from Artisan will carry three complete
versions of the film: the one that ran in theaters, another with 15
minutes added and another with five minutes on top of that. All
this before the added features, which from documentaries (three) to
production stills, number more than 40.
</P>
<P>
   Just released by Fox, ``Independence Day'' fills the first of
two discs (one-sided) with the original film and another version of
it with 9 minutes of material restored; a commentary by Roland
Emmerich, the director, and Dean Devlin, the producer and
co-writer; and another commentary from the effects supervisors. All
the other extras, including a 33-minute ``featurette'' (DVD-ese for
various pieces of film about the film), is left for the second
disc.
</P>
<P>
   Not all DVDs come so fully packed, of course. For example, it is
a relief to encounter ``The Woody Allen Collection,'' available
this week from MGM. Eight Allen films _ ``Annie Hall,''
``Bananas,'' ``Everything You Always Wanted to Know About Sex but
Were Afraid to Ask,'' ``Interiors,'' ``Love and Death,''
``Manhattan,'' ``Sleeper'' and ``Stardust Memories'' _ are
accompanied by just two extras each: a trailer for the film and an
informative four-page circular inserted in the disc case.
</P>
<P>
   DVDs often are dependent on the director to provide extras,
which some do by the trunkful. Allen is said to feel no such urge.
</P>
<P>
   All About My Mother
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Almodovar's complex film takes what he has called
``screwball drama'' to a more deeply felt level. When Manuela
(Cecilia Roth) sees her son run down in the street, she leaves his
heart beating in another man's body and goes off to refigure life
with a variety of iconoclastic women. These include a nun played by
Penelope Cruz and the irrepressible transsexual actor Agrado
(Antonia San Juan), an old friend of Manuela's since the days
before Agrado had breasts. ``Almodovar has expressed the idea of
acting as a divine form of life before,'' Janet Maslin wrote in The
New York Times, ``but never with the kind of clarity and beauty
that glitter here.''
</P>
<P>
   _ 1999. Columbia Tri-Star. $99.36; DVD, $29.95. 100 minutes.
Spanish with English subtitles. R.
</P>
<P>
   Angela's Ashes
</P>
<P>
   The very grimness of the poverty in Alan Parker's film, adapted
from Frank McCourt's celebrated book about his brutal Irish
upbringing, oddly contrasts with the lush beauty of its
cinematography and a tidily controlled palette that keeps real
suffering at bay. Jammed into tiny, waterlogged quarters in
Limerick, Ireland, the family of Malachy McCourt, a charming and
caring drunk, exists on little food and not much of anything else,
including shoes, while Malachy fails at any work he tries. But with
due respect to the pain described here, ``the film isn't wrenching
enough to do it justice'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   _ 1999. Paramount. $107.37; DVD, $29.99. 120 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: July 18.
</P>
<P>
   The Whole Nine Yards
</P>
<P>
   A nice-guy dentist named Oz (Matthew Perry) browbeaten by his
wife (Rosanna Arquette) and nasty mother-in-law is further rattled
by Jimmy ``the Tulip'' Tudeski (Bruce Willis), a former Chicago
organized-crime figure who moves in next door. Jimmy, as breezily
confident as Oz is anxiety-ridden, stirs the suburban pot with hit
men, love interests and large sums of money. But while Perry shows
a knack for slapstick, Jonathan Lynn's film remains
``underwhelming, amusing only in fits and starts'' (Elvis
Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   _ 2000. Warner. $108.97; DVD, $24.98. 101 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: July 18.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't She Great
</P>
<P>
   Probably the best line to sum up Jacqueline Susann (Bette
Midler) in Andrew Bergman's bio-pic comes from Jackie's best friend
(Stockard Channing): ``Talent isn't everything.'' Competence is
another matter. Jackie banged out her humid sex-and-drug adventures
_ ``Valley of the Dolls,'' ``The Love Machine'' _ with game
efficiency. Midler is perfectly equipped to give color to the
character, but she is stymied by a film that only makes Susann's
life campy and crude. ``It's not that there's no talent among the
collaborators; it's just that no one gets much of a chance to show
it'' (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   _ 2000. Universal. $107.37; DVD, $24.98. 90 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: July 18.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   SPIDERS and THE THOUSAND EYES OF DR. MABUSE. New editions of one
of Fritz Lang's earliest films and his last one find the director
in his thriller mode. Inspired by the serials of Louis Feuillade,
``Spiders'' (1919, 137 minutes) stars Carl de Vogt as the
adventurer Kay Hoog, who finds a note in a bottle from an
anthropologist being held captive by South American Indians.
There's Incan treasure to locate, a spider cult to avoid and a
treacherous femme fatale (Ressel Orla) to best. (Indiana Jones,
anybody? Well, sort of.) For ``The 1,000 Eyes of Dr. Mabuse''
(1960), Lang resurrected his master criminal Dr. Mabuse for a
latter-day and rather convoluted international conspiracy (and here
everybody thought Mabuse had died in the '30s). Kino. $24.95 each.
Information: (800) 562-3330.
</P>
<P>
   LATE AUGUST, EARLY SEPTEMBER. Olivier Assayas' film involves the
death of a middle-aged man, but the treatment concentrates on
myopic egos and changing relationships rather than morbidity or
pain. ``If Assayas doesn't always transport his film's events
beyond the all-too-commonplace,'' Janet Maslin wrote in The New
York Times, ``his understatement can also yield moments of quieter
simplicity.'' 1999. $89.99. 105 minutes. French with English
subtitles. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   DIVINE TRASH. Steve Yeager's documentary looks at the early
career of John Waters and his collaboration with Divine in ``Pink
Flamingoes.'' 1998. $19.98; DVD, $24.98. 105 minutes. No rating.
</P>
</TEXT>
