<SLUG> BC-WISDOM-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE WISDOM OF CROCODILES': A BLOODSUCKER FINDS IT HARD TO LIVE AS
A ROMANTIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whenever someone wears a collarless shirt in a movie, it's a
signal that there's something otherworldly about him, part of the
tradition that includes Bruce Lee, Steven Segal and Ben Kingsley in
``Gandhi.'' And such is the case with Steven Grslcz (Jude Law), the
languid, parchment-pale vampire in ``The Wisdom of Crocodiles.''
It's the kind of picture in which the bloodsucker is so chic he
probably uses the spelling ``vampyre.''
</P>
<P>
   As Steven takes to his victims, a decorative splatter of
arterial blood hits the backlighted bedroom wall of his groovy
bachelor pad. As he labels crystalline shards with the names of his
female victims and scribbles ``despair'' and ``disappointment'' in
notebooks, there's a glint of despair and disappointment in his
mostly impassive eyes, an expression you will soon recognize on
fellow audience members if you're in a theater showing ``Wisdom.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven is also the kind of vampire who may have spent too much
time reading Anne Rice, since his life has the fruity morbidity
associated with her vampire Lestat. He seeks victims who fall in
love with him, so that he can drain the love from their
bloodstreams. Otherwise he sucks down despair and disappointment,
which are taking a physical toll on him: He is dying and needs to
find pure love to stay alive.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Steven's dialogue sounds like the kind of florid pick-up
lines better used on second-year literature students or the kind of
lonely women seen only in movies. He comes up with insights like
the three-brains theory, saying that everyone has three brains:
Human, mammalian and reptilian. Not only does this lofty locution
confuse his victims, who were probably under the illusion that
humans were mammals, but it also makes one wonder which brain was
responsible for the script.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such lines, and ideas borrowed from Rice and David
Cronenberg _ Steven's dissipation feels like an AIDS metaphor, as
did Jeff Goldblum's state in Cronenberg's ``Fly'' _ ``Crocodile''
is too enervated to be garish. Even when a slow-witted gang whose
leader looks like a teddy boy from one of the musical numbers in
the 1985 film ``Absolute Beginners'' _ and is about as threatening
_ shows up, the movie seems bloodless. Law doesn't disgrace himself
here, though he doesn't have much to do, and the director, Po Chih
Leong, is deft at creating atmosphere, but it's an atmosphere we've
all seen before.
</P>
<P>
   Steven is being tracked by the dogged but kindly Inspector
Healey (Timothy Spall, who gets to offer some feeling that is
either human or mammalian, since he doesn't have to be cloaked in
stylish dissolution). When Steven chats with Healey about the
nature of evil, it's almost as if he is trying to pick up the
detective, but the movie doesn't follow up on the pansexual vampire
idea, since it has a prescribed number of marks to hit.
</P>
<P>
   And most of those marks are hit when Steven pursues Anne, played
by Elina Loewensohn, who for the first time in her career has found
someone paler than herself to play against (no small feat, since
she has been in Hal Hartley movies and played a vampire herself in
``Nadia''). Anne is moody and thin-skinned, and her temperament,
which suggests passion, brings dramatic tension to her scenes. It
was a good idea to make her not easily won over, though sadly
that's one of the few ideas ``Wisdom'' has.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE WISDOM OF CROCODILES'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Po Chih Leong; written by Paul Hoffman; director of
photography, Oliver Curtis; edited by Robin Sales; music by John
Lunn and Orlando Gough; production designer, Andy Harris; produced
by David Lascelles and Carolyn Choa; released by Miramax Films.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Jude Law (Steven Grslcz), Elina Loewensohn (Anne Levels),
Timothy Spall (Inspector Healey), Kerry Fox (Maria Vaughan), Jack
Davenport (Sergeant Roche) and Colin Salmon (Martin).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 99 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wisdom of Crocodiles'' is rated R (under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes nudity,
violence and bloodletting.
</P>
</TEXT>
