<P>
   NAACP-IMPACT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the four years that NAACP President Kweisi Mfume has led the
country's oldest and largest civil rights organization, he has
taken it from $4 million in debt to a $2 million surplus. By
boycotting South Carolina because of its Confederate flag on the
statehouse and bullying major television network executives into
hiring more African Americans, the NAACP's national image has
soared. But what impact have these efforts had at the local level?
Fort Worth's branch has struggled with an aging membership and
leaders who appear unable to attract young members. Some members at
chapters around the nation said Mfume's national success may not be
trickling down to their branches. By BECHETTA JACKSON. Story will
move in ``a'' general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
