<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BRADLEY (Green Bay, Wis.) _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley, who
accused Vice President Al Gore of distorting his proposals and
being a clarion of negative campaigning in the Democratic primary
contests, endorses his former rival and the two present a united
front while stumping in Wisconsin. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-VEEPS (Washington) _ The National Abortion and
Reproductive Rights Action League, a pro-choice advocacy group,
rates possible vice presidential nominees, 10 Republicans and 10
Democrats, on abortion issues. Of the Republicans, only New Jersey
Gov. Christine Todd Whitman is rated good, getting a B. The group
gives New York Gov. George Pataki a C and the other Republicans Ds
and Fs. NARAL gives all 10 Democrats good or excellent ratings. By
ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-TEXANS (Austin, Texas) _ Unhappy about the way the way
Texas is being portrayed by Al Gore's presidential campaign, some
Texans are trying to counter the vice president's efforts to
``distort the facts about our state'' in order to discredit Texas
Gov. George W. Bush. The Proud of Texas Committee says its members
include Democrats and independents. By PEGGY FIKAC.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-VETERANS (Pittsburgh) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush calls for
a five-year, $75-million effort to employ military veterans as
mentors for troubled youngsters. By R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ESTATE-TAX (Washington) _ The Senate debates legislation that
would abolish the estate tax, a step opposed by President Clinton.
Democrats argue it amounts to a costly windfall for the wealthiest
Americans, not the family farmers and small businesses that
sponsors say suffer most. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-CONTROL (Washington) _ Two months after mothers marched in
Washington and across the nation calling for stricter gun laws,
legislation that would curb access to weapons is stalled on Capitol
Hill. By LETITIA STEIN.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HIV-MEDICATION (Durban, South Africa) _ Despite free drugs,
refills by phone and medication by mail, 80 percent of HIV-positive
patients at two Houston clinics did not stick to their medication
schedules, according to a new study presented at an international
AIDS meeting. Spotty adherence to drug regimens leads to viral
resistance to the drug, which increases the danger that an
untreatable form of the AIDS virus could begin circulating. By
LEIGH HOPPER.
</P>
<P>
   BREAST-MILK (Durban, South Africa) _ The unusual results of a
new study suggest a safer way for poor, HIV-positive women to
breast feed their babies, an important discovery for women in
developing countries. By LEIGH HOPPER.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WACO-TRIAL (Waco, Texas) _ Twenty people, including several
children, died of gunshot wounds, not causes related to fire in the
Branch Davidian compound, according to autopsies read in court. The
information is not new, but the government argues that it makes the
case the cult leader David Koresh and his ringleaders were bent on
suicide. The judge in the federal civil suit brought by Branch
Davidian survivors against the government has ordered lawyers to
wrap up testimony. By JOHN GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ If it isn't canceled, CBS' ``Big
Brother'' is supposed to run through September. But ``Brother''
isn't worth the bother. Bad taste, of which it reeks, isn't even
the problem. Watching shallow, inarticulate people do nothing is
simply boring. It's better to read Harry Potter instead. By
MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SWIRE-PRIVACY (Washington) _ We profile Peter Swire, President
Clinton's adviser on people's rights to privacy in their medical,
financial and genetic data. Swire's concern with privacy issues
started in Albany, N.Y., in the 1970s when he worked on computers
in his family's furniture stores and began thinking about the
implications of the dawning age of cyberspace. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
