<HEADLINE>
BANKRUPTCY OF SOGO CORP. SPREADS ANXIETY OVER JAPANESE BUSINESS
WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The collapse of Sogo Corp., a department store operator
that owed more than $17 billion, cast a dark cloud over business
activities here Thursday and resurrected anxieties about the
fragilities in Japan's economy.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark Nikkei stock index fell 1.8 percent, as investors
sought to protect themselves from the potential fallout from Sogo's
bankruptcy filing on Wednesday. Even the currency and bond markets,
typically indifferent to the travails of individual Japanese
companies, were uneasy.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians and bureaucrats sought to blame one another for the
ham-handed way in which Sogo's bankruptcy, one of the biggest in
Japan, came about and the uncomfortable financial issues its demise
will force them to confront.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling Liberal Democratic Party laid responsibility for the
bankruptcy on the Financial Reconstruction Commission, the
government agency responsible for overhauling Japan's debt-ridden
financial system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regarding debt relief procedures in the future, the Financial
Reconstruction Commission should be more cautious,'' said Hidenao
Nakagawa, who as chief Cabinet secretary is the ruling party's
leading spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   On June 30, the commission announced that the government would
spend 97 billion yen, or $915 million at current exchange rates, of
taxpayer money as part of a rescue plan to reduce Sogo's debt, thus
setting the retailer back on its feet but inciting a rare burst of
public fury that forced politicians to call off the deal on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Reconstruction commission officials rejected Nakagawa's
accusation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's easy for him to say,'' said one commission official,
who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``He would be just as upset if
we had let Sogo fail right from the start.''
</P>
<P>
   Sogo, which operates 25 department stores in Japan and employs
10,000 people, has had one foot in the grave since April, when it
asked banks to forgive 631.9 billion yen, or $6 billion, in
outstanding debt, a legacy of its speculative borrowing during
Japan's boom years.
</P>
<P>
   But Shinsei Bank, a Sogo creditor with its own history of
financial crises, objected to Sogo's request. Shinsei, which a
group of foreign investors purchased from the government last year,
not only refused to forgive any Sogo debt, it also refused to cast
itself as the bank responsible for Sogo's demise. Instead,
Shinsei's foreign owners exercised a provision in their purchase
agreement that forces the government to take responsibility for
loans that have soured since they acquired the bank.
</P>
<P>
   There was some speculation Thursday that the indirect role of
Shinsei's foreign owners in the Sogo collapse would arouse some
resentment. Foreign ownership of Japanese banks is still a relative
rarity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, I think that in some quarters, this is going to
reinforce the idea of well, we shouldn't have sold an important
institution to people who won't play the game our way,'' said
Ronald Bevacqua, senior economist at Commerz Securities in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sogo debacle raises even more painful, pointed issues
for a country that typically defers hard questions.
</P>
<P>
   How can politicians allow legions of debt-laden construction
companies that are their biggest supporters to suffer the same fate
as Sogo? Shinsei is also a major lender to Kumagai Gumi and Hazama
Corp., which has already asked for debt forgiveness, and other
general contractors are suffering.
</P>
<P>
   Can the Japanese economy withstand a flood of bankruptcies?
Japan is nurturing what it hopes is a fledgling economic recovery,
but a large increase in bankruptcies could derail that recovery by
increasing unemployment, forcing fire sales of assets, eroding
consumer confidence and pushing the banking system toward a new
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's scary,'' said Minoru Nakano, an analyst who has been
following the Sogo saga at Teikoku Data Bank, a data collection and
credit-monitoring company.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Nakano said he believed the ruling party was trying to position
itself to avoid the fallout from a rash of big bankruptcies, not to
stop them from happening. He noted that the ruling party assigned
responsibility for the Construction Ministry, long the primary
source of party power, to a member of a coalition party, Chikage
Ogi, after the June election.
</P>
<P>
   ``This construction minister is not a member of the ruling
party, and that says the ruling party does not want to exert its
influence over the industry,'' he said. ``The Liberal Democrats do
not want to be involved right now.''
</P>
<P>
   How big an impact a series of large bankruptcies would have on
the banking system is unclear. Many banks have set aside reserves
to cover potential losses.
</P>
<P>
   The Industrial Bank of Japan was Sogo's biggest creditor,
holding some 380 billion yen, or roughly $3.6 billion, but it said
Thursday that while it might lose 235.6 billion yen of those loans,
the bankruptcy would have no impact on its bottom line. Asahi Bank
said it might lose 47.8 billion yen, or $451 million, but that the
loss would not affect its profits.
</P>
<P>
   But most analysts worry that the banks may have underestimated
the extent of the losses they may have to absorb. Many considered
the Financial Reconstruction Commission's planned rescue of Sogo as
little more than a bank bailout in disguise. ``If they do allow
these companies to collapse, it will precipitate a second banking
crisis,'' said one economist who asked to remain anonymous. ``The
public is going to pay for this one way or the other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
