<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHUCK-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHUCK AND BUCK': CHILDHOOD LONGINGS IN A GROWN-UP WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
 By A.O. SCOTT1    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shot in mostly hand-held video and featuring a character whose
mental balance is questionable, to say the least, ``Chuck and
Buck'' might be described as a Dogma 95 version of ``Disney's `The
Kid.''' The two films share some underlying themes _ the pain of
growing up, the persistence of primal fears and desires into
adulthood, the desperate human need for love _ but their methods of
exploring them could hardly be more different.
</P>
<P>
   The difference, ultimately, is between easy sentiment and
difficult emotion. Though ``Chuck and Buck,'' Miguel Arteta's new
film, is frequently funny and always sincere, there is nothing cute
or heartwarming about its view of childhood. It's an intimate,
slightly creepy, often disturbing look at loneliness and need _
something, in other words, for the child in all of us.
</P>
<P>
   Like Jon Turteltaub's sudsy ``Kid,'' ``Chuck and Buck'' tells
the story of a confident, successful man confronted by an unwelcome
visitor from his boyhood, a reminder of painful memories and lost
innocence. The revenant encountered by Charlie Sitter (Chris Weitz)
is not a time-traveling younger incarnation of himself, as in ``The
Kid,'' but rather his boyhood friend Buck (Mike White), who has
gotten stuck in time. Buck is functional enough to keep himself
supplied with lollipops _ his main source of nutrition, it seems _
and clean clothes. He can even drive a car. But for the most part
he dwells in the mental and emotional world of the 11-year-old he
was when he and Charlie, whom he insists on calling Chuck, were
inseparable buddies.
</P>
<P>
   The film begins with a slow pan across Buck's bedroom, a visual
inventory of the board games, figurines, model airplanes and cars
that furnish his life. In the background we hear his mother
coughing herself to death. Charlie, summoned by a handwritten
letter on juvenile stationery, goes to the funeral, and Buck, after
making a fumbling sexual advance at his old friend, decides to
follow him to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   There he installs himself _ along with his toys, his lollipops
and his vaporizer _ in a motel, which soon becomes the base of one
of the strangest stalking enterprises ever recorded on film. When
Charlie rebuffs Buck's incessant phone calls and unannounced
visits, Buck decides to catch his pal's conscience with a play
called ``Hank and Frank,'' an allegory of their fairy-tale
friendship and its cruel termination.
</P>
<P>
   With his weak, wobbly chin, pale skin and paler eyelashes, White
is an uncanny embodiment of arrested development. His character
elicits both protectiveness and revulsion. The movie's female
characters _ Chuck's fiancee, Carlyn (Beth Colt); his assistant,
Jamila (Maya Rudolph); and a sympathetic theater manager (Lupe
Ontiveros) _ respond to his guileless, scary innocence with
confusion, alarm and enough maternal solicitude to keep him from
unraveling entirely. The audience may find it hard to believe that
White is acting, despite a record of grown-up achievements that
include producing several television shows and writing the script
for this movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck and Buck'' as a whole exhibits the quiet sensitivity and
quicksilver intelligence that infuse White's performance. Ontiveros
is especially fine in a role that is in many ways the key to the
film; she's a bedrock of sanity and good humor. In a brilliant
stroke of casting, Weitz's brother Paul appears as Sam, a thuggish
would-be actor who becomes Buck's unlikely surrogate for the lost
Chuck.
</P>
<P>
   Arteta, whose first feature was the arresting and offbeat ``Star
Maps,'' presents Buck's world with delicacy and tact, but he never
flinches from the more discomfiting implications of the story.
Buck's childlike longing for attention and acceptance expresses
itself as sexual desire. He is desperate not only to recapture the
intimacy he and Charlie knew as boys, but also to revive the sexual
play that was part of their bond. How this longing is resolved is
both shocking and, by the time it happens, entirely credible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck and Buck'' is a strange, intense and moving film about
friendship and loss, an antidote to the current epidemic of lazy
nostalgia for the innocence of childhood and therefore, magically,
one of the few truly grown-up movies you're likely to see this
year.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `CHUCK AND BUCK'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Miguel Arteta; written by Mike White; director of
photography, Chuy Chavez; edited by Jeff Betancourt; music by Joey
Waronker, Tony Maxwell and Smokey Hormel; production designer,
Renee Davenport; produced by Matthew Greenfield; released by
Artisan Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Mike White (Buck), Chris Weitz (Chuck), Lupe Ontiveros
(Beverly), Beth Colt (Carlyn), Maya Rudolph (Jamila) and Paul Weitz
(Sam).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 95 minutes. This film is rated R. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck and Buck'' is rated R (under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It includes sexual references and
situations.
</P>
</TEXT>
