 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Friday, July 14. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Washington) _ Developments in the peace talks at
Camp David. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GAS-TAX-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The Senate considers an
amendment to cut the gasoline tax. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA-POLICE (Philadelphia) _ All decked out in bunting
and civic pride for the forthcoming Republican presidential
convention, the city reeled Thursday from the ignominy of seeing
its police on national television furiously beating and kicking a
suspect who had embarrassed them by allegedly stealing a police car
during a running gun battle through the streets. By Francis X.
Clines.
</P>
<P>
   NY-COLLAPSE (New York) _ Three people were unaccounted for after
a wall of a four-story commercial building in lower Manhattan
partially collapsed on Thursday afternoon. (Summary from wires)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BRADLEY (Green Bay, Wis.) _ With Al Gore at his side, Bill
Bradley endorsed the vice president for the White House on
Thursday, saying that ``winning is a team sport'' and Democrats
need the strength of unity. Gore called Bradley a leader ``who
brought high purpose and high ideals to our contest.'' With that,
the rivals in a harsh winter's presidential primary campaign, swept
by Gore, joined forces for the fall. It was Bradley's first
campaign appearance since he conceded to Gore after the March 7
presidential primaries. (Summary from wires) By Katharine Q.
Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DIAGEO-GENERAL-MILLS (Undated) _ In a move that would mean the
corporate union of Betty Crocker and the Pillsbury Dough Boy,
General Mills said it is in talks to acquire Diageo's Pillsbury
division. In a statement, Diageo confirmed the talks, which were
reported Thursday in The Wall Street Journal. While neither side
would say what the price might be for Pillsbury, analysts
speculated that it could end up between $9 billion and $11 billion.
By Constance L. Hays and Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GLOBAL-WARMING (Undated) _ A new analysis of the climate of
the last 1,000 years suggests that human activity is the dominant
factor behind the sharp global warming trend seen in the 20th
century. The research, described in the journal Science, offers the
most direct link yet between people and the 1.1 degree rise in
average global temperature over the last hundred years. The study
has already sparked debate among camps of scientists who dispute
the existing climate record and others who say the oceans play an
underappreciated role. But many climatologists said it marked a
substantial move forward in understanding forces that are warming
the earth _ and are likely to continue warming it in coming
decades. By Andrew C. Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NJ-COAST (Undated) _ Geologists have long viewed the West
Coast as the dynamic side of North America, the shore where
earthquakes, tidal waves, and other potentially dangerous
geological forces are most likely to strike. But there are
increasing signs that the outer sloping edge of the continental
shelf along the East Coast has the potential to cave in, possibly
abruptly enough to send destructive tidal waves, or tsunamis,
speeding toward shore. The latest evidence comes in a study being
published in the journal Science, which found that rock buried
nearly 2,000 feet under the sea bed off the New Jersey coast is so
porous that it is actually mostly water. By Andrew C. Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-INFANTS (Durban, South Africa) _ Research described
Thursday at the International AIDS conference shows that a simple
drug regimen given to pregnant women infected with HIV can protect
their infants, possibly as long as 18 months after they are born,
even if they are breastfed. The regimen differs from another
treatment, whose benefits, according to research reported last
week, seemed to be offset by transmission of the virus through
breastfeeding. Authors of both studies said they would work
together to attempt to unravel the apparent contradiction. By
Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
</TEXT>
