<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000713.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1202 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TECH-DIVERSITY-$ADV16     07-13 1820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-DIVERSITY-$ADV16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NO EASY SOLUTIONS TO MINORITY GAP IN THE HIGH-TECH WORLD
 &HT;    1000&AMP;add. With TECH-DATA. Moving in (w) Washington and (f)
financial categories for release Sunday, July 16.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALTHAM, Mass. _ Twenty-year-old Greg Bogin grew up in the mean
streets of Compton, Calif., just blocks away from the public courts
where the Williams sisters, Venus and Serena, got their
introduction to tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Like the famous duo, Bogin is a whiz, too _ at math and science.
He is using his intellect to lift him out of the gang-infested
neighborhood where he was raised and where he saw friends die.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see the computer world from the inner city. You
don't see Bill Gates as a role model. Well, I've seen it now,''
said Bogin, a college junior doing research this summer for Verizon
Laboratories near Boston in a program jointly sponsored by the
United Negro College Fund.
</P>
<P>
   America's business attire has changed from stuffy suits to
casual cool, but the faces remain largely the same. The New
Economy, like the old economy, is dominated by white males.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech professions have a disproportionately small number of
women, blacks and Hispanics in high-paying technical jobs. Bogin
and others like him are the exceptions in the fastest-growing
sector of the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   The trickling pipeline of science and math majors from American
colleges and universities suggests that the situation will not soon
improve, leaving the specter of a growing wage gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is, without a doubt, a vast untapped talent pool in the
United States among women and minorities, currently
under-represented in engineering and information sciences,'' the
president's Information Technology Advisory Committee said in a
report last year.
</P>
<P>
   The National Science Foundation called it a ``serious national
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a federal commission studying the imbalance warned
that America risks losing its competitive edge in the global
marketplace if it fails to provide adequate math and science
education to draw women, African Americans and Hispanics into the
work force.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Commerce Department estimates that women _ 51 percent
of the population _ make up only 28 percent of computer
programmers, 26 percent of computer scientists and 9 percent of
engineers.
</P>
<P>
   The White House advisory group noted that African Americans,
Hispanics and Native Americans constitute one-fourth of the total
U.S. work force, but only 6.7 percent of the information and
computer science work force and 5.9 percent of the engineers.
Asian-Americans, who comprise 4 percent of the nation's population,
tend to be over-represented, at least double their proportion to
the general public.
</P>
<P>
   Programs like the one operating at Verizon (formerly GTE before
its recent merger with Bell Atlantic) are seeking to correct the
imbalance for blacks. At its leafy campus west of Boston, Verizon
each summer offers 20 college students the chance to work side by
side with laboratory researchers brainstorming the company's next
leaps forward in technology.
</P>
<P>
   Bogin, a junior at Xavier University in New Orleans, is helping
write new data encryption software for the Palm Pilot handheld
device that would improve e-mail security. He works in the
facility's top-secret lab room and in a simple, cramped office
where he calculates algorithms and writes code.
</P>
<P>
   It is a road that began in fifth grade, when he scored high on
an aptitude test and was able to study at a math and science magnet
school that required him to rise at 4 every morning for a
three-hour bus ride to school.
</P>
<P>
   He credits his father, a baker for Nabisco, and his strict
mother for keeping his nose to the books and out of trouble. Yet he
is not necessarily looking for a pot of gold at the end of the
path.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in quick and easy money. Growing up in the
inner city, I saw it ruin too many people in my neighborhood who
were attracted to crime by the idea of a Mercedes and nice clothes
and all that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make a comfortable living for my family. But if
becoming a millionaire is part of that, I won't turn it down,'' he
added with a grin.
</P>
<P>
   Who's to blame for the lack of diversity?
</P>
<P>
   The industry faults public education for failing to prepare
students for careers in technology. Women and minority groups often
criticize the industry for not doing enough to support education
and training programs.
</P>
<P>
   Also blamed is the ``geek'' factor: a supposed cultural gulf
between the white and Asian male world of computers and women and
minorities, who feel they are not welcomed and thus do not wish to
be a part of it.
</P>
<P>
   The diversity problem, a politically charged issue as high-tech
wealth has grown, has prompted 25 tech corporations, including IBM,
America Online, Intel and Sun Microsystems to pledge $250 million
for recruitment and training aimed at bring more women and
minorities into the field.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is a high-risk, highly competitive world that rewards
talent, regardless of gender or skin color, said industry
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that people care about are your results,'' said Patricia
Sueltz, president of the software products division at Sun
Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a high-hurdle mark that is color-blind, whether
you're white, African-American Asian, Hispanic or whatever. The
issue is getting the numbers up in middle schools and high schools
and educating students to the opportunities in math and science
fields,'' said Erik Phelps, who heads education programs for the
Verizon Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   College students continue to shun math and science, despite
national efforts to promote them. And while the number of women and
minorities gaining degrees in technical fields has grown over the
past two decades, it remains small.
</P>
<P>
   The total of U.S. undergraduates earning computer and
information sciences degrees declined from a high of 41,889 in 1986
to just 24,768 in 1997, at a time when demand for them was growing.
Evidence suggests that the Internet boom has spurred more current
students to major in the field, but still far below the level of
industry demand.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Technology firms currently have about 800,000 job vacancies now
or projected through the end of 2000, according to the Information
Technology Association of America. The industry is seeking approval
from Congress to nearly double the current limit of 115,000 H-1B
visas, which allow technical workers from India, China, Russia and
elsewhere into the United States to take high-tech jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Importing talent would not be necessary with a full commitment
by government and high-tech companies to improve public schools and
training opportunities for workers in need for updated skills,
argue minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   The Coalition for Fair Employment in Silicon Valley, an
organization that represents minority professionals, is lobbying
against the bill in Congress, claiming that there are enough
Americans _ including minorities, women and older workers _ who
could be hired and trained to do the work.
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs almost to be a national emergency act to improve
the pipeline of engineering and computer science graduates,'' said
Butch Wing, director of the Silicon Valley office of Jesse
Jackson's Rainbow/PUSH Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is a great irony that with high-tech and the New
Economy creating jobs we find ourselves to unprepared, and we're
not doing enough to improve our education system and re-train
workers and make this a priority,'' Wing said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are small but positive signs.
</P>
<P>
   A national campaign led by government and industry is seeking to
close the ``digital divide'' by providing computers to inner city
schools, libraries and community centers.
</P>
<P>
   With the number of women and minorities earning undergraduate
and post-graduate degrees at an all-time high, evidence suggests
that they have begun to make inroads into jobs in marketing, public
relations and other non-technical areas of the New Economy.
</P>
<P>
   But the big money still goes to the people with the technical
skills. The starting salaries for computer systems managers at tech
firms in Silicon Valley can be as high as $80,000 a year. The
average annual income for software techies in Seattle is $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wage gap will only get worse. I think the consensus in the
industry is that the talent wars are going to get worse, not
better, and that means salaries are going to continue to
skyrocket,'' said Gary Chapman, head of the 21st Century Project at
LBJ School at the University of Texas in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Correcting the imbalance also may be a slow task of overcoming
cultural barriers and rigid attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   Black and Hispanic leaders fault insular attitudes within their
communities that do not fully value academic success and negatively
stereotype ``nerd'' professions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're put down if you're smart, and called a 'Tom' for trying
to get ahead,'' said Bogin.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the equation, those with the skills often
avoid the white dominated high-tech world in favor of careers in
medicine or teaching, which they can practice in their own
communities.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by the American Association of University Women
found that girls are avoiding high-tech careers not because of math
and science phobia, but because they consider computer-related jobs
to be boring and lonely.
</P>
<P>
   Raegan(CQ) Higgins, 20, another Verizon-United Negro College
Fund scholar, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   A math major from Baton Rouge, La., her summer experience in the
lab confirmed her belief that she would not enjoy a job working
exclusively with computers and software code. Higgins wants to go
on to earn a doctorate and then become a university professor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more of a people person,'' she said. ``It kills me to be
at a computer terminal all day.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Commission on the Advancement of Women and Minorities in
Science, Engineering and Technology Development:
www.nsf.gov/od/cawmset
</P>
<P>
   President's Information Technology Advisory Committee 1999
report to the White House: www.ccic.gov/ac/report
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Commerce Department's Digital 2000 report:
www.esa.doc/gov/de2000.pdf
</P>
<P>
   Diversity/Careers in Engineering and Information Technology:
www.diversitycareers.com
</P>
<P>
   American Association of University Women's Tech-Savvy 2000
report: www.aauw.org/2000/techsavvy.html
</P>
<P>
   Women in Technology International (WITI), a professional
development group: www. witi.org
</P>
<P>
   National Action Council for Minorities in Engineering:
www.nacme.org
</P>
<P>
   National Society of Black Engineers: www.nsbe.org
</P>
<P>
   Society of Hispanic Professional Engineers: www.shpe.org
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Holmes's-mail address is chuckh(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
