<SLUG> BC-SHADOW-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SHADOW HOURS': NIGHT CRAWLERS, BEWARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For someone who can recognize a cliche when he hears one,
Michael Holloway sure takes a long time to wake up, smell the
mercaptan and realize that his newfound pal, Stuart Chapell, is not
the big-time writer he professes to be.
</P>
<P>
   But if Michael did, ``Shadow Hours'' would not be the tedious
descent into cinema hell that it turns out to be.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart, a smug cicerone on Michael's tour of the Los Angeles
netherworld, stands for the proposition that it is an ill windbag
that blows no good. Part Mephistopheles with his black suit,
gleaming black Porsche and pearly white smirk, Stuart is also part
guardian angel, determined to save Michael's soul by showing him
that the path to goodness lies through the dens of iniquity.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely has debauchery been such a bore.
</P>
<P>
   In a film that seems to have been budgeted by the watt, Los
Angeles becomes a night town of drugs, alcohol, sex and seedy
premises that quarter everything from orgies and sadomasochism to
bare-knuckle, no-holds-barred fights and, shades of ``The Deer
Hunter,'' Russian roulette played for money.
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Isaac Eaton and starring Balthazar
Getty, one of its co-producers, as Michael, and Peter Weller as
Stuart, ``Shadow Hours'' is a sluggish tale of redemption dragged
down on the one hand by Michael's monotonous depression and on the
other by the asinine dialogue furnished Weller.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a murder investigation subplot and all sorts of
sketchily rendered sin, ``Shadow Hours'' remains a film without
dramatic momentum, an involving protagonist or more than a
skittishly voyeuristic and superficial approach to its conflict
between good and evil.
</P>
<P>
   When first encountered, the hangdog Michael is trying to recover
from a past of drugs, alcohol and treatment centers. Enrolled in a
group-support program, he has the good fortune to have a loving,
pregnant wife, Chloe (Rebecca Gayheart) and the not-so-good fortune
to have a depressing, low-paying job on the graveyard shift in a
self-service gas station that also peddles sodas and snacks.
</P>
<P>
   Owned by the drawling, advice-spouting Roland Montague (Brad
Dourif), the premises, besieged occasionally by raving derelicts,
drug-addicted robbers and combative husbands and wives, are also
right across the street from the apartment house where a serial
killer with a habit of twisting his victims' heads 180 degrees has
struck again.
</P>
<P>
   With surroundings like these, little wonder that the weak-willed
Michael is primed to accept the ever-so-friendly Stuart's
invitation to do a bit of night crawling, especially after Stuart
decks him out in a new suit and arranges for him to win a few
thousand dollars at one of those bloody brawls he likes to
frequent.
</P>
<P>
   So it isn't long before Michael is back to swilling hard liquor,
puffing on a ``magic cigar'' while Stuart fondles a couple of
bare-breasted hookers in a den of evil, snorting cocaine and lying
to poor Chloe, who would dearly and wisely like to move somewhere
up north.
</P>
<P>
   By this time, between the people with the fishhooks in their
faces and the Russian roulette game, not to mention the creeps
around the gas station, Michael is beginning to get a bad case of
the frights.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to go all the way down or you'll never finish it,''
Stuart has been telling him.
</P>
<P>
   As a cautionary tale, ``Shadow Hours'' may not persuade everyone
to swear off sin, but anyone who buys a ticket to it seems likely
to learn to become more discriminating in choosing movies.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SHADOW HOURS'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Isaac H. Eaton; director of photography,
Frank Byers; edited by Annamaria Szanto, Clayton Halsey and Bill
Yarhaus; music by Brian Tyler; production designer, Francis Pezza;
produced by Peter McAlevey and Eaton; released by CanWest
Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Balthazar Getty (Michael Holloway), Peter Weller (Stuart
Chappell), Rebecca Gayheart (Chloe Holloway), Peter Greene
(Detective Steve Adrianson), Michael Dorn (Detective Thomas
Greenwood), Richard Moll (Homeless Man), Frederic Forrest (Sean)
and Brad Dourif (Roland Montague).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 93 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shadow Hours'' is rated R (under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It includes scenes of sex, drug use,
sadomasochism, bloody fights and gunplay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 1640EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000713.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1205 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-RAGE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      07-13 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAGE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IT'S THE RAGE': LINKED, SOONER OR LATER, IN A SEMIAUTOMATIC
WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
 By A.O. SCOTT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It's the Rage'' begins with gunshots as a suburban homeowner
(Jeff Daniels) accidentally shoots an intruder who turns out to be
the business partner he has suspected of cuckolding him. From this
promising film noir beginning, James Stern's debut feature quickly
_ or rather, slowly, since the pacing is that of a long, talky
evening of repertory theater _ becomes an excruciatingly
literal-minded, floridly literary application of Chekhov's dictum
that a gun on the mantelpiece in the first act of a play must be
fired by the end.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the nine characters whose fates entwine in the manner of
a limping homage to Robert Altman is the victim or the perpetrator
of an act of gun violence, or sometimes both. ``It's the Rage,''
based on a play by Keith Reddin, who also wrote the screenplay,
purports to be a darkly comic look at our national obsession with
firearms, a satire of their seductive power and an expose of the
harm they do. But it's more like a ham-fisted high-concept public
service announcement, directed with stagy deliberateness and
written with tin-eared vernacular speechiness. Guns are bad, kids,
and if you can stay awake, you'll understand why.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt the high-mindedness of the project attracted its
impressive cast, one of the densest concentrations of Oscar winners
and nominees ever assembled for a noble bad movie. Some fare better
than others. Joan Allen as a repressed housewife who flees her
husband's murderous jealousy is, as ever, the picture of
understated, suffering poise.
</P>
<P>
   But Gary Sinise, as the reclusive computer genius with whom she
takes refuge, is all shtick in Coke-bottle glasses and ratty nerd
clothes. Anna Paquin as some kind of bleached-blond hip-hop
shoplifter is outdone in her pointless emoting only by Giovanni
Ribisi as her hopped-up hoodlum brother, who dresses in vintage Sid
Vicious fashions and looks, at one point, as if he might gnaw
through the chassis of a Lincoln Town Car just to vent his rage.
</P>
<P>
   The television actors do a bit better: David Schwimmer (Ross
from ``Friends'') and Andre Braugher (Pembleton from ``Homicide'')
shake loose their NBC personas in their portrayal of a gay couple
riven by jealousy and undone by the inevitable and implausible
outbreak of gunfire that pulls the movie to its conclusion. ``It's
the Rage'' does offer the dubious pleasure of watching superb
actors read terrible lines with evident conviction and impersonate
characters untethered to any known human reality. This wouldn't be
fatal if the film didn't festoon its literary posturing and its
contrived ``Columbo''-style narrative with the trappings of
political relevance. At the end, a Cheryl Wheeler song announces
that ``if it were up to me, I'd take away the guns.'' A fine
sentiment, but one that comes almost two hours too late.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `IT'S THE RAGE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by James Stern; written by Keith Reddin, based on his
play; director of photography, Alex Nepomniaschy; edited by Tony
Lombardo; music by Mark Mothersbaugh; production designer, Jerry
Fleming; produced by Stern, Peter Gilbert, Ash R. Shah, Anne
McCarthy and Mary Vernieu; released by Silver Nitrate Releasing.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Joan Allen (Helen Harding), Andre Braugher (Tim Sullivan),
Josh Brolin (Tennel), Jeff Daniels (Warren Harding), Robert Forster
(Tyler), Anna Paquin (Annabel Lee), Giovanni Ribisi (Sidney Lee),
David Schwimmer (Chris), Gary Sinise ( Morgan) and Bokeem Woodbine
(Agee).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 103 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's The Rage'' is rated R (under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It includes profanity and violence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
