<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1206 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0714-COX     07-13 1710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0714-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Out of seclusion, Bradley uses the e-word
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore and his vanquished rival, Bill Bradley, buried the
hatchet and campaigned together today for the first time since the
Democratic presidential fight ended. With Gore at his side in Green
Bay, Wis., Bradley said: ``Today I want to make it clear that I
endorse Al Gore for president of the United States.'' Bradley said
that ``winning is a team sport'' and Democrats need the strength of
unity. In turn, Gore called Bradley a leader ``who brought high
purpose and high ideals to our contest.'' It was Bradley's first
campaign appearance since he conceded to Gore after Super Tuesday,
March 7.
</P>
<P>
   A NEW MISSION FOR VETERANS
</P>
<P>
   Appearing before the Veterans of Foreign Wars Pennsylvania State
Convention in Pittsburgh, George W. Bush unveiled a $75 million
program today offering U.S. military veterans ``a new mission'' as
mentors and role models for the nation's youth. Pushing his
``compassionate conservative'' message ahead of the convention that
begins July 31, Bush's five-year proposal would provide matching
grants to organizations that connect veterans and retired military
personnel with young people through mentoring, tutoring,
after-school and other programs.
</P>
<P>
   ME, MYSELF, AND ONLY TWO OTHERS
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush said today he's winnowed his list of possible
vice presidential candidates, and he quickly added that only his
wife, Laura, and the man in charge of the search, Dick Cheney, also
know who remains in the running. With speculation rising about his
pick in the run-up to the convention, Bush said there has been
``serious vetting'' of medical, legal and financial records of the
contenders. He indicated he doesn't intend to invite candidates for
publicly disclosed meetings, saying, ``I know everybody pretty darn
well.''
</P>
<P>
   JUST A SLIP OF THE TONGUE?
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on MSNBC, Bush campaign spokesman Ari Fleischer was
discussing the relationship between George W. Bush and Arizona Sen.
John McCain since their meeting in Pittsburgh in May. Fleischer, on
McCain's role at the convention: ``The governor and the senator
have been in frequent touch on the telephone talking about various
issues, particularly saving Social Security. So we're working
shoulder to shoulder, and the vice president, of course, is going
to be featured prominently at the Republican convention in a prime
time speaking role.''
</P>
<P>
   BUSH SOLIDLY BEHIND CAMP DAVID TALKS
</P>
<P>
   In the days leading up to the Camp David peace talks, one of
George W. Bush's foreign policy advisers counseled Israeli
officials to accept only a comprehensive peace agreement and to
resist any efforts by the Clinton administration to use the summit
meeting in the presidential campaign. Those comments by Richard
Perle caused Bush to distance himself from those views. Bush said
Perle had been ``speaking for himself'' and not the Bush campaign.
``I wish the administration all the best when it comes to bringing
peace to the Middle East,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-SHRILLARY
</P>
<P>
   New York's Republican Party chairman has sent out a fund-raising
letter branding Hillary Clinton ``cold-blooded and hotheaded'' and
a ``shrill and scheming person'' who is trying to ``lie her way
into high office.'' In the letter, obtained today by the Associated
Press, William Powers also rips the first lady as ``abrasive and
annoying, brash and bitter, calculating and scheming, distant and
deceitful, polarizing and power-hungry.'' Clinton spokesman Howard
Wolfson said ``these kind of personal attacks have no place in
politics'' and called on Clinton's Senate opponent, Rick Lazio, to
disavow the letter. Lazio's campaign said, though, that Powers has
a right to express his opinions.
</P>
<P>
   PART OF THE SOLUTION OR PROBLEM?
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans, irked by Al Gore's complaints about a
``do-nothing'' Congress, had some advice for him: Quit campaigning,
come back to Washington and roll up your sleeves. ``Before he can
criticize us ... he ought to be willing to pitch in and help,''
said Roy Blunt (R-Mo.), George W. Bush's point man in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ALWAYS TIME FOR A FUND-RAISER
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee plans to cap its convention
next month by raising $2 million for its candidates. All of the
money raised will go for advertising and other vote-getting
activities for Democratic candidates all down the line. As a
result, contributions are limited to a maximum of $20,000 from
individuals and $15,000 from political action committees. No
corporate or union donations _ the unregulated sums known as ``soft
money'' _ will be accepted. The event is set for the Shrine
Auditorium in Los Angeles on Aug. 17, right after Gore delivers his
acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   WIRED UP IN PHILLY
</P>
<P>
   The electricians' union local in Philadelphia is in a dispute
with TV networks over wiring for the Republican convention, and the
mayor has stepped in to try to resolve the problem. The
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers Local 98 is
questioning why the major networks are not using local union
laborers for their telecommunications work. At least one network
says it has the right to use its own employees. The union has met
with Mayor John Street several times, and Street in turn has met
with network officials. The sides have yet to reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   JIG'S UP FOR 527S
</P>
<P>
   Political groups that until now have enjoyed the anonymity and
secrecy of Section 527 of the tax code will have to file disclosure
forms with the IRS by July 31. Moving quickly to implement a law
passed by Congress and signed by President Clinton on July 1, the
IRS sent word to the 527s that they must disclose their officers,
address and other identifying information, along with donor names,
size of donations and expenditures. Until now, 527s have not been
required to divulge even their addresses or phone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   PARENTHOOD AND POLITICAL PLANNING
</P>
<P>
   Planned Parenthood plans $2.5 million in TV ads spotlighting
George W. Bush's anti-abortion views, hoping to reach independent
and Republican women who support abortion rights. The group's
research suggests a sizable number of women respect Planned
Parenthood, but are leaning toward Bush. ``We're focusing on those
`compassionate conservative' Republican and independenrsal health
care coverage, a policy goal more popular with liberal Democrats
than conservative Republicans and even more sweeping and costly
than the plan proposed by Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY TO BURN
</P>
<P>
   The Republican and Democratic Senate campaign committees are
both showing big bank balances. The Democratic group said it had
$27 million in the bank on June 30 after having raised $49 million
since January 1999. The Republican counterpart reported $21 million
cash on hand at the end of June, having raised $55.7 million in
this election cycle. Both said they had more cash on hand at this
point in the election calendar than they ever had in previous
elections.
</P>
<P>
   THEIR KIND OF GUY NO LONGER
</P>
<P>
   For more than three decades, Democrats and other liberals have
reveled in Ralph Nader's success as a corporate scourge, an
all-round common scold of Big Business. But they're chortling no
longer. For Nader now has a new pack of scoundrels: Al Gore and the
Democratic Party. Gore, who rarely takes any position that might
offend anyone, would seem ill-cast as a villain. But in Nader's
view, the vice president is tainted by his association with the
pro-business, pro-globalism policies of the Clinton administration.
So Nader, as the nominee of the Green Party, is set on sending Gore
off into the political sunset.
</P>
<P>
   SHIPSHAPE AT OLD NAVY QUARTERS
</P>
<P>
   It's a defense contractor's dream: dozens of influential members
of Congress lodging for a week in old Navy barracks just a few
yards from where the companies do their work. This dream will
become reality at the Republican convention in a couple of weeks
courtesy of Rep. Curt Weldon (R-Pa.) The House Armed Services
subcommittee chairman arranged for his colleagues to stay in
kitchen-equipped quarters at the converted Philadelphia Naval
Shipyard. There's no pool, golf course, restaurant or bellhop, but
it's the closest digs to the convention hall: less than a mile.
Some hotels where delegations are staying are as far as 30 miles
away.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN GOING BACK ON THE BUS
</P>
<P>
   John McCain , the unsuccessful presidential hopeful, will be
revving up his Straight Talk Express this fall _ for House
Republican congressional candidates in at least half a dozen swing
states. McCain and Rep. J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, the fourth-ranking
House Republican, are planning to team up after the convention to
go on the road in several states, including Ohio, California,
Florida, New York, Illinois and Michigan. The campaign seeks to
exploit the appeal of McCain and Watts, the only Republican
African-African in Congress, with independents and other swing
voters.
</P>
<P>
   THE UPCOMING GENERATION
</P>
<P>
   As Al Gore and George W. Bush continue to kick up dust on the
campaign trail, their younger surrogates also are getting busy.
Earlier this week, George P. Bush, son of Florida Gov. Jeb Bush,
kicked off a tour on his uncle's behalf that will bring him to 20
college campuses before the Republican convention in Philadelphia.
On Friday, Gore's eldest daughter, Karenna Schiff, will speak to
the College Democrats of America Convention in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   CAN'T BEAT 'EM, SUE 'EM
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party candidate John Hagelin, the transcendentalist
meditating alternative to Pat Buchanan, threatened lawsuits against
the Buchanan campaign unless it releases its petition-signer list
to the Hagelin campaign. The list, which Buchanan submitted to the
national Reform Party, was used to determine who received ballots
in the party's primary, which is currently under way.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
