<HEADER>
A1208 &Cx1f; tab-z
u d BC-20MINUTE-MENUS-1STLD-     07-13 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-20MINUTE-MENUS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ADV02-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV02  
 HEALTHY 20-MINUTE MENUS: CHILLED SOUPS FOR A HOT SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDITORS: Refiling to include nutritional information.)  
 (For use Wednesday, Aug. 2, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's 20MINUTE-MENUS. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of 20MINUTE-MENUS _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By MARIAN BURROS    
 c.2000 Foxcraft Ltd.    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is nothing more refreshing than a chilled soup on a hot
summer day. And when the soup seems rich and satisfying but is not
calorific it offers a double bonus because it fills you up without
fattening you up. Soup, salad and really good country bread are all
that you need for a summer supper.
</P>
<P>
   The soup recipes here have another great feature: one requires
no cooking at all, another barely any cooking and even in the one
where some cooking is necessary it is only a matter of about 10
minutes. It will hardly heat up the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes are quite simple and easy to put together, but
everything depends on the quality and flavor of the ingredients. If
the corn is not sweet, if the tomatoes are not deeply red and very
ripe, and if the basil is not crisply fresh you will still have a
soup, but it will not provide you with the essence of summer. This
season is far too short for anything but the very best.
</P>
<P>
   The colors of the corn and basil soup and the corn and pepper
soup are particularly alluring. The tomato basil soup is not as
handsome but the flavors make up for what it lacks in beauty.
</P>
<P>
   You can make any of these soups thicker or thinner by adjusting
the amount of kefir or buttermilk that you use. If you have never
used kefir before think of it as a thinner version of yogurt.
</P>
<P>
   CHILLED CREAMY CORN AND BASIL SOUP
</P>
<P>
   2 cups corn kernels (about 2 large ears corn)
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch green onions
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup lightly packed basil
</P>
<P>
   2 cups low-fat plain kefir or low-fat buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   Basil leaves for garnish
</P>
<P>
   1. Steam the corn for about 3 minutes and scrape off kernels.
</P>
<P>
   2. Wash, trim the roots from green onions and trim leaving 2
inches of green with the white. Coarsely chop the onions.
</P>
<P>
   3. Wash the basil leaves.
</P>
<P>
   4. Place the corn, green onions, basil and kefir in blender and
process until it is quite smooth.
</P>
<P>
   5. Chill, overnight if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Serve decorated with basil leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: About 2 1/2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING LIST
</P>
<P>
   2 large ears corn
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch green onions
</P>
<P>
   Bunch basil (1/4 cup plus garnish)
</P>
<P>
   Container plain low-fat kefir or low-fat buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION INFORMATION PER SERVING: 241 calories, 2.4 grams total
fat, 1.4 grams saturated fat, 8.6 milligrams cholesterol, 269
milligrams sodium, 47.4 grams carbohydrate, 4.6 grams fiber, 13.6
grams protein.
</P>
<P>
   CHILLED TOMATO BASIL SOUP
</P>
<P>
   6 ripe medium tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Bunch basil to yield 1/4-cup tightly packed leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 cup low-fat buttermilk or low-fat plain kefir
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Basil leaves for garnish
</P>
<P>
   1. Wash tomatoes, trim and coarsely chop.
</P>
<P>
   2. Wash and remove basil leaves from stems; coarsely chop
garlic.
</P>
<P>
   3. Place tomatoes, 1/4-cup basil leaves, garlic and buttermilk
in blender. (You may have to do it in batches) and puree until
smooth. Season with pepper and chill several hours or overnight.
</P>
<P>
   4. To serve, stir in olive oil. Garnish with basil leaves and
serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: About 3 cups.
</P>
<P>
   YOUR PANTRY
</P>
<P>
   Garlic
</P>
<P>
   Whole black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING LIST
</P>
<P>
   6 ripe medium tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Bunch basil (1/4 cup plus garnish)
</P>
<P>
   Container low-fat buttermilk or low-fat plain kefir
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION INFORMATION PER SERVING: 109 calories, 4.5 grams total
fat, 1 gram saturated fat, 2.9 milligrams cholesterol, 106.4
milligrams sodium, 14.9 grams carbohydrate, 2.7 grams fiber, 4.8
grams protein.
</P>
<P>
   CHILLED CORN AND PEPPER SOUP
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces whole or 5 ounces chopped, ready-cut onion (1 1/3 cups)
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces whole red pepper or 7 ounces chopped ready-cut pepper
(1 1/2 cups)
</P>
<P>
   4 cups corn kernels (4 large ears corn)
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2 cups no-salt-added chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   Few shakes salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Sprigs of cilantro for garnish
</P>
<P>
   1. Chop whole onion. Heat pan large enough to hold all the
ingredients until it is hot. Reduce heat to medium high and add
oil. Stir in onion and saute until it begins to soften and color.
</P>
<P>
   2. Mince garlic; wash, trim, seed and coarsely chop pepper.
</P>
<P>
   3. Add garlic and saute for 30 seconds. Add peppers and saute
until peppers begin to soften, about 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   4. Add the stock and simmer until vegetables have softened,
about 3 more minutes. Add the corn and cook 2 or 3 minutes. Puree
in blender and season with salt and pepper. Chill, overnight if
desired.
</P>
<P>
   5. Wash and dry cilantro and use to garnish soup.
</P>
<P>
   6. Yield: About 4 1/2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   YOUR PANTRY
</P>
<P>
   Onion
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Garlic
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Whole black pepper
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING LIST
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces whole red pepper or 7 ounces chopped ready-cut
</P>
<P>
   4 large ears corn
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2 cup no-salt-added chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   Sprigs of cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION INFORMATION PER SERVING: 210 calories, 4.4 grams total
fat, 0.3 grams saturated fat, 6.1 milligrams cholesterol, 120
milligrams sodium, 39.8 grams carbohydrate, 5.6 grams fiber, 9.1
grams protein.
</P>
