<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BRADLEY MEETS, VOWS TO CAMPAIGN FOR GORE
 &HT;    Duplication alert: Moving in the (w) Washington and (p)
Political categories
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREEN BAY, Wis. _ After staying silent for months, former
basketball great Bill Bradley became a cheerleader for Vice
President Al Gore Thursday as the former rivals for the Democratic
presidential nomination united here in a two-on-one break against
Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   With a noticeably tanned Bradley at his side, Gore reacted to
news accounts of a potential budget shortfall in Texas with the
suggestion that federal tax cuts proposed by Bush could undermine
the national economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now Governor Bush wants to do for America what he's done for
Texas: go to Washington and spend our surplus and then more for
budget-busting tax cuts _ and then hope that somehow it will all
add up,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was responding to statements this week by Texas Lt. Gov.
Rick Perry that higher-than-expected costs in existing programs
would eat into the state's surplus. The rising costs mean the state
will be able to carry over just $540 million into the next budget _
less than 10 percent of what it rolled over from the 1998-99
budget. Critics immediately began pointing fingers at Bush, blaming
the $1.7 billion in tax cuts the governor helped push through the
Legislature last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign reacted with the release of a statement from
Rob Junell, the Democratic chairman of the Texas House
Appropriations Committee, calling Gore's attack ``shameful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is dead wrong to claim there is a budget shortfall in
Texas,'' Junell said. ``The current $1 billion surplus in the state
treasury easily meets these routine and unforeseen expenditures.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley ended a five-month absence from the presidential
campaign with a formal endorsement of Gore that was less than
glowing but included a vow to work this fall for the election of a
Democratic president and a Democratic majority in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, the only Democrat to challenge Gore for the party's
nomination this year, largely ignored his political differences
with the vice president in their first joint appearance since a
March 1 debate in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democratic Party is a place of many different voices, but
we all share the same values,'' Bradley declared to a sun-drenched
crowd of nearly 1,000 supporters at a waterside amusement park.
``It's why we're Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said Gore would do more to tackle child poverty, racial
discord, inequalities in health care, education and employment, and
``a political process dangerously awash in money.'' Compared to
Bush, ``it's not even close,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, after accepting an NBA-style high-five handshake from his
vanquished foe, praised the former New York Knicks star and
basketball Hall of Famer for bringing ``high purpose and high
ideals'' to their often bitter contest.
</P>
<P>
   With the 6-foot 5-inch Bradley sitting on a stool beside him,
Gore repeatedly quoted from speeches Bradley made in their campaign
against each other as he vowed to make Bradley's causes his own in
his challenge of Bush this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently in an effort to make public amends for some of his
bare-knuckled assaults on Bradley during the primaries, Gore
emphasized that Bradley ``is a good Democrat who speaks and stands
for the principles we all believe in.''
</P>
<P>
   During the primaries, Gore had suggested that Bradley quit the
Senate in 1996 rather than ``stay and fight'' the new Newt
Gingrich-led Republican congressional majority with President
Clinton and himself.
</P>
<P>
   Before the mid-day reunion of the two Democratic rivals, the
Republican National Committee (RNC) distributed 17 pages of quotes
of Bradley criticizing Gore during the Democratic presidential
primaries.
</P>
<P>
   They included a remark Bradley made to Gore during a debate in
New Hampshire after weeks of not responded to what he considered
misrepresentations of his health care proposals: ``Why should we
believe that you will tell the truth as president, if you don't
tell the truth as a candidate?''
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen hecklers made the same point during Gore's remarks
Thursday. Holding up a photograph of Gore at the Buddhist temple
that is at the center of a controversy over the Clinton-Gore
fundraising in 1996, the hecklers chanted: ``Liar, liar, liar.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Thursday's event helped heal a rift in the Democratic
Party, it was far from clear what effect Bradley's endorsement
would have on the Gore campaign since Bradley did not carry a
single state in the Democratic primaries this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Eric Hauser, the chief spokesman for the Bradley campaign,
offered one explanation: Bradley, like Sen. John McCain in the
Republican primary, attracted new and independent voters to the
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they are going to be valuable in this election,'' Hauser
added.
</P>
<P>
   ---STORY COULD TRIM HERE---
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has won 300 delegates to the Democratic National
Convention, which will be held in Los Angeles next month. But he
has yet to release those delegates to vote for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bradley met privately for about 40 minutes before
taking the stage at Bay Beach Park. They have spoken only twice by
telephone since Bradley suspended his campaign in March, according
to Gore campaign officials.
</P>
<P>
   The park was one of the sites Franklin D. Roosevelt visited in
1934 to promote his ``New Deal'' economic program.
</P>
<P>
   The Roosevelt connection provided Gore the opportunity to
compare his economic priorities to Bush's. And the Green Bay
setting allowed both Gore and Bradley to quote the legendary Green
Bay Packer football coach, Vince Lombardi.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said his economic priorities are ``the same priorities that
brought us today's prosperity: balance the budget, pay down our
debt and invest in the best enterprise of all _ the American people
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Bush's top economic priority is tax cuts, adding, ``The
last thing this country needs is an era of Bush economics that
brings us back to deficits, high interest rates, high unemployment,
recession and the bad times of the 1980s.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, noting his presence in Green Bay, said, ``What Vince
Lombardi said is true. `Winning is a team sport!' Our party is
strongest when we're unified, when we speak with one voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he was reminded of other words from Lombardi: ``People
who work together win.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he endorsed Gore, on Thursday, Bradley reflected a
lingering disappointment over his loss to the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 15 months I ran for President of the United States,'' he
said. ``I'm honored and grateful to those people across America who
supported me. I had a remarkable experience. Though someone once
told me, when one uses the term `experience' in this context,
`experience' is what you get when you don't get what you really
wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   After the appearance in Green Bay, the two men went their
separate ways _ Gore to a town hall meeting with undecided voters
in Saginaw, Mich., Bradley to an undisclosed location where he is
writing a book, which is set to be published this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's email address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: http://www.AlGore2000.com/
</P>
<P>
   endit
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
