<SLUG> BC-GORE-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LONE STAR GROUP ACCUSES GORE OF TRASHING TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PEGGY FIKAC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texans unhappy about their state being the
target of political broadsides by the Gore presidential campaign
have formed an organization to counter the attacks on health care,
education and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   The Proud of Texas Committee described itself in a letter to
Vice President Al Gore as a group of independents and Democrats who
plan to speak out when incorrect or misleading information about
the Lone Star state.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic presidential hopeful, has
criticized Texas' record under Republican Gov. George W. Bush's
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``The members of the Proud of Texas Committee are disturbed by
the extent to which the Gore campaign appears to be willing to
distort the facts about our state in order to discredit Governor
Bush,'' says the letter signed by Texas Monthly publisher Michael
R. Levy and other members of the group, including some Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Doug Hattaway said the campaign is not casting
aspersions on Texas but ``pointing out the facts about Bush's
record in the state.''
</P>
<P>
   The Proud of Texas Committee disputed criticism that it said
Gore has directed at Texas education, health care and criminal
justice, using other sources to defend the state's record in those
areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call these inaccuracies to your attention not as your
rivals, but as concerned citizens who demand truth in
campaigning,'' the letter says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps you have written off our state electorally, but don't
treat us like second-rate citizens,'' it states. ``There are 20
million people in Texas who also are Americans and who take great
pride in our state.''
</P>
<P>
   Others whose signatures appear on the letter are State Board of
Education member Will Davis, an Austin lawyer who was chairman of
the state Democratic Party in the 1960s; Mark Stiles, a businessman
and former Democratic lawmaker from Beaumont; Dr. David Smith,
president of the Texas Tech University Health Science Center and
former state health commissioner; and Dan Pearson, former executive
director of the Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The group also sent a letter to Bush informing him of the
formation of the committee. The groups leaders said they intend to
disband the committee after the November election. Both letters
said the group does not give or take orders from any campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one's trying to insult Texas, but point out the reality of
Bush's record as compared to the rhetoric that comes out of the
campaign,'' Hattaway said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, ``The fact is under Bush, Texas has become
one of the most polluted states in the country. That's not an
aspersion on the people of Texas. It's a blight on Bush's record.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign has defended the governor's record on the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   In answering criticism by Gore on the campaign trail, the Bush
campaign has been known to cite statistics about the United States
under the current administration's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Gore was reported as saying that under Bush,
Texas has become first in the nation for the number of people
without health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer told the Associated Press that
since Gore was elected, there are millions more Americans without
health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, of the Proud of Texas Committee, said the concern is over
facts that ``sometimes get bent or broken in reporting on a state
as large and varied as Texas. We want to keep the information that
is disseminated about our state honest from now until the end of
the campaign.''
</P>
</TEXT>
