<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAME-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NAME OF THE WORLD': CIRCLES AND RECTANGLES OF GRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
 
 By RICHARD EDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are a yellowed globe and an antique telescope in the
living room of Ted MacKey, the chairman of the music department at
a Midwestern college. They are elements of a mellow scholarly decor
in which the guests sip hot buttered rum by a blazing log fire. It
is Currier &AMP; Ives does academe, or, as Michael, an adjunct
professor and the shattered narrator, remarks in ``The Name of the
World,'' ``a very expensive gift shop.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a fine, acid phrase. The decor comes in more suggestively
in Michael's comment about some of his older colleagues regularly
dusting off ``the lectures they'd been dragging out ... since the
days when Ted MacKey's big beige globe had known what it was
talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   In Denis Johnson's fiction, the world no longer knows what it is
talking about, and its denizens' heads are filled with babble. It
and they are fragmented, though the fragmentation varies from book
to book. It is an outright post-apocalyptic vision in
``Fiskadoro,'' his finest work. Fragmentation is intricate social
and personal disarray in the charming if doleful picaresque of
``Resuscitation of a Hanged Man,'' underrated when it appeared.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Angels'' and ``Jesus' Son,'' it is young Americans drugging
and drifting; in the much weaker ``Stars at Noon,'' young
drugs-and-drifts meet a chilling, CIA-backed repression in Central
America. In ``Already Dead,'' declaredly gothic, the writing itself
is fragmented, as if the writer had been abducted and blown up,
with shards of character, vision, pith and coherence drifting down
together.
</P>
<P>
   The novella-length ``Name of the World'' is also shards, though
better ones, and for a while they hold a promise of reassembling,
until the author relinquishes them in a swirl of visionary cloud.
The writing gives way to poetic curdle.
</P>
<P>
   The fragmenting event is specific, and mournfully promising: two
deaths. Michael, a onetime high school teacher who became the aide
to a senator from his state, had spent a dozen years as a
Washington insider. (This occupies a page or two; it is a bit of
glib telescoping, like affixing a mask stamped ``King,'' but it is
nothing compared to the arbitrary sped-up dizziness at the end.)
Michael loses his wife and daughter in a car crash for which he
blames himself. He loses himself, as well; his protracted mourning
and disorientation play out in the refuge his connections obtain
for him: a temporary, year-by-year contract to conduct a vague
seminar in history. It is, he admits, a vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson creates a few sharp academic scenes. At a dinner party,
a visiting novelist puts down a brash young instructor who
complains that his characters are ``morally uninstructive.'' The
sardonically (perhaps self-mockingly) deconstructive retort: ``Do
you really hope to get your moral lessons from people who don't
exist?''
</P>
<P>
   In another scene, Michael attends a faculty party, only to learn
it is to bid him farewell. As someone who hates confrontation, his
department head had neglected to tell him his contract would not be
renewed. Michael recalls confrontation-happy Washington. A campaign
manager calls in an aide. ``Do you want to know how a loser
stinks?'' she asks. ``Put your nose in your armpit. Then empty your
desk.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Johnson scants external circumstances in
favor of internal states of spirit. Incidents and characters get a
dab of treatment, sometimes quite promising, and are relinquished.
The narration is a series of chronological twitches, as if trying
to shake itself off. In ``Resuscitation of a Hanged Man,'' Lenny,
the protagonist, was vividly present, even as the world revolved
cloudily in eccentric orbit around him. Here Michael is sucked into
the orbit; we see him only erratically.
</P>
<P>
   What we do see, though, and it is the strongest part of the
book, is his grief. Johnson renders it with two images. One is the
round campus pond, frozen in winter, where skaters circle
endlessly. Watching them, Michael's obsessive circling of his own
tragedy plays out.
</P>
<P>
   The image is replaced by a stronger one. He sees a drawing by an
amateur painter: a series of concentric rectangles. The innermost
is imperfect, the second imperfectly reproduces the imperfection,
the third magnifies the mistakes of the first two and so on, until
the outer figure is a grotesque distortion of the original.
</P>
<P>
   It is a metaphor, beautifully conceived, for the falsity of
excessively protracted mourning. The beginning of Michael's
deliverance comes in a phrase: he is ``less the man who'd lost his
family, and more just somebody who didn't happen to have one.''
</P>
<P>
   The deliverance buries the book. Deliverance starts with an art
student who calls herself Flower. Michael sees her in a performance
piece, shaving her pudendum. He meets her when she is serving at a
cocktail party, and she recognizes him. He sees her winning a
striptease contest in a bar. It is not the nudity, mainly, that
arouses him, nor is the arousing mainly physical. Johnson conveys
the witchery of sexual attraction and transforms it into the
life-restoring inklings of love.
</P>
<P>
   So far so good. But then Flower performs a bewildering series of
transformations. Michael meets her at a Mennonite-style church
service, goes to the deserted schoolhouse where she lives, is led
through various rituals that seem to summon up the ghost of his
dead daughter. He begins to make love to her, then breaks off,
flees and never sees her again. It is all arbitrary and gestural, a
necromancy that is incantation and very little magic.
</P>
<P>
   Michael goes to Alaska, to Greece (a couple of paragraphs for
each), becomes a free-lance journalist, covers the Persian Gulf
War. The writing gets wilder and emptier:
</P>
<P>
   ``I remain a student of history, more of one than ever, now that
our century has torn its way out of its chrysalis and become too
beautiful to be examined, too alive to be debated and exploited by
played-out intellectuals. The important thing is no longer to
predict in what way its grand convulsions might next shake us. Now
the important thing is to ride it into the sky.'' Sky-riding is
announced, but ``The Name of the World'' fails to provide a
serviceable horse of any kind, let alone winged.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE NAME OF THE WORLD'
</P>
<P>
   By Denis Johnson
</P>
<P>
   129 pages. HarperCollins. $22.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 1702EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
