<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1221 &Cx1f; tad-z
b e BC-X-MEN-REVIEW0714-COX     07-13 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-X-MEN-REVIEW0714-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Xceeding xpectations
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Holy blockbuster! Hollywood finally got one
right. With the faltering ``Batman ``and ``Superman `` franchises
grounded, at least temporarily, Marvel's top-selling ``X-Men'' saga
is the comics world's only hope for big-screen salvation.
</P>
<P>
   Launched in 1963, the Stan Lee-created comic-book series centers
around a team of mutant superheroes. The ``X-Men'' universe has
since expanded to include more than 200 characters and as many as
15 related monthly comics titles.
</P>
<P>
   Given the series' complex story lines and its legion of fans _
as well as the number of disappointing comic-book movies in recent
years _ Bryan Singer's $75 million adaptation, ``X-Men,'' is the
year's most anxiously watched and eagerly awaited film.
</P>
<P>
   The heroic achievement is one of the best comics-based movies
ever.
</P>
<P>
   Singer's faithful production is a beautifully rendered, credible
fantasy that features sympathetic characters in a compelling story
with sharp social and political themes.
</P>
<P>
   The film emphasizes character relationships over action, yet
Singer's intense set pieces capture superhero battles the way
they're depicted on comics pages _ with costumed bodies hurling
through the air, leaving a wake of havoc and destruction _ as
opposed to the hard-to-follow fast cutting of Joel Schumacher's
``Batman'' sequels.
</P>
<P>
   ``X-Men `` will please most ardent fans and entertain casual
viewers. One need not be familiar with the comic books to follow
the film's allegorical story or to relate to its characters, who
have superhuman powers but suffer from mortal flaws.
</P>
<P>
   A dark, gripping prologue set in a Nazi concentration camp
grounds the story in reality. A subsequent sequence, set in the
near future and involving McCarthy-like congressional hearings on
the ``mutant phenomenon,'' establishes a dramatic parallel between
mutant persecution and the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Mutants are the next step in human evolution, possessing
extraordinary powers that manifest themselves at puberty.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Charles Xavier (Patrick Stewart) is a wheelchair-bound
telepath who operates a school for ``gifted'' children, where he
teaches young mutants to control and direct their powers for the
greater good of humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Xavier is mentor to the X-Men _ Cyclops (James Marsden), whose
eyes release an energy beam; Jean Grey (Famke Janssen), who
possesses both telekinetic and telepathic abilities; and Storm
(Halle Berry), who can manipulate all forms of weather.
</P>
<P>
   Professor X's former friend and colleague, Eric Lehnsherr (Ian
McKellen), is the world's most powerful mutant. Known as Magneto,
he can harness the Earth's magnetic forces.
</P>
<P>
   Magneto believes a war is brewing between mutants and the humans
who fear and despise them. Leading the evil Brotherhood of Mutants
_ who include the vicious Sabretooth (Tyler Mane), shape-shifting
Mystique (Rebecca Romijn-Stamos) and lethal-tongued Toad (Ray Park)
_ Magneto plans to be on the winning side of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   With these two opposing forces locked in physical and
philosophical battle, the deft screenplay by David Hayter focuses
on two solitary mutants who reluctantly team with Xavier: Wolverine
(Hugh Jackman), a fierce fighting machine with retractable metal
claws; and Rogue (Oscar winner Anna Paquin), an alienated teen who
can absorb the powers of anyone she touches, with potentially fatal
results.
</P>
<P>
   Singer (''The Usual Suspects'') is adept at handling multiple
characters and simultaneous action, which suits the story's human
and superhuman elements.
</P>
<P>
   The elaborate effects sequences are terrific, as are the
performances.
</P>
<P>
   Australian stage actor Jackman delivers a charismatic turn as
the belligerent but soft-hearted Wolverine. Royal Shakespeare
Company veterans Stewart and McKellen are well-matched as cerebral
foes who share mutual admiration as well as animosity.
</P>
<P>
   Far from invincible heroes, the X-Men grapple with pain, anguish
and self-doubt. Amusingly, they get on one another's nerves. The
film turns on a conventional plot device and drags in spots, but it
succeeds at humanizing the cartoon figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``X-Men'''s cast has signed to do two sequels. As Wolverine
would say, bring 'em on.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
