<HEADER>
A1224 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      07-13 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE KEHR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   REVOLUTIONARY PRODUCTION
</P>
<P>
   In St.-Ouen, a nondescript industrial suburb on the northern
edge of Paris, Eric Rohmer is recreating the French Revolution
inside a converted warehouse. His new film, ``The Lady and the
Duke,'' promises to be the most expansive reconstruction of the era
ever undertaken, a significant change of pace for a filmmaker
famous for intimate romantic, philosophical dramas like ``Claire's
Knee'' and ``An Autumn Tale.''
</P>
<P>
   But this set, too, is surprisingly intimate. On a recent day,
Rohmer was restaging a triumphant march down a Parisian boulevard,
a process that involved no more than nine or 10 people: Rohmer (now
a spindly 80), his cinematographer, Diane Baratier (who, in her
30s, looks as if she could be a Rohmer heroine herself), a couple
of electricians and half a dozen extras.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Rohmer is shooting ``The Lady and the Duke'' on
digital video and using the new medium's resources electronically
to create a Paris that hasn't existed in 200 years.
</P>
<P>
   There are two cameras on the set, one pointing toward a
3-by-4-foot painting, based on a period engraving, of the wide
boulevard, and another aimed at a wooden window frame placed
against a bright green backdrop. Rohmer instructs an extra on how
to lean out and wave while Baratier lines up the image so that it
matches a window on the painted street. By repeating this
meticulous process several dozen times, Rohmer will be able to fill
his 18th-century street with a crowd composed of distinct
individuals, laid in one by one.
</P>
<P>
   In Hollywood, this shot would involve dozens of technicians and
weeks of meticulous post-production. But the less affluent French
cinema is used to a hands-on, do-it-yourself technique that finds
even a figure as august as Rohmer pitching in with the detail work.
Francoise Echegarray, who is producing ``The Lady and the Duke''
for Pathe Images, the specialized division of the French studio
Pathe, suggests that the detail work may be what fascinated Rohmer
in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is obsessed by architecture,'' she said, ``the architecture
of the street as well as the architecture of a film.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie's $6 million budget is high by French standards but
extremely low by American. It is based on the memoirs of Grace
Elliot, a British aristocrat who during the revolution became the
mistress of the Duke of Orleans, the king's brother. The lady will
be played by the English newcomer Lucy Russell, the duke by the
French character actor Jean-Claude Dreyfus.
</P>
<P>
   Rohmer approaches his job with quiet concentration. He makes it
a rule to decline interviews during production, and a hushed
atmosphere prevails on his set, with none of the usual chatter
among crew members and cast. It feels less like a sound stage than
a laboratory where researchers silently go about their work. For
all of the torrents of conversation that have passed before
Rohmer's camera, very little is to be heard behind it.
</P>
<P>
   BROTHER ACT
</P>
<P>
   The Weitz brothers _ Paul, 34, and Chris, 30 _ share an
impressive resume: They wrote the 1998 computer-animated film
``Antz'' and then directed last summer's hit comedy ``American
Pie.'' They wrote the script for ``The Klumps,'' Eddie Murphy's
sequel to ``The Nutty Professor,'' and they've just completed
filming of their own second feature, ``Down to Earth,'' a remake of
``Here Comes Jordan'' (No. 2, after Warren Beatty's ``Heaven Can
Wait'') that stars Chris Rock and is set for release this fall.
</P>
<P>
   And in the middle of all that they found the time to star in
``Chuck and Buck,'' an independent feature that was a hit at the
Sundance Film Festival and opens in New York Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Weitz plays Chuck, a Los Angeles music producer who finds
himself being stalked by Buck (Mike White, who also wrote the
script), a childhood friend who has preserved an adolescent crush
on him. Buck, rejected, writes a play based on his unrequited
passion, and hires Sam (Paul Weitz), an unemployed actor who looks
strangely like Chuck, to play him onstage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't do this normally,'' Chris said over lunch at a
restaurant in New York City. He has known the director, Miguel
Arteta, since they were film students together at Wesleyan
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day Miguel left a message on my machine asking if I'd act
for him,'' he said. ``I thought he was making a short, or messing
around with a new digital video camera. So I left him a message
saying, `OK, as a matter of fact you've spotted my hidden vanity.'
So then Paul came on board.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul continued: ``Yeah, first they had the idea of Chris, and
then they realized that this other character was supposed to look
like that character, and they thought of me to play a grotesque
version of Chris. Apart from its humor, the script was so bizarre
and essentially unappealing that it had trouble attracting
investors. The advantage of casting us was that you didn't have to
pay us.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Weitzes had never acted before, they did have the
genetic material. Their mother is Susan Kohner, whose performance
in Douglas Sirk's ``Imitation of Life'' (1959) earned her an Oscar
nomination. And their grandmother is Lupita Tovar, a Mexican
actress who went to Hollywood to star in Spanish-language versions
of early talkies, including ``Dracula.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time we certainly had no idea either that it was going
to get into Sundance or that anyone would see it, so it seemed like
doing something for the heck of it, just for a challenge,'' said
Chris.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of glowing reviews, the brothers have no further acting
plans. ``We're going to keep trying to make different kinds of
films, as opposed to staying in the `American Pie' niche and trying
to do that better and better,'' said Paul. ``That's what's going to
allow us not to be incredibly bored by being a team.''
</P>
<P>
   WINNING GAMBLE
</P>
<P>
   The indie hit of the summer is turning out to be the British
thriller ``Croupier,'' which opened on April 21 in New York and has
now spread to 117 theaters nationwide. ``It's an old-fashioned
word-of-mouth picture,'' said Eamonn Bowles, president of Shooting
Gallery Films, the company distributing ``Croupier'' in the United
States. ``It just keeps getting bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Made three years ago for Channel Four television in Britain by
the veteran director Mike Hodges (``Get Carter'') and given a very
brief theatrical run in London, the film was rescued from obscurity
by a sales agent, Mike Kaplan, who brought it to Bowles' attention.
In 13 weeks of release ``Croupier'' has taken in $2.1 million in
the United States, not a staggering figure by Hollywood standards
but enough to make it a smash in the independent world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gone up 20 percent a week,'' said Bowles. ``I've never
seen anything like it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
