<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1225 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-KADOSH14-COX     07-13 0400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-KADOSH14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A sleepy Orthodox Jewish soap opera
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When he wakes every morning, Meir (Yoram Hattab) begins a day of
prayer. One of his first is this one: ``Blessed is our eternal God,
who has not made me a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   He's a lucky man indeed in ``Kadosh,'' a study of the ways
religion can sometimes be crushingly sexist. As an almost
documentary look at Orthodox Jewish life, the movie can be
fascinating. After all, in this insular community, every facet of
life seems to come with a ritual attached. Even making a cup of tea
on the Sabbath day can provoke a long argument about the proper
brewing method. But as a drama, ``Kadosh'' is a very slow go.
</P>
<P>
   Director Amos Gitai penetrates Jerusalem's Orthodox quarter, Mea
Shearim, with a tale of two sisters, Rivka (Yael Abecassis) and the
younger Malka (Meital Barda). Rivka is married to Meir, the rabbi's
son, and now it's time for Malka to wed _ at least according to the
men of the community.
</P>
<P>
   She's in love with the singer Yaakov (Sami Hori), who
scandalized friends in yeshiva school when he voluntarily left to
join the Jewish Army. But the rabbi has arranged for Malka to marry
Yossef (Uri Ran Klausner), a devout man who motors through the
narrow streets in a speaker-mounted van, praising God to
passers-by.
</P>
<P>
   There's another conflict. After 10 years together, Rivka has
failed to bear a child. Because, in the words of one character, a
barren woman is no better than a dead woman, this is cause for more
than personal sorrow. It's enough to dissolve the marriage
contract, no matter how much Rivka and Meir love each other.
</P>
<P>
   The plot of ``Kadosh'' scans as soap opera. But the pace is
stubbornly slow. The script, by Eliette Abecassis, herself an
Orthodox Jew living in France, makes its point about women's
subordinate status in the culture. And it just keeps making the
same point. It doesn't help that Gitai often films his scenes in
long, unbroken takes and has encouraged his actors to bracket their
lines with long, mournful silences. They're like sleepwalkers, and
by the end of ``Kadosh,'' you might feel the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kadosh''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Yael Abecassis, Meital Barda and Yoram Hattab. Unry
writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
