r e BC-MOVIES-TIPS14-COX     07-13 0335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-TIPS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alternative picks to the most recent flicks
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``X-Men'' and its comic-book heroes aren't your bag? You'd
prefer not to face a Wolverine sporting Freddy Krueger claws? There
are good movies out there, just not always brand-spanking-new ones.
Here are a few recent worthy films you can see in new ways. See our
Weekend Movie Guide and showtimes listing for details.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Douse the drought: There's so much water in ``The Perfect
Storm'' that you can't come out and not feel wet. Appreciate the
near-perfect special effects. Every time lightning flashes, you get
a better peek at the immense ocean's rolling waves.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A midsummer night's dream: You've seen ``Hamlet'' a thousand
different ways _ but not like this. Modern New York is the setting,
and though the play has been cut, it remains compelling.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  It's a date: Take him to see ``Croupier,'' a mostly smart
gambling-and-intrigue movie where, for once, all the dough was
spent on the script instead of special effects. Or break down and
finally take her to see ``Erin Brockovich,'' the smartest move
Julia Roberts has made in years. Or make both of you happy and take
each other to ``High Fidelity,'' a movie that makes you love every
character, flaws and all.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  No, you can't see ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene'': Get those hot,
restless kids into a cool theater. The Oscar-winning animated Imax
film ``The Old Man and the Sea'' is a visual, painted wonder. For
the wee ones, there are also two instant classics: ``My Dog Skip''
and ``Chicken Run.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Force yourself to read: Subtitles aren't as bad as you think.
Let yourself go with the excellent ``The Color of Paradise,'' a
visually arresting Iranian film about a young blind boy.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The old standby: You remember ``Ben-Hur.'' It's now called
``Gladiator.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
