<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1229 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-ATLANTA-CHILDREN14     07-13 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ATLANTA-CHILDREN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Atlanta's Children' full of innuendo
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Purely as a piece of drama, ``Who Killed Atlanta's Children?''
is a typical cable TV movie with generic acting, lots of bluster,
the obli-gatory/gratuitous scene set in a strip club and an
overwrought sense of its place in the universe.
</P>
<P>
   But of course, ``Who Killed Atlanta's Children?'' cannot be just
another TV movie for Atlanta. It strongly suggests that white
supremacists were behind at least some of the 29 African-American
missing and murdered children and young adults in the case that
paralyzed this city in the early '80s.
</P>
<P>
   The Showtime movie never says this is absolutely so, just as it
never says that Wayne Williams, who was convicted of two of the
murders (and linked to 21 others, according to law enforcement
officials at the time), is innocent. (Williams is a very minor
character in the movie.)
</P>
<P>
   In truth, ``Atlanta's Children'' implies a lot and proves almost
nothing, other than how easy it is to still push people's hot
buttons almost 20 years after the fact. Oliver Stone knew this when
he made ``JFK,'' which shares some of this movie's approach to
cobbling together fact and conjecture.
</P>
<P>
   The movie takes place four years after Williams' conviction.
Spin magazine editor Ron Larson (Gregory Hines) and reporter Pat
Laughlin (James Belushi) come to town to investigate the murders.
Mothers of some of the victims believe (as some do to this day)
that Atlanta police, anxious to end the city's nightmare, pinned
everything on Williams whether he was guilty or not.
</P>
<P>
   Right away, we're in a strange game. Larson and Laughlin are
pseudonyms; their real names were Rudy Langlais and Robert Keating.
Langlais is executive producer of ``Atlanta's Children'' but
appears as a ``fictional'' character. Writer Charles Robert Carner
says he took liberties with the journalists' characters, hence the
name change.
</P>
<P>
   After a red herring that some of the victims were involved in
``a child sex-for-hire ring involving high city officials''
(there's never a single fact given to bolster such an outrageous
charge), the reportorial duo stumbles onto an investigation by the
Georgia Bureau of Investigation. A GBI informant (of questionable
credibility) had heard some rednecks talking about being involved
in the murders; the GBI investigated, but could never make a case.
</P>
<P>
   While it is true that the GBI investigated the informant's lead,
this idea becomes the movie's equivalent of the grassy knoll near
Dallas' Dealey Plaza, spawning fictitious scenes in which heavily
armed Klansmen roam the outskirts of metro Atlanta firing automatic
weapons. Also depicted are a GBI agent ``interrogating'' a Klansman
by schmoozing and laughing with him and another agent destroying
evidence by dumping it into a furnace.
</P>
<P>
   What's telling is that the movie repeatedly pulls back from
saying this is what actually happened. There is not a single scene
in which a white is shown harming a black. Hines and Belushi
vacillate in their conviction about white involvement and, although
Hines' character obviously believes there was something to it, one
of his last lines is, ``All we have are unanswered questions.''
</P>
<P>
   (``Unanswered Questions,'' was, in fact, the very apt working
title of the movie, which was shot entirely in Toronto.)
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of unanswered questions in the case of
Atlanta's missing and murdered children. The dead, and their
survivors, deserve answers. But they will not get them from
cut-and-paste collages of fact and fiction such as ``Who Killed
Atlanta's Children?'' any more than they got them from ``The
Atlanta Child Murders,'' the factually slippery 1985 CBS movie that
tried to establish Williams as an innocent victim of hysteria.
(That CBS movie generated enormous controversy; Showtime, available
in fewer than 20 percent of homes, may cause less.)
</P>
<P>
   This is a topic better left to serious, objective historians,
not makers of docudramas in which it's almost impossible to figure
out where the ``docu'' leaves off and the drama begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Killed Atlanta's Children?''
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Sunday
</P>
<P>
   on Showtime
</P>
<P>
   (614603).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
