<DOCNO> NYT20000713.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1230 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-NUREMBERG14-COX     07-13 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NUREMBERG14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-congressman Stephens recalls real Nuremberg role
 &HT;    By Rebecca McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Robert G. Stephens Jr. doesn't need to watch TNT's
``Nuremberg.'' He lived it in a way few others could.
</P>
<P>
   For four months in 1945, the Army major and University of
Georgia law school graduate worked in the documents division of the
trial staff, helping assemble the paper trail necessary to brand
both the Nazis' Schutzstaffel (SS) and the Sturmabteilung (SA)
criminal organizations. He was chosen because of his facility in
German and his legal training.
</P>
<P>
   By the time one of the most dynamic legal teams completed its
work, 12 Nazis would be sentenced to hang, three would spend their
remaining years in prison and four others would serve nearly 20
years each in confinement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it was a big responsibility,'' says Stephens, 86, an
Atlanta native who later served as Athens city attorney, a General
Assembly member and finally in Congress for 17 years. ``I felt
these people had caused the deaths of millions of people and should
be punished. They had killed six million Jews and they had caused
the deaths of thousands of British, French and American boys.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not depicted in the production but says he'll ``try to
watch it.''
</P>
<P>
   A droll man with a sudden smile, Stephens says he simply was one
of numerous attorneys and military officials assembling materials
for Supreme Court Justice Robert H. Jackson, the head of the U.S.
prosecution team (played by Alec Baldwin).
</P>
<P>
   As grueling as the trial was, Stephens also was moved by
conditions in postwar Nuremberg.
</P>
<P>
   He first saw the city from a train window in 1935 while touring
Europe as an exchange student. Nuremberg deserved its reputation as
one of the best-preserved medieval cities in Europe, a place
steeped in beauty and tradition, where families had been operating
businesses in the same buildings for five centuries, Stephens
recalls. It was a renowned toy center.
</P>
<P>
   He likewise remembers, with noting alarm, the country's military
build-up, the rise of Adolf Hitler and the growing force of the
ubiquitous Schutzstaffel, the black-uniformed elite corps of the
Nazi party.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1988 column for the Athens Observer, Stephens wrote of a
rally he witnessed, attended by 40,000. He wrote that he could
still feel ``the hot and cold waves of feeling passing over me,''
the hair rising on his neck at the sight of the storm troopers and
the sounds of their hobnailed boots and roaring motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
   Most vivid was his sense of ``impending, but inescapable,
disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nuremberg he returned to in August 1945 had been reduced to
rubble, which seemed somehow fitting to him because the city had
become the symbol of the Nazis. Hitler had built a huge stadium and
massive arena there for annual conventions of the National
Socialist Party and for military reviews.
</P>
<P>
   The badly damaged Grand Hotel was being repaired while
international visitors housed there prepared for the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most depressing place I've ever been,'' Stephens
says. ``The city had been utterly destroyed. The Nuremberg trial is
unique in many ways and probably is the only time the prosecutors
had to first build a courthouse before the trial could begin.''
</P>
<P>
   He received a letter of commendation and was discharged in March
1946. He returned to Athens to open his law practice and launch his
political career.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Stephens remains a committed history buff _ not
surprising, since his great-uncle was Alexander Stephens, vice
president of the Confederacy, and his grandfather was Clement
Evans, a Confederate officer who became a Methodist minister.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca McCarthy writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitutution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
