<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TV for the week
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Biography: John F. Kennedy Jr. _ Child of a Dream'' (8 p.m.
on A&AMP;E) and ``JFK Jr.'s Last Flight'' (10 p.m. on The Learning
Channel, 614646) _ Sunday marks one year since John F. Kennedy
Jr.'s small plane crashed into the Atlantic Ocean, killing him, his
wife and sister-in-law. Television couldn't possibly just let this
pass, so A&AMP;E reruns its JFK Jr. ``bio'' and TLC focuses on the
crash itself.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Kennedys: The Curse of Power'' (9 p.m. on The History
Channel) _ Also keyed more or less to the anniversary of JFK Jr.'s
death, this new two-hour documentary retraces the sad family story,
starting with Joe Jr.'s death in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Who Killed Atlanta's Children?'' (8 p.m. on Showtime) _ This
new cable movie never quite says categorically that Wayne Williams
was innocent and never really proves that white supremacists were
behind the murdered black youths in 1979 to 1981, but it strongly
implies both. And just for good measure, it knocks Atlanta around.
See review, page E1.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Sex and the City'' (9 p.m. on HBO) _ John Corbett, formerly
Chris the DJ on ``Northern Exposure'' (and last seen battling a
killer sinkhole in a TBS movie) is Carrie's (Sarah Jessica Parker)
latest partner on HBO's lubricious little comedy. He'll be around
for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Movies
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Cocktail'' (8 p.m. Friday on Cinemax) _ ``Coyote Ugly'' (the
feature film opens Aug. 4) but with guys as bartenders.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Sweet Smell of Success'' (5 p.m. Saturday on Turner Classic
Movies) _ Burt Lancaster plays a ruthless gossip columnist in what
many consider the best role of his career. The actress playing his
sister is Susan Harrison. Harrison later had a daughter, who grew
up to be (drumroll, please) ... Darva Conger, the
multimillionaire-marrying, Playboy-posing ex-nurse whose compulsive
ambivalence about exposure has made her perfect fodder for, among
others, gossip columnists. This is absolutely true. Must be some
Zen thing.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Grumpier Old Men'' (9 p.m. Saturday on NBC) _ Of all the
ways to remember the late, great Walter Matthau, this shouldn't be
one of them.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Blair Witch Project'' (10 p.m. Sunday on Showtime) _ The
most parodied movie of recent years makes its TV debut.
</P>
<P>
   Big Event
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Nuremberg'' (8 p.m. Sunday and Monday on TNT)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not meant to be an entertainment, it's meant to be a
trial!'' rages Alec Baldwin as Robert Jackson, the chief prosecutor
of Nazi war criminals at Nuremberg. He's right, of course, but
TNT's new docudrama, which has some stunning moments but is rather
ponderous overall, could use a little more entertainment value.
</P>
<P>
   In a four-hour movie based closely on the trial transcripts (as
opposed to the 1961 movie ``Judgment at Nuremberg,'' which was
heavily fiction), Baldwin projects intelligence, integrity and the
charisma of lumber. Maybe that's how Jackson, a Supreme Court
justice, was, but it's tough on a movie when the hero is frequently
the least interesting person on screen.
</P>
<P>
   For the historically impaired, Nuremberg was an international
tribunal in which the Allies (United States, Great Britain, France
and the Soviet Union) tried 21 Nazis after World War II. It was a
radical concept, given what the defendants had just done, to give
them counsel and rights instead of summarily executing them (as the
Soviets wanted).
</P>
<P>
   ``Nuremberg'' takes forever getting going, but soon delivers at
least some of the goods. Actual film footage of the liberated death
camps is played within the movie, as it was at the trial, and is
profoundly moving and disturbing. And British actor Brian Cox is
unforgettable as the highest ranking Nazi on trial, Reichsmarshal
Hermann Goering: fat, smug and evil, but with a dangerous, oily
charm. (Buffs know Cox originated the role of Hannibal Lecter in
the film ``Manhunter.'')
</P>
<P>
   You don't expect a movie called ``Nuremberg'' to be fun,
exactly, but it would have been a less numbing four hours if it had
struck some notes other than earnestness.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
