<SLUG> BC-CHURCH-EXTREMISTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGLE-ISSUE INTEREST GROUPS THREATEN CHURCHES' PLURALISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    In recent weeks, many denominations have held their summer
conventions, large national gatherings to discuss church issues and
set policies regarding theology and practice.
 &HT;    This year the hot-button issue is, as it has been for decades,
sex.
 &HT;    For Southern Baptists, issues of sex centered on whether women
could be ordained and serve as senior pastors in their churches.
The Southern Baptist Convention, having effectively silenced all
liberal voices in their decision-making body, voted overwhelmingly
to support an all-male pastorate.
 &HT;    Most American Protestants, however, approved women's ordination
half a century ago. Methodists, Presbyterians, Lutherans and
Episcopalians are struggling with the issues related to gay and
lesbian persons in their communions. Should homosexual persons be
(officially) ordained? Should their unions be blessed? The
Protestant jury is still out on these questions.
 &HT;    At this year's conventions, pro-homosexual rights advocates have
been arrested. And convention delegates have been forced to avoid
anti-gay rights protesters on their way into meetings. Some of
these activists _ whether liberal or conservative _ are members of
the church itself. But many more are not.
 &HT;    The denominational meetings have been targeted by two groups,
Soulforce (a pro-homosexual religious organization) and ``God Hates
Fags,'' to push the issue in churches to which they do not belong.
 &HT;    These groups follow a long tradition in American religious
history. Outside special interest groups have often pressured
centrist denominations on highly charged political issues. These
groups are not affiliated with a single church body and draw their
members from a variety of religious bodies.
 &HT;    From temperance and slavery to civil rights and abortion, such
single organizations have energized our society with passionate
commitment to the common good, justice, and human rights.
 &HT;    But for all they contribute, they also have a dangerous
downside. Unlike the single-issue vision of the special interest
groups, mainline churches are diverse institutions comprehending a
wide variety of persons and opinions.
 &HT;    Although not often depicted as such, religious congregations are
pluralistic, flexible and inclusive institutions. In order to
belong to a group, members must submit to baptism or confirmation,
circumcision or bar mitzvah, but beyond the basics congregants
display widely divergent opinions on biblical interpretation,
theology, politics and religious practice.
 &HT;    Priests, ministers and rabbis know this. It is part of what
makes their job so difficult. Getting a congregation to agree on
anything can be a monumental task. So, forget about homosexual
ordination _ how do you agree on a new organ?
 &HT;    Despite being notorious contrarians, church members possess a
skill lacking in civic debate: they know how to remain in community
while disagreeing with each other. They argue about organs
precisely because they know they can. Half the church wants a
traditional pipe organ; the other half, an electronic one. Five
years from now, they will have their new organs. Whoever lost the
argument will be lustily singing ``For All the Saints'' sitting
next to the winner. And neither will remember the conflict.
 &HT;    Ultimately, local congregations know how to argue. Sure, they
sometimes split. But they more often stay together. In the long
run, community is more important then personal opinion. They
practice a kind of relational pluralism in the pews.
 &HT;    Single-issue interest groups are dangerous because they drive a
wedge into pew pluralism. They set Jane against Mary in a
``gay/lesbian rights issue.'' In reality, Jane's son is gay. Yet
Mary, who always thought homosexuality a sin, supported and prayed
for her friend as Jane came to terms with her son's sexual
orientation. Much to her own surprise, Mary even attended a
celebration of his union with a life partner while still
maintaining her own questions about sexual morality.
 &HT;    No matter their politics, Jane and Mary are friends. They have
coffee and serve on the altar guild together. That will not make
the news, but it is the matrix of faith in which millions of
Americans live and worship.
 &HT;    In ``Center Aisle,'' a newsletter circulating at the Episcopal
convention, an editorial stated, ``The real threat to the Episcopal
Church comes from advocates bent on premature closure to a lasting
and complex issue.Extremes must be rejected.''
 &HT;    Yes, extremes should be rejected _ but not in favor of mushy
tolerance or continued injustice. They must be rejected in favor of
working together in community, listening to, caring for, and
respecting one another while seeking to do the right and the good
amid our differences.
 &HT;    The pluralism of the pews is an icon of the kind of society a
religiously diverse America needs to become.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.2000 Diana Butler Bass
