<HEADLINE>
STAINED GLASS, WITH SINNERS, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Mo., Mass., Austria, Germany, Switzerland)   By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you think you know what 15th-century German stained glass
looks like, you may be wrong. It's not what you see in the Chartres
Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us have never seen stained glass like the panels in the
J. Paul Getty Museum's exhibition ``Painting on Light: Drawings and
Stained Glass in the Age of Durer and Holbein,'' which opened on
Tuesday and runs through Sept. 24.
</P>
<P>
   The show is full of surprises. Along with the ravishing angels
and pious saints, there are soldiers in the midst of a massacre,
men and women playing roulette, Heracles slaying the Nemean lion
and nude women in a bathhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The show, organized by the Getty, in Los Angeles, and the St.
Louis Art Museum, where it opens on Nov. 4, has 80 preparatory
drawings that artists made for these commissions. They are shown
alongside 60 stained-glass panels that talented glass painters
translated into windows. They were ordered for guild headquarters,
town halls and private houses, as well as churches and monasteries.
</P>
<P>
   Stained glass is a collaborative art. Artists prepare the
drawings; then they or their assistants work out the designs in
proportion to the size of the glass panels. These second drawings
become the cartoons for the glaziers. (Cartone is an Italian word
meaning big paper.)
</P>
<P>
   The glazier blows the glass by hand in various colors. The glass
is then painted on both sides. The material is called stained glass
because the outer surface is painted with an enamel called silver
stain. When fired, the stain turns yellow. If the underlying glass
is blue, the stain turns it green. Details are drawn on the inner
surface of the glass with vitreous paint, which ranges in color
from gray-brown to black. Details can also be scratched into the
paint. The glass pieces are then joined together with lead strips
called cames. The process requires close collaboration, to say the
least.
</P>
<P>
   The Getty show is the result of an equally intense collaboration
that lasted 15 years. The story behind it is a bit like the
off-Broadway play ``A Coupla White Chicks Sitting Around Talking.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1985 two American art historians, both specialists in
Renaissance drawings, met in Vienna at a seminar on Durer, the
great German painter and engraver. Lee Hendrix, the drawings
curator at the Getty, was looking for art for her department.
``Begun in 1981, our drawings collection is young,'' she said.
``Our greatest strength in our German drawings is stained-glass
drawings from 1480 to 1530.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Butts had just completed her doctorate at Harvard and
was going to the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston as a drawings
curator. The two were young and shared a passion for German
Renaissance drawings. They became great friends.
</P>
<P>
   Butts confided that she hoped to organize a show on Durer,
comparing his preparatory drawings with the actual glass panels the
drawings inspired. Hendrix loved the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized the drawings had never been seen next to the glass
panels they were made for,'' she said. ``This material is so
overlooked.'' She said the last survey was a two-volume book,
published in German in 1913, on the King of Prussia's collection.
``That glass was stored in Berlin,'' she added, ``and 80 percent of
it was destroyed in World War II.''
</P>
<P>
   Butts said, ``We knew the drawings, but there was a lot of
confusion about what glass had survived and where it was.'' The two
curators spent the next 13 years matching the drawings to their
stained-glass counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   The art of drawing flourished in Germany and Switzerland from
the late 1400s to the 1600s. Artists like Durer (1471-1528) went to
Italy to study Renaissance painting and returned home with new
ideas. Drawing was no longer simply a process to record nature. It
developed into a true art.
</P>
<P>
   This art is the subject of a companion show of 16th- and
17th-century German and Swiss drawings the Getty has organized from
its own collection (through Aug. 20). It includes detailed figure
drawings, compositional studies, portraits and designs for
woodcuts, stained glass and decorative objects by Durer, Lucas
Cranach the Elder (1472-1553) and Hans Holbein the Younger
(1497-1543).
</P>
<P>
   ``Painting on Light'' explores technique and artistry, but it
also places stained glass in political and religious contexts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stained glass is an art form that vividly reflects its time,''
Hendrix said. ``By the Reformation, the commissioning of monumental
stained-glass church windows was dying out in Germany. Secular
glass came in.'' Soon stained glass became ubiquitous in Southern
Germany and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   From 1400 to 1550 it was used to decorate town halls, private
houses, inns, universities, even hospitals. Themes included the Old
and New Testaments, classical mythology, heraldry, planetary
movements and chivalry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reflects things people liked to do at that time:
card-playing, wrestling, wine-drinking, fishing and swimming, even
cooking,'' Hendrix said. ``History is also profoundly reflected in
the glass.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hapsburg emperor Maximilian I, called ``the last knight''
because he was constantly at war, and his courtiers became great
patrons of stained glass. They commissioned panels glorifying
knighthood, with scenes of jousting and courtly love.
</P>
<P>
   In Switzerland, by contrast, stained glass was more political,
promoting the drive for independence. In 1513, the Swiss Federation
began an anti-Hapsburg uprising in the Alps that lasted more than a
century. The Swiss cantons eventually won; the secession of the
Swiss Confederation was legalized with the Treaty of Westphalia in
1648.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss ordered stained glass that glorified their legendary
image, the Wild Man of the Alps, the freedom fighter whose body is
covered with hair and who carries a tree trunk as his weapon. He is
``a mythical figure from the medieval imagination, depicted in art
and literature far into the 16th century,'' Barbara Giesicke and
Mylene Ruoss write in a catalog essay: ``The Wild Man's popularity
as shield-bearer was essentially based on the symbolism of his
strength and drive for freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   One Holbein drawing shows the Wild Man leaping through a
classical portal from the Alps right into the viewer's space. ``He
is as tall as a tree, a symbol of strength, virility and invincible
power,'' Hendrix said. ``Behind him are Alps.''
</P>
<P>
   In organizing the show, she and Butts went to Europe several
times. ``We got Eurorail passes,'' Butts recalled. ``We crossed and
recrossed Germany and Switzerland.''
</P>
<P>
   Hendrix added: ``In 1998, we did 14 cities in 28 days. It was a
journey of discovery.''
</P>
<P>
   They sought out a thermal bath in a spa in Switzerland. The
doctors and nurses did not recall a stained-glass window there. The
curators obtained a key to search the chapel but couldn't find the
panel. ``On the way out, we noticed that a curtain had been pulled
back by the front door,'' Hendrix said. ``There was our panel.''
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing the glass for the show was the next nightmare. ``We
visited nearly all the lenders because we had to explain why we
needed their stained-glass pieces,'' Hendrix said. ``This show
could never happen again because it took four years just to
negotiate the loans.''
</P>
<P>
   Would they try to do it again? ``It was the collaboration of a
lifetime,'' Butts said.
</P>
</TEXT>
