u w BC-IDENTITY-THEFT14-COX     07-13 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IDENTITY-THEFT14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BILL WOULD TIGHTEN ACCESS TO SOCIAL SECURITY NUMBERS
 &HT;    By ROB O'DELL
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The dramatic increase in cases of identity theft in
the United States prompted legislation in the House on Thursday to
restrict the use of Social Security numbers in both the public and
private sectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Social Security numbers have become the gateway for crooked
con artists to raid your bank accounts, max out your credit cards,
and literally steal your own identity,'' said co-author of the
bill, Rep. E. Clay Shaw, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``Social Security was created to help Americans enjoy their
golden years, not spend their days trying to restore their good
name,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would prohibit all sales of Social Security numbers by
governments, agencies, or private industries. It would also bar
third parties from offering services to obtain Social Security
numbers, such as advertising agencies who offer services to stores
in order to obtain the names and Social Security numbers of
prospective customers.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, Social Security numbers would be prohibited from
appearing on driver's licenses, motor vehicle registration cards,
or other identification-related records, Shaw said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Identity theft is the fastest-growing crime in the nation,
affecting 600,000 Americans nationally,'' Shaw said. ``Last year,
the number of reported misuses of Social Security numbers increased
233 percent, and we seldom think of that a number as unique as a
fingerprint is such a prime target for theft and abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Mark Foley, R-Fla., a supporter of the bill who was himself
a victim of identity theft, said he felt frustrated and violated
that someone could steal his private information and use it to
obtain merchandise at a department store.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised when I found out that I owed over $700 to
Target because someone had stolen my Social Security number and
obtained a credit card with it,'' Foley said. ``I received horrible
treatment from the credit agencies, and I felt violated that
someone could steal my personal information.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill would strengthen the government's power to investigate
fraud, and penalties for identity fraud would be increased.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation also makes denial of services to people who
refuse to provide their Social Security number a violation of the
unfair trade practices law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Social Security number was not invented as a means of
identification, and some of the services that require it are
outright ridiculous,'' Foley said. ``I have heard stories of Social
Security numbers being needed to buy Girl Scout cookies, purchase
videos, and even for funerals.''
</P>
<P>
   The new bill would not bar the use of Social Security numbers in
all situations, but would simply prohibit all sales of the numbers,
Shaw said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers would still be used in banking, by law
enforcement, and for special cases like tracking down deadbeat
dads,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   House of Representatives: www.house.gov
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
