<SLUG> BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIL' KIM: `THE NOTORIOUS K.I.M.' 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANN POWERS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIL' KIM: ``The Notorious K.I.M.'' (Queen Bee/Undeas/Atlantic
Records
</P>
<P>
   Lil' Kim, hip-hop's Queen Bee, returns after a long hiatus to
the same base she used to gain supremacy on ``Hardcore,'' her
hugely popular debut: the bedroom. Yes, this album is a declaration
of sexual prowess. But the themes Lil' Kim develops here have more
to do with machismo than with feminine wiles. Declaring herself
``the first female king,'' she explores the fallout from a woman's
decision to take a masculine stance and finds it perilous as well
as powerful.
</P>
<P>
   In fat, highly aggressive mixes that sample widely from the
women-in-pop palette (tracks interpolate work by Sade, Pat Benatar,
Suzanne Vega and Grace Jones), Lil' Kim relentlessly equates
eroticism with her urge to dominate and the male hostility it
causes. The album's many producers, including Puffy Combs and
Yellowman Winans, create action-movie soundtracks for Lil' Kim to
move through. She comes out with guns blazing under her belt: the
album's dominant metaphor is oral gratification as a power play.
It's a mixed-up, cynical vision of female empowerment, but Lil' Kim
clearly believes in it. As she declares in the album's final cut, a
vision of a female-run America, ``Inside we're all animal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 1719EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
