<HEADER>
A1250 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-IVOR-TOM-LEHRER-REVIS     07-13 1485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-TOM-LEHRER-REVISITED-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT OF THE PAST, SONGS THAT BITE: CATCHING UP WITH TOM LEHRER 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of
singer/songwriter Tom Lehrer. 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    To some of us who were in college in the early 1960s, Tom Lehrer
ranks in a pantheon somewhere below the Almighty and above the
Beatles.
 &HT;    The first time a Catholic friend played me Lehrer's ``The
Vatican Rag'' _ with those memorable lines, ``Ave Maria/Gee, it's
good to see ya!'' _ I was hooked. I needed more and still more of
this cynical rhymester whose humor was as subversive as a
flag-burning and twice as dangerous.
 &HT;    When he deserted the music scene for academia, he left an
enormous vacuum. Such pale imitators as Mark Russell and the
Capital Steps were small consolation for those who dreamed of what
Lehrer would have made of Richard Nixon, Ronald Reagan or Bill
Clinton.
 &HT;    The bad news is that no new Lehrer songs are forthcoming. The
good news is that Warner Archives/Rhino Records have collected the
entire Lehrer opus for a three-CD set, ``The Remains of Tom
Lehrer.''
 &HT;    To those unfortunates who have never savored Lehrer's acid takes
on everything from senatorial politics to nuclear war _ ``So long,
Mom,/I'm off to drop the bomb,/so don't wait up for me!'' _ allow
me to introduce you.
 &HT;    His father was a well-to-do tie manufacturer, his mother a
lifelong devotee of Gilbert &AMP; Sullivan. He entered Harvard at 15 as
a math major, won his undergraduate degree at 18 and, along the
way, penned a little ditty called ``Fight Fiercely, Harvard,'' a
college-football-song spoof _ ``Won't it be peachy if we win the
game? Oh, goody!''
 &HT;    As a graduate student in Cambridge, Mass., he became a fixture
at local nightspots and in 1953 self-produced an album, ``Songs by
Tom Lehrer.'' It became a cult hit, eventually selling 370,000
albums and counting.
 &HT;    In the conformist 1950s, of course, it was foreordained that
mainstream success would elude the author of, for example, ``The
Masochism Tango'':
 &HT;    ``Let our love be a flame, not an ember,
 &HT;    Say it's me that you want to dismember!''
 &HT;    Nor ``I Hold Your Hand in Mine,'' in which it is gradually
revealed that the hand in question is no longer attached to its
body, or ``The Old Dope Peddler,'' which celebrates a favorite
neighborhood fixture.
 &HT;    A second and third album, ``More of Tom Lehrer'' and ``An
Evening Wasted With Tom Lehrer,'' were followed in 1965 by ``That
Was the Year That Was,'' featuring political songs he'd written for
the satiric television program ``That Was the Week that Was.''
 &HT;    Who else would have spoofed that 20th-century man for all
ideologies, German rocket scientist Werner Von Braun, with a
sardonic:
 &HT;    ```Once the rockets go up
 &HT;    Who cares where they come down?
 &HT;    That's not my department,'
 &HT;    Says Werner Von Braun!''
 &HT;    And then, at the height of his success, Lehrer virtually
disappeared. He became a full-time teacher, teaching mathematics
first at Harvard and then at the University of California at Santa
Cruz, where he also offered a course on the American musical
theater. But he stopped writing songs, except for a couple of
specialty numbers for public television's ``The Electric Company,''
and rarely performed in public again.
 &HT;    Nonetheless, on the telephone from his summer home in Cambridge
the 72-year-old Lehrer sounds much as he did in his 30s. To hear
him tell it, the much-speculated-upon reason for his departure from
the public eye wasn't all that complicated.
 &HT;    ``I like to think it's maturity,'' he says, ``the liability that
I can see both sides. You can't write satire that says, `On the
other hand ... '''
 &HT;    This creeping recognition of life's shades of grey, he says, has
killed his desire to pillory.
 &HT;    ``For instance,'' he says, ``I'm for the legalization of drugs _
but you can't write a song about that, because I can see the other
side. I think in the old days my view of life was much simpler:
There were good guys and there were bad guys. Now I feel there are
bad guys and slightly better guys.''
 &HT;    Is he saying that you have to be young to be funny?
 &HT;    ``I think it helps,'' he admits.
 &HT;    Because Lehrer disappeared at the height of his fame, the
wildest rumors found their way to the surface: Lehrer was dead. He
had committed suicide. He'd had a nervous breakdown. He'd been sued
for everything he owned by Werner Von Braun, and had to pay him all
his future royalties.
 &HT;    ``There's an interesting story about that,'' Lehrer says with a
laugh. ``It turns out his daughter applied for admission to Bryn
Mawr, years after my song. And in the course of her interview, she
told the person interviewing her that her father, Werner, was not
just a narrow scientist. In fact, he was learning Chinese.''
 &HT;    The anecdote made its way quickly to Lehrer, whose infectious
ditty had included the following barb:
 &HT;    ```In German or English
 &HT;    I know how to count down,
 &HT;    Und I'm learning Chinese,'
 &HT;    Says Werner Von Braun.''
 &HT;    All those rumors were sparked simply by people's difficulty in
believing that a successful performer could simply have quit.
 &HT;    ``I didn't decide to become the J.D. Salinger of music,'' Lehrer
says, ``although I've always said Salinger and Deanna Durbin were
my role models. People assume, if you're a modest success and then
you stop, there must be a reason. It was simply that funny ideas
occurred to me at a gradually decreasing rate, so I just stopped
doing it.''
 &HT;    Long before he officially retired, however, Lehrer had struggled
with the drawbacks of live performance. A thoroughly private
person, he is generally camera-shy and cringes at the culture of
celebrity.
 &HT;    Not, he adds, that he ever had to face real fame, since his
material ensured that his would be a small, if passionate,
following.
 &HT;    ``I suspect most of the people who liked these things thought,
`Well, we get it, but of course the masses wouldn't,''' he says.
``So it wasn't like women throwing themselves in front of my
chariot. It was people who considered themselves educated and
superior.
 &HT;    ``They wouldn't descend to tearing my clothes off in public,''
he adds. ``They were like the people in New York who pretended not
to recognize Greta Garbo.''
 &HT;    As for today's political scene, he says that he's not sure his
approach would work now. His songs assumed a common philosophy
shared by most in his audience, a consensus which may have faded in
the intervening decades.
 &HT;    ``That's the whole thing,'' he explains, ``a certain literacy, a
certain education and a certain liberal consensus that there was at
that time. There was a general understanding in the '50s about
where we stood vis a vis Joe McCarthy and Adlai Stevenson.
 &HT;    ``Today that doesn't exist anymore,'' Lehrer says. ``The people
who would be my natural audience are split on any given issue _
affirmative action, Israel or whatever.''
 &HT;    Now in semi-retirement from academia, Lehrer says he has no
intention of returning to the music that made him famous. However,
he admits to a sneaking interest in the American musical _ not the
hyper-inflated megashows of today, but the witty, acerbic sort
created by Stephen Sondheim, with whom Lehrer went to summer camp
as a boy. He calls Sondheim ``the greatest lyricist the English
language ever produced.''
 &HT;    So he might yet write a small musical, he says, perhaps for
Off-Broadway _ where a 1980s revue, ``Tom Foolery,'' offered some
of his old songs in a theatrical context. But he'd be interested
only if he could find collaborators who shared his philosophy:
``Let's try it, and if it doesn't work at least we'll have had a
good time.''
 c.2000 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
