<HEADLINE>
PATRICK STEWART MASTERMINDS `X-MEN' 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Patrick
Stewart in a scene from ``X-Men.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Patrick Stewart was born to play Professor Charles Xavier.
 &HT;    Sure, Stewart does pretty well for himself playing ``Star
Trek's'' chrome-domed Captain Picard. Yes, his stage turns in ``The
Tempest,'' ``A Christmas Carol'' and ``The Ride Down Mt. Morgan''
have been impressive.
 &HT;    But it was his destiny to portray the wheelchair-bound leader of
the mutant superheroes in ``X-Men.'' Everyone on the planet knew
that ... everyone except Stewart.
 &HT;    ``The world kept that a secret from me,'' Stewart says during a
press conference at New York's Essex House. ``It was (producer)
Lauren Shuler Donner who first introduced me to that notion. So I
only lived with it for three or four years.''
 &HT;    Stewart's own family warned him that ``X-Men'' could be an even
bigger enterprise than ``Next Gen.'' And the actor himself harbored
serious concerns about portraying yet another iconic character who
might return again and again in sequels.
 &HT;    ``It felt, right at the beginning, like a lot of baggage,'' he
says. ``But the nature of the story and of this movie is that he's
a modern man in a modern context, in a 21st-century context.
 &HT;    ``Because I wasn't involved in a lot of the sequences that the
rest of the cast were, I didn't feel as though I was in a
comic-book movie,'' Stewart adds. ``I was in a real, modern movie
with serious themes, and `X-Men' is so different from the tone and
quality of `The Next Generation' that I no longer feel any kind of
conflict at all or any unease about this.
 &HT;    ``I'm just proud of the work.''
 &HT;    Much of ``X-Men'' explores the theme of outsiders struggling to
get by in the world. Stewart says it's a feeling that he could
identify with.
 &HT;    ``I grew up with what I experienced as the shame of poverty,''
the Brit says in his familiar booming voice. ``I left school when I
was 15, so my education was minimal. In my late teens, when I went
to acting school, I felt acutely that background.
 &HT;    ``Then I was also made aware of what Dr. Martin Luther King
described as the significant thing being the nature of your
character,'' he says. ``That helped me to change how I viewed
myself. And it's the nature of these characters that Xavier
emphasizes in this movie.''
 &HT;    Many moviegoers who've seen ``X-Men'' may be shocked that
Professor X spends a hefty chunk of the saga in a coma _ though
fans of the comic books will recall that the professor is usually
absent for long periods, for one reason or another. Others may
bemoan the lack of scenes between Stewart and Ian McKellen, who
plays Magneto, a former friend who is now Professor X's greatest
nemesis.
 &HT;    ``I don't think it's out of order to say that there were a lot
of discussions about whether there should have been more scenes,
about whether we should have met more often, about whether there
should have been more open conflict between us,'' Stewart says.
``Simply because I enjoyed Ian's company a lot, I would have liked
that.
 &HT;    ``I do think the two encounters, coming at the beginning and end
of the movie, are so strong and reverberate so well that, in fact,
there is no need for other encounters,'' he says. ``Actually, there
is a third encounter, isn't there? But it's a little odd, that
middle one.
 &HT;    ``And the film never allows you to forget the fundamental
philosophical differences the two men have,'' Stewart says, ``while
we're also sharing some points of view and a history, which is a
history of companionship and collaboration, in fact, until some
time when they parted ways.
 &HT;    ``I would hope,'' he adds, ``that, if there is a future for this
franchise, we might find more time for Magneto and Xavier to be
together.''
 &HT;    In closing the ``X'' file for now, there's one more
not-so-philosophical question for Stewart to consider: If Professor
X and Captain Picard duked it out, would the good professor kick
Picard's butt?
 &HT;    Stewart smiles.
 &HT;    ``No, but he certainly could kick s--t out of Captain Kirk,'' he
says. ``And you may quote me.'' 
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
