<SLUG> BC-EYE-SURGERY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ELDERLY MAN SEES `MIRACLE' IN VISION PROCEDURE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Jim Beebe loved to read, play poker and mow the
lawn until deteriorating eyesight prevented him from doing those
things.
</P>
<P>
   Now an experimental form of eye surgery has restored much of his
vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``My God, it's saved my life,'' said Beebe, 78, a former trader
at the Pacific Stock Exchange who underwent the surgery at the
University of California at Davis Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   The surgery involves replacing the eye's deteriorating cornea
with lab-grown cells from a donor, in this case, Beebe's sister,
Sally Kittredge of Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   An article on mostly positive results of similar surgery,
performed on six Taiwanese patients left blind or nearly blind by
damaged corneas, appears in the Thursday issue of the New England
Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, a report on mostly upbeat results of surgery on 15
patients at UC-Davis Medical Center in Sacramento is featured in
the July issue of the medical journal Cornea.
</P>
<P>
   The achievement is ``a unique and important step'' toward
producing off-the-shelf replacement tissue for damaged corneas,
Ivan Schwab, the ophthalmologic surgeon who operated on Beebe, said
in a statement released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors have been transplanting corneal cells from donor eyes
for years. But the new technique allows the donor to furnish a far
smaller percentage of corneal cells (about only 5 percent, compared
with about 50 percent in the past).
</P>
<P>
   Similar techniques might allow future doctors to grow tissue for
other parts of the body.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the future, we hope to translate this knowledge to the
lung, the gastrointestinal tract, the bladder and other epithelial
tissues throughout the body,'' said Schwab's colleague, Dr. R.
Rivkah Isseroff. Isseroff, a UC-Davis cell biologist and
dermatologist, grows the donated cells in tissue cultures for
several weeks before surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Before the surgery, Beebe said he was an omnivorous reader. He
and his wife, Jean, live in Brookings, Ore., near the California
border.
</P>
<P>
   But starting in the mid-1980s, Beebe's vision gradually was
spoiled by glaucoma, or damage to the optic nerve caused by high
pressure within the eyeball.
</P>
<P>
   To read, Beebe said, he had to use ``four-power glasses plus a
magnifying glass,'' and to hold his head no more than a foot from
the printed page. He found himself paying more and more visits to
the local library, where he checked out large-print books.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to quit driving,'' Beebe said. ``That was my decision,
not the state's.''
</P>
<P>
   During several years of frustration and ineffective treatments
with eye drops, he never lost hope of regaining effective vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``His eyes kept getting worse and worse,'' Jean Beebe said. ``I
thought it would take a miracle, and I didn't believe in miracles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem for me, was that last Christmas Eve, he
told me he couldn't drive anymore, and I hadn't driven for 30
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, experts referred Beebe to UC-Davis Medical Center, one
of at least two international research centers developing the
corneal growing technique.
</P>
<P>
   Kittredge donated a small percentage of the corneal stem cells
from one of her eyes. Doctors placed the stem cells in a tissue
culture and grew them for six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in August 1998, Beebe underwent the surgery at UC-Davis
Medical Center. Schwab sewed the newly grown corneal tissue into
Beebe's eye.
</P>
<P>
   Beebe went through several months of recovery, which included
drugs to prevent his immune system from rejecting the new corneal
tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Now Beebe can see with 20/40 vision, compared with the former
20/200. Not perfect, but it beats the blurry vistas he once
perceived.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a miracle,'' Jean Beebe said.
</P>
<P>
   The article in Thursday's New England Journal, by Dr. Ray
Jui-Fang Tsai, reported that the surgical procedure appeared to
benefit about 60 of more than 90 patients who underwent it at Chang
Gung Memorial Hospital in Taipei. The article includes detailed
case histories on six of those patients.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
