<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANTANI WINS ON MONT VENTOUX 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARPENTRAS, France _ A Tour de France daily stage has finished
atop the barren Mont Ventoux six times in the race's 97-year
history, and some of bicycle racing's strongest climbers have won
there _ Eddy Merckx, Raymond Poulidor and Charly Gaul, among them.
On Thursday, Marco Pantani added his name to the list. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Italian won with a gracious assist from Lance Armstrong, who
allowed Pantani to pass him at the finish line without a fight.
</P>
<P>
   With the American setting the pace for the last 2 kilometers
(1.2 miles), the pair opened a lead of nearly half a minute over a
few chasers, including Jan Ullrich, the German who is in second
place overall behind Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took the opportunity because Ullrich was there and he's my
top rival,'' Armstrong, the leader of the U.S. Postal Service team,
said afterward, referring to his sudden acceleration with nearly 3
kilometers (1.9 miles) left in the 149-kilometer (93.2-mile) 12th
stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not important to win the stage,'' he continued. ``It's
more important to win in Paris,'' where the three-week Tour
finishes July 23. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong acknowledged that he had not contested Pantani's final
surge, saying: ``In the minds of many people, he's the greatest
climber in the world. He deserved to win here.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pantani acknowledged it, too, calling the Texan ``exceptional.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great champion,'' said the Mercatone Uno rider, the
winner of the 1998 Tour. Great champions, especially Miguel
Indurain, the Spaniard who won five consecutive Tours last decade
and who is an idol to Armstrong, have occasionally let a companion
in a long attack win at the line while they consolidated their hold
on the overall leader's yellow jersey. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the second-place bonus of 12 seconds deducted from his
overall time and with the 29 seconds he finished ahead of Ullrich,
in fourth place, Armstrong widened his lead to 4 minutes 55
seconds. He also further demonstrated his climbing power and
domination. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pantani and Armstrong were clocked in 4 hours, 15 minutes and 11
seconds, a speed of 35 kilometers (21.9 miles) an hour into a
mistral wind blowing from the front. The stage, which started in
Carpentras in sunny and moderately warm weather, finished with the
same sun but temperatures in the 40s. ``The wind was the hardest
part,'' Armstrong said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Pantani, the victory was his first in more than a year.
After he failed a blood test that indicated the use of illegal
drugs, he was expelled from the Giro d'Italia, the world's
second-ranked multiple-day race, in June 1999. He was then two days
from the finish and on his way to easy victory.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Humiliated and crushed psychologically, the Italian retired from
racing until this spring. He competed for two days then in a minor
race in Spain before withdrawing into solitude again. Late in May,
he entered the Giro at the last moment and showed his rustiness
despite a strong showing on just one of many mountain stages, where
he formerly danced away from the pack. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His lack of competition has been evident in the Tour, where he
ranked 24th, more than 10-and-a-half minutes behind Armstrong, at
the start Thursday. He now ranks 12th. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Left behind early in the ascent of the Ventoux, Pantani fought
back, with the veins standing out on his shaved head testifying to
his struggle. When he rejoined the leaders, he tried four times to
bolt away from them.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Each time he was caught, but remained strong. When Armstrong
made the decisive attack, only Pantani could stay with him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As they neared the top, Armstrong was still doing all the work
at the front, continually glancing over his shoulder to see if he
had left his rival behind. He hadn't.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As usual in a bicycle race on the Ventoux, honor was paid
beforehand to Tom Simpson, the Briton who was world road race
champion in 1965 and the winner of many one-day classics in the
1960s.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Simpson was just short of his 30th birthday in 1967 when he
began the 13th stage of the Tour in blazing heat. Determined to win
a race in which he had never finished higher than sixth, the rider
had slid in the Alps to seventh place in the overall standings.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Briton attacked early on the Ventoux, fell back, struggled
upward past the tree line, weaved across the road and then fell. He
was clearly exhausted and workers for his team begged him to quit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He refused, rode 200 meters more and then collapsed. Doctors
worked on him for 40 minutes and he was taken by helicopter to a
hospital in nearby Avignon, where he was pronounced dead. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Traces of amphetamines, a common performance-booster then, were
found in his blood and his belongings. The medical explanation for
his death was that the drug had shut down his body's warning system
against overexertion in the day's terrible heat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
