<SLUG> BC-FLA-GATOR-BITE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHWEST FLORIDA TEEN BITTEN BY 9-FOOT ALLIGATOR, SURVIVES 
</HEADLINE>
  By ROBERT ECKHART   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PUNTA GORDA, Fla. _ Daniel Denslinger didn't worry about the
9-foot-5-inch alligator that lived in his favorite swimming hole
until it bit him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came up to get air and then went back down real fast,'' said
Daniel, 14, who was swimming Tuesday afternoon with two friends in
Preacher's Lake, a 9-acre lake in this southwest Florida town.
``Wham, it snuck up on me.''
</P>
<P>
   He first thought one of his swimming buddies had grabbed him.
Then he reached down and felt the alligator's jaws locked on his
calf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I punched it three times,'' said the 6-foot-tall, 220-pound
boy. ``I guess I hit it hard enough because it let go.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Martinoli, 15, who also was swimming, yelled at Daniel
to leave the water. Once he was on the bank, Daniel saw the blood
and said he threw a brick at the alligator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I put on my clothes and left,'' he said. ``I didn't want
it coming back for seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel and his friends scrambled to a nearby street and flagged
down a sheriff's patrol car. The youth was taken to Charlotte
Regional Medical Center, where he received 11 stitches in his left
calf and five in his right.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Greg Cadzow, 38, said he has told the boy not to
swim in the lake, but can't monitor him during work hours. ``Short
of chaining him to the fence, I can't watch him every minute of the
day,'' Cadzow said.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel promised that he would listen from now on. Several of his
friends, however, said they'll go back to the lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids have always done it. This isn't going to stop them,''
said John McGaughey, whose son also swam at the lake Tuesday.
``I've been here for 20 years. We used to go swimming there. It's
part of living in Florida. The gators are around.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel and his friends said they saw the alligator regularly
during their swims. Most days, it came out at about 7 p.m. and
stared them down as they were leaving.
</P>
<P>
   The gator attacked Daniel at about 5:30 p.m. Tuesday, while he
and Michael were seeing who could hold his breath under water the
longest. Daniel had rolled himself into a ball and was holding his
knees to his chest.
</P>
<P>
   Officers from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation
Commission trapped and killed the 9-foot-5-inch alligator late
Tuesday. Harry Dutton of the commission's alligator management
section speculated that the gator and the boy accidentally bumped
into each other underwater, where visibility is limited.
</P>
<P>
   It was the sixth reported alligator bite in Florida this year.
None have been fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Conservation commission spokesman Gary Morse said Daniel was
lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he extended himself and started beating on this
alligator, it probably figured it was more than it could handle,''
Morse said. ``Alligators are opportunistic feeders, but they are
not indiscriminate. They are generally afraid of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Morse said the alligator was the only one in the lake. Last
fall, officials drained most of the water out of Preacher's Lake to
search its muddy bottom for a missing 4-year-old girl. At that
time, trappers pulled three alligators out of the lake and killed
them to search their entrails for signs of the girl, who is still
missing.
</P>
<P>
   (The Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla., is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
