<HEADLINE>
`NUREMBURG' :  HUMANIZING HISTORY IS A TRICKY BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By JULIE SALAMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's the defining problem with ``Nuremberg,'' TNT's ambitious,
well-meaning two-part miniseries about the trial of Nazi war
criminals: the ``best'' character in the movie is Hermann Goering.
</P>
<P>
   Through Brian Cox's complex performance, Goering _ founder of
the Gestapo and Hitler's No. 2 _ becomes his finest self. He is
urbane, loyal and courageous _ and he gets the best lines. ``The
victors will always be the judges, the vanquished always the
accused,'' he says with world-weary knowingness.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many of his fellow defendants, he refuses to cower or
apologize to curry favor with his accusers. He even sounds
reasonable as he explains German anti-Semitism to the Jewish
therapist sent by the Allied lawyers to gather information. When
his wife and young daughter are kept from visiting him in prison,
it seems downright unfair.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the filmmakers haven't whitewashed Nazi war crimes.
Like the 1961 film, ``Judgment at Nuremberg,'' this docudrama turns
testimony of deprivation and unimaginable cruelty into riveting
courtroom drama and plays its emotional trump card with film from
the Nazi camps. So while the production's Goering may seem like an
engaging fellow, he was clearly a reigning spirit in an enterprise
of unsurpassing evil.
</P>
<P>
   The humanizing of history _ especially in dealing with difficult
subjects like genocide _ is a tricky business, especially in the
context of a television miniseries. The dialogue is crammed with
explanations: ``Our task is to make sure this is not the trial of
superior might, but the trial of superior morality,'' says Robert
Jackson (Alec Baldwin), the U.S. Supreme Court justice who was the
chief prosecutor at Nuremberg.
</P>
<P>
   But even trials of superior morality can become tedious, so the
filmmakers decided to spice the proceedings with Jackson's budding
extramarital romance with his assistant, Elsie Douglas (Jill
Hennessy). Two questions compete for our attention during the first
two-thirds of Part 1: Will the Nazis be given a fair trial? Will
Elsie and Bob kiss?
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin, sober and appropriately more portly than sexy, delivers
Jackson's lofty courtroom speeches with quiet dignity. There isn't
much, however, that he can do to deflate the pompousness of his
character's private musings. When Elsie admires his eloquence, he
agrees with her: ``I've tried to capture a tone, a mood for the
entire case, a melancholy grandeur if you will.''
</P>
<P>
   Poor Hennessy has the thankless task of casting moony glances at
her boss-lover _ and the equally thankless task of elucidation
through stating the obvious. When she and Jackson _ she calls him
Bob _ first confront the sad rubble of Nuremberg the city, she
says, ``When my brother came here as a college student _ I still
have a picture book he bought me _ it was nothing like this. This
isn't even the same city. There were medieval bridges and
gingerbread houses.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob explains further, like a tour guide, ``Nuremberg was also
the spiritual center of the Third Reich.''
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers have set themselves an enormous task, trying to
sort out the moral and behavioral conundrums that gave rise to the
Third Reich. They've assigned the job of illuminating the biggest
questions _ of German compliance and the very nature of evil _ to
Capt. Gustav Gilbert (Matt Craven), the American psychotherapist.
</P>
<P>
   Goering, amused to find out that his shrink is a Jew, says to
him, ``This is a very interesting situation for both of us.'' The
obedient Albert Speer (Herbert Knaup) explains to the doctor that
Germans like to follow orders.
</P>
<P>
   Later, to Jackson, Gilbert confides his conclusions. ``I think
I've come close to defining it,'' he declares. ``Evil, I think, is
the absence of empathy.'' Well, maybe, but aren't there many cold,
unfeeling unempathetic people who don't commit torture and murder
on a genocidal scale?
</P>
<P>
   Through its educational division, Turner Broadcasting will
distribute study guides to schools along with the film to help
students ``analyze the trials from multiple perspectives, explore
how history is interpreted in film and study themes of individual
responsibility and the nature of evil.'' That sounds promising.
</P>
<P>
   But the film itself reminded me of the conclusions of the
novelist and journalist Rebecca West, in her brilliant first-hand
reports on the Nuremberg trials. ``We were going to hang 11 of
these 18 men, and imprison the other seven for 10, 15, 20 years or
for life; but we had no idea why they had done what they did,'' she
wrote (never mentioning their empathy, or lack thereof). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She continued: ``We had learned what they did, beyond all doubt,
and that is the great achievement of the Nuremberg trial. No
literate person can now pretend that these men were anything but
abscesses of cruelty. But we learned nothing about them that we did
not know before, except that they were capable of heroism to which
they had no moral right, and that there is nothing in the legend
that a bully is always a coward.''
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `NUREMBERG'
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Sunday on TNT,
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Yves Simoneau. Written for television by David W.
Rintels. Based on the book ``Nuremberg: Infamy on Trial'' by Joseph
E. Persico. Peter Sussman, Suzanne Girard, Alec Baldwin, Jon
Cornick and Gerald W. Abrams, executive producers; Ian McDougall
and Mychele Boudrias, producers; Alain Dostie, director of
photography; Guy Lalande, production designer; Mario Davignon,
costume designer; Yves Langlois, editor. Music composed by Richard
Gregoire. Casting by Deirdre Bowen and Iris Grossman, CSA.
</P>
<P>
   With: Alec Baldwin (Justice Robert H. Jackson), Jill Hennessy
(Elsie Douglas), Brian Cox (Hermann Goering), Michael Ironside
(Col. Burton C. Andrus), Matt Craven (Capt. Gustav Gilbert), Max
von Sydow (Samuel Rosenman), Christopher Plummer (Sir David
Maxwell-Fyfe) and Herbert Knaup (Albert Speer).
</P>
</TEXT>
