<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-VEEPS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ABORTION GROUP GIVES WOULD-BE BUSH RUNNING MATES A FAILING
GRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A leading abortion advocacy group on Thursday
attacked potential running mates for Texas Gov. George W. Bush,
giving all but two poor or failing grades on abortion rights while
awarding good or excellent marks to likely Democratic vice
presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League, a
30-year-old Washington-based organization that lobbies lawmakers
and runs a political action committee that gives money to
pro-choice candidates, rated the 10 possible nominees from each
party on a scale from ``A'' (staunchly pro-choice) to ``F''
(staunchly anti-choice).
</P>
<P>
   Among Republicans, NARAL gave New Jersey Gov. Christine Todd
Whitman and New York Gov. George Pataki good marks for supporting
abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   None of the Republicans received the organization's top score.
Whitman, considered one of the most pro-choice among her party's
leaders, received a ``B.''
</P>
<P>
   NARAL said in its assessment of Whitman that she ``demonstrates
leadership'' on pro-choices legislative matters, however, ``more
consistency is needed.''
</P>
<P>
   The group said Whitman's record was tarnished because she signed
a bill last year requiring women under 18 to notify their parents
to obtain an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   NARAL gave Pataki a ``C,'' calling his efforts to support
abortion rights ``unfocused.'' While Pataki ``has urged the
Republican Party to moderate its anti-choice stance,'' the group
said in a statement, he also has supported restrictions on access
to abortion services.
</P>
<P>
   The group gave Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge a ``D,'' labeling his
record ``disappointing,'' and asserting that his state is one of
the most restrictive in the nation in terms of access to abortion
services.
</P>
<P>
   The other possible GOP vice presidential nominees assessed
received ``Fs.'' They are: former Red Cross chief Elizabeth Dole;
Michigan Gov. John Engler; Nebraska Sen. Chuck Hagel; Ohio Rep.
John Kasich; Oklahoma Gov. Frank Keating; Tennessee Sen. Fred
Thompson; and Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, NARAL said seven of the possible vice
presidential nominees earned ``As'' on abortion rights. They are:
Illinois Sen. Richard J. Durbin; California Sen. Dianne Feinstein;
Massachusetts Sen. John F. Kerry; Connecticut Sen. Joseph
Lieberman; former Maine Sen. George Mitchell; Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson; and New Hampshire Gov. Jeanne Shaheen.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Sen. Bob Graham received a ``B,'' while the lowest
grade, a ``C,'' went to Indiana Sen. Evan Bayh and Missouri Rep.
Richard Gephardt, the House Democratic leader.
</P>
<P>
   Graham received his grade, the organization said, because he has
voted to trim public funds for abortions. While Gephardt's record
has become increasingly pro-choice, NARAL concluded that his
``votes that safeguard the tenets of Roe and access to reproductive
health care and abortion services for low-income women are
wanting.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic presidential
hopeful, and Bush are keeping the names of potential running mates
closely guarded secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Referring the vice presidential candidates, NARAL executive vice
president Alice Germond said: ``These are the people who may one
day be president. Will they protect or jeopardize every women's
right to choose? For the millions of pro-choice Americans who take
their values with them to the voting booth, the answer could well
determine whether and how they vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the advancing age of Supreme Court members, some abortion
rights activists believe that Bush might seek to undo the 1973 Roe
vs. Wade decision to legalize abortion by naming anti-abortion
justices to the high court.
</P>
<P>
   Bush opposes abortion except in the case of rape, incest or when
the life of the mother is in danger. Gore supports abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue of a woman's right to choose may well determine the
outcome of this election, and this right may ultimately be
determined by its result,'' Germond told a news conference, calling
abortion rights a ``swing issue'' with voters that could resonate
in key battleground states in the November general election.
</P>
<P>
   In its assessments of the officials, NARAL considered voting
records, overall commitment to upholding the Roe vs. Wade decision,
whether the individual supports access to family planning services,
and whether the prospective running mate promotes women's health
issues and supports human embryo research.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
