<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-MEDICINE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN FAIL TO GET PRESCRIBED MEDICINE, UNIVERSITY REPORT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By TIM LOCKETTE   
 The Gainesville Sun   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ Many children who suffer from chronic
illnesses don't receive the daily medications they need, even
though medications are available, a recent University of Florida
study suggests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that failure to take prescription medication is the
biggest health care problem we face today,'' said Leslie Hendeles,
a pharmacy professor at the University of Florida and one of the
study's authors.
</P>
<P>
   Hendeles and pediatric medicine professor Dr. James Sherman
conducted a study of the pharmacy refill histories of 116 children
who suffer from asthma. The refill histories _ obtained with the
permission of the children's doctors _ showed that 43 of the
children had received only half the medication they were
prescribed.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers determined that only half the doctors they contacted
knew their patients weren't taking their medicine as prescribed.
The researchers say they were not surprised to find that one-third
of the children were receiving only half their medication. Previous
studies have shown that as many as 30 percent to 70 percent of
adult asthma patients don't take their medications as prescribed,
Hendeles said, and similar results have been reported in studies of
patients with other chronic illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The problem,is known as ``medication non-adherence,'' Hendeles
said. And patients may lie to their doctors about the medicine they
take.
</P>
<P>
   ``People lie to their doctors all the time,'' Sherman said.
``About 10 percent of the patients I see for the first time never
pick up their prescription, but they leave here saying they will.''
</P>
<P>
   Previous studies have shown that adult patients cite a number of
reasons for not taking medications doctors prescribe, Hendeles
said. Adults often avoid medications because they have busy
schedules, have begun to feel better or don't trust a doctor's
diagnosis, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The parents in the study were not asked why they didn't fill
prescriptions for their children, though Hendeles said some parents
may cut back on the dosage for their children because they don't
trust the doctor's opinion. ``They do it as a form of passive
resistance,'' Hendeles said.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-age patients often refuse to take medications because they
don't want to admit they have an illness, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers are urging doctors to check with their patients'
pharmacists to determine whether patients are filling
prescriptions. Most doctors do not check, Sherman said, because of
the time required.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman said the practice disturbs some patients. ``I've had a
lot of patients get very angry at me when I've checked on them this
way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Hendeles said that doctors should take the time to check,
especially when their patients are children. ``It's not a
comfortable subject, and a lot of doctors don't want to deal with
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (The The Gainesville Sun in Gainesville, Fla., is part of the
New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 1758EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000713.0174 </DOCNO>
