<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1263 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FIVE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      07-13 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIVE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE FIVE SENSES': FILM DRIFTS AMID SHALLOWNESS OF CHARACTERS AND
PLOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Five Senses'' engages the sense of sight.
</P>
<P>
   The director, Jeremy Podeswa, gives the picture the warm
darkness of autumn, with shadows drifting through the scenes like
lost thoughts. It's too bad narrative isn't a sense; the attempt to
deal with each of the senses here is so schematic that the movie
drifts just like those shadows.
</P>
<P>
   The most enjoyable scenes are those between Rona (Mary-Louise
Parker, who, with her suggestive lower lip and brimming, clear
eyes, looks like Mary Tyler Moore with all the primness ironed out)
and her best friend, Robert (Daniel MacIvor), cattily going over
the pitfalls of relationships. Their sense of smell is involved
because they think most relationships stink. Robert also thinks he
can smell love, which is why he is meeting with his former lovers,
male and female, to determine if any have true feelings for him. He
wants to meet Rona's current lover, an Italian chef (Marco
Leonardi) with whom she had a fling while on vacation in Europe.
And although they have no language in common _ no spoken language,
anyway _ he is about to move in with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Five Senses'' is centered on a single office building
where Rona is a baker. On another floor is an ophthalmologist
(Pascale Bussieres), who is going deaf and wants to re-experience
the sounds that have brought him comfort before he completely loses
his hearing. Down the hall from him is Ruth (Gabrielle Rose), a
masseuse who is totally out of touch with her teen-age daughter,
Rachel (Nadia Litz). When the young child of one of her clients
disappears while in her daughter's care, their rocky relationship
is further disrupted.
</P>
<P>
   The film uses its umbrella to deal with urban alienation, and
all its characters are out of touch and having a hard time
communicating except on the shallowest levels. Each character is
estranged from the world and has a hard time trusting others. By
interweaving several stories, the movie suffers from a peculiar
multiplier effect: it deepens its shallowness. The vanished-child
subplot, a dreary melodrama, almost derails a movie that is too
diffuse for its own good anyway. And as a metaphor for loss, this
plot element brings added strain to a movie that's almost all
metaphor.
</P>
<P>
   The Rona-and-Robert scenes (the names of all the major
characters start with R) have a prickly zest. Parker's squirminess
radiates unsureness; she can often seem like a little girl trying
to get comfortable in a grown woman's body, and the shifting
translates into a physical manifestation of neurosis. MacIvor's
character is an eager busybody whose discomfort comes from
involving himself in his own life. There is more going on with
these characters than with the others because they are talking to
each other, and their inability to assess themselves is a more
satisfying version of the ideas that Podeswa, who also wrote the
script, is pushing to get across elsewhere. The film's smaller
moments last. Rachel is lured into a park by a boy (Brendan
Fletcher), and the charge that these two misfits get from their
voyeurism _ watching a couple make out in the park is almost
presexual _ is a boon.
</P>
<P>
   Podeswa shows some talent with his actors, but there is too much
underplayed sobriety, a deliberate quality that may strike some as
nuance but is more like politeness filling in for anomie. What he
wants to do in ``The Five Senses'' is show residents of a city,
members of a community _ as represented by the building _ as being
so wrapped up in themselves that they've lost the capacity for
simple stimulation. This is overarticulated in the scene with
Bussieres, who is instructed in smaller joys by a heart-of-gold
hooker with a deaf child. If all compromises were worked out as
easily as they are in this movie, there would be no need for drama.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE FIVE SENSES'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Jeremy Podeswa; director of photography,
Gregory Middleton; edited by Wiebke Von Carolsfeld; music by
Alexina Louie and Alex Pauk; production designer, Taavo Soodor;
produced by Podeswa and Camelia Frieberg; released by Fine Line
Features.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Mary-Louise Parker (Rona), Molly Parker (Anna Miller),
Daniel MacIvor (Robert), Gabrielle Rose (Ruth), Philippe Volter
(Richard), Marco Leonardi (Roberto), Pascale Bussieres (Gail),
Nadia Litz (Rachel) and Brendan Fletcher (Rupert).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 105 minutes. This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Five Senses'' is rated R (under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It includes strong language, sexual
content and child endangerment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
