</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-TRADE (Undated) _ President Clinton announces a landmark
US-Vietnamese trade agreement, which provokes passionate reaction
from some veterans and Vietnamese immigrants. By Charles A. Radin.
1100 words. (i and f coding)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-SUMMIT (Thurmont, Md.) _ Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat hold their first
one-on-one talks at Camp David summit. By Anne E. Kornblut and
Charles M. Sennott. 1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-GORE (Green Bay, Wis.) _ Ending his loud and long
silence since the primaries, Bill Bradley says he'll support Al
Gore. By Susan Milligan. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BUSH (Pittsburgh) _ Goerge Bush to offer a plan to use
former soldiers as mentors for at-risk youth. By Jill Zuckman. 800
words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CIVIL-UNION (Putney, Vermont) _ In the two weeks since it became
the nation's first state to sanction civil unions for same-sex
couples, Vermont has become a sort of ``Las Vegas wedding chapel''
for out-of-state gay couples. By Rafael Lewis. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   HARVARD-PRESIDENT (Cambridge, Mass.) _ The academic world's
biggest professional plum officially goes on the market as Harvard
University kicks off its search for a new president, a process
already generating intense buzz despite being shrouded in secrecy.
A short list of candidates is months away, university officials
say. By Patrick Healy. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CABOT-LNG (Boston) _ Cabot Corp. sells its Cabot LNG unit to
French-owned Tractabel Inc. for $680 million. Sale includes big
Distrigas tanks in Everett, Mass., a share in a Trinidad gas
liquefaction plant, contracts to supply gas to electric utilities
in Puerto Rico as well as gas distribution companies in the United
States, and a ship. By Jerry Ackerman. 60 words.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-POTTER (Undated) _ Those Muggles can't do anything right.
Several thousand customers who pre-ordered ``Harry Potter and the
Goblet of Fire'' from Amazon.com and were promised free delivery on
Saturday did not get the book until Wednesday due to Amazon
mailing-list snafus. By Stephanie Stoughton. 60 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HKN-BRUINS-COFFEY (Boston) _ Thirty-nine-year-old Paul Coffey
and the Boston Bruins come to terms on a two-year deal. General
Manager Harry Sinden says he hopes the fluid-skating defenseman can
aid the Bruins in changing their too-tentative style to a more
offensive brand of hockey. By Nancy Marrapese-Burrel. 850 words.
</P>
<P>
   CYC-TOUR (Mont Ventoux, France) _ When it was all over, Lance
Armstrong -- the man who wears the overall leader's yellow jersey,
and the man who wears the No. 1 on his back as defending champion
-- retained the lead, while pink-jerseyed Italian Marco Pantani was
given the stage win. By Susan Bickelhaupt. 850 words.
</P>
