<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, July 14, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and showers will increase in coverage over the northeast
quarter of the nation as a large disturbance in the jet stream
develops over the eastern Great Lakes. A warm, humid air flow from
the south will draw moisture inland along the East Coast. At the
same time, cooler winds from the northwest will follow a cold front
as it traverses the Ohio Valley. A few strong thunderstorms will
erupt in western New York and Pennsylvania and move slowly east.
</P>
<P>
   A torrid air mass will cover the Plains and eastern Rockies with
afternoon temperatures approaching 100 degrees in many sections
from Texas to Montana. Slightly cooler air will filter into
Minnesota and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Sultry air over the South will produce a few clusters of
thunderstorms. Gusty winds will accompany the storms in northern
Florida. Afternoon thundershowers will spread into the deserts of
the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Cooler weather is expected in the Northwest as a front pushes
inland. Clouds will cover the coastal regions.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: SUMMER SNOW
</P>
<P>
   Snow showers fell over the higher terrain of eastern France on
Thursday as an unusually cold air mass swept inland from the North
Sea. Snow was noted as low as 5,940 feet or the altitude of the
suburbs of Denver. The remarkable feature of this mid-summer cold
snap is its proximity to last week's record heat wave along the
Mediterranean. Just a week ago, temperatures exceeded 100 degrees
in southern France.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
