   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-NAACP _ BALTIMORE _ President Clinton launched a
broadside attack against the Republican Party on Thursday, saying
the record of Senate opposition to his judicial appointments _ and
the ``stone cold silence'' on the matter by Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas _ reflects a bias against African Americans and other racial
minorities. ``They don't want them on the court, but they don't
want you to know they don't want them on the court,'' Clinton said
in remarks before the NAACP's national convention. Clinton singled
out Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., by name as a long-term opponent of
African Americans on the Supreme Court. And, while he didn't name
them, Clinton assailed both Texas senators for their role in
thwarting his nomination of Enrique Moreno to the 5th Circuit
Federal Court of Appeals. (Deans, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location Atlanta, category National, subcategory Other
</P>
<P>
   TEACHERSHORTAGE _ (30, graphic,) With newly hired teachers
coming to town and key teaching positions remaining open, some
school officials say the district needs to address housing issues.
Some ideas include reaching discount agreements with landlords and
seeking city support for affordable housing for teachers. (Bahadur,
Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   IDENTITY-THEFT _ WASHINGTON _ The dramatic increase in cases of
identity theft in the United States prompted legislation in the
House on Thursday to restrict the use of Social Security numbers in
both the public and private sectors. (O'Dell, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   BARTON-ANNIV _ ATLANTA _ Nine lawsuits have been filed against
All-Tech, Momentum Securities and Barton Security (no relation) as
a result of Mark Barton's rampage last July. At least one more is
expected. Most of the families are represented by Atlanta lawyer
Michael Weinstock. All will be heard in the same courtroom. Trying
to find out when. (Dyer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BARTON-MEMORIAL _ ATLANTA _Gulshan Harjee, the widow of Dean
Delawalla, one of Barton's victims, has spent the last six months
organizing a community memorial service to remember those slain and
wounded in Mark Barton's rampage. It will be held at the Cathedral
at Chapel Hill in Stone Mountain. Victims' families, friends, and
the public ``are invited to join in a prayer for Global peace,
tranquility and to pray for an end to violence and guns. Harjee has
talked to many of the victims' families and expects 2,000 people or
more to attend. (Shelton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BRADLEY _ GREEN BAY, Wis. _ Vice President Al Gore and his
vanquished rival, former Sen. Bill Bradley, bury the political
hatchet and campaign together for the first time since the
Democratic presidential fight ended. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   ESTATE-TAX _ WASHINGTON _ The Senate takes up a bill to sharply
reduce what they call ``death taxes'' on large estates. (Lipman,
Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location Atlanta, category National, subcategory U.S.
Government
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TURNER-NUKES _ ATLANTA _ Two of Georgia's most prominent
citizens _ Atlanta billionaire Ted Turner and former U.S. Sen. Sam
Nunn _ are teaming up in a major effort to create a foundation
dedicated to reducing the threat of nuclear weapons and materials
around the world. The two men will announce today they are
launching a study ``to determine the impact that a private
organization with significant resources could have on reducing the
nuclear threat.'' (Melvin/Saporta, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-FOOD _ WASHINGTON _ KIDS-FOOD _ WASHINGTON _ Only one-fifth
of the children who receive free and
</P>
<P>
   reduced-price school lunches get meals through similar federally
subsidized programs in the summer, according to a report to be
released Thursday by the Food Research and Action Center. Among Cox
states, Colorado ranks 33rd, Florida 19th, Georgia 15th, North
Carolina 22nd, Ohio 36th and Texas 44th in percentage of regular
school-lunch recipients who get fed in the summer programs.
(Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WACO-TRIAL _ Davidian trial entering its final days with closing
argument possible late today. Developing. (Witherspoon, Waco
Tribune Herald) WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   ERNESTMURRAY-COLUMN _ My cousin, who does a good job of keeping
my e-mail in-basket stocked, sent me this list of interesting yet
questionable bits of cyber wisdom. Most of these have been floating
around for years, but every item in this particular compilation is
a gem. (Murray, Lufkin Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ BOSSIER CITY, La. _ My cousins are having a
rough day on the ponies. I keep laying money on their nags to no
avail, so that by the seventh race I'm down $185. I don't know if
the Bourque brothers, Coby and Cody, are really my cousins, though
they share my mother's maiden name. (Actually, I don't know for
sure if they're even brothers, though the odds are good given the
similarity of their first names and the fact they're both riding
horses here in Louisiana.) (Gary Borders is editor and publisher of
the Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel.) EMBARGOED for Sunday. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCNEELY-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ DALLAS _ Rosa Meraz de Montoya,
stuffing envelopes in an East Dallas campaign office, cares about
the 5th District congressional election more than the average
volunteer. She wants her only daughter to go to Congress. ``She's
my princess,'' said Montoya, who also has three boys. Dallasite
Regina Montoya Coggins, 46, a graduate of Wellesley and Harvard Law
School, is running a surprisingly well-financed campaign to unseat
two-term Republican Pete Sessions. (McNeely, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
