<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   NOT-DOTCOM _ ATLANTA _One executive bigwig doesn't know how to
type. A young mother is afraid for her daughter's safety. A school
custodian says he fears for his privacy. They are notcoms, people
who are choosing to ignore the internet revolution which has made
Atlanta one of the most wired cities in the nation. In their own
words, they tell us why they choose to remain unplugged. (Harris,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FLU _ The CDC warns that manufacturing problems will cause a
substantial problem with flu vaccine availability in teh coming flu
season - the first season since CDC recommended that everyone over
50 receive the shot. The agency says the shortfall is raisiing
``difficult questions'' of how to distribute the vaccine to those
most at risk. In a well-protected year, flu kills 20,000, mostly
among the elderly, so this is not a trivial problem. (McKenna,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   CYC-TOUR-HITECH-BIKES _ What do the best cyclists in the world
do to stay on top (of their bikes)? While it may be a test of human
endurance, the month-long tour is also about precision equipment
and one of the ultimate pairings of mankind and machine. We'll take
a look at the latest in gear, gadget and equipment from the tour,
including a peek at what Lance Armstrong is using. From two-way
pagers to bikes that hold thirst-quenching water, we'll see what's
high tech about the tour. (Halliburton, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR
</P>
