<DOCNO> NYT20000713.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1274 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e KIMBELL-STROGANOFF-TEXST     07-13 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
NATION'S HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
KIMBELL-STROGANOFF-TEX STROGANOFF COLLECTION A RARE INSIGHT INTO A(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) By ANDREW MARTON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Once in a very long while, an art exhibition
bursts on the scene that holds the imagination hostage.
``Stroganoff: The Palace and Collections of a Russian Noble
Family'' is just such an exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   Through its sheer size and stellar quality, Stroganoff acts as a
polished mirror on the cultural ebb and flow of an entire nation
over a long swath of time. On display for the next three months at
the Kimbell Art Museum, the collection sets innumerable high-water
marks. Almost all of its 230 pieces deserve the encomium
``masterwork.'' To add to the allure, the art comes shawled in
mystery, as so much of it has been hermetically sealed away from
public view, not seen together since the collection's
nationalization following the 1917 Russian Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the Stroganoff collection's ultimate distinction is
how singular it is. It is synonymous with the bubbling aesthetic
ferment of a historically shuttered society yearning to Westernize.
The Stroganoffs, both as a family and as Russia's unofficial
cultural curators, maintained their noble standing over 500 years
of Russia's imperial history, even as they steered the
sensibilities of its famed autocrats (Peter the Great and Catherine
the Great, among others) toward the highest expressions of the
Western aesthetic.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the rarefied altitude of the Stroganoffs' collection
that it is comparable only to that of the Russian czars. Everything
including gilded, large-paneled Russian icons (taken from several
of the Stroganoff family churches), choice classical antiquities,
sumptuous palace furnishings, and a selection of some of the most
noteworthy old-master paintings have been assembled in an
unprecedented reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Culled from the opulent collections at the State Hermitage
Museum in St. Petersburg, the State Russian Museum in Moscow and
various imperial palaces, many of the Stroganoff pieces stand out
simply because of their link to Russian history. A stunning
tripod-legged coupe done in malachite, mosaic and gilt bronze, for
example, acts as an artistic greeting card from the picture gallery
of the Stroganoff Palace, one of 18th-century St. Petersburg's
finest architectural statements.
</P>
<P>
   Though the scope of the Stroganoff collection will tug a
patron's attention in many directions, it is a safe bet that one
will be inexorably drawn to the exhibit's collection of old-master
paintings. Works by Sandro Botticelli, Anthony Van Dyck, and Claude
Lorrain are of particular note. Such is the collection's
versatility that it can time-travel from the 17th century's ``The
Battle of Lapiths and Centaurs'' by Luca Giordano through some
choice 18th-century French works by Antoine Watteau and
Jean-Baptiste Greuze.
</P>
<P>
   But the Stroganoff exhibit's breadth cannot be overestimated.
The exhibit lopes through hundreds of years of civilization,
showing neither geographic nor epochal favoritism. The family's
peregrinations helped it accumulate antique silver from the Middle
East's Sasanian dynasty, pre-Columbian works unearthed in ancient
Mexico, Chinese decorative pieces, and medieval crosses from
Germany, France and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   And from the era when the Stroganoffs founded various churches
and monasteries come textiles richly braided in gold and silver
thread, various precious objects filigreed in enamel and silver,
and a jaw-dropping collection of icons acting as powerful
ecclesiastic tools with intrinsic artistic value.
</P>
<P>
   Given such a rich selection of objects and objets d'art _ from
figurines to grand tableaux _ ``Stroganoff: The Palace and
Collections of a Russian Noble Family'' is an exhibit to be seen
more than once. ___
``Stroganoff: The Palace and Collections of a Russian Noble
Family''
</P>
<P>
   Today through Oct. 1: 10 a.m.-5 p.m. CDT Tuesday-Thursday and
Saturday; noon-8 p.m. Friday; noon-5 p.m. Sunday. Closed Monday.
The Kimbell Art Museum, 3333 Camp Bowie Blvd., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   Tickets: $10 adults; $8, senior citizens and students with
identification; $6, children ages 6-11 accompanied by adult; free
for children under 6 and for Kimbell patron members. Same-day
tickets are available on a first-come, first-served basis at the
exhibition box office. Half-price tickets available on Tuesdays if
purchased at the Kimbell to be used on the same day.
Advance-purchase tickets are available through Ticketmaster.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (817) 332-8451
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
