<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1277 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-POTTER-INTERVIEW-TEX     07-13 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POTTER-INTERVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXCLUSIVE! INTERVIEW WITH HARRY POTTER!
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editor's Note: After months of secret negotiations,
Star-Telegram Books Editor Jeff Guinn was granted an exclusive
interview with boy wizard Harry Potter, star of the J.K. Rowling
books bearing his name.
</P>
<P>
   Following three international bestsellers, ``Harry Potter and
the Goblet of Fire,'' the fourth book in the series, was released
last weekend. In a wide-ranging interview with Guinn, the
14-year-old discussed the pressures of fame, the real stories
behind certain hitherto-inexplicable phenomena, and even his crush
on an American TV star.
</P>
<P>
   The chief difficulty in securing the interview was in reaching
agreement with Albus Dumbledore, headmaster of Hogwarts School of
Witchcraft and Wizardry, on just how much Harry would be allowed to
tell us about magic, parallel universes and the school.
</P>
<P>
   It was well worth the protracted negotiations. Guinn reports:
``I thought I'd meet with Harry at Hogwarts, but instead Hogwarts'
groundskeeper Hagrid took me to a nearby village called Hogsmeade,
where he said only `magic folk' can live. He kept repeating what an
honor it was for a `Muggle' like me to be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry was waiting in a pub called Three Broomsticks. I
recognized him right away _ the round glasses, the zigzag scar on
his forehead, and his bright green eyes were giveaways. But as he
asked if I'd care for a mug of butterbeer, I found myself overcome
by the feeling that I'd seen this kid somewhere before.'' ___ &QC; 
By JEFF GUINN &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Q: First, I have to say I feel like I've seen you before _
somewhere else, that is, outside of Rowling's books.
</P>
<P>
   HP: (Smiling sheepishly) Well, before Ms. Rowling began writing
about my life, I did some modeling. It was for another book series,
so they don't really want me talking about it. There were quite a
few titles, fiction books, and they were all about finding this boy
Waldo. I modeled for the illustrations. My Uncle Vernon set that
job up for me.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whoa! In the first three ``Harry Potter'' books, your Uncle
Vernon, his wife, Petunia, and their son, Dudley, are portrayed as
nasty Muggles _ nonmagical humans _ who hate you. So why would
Vernon help you get the Waldo job?
</P>
<P>
   HP: (Laughs.) You don't believe everything in the Rowling books,
I hope. Haven't you heard of dramatic license? Uncle Vernon is my
business manager. He and Aunt Petunia lovingly raised me. They're
really a bit put out with Ms. Rowling, how she characterizes them.
The whole idea behind the books was to raise money for the school's
endowment, and none of us knew why they hired an unknown writer.
But I guess Ms. Rowling has turned out OK. And besides, Uncle
Vernon got a nice royalties deal for the books, so why complain?
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm confused. Are Rowling's books about real things that
happened to you, or not?
</P>
<P>
   HP: Oh, there's some truth in each of them. There are some of us
in the world with magical powers. We call the rest of you
unfortunates ``Muggles,'' as you know. We go to Hogwarts for seven
years to become fully trained wizards and witches.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So the Sorcerer's Stone, and the Chamber of Secrets _ was all
that made up?
</P>
<P>
   HP: No, no. Well, not entirely. There's a boulder on the
Hogwarts grounds we call the Sorcerer's Stone. They have to
sandblast it about once a month to remove graffiti. It's sad,
really. The Chamber of Secrets is the faculty lounge, where our
teachers prepare their examination papers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about other characters in the books, like your pals
Hermione and Ron?
</P>
<P>
   HP: They're really students at Hogwarts. Look, don't be mistaken
_ the magic is real. You Muggles occasionally encounter some of it,
which in turn creates many of your myths and legends.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you prove that?
</P>
<P>
   HP: Fine. Where do you think you are?
</P>
<P>
   Q: The Three Broomsticks in Hogsmeade. We're drinking
butterbeer, which, by the way, is good stuff.
</P>
<P>
   HP: That's where you think you are. But where is Hogsmeade,
really?
</P>
<P>
   Q: Somewhere in England.
</P>
<P>
   HP: Wrong! When you got aboard the Hogwarts Express, you passed
through spatial dimensions to another part of the world entirely.
This town, this pub, though invisible to other Muggles, is actually
in the American state of New Mexico, just outside a rather
interesting little town. I believe you have a TV series that's
supposed to be set here.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Not Roswell?
</P>
<P>
   HP: How did you know that? Oh boy, I think I might be in
trouble. Well, what the heck. You see, we needed space to practice
quidditch, the sport where we fly around on brooms. Over the years,
sometimes one or another of us would get frisky and fly a little
too close to the Muggle townspeople. ``Voila,'' your alien invasion
stories begin. See?
</P>
<P>
   Q: Yes, I'm beginning to. What other inexplicable phenomena are
you responsible for?
</P>
<P>
   HP: Just think for a minute.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Um ... Sasquatch?
</P>
<P>
   HP: Yep. He strayed away from one of our Care of Magical
Creatures classes. Very docile, really. Loves almonds.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The Loch Ness Monster?
</P>
<P>
   HP: Ditto.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And Britney Spears?
</P>
<P>
   HP: We had nothing to do with that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: No, what I meant was, any truth to the rumors that you're
dating her?
</P>
<P>
   HP: None whatsoever. This is what I hate about fame. The media
and the fans think they should know everything about your private
life, and they make up what they can't learn. Yes, I met Britney.
Nice girl, I guess. But, really, she's a bit old for me. To be
honest, though, there is an American girl I have a bit of a thing
for.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Not that I, personally, am curious, but, for the sake of our
readers, could you tell us more?
</P>
<P>
   HP: (Sighs.) All right. Alyson Hannigan. You know, Willow on the
TV show ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer.'' She's a great girl. Hogwarts
alum, in fact. She was graduating just as I came in. The witchcraft
she practices on the show? Learned it all in school.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It all makes sense when you explain it. But I'm still
wondering about something else.
</P>
<P>
   HP: Ask whatever you like.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the books, there's so much about evil Lord Voldemort, who
supposedly killed your parents and gave you that scar on your
forehead. The one who is trying to take over the world for his own
evil purposes. True or false?
</P>
<P>
   HP: True AND false. I got this scar playing Zorro with Ron and
Hermione. At Hogwarts, when we have pretend duels we use real
swords. But there IS an evil wizard out to rule the world, and he
has equally evil minions. And my poor parents, yes. I don't like to
talk about that, if you don't mind.
</P>
<P>
   Q: That's frightening! Evil minions? Can you tell us who?
</P>
<P>
   HP: Frankly, all of us magical folk are amazed you Muggles
haven't figured it out. It's so plain. (Looks at his watch.) Are we
nearly done here? I hope I'm not being rude.
</P>
<P>
   Q: No, not at all. Last thing. What about you? What's in Harry
Potter's future?
</P>
<P>
   HP: Well, I'm under contract for three more books. After that, I
graduate, and we'll see what happens from there.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Now that you're so well-known for these books, will it be
hard to move on to something else?
</P>
<P>
   HP: I don't think so. After the second book sold in the tens of
millions, Uncle Vernon renegotiated my contract. Now I get a cut of
everything _ book royalties, film rights, video games, clothing
lines ... the money will be there to let me do exactly what I want.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And what would that be?
</P>
<P>
   HP: What I really want to do is direct.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
