<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1283 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FLY-FISHERMAN-HNS &LR;      07-13 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLY-FISHERMAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NOTED FLY FISHERMAN PROTECTS HIS WATERY DOMAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRED LeBRUN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The king and his river, Lloyd Bull and the West
Canada Creek.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other legends of fly fishing in New York state _ Lee
Wulff, Harry Darbee, Walt Dette and Fran Betters, to name a few _
Lloyd was never one to court the limelight.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, like the river he's fished for more than a
half-century, Lloyd has kept a low profile and kept relatively
obscure considering the high level of his expertise, the company
he's traveled in, and his innovations and accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good,'' is Lloyd's immediate and thunderous reaction to that
assessment, complete with big, beaming smile. ``Let's keep it that
way. We have somewhat of an unspoiled river here, and the quickest
way to have that change is too many fishermen. Oh yes, it has
changed anyway, sure. It's a lot busier than it used to be ... but
one of the reasons I resisted writing a book about the West Canada
is that I know the pressure would increase incredibly if word got
out.''
</P>
<P>
   And yes, this man could write some book.
</P>
<P>
   West Canada Creek _ but it's really a river _ originates for all
practical purposes from the Hinckley Reservoir, some 15 miles north
of Utica. But the reservoir, notes Randy Kulig, owner of the Golden
Drake Fly Shop in Middleville, fills up from the Moose River
drainage in the Adirondacks. Acid rainwater neutralizing over
limestone.
</P>
<P>
   There's about 30 miles of surprisingly uniform river on the West
Canada, all of it good general trout water, dropping at a pretty
steady pitch, from Trenton Falls out of Hinckley down to Herkimer,
where it joins the Erie Canal. The top 2 1/2 miles are maintained
by the state as a year-round, no-kill trophy section, and gets a
lot of use. Department of Environmental Conservation (DEC)
biologist Al Schiavone, supervisor of natural resources out of
region 6 in Watertown, said, ``We'd like to expand the no-kill. But
we have to hear from the sportsmen's groups and the fishermen
before we can, and sure, there's always opposition. Maybe over
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown trout, big browns and lots of them, dominate the upper
reaches. Some escaped rainbows and brookies from the feeder streams
and tribs are there, as well, Schiavone said. ``There are no
waterfalls or dams breaking up the West Canada, which is unusual in
New York State,'' he said. ``This stream is more like a western
river. It's mostly gravel base, a freestone, with good hatches.
Water quality has definitely improved, and so has the fishing, and
that is primarily due to improved water release out of Trenton
Falls.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, especially, with all the rain, water flows have been
constant and substantial. Hatches are outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at the West Canada as two distinct rivers,'' Kulig
said. ``It's a freestone stream when the dam opens up. But when it
shuts off, the river is more like a spring creek, low, clear, and
very tough fishing. The trout get very spooky.''
</P>
<P>
   When the dam does open up, and water temperatures drop as the
river rises, it takes eight hours for the effect to be felt all the
way down river in Herkimer.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last few years, the water on this river has gotten much
better,'' Kulig said. ``There's been a lot of septic cleanup by the
state, and the Borden condensed milk plant is gone, and so is the
plywood plant. No tanneries anymore. This used to be known far and
wide as a caddis river. But now we're noticing more and more
mayflies that used to be rare, like brown drakes and little
sulphurs dominating the hatches.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the Blue Rose Diner in Newport on Route 28, about
halfway up the river, Lloyd paused over his meat loaf and made an
observation as if it just occurred to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The West Canada is the best trout stream in the state.'' He
raised his eyebrows and smiled conspiratorially. His wife, Carol,
used to his antics, just laughed. You can tell, they still get a
kick out of each other.
</P>
<P>
   At 75, Lloyd has the limber walk and confidence of a man half
his age. Later, when we strode down to the stream not far from the
diner, he walked right along and shuffled over slick boulders like
he'd done this all his life, which he has. He's a wet-fly
fisherman, somewhat out of vogue these days, but still darned
effective in the right hands, and these are the right hands. He
uses a tandem setup of three flies at a time, minuscule gray and
brown nymphs that he has tied lean and mean. Patterns he's devised
himself.
</P>
<P>
   He reads the water, stares hard at it, then makes a purposeful
cast of a moderate distance, and quickly mends the line back
against the current to maintain a drag-free drift. A sharp dip to
the rod. He's got a good brown on, which he plays and releases in a
quick motion. It's a rare day when Lloyd Bull goes fishing that he
doesn't hook more than a dozen.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I only keep one good one, for Carol. And then not
always,'' says Lloyd, who's a little hard of hearing but otherwise
as sharp and full of life as ever.
</P>
<P>
   He can be a rascal. He's long been a professional angler on the
Cortland Line Company team of endorsers and pros, and he loves
nothing more than guiding fly fishers and teaching them. Or merely
following the experts down a stream and catching twice as many as
they did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lady luck always seems to be good to me,'' he said, beaming.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The West Canada has been good to Lloyd, but he's made his own
luck. He turned out to be a very good businessman, retiring from
the fuel oil business, which afforded him the luxury of plenty of
travel and all the fishing he wants. As a young man, he was in the
right place at the right time. He was at Penn State taking the
first fly fishing course from George Harvey, the dean emeritus of
American fly fishing, who has remained his lifelong friend.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd Bull has a ton of stories about his friend Leon Chandler,
the president of Cortland and a member of the Fly Fishing Hall of
Fame. Of meeting Vince Marinaro on a stream outside State College
and being persuaded into trying an ant pattern for a big brown, and
the ensuing battle. Of the yearly family outings on Great Bear Lake
and his catching world-record lake trout.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are his designs and innovations. His peacock herl
nymph, introduction of lead core shooting head. After the DEC
closed Catherine Creek to fishing with natural fish eggs, he
devised from bits of sponge the first egg patterns, ``and I caught
76 rainbows in one day, some big ones,'' Bull said
matter-of-factly. Not bragging, not exaggerating. A 10-inch fish is
a 10-inch fish, I found when we got on the stream.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a man who's forgotten in one week more about this river
than I've accumulated in 25 years,'' said Randy Kulig, no slouch
himself with a fly rod.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yep. All important stuff you're writing down there,'' Bull
said, rising from the Blue Rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you know what? Let's go fishin'.''
</P>
</TEXT>
