<HEADER>
A1291 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-KRUGER-RETROSPECTI     07-13 1258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-KRUGER-RETROSPECTIVE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIAR ICONS WITH A BOLD FACE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A lot has changed about the art world during the 20
years or so since Barbara Kruger came onto the scene with her
photomontages, but a lot has not changed about her work. Depending
on one's perspective, she has bravely stuck to her guns or she has
become a one-note relic. Either way, her retrospective, which has
landed at the Whitney from the Museum of Contemporary Art in Los
Angeles, where it was even bigger and flashier, represents a career
whose concerns were fixed, as were the arguments about it, by the
early '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Let's put off those arguments for just a moment to delay what
has become a familiar and fairly dreary debate over politics and
art. You probably know Kruger's work, even if you don't recognize
her name. Not many contemporary artists can say their art has
reached masses of people outside the art circuit. Kruger can.
</P>
<P>
   Her message-bearing billboards, magazine covers, op-ed
illustrations and window displays (there's one now at Saks on Fifth
Avenue), along with her designs for T-shirts, coffee mugs, baseball
caps and tote bags have made her art part of the visual culture at
large. There have even been knockoffs. The recent pro-abortion
rights advertising campaign in the New York City subways is one.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to say whether Kruger's own messages about women,
money and power have in the slightest way changed the minds of
these anonymous masses whose minds she presumes need changing. But
just the visual format of the work, the trademark red, white and
black text-and-photograph montage, became, if nothing else, a brand
product of the immediate past.
</P>
<P>
   She hit upon her style by the early '80s, borrowing heavily from
Russian Constructivism, Hannah Hoch, John Heartfield and
advertising. The style consists of red frames enclosing old
black-and-white pictures culled from magazines, manuals and
photographic annuals. The pictures are overlaid with words in bold
italics. Kruger favors offbeat and opaque photographs, '40s and
'50s vintage, often funny. Her texts are short, blunt and
accusatory. They are sometimes cliches, egregiously sarcastic,
inferentially linked to the photographs. Pronouns, liberally used,
incline toward you, we and I.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hear the word culture, I take out my checkbook,''
across a photograph of a ventriloquist's dummy, is a typical print
from the mid-'80s that you'll find in the Whitney show. The
implications that money corrupts art and that rich collectors are
dummies, as is usual with Kruger, jokes about without quite
resolving the tricky problem that her work is a part of the
commodity culture it ridicules. And not a cheap commodity, by the
way. But that is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   Dense and noisy, the Whitney exhibition, including audio
embellishments, has an intended carnival atmosphere without
frivolity. Your reaction will necessarily depend on a blend of
generational sympathy, political concord, aesthetic expectation and
sense of humor. People tend to praise political art that confirms
their own politics. But an art about control and button pushing
demands that you give yourself over to it completely. If not _
well, then you are missing the point or don't get the joke or
aren't trying hard enough or actually hate political art or hate
women or hate yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your comfort is my silence'' accompanies a picture of a man
holding a finger over his lips. Notice once again Kruger's use of
pronouns.
</P>
<P>
   She has packaged her messages variously, printing images on
vinyl and on convex lenses called lenticulars. She has engraved
them into metal plates. She has designed video installations and
sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   The show starts with an adaptation of an installation she did
for Mary Boone's gallery years ago: ``All violence is the
illustration of a pathetic stereotype,'' printed big on a wall,
flanked by screaming faces and sandwiched into a list of racial and
ethnic epithets. In the room directly behind this installation is a
sculpture, from a recent Boone show, of John and Robert Kennedy
beaming, a peek-a-boo Marilyn Monroe on their shoulders. Another
installation, of videos of scolding heads in a room with projected
texts, pushes confrontation to an extreme _ you may judge it to be
condescension rather than confrontation _ borrowing a tip or two
from the work of Bruce Nauman, minus his essential black humor.
</P>
<P>
   Being a product of her generation, Kruger articulates its
familiar obsessions and self-regard. She was born in Newark, N.J.,
in 1945, and studied with Diane Arbus and Marvin Israel at the
Parsons School of Design in the '60s, getting a background in
photography and graphic design. A starter job at Mademoiselle
magazine turned into a position as head designer. She quit
full-time magazine work after a while and began to write poetry,
dabbled in painting and made woven pieces of brightly patterned
cloth laced with metallic yarn and sequins, one example of which
was in the 1973 Whitney Biennial.
</P>
<P>
   Then in the mid-'70s she switched gears, juxtaposing deadpan
photographs with texts. She took her own pictures at first, of
parts of the outside of nondescript stucco buildings. The
photographs looked like the work of the Los Angeles artist Ed
Ruscha, which Kruger says didn't occur to her. Accompanying her
pictures were paragraphs she wrote about imaginary people,
presumably in the buildings. Personal melodrama belied anonymous
architecture. Distress beneath implacable surface became an
essential ingredient in her artistic recipe.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Hospital'' (1978) the texts shrank to short phrases or
words. She printed ``the manipulation of the object/the blaming of
the victim/the accusation of hysteria/the making mute'' beside a
photograph of tongue depressors, for example.
</P>
<P>
   It was then simply a matter of superimposing text onto image,
which she did in a 1980 collage of a woman on a bed with a fashion
magazine, the image stamped ``deluded.'' Kruger had gone full
circle back to Mademoiselle, which prints words on its cover
photograph every month, except, of course, that her messages were
different.
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing pictures rather than photographing them made Kruger
one of the appropriationists of the '80s. The issues they raised
can seem trite now: how photographs create reality, how the media
shape power and reinforce stereotypes. Feminist artists being
particularly focused on stereotypes of women, Kruger was linked
most closely with a group that included Louise Lawler, Sarah
Charlesworth, Cindy Sherman, Silvia Kolbowski, Yvonne Rainer and
Chantal Akerman.
</P>
<P>
   Does it need to be said again how victim credentials often came
before aesthetic value? Or that choosing the art community as a
context in which to denounce elitism always seemed strangely
contradictory and unreflective? These things having been pointed
out ad nauseam, we might say instead that Kruger was one of the
'80s artists adapting Conceptualism via mass-media forms for
political ends, thereby helping to broaden the purview of
contemporary art, if not necessarily to change the world.
</P>
<P>
   The art world became more sex-balanced by the end of the '90s,
which was certainly a contribution. The already shaky hierarchy
involving fine art, photography, graphic design, film and video was
further disturbed. This allowed the next generation of artists to
move about more freely and un-self-consciously among different
media.
</P>
<P>
   Which is where we are today.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Where is Kruger? It's hard to get too worked up about her art
any longer. An art that lives by the rules of advertising dies by
the rules of advertising. Politicians and Madison Avenue executives
know to accommodate the shifting mood. Strategies change so that
the messages won't. Images now get old by the minute. Watch
television: beer ads about beer ads' being manipulative try to
manipulate a generation that takes for granted what artists in the
'80s evidently found shocking about mass-media manipulation.
</P>
<P>
   As for what has happened inside art, young artists reacting
against the previous political stridency now explore subtler, more
aesthetically varied routes toward expressions of selfhood. Kruger,
operating at the same pitch and in the same modes as before,
occupies a curious place. She helped to pave the way for her own
diminished currency.
</P>
<P>
   For a political artist, at least, this probably should be viewed
as a kind of success.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
