<HEADLINE>
AMAZON.COM MUGGLES FOUL UP HARRY'S LATEST ENTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blame it on the Muggles.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to trump traditional bookstores, Amazon.com Inc. promised
to deliver copies of the latest Harry Potter book to customers'
doorsteps on Saturday, July 8, the first day of its release.
</P>
<P>
   But this week, the Web's biggest retailer acknowledged that it
missed about 3,800 orders of ``Harry Potter and the Goblet of
Fire,'' the fourth in the popular series about a young orphan
wizard-in-training. The company blamed a glitch in software
installed to handle the anticipated surge in orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We received well over 300,000 pre-orders for this title and
unfortunately omitted a small percentage of eligible orders by
accident,'' the company told a customer in an e-mail message
obtained by The Boston Globe. ``We are very sorry that your book
was not shipped via FedEx Saturday Delivery.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Amazon.com would not have botched the deliveries if
it had continued processing these orders by hand _ the old-way of
doing business.
</P>
<P>
   The new software failed to recognize addresses if customers did
not fill out the first of three lines on the Web site's address
box. An Amazon.com employee _ or Muggle, meaning nonwizard, in the
Potter books _ would have started reading on the second line.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the beauty of software,'' said Patty Smith, a
spokeswoman for Seattle-based Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   After discovering that their packages had not arrived, jilted
shoppers began flaming Amazon.com on Web chat sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just found out that Amazon screwed up on my Harry Potter
(number)(NU)4 order,'' a shopper wrote Saturday. ``So everyone else
who may be expecting FedEx to show up later this morning, you might
want to re-check that order confirmation e-mail and see if they
blew it for you or your child, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 1.5 percent of orders were not delivered on time, Smith
said. To make up for the inconvenience, the retailer has promised
to refund customers for the cost of the book and shipping fees _ a
remedy that could run as much as $75,000.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Van Winkle, an analyst with Adams, Harkness &AMP; Hill, said
he doubted the late deliveries would affect Amazon.com's
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot more people who walked into their local
bookstore, which didn't have the books _ and their kids screamed
all the way to the car,'' Van Winkle said. ``They got nothing.
Amazon gave them free books and free shipping.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
