<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KRAMER-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE NIGHT LARRY KRAMER KISSED ME': 1-MAN FILM CAPTURES THEATER
SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Commanding the stage in a one-person show is a daunting
undertaking. Even more daunting is the attempt to command the movie
screen with such a show.
</P>
<P>
   But in ``The Night Larry Kramer Kissed Me,'' David Drake,
reprising his roles as writer and performer of this Obie
Award-winning monologue, manages that feat to a praiseworthy degree
under the intelligent direction of Tim Kirkman, whose credits
include ``Dear Jesse.''
</P>
<P>
   The translation of a series of monologues about the life and
times of a gay American growing up in the era of the Stonewall
riots, the first Gay Pride parade and the plague of AIDS poses the
challenge of making material based mainly on words at home in a
medium normally at its most hospitable to action.
</P>
<P>
   But Drake, whose actorly skills include movement, and Kirkman,
who resists any impulse to open the proceedings beyond the bounds
of theater while deftly employing restrained lighting and a few
props, meet and overcome this challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The title ``The Night Larry Kramer Kissed Me'' is a reference to
the life-changing occasion on which Drake, on his 22nd birthday, on
June 27, 1985, went to see ``The Normal Heart,'' the play by
Kramer, who founded the gay rights organization Act Up and was
shaken into an angry awareness of society's indifference to the
AIDS epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   Drake's performance takes the audience through his early years
of gayness in Baltimore and his decision to leave for New York. He
recalls a symbolic Christmas gift for his father, and in the most
affecting three scenes he recreates the ambience of a gay
gymnasium, takes the onlooker through a sex-drenched night in a gay
bar, recalls friends who died of AIDS and envisions a future of gay
power.
</P>
<P>
   At his least interesting, in some of the material about Barbie
dolls and his childhood neighbor Janice, Drake can be cloying; and
the show's little touches of humor draw only titters of recognition
from its unseen audience. But in discussing indifference to AIDS,
in recreating the charged, curious atmosphere and mixed motives of
the gym, at the gay bar, and in the midst of death, Drake can be
rivetingly angry, intense, frenetic, frank and touching.
</P>
<P>
   Theater is ephemeral. The film ``The Night Larry Kramer Kissed
Me'' serves the valuable function of preserving not just a
performance but the spirit of a time.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE NIGHT LARRY KRAMER KISSED ME'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Tim Kirkman; written by David Drake; director of
photography, James Carman; edited by Caitlin Dixon; produced by
Michael Caplan and Kirkland Tibbels; released by FilmNext/Montrose
Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   With: David Drake.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 79 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Night Larry Kramer Kissed Me'' is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 1833EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
