<DOCNO> NYT20000713.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1298 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CYC-TOUR-HITECH-BIKES     07-13 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-HITECH-BIKES0714-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    There are no bionic bikers, yet
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The director sportif of the U.S. Postal Service recently ordered
Lance Armstrong and his teammates to take their laptops out of
their suitcases. For three weeks, while the Postal Service team
competes in the Tour de France, Armstrong must be without one of
his constant traveling companions.
</P>
<P>
   However, he and just about every other competitor in the Tour's
180-man field carries a cell phone at all times.
</P>
<P>
   The cyclists have lots of gadgets that make it easier for them
to ride and communicate during this intense, three-week long
marathon of a race that will end July 23 in Paris. The bikes are
high-tech and are made of carbon fibers to make them lightweight,
aerodynamic and durable.
</P>
<P>
   The watches the cyclists wear measure heart rates as well as
tell time. Even the shoes are aerodynamic and give cyclists every
advantage for a sport in which mere tenths of a second can
determine first and second place.
</P>
<P>
   Even communication is high-tech. In past Tours, sportifs would
ride by their cyclists and scratch words on a chalkboard, urging
the riders to pedal faster, even to slow down.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is two-way radio.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong wears an earpiece and a microphone, which is pinned to
the collar of his racing jersey. Wires run under the jersey to a
lightweight pack carried in his back pocket.
</P>
<P>
   The radio allows him to stay in constant contact with his
sportif, Johan Bruyneel, during the race. Bruyneel, using his
radio, then can locate members of the peloton, or pack of riders,
such as Kevin Livingston, and inform Armstrong of their
whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   Here's our look at some of the gizmos this year's stylish,
high-tech, hometown hero is using.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD WIDE WHEELS
</P>
<P>
   Chris Carmichael, Armstrong's private coach, has known the
defending Tour champion for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   But with Carmichael in Colorado Springs, Colo., and Armstrong
either in Austin or somewhere in Europe, it got to be hard to
communicate.
</P>
<P>
   So the two started e-mailing each other workout information.
Last fall, Carmichael, a 1984 Olympian and a competitor in the 1986
Tour, started his own Web site _ www.ridefast.com, which is the
home of Carmichael Training Systems _ that gives any cyclist,
amateur or professional, expert advice. All a cylist has to do is
log on to the site and provide information on past and current
fitness levels, specific goals and a telephone number. A CTS
representative will call the cyclist and assign him or her a coach.
There are five training programs.
</P>
<P>
   The process is easy . . . and expensive. Want to be coached by
Carmichael for a mandatory six-month period? That will be $13,800,
please.
</P>
<P>
   The cyclist gets a personalized training regimen and then must
log on and furnish specific data each time he or she works out. The
training regimen changes as the cyclist reaches his or her goals.
</P>
<P>
   That's the same way Armstrong interacts with his coach when he's
on the road.
</P>
<P>
   BIKE TO THE BEAT
</P>
<P>
   Heart-rate monitors are the only accurate measurement of an
athlete's intensity or exertion level. Defending Tour de France
champion Lance Amstrong wears a monitor made by Polar Electro, Inc.
($100 to $300; www.polar .fi). It comes with an elastic belt and a
strap that wraps around the chest, transmitting information to a
wrist watch, which is attached to the handlebars of the bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can look down and see his heart rate as he rides,'' said
Jim Autberg, a Carmichael Training Systems Coach. ``The information
can be downloaded and printed out so Chris (Carmichael, Armstrong's
coach) can analyze the data.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's monitor can calculate time spent above, below or
within a target heart-rate zone. In other words, Armstrong can tell
if he is exerting too much energy at a given place in the tour
race. ``The technology is similar to an EKG. It measures electric
impluses of your heart rate,'' Autberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Heart monitors have been around for a decade, but the latest
models on the market are more accurate, less cumbersome and more
readily available. Basic models cost $100 or less. Higher-end
models can reach $300.
</P>
<P>
   A LOT TO WATCH
</P>
<P>
   When you're on the road in the middle of France, you may care
about shaving time in the race, but you may not particularly care
what time of day it is. Nike's ACG Ascent Compass ($199,
www.nike.com) is more than a watch _ it's a self-contained crew.
The watch, being used in the Tour de France, includes a digital
compass, an altimeter with ``Zero Drift Technology'' to give you an
accurate altitude reading and functions that will tell you
barometric pressure, the temperature and even forecast the weather.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that a rugged aluminum outer shell, data capture,
chronograph, multiple-time-zone calendars, alarms, backlighting and
_ whew, you may get more worn out describing the features in the
ACG than actually pedalling through the race. The watch will be
available to the public later this year.
</P>
<P>
   THE FRAME OF THE GAME
</P>
<P>
   When all is said and done, the most important piece of gear on
the Tour (besides the human body itself) is the bike. Lance and the
rest of the U.S. Postal Service team ride three varieties of Trek
bicycles (prices range from $1,400 to $4,500 for frames. Some are
sold as complete bikes; www.trekbikes.com). The team uses the USPS
Team Time Trial Bike, the USPS Team Bike and the USPS Team
Superlight, which Trek boasts is the lightest stock frame ever at
2.27 pounds. That frame uses 110 grams of carbon fiber per square
meter, shaving nearly a third off of the carbon fiber used on
Lance's 1999 Tour-winning bike. One of the most interesting
features is a ``hydration system'' (read: for drinking water) using
a water bladder in the downtube for fast, fast drinking.
</P>
<P>
   The Trek bikes are American-made, just like Lance, and also are
able to withstand a grueling 2,300-mile trek.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
