<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1299 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-COFFEY-BOS     07-13 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-COFFEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS HOPE COFFEY WILL BRING WELCOME CHANGE TO TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When the phone rang last Friday, Paul Coffey had a hard
time believing who was calling. It was Bruins president/general
manager Harry Sinden, asking if the unrestricted free agent would
be interested in coming to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the 39-year-old Coffey and the club agreed on a
two-year deal. Sinden said he's hoping the fluid-skating
defenseman, who has won the Norris Trophy three times and the
Stanley Cup four times, can help the Bruins change to a more
uptempo and offensive style of hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things is our obvious lack of offense from our
blue-line group, not only on the power play, but in five-on-five
situations as well,'' said Sinden, when asked what attracted them
to Coffey. ``Also, the way Paul plays, I felt he could bring
something to this team that we really haven't had for awhile, and
that is a little bit of offense and risk. I think our conservatism
is a result of some players being not sure of whether they can get
away with that or not, and he's been able to show almost everybody
that you can if you do it properly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he could bring that to the team and show people like
(Kyle) McLaren and (Jonathan) Girard and (Nick) Boynton in
particular that there's a way to go about this that works pretty
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Coffey, who will be playing for his eighth NHL organization, had
wanted to land in his native Toronto, but the Maple Leafs weren't
interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toronto was always in my plans, it just seemed as if I wasn't
in theirs,'' said Coffey. ``We had talked a couple of times but
nothing real serious. I had this opportunity with Boston and the
team definitely intrigues me. That's why I went that way. To be
perfectly honest, when Harry called me last Friday, it was a total
surprise but something that intrigued me right off the bat, looking
at their lineup. It really excited me.''
</P>
<P>
   Coffey said he's completely healthy now. Over the last few
years, Coffey has struggled with his health. The worst of it was
the 1998-99 season, when he was in Chicago. He suffered a
debilitating sciatic nerve problem that extended down his leg. For
a time, it appeared his career was in jeopardy. But doctors told
him it would take 8-10 months to heal completely. After a slow
start with Carolina last year, he finished strong and looked more
like the Coffey of old.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last three years prior to last year hadn't been great, so
it's a chance for me to get back out there and show what I can
do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The one dilemma facing both team and player is what number he
should wear. The first seven years of his career, Coffey wore No.
7, which is out of the question since the Bruins retired Phil
Esposito's sweater. For the last 13 seasons, he has worn No. 77.
Sinden said Coffey will not wear the number that belongs to Ray
Bourque.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't yet figured what number he'll wear but we'll give
him a number of options,'' said Sinden.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know,'' said Coffey. ``Maybe Ray would let me wear
it for a couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said this signing was in no way an attempt to replace
Bourque either in the hearts and minds of Bruins' fans or in the
club's lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't lose a player like Ray and ever get over it,'' said
Sinden. ``In terms of numbers only, we replaced Ray with Peter
Popovic and Don Sweeney and the two draft choices (27-year-olds
Jarno Kultanen and Pavel Kolarik). The reason for Coffey is very
evident to me. If this team is going to move up, make the playoffs,
and move up further than that, we're going to have to complement
what I consider to be a highly skilled group of forwards
offensively with a defenseman like Paul Coffey. We're fortunate
he's available to come in and really give this group of forwards a
feeling that, yes, you can play offense and you can entertain your
fans and still win games in this league.
</P>
<P>
   ``That, to me, was one of the biggest reasons I thought Paul
could come in and help us.''
</P>
<P>
   Coffey said he's looking forward to being reunited with coach
Pat Burns, for whom he played during two Canada Cups.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a man I really respect,'' said Coffey. ``He, especially,
doesn't take losing easily. Nobody wants to change the team around
successfully more than Pat Burns. I'm quite excited about playing
for him again. Harry and I talked about what I can bring to the
team. I know the way I play and the way I've played on every team,
and that's trying to play an upbeat tempo with give and gos and
skating. With some of the younger forwards they have, things should
work out very well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
