<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1309 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CLINTON-NAACP14-COX     07-13 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NAACP14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON SAYS INACTION ON JUDGES REFLECTS BIAS IN GOP
 &HT;    Eds: Seeking Bush response to Clinton remarks.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ In a broad attack on his Republican foes, President
Clinton said Thursday that Senate opposition to his judicial
nominations reflects a party bias against African Americans and
other minorities.
</P>
<P>
   He took specific aim at Sens. Phil Gramm and Kay Bailey
Hutchison, both Texas Republicans, for blocking his nomination of
El Paso attorney Enrique Moreno to the U.S. Court of Appeals for
the 5th Circuit.
</P>
<P>
   At the urging of those senators, who contend that Moreno was
nominated to help Clinton raise Democratic funds from the Hispanic
community, the nomination has been stalled in the Senate Judiciary
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't they want to give these people a hearing and a
vote?'' Clinton asked during remarks at the annual convention of
the NAACP. ``Because they don't want him on the court, but they
don't want you to know they don't want him on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   In a clear reference to Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the
presumptive GOP presidential nominee, Clinton said, ``the leader of
the Republican Party of Texas'' has responded only with ``stone
cold silence'' to the inaction on Moreno.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint June 19 letter to Clinton, Gramm and Hutchison
chastised Clinton for ``trading on judicial nominations as a device
to generate money for Democratic political campaigns,'' and went on
to cite the Moreno nomination as part of a ``strategy of mixing
judicial nominations with partisan hectoring in order to extract
contributions.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton contends that Moreno is a highly qualified nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also singled out Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., by name,
accusing him of standing in the way of Clinton's efforts to
integrate the U.S. Court of Appeals for the 4th Circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Helms won't let these people get confirmed,'' said
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``For over seven years now, he has stopped my attempts to
integrate the 4th Circuit Court of Appeals, and the Republican
majority has made no move to change the tide,'' said Clinton.
``This is outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   A Helms aide dismissed the criticism as ``election-year
politics,'' and said the senator stands by his contention that the
Fourth Circuit doesn't need any additional judges.
</P>
<P>
   When Helms was told of the president's remarks, ``he chuckled
and he said, 'the president just can't tell the straight (truth)
about anything, can he?' '' said Helms's aide, who declined to be
quoted by name.
</P>
<P>
   The 4th Circuit _ comprising Virginia, West Virginia, Maryland,
North Carolina and South Carolina _ has the largest black
population of any federal circuit in the country, and has never had
a black judge. There are 15 federal judgeships on the circuit; four
are vacant.
</P>
<P>
   Helms has opposed Clinton's nomination of two African Americans
_ Richmond, Va., attorney Roger Gregory and North Carolina state
appellate Judge James Wynn _ to the 4th Circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all want justice to be blind,'' said Clinton. ``But we also
know that when we have diversity in our courts, as in all aspects
of society, it sharpens our vision and makes us a stronger
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   All presidential nominations for the federal bench are subject
to the review of the Senate, which is controlled by a Republican
majority.
</P>
<P>
   White House statistics show that Senate confirmations closely
mirror Clinton's nominations in terms of percentage of women and
minorities allowed to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has nominated 104 candidates to the federal bench over
the past year and a half, 50 of whom _ 48 percent _ are either
women or minorities. The Senate has confirmed 64 of those nominees,
30 of whom _ 47 percent _ have been women or minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, though, has highlighted a few high-profile cases that
have drawn sharp criticism from groups like the NAACP, including
the nominations of Gregory, Moreno and Missouri Supreme Court Judge
Ronnie White.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, the Senate voted, in a straight party-line vote,
to kill the nomination of White _ the first African American judge
to sit on the Missouri Supreme Court _ to the federal appeals
court, contending that he was not likely to be tough enough on
death-row cases.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton lambasted the vote, which drew sharp criticism from the
African American community, but he stopped short of calling his
opponents racist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the president was being polite when he called it
partisanship,'' said Julian Bond, chairman of the NAACP _ the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
</P>
<P>
   Bond said Clinton's remarks would persuade many African
Americans to see the judicial nomination process as a key issue in
November elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're as outraged as he was,'' said Bond. ``They're going to
go back to their homes and say to their senators, 'What about
it?'''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deans's e-mail address is bobdeans(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
