<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service has move the following
entertainment/arts and travel articles this week for release
Sunday, July 16, 2000. The scheduled business/finance articles will
move later today and Friday. If you have questions about stories,
call 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (moving in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE STORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GERGIEV-BALLET (St. Petersburg, Russia) _ Every year, around the
summer solstice, this faded imperial city steps back into the
limelight. On those long white nights, when the sun dips out of
sight for only a few hours, crowds gather on the banks of the Neva
River, even shabby hotels fill up with tourists and at the
venerable Maryinsky (formerly Kirov) Theater, the seats at the
``Stars of the White nights'' festival are taken up by rich patrons
from all over the world. This is also the one time when Valeri
Gergiev, one of the world's most sought after conductors who also
happens to be theater's artistic director, bring a his star quality
home to this gritty city with a pretty face. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   BOLSHOI-BALLET (New York) _ Power and passion: The Bolshoi
Ballet's dancing has been synonymous with these qualities, making
it a company unlike any other. Virtually sold out for its
appearances at Lincoln Center Festival 2000 this week, as was its
recent five-city U.S. tour, the fabled company from Moscow returns
to New York for the first time in 10 years, and with its potent
mystique intact. Nonetheless, as Aleksei Fadeyechev says, ``It is a
different company now. Time chooses dancers for its own time.'' By
Anna Kisselgoff.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHUCK&AMP;BUCK-FILM (Undated) _ Insinuating its way into a summer of
movies of negligible ambiguity comes one of the major chew bones of
this year's Sundance Film Festival, ``Chuck and Buck.'' The movie,
scheduled to open July 14, is about boyhood friends who
re-encounter one another after many years. It's a movie that
careens into one cringe-inducing circumstance after another: the
sexuality of children, the old relationship that will not die, the
overweening confidence of jerks, the cruelty of the panicked, the
geek who will not go away. And it's a comedy. By Jamie Malanowski.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   COMMIE-COMEDY-FILM (Undated) _ The phrase ``Communist musical
comedy'' may sound like an oxymoron, but even the officially
achieved utopia of no-longer-extant East Germany required a few
measures of utopian song-and-dance. ``Hot Summer,'' the teenage
musical that was the DDR's second-highest-grossing film in 1968, is
not quite socialism a-go-go but it's an entertaining artifact
nonetheless. By J. Hoberman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ZAKS-THEATER (New York) _ Sitting in the cool darkness of the
theater balcony where ``The Man Who Came to Dinner'' was about to
start previews, Jerry Zaks did not come across as a burdened man.
Yet if his experiences of the last few years have not succeeded in
darkening the Broadway director, they have certainly left him more
defended. And no wonder. Zaks, 53, is coming off a bad run of
flops, including last season's ``Epic Proportions'' and the 1999
``Civil War.'' But one could also argue that Zaks has not so much
failed his more recent projects, as they have failed him. By Robin
Pogrebin.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCHUBERT-MUSIC (Undated) _ Christopher Gibbs begins his brief
new book on Schubert (``The Life of Schubert,'' Cambridge
University Press) by avoiding any claim to the ``true'' man and
composer. He will, in his words, ``recount what can be reliably
documented and examine some of the persistent images.'' Knowing the
chronologies and the anecdotes from friends is a help, but they do
not tell us who Schubert was. Indeed, the truth of Schubert is that
he knows more about us than we about him. Some creative people are
this big. By Bernard Holland.
</P>
<P>
   LEHRER-MUSIC (Santa Cruz, Calif.) _ His songs are the stuff of
your fondest adolescent imagination, subversive send-ups of the Boy
Scouts, religion, lynching, college cheerleading, pollution,
plagiarism, prudishness. They are twisted, erudite parodies of the
perverse. So it comes as a bit of a surprise on meeting Tom Lehrer,
the Harvard-trained mathematician-cum-musician that the disc jockey
Barry Hansen has called ``the most brilliant song satirist ever
recorded,'' to learn that he seems a lot more like the gently
whimsical voice behind his children's songs for the television
series ``The Electric Company,'' than the sick-genius author of
``Poisoning Pigeons in the Park.'' By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-SWEENEY-TODD (Undated) _ There are nights in the
theater, the opera house, the symphony hall that earn the
designation legendary. We've all heard about them, or perhaps, with
luck, even caught a few. And that, of course, is the point. Beyond
their momentary transcendence, legendary nights linger largely
because of their evanescence. What becomes a legend most is the
very fact that you had to be there. But what about the Internet?
Can the Webcam actually make every live performance a widely
shared, even permanently preserved, event? By Barry Singer.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MAURY-TV (Undated) _ ``Entertainment Weekly,'' this season's
``biggest success story'' in syndicated daytime television. The
ratings are up some 19 percent since last year, and it now
occasionally outpoints the popular ``Rosie O'Donnell Show'' in the
same time slot here in New York. This ``daytime yakker'' has got
the ``big mo,'' they say. How did ``Maury'' do it? By Jeff
MacGregor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART/PHOTOGRAPHY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PULITZER-PHOTOGRAPHY (New York) _ Now for the bad news: good
news is on vacation. Permanently. In the news media, anyway, ``no
news is good news'' just might be read as ``there is no such thing
as good news,'' something local television has been trying to
convince viewers of for years. That goes double for news
photography: the news photographs you remember are likely to
compose a litany of grief and terror, from the murder of Lee Harvey
Oswald to the execution of a Vietcong prisoner on the streets of
Saigon to the dragging of a dead American soldier's body through
the streets of Somalia. Pictures of those three events won Pulitzer
Prizes. A show called ``The Pulitzer Prize Photographs: Capture the
Moment,'' at the Newseum/NY in midtown Manhattan through Sept. 23,
reinforces the widespread impression that news tends to be violent
and morbid. By Vicki Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ARCHITECTURE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HEJDUK-ARCHITECTURE (Undated) _ Though John Hejduk was little
known outside the world of architecture, his influence exceeded
that of many of its most prominent figures. His death last week, at
71, leaves a profound emptiness _ a quality that, as it happens,
Hejduk often reflected on in his work. Like many gifted architects,
he was a contradictory figure: a solitary artist who chose to work
in a highly social form of art. But he had a particular way of
living out the contradiction. By Herbert Muschamp.
</P>
