<HEADLINE>
TIMING IS EVERYTHING, ARMSTRONG, PANTANI AGREE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONT VENTOUX, France _ The last mile and a half came down to a
battle between the man in pink and the man in yellow. Wheel against
wheel, pedal against pedal, desire against desire.
</P>
<P>
   And the two reached the summit of the 93-mile race in a virtual
photo-finish as they looked more like friends than rivals. Lance
Armstrong _ the man who wears the overall leader's yellow jersey
and the No. 1 as defending champion _ retained the lead, while
pink-jerseyed Italian Marco Pantani was given the stage win.
</P>
<P>
   Which was fine with Armstrong, since he holds more than a
10-minute lead over Pantani (and a lead of 4:55 over second-place
Jan Ullrich) after 12 stages of the 21-stage Tour de France that
ends in Paris a week July 23.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if a couple of formidable playground bullies decided
to play nice when Armstrong said a few words to Pantani as the two
made their way to the finish, and Armstrong seemed to coast just
enough to let Pantani cross the line first and raise his arms in
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Both were given the time of 4 hours 15 minutes 11 seconds as
they rode in 30 seconds ahead of the next rider, but Pantani was
given the race's win. More important to Armstrong, he finished 48
seconds ahead of Ullich.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong made clear that declaring victory at the end of the
race holds much more significance than declaring it at the end of a
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not important to win the stage, I think in the minds of
many Marco Pantani is the best climber in the world,'' Armstrong
said. ``So I'll forgive the stages for now.''
</P>
<P>
   Pantani, who won in 1998, but didn't participate last year after
a drug expulsion in the Tour of Italy earlier in the spring, was
just as diplomatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armstrong was in exceptional form today; he proved he is a
champion,'' Pantani said. ``I had a great will to win. I wanted to
win at all costs, but was bothered by the wind and a cramp in my
left quadricep. I know I won a nice stage, but there's a lot of
road to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Livingston and Tyler Hamilton, of Marblehead, Mass.,
surrounded Armstrong, their team leader, for almost the entire race
as they shielded him from the wind that gusted to 40 miles per hour
and ensured that opposing riders didn't get an advantage. For
Hamilton, the ride was payback for his win on this mountain in a
stage race last month, when he was the one getting support from
Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   The team stayed together on the final ascent. Suddenly, Pantani,
who had been riding with the main group two minutes back, surged to
join the lead pack and then attacked to take the lead.
</P>
<P>
   But the defending champion would not give in, and for the last
two miles, Armstrong caught up with Pantani as the two rode to the
finish.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, who seemed to encourage Pantani when he lowered his
left hand as if to usher on Pantani, acknowledged that he was
encouraging the Italian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see what a big effort he was making, so I wanted him
to ride with me and stay together in the wind,'' Armstrong said.
``Just some encouragement.''
</P>
<P>
   Encouragement that resulted in both cyclists being declared
winners.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To the French, Mont Ventoux means windy mountain; to cyclists,
it's known as the Giant of Provence. The race ends up at an
altitude of 6,000 feet as the final climb juts up at an almost
eight percent grade for 12 miles. Mont Ventoux has been on the Tour
map just 11 other times since the race's start in 1903, and in
1967, cyclist Tom Simpson collapsed and died on the mountain. But
the elements were not totally to blame _ Simpson was found to have
been taking amphetamines.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the wind and 40-degree temperature at the summit this
week, Tour organizers decided to abandon the press room that's
always at the finish of the race. So the horde of media that
follows the cyclists was told to stay at a press center at the
start of the race in Carpentras, in southern France.
</P>
<P>
   Director of communications Philippe Sudres said that about 1,000
print jounalists are given credentials, and that amount doubles
when all the drivers and technicians are factored in.
</P>
<P>
   The Tour continues to take its toll. German racer Marcel Wust,
who won last week's fifth stage, did not start Thursday's race, and
American Chann McRae was among eight riders who were victims either
of crashes or the mountain. Another rider who had to ``abandon''
(as the Tour so harshly puts it) was Tom Steels, winner of the
second stage. The field is now down to 151 from the original 198.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
