<P>
   MIDEAST-CLINTON (Thurmont, Md.) _ During President Clinton's
seven years in office, no world leader has journeyed more often to
the White House than Yasser Arafat. The Palestinian leader has met
Clinton there a dozen times, and his image in Washington has become
almost commonplace. In turn, Clinton made the risky gesture of
being the first American president to visit Arafat on his home turf
in Gaza. In the coming days, as the Camp David summit rolls towards
a climax, the White House will see whether that investment can be
made to pay in a peace settlement. Clinton believes that
personalities and relationships can fundamentally alter history,
and according to his aides, he is banking on his affinity with
Arafat, and with the Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel, to make a
critical difference at Camp David. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
