<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-VIETNAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIETNAM: SYMBOL AND SUBSTANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The trade accord with Vietnam that President Clinton announced
Thursday represents, for America, an overdue recognition that there
is no longer any reason to prohibit normal relations with the only
country to defeat the United States in a war.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the primary effect of the trade deal on Americans will be
psychological and symbolic. It is a way of acknowledging that, with
the passage of time, Vietnam has become a nation like any other in
the American psyche. Most Americans no longer feel an emotional or
political need to retain high tariffs on textiles from Vietnam or
to discourage US companies from investing there.
</P>
<P>
   In Vietnam, however, the pact that Vietnamese Trade Minister Vu
Khoan negotiated with US trade representative Charlene Barshefsky
promises to have momentous economic and political effects.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, Vietnam's commitment to open itself to investment
from American corporations signifies a surrender by Communist Party
hardliners who, until now, had clung tenaciously to the statist
structures of their foundering economic system.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, hardliners nixed a similar trade accord that had
been negotiated with Washington because of a well-founded fear that
the inefficient state-owned enterprises controlled by their
relatives and cronies could not survive competition with unfettered
private enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Two dramatic illustrations of the hardliners' blunder have
tilted Hanoi toward a change of attitude. Economic output in
Vietnam has plunged since 1995, and there has been a precipitous
falloff in foreign investment since 1996, when it reached an annual
peak of $8 billion on the erroneous assumption that Vietnam would
become the next Asian tiger.
</P>
<P>
   It is no accident that Vietnam's change of heart follows hard
upon China's impending acquisition of permanent normal trade
relations with the United States. If America's leaders had
appreciated the deep-seated rivalry between Hanoi and Beijing, they
might never have made war on Vietnam in the first place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
