<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1351 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-REVIEW-SUNSHINE-COX     07-13 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-SUNSHINE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A dark drama, `Sunshine' sheds light on brutality
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _Emmanuel Sonnenschein, patriarch of a
Hungarian Jewish family, raises his glass on the eve of 1900 and
predicts that the new century will be a time of ``love, justice and
tolerance.'' He may be a wise man, but he'll never make it as a
prognosticator.
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine, the ironically named epic by Istvan Szabo (Oscar
winner for 1981's Mephisto), is both the translation of the family
name and what they call the alcoholic health elixir they produce
from a secret, blood-stained recipe. The film chronicles three
generations of abject hardship, brought on by the family's
impatience to assimilate in the face of anti-Semitism and
self-loathing.
</P>
<P>
   At three hours, it is an exhausting, difficult viewing
experience but ultimately a tribute to human endurance in the face
of adversity.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it is about one family's stubborn inability to learn,
repeating the same mistakes, generation after generation. So
similar are the choices and fates of the Sonnenschein men that, in
a stunning bit of stunt casting, grandfather, father and son are
all played by the intense Ralph Fiennes, with slight changes in
demeanor and more overt adjustments of facial hair.
</P>
<P>
   As sober, ambitious lawyer Ignatz, he is persuaded to change his
name to the more Hungarian-sounding Sors to be appointed judge and
rise in politics. With each move closer to the center of power, he
grows more corrupt, only to be ostracized as the Austro-Hungarian
Empire begins to crumble. His son Adam _ Fiennes again _ is intent
on fencing for Hungary in the 1936 Olympics, even if it requires
converting to Catholicism and allying with military officers who
openly disdain him.
</P>
<P>
   Although Adam wins a gold medal, which affords him momentary
immunity as Hitler comes to power, he learns that no attempt to
deny his heritage can shield him. On a wintry day in a
concentration camp, Adam is singled out, stripped, hosed down and
left to freeze to death as his son silently looks on. That son,
Ivan, consumed by guilt, will later help punish Nazi sympathizers,
but as a pawn of the Communists. As regimes replace each other, as
the labels and ideologies change, intolerance remains a constant.
</P>
<P>
   As with so many historical novels, romantic involvements
parallel the politics. Foremost among the women of Sunshine is
Ignatz's cousin Valerie (the radiant Jennifer Ehle, this year's
Tony winner for The Real Thing), whom he marries over the protests
of his parents. A photographer and observer of life, Valerie breaks
from Ignatz as he climbs the political ladder but returns when he
lapses into ill health.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie is the film's spine, cursed with an ability to survive
through the ages. And, in another casting coup, Ehle is succeeded
in the role by her mother, the expressive, delicate Rosemary
Harris. Involved with latter-day Sors men are Rachel Weisz, who
seduces brother-in-law Adam, and Deborah Kara Unger as a Soviet
soldier attracted to Ivan. And late in the movie, William Hurt
gives his best performance in years as an Auschwitz survivor
brutalized by the Stalinists.
</P>
<P>
   Structurally, Sunshine breaks neatly into one-hour segments, as
if it were intended to be a miniseries. Even at three hours,
though, this vast tale often feels rushed and truncated. Surely, it
is a quirk of film distribution that such a serious, thoughtful and
demanding work as this arrives in the summer amid the crowded field
of smirking comedies and mindless eye candy. For those willing to
devote the time and make the emotional commitment, Sunshine is a
rewarding walk through the dark history of
</P>
<P>
   the past century.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
