<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABOT-LNG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CABOT SELLING LNG ARM TO FRENCH COMPANY FOR $680 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Cabot Corp. is selling its liquefied natural gas
business, including the landmark Distrigas storage tanks alongside
the Mystic River, to a French-owned energy company for $680 million
in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of the unit formally known as Cabot LNG LLC also
includes a 10 percent share of a liquefaction plant in Trinidad, a
ship to transport that gas to Boston, long-term contracts to supply
gas to two large electric generating plants and several utility
companies, and the right to build a $150 million, gas-fired power
generating plant at Island End in Everett.
</P>
<P>
   The buyer is Tractebel Inc., the US subsidiary of Tractebel S.A.
of Belgium, which operates that country's largest electric utility
and has other gas and electric power interests around the world
that employ more than 60,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Tractabel Inc.'s operations in New England include a half
interest in a 330-megawatt gas-fired power plant in Bellingham;
full ownership of wood-fired electric generating stations in
Westminster, Tamworth, and Bethlehem, N.H., and East Ryegate, Vt.;
and a hydroelectric generating station in Winooski, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to continue to build our presence in the region, to be
an owner and operator of assets,'' William P. Utt, chief executive
of Tractabel Power Inc., said in a telephone interview from his
office in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   With several gas-fired power plants planned or being built in
New England, Utt said Tractabel foresees a need to eventually
expand the Distrigas terminal. The terminal is scheduled to receive
40 deliveries by ship this year, 10 more than in 1999, as demand
for natural gas grows.
</P>
<P>
   Tractabel S.A., based in Brussels, is a wholly owned unit of
Suez Lyonnaise des Eaux, a publicly traded conglomerate based in
Paris that also operates water systems and wastewater treatment
plants and has a worldwide construction division.
</P>
<P>
   Cabot Corp.'s primary business is specialty chemicals, but for
more than 130 years the company has also been a producer and
distributor of natural gas and, to a lesser degree, oil.
</P>
<P>
   Cabot's Distrigas unit began importing gas from Algeria in 1971.
Depending on weather conditions, Cabot LNG supplies about 10
percent of all gas burned in New England, mostly distributed by
pipeline to local utilities, including the Boston Gas Co.
</P>
<P>
   Cabot's chairman and chief executive, Samuel W. Bodman, said the
sale of Cabot LNG is expected to close by Sept. 1. Approval from
the Justice Department and the US Securities and Exchange
Commission is required, but federal and state energy officials said
the transaction appears to be exempt from their rules.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Gas said it expects the sale to have no impact on its
operations or ability to serve its customers.
</P>
<P>
   Utt said no personnel changes are planned among Cabot LNG's 86
employees, but added there could be some consolidation in the
future with Tractebel's LNG operations in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   Bodman, in a telephone interview, said Cabot Corp. expects
proceeds from the sale after taxes to be about $500 million, to be
earmarked for repurchase of Cabot shares and to develop new
products based on its core chemical products. The Cabot Corp. board
is scheduled to meet Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This eliminates the last vestiges of our energy business,''
Bodman said. ``We are now truly a chemical company.''
</P>
<P>
   Bodman said Cabot hopes that shedding its reputation as a
conglomerate will improve investor opinion about its shares, which
have lagged for the past three years during one of the strongest
bull stock markets in US history.
</P>
<P>
   Investors did, in fact, respond favorably to the LNG deal. Cabot
shares closed Thursday on the New York Stock Exchange at $31.7188,
up $1.5938.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Suisse First Boston analyst John Cochran said while
Cabot's LNG division has been profitable in colder-than-normal
years, slack sales during warmer years cut deeply into the
company's overall financial performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their earnings were practically zero'' in 1998, he said,
because of LNG losses. Changes in gas purchasing were pointing to a
profit for LNG of about $20 million this year, Cochran said, but
chemicals still would account for 80 percent of earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Cabot's primary chemicals are carbon black, used in dyes and
manufacturing tires; fumed silica, a thickener for paints and
adhesives; tantalum metals for electronics; and cesium compounds
used in drilling oil wells to prevent pressure blowouts.
</P>
<P>
   With 4,400 employees and plants in 23 countries, Cabot Corp.
reported operating profits of $229 million on $1.7 billion in sales
during its 1999 fiscal year that ended Sept. 30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 1924EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000713.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1354 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CLINTON-NAACP14-1STLD     07-13 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NAACP14-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON SAYS INACTION ON JUDGES REFLECTS BIAS IN GOP
 &HT;    Eds: Inserts grafs 8-13 with Bush response.
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ In a broad attack on his Republican foes, President
Clinton said Thursday that Senate opposition to his judicial
nominations reflects a party bias against African Americans and
other minorities.
</P>
<P>
   He took specific aim at Sens. Phil Gramm and Kay Bailey
Hutchison, both Texas Republicans, for blocking his nomination of
El Paso attorney Enrique Moreno to the U.S. Court of Appeals for
the 5th Circuit.
</P>
<P>
   At the urging of those senators, who contend that Moreno was
nominated to help Clinton raise Democratic funds from the Hispanic
community, the nomination has been stalled in the Senate Judiciary
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't they want to give these people a hearing and a
vote?'' Clinton asked during remarks at the annual convention of
the NAACP. ``Because they don't want him on the court, but they
don't want you to know they don't want him on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   In a joint June 19 letter to Clinton, Gramm and Hutchison
chastised Clinton for ``trading on judicial nominations as a device
to generate money for Democratic political campaigns,'' and went on
to cite the Moreno nomination as part of a ``strategy of mixing
judicial nominations with partisan hectoring in order to extract
contributions.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton contends that Moreno is a highly qualified nominee.
</P>
<P>
   In a clear reference to Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the
presumptive GOP presidential nominee, Clinton said, ``the leader of
the Republican Party in Texas, who I think talked here a couple
days ago _ stone cold silence. Nobody says, 'Give this guy a
hearing.' ``
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, Bush campaign spokesman Scott McClellan said, ``The
recent attacks by President Clinton, Hillary Clinton and Al Gore
only confirm the fact that Governor Bush is a different kind of
Republican who is making inroads among African-Americans and
Hispanics.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Bush should be urging GOP senators to convene hearings
on the appointees,
</P>
<P>
   McClellan said, ``The Constitution gives that authority and
responsibility to the United States Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush has a proven record in Texas of appointing
people from all walks of
</P>
<P>
   life, including many Hispanics, African-Americans and women. He
will do the same as
</P>
<P>
   president,'' said McClellan.
</P>
<P>
   SInce taking office in 1995, Bush has named 3,017 appointees to
state boards, commissions and vacant judgeships. Of those, 1,109
were female, 258 were African-American and 397 were Hispanic. Over
all, 2,329 were white.
</P>
<P>
   In his address to the NAACP on Monday, Bush did not address the
topic of judicial nominations, but he acknowledged that the
Republican Party had not always been in tune with the NAACP's
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``For our nation, there is no denying the truth that slavery is
a blight on our history and that racism, despite all the progress,
still exists today,'' Bush said in his speech. ``For my party,
there is no escaping the reality that the party of Lincoln has not
always carried the mantle of Lincoln.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Clinton singled out Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., by
name, accusing him of standing in the way of Clinton's efforts to
integrate the U.S. Court of Appeals for the 4th Circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Helms won't let these people get confirmed,'' said
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``For over seven years now, he has stopped my attempts to
integrate the 4th Circuit Court of Appeals, and the Republican
majority has made no move to change the tide,'' said Clinton.
``This is outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   A Helms aide dismissed the criticism as ``election-year
politics,'' and said the senator stands by his contention that the
Fourth Circuit doesn't need any additional judges.
</P>
<P>
   When Helms was told of the president's remarks, ``he chuckled
and he said, 'the president just can't tell the straight (truth)
about anything, can he?' '' said Helms's aide, who declined to be
quoted by name.
</P>
<P>
   The 4th Circuit _ comprising Virginia, West Virginia, Maryland,
North Carolina and South Carolina _ has the largest black
population of any federal circuit in the country, and has never had
a black judge. There are 15 federal judgeships on the circuit; four
are vacant.
</P>
<P>
   Helms has opposed Clinton's nomination of two African Americans
_ Richmond, Va., attorney Roger Gregory and North Carolina state
appellate Judge James Wynn _ to the 4th Circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all want justice to be blind,'' said Clinton. ``But we also
know that when we have diversity in our courts, as in all aspects
of society, it sharpens our vision and makes us a stronger
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   All presidential nominations for the federal bench are subject
to the review of the Senate, which is controlled by a Republican
majority.
</P>
<P>
   White House statistics show that Senate confirmations closely
mirror Clinton's nominations in terms of percentage of women and
minorities allowed to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has nominated 104 candidates to the federal bench over
the past year and a half, 50 of whom _ 48 percent _ are either
women or minorities. The Senate has confirmed 64 of those nominees,
30 of whom _ 47 percent _ have been women or minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, though, has highlighted a few high-profile cases that
have drawn sharp criticism from groups like the NAACP, including
the nominations of Gregory, Moreno and Missouri Supreme Court Judge
Ronnie White.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, the Senate voted, in a straight party-line vote,
to kill the nomination of White _ the first African American judge
to sit on the Missouri Supreme Court _ to the federal appeals
court, contending that he was not likely to be tough enough on
death-row cases.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton lambasted the vote, which drew sharp criticism from the
African American community, but he stopped short of calling his
opponents racist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the president was being polite when he called it
partisanship,'' said Julian Bond, chairman of the NAACP _ the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
</P>
<P>
   Bond said Clinton's remarks would persuade many African
Americans to see the judicial nomination process as a key issue in
November elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're as outraged as he was,'' said Bond. ``They're going to
go back to their homes and say to their senators, 'What about
it?'''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman of the Austin American-Statesman contributed to this
story.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deans's e-mail address is bobdeans(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
