<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-PRESIDENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD SEARCH FOR NEW PRESIDENT BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICK HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ The academic world's biggest professional
plum officially went on the market Thursday, as Harvard University
kicked off its search for a new president, a process that is
already generating intense buzz despite being shrouded in secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard wants to name a successor by spring for President Neil
L. Rudenstine, who has led the institution since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   A short list of candidates is months away, university officials
said in announcing the team that will run the search. But
name-dropping of star candidates in higher education _ and even one
in the White House _ has already begun. And Harvard neighbors are
pressing agendas that they say did not get aggressive action from
Rudenstine.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about as close to a unique search as you're going to
see,'' said John Kuhnle, head of the education practice at
Korn/Ferry International, an executive-recruitment firm. ``The bar
will be high _ for academic prestige and institutional affiliation,
especially.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading the search will be Robert G. Stone, Jr., who was
national co-chair of Harvard's recently completed $2.6 billion
fund-raising campaign. D. Ronald Daniel, treasurer of the
university, and Hanna Gray, former president of the University of
Chicago, are also on the nine-member committee.
</P>
<P>
   Officials plan to mail about 350,000 letters to alumni, donors,
students, and others, soliciting both views about the university's
direction and nominations for candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to have any limits on the type of person we're
looking for, or the specific categories of expertise,'' said Joe
Wrinn, a university spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The next president will focus on academic planning and
development issues. Harvard has nearly closed a deal to purchase 48
acres in Boston's Allston section from the Massachusetts Turnpike
Authority, and is considering putting academic buildings,
dormitories, or other facilities there. Rudenstine, while dealing
with these issues, dove into fundraising, recently completing a
$2.6 billion campaign. No new campaign is on the boards yet.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's business school dean, Kim B. Clark, and the provost,
Harvey V. Fineberg, are seen as strong managers and fundraisers,
making them insider favorites. Both are known quantities, with
Clark's ties dating to the 1970's, when he earned his undergraduate
and graduate degrees in economics at the university. Fineberg also
attended Harvard and previously led the school of public health.
</P>
<P>
   Several women have also been mentioned as contenders, according
to Harvard administrators and executive-search experts. Those
include Duke University's Nannerl O. Keohane, who previously led
Wellesley College, and Alison F. Richard, an anthropologist who has
been provost of Yale University since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   With political figures revolving in and out of education posts,
some has speculated that President Clinton may also be Harvard
material. But one adviser to the president said a
White-House-to-Ivy-League scenario was unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president will be a player on the world stage, on a great
many issues, and that kind of role is inconsistent with the
institutional stewardship required of a university president,''
said Christopher Edley, Jr., a Harvard law professor who works on
race and education issues for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy R. Knowles, dean of Harvard's Faculty of Arts and
Sciences, pooh-poohed the Clinton rumor. ``I suppose if you could
run the country, you could run Harvard,'' he said. ``But I think
the country may be easier.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the prospects returned phone calls Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Several committee members did not return calls.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard will advertise the position in only a few newspapers,
and may keep the ad to just a few sentences, according to one
university official. Many schools draft pages of detailed criteria
and aggressively court prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Grogan, vice president for government, community and public
affairs at Harvard, said consultation with constituents would not
be lip service.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be extensive communications with all of the
stakeholders, and that will include a very strong emphasis on local
issues and local stakeholders,'' Grogan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 1927EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
