<HEADER>
A1359 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-HIV-MEDS-HNS &LR;      07-13 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIV-MEDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG ADHERENCE MAJOR PROBLEM WITH HIV PATIENTS, AIDS CONFERENCE
TOLD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LEIGH HOPPER 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURBAN, South Africa _ Despite free drugs, refills by phone and
medication by mail, 80 percent of HIV-positive patients at two
Houston clinics did not stick to their medication schedules,
according to a study presented Thursday at the 13th International
AIDS Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Drug adherence, or the taking of medications as prescribed, has
emerged as one of the most serious obstacles to using the powerful
medicines that have given new life to people with HIV.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to making people sick, haphazard adherence to drug
regimens leads to viral resistance to the medicine, increasing the
danger that an untreatable form of the AIDS virus could begin
circulating within the community.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Grimes, a professor of management and policy at the
University of Texas-Houston School of Public Health, said he
initiated the study in 1996, just after the introduction of
protease inhibitors, the successful drugs that have turned HIV
infection into a manageable disease in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He was concerned that people with HIV, like people with
tuberculosis, would have difficulty taking their medication as
prescribed, leading to increasing ineffectiveness of the medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The research confirmed Grimes' hunch, providing a sobering
snapshot: Among patients in three consecutive studies, the number
of patients who didn't stick to the regimen ranged from 73 percent
to 95 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably worse than this,'' Grimes said, since the study
looked only at prescription refills rather than pills swallowed or
taken at the appropriate times. ``It takes a really motivated
person to do it. Bottom line is, adherence sucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Between 1996 and 1997, he recruited 310 patients into the study
at a Houston clinic. The patients were taking combination therapy
including a protease inhibitor.
</P>
<P>
   He defined non-adherence as failing to renew their prescriptions
within 37 days of receiving a 30-day supply within any month for
six consecutive months. This allowed patients to miss up to 20
percent of their doses every month before they were considered
non-adherent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rate was so poor, I thought it was too early in the
game,'' Grimes said, assuming that people still hadn't learned how
to use the drugs.'' So he and his colleagues launched another study
at the same clinic, recruiting 257 patients between 1997 and 1998,
``and got the same results.''
</P>
<P>
   He took his research to the Veterans Administration Hospital,
which has a ``user-friendly'' system, he said, and provides a
convenient way for patients to phone in prescription refills and
receive their drugs through the mail. He recruited 191 patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things were slightly better at the VA, but still dismal,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, the immune systems deteriorated among patients who
failed to take their drugs properly and their health declined.
</P>
<P>
   The research team tried to figure out why people didn't take
their medicine. They looked at such possible factors as race,
gender, stage of disease, drug abuse and language barriers. They
took into consideration age, daily pill counts and mental health.
They compared patients who saw multiple doctors with those who had
a single specialist overseeing their care.
</P>
<P>
   None of it mattered. Now Grimes is planning to investigate a new
theory.
</P>
<P>
   In conversations with friends who are HIV-positive, Grimes asked
them how soon after their diagnosis they were ready to begin highly
active anti-retroviral therapy, or HAART, which consists of three
or more AIDS drugs.
</P>
<P>
   With the exceptions of two pregnant women, everyone said it took
at least a year before they were mentally prepared.
</P>
<P>
   While a physician is ready to prescribe medication as soon as
the amount of virus in the patient's blood warrants it, patients
may still be adjusting to the shock of an HIV diagnosis, Grimes
said. They may not be ready to commit to a lifetime of pills that
often have unpleasant side effects such as nausea, diarrhea and
fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   As a friend of Grimes' said: ``I had to have a period of not
being sick before I made myself sick taking those drugs.'' She
waited until three years after her diagnosis to begin taking drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Grimes suspects doctors are putting people on anti-AIDS drugs
before they are ready. Through questionnaires and focus groups, he
hopes to ferret out the signs that a patient is prepared to start
therapy, and pass those guidelines along to doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Just as misuse of antibiotics leads to stubborn strains of
bacteria, improper use of anti-retroviral drugs leads to strains of
HIV that no longer respond to drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Once that happens, a patient can switch to drugs in a different
family, but the results are not as good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Salvage therapy is about half as effective as first therapy.
Your first shot is your best shot,'' Grimes said. ``This is a
lifelong commitment. This is getting married to a pill bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
