<HEADER>
A1360 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-BREAST-MILK-HNS &LR;      07-13 0363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAST-MILK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAST-FEEDING BEST FOR HIV-POSITIVE BABIES, STUDY SUGGESTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LEIGH HOPPER 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURBAN, South Africa _ The unusual results of a new study
suggest a safer way for poor, HIV-positive women to breast-feed
their babies _ an important discovery for women in the developing
world who have no choice but to nurse.
</P>
<P>
   The report was presented Thursday at the 13th International AIDS
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Of infants who acquire HIV from their mothers, about one-third
get the virus through breast milk. Despite the risk, breast-feeding
is an economic and cultural necessity for most African women.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers in KwaZulu Natal, the South African province where
one-third of pregnant women are infected with the AIDS virus,
compared exclusive breast-feeding, mixed feeding and formula
feeding among 551 HIV-positive women.
</P>
<P>
   Exclusive breast-feeding was defined as mother's milk only _ no
water, tea or formula. Mixed feeding, which is common among African
women, includes breast-milk and other liquids or soft foods.
</P>
<P>
   Among the babies who were formula-fed, 19.4 percent were
HIV-positive at the end of six months. Among the babies who
received mixed feedings, 35 percent were infected after six months.
</P>
<P>
   The infection rate among babies in the group fed breast milk
exclusively was 24.7 percent _ a significant improvement over the
mixed-feeding group.
</P>
<P>
   While it would seem that exclusive breast-feeding is inherently
more dangerous because it increases the amount of time the baby is
exposed to the virus through mother's milk, the research shows this
not to be the case.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at University of Natal in Durban, including Dr.
Hoosen Coovadia, chair of the AIDS conference, believe that mixed
feeding may cause inflammation, or create small breaks in the
lining of the digestive tract, creating portals through which HIV
can enter the body.
</P>
<P>
   A diet of mother's milk alone may prevent that. And, as an added
benefit, breast milk protects the baby from potentially fatal
diarrhea caused by formula mixed with unclean water.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 1927EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000713.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1362 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ELIMINATE-LOW-BIRTH-W     07-13 0034
