<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1367 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-VIETNAM-TRADE-BOS &LR;      07-13 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-TRADE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US-VIETNAM TRADE DEAL HAILED   BY OFFICIALS, IMMIGRANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Negotiators for the United States and Vietnam Thursday agreed to
normalize trade relations, marking the end of an era of bitter
animosity and deep distrust between the two countries dating back
nearly 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   The pact still must be approved by Congress _ not necessarily a
sure thing given the recent political slugfest over a similar trade
agreement with China. But the movement toward agreement was hailed
widely, both by political leaders and Vietnamese Americans, as a
boon for both nations.
</P>
<P>
   Benefits to Vietnam are largely economic, opening its small and
feeble economy to the world's largest market, said Thomas J.
Vallely, director of the Vietnam program at Harvard University's
Kennedy School of Government. The benefits to the United States, he
said, are largely diplomatic, stabilizing and strengthening a major
country in Southeast Asia at a time of instability in Indonesia,
long a principal US ally in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Boston's large and thriving Vietnamese community saw
the issues on a much more personal plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good thing for Vietnam because it will help the
people understand how bad the communists are,'' said An Le Dang, a
veteran of the South Vietnamese armed forces that were defeated and
disbanded when North Vietnam's communist rulers unified the country
25 years ago. ``For so long the communists closed our eyes to the
world. This will let people open their eyes and see. It will bring
more freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Deeply Americanized Vietnamese, born long after the end of the
shooting war that cost the lives of millions of Vietnamese and
58,000 Americans, had very different ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will help people over there, but it will also help the
attitude of people here,'' said Vuong Nguyen, a 17-year-old senior
at Boston College High School, as he and his friends emerged with
their lunches from the Fields Corner McDonald's. ``I still feel the
tension, the prejudice here. . . . That all comes from the war.''
</P>
<P>
   Broader, more normal contacts between the countries, he said,
``will help break the discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Vietnam have been at odds since the early
1960s, when the US gradually took over what had been French support
of the Western-allied South Vietnamese regime against the
communist-bloc-allied North. Despite massive American military and
economic aid, the south never was able to defend itself. It
collapsed in 1975, two years after US troops withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   For the next two decades, the United States banned trade,
investment, and most travel between the countries; the embargo was
lifted in 1994 and diplomatic relations were restored in 1995. By
the time that occurred, other nations _ in particular Japan,
Singapore, Hong Kong, and South Korea _ were far ahead of the
United States in trade and investment in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Economically, that is not very significant to the United States.
As Vallely pointed out, Vietnam exports $12 billion a year to the
entire world; the United States imports 100 times that sum.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, said US Sen. John F. Kerry (D-Mass.), one of a
group of Vietnam War veterans in Congress who have spearheaded the
drive for normalization of relations, ``this is a place where the
United States has tremendous opportunities over the long haul.'' He
stressed that, with 77 million people, Vietnam is one of the more
populous countries in the world, with young, relatively
well-educated citizens.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the tariff reductions that make up a major part of
the agreement take effect, products made by that work force will
become competitive on the American market.
</P>
<P>
   The Nike sporting goods company is already in effect the largest
private employer in Vietnam, with about 50,000 workers, but it
employs them through South Korean and Taiwanese subcontractors, and
the shoes they produce are sold on the European market. The work
force could quickly double as a result of tariff cuts.
</P>
<P>
   That does not add up to an unmitigated good to all Vietnamese
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diplomatic relations is good, but not trade right now,'' said
Ton Huu, 73, the style of her white hair and blue suit more likely
to be seen in her former hometown of Saigon than in Boston. ``First
(the Vietnamese government) has to be more fair to citizens. They
should have the right to do business and not have the government
control it.''
</P>
<P>
   Her son, John Truong, a pharmacist who graduated from
Northeastern University, translated for Ton and added his own
skepticism. ``With this you empower the government, the high
officials. There's just a little benefit, some job creation, to
ordinary people.''
</P>
<P>
   Because it is an election year and the China trade agreement
battle is already on the legislative calendar, Congressional
approval for the Vietnam pact may not be immediately forthcoming,
but several observers believe it will come more easily than
President Clinton's proposal for permanent normal trade relations
with China.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that the small size of Vietnam's economy means
that it does not pose an economic threat. Another is that there are
no complicating issues such as the American dispute with China over
missile proliferation.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Vietnam War veterans dominate discussion of the
issue also means Vietnam has much better congressional relations
than China. And, given the Sino-US tensions, many on Capitol Hill
appreciate the value of improving relations with a country that
borders China.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is now a large Vietnamese-American population
whose members want to be able to visit relatives without the fears
they now harbor. Unlike the Cuban American population, they favor
improving relations even though many loathe communism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all wish for better relations,'' said Kim Hall, 54, a
Vietnamese outreach worker at the Kit Clark Senior Center in
Boston's Dorchester section. ``We are still scared (when visiting)
because they don't have human rights. Trade will help a lot of
Vietnamese people feel more secure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
