<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1376 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TELECOM14-COX     07-13 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELECOM14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WorldCom, Sprint end deal but new matches seen
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WorldCom and Sprint on Thursday formally ended the deal that
would have led to a massive merger, bowing to objections of
regulators on both sides of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   But the move, accompanied by some bitter asides directed at the
U.S. government, hardly signals the death of big-ticket mergers.
Instead, it eliminates one matchup and slightly reshapes the rules.
It also makes it more likely that two Georgia-based companies _
BellSouth and Powertel _ will get into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Sprint and WorldCom are through. In fact, the
announcement frees both to negotiate with other companies, while
mulling the lessons of a long, costly and ultimately doomed deal.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman and Chief Executive William Esrey said Sprint isn't for
sale, yet his comments were similar to those made before he agreed
to the WorldCom purchase. ``We're focused on building shareholder
value as we always have.'' As to Sprint buying other companies?
``Yes, if the deal would build size or scope.''
</P>
<P>
   A slew of telecom companies are rumored as hunter _ and nearly
all could be prey.
</P>
<P>
   Among those that could be on either side is BellSouth, which in
October launched a vain $100 billion bid for Sprint, but has also
been mentioned as a target for foreign firms seeking a U.S.
foothold. Since the fall, the $25 billion-a-year Atlanta-based
company has made some dramatic changes, but none that flat-out
overule renewed courtship with Sprint if BellSouth's management and
directors believe merging with Sprint is the best bet for survival.
And it would help if Sprint is willing.
</P>
<P>
   But BellSouth is expected first to wait for a decision from the
current Goliath in the rumor market, Deutsche Telekom. The company
has vowed to become a global player and has been reportedly
negotiating with a host of takeover targets, from Cable &AMP; Wireless
to Qwest Communications. While WorldCom Chief Executive Bernard
Ebbers suggested that the Germans should be talking to him, their
initial interest seemed to be in Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   But after a fluttering of congressional concern about letting
Sprint be bought by a European carrier that is still more than
half-owned by its government, Deutsche Telekom has apparently
shifted its attentions to deals. The company has reportedly bid
more than $40 billion for wireless provider VoiceStream, while
considering a parallel bid for Qwest, which would provide a local
service presenceas well as Qwest's high-speed Internet lines. Those
acquisitions would presumably draw less regulatory fire than buying
Sprint. But for BellSouth to rekindle its romance with Sprint, it
would have to rewrite its deal to combine wireless units with SBC
Communications, presumably by selling out.
</P>
<P>
   Would that make sense? Together with SBC, BellSouth will have
the nation's second-largest wireless business, but not the national
reach or brand name of Sprint. Compared to a massive purchase of
Sprint, the SBC agreement will cost little to get started but would
need increasing investment to build a network or buy more licenses.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth too has pondered a purchase of Qwest, in which it
already has invested $3.5 billion, giving it less than 5 percent of
the company.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing against a play for either Qwest or Sprint is the
continuing ban on a BellSouth offering long-distance in its
nine-state region. Detours around that hurdle can be found, but
they do make an already costly deal a bit more complex.
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom's purchase of Sprint was valued between $115 billion
and $156 billion, depending on the fluctuating stock prices of the
companies. For months, the huge merger seemed bound for approval
while regulators gave the nod to a string of big-ticket mergers.
True, the Federal Communications Commission of late had started to
impose conditions _ as on AT&AMP;T's acquisition of MediaOne _ but the
government showed no signs of calling a halt to the march of
consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   But last month the Justice Department sued to block
WorldCom-Sprint. Coming after the department had won at least the
first round of its legal case against Microsoft, the rejection
signaled a readiness to do antitrust battle that any potential
partners must at least take into account.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Ebbers slammed Attorney General Janet Reno and FCC
Chairman William Kennard as blocking innovation and hurting
competition for local service _ which WorldCom and Sprint had hoped
to offer using wireless technology.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the heart of WorldCom's longing for Sprint was wireless.
That market is surging and, with the much hyped new technologies,
could explode as phones become common connections to the Internet
and tools of electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom too would like to arrive by both air and land.
Its interest in VoiceStream is at least partly spurred by that
company's use of a technology known as GSM, which is also used
throughout Europe. Travelers on a Deutsche-VoiceStream network
could carry one phone and receive calls on both sides of the
Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   And that could be why West Point-based Powertel has jumped this
week. Because, with coverage in parts of 11 states, Powertel with
VoiceStream would form a national GSM network. Powertel stock shot
from $74.75 to $89.43 in two days, before drifting down to $84.81 a
share Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The end of WorldCom-Sprint didn't slow industry jockeying for
position.
</P>
<P>
   Because local service is seen as growing too slowly,
Bermuda-based Global Crossing this week announced plans to sell the
local service business that came with its purchase of Frontier
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   And the interconnections grow even without full-fledged mergers.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Dutch-based KPN Telecom _ another company in which
BellSouth has an investment _ announced plans to bid for wireless
licenses in Europe with Hong Kong-based Hutchison Whampoa and NTT
DoCoMo of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   And either Hutchison or NTT are cash-rich and ambitious enough
to be bidders for U.S. assets as well.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
