</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-WHITE-VAN-MAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WHITE VAN MAN OF ENGLAND: OH, HE'S A DEVIL! 
</HEADLINE>
  (Foreign Journal) 
(ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036.) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEATHERHEAD, England _ In his hands he has a wheel; in his ears,
rings; on his arms, tattoos; and in his heart, loathing for anyone
he sees through his windshield. He is known as White Van Man, and
he is identified in motorist surveys as the scourge of the
stressed-out British road.
</P>
<P>
   Once in the driver's seat, he considers red lights relative and
his own authority absolute. His vocabulary is the kind represented
in newspapers by asterisks, and the hand signals he uses to find
his way are the kind that tell everyone else to get lost.
</P>
<P>
   That, at least, is the popular caricature of the men who pilot
the estimated 2.5 million commercial vans every day around Britain,
a country with the most congested roads in Europe and probably
higher road rage than any country on the Continent.
</P>
<P>
   The Oxford-based Social Issues Research Center found that white
van men are viewed with the hostility and opprobrium Britons
previously reserved for the soccer hooligans who almost got England
disqualified from the European soccer championship last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Van drivers have taken on the mantle of what sociologists
refer to as `folk devils,' '' said Peter Marsh, the center's
director. ``Like other species of animal, he feels most confident
on his own turf, so a note of caution. When you obstruct the
passage of a white van, you are often preventing the driver
traveling freely on what he perceives to be his road.''
</P>
<P>
   White Van Man gets his name from his vehicle. Most vans in
Britain are white because that's the way they arrive from the
factory. Delivery services do not want the expense of painting
them, and their resale value is higher if they stay that color.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness to White Van Man, the world he inhabits is given to
aggravation. A study of 10,000 drivers in 16 European countries by
Gallup International showed that British motorists suffered from
intense road rage and were the first to resort to obscene gestures
to relieve pent-up anger.
</P>
<P>
   The main factor behind the prevalence of aggressive driving is
congestion. At any time, there are up to 24 million cars on the
road, and there is an average of 108 vehicles per mile, twice that
of France.
</P>
<P>
   A study by Britain's Automobile Association said that British
drivers faced longer commuting times, higher costs and bigger risks
of car crime than any of their European counterparts. They are also
the least likely to have acceptable public transportation or
cycling options. Investment in public transportation and roads
relative to the size of the economy is a third lower in Britain
than typical European levels, and 9 in 10 journeys in Britain are
made by car, the highest proportion in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Road repair also seems to take inordinate amounts of time. One
set of ``temporary'' emergency traffic barriers still stands along
an infamous stretch of highway at Barking Creek in East London
where they were installed in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Although Marsh found in his study that the white van drivers
were victims of negative stereotyping, he also discovered that they
did operate under their own tribal rules.
</P>
<P>
   He uncovered, for instance, White Van Man's standards for
permitting someone to cut ahead: black taxis: never; buses: very
rarely; women drivers: depends what they look like; other white van
drivers: always.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists may think the London cabdriver the world's politest,
but to Andrew Hall, 30, a four-year white van man from Leatherhead
in the London suburbs, ``they drive like they own the world.'' Even
more irritating are bicyclists. ``You hit a bicycle, you get the
blame, right?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hall was relaxing in The Running Horse pub after a nine-hour day
of delivery runs that took him 200 miles around southeast England.
</P>
<P>
   He protested the criticism of his class but admitted he
understood how it got started. ``I don't go through red lights, for
instance, but if it's, well, just going into red, I might slip
through,'' he said. ``And,'' he warned, ``I never stop on amber.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he avoided road arguments himself but that he had
seen colleagues ``in a bit of a right row many times, especially at
the traffic lights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally at the lights,'' he said, ``that's where the verbals
start.''
</P>
<P>
   Marsh said he was not surprised to find that white van men think
they are good drivers because, he said, all men do. ``Previous SIRC
research has shown that for 75 percent of male drivers, to admit
that you are a bad driver is a bit like confessing that you are
lousy in bed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   New gasoline price increases that have taken the price of
filling up a van to $80 have become a big issue in Britain, and
what car you drive has become a defining point in British politics.
The two leading parties are fighting for the votes of the middle
Englander, an everyman character often identified in the press as
Mondeo man, after the midrange Ford model with that name. When
Conservative officials made their first moves last year to recover
the middle-class voters who deserted the party for Labor in the
1997 election, one of the first things they did was try to buy the
membership lists of the Royal Automobile Club and the Automobile
Association.
</P>
<P>
   With a national election widely considered to be less than a
year away, White Van Man may finally start getting some respect.
The ardently populist Sun, Britain's largest selling daily tabloid,
has created a question and answer column with a new driver each
week. In a typical submission, Jamie Valler, 32, of
Newcastle-Upon-Tyne, said: ``In the past we've been stereotyped as
nutters on the road. But now the nation can see most of us have
sensible opinions.''
</P>
<P>
   The column is promoted as ``the authentic voice of the street,
the real views of real people, the opinions of people who vote
rather than those who get elected, the views of people who pay
taxes and bills rather than just pontificate on them.''
</P>
<P>
   People claiming those credentials are going to get a lot of
attention from politicians. Shortly after the debut of the feature,
another contributor, Simon Todd, 43, of Gillingham, Kent, found
himself not only no longer maligned. He and his white van were
invited to have pictures taken with government officials in front
of 10 Downing Street.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
