<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPISCOPAL-GAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPISCOPAL CHURCH RECOGNIZES UNMARRIED AND SAME SEX RELATIONSHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Ill.)   By GUSTAV NIEBUHR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Leaders of the Episcopal Church reached agreement
Thursday on an unusual resolution about human sexuality, in which
the church officially acknowledged that its parishioners include
unmarried couples living in long-term relationships and that those
relationships are worthy of pastoral care.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution makes no distinction between heterosexual and
homosexual relationships, but the discussion among church leaders
focused almost entirely on its use in acknowledging long-term
relationships among gay and lesbian Episcopalians.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution, approved by the church's bishops in a lopsided
vote of 119-19, with four bishops abstaining, said that the church
``expects'' long-term relationships among unmarried couples to be
monogamous and characterized by ``mutual affection and respect.''
It condemns promiscuity and, in a clause cited by some bishops who
spoke warily of the broader resolution, notes the church's
traditional teaching on the sanctity of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the resolution was approved by clergy and lay
representatives at the denomination's General Convention, its top
policy-making body, whose meeting at the Denver Convention Center
ends Friday. The convention, which meets every three years, is
divided into two chambers, a House of Deputies, with clergy and lay
people, and a House of Bishops. For any measure to become church
law or policy, it must be approved by both houses.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the bishops approved the resolution on sexuality, a
new debate erupted among clergy and lay people concerning an older
issue, the ordination of women as priests.
</P>
<P>
   The topic specifically addressed the reluctance of two of the
church's 106 dioceses, its regional jurisdictions, to perform such
ordinations. Episcopalians began ordaining women in the 1970s, but
some dioceses did not do so for years. In the mid-1990s, impatient
with the slowness of a few hold-outs to change, the convention
approved a law that no diocese could refuse to ordain a candidate
for the priesthood on the basis of gender.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the dioceses of Fort Worth, Texas, and Quincy, Ill., have
not ordained women, prompting a majority of clergy and lay
representatives at the convention to pass a resolution this morning
that would set up a task force to ``assist'' the two dioceses _ as
well as the Diocese of San Joaquin in California, which only
recently began ordaining women _ in complying with the church law.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the vote totals were announced, about a dozen
members of the Fort Worth and Quincy dioceses rose from their seats
in the convention hall and joined hands for a moment of silent
prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards, the Rev. Charles Hough 3d, a Fort Worth priest, said
he objected to the resolution's intention, on the grounds that
opponents of women's ordination were ``being asked to deny what we
believe.'' Another Fort Worth priest, the Rev. Ryan Reed, said he
and others based their beliefs about restricting the priesthood to
only men on their understanding of Scripture and the example of
Jesus calling only men as disciples.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, other priests from the Fort Worth and Quincy
dioceses noted that several churches of the Anglican Communion _
the global association of church bodies that trace their roots to
the Church of England and to which the Episcopal Church belongs _
do not ordain women as priests.
</P>
<P>
   But Katie Sherrod, a Fort Worth resident and member of the
Episcopal Women's Caucus, a group that supports women's ordination,
said that the diocese's stand was having a negative impact on some
Episcopalians there. The reluctance of the diocese to embrace woman
as priests, she said, had led some couples to be married in other
denominations and some families not to have their daughters
confirmed in the Episcopal Church. ``I do feel we need the ministry
of female priests in our diocese,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
