<DOCNO> NYT20000713.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1391 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-TEACHER-SHORTAGE0714-     07-13 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-SHORTAGE0714-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Urban teacher exodus linked to housing costsBy Gaiutra Bahadur
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The connection is clear to Velma Wilson,
principal of an East Austin school that has lost more than a tenth
of its teachers in four years to the city's high housing prices.
</P>
<P>
   Austin vies for some of the same trophies as one of its tech
sisters, San Francisco _ ``Best City to Do Business'' or ``Most
Livable City.'' And it mimics nearby Silicon Valley _ down to a
skyrocketing cost of living that has made it even harder to find
teachers in an already scarce national market.
</P>
<P>
   To cope, several of the California school districts have gone
into the real estate business. They are building apartment
complexes for their teachers.
</P>
<P>
   If Austin mirrors their problem, Wilson reasons, then why not
also copy their attempt at a solution?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an idea worth exploring,'' she said _ along with other
strategies, like lobbying City Hall to offer tax abatements to
landlords who give discounts to teachers or directly negotiating
reduced rents with apartment complex owners.
</P>
<P>
   At this stage, Wilson and the district's recruiters are just
brainstorming. While it is not clear how attainable some of their
plans are, it is clear that housing costs contribute to problems
recruiting and retaining teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Since Wilson arrived at Barbara Jordan Elementary School in
1996, at least five of her 38 teachers have left, saying they could
not afford to live in the hub of Silicon Hills. Others moonlight or
live ``doubled-up'' in one-bedroom apartments.
</P>
<P>
   And as vice president of the Austin Area Alliance of Black
School Educators, an organization that recruits across the country,
Wilson discovered that the city is a tough sell to teachers just
out of college or trying to raise families. Applicants often choose
districts with a more accessible housing market, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big question for anybody who is moving is 'Where am I
going to live and how am I going to pay the rent?''' Wilson said.
``I'm sure that when Dell or Motorola fly people in, they get them
established. It's just part and parcel of big business. If we could
just pattern our recruiting efforts after them . . .''
</P>
<P>
   The Austin Independent School District agrees that affordable
housing is key.
</P>
<P>
   But financial hardships next year, such as the anticipated loss
of $35 million due to the state's share-the-wealth law and modest
pay raises to staff and teachers, make the prospects of a foray
into the landlord business look dim.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got our hands full right now just building enough
schools to accommodate the growth,'' said Andy Welch, a spokesman
for the district.
</P>
<P>
   And not everyone thinks that the smattering of districts
nationwide constructing housing _ San Jose, Santa Clara, San
Francisco and Aspen _ are following the best path to allay the
estimated shortage of about 200,000 teachers every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're grateful for anything done to attract teachers,'' said
John Cole, president of the Texas Federation of Teachers. ``But the
solution to the problem is not to build 'teacher-ages,' like
orphanages. It might attract some young people for a very short
time. But as a long-term strategy, it's not going to work.''
</P>
<P>
   The key, he said, is to pay salaries that would allow teachers
to buy homes and raise families. That's especially important in
Texas _ with its demand of about 41,000 teachers and its average
wages ranked 37th in the country, according to a 1999 American
Federation of Teachers report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Austin was the place to teach in the 1980s,'' said Louis
Malfaro, co-president of the union. ``Austin schools had the luxury
of hiring people who had some experience. Now the opposite is
occurring. We've started to lose teachers to the other districts.''
Other districts are ``actively recruiting Austin teachers, and I
think Austin teachers are actively wanting to leave,'' said David
Buffington, a former Dobie Middle School instructor. Of 35 people
at an orientation for new Round Rock teachers this spring,
including Buffington, he estimated that about 80 percent were from
AISD.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors contribute to the exodus to other districts.
</P>
<P>
   For some, once they have moved outside the city to escape high
housing costs, traffic makes commuting unappealing. Others, like
Buffington, leave because of the frustrations of working in an
urban school.
</P>
<P>
   He won't have to move when he starts his new job. Buffington and
his wife, also a former Austin teacher, live so far along the
northern periphery of the city that they pay Round Rock taxes.
Their two incomes just about sustain their $925 a month,
two-bedroom house in the Wells Branch area.
</P>
<P>
   But for others, rising real estate costs loom larger.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Austin Board of Realtors, the median price of a
house in the Austin area is $212,052 _ outside the range of a
family with no debt earning the city's median income of $23,770.
</P>
<P>
   For Bruce Hays, a special education teacher at Charles Akins
High School, that figure is daunting.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one reason he hasn't moved to a surrounding
district yet. Since he is legally blind, he can't drive and worries
about access to public transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Living outside city limits is not really an option for me,''
he said. ``It's becoming a concern, as property values are rising
out of control. I'm kind of losing the dream of being able to
afford a house within city limits.''
</P>
<P>
   Hays already gets a 5 percent, or $30, discount on his rent at
Tanglewood Forest Apartments, one of several complexes in the city
that offer slightly reduced rates to those who work for major
employers in their vicinity.
</P>
<P>
   The complex offers the discount of its own initiative, but
school districts in other cities have formally negotiated housing
breaks.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, for example, the school district has brokered 3
percent to 5 percent discounts on rent and 50 percent to 100
percent breaks on security deposits. Its employees also get lower
mortgage rates through lending companies and rebates from real
estate companies when they buy or sell a home.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Veselka, an HISD deputy superintendent for human resources,
said the decade-old program gave the district a competitive edge as
cities across the country try to woo from the same applicant pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to do something for them to help (new teachers) get
established in the city,'' he said. ``Many just graduated from
college, never had a job before and are coming to city of Houston
from more rural parts of the country. For many, it's their first
time away from home.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
