<HEADER>
A1393 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ABOUT-CARS-SUBARU-ART     07-13 1367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-SUBARU-ART-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBARU OUTBACK: NEW ALL OVER AND DOWN UNDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, July 16) 
 By BOB KNOLL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone who has watched network television in the last few years
has seen Crocodile Dundee (i.e., Paul Hogan) tearing through desert
and swamp in the ``world's first sport utility wagon,'' the
all-wheel-drive Subaru Outback. But those with an interest in auto
history will recall a few other wagons that also offered all-wheel
drive and could have made a case for an SUV label: The 1988-91
Dodge Colt Vista, the 1992-94 Mitsubishi Expo LRV, the 1988 Nissan
Stanza and the 1990 Nissan Axxess.
</P>
<P>
   None of those are around today, perhaps because they failed to
capitalize on the rising trend, perhaps because they were not very
good. The auto industry is replete with successes and failures, of
cars that caught fads on the rise and others that arrived during
the descent.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that Subaru had the timing right with its
Outback, which arrived as a trim package for the 1995 Legacy wagon.
Since then, the Outback gained higher ground clearance and a raised
roofline to set it apart, and it spawned a whole series of models,
including a fancy Outback Limited. Last year, Legacy Outbacks _
which are nearly identical, mechanically, to other, less expensive
models _ accounted for 39 percent of all Subaru sales and 69
percent of Legacy production. Subaru's full line of wagons has been
first in wagon sales in the United States for three years.
</P>
<P>
   The Legacy/Outback wagon underwent few changes from 1996 to
1999, though an Outback sedan arrived for 1999. For the current
model year, Subaru performed a major redesign for the Legacy and
the Outback (which no longer carries the Legacy name).
</P>
<P>
   The new body is smoother, rounder and about 3 inches longer,
with a slightly longer wheelbase. But those familiar with the
previous model will have no trouble recognizing the Outback wagon,
since most of its visual cues have been kept, including the
slightly raised roof and large fog lamps. The engine remains a flat
four cylinder _ known as a ``boxer,'' for the way its pistons flail
outward, rather than move up and down _ but it has been redesigned
for more low-end torque and better fuel economy. Cars with
automatic transmissions have a slightly different all-wheel-drive
system than those with stick shifts, but drivers will not notice
any difference in their smooth function.
</P>
<P>
   The front suspension is largely unchanged, but the rear
suspension is a new multilink design that reduces the intrusion
into the cargo area. The result is not only better ride and
handling, but a cargo floor that is 5.2 inches wider and
significantly more useful. There are disk brakes on all four wheels
and an antilock system.
</P>
<P>
   Safety improvements include three-point seatbelts for all five
occupants and child-safety-seat anchors for all three rear-seat
positions. The Outback (except for the Limited, which comes with
leather upholstery) offers as a $200 option a folding, integrated
child seat in the center rear position.
</P>
<P>
   The front safety belts incorporate pretensioners to better
position the occupant during a crash and force limiters that work
in conjunction with the front airbags to limit loads on the chest.
The Outback Limited has front seat side-impact air bags in the
upper portion of the front seat backs. The body structure has been
designed to dissipate energy better in front, side and rear
crashes.
</P>
<P>
   This new design seems to have paid off. The Insurance Institute
for Highway Safety has given the Legacy wagon a good rating and
calls it a ``best pick'' for its performance in an offset-front
crash test at 40 miles an hour _ a severe test of the body
structure. Few automobiles in this class have received such a high
rating.
</P>
<P>
   In front- and side-impact tests by the National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration, a Legacy sedan received four stars for the
driver and passenger in the front crash. In side-crash tests, the
Legacy got four stars for driver safety and five, the top rating,
for rear passengers. The tested car did not have side air bags,
which might have improved the driver rating.
</P>
<P>
   In these days of extreme popularity for truck-based sport
utilities, it is worth noting that the Outback is certified as a
passenger car. Other manufacturers are classifying car-based SUV's
as trucks to take advantage of less stringent regulations on the
safety and emissions of light trucks. This means that the Outback
has complied with the full set of Federal safety and emissions
regulations, in contrast to vehicles like the Lexus RX 300, the
Honda CR-V and the BMW X5, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with previous Outbacks I have driven, and a 1996 model
that my wife owns, the 2000 model is a step up in ride quality,
interior noise, and steering and handling. The wagon feels more
``European'' in its control over challenging roads and in its
precise, nicely weighted steering. Braking is smooth and sure,
although there is a bit more free play in the pedal than I would
like. The annoying throbbing sound of the 2.5-liter engine has been
all but eliminated, and wind noise is fairly low.
</P>
<P>
   Powerful engine response has never been a Subaru virtue. It
still is not, but the new engine has more low- and midrange torque
so that at less than full throttle it feels fairly strong. One
unfortunate result: The wagon moves out almost too abruptly on
takeoff from a stop.
</P>
<P>
   In October, there will be two additional 2001-model Outbacks:
The H6-VDC and the H6-3.0 L.L. Bean Edition. These cars will have
an all-new 3-liter six-cylinder engine _ the only six Subaru has
offered in this country since the sporty SVX coupe was discontinued
in 1996. The L.L. Bean model will wear the logo of the mail-order
company inside and out.
</P>
<P>
   As one who has driven many thousand miles in Subarus, I am
always impressed by the completely seamless action of their
all-wheel drive. Many manufacturers claim that their SUV's have
all-wheel drive that reacts instantly when a wheel loses grip, but
in reality they delay, stutter and bump as they compensate for this
loss of traction.
</P>
<P>
   Those drivers who intend to take their vehicles into challenging
four-wheel drive territory will find that the lack of special
low-range gearing and relatively soft suspension do not equip the
Outback for this kind of duty. Subaru says that the Outback is
capable of recreational off-roading, and with its generous
7.3-inches of ground clearance and large tires, that claim seems
fair. But the main advantage of a seamless all-wheel drive system
comes in the smooth response on dry pavement and the increased
security in foul weather, rain or moderate snow.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Outback, consumers looking for a user-friendly
instrument panel and control layout will like what they see. Owners
of previous Legacys who have cursed the awkward cup holder will
feel much better about the new one. Window and lock switches, wiper
and light stalks are simple and easy to use. The Limited model
includes heated front seats with leather seating surfaces. The
Limited also has two power moonroofs, one over the front seat and
one forward of the rear seat. Their operation is rather strange in
that the front one doesn't slide; it only tilts. And although the
rear one slides open, it won't move unless the front one is tilted.
One wonders what the advantage of this curious arrangement may be.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers looking for the safety and security of all-wheel drive,
and who would not be happy with a cruder, truck-based sport utility
have a number of very good station wagons to choose from. Subaru
has the lowest-priced wagon in this category, the $20,000 Outback
Sport _ based on the smaller Impreza, not on the Legacy. The Sport,
however, cannot match the size and comfort of wagons in the $25,000
to $30,000 group.
</P>
<P>
   There, the regular Legacy-based Outback, the Volkswagen Passat
4Motion and the Audi A4 Avant Quattro are attractive,
good-performing wagons. Once the price jumps above $30,000, it goes
quickly to $40,000, where the Audi A6 Avant and the Volvo Cross
Country compete. Another $10,000 puts you into Mercedes territory.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
