<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPR-MERGER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPR, ANADARKO STOCKHOLDERS VOTE FOR MERGER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By DAN PILLER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Shareholders of Union Pacific Resources
Group Inc. on Thursday voted to sell their company to Anadarko
Petroleum Corp. of Houston for about $8.2 billion in stock and
debt, finalizing a deal that will move Fort Worth's biggest energy
company to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The shareholder vote ended the independent existence of a
company that moved to Fort Worth from Enid, Okla., in 1954, when it
was known as Champlin Oil Co. Just 40 shareholders turned up for
the meeting at the Fort Worth Club, and none asked Chairman George
Lindahl any questions during the 20-minute session.
</P>
<P>
   Lindahl estimated that about 300 of UPR's 802 local employees
will transfer to Houston to work for Anadarko, starting this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   The final tally showed 78 percent of UPR's stock voting in favor
of the merger. In Houston, 93 percent of the stock represented at a
special Anadarko meeting voted in favor of buying UPR.
</P>
<P>
   UPR shareholders will receive 0.45 shares of Anadarko stock for
each of the 252 million common shares. The deal will solidify
Anadarko's position as the nation's top independent oil and gas
driller.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction will end up a little richer for UPR shareholders
since when .MDBO/.MDNM/it was announced in early April. At that
time, the $35 per share trading price of Anadarko stock would have
given each UPR share a value of $16.
</P>
<P>
   But Anadarko's stock has moved up with other energy stocks,
boosted by $4 natural gas and $30 per barrel crude oil. With
Anadarko closing yesterday at $47.43 a share, the exchange will be
worth about $21.58 for each UPR share.
</P>
<P>
   The price will be set with today's closing price for Anadarko
stock. Anadarko will also assume $2.8 billion of UPR debt.
</P>
<P>
   The merger will create a company with drilling assets about
evenly divided between crude oil and natural gas. Anadarko's
reserves are concentrated in the Hugoton Embayment of Kansas and
Oklahoma, plus reserves in east and west Texas, Alaska and the Gulf
of Mexico as well as some projects in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   UPR drills in the Austin Chalk Field of South Texas, as well as
on old land grants from the Union Pacific Railroad in Colorado and
Wyoming, western Canada and South America. UPR spun off from its
railroading parent, Union Pacific Corp., in 1995. Its stock has
been listed on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Lindahl said that 535 of UPR's employees at the Fort Worth
headquarters were offered jobs in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not all have accepted and the deadlines for acceptance haven't
passed, so I would guess that about 300 of the workers probably
will relocate,'' said Lindahl. He said transfers will include
workers from all disciplines, ranging from clerks to geophysicists,
geologists and information service workers.
</P>
<P>
   All UPR headquarters employees, including those transferring,
will receive severance of two months' pay plus three weeks pay for
each year served up to two years. Terminated employees will receive
their severance in a lump sum. The tranferees will receive half of
the severance this year and the remainder in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The transfers will begin later next month and be concluded by
the first quarter of next year, Lindahl said. Anadarko will take
over UPR's lease of the top 23 floors of UPR Plaza, covering
525,000 square feet. The glass skyscraper was one of several
downtown buildings damaged in the March tornado.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anadarko will be responsible for the last eight years of our
lease, but there are already a couple of good local prospects who
have indicated interest in the space,'' said Lindahl.
</P>
<P>
   The 54-year-old Lindahl, who became chief executive of Union
Pacific Resources a year ago this month with the abrupt resignation
of former chairman Jack Messman, will be among those relocating to
Houston. He will become vice-chairman of Anadarko, serving under
.MDBO/C.MDNM/hairman Robert Allison.
</P>
<P>
   Lindahl said that he will be responsible for Canada, Latin
America and new acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, the vice-chairman isn't given anything to do,
but I have specific line responsibilities,'' said Lindahl, who
received a three-year employment contract.
</P>
<P>
   Lindahl said that 30 UPR executives were offered positions with
Anadarko, but only nine opted to join the company. Of UPR's seven
senior executive vice presidents, only Lindahl and Donald Niemiec
will sign on with Anadarko.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not too surprised, given that our executives had stock
options and the severance, and also that with good crude oil and
natural gas prices right now, this is a pretty good time to go out
into other areas of the business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Anadarko's nine-member board will be enlarged to 15 to
accommodate five of UPR's 12 directors. Lindahl said the identities
of the other UPR directors who will be added to the Anadarko board
will be determined at an Anadarko board meeting July 31.
</P>
<P>
   Lindahl said that in addition to fulfilling its lease
obligations for the headquarters building that Anadarko will honor
UPR's civic commitments, which include financial contributions to
the Bass Performance Hall, the National Cowgirl Museum, the Fort
Worth Public Library, the Summerbridge reading program and the
Tarrant Area Food Bank.
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
