<HEADER>
A1396 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BARTON-ANNIV0714-COX     07-13 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARTON-ANNIV0714-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nine suits sparked by Atlanta massacre
 &HT;    By Jim Dyer and Stacy Shelton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With the one-year anniversary of Mark O. Barton's
shooting rampage in Atlanta 15 days away, the number of lawsuits
stemming from the massacre has climbed to nine.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits, which were consolidated by Fulton County State
Court Judge Susan B. Forsling, do not represent all of the victims
of the July 29 shooting spree, which left nine people dead and 13
wounded. But more parties likely will join in, said Jan Cohen, an
attorney at Weinstock &AMP; Scavo, which represents seven of the
plaintiffs. He expects at least one more of the victims to join the
lawsuit. Another Atlanta law firm, Kilpatrick &AMP; Stockton,
represents the other two plaintiffs. The statute of limitations on
such lawsuits expires two years after the incident.
</P>
<P>
   One of the plaintiffs, Dr. Gulshan Harjee, hopes legal action
will prevent future tragedies. She says the brokerage firm where
her husband, Dean Delawalla, was killed could have done more.
``What makes me so frustrated is we could have prevented this whole
thing,'' said Harjee, an internist at DeKalb Medical Center. ``I
hope this increases the awareness of keeping our environments
safe.''
</P>
<P>
   But beyond better security in the offices, she said, day trading
needs to be better regulated.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain things between the lines, in the fine print,
that need to be clarified,'' she said. ``Legislation needs to come
in place for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Although some of the specifics of each lawsuit differ, each
maintains that the securities firms frequented by Barton could have
prevented the multiple killings if employees had more carefully
scrutinized their traders, especially Barton, who had suffered
major losses in the high-stakes trading.
</P>
<P>
   The suits claim that the two security firms _ All-Tech
Investment and Momentum Securities _ should have known the
``potentially dangerous conditions'' contained on the premises and
should have taken ``reasonable precautions'' to protect the people
in the office complex from reasonably foreseeable criminal acts by
a third person.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Houtkin, All-Tech's chief executive officer, said he was
not surprised when the first of the lawsuits was filed last August.
``This is a tragedy, but in today's litigious society, I expected
this to happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other defendants named in the suit are Barton Protective
Services, which supplied building security; Jones Lang LaSalle
Americas, which manages and leases one of the buildings where the
shootings occurred; and the Piedmont Office Center, a complex of 11
buildings where All-Tech's offices are located. All of the other
defendants have declined to comment. The plaintiffs, who are
seeking unspecified compensatory and punitive damages, also are
suing Barton's estate.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
