<HEADLINE>
EARNING REPORTS PROMPT TECHNOLOGY BUYING SPREE, DRIVING NASDAQ
HIGHER 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Strong quarterly reports from several companies
touched off fresh buying in technology stocks Thursday, lifting the
Nasdaq composite index to a second consecutive solid gain as the
rest of the market mostly languished.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq, which climbed 75.27 points, or 1.8 percent, to
4,174.86, moved more solidly into positive territory for the year.
With a gain of 2.6 percent, it has now outperformed the broader
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, which is up 1.8 percent this
year. Nasdaq has surged 31.9 percent since May 23, when its
springtime plunge _ a drop of 37.3 percent from its March peak _
hit bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The earnings announcements are giving people confidence'' that
Internet and other high-technology companies will sustain profit
growth, said Michael Jamison, managing director at Brandywine Asset
Management in Wilmington, Del.
</P>
<P>
   Ariba, for example, jumped 27 11/16, to 131 3/16, after issuing
its quarterly report, and Applied Micro Circuits, which reported
late Wednesday, added 28 1/16, to 153 1/2. Motorola, a New York
Stock Exchange company that also posted results on Wednesday,
gained 3}, to 39\, as the second most actively traded stock of the
day, after Cisco Systems, which rose 1], to 65\.
</P>
<P>
   But there was little enthusiasm for other than technology
shares.
</P>
<P>
   The S &AMP; P 500 rose 2.92 points, or 0.2 percent, to 1,495.84. The
biggest upward force was WorldCom, which rose 3 7/16, to 47 15/16,
after its merger with Sprint was officially ended. Pfizer was the
biggest drag, falling 1 7/8, to 46 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average edged up 5.30 points, or 0.05
percent, to 10,788.71, its fifth consecutive rise, but is still
down 6.16 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Drug stocks were battered again as Washington appeared to move
closer to adding prescriptions to Medicare coverage. Investors fear
that will bring price limitations.
</P>
<P>
   Schering-Plough and Merck each lost more than 4 points, and
Bristol-Myers Squibb dropped more than 3.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were also bracing for government reports Friday on
producer prices, retail sales and industrial output for June and
for the initial July reading on consumer sentiment by the
University of Michigan. Evidence that the pace of inflation has
become more than a creep or that the economy is not slowing
markedly would undermine a widely held assumption that the Federal
Reserve's yearlong raising of short-term interest is near an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conclusion that most people have is that the Fed is
finished,'' said Robert Bloom, president of Friends, Ivory &AMP; Sime,
a money manager. But he said he disagreed, citing, among other
things, a still-taut job market in which job growth is slowing
because the pool of potential workers is drying up, not because
demand for them has slackened.
</P>
</TEXT>
