<HEADLINE>
`BROTHERS AND SISTERS': A STORY THAT FLIES LIKE GOSSIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes at end of review) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The thick, wet aroma yanks at the nostrils, a scent
to warm the heart of any meat lover. At that point you have been
hearing rhapsodies about food from hungry people for so long that
you may well think you have imagined it. After all, plays don't
usually smell, except metaphorically.
</P>
<P>
   But no, that seems to be real boiled beef being dished out in
the Maly Theater's robust two-part production of ``Brothers and
Sisters,'' which runs through this weekend at the John Jay College
Theater as part of Lincoln Center Festival 2000. Your disbelief at
this sudden olfactory invasion is mirrored in the faces of the
actors onstage, whose expressions are those of people afraid to
wake up from a wonderful, improbable dream.
</P>
<P>
   None of the five senses feel safe from assault in ``Brothers and
Sisters,'' adapted from a trilogy known as ``The Prysalins,'' by
the Russian novelist Fyodor Abramov. The scene just described
portrays a rare celebratory feast in a postwar Soviet village, and
it has been arranged for a cow on the collective farm to have an
accident. Those gristly, gray hunks of meat may not be pretty, but
it's hard not to taste them vicariously or to be transported by
gratitude, even if you're a vegetarian.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of appetite looms large during the more than six
hours of this tale of hope and privation in the land of Stalin,
which has been staged by the Maly's fabled artistic director, Lev
Dodin, and was first seen in Moscow 15 years ago. Appetite is the
central word in a ribald joke told early in the play by one naked
young man to another in a sauna; it is also what keeps the play's
portrait of unending hardship from seeming arid or depressing.
</P>
<P>
   Hunger of many varieties is painful and destructive here, but
the urge to satisfy it comes across as bracingly dynamic. It whets
the senses instead of numbing them, suggesting that the pleasures
of the flesh are never more appreciated than in their absence. The
image of a perfectly formed loaf of bread assumes, in this context,
a voluptuousness you would never have thought possible.
</P>
<P>
   The 36 Maly performers, most of whom have been with the
production since its inception and performed it in more than a
dozen other countries, have that second-skin connection with their
roles that is born of long association. More surprisingly, their
fervor is that of actors who have just discovered the hidden keys
to their parts.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a densely textured, overwhelmingly physical
production that has the hypnotic hold of a fat, fine historical
novel. Not that the literary merits of the text _ spoken in Russian
with projected English supertitles _ gleam on their own. Simply to
quote from the script, adapted from Abramov's novel by Dodin,
Sergei Bekhterev and Arkady Katsman, is not to do the play any
favors.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the dialogue, to American ears, verges on a parody of
the dark gray Russian angst of Dostoyevsky and Chekhov. The
evening's early scenes feature characters remarking that spring
feels ``worn out,'' that even the birds sound weary. And here is a
typical lament wailed toward the drama's end: ``Why do we waste our
lives and constantly deprive ourselves of happiness?''
</P>
<P>
   You might also reasonably wonder just how much excitement can be
mined from heated discussions of party policy on the distribution
of grain, the subject of much of the play's second half.
</P>
<P>
   This, however, is to ignore the purely theatrical engine that
gives the production its locomotive strength. Dodin has a sure and
powerful sense of both narrative momentum and the grand,
goose-bump-inspiring set piece. (Had the Maly company under Dodin
been responsible for Stalin's propaganda films, Soviet history
might read differently.)
</P>
<P>
   And playing characters who might seem like stick figures on the
page, the Maly actors provide compelling emotional detail. Every
face is stamped with a deeply individual response to a shared
history, and you are unlikely to mistake one of the work's 40-odd
characters for another.
</P>
<P>
   That this production has now assumed a legendary quality has
something to do with the timing of its birth. Its opening in March
1985, on the eve of Mikhail Gorbachev's coming to power, made it a
talismanic work for many Russians, a preface to glasnost.
</P>
<P>
   That association has caused some critics (including a reviewer
for a Moscow paper who sat next to me the other night) to argue
that ``Brothers'' is dated now, a relic of the so-called Socialist
Realism to which the play would seem to subscribe even as it
subverts it.
</P>
<P>
   But that is to deny the work's fierce pull as a piece of
storytelling and its crafty manipulation of the appeal of being
involved with other lives that makes gossips of us all. Indeed, in
its compelling anatomies of alliances and betrayals in a tight-knit
community where everyone is closely watched, ``Brothers'' can be
savored as a sort of collective farm version of ``Peyton Place.''
You simply want to know what happens to everyone next.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
