<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Small minority not earger to surf the Net
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Go ahead, ask for their e-mail addresses. They'll just shrug
their shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Start yakking about the oh-so-funky Website you just bookmarked,
and you'll get a blank stare.
</P>
<P>
   Wondering how fast their modems are? Don't bother.
</P>
<P>
   While a recent AJC poll showed that 70 percent of metro
Atlantans own a home computer, and 68 percent use the Internet,
some people aren't surfing the Net. They're swimming against the
tide.
</P>
<P>
   Some are technophobes who can't cope with modern gadgetry.
Others are stuck on the far side of the ``digital divide,'' people
who can't afford a computer and don't have access to one at school
or work.
</P>
<P>
   But there's another group who says their decision to stay
off-line is not technical or financial, it's strictly a personal
choice.
</P>
<P>
   They are the few. They are the proud. They are the not-coms.
</P>
<P>
   We asked several members of this shrinking subspecies to explain
why they have chosen to live outside the Net:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  LYNN GREENWAY
</P>
<P>
   Age: 26
</P>
<P>
   Residence: Cartersville, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Occupation: Waitress
</P>
<P>
   Quote: Everything you hear these days is `www this and that.' I
just want to go `blah, blah, blah.' I just have too much to do. At
night I'm working, and during the day I'm busy taking care of kids.
During the school year, I'm doing school stuff. I'm sure if I was
online I could find something that would interest me, but I like to
read books. And I'm afraid that if I started, I'd get sucked into
it. I'll admit it's weird sometimes. It seems like everybody is on
it except me. My friends are always on me, ragging me about not
having e-mail. I hang out with two other moms whose kids go to
preschool and they use the Internet to find places for our kids to
play. It's irritating sometimes, and I just roll my eyes. I guess
it's just who I am. I don't have the patience for it. I worry
sometime I'm going to wake up 15 years from know and realize all
the stuff I missed. But right now, I have other things to worry
about.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  EARNEST PICKELSIMER
</P>
<P>
   Age: 53
</P>
<P>
   Residence: Cumming, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Occupation: Electrician
</P>
<P>
   Quote: I've thought about buying a computer and going on the
Internet. But most of the people I need to talk to, I can
communicate with them over the phone. All the information I
require, I can go to the library. I read a lot of newspapers and
magazines. For me, reading information out of a book or magazine is
better because you don't have to keep scrolling up and down to get
to the next page. Trying to read something like that is just
nonsense. I don't believe in e-mail either. If I want to say
something to somebody, I want to see them in person, or at least
hear their voice. That way I know the information gets across, and
it's not accessible to anyone else. Anybody can hack into a
computer and find out anything about you. I think the Internet
gives people too much access into our private lives. They can find
your medical records or anything they want about you. I don't have
a problem with technology; I'm an electrician. I have a beeper and
a cell phone. I know anybody can tap into those, but when I'm using
the cell phone I'm extremely careful about what I say. If I used
the Internet, it would be too much of an invasion of privacy. I may
break down and buy a computer, but I still don't think I'll ever go
on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  LORNA KNIGHT
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Age: 30
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Residence: Conyers, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Occupation: Housekeeper
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quote: My husband and I discussed getting a computer. He's
heard terrible stories about how people have surfed the Internet on
some of those sex sites, and it has ruined their marriages. And
I've heard those stories too. My greatest concerns, really, are the
kids. I have three kids who are 6, 9 and 12. They use the Internet
at school, but I'm afraid if they're at home they'll get on some
chat line they shouldn't be getting into. I don't feel like there's
a good safeguard against that happening. We find other things to do
as a family to occupy our time. Sure, the kids have TVs and video
games, but we also make sure they spend a lot of time outside with
other kids. I just think that's healthier for them. Just about
every night we sit down and cook together and eat at the table. The
kids bug us sometimes about getting a computer, because most of
their friends have one. I tell them we don't need to have what
everybody else has.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  CHARLES LOUDERMILK SR.
</P>
<P>
   Age: 72
</P>
<P>
   Residence: Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Occupation: Chairman of Aaron Rents
</P>
<P>
   Quote: I don't have the time to surf the Net. I read the paper
every night and watch sports on TV and have some recreational
things like hunting and going to ball games. If we had more swings
on front porches where people visited each other like we used to,
you'd have a lot fewer psychologists. People used to visit after
supper, and talk about their problems until it was time to go to
bed. Those were great psychiatric times. People need to interact
with each other, not a computer monitor. I'm afraid the computer
age is coming in and eliminating family and relationships. You
can't get religion off a computer. You need to go to church and
hear a good sermon. We're online with our 500 stores and every
night we know what happened in that store the day before, and
that's invaluable. But I don't think it will replace the human
touch. When I visit stores, that's a real boost to employees.
That's the only way you can shake a person's hand and look them in
the eye. You can hide behind it all on a computer. I'm not
anti-technology at all, but I just have better things to do. I'm
not typist, for one thing, and at my age I'm not going to learn to
type anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Lyle V. Harris writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
