<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000713.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1401 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BROTHERS-THEATER-REVI     07-13 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROTHERS-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: everyone next.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The short and unsatisfactory answer to that question is
wholesale disillusionment. ``Brothers'' begins with the women of
Pekashino looking forward to the return of their men from World War
II and to an era in which, in a phrase repeated with increasing
dissonance, they will be able ``to eat their fill.'' Most of the
men never come back, however, and the postwar bureaucracy of
collective farming will keep the villagers hungry for many years to
come.
</P>
<P>
   Within this framework, the drama focuses on two central
characters: Mikhail Pryaslin (Pytor Semak), who was a boy when the
war began and has stayed behind, assuming a grown man's
responsibilities, and Anfisa Petrovna Minina (Tatyana Shestakova),
who has headed the collective farm during the war.
</P>
<P>
   The fortunes of these two are inescapably tied in with those of
the village. The play accordingly unfolds as a study in the
friction between public and private, between individual and
collective morality and responsibility. It is hard to think of a
director more expert, or successfully shameless, than Dodin in
manipulating these contrasts and in conveying the consuming pull of
the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   At moments, the production seems like an animated version of
those famous propaganda posters of the Stalin era, as smiling women
in babushkas toss grain in synchronized movement while singing. The
implicit optimism of such scenes is given the lie by other group
tableaus in which the cast stands frozen in grim postures of sorely
tested patience.
</P>
<P>
   The set designer, Eduard Kochergin, has created a world that
looks to have been hewn in rough wood, with a suspended, mobile
central wall of logs and an immense gate that opens to swing out
over the audience. These two basic elements, splendidly enhanced by
Oleg Kozlov's lighting, define every shift of scene, conjuring both
hard realities and air-borne fantasies, both claustrophobic
confinement and tantalizing openness.
</P>
<P>
   The sense of a visceral reality in which the audience is meant
to share is insisted upon throughout. Actors are often found in the
theater's aisles, bustling through with sheafs of twigs or armloads
of hay. (The hay is as evocatively aromatic, in its own way, as the
boiled beef.) We are, in effect, the larger village beyond their
meeting places, and when the political gatherings are held, we feel
uncomfortably implicit in the ways the crowd turns on its own.
</P>
<P>
   The sexually segregated group scenes are marvelous, especially
those in which the women without men sexually bait and tease one
another, eventually falling into one wriggling mass of giddiness.
Equally rousing are the drunken party scenes, in which ecstasy is
only a hair's breadth from abysmal despair.
</P>
<P>
   The great strength of the cast, as of so many good Russian
actors, is in its ability to convey both extremes of emotion at
once. This sensibility is fine-tuned with exquisite variations in
the more intimate scenes.
</P>
<P>
   One thinks especially of two brilliant, largely wordless
sequences centered on the return of Anfisa's first husband, Grigory
(Vladimir Artyomov), from the war, when the distribution of luxury
gifts assumes tragicomic dimensions. There is also the hauntingly
erotic moment in which horseplay between the widow Varvara (the
luscious Natalya Fomenko) and the young Mikhail turns serious.
</P>
<P>
   Shestakova, who has the waif-ish gravity of Giulietta Masina,
and the open-faced Semak provide affecting maps of instinctive
integrity worn down by circumstance. I also particularly enjoyed
Sergey Vlasov as Mikhail's ambitious, self-glamorizing friend, who
becomes a tractor-driving advertisement for the Communist Youth
League. And the honey-and-butter-skinned Fomenko, who suggests a
Slavic answer to Sophia Loren, gives the work an essential
sexuality that pervades the entire production like a brisk perfume.
</P>
<P>
   You will surely long remember the extraordinary imagistic use
that is made of bread. There is the loaf that Mikhail, freshly
returned from a logging camp, solemnly unwraps before his
awe-struck family, and the golden, seemingly self-replenishing
bread that figures in the heartbreaking fantasy sequence that
concludes the first evening.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the sacks of grain, representing months of labor
by the villagers, that are raised into the air, like effigies on a
floating temple, before disappearing. It is perhaps the cruelest
moment of dashed hopes in an evening that specializes in such
disappointments, a harbinger of another long season of near
starvation. You share in the villagers' sensations here. This is
definitely not to say that you leave this production hungry.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BROTHERS AND SISTERS'
</P>
<P>
   Part 1: Meetings and Partings
</P>
<P>
   Part 2: Roads and Crossroads
</P>
<P>
   By Lev Dodin, Sergei Bekhterev and Arkady Katsman, based on the
trilogy of novels by Fyodor Abramov; directed by Dodin; set by
Eduard Kochergin; associate directors, Roman Smirnov and Bekhterev;
costumes by Inna Gabai; speech and voice coach, Eugenia Kirillova;
lighting by Oleg Kozlov; technical director, Nikolai Murmanov. The
State Academic Maly Theater of St. Petersburg, Russia, Theatre de
l'Europe, presented by Lincoln Center Festival 2000. Performed in
Russian with English supertitles. At John Jay College Theater, 899
10th Avenue, at 59th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Natalya Akimova, Misha Arakcheyev, Vladimir Artyomov,
Sergei Bekhterev, Galina Filimonova, Natalya Fomenko, Svetlana
Gaitan, Lidiya Goryainova, Marina Gridasova, Svetlana Grigoryeva,
Igor Ivanov, Anatoly Kolibyanov, Arkady Koval, Sergei Kozyrev, Ilya
Kudriavtsev, Liya Kuzmina, Nikolai Lavrov, Sergei Muchenikov,
Kseniya Naumova, Irina Nikulina, Bronislava Proskurnina, Nadia
Radionycheva, Tanya Radionycheva, Tatyana Rasskazova, Mikhail
Samochko, Pyotr Semak, Alla Semenishina, Nina Semyonova, Tatyana
Shestakova, Vasili Skliar, Igor Sklyar, Nikita Slabodyanyuk, Yelena
Vasilyeva, Sergei Vlasov, Vladimir Zakharyev and Alexander
Zavialov. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
