<HEADER>
A1404 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BARTON-MEMORIAL0714-C     07-13 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARTON-MEMORIAL0714-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Service planned for nine killed last year in Atlanta
 &HT;    By Stacy Shelton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The worst part of the toughest year of her life has
been explaining to the children why their father was taken away so
suddenly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day is a trying day,'' Dr. Gulshan Harjee said quietly
while holding her baby daughter, wrapped in a Tigger blanket.
</P>
<P>
   Shahla, 4, is losing some memories of her father. But she
remembers he called her ``Cookie,'' and doesn't want anyone else to
use the pet name. When her mother tries, she's told ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Shahla's father _ Harjee's husband _ was one of 9 people killed
when Mark Barton went on a shooting spree through two Atlanta
offices last July 29. At 52, Dean Delawalla was weeks away from
moving his family into his dream house.
</P>
<P>
   Harjee hasn't been able to explain the senselessness of
Delawalla's death to Shahla or the couple's son, 16-year-old
Faisal. She can't explain it to herself. ``He was taken away from
us at such a critical time in our life and there has to be a reason
for it,'' said Harjee, an internist at DeKalb Medical Center. ``I
just keep searching.''
</P>
<P>
   Her search led her six months ago to begin planning a memorial
service for those killed and wounded in the bloody rampage. Their
family and friends share a deep grief, victims of the same moment's
violence that cut short lives and forever changed others.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for families to get together and see where we
are,'' Harjee said. ``I myself have had such a trying one year, and
I just don't know how other families are coping. We need to see how
we can help each other.''
</P>
<P>
   But she also realizes the massacre jolted the entire city.
That's why she asked one of the largest churches in the region to
host the gathering. The Cathedral of the Holy Spirit can hold 8,000
people. The service is set for 3 p.m. on July 30, a day after the
one-year anniversary of the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Harjee and the church leader, Bishop Earl Paulk, are planning a
non-denominational service with a reception to follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone is welcome,'' the bishop said Thursday. ``We all
experienced it, didn't we? We all felt the uneasiness of going to
work in a world that is so explosive. I hope in that service we can
give some new perspective on life itself.'' The service has the
support of Mayor Bill Campbell.``This memorial service is a
poignant reminder of the healing process Atlanta is still going
through,'' he said in a statement. `` I encourage all citizens to
attend this significant and moving event so that the spirt of
`triumph over tragedy' will continue to empower us to remain strong
and committed to creating more peaceful tomorrows.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Langford, the mayor's director of community affairs,
said memorial services serve as a reminder that violence should
never become part of daily life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our children must know that that's not a part of the norm and
it's not acceptable,'' Langford said. ``It's not to glorify what
happened but to pause and. . . make sure that a tragedy of this
magnitude never happens again.''
</P>
<P>
   When Harjee thinks about the year since her attorney husband was
killed , she believes violence has become all too common.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every single day there is still shooting,'' she said. ``After
all this suffering our families have gone through we ask `Has
anything changed?' and nothing has changed. Things are just going
on out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   She can only hope the memorial service will make a difference.
Exactly how, she's not sure. Her goals are to connect grieving
families and raise awareness about gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, she has questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will anything change afterwards? Does coming together help?
Will prayer help? That's all I found to help me cope is to
literally get on my knees and pray. The world can be so cruel out
there. I've found that is my best support.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
