<HEADER>
A1405 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FORD-NORRIS-COLUMN-NY     07-13 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-NORRIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD NEEDS A BETTER IDEA FOR GETTING CASH TO SHAREHOLDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Ford Motor Co. figures it has too much cash on its hands and
thinks its shares are undervalued. So it plans to distribute $10
billion to its owners.
</P>
<P>
   So far so good. If Ford were a normal company, it would simply
declare a special dividend or buy back a lot of shares. Instead, it
is undertaking a bizarrely complicated transaction that calls for
Ford to be acquired by another company, known as the Ford Value
Corp. Shareholders will get stock in the new company plus their
choice of $20 a share in cash or additional shares. Those who take
cash will get smaller dividend checks in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Why the machinations?
</P>
<P>
   They will allow the company to evade clauses in its certificate
of incorporation that would deprive the Ford family of its voting
control if family members sell too many shares. Right now, they
must own a bit over 5 percent of the company through Class B shares
to keep the right to have 40 percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
   That certificate bars a number of tactics that might be used to
let the Fords keep their votes while reducing their economic stake
in the company. One maneuver that is specifically prohibited is
declaring a stock dividend in which all shareholders get Class A
shares _ the kind you and I can buy _ in addition to their existing
shares. Yet that is exactly what this recapitalization
accomplishes.
</P>
<P>
   When the dust settles, the Ford family members will have
received about 7 new shares of Class A stock and 10 new shares of
Class B in exchange for each 10 old Class B shares. (The exact
ratio will depend on the price of Ford stock in the days before the
recapitalization is completed.) They will then be able to sell
those Class A shares when they need cash, maintaining the 40
percent vote even if their economic stake in Ford falls to 3.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are changing the rules in the middle of the game,''
complains Ken Bertsch, the director of corporate governance at
TIAA-CREF, a large money management firm. ``The reason they can do
that is that they have so many votes to start with. They can do
this over and over again if they want to. They could go down to a
tenth of a percent if they want to. What is to stop them?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer is that nothing can. TIAA-CREF will announce Friday
that it will vote its 8.4 million shares against the plan at the
shareholder meeting on Aug. 2. But that is not likely to have much
of an effect, because the Ford family will be able to cast its 40
percent of the votes in favor, making it virtually impossible for
its side to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Wallace, Ford's chief financial officer, seemed puzzled
Thursday as to why anyone would object. ``This was meant as a good
strategy for all our shareholders to put cash out there in a
tax-efficient way,'' he said in an interview. The certificate of
incorporation's bar on stock dividends is irrelevant, he said.
``This is a recapitalization. It fully meets and complies with the
letter of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt it does. In all probability the public shareholders
understand why the Ford family will eventually need cash to pay
estate taxes and would approve letting the family sell some shares
without losing votes. But Ford is not offering them the chance to
make that decision.
</P>
<P>
   It is not too late for Ford to change course. It could propose
an amendment to its certificate of incorporation. Alternatively,
William Clay Ford Jr., Ford's chairman, could announce that the
family's shares will be voted in the same proportion as those of
public holders at the Aug. 2 meeting. Either way, Ford would do the
right thing by not evading the rules that public shareholders
relied upon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 2002EDT &QL; 
