<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1407 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f BC-BIZBOOKS-TEX     07-13 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORSOOTH, SHAKESPEARE KNEW ALL ABOUT CORPORATE POWER PLAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the musical ``Kiss Me Kate'' Cole Porter offered up this
lyrical advice:
</P>
<P>
   ``Brush up your Shakespeare
</P>
<P>
   ``Start quoting him now,
</P>
<P>
   ``Brush up your Shakespeare
</P>
<P>
   ``And the women you will wow.''
</P>
<P>
   John O. Whitney and Tina Packer, authors of ``Power Plays,''
agree wholeheartedly with Porter about the usefulness of a good
acquaintance with the wit and wisdom of William Shakespeare. But
they see more far-reaching benefits deriving from brushing up on
one's Shakespeare than that is suggested by the refrain of Cole
Porter's song.
</P>
<P>
   Subtitled ``Shakespeare's Lessons in Leadership and
Management,'' ``Power Plays'' offers valuable advice to those
endeavoring to climb the corporate ladder or expand the scope and
profitability of their companies. But Whitney, a management
professor at Columbia Business School, and Packer, founder and
artistic director of Shakespeare &AMP; Co., eschew the typical model of
the how-to-succeed-in-business manual.
</P>
<P>
   By blending examples of how contemporary business leaders have
succeeded or failed with examples from Shakespeare's plays of
characters who soared or plummeted, Whitney and Packer succeed
magnificently in provide a guide to effective business leadership
that is relevant to today's rapidly changing economic realities and
highly readable and entertaining in the bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Among the parallels they draw are the mistakes made by Henry IV
in the play of the same name and Disney Chairman Michael Eisner in
dealing with the problem of yielding power.
</P>
<P>
   After Disney President Frank Wells died in a helicopter
accident, Eisner brought in his old friend Hollywood power broker
Michael Ovitz as the potential successor. But Ovitz quickly
realized that he had no power in the company because Eisner, like
Henry IV, could not bring himself to share it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within eighteen months, Ovitz was back on the street, albeit
with a severance package that cost Disney some $90 million,'' write
Whitney and Packer.
</P>
<P>
   The motivation of Iago, the villain in ``Othello,'' has invited
an abundance of varying scholarly interpretation. Whitney and
Packer pinpoint the reason for Iago's malice toward his boss, the
moor, the brave general and war hero. The guy had been passed over
for promotion. He had expected to become Othello's
second-in-command. But the general picked Michael Cassio because he
was a ``great arithmetician.''
</P>
<P>
   The lesson there is that an executive who has been passed over
for promotion can be a danger to the organization. If that person
cannot be consoled with promises of consideration for the next
promotion, he or she has to be fired.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is more important for the modern CEO, say Whitney and
Packer, than the ability to communicate well. Communication, they
note, must go beyond the standard office memorandum, which tells
the employees and stockholders what it is going to tell them, tells
them and then tells them that it has told them.
</P>
<P>
   In exhorting CEOs to be creative in their communications,
Whitney and Packer cite the examples of Henry V's exhortation of
his exhausted and badly outnumbered troops at the Battle of
Agincourt and Mark Anthony's oration to the Roman mob in ``Julius
Caesar.''
</P>
<P>
   They point out that instead of harping on the weariness of his
troops and the odds against them, Henry V appealed to their vanity.
The theme of his speech was honor, and his message was that they
would be remembered forever for the valor they displayed on that
day of the feast of St. Crispin.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the authors point out how craftily Mark Antony sized
up the mood of his audience and manipulated the crowd so that its
feelings of hostility toward him were changed to sympathy for
murdered Caesar and anger at his assassins.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best parallel of the many drawn from scores of
Shakespeare's plays centers upon Hamlet and his inability to decide
upon a strategy of action and carry it out. Hamlet's
indecisiveness, the authors point out, is a problem that afflicts
many corporate leaders confronting such phenomena as ``e-commerce,
wild currency swings, and market values calculated as a multiple of
next year's revenues instead of last year's earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitney and Packer pinpoint Jeff Bezos of Amazon.com as a
sterling corporate leader who has transcended the Hamlet syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether or not Amazon.com will eventually lose (under his
direction) is not the main issue,'' they write. ``He has built a
stupendous business, not by waiting to see what was going to
happen, but by making it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Power Plays'' should be on the reading list of every corporate
leader, every person who aspires to be one and everyone who wants
to find his or her niche within a corporate pyramid and be an
effective member of the team. Not only are the business insights
valuable; it can also uplift the culture quotient of business
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But the appeal of the book should extend beyond the business
community. It is an enjoyable read that in addition to providing
valuable business leadership insights also offers a good refresher
course to anyone who wants to brush up on his or her Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a retired editorial writer and columnist for
the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. He is subbing this week for regular
BizBooks reviewer Teresa McUsic. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
