<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GALLOWAY-BEANBALL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYBE PIAZZA SHOULD HAVE SEEN IT COMING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's up for debate whether Rogers Clemens of the Yankees
intentionally hit the Mets' Mike Piazza in the head last week. But
without question, he purposely mailed a fastball into the same zip
code as Piazza's noggin.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, major-leaguers called this ``pitching.''
Nobody questioned the intent of the guy who threw the ball.
Everybody knew why. The responsibility of moving his head out of
harm's way rested with the hitter. You got a problem with that?
</P>
<P>
   Watching all the gruesome replays of the Clemens-Piazza
incident, one thought came to mind. Or two, when you consider how
lucky Piazza was to have escaped with a mild concussion. But a
big-time hitter like the Mets catcher, who routinely feasts on
pitchers, Clemens included, was apparently caught by total surprise
that somebody might attempt to stick a fastball in his ear.
</P>
<P>
   And particularly when this ``somebody'' was Clemens, who carries
one of the few ``headhunter'' reputations remaining in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Even Sandy Koufax, a true gentleman who was the best pitcher of
not only his era but maybe any era, described his craft as ``the
art of instilling fear ... making a man flinch by making him look
for the wrong pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to guess along with Piazza (and I'm 1,200 miles away from
Yankee Stadium seeing it repeatedly on TV replays), it appeared he
never suspected what might be coming. Being a bit scared in the
batter's box is not an unmanly act. The great Reggie Jackson said
of Nolan Ryan, when both were still playing against each other:
``Ryan is the only guy who puts fear in me. Not because he can get
you out, but because he can kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   No hitter ever went to the plate against Ryan without being
ready for anything. Today, however, the fear factor is gone in
baseball, the main reason being that ``purpose'' pitches, or even
merely pitching a batter inside, have become a lost weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens' explanation on drilling Piazza in the head was a firm,
``I was only trying to pitch him inside.'' If you could believe
that, then Clemens was doing what every pitcher in baseball should
be doing to the Piazzas of the batting orders. Move those bombers
off the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, if a pitcher comes within a foot of a hitter with a
fastball, there is glaring at the mound, squawking with the
catcher, and the next thing you know, both benches have emptied.
It's believable that a Clemens' fastball to the head could freeze a
Piazza. It's extremely rare today to find a pitcher with that kind
of mean streak. Or even a pitcher who legitimately wants to work
inside. Piazza has had no practice at bailing on beanballs. What
hitter of today has?
</P>
<P>
   ``We sit at the ballpark every night watching games and
commenting about the lack of purpose pitches or intentional
pitches,'' said Reid Nichols, a former major-league outfielder and
now the Rangers' director of player development. ``Of all the games
I've seen this year, I can remember only one time saying that a
pitcher was throwing at a hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Nichols is an advocate of such a thing. Remember he's a
former major-league hitter, who was quick yesterday to point out
Bruce Kison, a Pirates' pitcher of the early '80s, as someone who
would repeatedly buzz you inside.
</P>
<P>
   But being in charge of the Rangers' minor-league system, Nichols
and his instructors are attempting to teach young pitchers to throw
the ball inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I had the answer on why we don't see it anymore, but my
guess is it started with the shrinking of the strike zone by the
umpires,'' he said. ``The way the game is called now, if you come
inside on a hitter, it's ball one. If you miss again, it's ball
two, and now the hitter has you where he wants you. The pitcher
feels he can't waste a pitch. To me, all the offense we are
suddenly seeing in baseball goes back to the strike zone being a
postage stamp.''
</P>
<P>
   In the minor leagues, charts are kept on how many times a
pitcher makes the hitter move his feet. ``The more, the better,''
Nichols said. ``It is teaching them to move hitters off the plate,
to take away the inside corner. Even the best hitter can only cover
about three-fourths of the plate. If you let the hitter have the
inside corner, he will also own the outside corner on you.''
</P>
<P>
   To pitch inside, however, means you will hit batters. It's
inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't teach pitchers to throw at the hitter, but if that
happens accidentally, then how the hitter reacts is up to him, I
guess,'' Nichols said. ``All I know is the pitchers have to take
back the inside corner to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens appeared to go to the extreme edge of that philosophy
last week. And one great hitter of this era never knew it was
coming.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 2010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
