r s BC-BBN-CARDINALS-MAKEOVE     07-13 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CARDINALS-MAKEOVER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESHUFFLED CARDS RUNNING AWAY WITH NL CENTRAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Cincinnati Reds general manager Jim Bowden carefully
considered the ramifications of trading his best pitcher, Denny
Neagle, before even one game had been played in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   He considered the club's payroll, considered the fact that
Neagle can become a free agent after the season, and considered the
chances of re-signing the left-hander. He considered the potential
negative reaction from fans and the media, who might see a trade as
giving up prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   Then he considered the standings. Despite winning six of 10
games before the All-Star break, and despite being in second place
in the National League Central, the Reds were a game under .500 and
eight games behind the St. Louis Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   All things considered, Bowden ran the white flag up the flagpole
and traded Neagle to the New York Yankees on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A business decision, he called it, but it was more than that. It
was a realistic one.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, a badly beaten fourth in the division last year,
aren't likely to be caught this season. They entered the break with
the second-best record in the NL (51-36), half a game behind the
Atlanta Braves, and had the biggest lead in any division.
</P>
<P>
   The team is winning thanks in part to general manager Walt
Jocketty, who rebuilt the club with a series of astute trades and
free-agent signings after last year's disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a whole new team; that's the difference,'' slugger
Mark McGwire said. ``We have new guys at a lot of positions. Walt
did a great job with free agents and some trades this winter, and
he deserves a lot of credit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals won 158 games the past two seasons, only 23 more
victories than McGwire had home runs. McGwire thrilled baseball
fans everywhere with his record-breaking exploits, but, all too
often, the newspaper headlines read, ``McGwire goes deep in Cards'
loss.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire is again leading the majors in home runs with 30, but he
is less the center of attention, and he couldn't be happier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course it's better,'' he said. ``Who doesn't want to be on
a winner? It's pretty hard to accommodate the media when you're
talking about yourself all the time. Now the team wins, and the
media wants to talk about the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Jocketty revamped the pitching staff by trading for starters
Darryl Kile and Pat Hentgen and closer Dave Veres, and by signing
free agent Andy Benes. With help from rookie Rick Ankiel and
Garrett Stephenson, the rotation is 43-23. That's a marked
improvement from last year, when starters went 50-45. Injuries
forced manager Tony La Russa to put together a patchwork staff and
wear out the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have stability in the rotation,'' La Russa said. ``That's
been important because we haven't had to mess with the bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   The GM improved the offense by trading for center fielder Jim
Edmonds and second baseman Fernando Vina.
</P>
<P>
   His new teammates didn't know what to expect out of Edmonds. He
suffered through an injury-plagued season in '99, and came from
Anaheim with a reputation as a divisive force in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   But Edmonds has fit in off the field, and played like an
All-Star on it. With 25 home runs, he has teamed with McGwire to
give the Cards the best one-two power punch in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing an unbelievable job, I think better than anybody
expected,'' outfielder J.D. Drew said. ``He's definitely one of the
key parts of this team.''
</P>
<P>
   The lineup is more than the Mark-and-Jim show, however. The
supporting cast is good enough that the Cardinals entered yesterday
on pace for 277 homers, which would break the major-league record
of 264 set by the Seattle Mariners in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes our lineup tough is it goes all the way down to the
eight hole,'' Kile said. ``We've got a good mix of guys who drive
the ball into the gaps or out of the ballpark. If you pitch around
McGwire, the next guy can hit one out.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the potent offense, the improved pitching and their big
lead, the Cardinals don't have the champagne on ice.
</P>
<P>
   They open the second half with a four-city, 11-game road trip,
and McGwire is hurt. He missed the All-Star Game because of
tendinitis below his right knee, which kept him out of action last
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing we talk about now is don't get carried
away,'' La Russa said. ``I like the way everybody's approaching
things like that. They're confident, but not comfortable at all.''
</P>
<P>
   All things considered, they have every reason to be confident.
Their closest pursuers acknowledged that by trading away their best
pitcher.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
