u f BC-MEDIAONE-INVESTORS-NY     07-13 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIAONE-INVESTORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: DIFFERENT GAINS FOR MEDIAONE STOCKHOLDERS RELATES TO
AT&AMP;T'S VALUE 
</HEADLINE>
   By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Do you want to avoid paying taxes? If you're a
MediaOne shareholder, that tax aversion could prove very costly.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's takeover of MediaOne has already taken effect, but only
now are shareholders of the cable television company having to
decide what they will be paid for the company. Those who decide to
minimize the tax hit will do so, but at a considerable cost.
</P>
<P>
   That is because AT&AMP;T is offering MediaOne shareholders three
choices of compensation, varying in the amount of AT&AMP;T stock and
cash that will be received. The deadline for shareholders to make
their choice is Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The smallest immediate tax hit will come for shareholders who
choose to take as much of their compensation as possible in AT&AMP;T
stock. Those shareholders will receive 1.4912 shares of AT&AMP;T plus
$8.50 in cash for each share of MediaOne they tender. Because the
shares are not taxable now _ in tax jargon, the cost of the
MediaOne shares carries over to the cost of the AT&AMP;T shares _ those
holders would pay tax only on $8.50 in cash, or perhaps on less,
depending on the profit recorded on the MediaOne shares, which is
based on what the investor paid for the shares.
</P>
<P>
   The catch is that offer is not worth nearly as much as the other
offers available. At close of trading Thursday with AT&AMP;T's stock
price at $33.75 that offer is worth only $58.83 for each MediaOne
share.
</P>
<P>
   By far the best alternative for shareholders would be an
all-cash offer of $85 a share, which will not actually bring that
much cash but will provide more cash than either of the other
offers. The other alternative is an offer of 0.95 share of AT&AMP;T,
plus $36.27 in cash, for each MediaOne share. That has a value of
$68.33 at current prices and is close to what investors will
actually receive if they choose the cash version.
</P>
<P>
   That is true because AT&AMP;T has fixed what it will pay _ about $23
billion in cash and 606 million shares _ and the shareholder
elections will simply decide how the cash and stock are divided up.
If everyone chose the same option, all would end up with the
blended deal, which AT&AMP;T calls the standard election.
</P>
<P>
   One reason that the number of shares tendered for stock could be
unusually high is MediaOne's history. It was spun off in 1995 from
U S West, which itself was spun off from AT&AMP;T when the phone
company was broken up in 1984. Like all the companies that were
spun off from AT&AMP;T, it has a lot of individual holders, many of
whom own small positions.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T will not give details on the results thus far, but Connie
Weaver, AT&AMP;T's vice president for investor relations, says,
``People are taking all three of the options.'' She said MediaOne
had about 800,000 investors.
</P>
<P>
   Why would anyone choose the clearly inferior offer that contains
mostly stock? One reason may be that brokerage firms are not
offering much advice. PaineWebber put out a report saying the cash
option was clearly the most valuable, but other firms seem not to
have done so.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not advising, because it depends on the individual's tax
situation,'' said Megan Kulick, a telecommunications analyst for
Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it is hard to imagine any investor who would be better
off to take the stock deal. Someone who took the blended deal and
had a low enough cost of MediaOne stock to owe taxes on all the
cash received _ meaning that investor paid less than $30.40 each
for their shares in MediaOne _ and who owed combined federal and
state capital gains taxes of 25 percent, would still have an
after-tax value of $59.27 a share, compared with $56.70 for the
investor who took the primarily stock package.
</P>
<P>
   An investor who did want to own more AT&AMP;T could take the cash
and buy more AT&AMP;T shares than the stock offering would provide. And
that investor would owe less taxes later when the AT&AMP;T shares were
sold.
</P>
<P>
   The two packages are so disparate in large part because AT&AMP;T
stock has been a poor performer since the deal was announced on May
6, 1999. Its shares are trading for just over half the $61.9375
they were worth then, the result of a series of corporate
disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the lure of simplicity and tax savings is likely to
make at least some shareholders choose the stock alternative. When
they do, the beneficiaries of that decision will be the other
owners of MediaOne stock, who will get more cash and less AT&AMP;T
stock than they otherwise would have received. Those owners will
include institutional investors and the risk arbitrage departments
of some of the very firms that seem hesitant to offer advice to
their customers.
</P>
</TEXT>
