<SLUG> BC-GE-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GE STOCK EARNINGS TOP ESTIMATES, RISING 20 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The General Electric Co., benefiting from a robust
economy and its aggressive push into selling products online, said
Thursday that its second-quarter earnings rose 20 percent, beating
analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended June 30, net income rose to $3.38 billion,
or 34 cents a share. That compares with $2.82 billion, or 28 cents
a share, in the quarter a year earlier when adjusted for a 3-for-1
stock split in April. Revenue surged 20 percent, to $32.9 billion
from $27.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected the company to earn 33 cents a share,
according to First Call/Thomson Financial, which tracks company
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``A strong quarter is business as usual for GE, but this quarter
was even better than normal,'' said Charles Hill, director of
research at First Call.
</P>
<P>
   Investors seemed unimpressed as shares of GE, based in
Fairfield, Conn., fell $1, to $52.50. Analysts, in contrast, were
practically adulatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most industrial companies are experiencing no more than 5
percent organic growth, so GE's results are just phenomenal,'' said
Jeffrey Sprague, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Heymann, an analyst with Prudential Securities, said:
``You'd need a jeweler's glass to find a problem here.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers did little to help handicap the race to succeed Jack
Welch, the GE chairman, who will retire next year. Analysts expect
the heir to be one of three executives: Robert Nardelli, head of GE
Power Systems; Jeffrey Immelt, head of GE Medical Systems; or W.
James McNerney Jr., head of GE Aircraft Engines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Succession wouldn't swing on one quarter anyway, but all of
the contenders had good results,'' said Russell Leavitt, an analyst
at Banc of America Securities.
</P>
<P>
   GE Power Systems had a particularly robust quarter, with sales
up 60 percent. All makers of turbines had growth spurts as
utilities continued their buying spree, but analysts say that GE
grabbed share away from competitors like ABB and Siemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Power systems knocked the cover off the ball,'' said Richard
Nelson, an analyst with ING Barings.
</P>
<P>
   GE Medical nearly doubled its sales of X-ray machines, while
sales of CAT scanners and ultrasound machines were up more than 35
percent. Thanks to robust sales of high-margin services, GE
Aircraft Engines saw its profit rise 20 percent on a revenue
increase of just 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even without new reality or game shows, GE's television network,
NBC, held onto a high share of viewers aged 18 to 49 _ the ones
advertisers pay most to reach.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings at GE Capital, meanwhile, were up 17 percent on a
revenue rise of 23 percent. Analysts expect those earnings to rise
even higher as GE Capital continues to de-emphasize businesses like
the leasing of rail cars in favor of those featuring financial
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all over the Internet, capturing customers for
services rather than for leases of depreciable assets,'' Heymann
said.
</P>
<P>
   GE, never short of cash, will soon have even more. On Tuesday,
UBS said it would buy PaineWebber for $12.4 billion. GE owns part
of PaineWebber and should reap $1.4 billion from the deal. Gary
Sheffer, a GE spokesman, insists that GE was not consulted on the
merger and has not yet made plans for the money.
</P>
<P>
   Buying back stock is one option. GE, in fact, bought back $523
million in stock during the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But not all analysts like that idea. ``Theirs isn't a cheap
stock,'' said Nelson of ING Barings. ``They should invest in
Internet companies whose stories they believe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
