<HEADER>
A1426 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CARRACCI-BAROQUE-ART-     07-13 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARRACCI-BAROQUE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADING THE BAROQUE BACK TO NATURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT9 and 10 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the three artists from Bologna named Carracci _ Annibale
(1560-1609), his brother Agostino (1557-1602) and their cousin
Ludovico (1555-1619) _ did not exactly invent Baroque art, they
gave their all to it. In the 1580s, unhappy with the Mannerist
preciosity that dominated the art of their time, they started an
academy that pushed for a return to nature and the classical
heritage of the great Italian masters who preceded them, in
particular Correggio, Veronese and Titian.
</P>
<P>
   A significant institution in the history of Western art,
essentially developed by Ludovico, the academy insisted that art
can be taught on academic principles, along with more practical
apprenticeships, and that pupils must study the antique and
Renaissance traditions as well as anatomy and drawing from life. It
produced a generation of artists, among them Guido Reni,
Domenichino and Annibale Carracci himself.
</P>
<P>
   Later the three Carraccis went on to their own pursuits.
Annibale, considered one of the greatest draftsmen of the age,
moved to Rome in 1595 to work for the powerful Farnese family. With
the help of Agostino, he created a highly influential fresco cycle
for the ceiling of the Farnese Palace that was lauded as the equal
of Raphael's work in the Vatican. Done in a vigorously sensuous
style, it brought back the Renaissance love of human drama and
emotion. Natural forms, modified by the classicism of the masters,
replaced what the Carraccis perceived as the distortions of
Mannerism. In short they were significant figures in the
development of the dynamic art known as Baroque.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 30 years, the Metropolitan Museum has assembled a
splendid collection of work by the Carraccis: four paintings _
three acquired in the last six years _ 17 drawings and a slew of
prints. A selection from these holdings is on display in ``The
Birth of Baroque: The Carracci at the Metropolitan'' through Sept.
17.
</P>
<P>
   Among the oils, Ludovico's innovative ``The Lamentation''
(1582), said to be a landmark in European painting, is the most
shockingly ``real.'' The very dead figure of Jesus, based on a
posed model, lies contortedly across the matronly Virgin's lap as
she slumps back in a faint. Light falls brightly on the two figures
and the faces of St. John and Mary Magdalene, illuminating the
contrast between live and dead flesh. The corpse's attendants,
including the Virgin, are stylized compared with the figure of
Jesus, but they avoid the idealization that was a given of
Renaissance art.
</P>
<P>
   Less of a shocker, but of equal weight, is Annibale's
``Coronation of the Virgin'' (about 1596), done after his arrival
in Rome for the private chapel of Cardinal Pietro Aldobrandini. The
symmetrical composition shows the Virgin crowned Queen of Heaven by
Jesus and God the Father as she is seated on a bank of clouds. She
is attended below by a band of music-making cherubs seen close up
and above by a ghostly cast of thousands in the infinity of
Paradise. Scholars say that the compositional symmetry and the
apselike view of Paradise reflect the classicism of Annibale's
influential Roman style as well as his response to Raphael's
Vatican frescoes.
</P>
<P>
   But brilliant as they are, these paintings can only offer a
glimpse of the Carraccis' achievements, which ran mostly to complex
fresco cycles and monumental altarpieces. Their painstaking
observation and their ability to handle complicated narratives is
better seen in their drawings and prints. The drawings, which
served largely as a way to explore ideas, were fundamental to the
making of the Carracci pictorial language. They range from
Annibale's charmingly intimate ink with wash, ``A Domestic Scene''
(probably early 1580s), in which a mother warms her child's
nightgown before a fire, to Ludovico's ambitious ``The Last
Communion of St. Jerome'' (no date), a tightly composed altarpiece
proposal for a Bolognese church in which the saint undergoes the
sacramental rite as he lies supported by Mary, among a bustle of
other figures.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are powerful figure studies, like Annibale's ``Triton
Sounding a Conch Shell'' (probably around 1597), one of the many
preparatory drawings for the Farnese Palace project. It depicts a
hugely muscled sea god blowing strenuously on a conch shell, the
finished version of which appears in the ceiling fresco ``Thetis
Carried to the Bridal Chamber of Peleus.'' Most of the energetic
figures for the gigantic fresco cycle were invented by Annibale
(although some were done by Agostino) using poses by live models.
At least 90 drawings for the project are extant.
</P>
<P>
   Annibale's drawings include biblical themes as well. One of the
loveliest is the ink and wash ``Landscape With Jacob Sleeping''
(probably 1590-1595), relating to the story in Genesis. During a
journey, Jacob, the future patriarch, falls asleep on a heap of
stones. He dreams of a ladder rising to Heaven, with people
climbing and descending and God speaking from the top about the
Promised Land. In Annibale's version, the huddled figure of Jacob
lies under a sheltering tree, while in the middle distance a
faintly sketched ladder is seen. The pastoral landscape is airy and
luminous, with a glowingly expansive rendering of space.
</P>
<P>
   Agostino was the only Carracci trained as a professional
printmaker, although his brother and cousin did not lack for skills
in the medium. The more than 200 engravings by Agostino include
many that reproduced the endeavors of earlier masters like Titian
and Tintoretto, helping to spread knowledge of their work.
Annibale, taught by Agostino, made only 21 prints over a 25-year
period, starting in 1581 with engraving but going on to the
livelier challenge of etching. Only four prints by Ludovico are
known.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One of Annibale's most dramatic prints, combining etching and
engraving, deals with the biblical tale ``Susanna and the Elders''
(circa 1590-92), in which a fleshy Susanna is spied on at her bath
by two dirty old men. She hastily pulls her clothes around her in a
beautifully delineated milieu of sun, lush vegetation, drapery,
water and the stone of the bathing pool. The menace of the two men
is heightened by frowning stone masks at the edge of the pool. The
action in a much smaller ``Susanna'' engraving by Agostino, done
around the same time, is more lascivious; it drew a rebuke from
Pope Clement VIII. In this print one of the elders actually gropes
her.
</P>
<P>
   Two strong renditions of saints by Agostino also stand out among
the prints. ``The Stigmatization of St. Francis'' (published 1586)
is an arresting engraving of the saint in the wilderness, kneeling
in ecstasy, hands outstretched to receive the stigmata conveyed by
rays from above. The work of several other artists influenced this
print, but Agostino's intense, theatrical depiction of the saint's
ecstatic expression shows how he embraced the Baroque style.
</P>
<P>
   His last engraving, done shortly before his death and finished
by another artist, is ``Saint Jerome'' (1602). The saint, attended
by a sleeping lion, kneels on a rock, holding a cross and gazing
rapturously upward. In this print Agostino looks more to Mannerism,
expressed in the saint's well-muscled body. This small but
illustrious show is another example of the Met's commendable
practice of building exhibitions from its own collection with
little or no call on outside sources. Admittedly not every museum
can muster the material owned by this treasure house, but the Met
has become adept at proving that there are more ways than
blockbusters to get people looking at art.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
