<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 
 PERSONALS: The Most Expensive Food in New York 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
``The signing of the check at  &UR; Alain Ducasse  &LR; is a special
moment,'' writes New York Times restaurant critic  &UR; William Grimes &LR; 
in a description forwarded by  &UR; David Schwoegler &LR; . ``With exquisite
timing, a waiter appears and holds up a velvet display board
containing a dozen finely made pens. It's hard not to feel that you
are about to sign a document imposing humiliating terms of
surrender.''
</P>
<P>
   A fixed-price dinner at the restaurant, which opened recently,
is $160; customers calling for reservations must leave a credit
card deposit of $150 a person. The restaurant has one sitting a
night, is open for lunch only twice a week and is closed on
weekends.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing New Yorkers like better than a challenge. Grimes
writes that within days of its phone being hooked up, 2,700
reservation requests were wait-listed. Right now, Ducasse has
stopped taking reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the amenities: a stainless-steel six-pack of various
kinds of mineral water; a wine list with a wax seal that needs to
be broken; herbal tea, offered at the end of the meal, is created
after the waiter arrives with a cart of herbs growing in pots,
grasps the plant, cuts a few leaves off and brews it.
</P>
<P>
   Grimes' bill, for four people, came to nearly $1,500, excluding
tip. ``In one Olympic clean-and-jerk motion,'' he writes, ``I had
broken all previous records by several hundred dollars. I felt the
kind of mad exhilaration that criminals must feel when they've done
something terribly, irrevocably wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; HEARST TOUR GUIDE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Patty Hearst &LR; , recovered kidnap victim, will film two TV tours
of the Hearst Castle to be broadcast next year by the Travel
Channel.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst Castle was built by  &UR; William &LR;   &UR; Randolph Hearst &LR; , the
heiress' grandfather, between 1922 and 1947; it was made a
California State Historical Monument in 1951. Hearst will talk
about the history of the estate, its splendors and her
grandfather's relationship with various celebrities, including
 &UR; Charlie Chaplin &LR;  and &UR; Clark Gable,  &LR; and probably including his
mistress,  &UR; Marion Davies &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The TV tour guide will be testifying early next year in the case
against  &UR; Sara Jane Olson &LR; , one of the SLA associates who hid out
with her in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Jane Fonda &LR;  told the Atlanta Journal Constitution that she
has bought four new lofts to combine into one top-floor apartment
in Atlanta just across from the Carter Center.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Times of London reports that framed 4-inch-square tiles of
linoleum from  &UR; Karl Marx &LR; 's old office are being sold for $150 each
at the gift shop of the Marx Memorial Library in Clerkenwell.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Nana &LR; , an aging Chihuahua who lives in Santa Rosa and has
been voted the world's ugliest dog three times, will grace the
cover of  &UR; Bob Weir &LR; 's new CD, ``Evening Mood.'' Weir's band is
called Ratdog.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Lauren Bacall &LR; , who was honored as a Woman of Achievement by
the Women's Project &AMP; Productions, a nonprofit theater group in New
York, required $2,000 for hair and makeup before she would agree to
appear at a fund-raiser. Artistic director  &UR; Julia Miles &LR;  told New
York magazine that the group depended on Bacall for help in raising
money, so paying for her beautification ``is a small thing for us
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; IS MONEY GREEN? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; T.S. Bolton  &LR; hopes that before it created its new green
ketchup, Heinz sought advice from the whiz kids who thought up
Pepsi Clear.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gourmet magazine looked into the cupboard of food
maven  &UR; Marion Cunningham &LR; , right-hand woman to  &UR; James Beard  &LR; and
 &UR; Fannie Farmer  &LR; and Chronicle Learning to Cook columnist, and
discovered plentiful supplies of less-than-cutting-edge standards:
Crisco, Heinz ketchup and canned Ortega chiles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; MORE OUT-OF-IT THAN THOU &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``So who is this Britney Aguilera?'' asks  &UR; A.M. &LR;  And ``Why does
the phone company need its own park?'' asks  &UR; Steve Abney &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ```Scream' is already such a parody of the slasher genre, and &LR; 
 &UR; `Scary Movie' (is) a parody of a parody. If `Scary Movie' stays &LR; 
 &UR; strong, I think it will end the `Scream' series and take over &LR; 
 &UR; from it with its own `Scary Movie' sequels.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Scream'' producer  &UR; Cary Woods  &LR; on the state of cinema art,
to  &UR; Baird Jones  &LR; at a DKNY party in New York.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
