<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1433 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-BROTHER-ART-835(     07-13 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BROTHER-ART-835(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEB BUSH, DEEP IN THE SHADOWS OF HIS BIG BROTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT4 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ As Gov. George W. Bush mulls over potential
running mates, here is an appealing choice: He is a popular young
governor from the fourth largest state, one where Democrats hope to
compete ferociously. He is something of a policy wonk, a nice
balance to Bush's celebrated aversion to minutiae. He is beloved
among many Latino voters, a crucial voting bloc. He is Roman
Catholic, a big plus since Bush faced accusations in the primaries
that he was anti-Catholic. And he has star appeal as a scion of one
of the most famous political families.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, his last name is Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Because of an odd twist of fate, or, more precisely, electoral
fortune, Gov. Jeb Bush of Florida, who had long been seen in the
family as the one with the greatest political promise, has been
crowded off the national stage by his older brother.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than capitalize on his brother's fame, Jeb Bush has
receded into the shadows far more than is typical for a new
governor of a big state. Resisting entreaties from other governors
and Republican officials, Bush rarely ventures beyond Florida to
take part in party functions. He shuns opportunities to speak out
about his brother's campaign, except when asked about its prospects
in Florida. And he will not have a high-profile speaking slot at
the party's national convention in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've really been almost reclusive,'' Bush said in the first
extensive interview he has given about his brother's campaign and
how he fits in _ or does not. Explaining his deliberate attempts at
low visibility, he cited the Bush name. ``Maybe I'm overly
sensitive to it about the legacy and all that.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a driving force behind Bush's low profile, besides his
priority of tending to Florida business, is what he said is the
tangled, and often hurtful predicament of constantly being compared
to his father, the former president, and his brother, the would-be
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any good things that are said about anything I'm doing have
been historically posted up against George in a negative way,'' he
said. ``Any bad things that might be said about me would be used
negatively against George. I don't see how I help George by having
a high profile nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   Another inescapable reality for Jeb Bush is that as much as he
and his brother love each other, friends and associates say their
relationship has never been like that of another famous set of
political siblings, John and Robert Kennedy. Robert Kennedy was
President Kennedy's closest adviser in the White House and was
known as the enforcer who would make things happen for his brother
_ and take on his enemies.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Jeb Bush, who is 47, said he chatted with his
54-year-old brother only about once a week. He does not appear to
be steeped in the presidential campaign, or at least is not eager
to show that he is.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is his brother. Asked recently if he would appoint Jeb Bush
to a cabinet position, as President Kennedy did with his brother,
George Bush offered a resounding, ``Uhhhhhh, no!''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting by his computer (e-mail messages popped up continuously)
in his small anteroom next to his larger ceremonial office in the
Capitol here, Jeb Bush talked about how he resented the contrasts
with his brother and father. Jeb Bush is often portrayed in the
press as more cerebral than his brother, while George W. Bush is
depicted as more of a natural politician. They are both frequently
described as more agile campaigners than their father.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hurtful to see George being criticized,'' he said. ``It's
painful to see the comparisons used in a way that are hurtful. The
most painful thing for me, and I know it is for George, is to see
comparisons about my dad where a compliment is given to George or
in some cases maybe to me, saying, `Well, he's better.' As far as
I'm concerned, my dad is as close to perfection as a human being
can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he was particularly pained by how his brother was
sometimes typecast as a lightweight. ``I don't understand why
people would say it,'' he said. ``Perhaps because he's a guy's guy.
He's easygoing. He has interests outside of politics and all this
wonky stuff. People that really bother me are intellectuals that
think they've got it all figured out, that he doesn't have the
gravitas to serve. The only comfort I get is they get it wrong all
the time. There's actually a political advantage to being
underestimated in George's case.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jeb Bush would much rather talk about Florida than about his
brother's intellectual prowess. He is so averse to the limelight
that he said he consented to this interview not because he finally
relented after requests stretching back to last year, but because
he was told that the reporter planned to write an article anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeb has been in hot demand,'' said Gov. John Engler of
Michigan. ``We're tried to have Jeb come to Michigan _ and many
other have tried. Jeb just doesn't. His focus is in Tallahassee.
He's very careful.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
