<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1434 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GORE-BRADLEY-HNS &LR;      07-13 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BRADLEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY, GORE BURY THE PRIMARY HATCHET 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREEN BAY, Wis. _ Bill Bradley, who once suggested that Al Gore
twisted the truth, endorsed the vice president Thursday in their
first meeting since Gore won a bitter Democratic presidential
primary.
</P>
<P>
   The lanky ex-professional basketball player and New Jersey
senator introduced his former rival at an outdoor rally in Green
Bay and said he will work to see the Democrats keep the White House
and regain control of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today I want to make it clear that I endorse Al Gore for
president of the United States,'' he said. Although Bradley had
said in March that he would support the Democratic presidential
candidate, he had not previously used the word ``endorse''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said Gore would do better than Republican candidate
George W. Bush in solving such problems as racial divisions, health
care costs and the influence of special interest money on political
campaigns. ``It's not even close,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who during the primaries accused Bradley of proposing a
budget-busting health plan, lavished praise on his former rival,
saying that that the two men had a number of goals in common
including moving toward universal health care and adopting campaign
finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I treasure Bill Bradley's support. He is a good Democrat who
speaks and stands for principles we believe in,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite past tensions the two appeared comfortable together
during the event, held at a park on the shores of Lake Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Looking tanned and relaxed, Bradley shook Gore's hand and patted
him briefly on the back after introducing the vice president, who
was dressed casually in a polo shirt and slacks.
</P>
<P>
   To underscore why they decided to put past acrimony behind them,
both men cited the folk wisdom of the football legend who put Green
Bay on the map, the late Packers Coach Vince Lombardi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here in Green Bay today because I believe what Vince
Lombardi once said is true. `Winning is a team sport!''' said
Bradley. To which Gore offered another Lombardi maxim, ``People who
work together win.''
</P>
<P>
   Still lagging in the polls behind Bush, Gore needed this
official display of peace with Bradley to energize Democratic
voters and avoid more divisiveness in the party before its
convention in Los Angeles next month.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of lengthy negotiations between the two camps,
Bradley appears to have been assured a speaking role at the
convention, said his spokesman, Eric Hauser.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has not yet agreed to release several hundred delegates
committed to him from the primaries. But it appears likely that
Gore will secure the support of most of them by the time the
convention rolls around.
</P>
<P>
   While Bradley vowed to work for Gore and Democrats in the fall
election, it is not clear just how much time he will spend on the
campaign trail. He appeared with Gore at only one event Thursday,
flying on his own to and from Green Bay. Later in the day Gore flew
to serve as host of a town hall meeting in Saginaw, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   As he departed, Gore told supporters at the Green Bay Airport
that Thursday was one of the most important days in the election
campaign because of Bradley's endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has ``a big following and an even larger number that
respect his judgment,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Before their joint public appearance, the two men met privately
for about 40 minutes, their first encounter since the last primary
debate in Los Angeles on March 1.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley clearly had been angry at Gore during the heated
primary, particularly after the vice president ripped into his plan
to provide health insurance for all Americans. The vice president
charged that the plan would increase the deficit and drain funding
from other programs.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, meanwhile, was resentful that Bradley challenged the
sitting vice president, who spent the past seven years dutifully
serving in the No. 2 spot and positioning himself for the
presidential run.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have enthusiastically seized on Bradley's most
biting criticism: that Gore does not tell the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should we believe that you will tell the truth as
president if you don't tell the truth as a candidate?'' Bradley
asked in a Jan. 26 debate in new Hampshire. The quote now appears
as a heading on Republican contender George W. Bush's campaign
releases challenging Gore's credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer Bradley, stressing a populist platform, appeared to
be making a credible challenge against Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But by early winter the Bradley effort fizzled as Gore
intensified his campaign and consolidated the support of key
Democratic groups such as minorities and labor. Meanwhile,
Republican candidate John McCain was siphoning off independent
voters drawn to the outsiders' message.
</P>
<P>
   In his address Thursday, Gore quoted Bradley numerous times as
he sought to convey that he championed many of the same causes.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Bradley is right when he says, `It's not right that kings
and dictators can come to this country to get the best medical care
in the world while children and families two blocks away may not be
able to afford to afford any care at all,''' Gore said. Bradley,
sitting behind Gore on the platform, did not clap at the mention of
his health care priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley did not mention Gore's proposals on health care or
campaign finance reform. The one area in which he singled out Gore
for praise was his grasp of the technological changes taking place
in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In endorsing Gore, though, Bradley gave a hint of the lingering
disappointment at his primary defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a remarkable experience _ though someone once told me,
when one uses the term `experience' in this context, `experience'
is what you get when you don't get what you really wanted,'' he
said. ``Indeed the Democratic voters spoke and selected the vice
president as our party's nominee.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
