<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unser Jr: IRL here to stay
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Al Unser Jr. says he knows why the Indy Racing
League's Northern Lights Series can win the war between factions of
open-wheel racing.
</P>
<P>
   Dictators always beat committees, and CART is run by a
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Tony George runs the IRL with a firm hand, and Unser said he
likes the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill France is the perfect example,'' Unser said. ``France had
a vision and implemented it through NASCAR.''
</P>
<P>
   Like France, George chases his vision without discussion or
votes.
</P>
<P>
   Unser, the two-time Indy 500 winner who will be racing in
Saturday night's Midas 500 Classic at Atlanta Motor Speedway, has
seen both sides of the fray. He moved to IRL during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IRL is definitely here to stay,'' Unser said, citing the
expansion of the series schedule from nine races this year to 12
and counting in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the recent change in CART leadership, Bobby Rahal
replacing Andrew Craig, Unser doesn't see any big changes. ``A
committee runs CART,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The IRL and CART cars don't have many differences, except CART
cars have more power, Unser said. But he said speed can outrun the
technology and create unsafe conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Both series are very competitive, but IRL drivers give each
other more respect on the track, Unser said. Indy 500 winner Juan
Montoya has said the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, NASCAR is setting the standard for Americans to view
races, Unser said.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 500 miles, you have five to seven cars door to door at
the end of the race,'' Unser said. ``In NASCAR, we don't know who
is going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what George wants for the IRL, and he got it at Texas
Motor Speedway with packs of 15 cars drafting in a race nearly free
of accidents.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of racing helped Unser make up his mind to choose CART
when the IRL was first formed. ``We didn't know about these G-Force
and Dallara cars,'' he said. ``I was very hesitant.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he likes the way the IRL keeps control of the speeds; it
promotes safety and competition. This year, six different drivers
have won the six races held.
</P>
<P>
   But even with competitive cars and strong leadership, the IRL
still has trouble moving into the South. The CART series had the
same problem when Unser first raced here in 1983, starting 21st and
finishing sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta Motor Speedway is a vastly different track now than it
was then,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cars have changed every bit as much. I invite Southern
race fans out to see what we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
