<HEADER>
A1437 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-BROTHER-ART-3RDT     07-13 0443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BROTHER-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 TALLAHASSEE, Fla.: to fear. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like any successful siblings, there is a competition edge
between the two. Yet if Jeb Bush harbors any jealousy, he does his
best to suppress it. Playfully, he lets it be known that his more
famous brother is not above appropriating his ideas. In the 1994
campaign, one of Jeb Bush's favorite lines was that he was running
not because he was George and Barbara's son, but because of his own
children's futures. ``He stole it lock, stock and barrel,'' said
Jeb Bush.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, he said George Bush picked up his idea of
offering school vouchers, or state scholarships, to students in
schools where high percentages are not performing well.
</P>
<P>
   And when the two appeared at a news conference in Plant City,
Fla., in March, George Bush said he might consider reducing the gas
tax. Then Jeb Bush piped in with an eloquent explanation for why he
did not think that was wise because it would take away much needed
money for highways. George Bush later relented.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said one of the problems with reducing the gas tax in
Washington is states like Texas and Florida have to make
adjustments in their road construction programs because in our
state we have real congested roads,'' he said. ``I should have kept
my mouth shut. But he acknowledged it was a good point.''
</P>
<P>
   In return, Jeb Bush said he had learned from his brother, to the
point that he emulated him. ``I've tried to steal the very formula
that made him successful,'' he said. ``To have a clear agenda. To
let the world know what it is. And then do what you said you were
going to do. It's so easy to do the opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   While Jeb Bush is shunning the national stage, George P., the
eldest son of the governor, and his Mexican-born wife, Columba, are
filling the void in his own way. At 24, he has a poise and good
looks that have made him something of a sensation on the campaign
trail.
</P>
<P>
   Told that his visitor had not seen George P.'s television
commercials for his uncle in which he appeals to Latinos and
Generation X-ers, Jeb Bush grabbed a videotape, bounded into his
chief of staff's office, and seemed on the verge of tears as he
proudly showed off his son.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was not even disapproving of his son posing in bed for
photographers at People magazine, where he made the list of 100 (he
ranked 4th) most eligible bachelors.
</P>
<P>
   Jeb Bush is well aware that there could be ``missed
opportunities,'' but seems resigned to leaving the big stage to his
brother and son. Asked why he had is retreating to the sidelines at
the convention, Jeb Bush said, ``I'll yield my time to George P.''
</P>
</TEXT>
