<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING THE KIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Disney's `The Kid'
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Willis, Spencer Breslin, Emily Mortimer, Lily Tomlin, Jean
Smart &QL; 
Directed by Jon Turteltaub
</P>
<P>
   PG _ 101 minutes
</P>
<P>
   As an ``image consultant,'' Russ Duritz (Willis) makes a lot of
money telling entrepreneurs to lose the beard if they want to make
the front page of The Wall Street Journal. As a person, he prides
himself on arrogant aloofness and is called a jerk four times a
day. That bothers the chubby little boy (Spencer Breslin) who
suddenly materializes inside Duritz's Hollywood compound.
</P>
<P>
   On first sight of him Russ orders the security turned up to
electrocution level. Shortly afterward, however, he finds Kid, as
Duritz dubs him, munching popcorn in front of his television set.
After the consternation subsides, both make a discovery. Kid is
really Russ Duritz when he was about to turn 8, and he is there to
find out what has gone so wrong in Russ' life that he's about to
turn 40 loveless, childless and (here's the crusher) dogless.
</P>
<P>
   More or less the same question plagues Amy (Mortimer), Russ'
attractive assistant. She and Kid make friends; in fact, Kid,
realizing the opportunity his older self is wasting, actually
proposes to Amy.
</P>
<P>
   But Russ goes on spurning everybody, especially Kid. In boyhood
Rusty, as he was called, was a bit of a klutz, with social troubles
in school and a father who relentlessly applied pressure. Regarding
his childhood self as a loser, Russ doesn't want any part of the
little boy in him now. ``Russ, we have to change,'' says Kid.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE _ None.
</P>
<P>
   SEX _ None.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY _ None.
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-8 _ Kid gets some pretty rough emotional treatment at
times, and this could distress young children.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 9 AND UP _ Willis has already had one spectacularly
successful collaboration with a child character in ``The Sixth
Sense.'' Here the boy's relation to the man is cuter and more
manipulative, and the film, while exploring childhood stress and
exhorting family values, lacks the same kind of intrigue.
</P>
<P>
   The Perfect Storm
</P>
<P>
   George Clooney, Mark Wahlberg, Diane Lane, Elizabeth
Mastrantonio, William Fichtner, Karen Allen, Allen Payne, Bob
Gunton, John C. Reilly
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Wolfgang Petersen
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 _ 150 minutes
</P>
<P>
   ``Could be a triple-header,'' says Linda Greenlaw (Mastrantonio)
over the radio to the sword-boat skipper Billy Tyne (Clooney). With
the swordfish scarce and scrawny on the Grand Banks, Billy has
headed the 90-foot Andrea Gail east toward a dangerous but more
fish-filled area called the Flemish Cap. Heading toward Billy are a
combination of weather conditions ranked in the ``oh, my God''
category.
</P>
<P>
   First there is Hurricane Grace out in the Atlantic. Descending
from Canada is a cold front, and off Nova Scotia another
disturbance is waiting to merge with the other two. ``A disaster of
epic proportions,'' says an excited weatherman, practically
climbing into his computer monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Digital effects churn the seas into black cliffs. A huge
container ship staggers in mountainous swells, spraying tons of
cargo from its decks. A sailboat with three people aboard rolls
completely over and rights itself, the crew sputtering and yelling
mayday. A rescue helicopter falls into the maelstrom.
</P>
<P>
   On the Andrea Gail, still north of major trouble, the crewman
Bobby Shatford (Wahlberg) is starting to get a bad feeling. A shark
washes on deck and chomps his leg. A rogue wave nearly flips the
boat. Fishermen are tossed overboard. When the ice compressor
breaks, Billy swings around and heads back for Gloucester, their
Massachusetts port.
</P>
<P>
   By then they are in the teeth of a once-in-100-years storm.
Billy turns again and tries to run before a following sea. But the
ocean, whipped several ways at once, is back-watering, so to speak,
and the waves are coming from everywhere. The Andrea Gail is
seaworthy, but it can't go vertical.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE _ There are some nasty accidents, and everybody gets
mugged by the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   SEX _ Back in Gloucester, where the women wait, there are
suggestive situations.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY _ The talk is salty.
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-8 _ It gets scary on the water. Parents have been sighted
fleeing theaters with very small children.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 9-11 _ Put on the life vests, but most viewers should ride
it out. The not exactly scintillating preliminaries setting up the
story will claim more victims than the storm.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 12 AND UP _ Beyond big waves this isn't a film with much
appeal for teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle
</P>
<P>
   Rene Russo, Jason Alexander, Robert De Niro, Randy Quaid,
Janeane Garofalo, Piper Perabo and the voices of June Foray and
Keith Scott
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Des McAnuff
</P>
<P>
   PG _ 88 minutes
</P>
<P>
   In 1964 Lyndon Johnson won in a walk, and ``Rocky and
Bullwinkle'' cartoons spread their goofy charm on the tube. Now,
though, residual checks for the squirrel and the moose have shrunk
to 3 and a half cents, and their hometown, Frostbite Falls, Minn.,
is a melting ruin. A trip to Washington seems to be in order _ for
what neither of them is sure _ and off they go at about the same
time their old Cold War foes from Pottsylvania, Fearless Leader,
Boris and Natasha, are springing themselves from cartoonland
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Having tricked a television executive (Garofalo), the three jump
out of a television set and become human. Fearless Leader (De Niro
with dueling scars and a greased-down skull-cap hairdo) plans to
take over the United States by turning the populace into zombies
with very bad television. (What else is new?)
</P>
<P>
   A cherubic FBI agent, Karen Sympathy (Perabo), is sent to
squelch the scheme. Hooked on ``Rocky and Bullwinkle'' reruns
during her formative years, she enlists them for the struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Fearless Leader counters by assigning Boris (Alexander) and
Natasha (Russo) to get rid of all opposition. After a cross-country
chase they fetch up in New York, where a 6-foot-7-inch talking
moose wouldn't get a glance anyway, let alone with the whole city
zombified.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE _ The live-action figures try some cartoon-style
mayhem, but to little lasting effect. For Rocky and Bullwinkle the
problem is that as their old cartoon selves in a live-action world,
they really do go splat falling from heights. Don't worry: they
recover as ever.
</P>
<P>
   SEX _ None.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY _ A modicum.
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-9 _ With cameo appearances by John Goodman, Billy
Crystal, Whoopi Goldberg and Jonathan Winters, the film seems as
geared to baby boomers who doted on Rocky and Bullwinkle in the
'60s as it is to current little ones. Still, there's nothing more
cartoonish than an upright moose and a flying squirrel.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 10 AND UP _ The film is neither here nor there for older
children. Many of the live characters are too old and far removed,
and much of the dialogue falls flat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
