<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1440 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-GAS-TAX-CONGRESS-ART-     07-13 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-TAX-CONGRESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE REJECTS EFFORT TO SUSPEND FEDERAL GASOLINE TAX 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate on Thursday voted overwhelmingly against
suspending the federal gasoline tax through the November election,
calling the measure a calibrated attempt to cozy up to voters at
the expense of the nation's roads and highways.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment required that 60 senators vote to bypass the law
governing the nation's budget. But it was defeated when only 40
senators agreed to waive the law. An additional 59 voted against
waiving the budget law, including 15 Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Despite cries from voters for relief from record-high gasoline
prices, opponents denounced the measure on Thursday, saying it
would conveniently suspend 18.3-cents-a-gallon of the federal gas
tax for 150 days, or until after the November elections, and then
re-institute it. What's more, the measure, attached to a bill that
would reduce inheritance taxes, could imperil favorite road,
highway, bridge and safety projects, opponents asserted.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really in some sense a disingenuous amendment,'' said
Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont. ``It would make Tammany Hall blush. It
purports to lower taxes before an election and then increase taxes
right after the election. I tell you. Is that what the American
public wants us to do?''
</P>
<P>
   The amendment was put forward by Sen. Spencer Abraham, R-Mich.,
who is in a close re-election race, and several other senators from
the Midwest, the region that has been hardest hit by increasing
gasoline prices. Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, a Republican from
oil-rich Texas, also co-sponsored the measure.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks motorists have expressed outrage over high prices at
the pump, turning the increases into a touchy political issue.
Lawmakers have scrambled to appease motorists and assign blame, and
several states went so far as to suspend their own gasoline taxes
temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, the presumed Democratic presidential
nominee, tried to capitalize on the issue by painting his likely
opponent, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, as a lackey for the oil
industry, which has profited from high gas prices. Bush, in turn,
has accused Gore and the Clinton administration of failing to
devise a coherent domestic energy policy and relying too much on
foreign oil. Last month, Gore laid out a plan to reduce dependence
on foreign oil.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission has begun an investigation, at
President Clinton's behest, to determine why gas prices climbed so
high and whether oil companies were engaged in price-fixing.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say gas prices have spiked for a number of reasons:
Past decreases in oil production from oil-producing countries,
pipeline disruptions, shortages at refineries and new rules on
clean-burning fuel have all contributed to the increase.
</P>
<P>
   After peaking several weeks ago, the price of gas is now
falling. Regular gasoline averages $1.59 a gallon both nationally
and in the Midwest, down from average highs of $1.68 nationally and
$1.87 in the Midwest. When prices spiked to that $1.68 figure, they
were nearly 44 percent higher than last summer's average.
</P>
<P>
   Oil producing countries remain reluctant to support Saudi
Arabia's proposal to increase output to send oil prices back to $25
a barrel from the current level of around $30. OPEC nations did
raise output quotas on July 1, but the additional production goals
proposed by Saudi Arabia were criticized by other OPEC members, who
describe current prices as reasonable and supply as sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   While gas prices in the Midwest have eased in the past two
weeks, Abraham said they are still much higher than they were last
year. Mothers with mini-vans, farmers and truckers, some of whom
have lost jobs because they could not afford the gas, deserve
immediate relief, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the one thing we can do in the Congress to bring down the
price of gas and bring it down immediately,'' Abraham said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the opponents of the amendment said a suspension of the
federal gasoline tax would mean an estimated $12 billion loss for
the Highway Trust Fund, which provides vital chunks of money to
build highways, fix roads and maintain safety. Many state and local
leaders also opposed the measure, fearing an interruption in their
own transportation planning. There are also some who make an
economic argument against cutting the price of gasoline, saying it
would only encourage consumers to buy more.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham and others sought to allay those concerns, saying the
$12 billion would be replenished by money from the budget surplus
that is not reserved for Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the highway trust fund were going to be affected at all, I
would not be a sponsor of this amendment,'' Hutchison said.
</P>
<P>
   Most senators disagreed with her assessment. ``It would, over
the long run, put at risk billions of dollars of necessary
investment in our nation's highway infrastructure, while providing
absolutely no guarantee that the consumer will see even one penny
of this tax reduction at the gas pump,'' said Sen. Robert Byrd, the
ranking Democrat on the Appropriations Committee, who called the
measure ``nefarious.''
</P>
<P>
   Countering conventional wisdom, Sen. Daniel Moynihan, D-N.Y.,
said that gasoline prices were not high. In fact, taking inflation
into account, motorists are paying one-third less today than they
were in 1981. ``We are not paying more for gasoline,'' he said.
``We are paying less for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal gasoline tax is actually 18.4 cents per gallon, but
Abraham's amendment protected the .1 cent earmarked for underground
fuel storage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
