<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1444 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ART-NOTES-NYT &LR;      07-13 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GETTY'S NEWEST OLD MASTER; SALE OF THE CONTENTS OF MERCER HOUSE
IN SAVANNAH; APPOINTMENTS AT THE NATIONAL GALLERY OF ART AND THE
HIRSHHORN MUSEUM;   A RESIGNATION AT SOTHEBY'S 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Md., Ga., Ill., England)   By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The J. Paul Getty Museum in Los Angeles had its eye on several
paintings at the old master auctions in London last week. It ended
up buying an El Greco.
</P>
<P>
   Four bidders at Sotheby's on July 6 fought over ``Christ on the
Cross,'' a haunting image of Jesus set against a dark background of
swirling clouds. The Getty ended up buying it for $5.8 million, a
record for the artist.
</P>
<P>
   While many experts thought the museum paid too much, Scott
Schaefer, the Getty's curator of paintings, said he believed the
work was ``the best version of that composition and entirely by the
artist.'' The painting is also ``the first important El Greco to
enter the collection of a Los Angeles museum,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Few paintings can be attributed to El Greco with certainty, and
when Sotheby's had the painting cleaned before it went up for sale,
his signature became clearly visible at the foot of the cross. The
painting also relates closely to others by him, especially in the
manner in which he painted Jesus' attenuated body hanging from the
cross with his head and his eyes looking toward heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Schaefer bid by telephone to George Wachter, director of old
master paintings for Sotheby's worldwide. For a museum to bid
through an auction house executive is rare. Most museums ask a
dealer to bid for them and try to keep their interest secret,
fearing that if word gets out, collectors will be even more eager
to buy the work, increasing not only the competition but also the
price.
</P>
<P>
   ``We choose to bid in different ways,'' said Schaefer, who
worked for Wachter at Sotheby's in New York before joining the
Getty. His museum also bid on de Troy's ``Retour de Bal,'' which
was up for sale at Phillips on July 4. The painting ended up
selling to Konrad O. Bernheimer, a London dealer, for $3.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the Getty did not bid higher for the de Troy, Schaefer
said, ``The problem when a museum buys at auction is that we have
to get approval on the price in advance.'' In this case, he added,
he did not think the painting was worth the selling price.
</P>
<P>
   SALE IN THE GARDEN OF GOOD ...
</P>
<P>
   Those who read ``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil'' or
saw the movie will remember Mercer House, the 19th-century
Italianate mansion in the heart of Savannah, Ga. The house, which
fills a city block, was built for Hugh Mercer, a Civil War general
who settled in Savannah in 1835 and was a great-grandfather of the
songwriter Johnny Mercer. It was also the scene of the 1981
shooting of 21-year-old Danny Hansford, the young lover of Jim
Williams, who owned the house then. Williams, who died in 1990, was
an antiques dealer known for his unusual collection.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 20 Sotheby's is to auction the contents of Mercer House
in a sale that will range from English furniture and export
porcelain to a marble bust of King Edward VII and a sword said to
have been owned by Napoleon II. Sotheby's estimates the sale will
total more than $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The estimate is low, in part because of the objets' decorative
nature and in part because the auction house tends to undervalue
objects in house sales purposely. But that isn't stopping Sotheby's
from treating this as a celebrity sale. As the auction house did
for the four-day sale of the Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis estate in
1996 or the 1998 auction of the contents of the Paris villa that
once belonged to the Duke and Duchess of Windsor, it will recreate
the rooms in Mercer House in its York Avenue galleries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a Southern gentleman's view of the Grand Tour,'' said
Ronald D. Varney, a senior vice president in Sotheby's trusts and
estates department. The Southern gentleman was Williams, who was
tried four times in Hansford's murder and ultimately acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``His taste was showy, but he had a good eye,'' said John
Berendt, author of ``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil.''
``He went for objects with a noble if not royal provenance.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams left the house and its contents to his mother, who left
it to her daughter, Dorothy Williams Kingery. (All Williams had
left his sister in his will was $10, his papers and the rights to
``Psycho Dice,'' a game he invented.) But now that Kingery owns the
house and its contents, she has decided to keep some things for
herself, including an oil sketch by John Singer Sargent that was
estimated at $125,000 to $175,000 when it was was originally listed
with the objects Sotheby's was planning to sell. (People in
Savannah familiar with the work say they believe it was withdrawn
from the sale over a question of authenticity.)
</P>
<P>
   But there are still many curiosities left for Sotheby's to
auction. Among the highlights is the 19th-century Yusupov Dagger,
mounted in silver gilt and turquoise, thought to have been worn and
used in the assassination of the Russian monk Rasputin. Williams
bought the dagger at auction at Sotheby's in 1987 for $15,400,
nearly twice its high estimate of $8,000. This time Sotheby's
experts have not decided on an estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Also for sale is a leather desk folio, mounted on silver gilt
and enamel, with the monogram ``N II,'' made for Czar Nicholas II.
Williams bought the folio at Sotheby's in 1979 for $16,500. Today
it is estimated at $20,000 to $30,000. An ormolu armorial coach
fitting dating from 1810, used for Napoleon's coronation in 1804,
will also be auctioned. One of a pair (the other is in the
Philadelphia Atheneum), it is expected to fetch $20,000 to $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year Mercer House has been on the market through
Sotheby's International Realty and Cora Bett Thomas Realty. The
price was $8.95 million, but it has been reduced to about $7
million, Varney said.
</P>
<P>
   ADD TWO IN WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   Two Washington museums announced appointments this week.
Elizabeth Cropper will become dean of the Center for Advanced Study
in the Visual Arts at the National Gallery of Art. Cropper,
professor of art history at Johns Hopkins University, is replacing
Henry A. Millon, who will retire in December.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Brougher, director of the Museum of Modern Art in Oxford,
England, has been named chief curator of the Hirshhorn Museum and
Sculpture Garden at the Smithsonian Institution. He succeeds Neal
Benezra, who left the Hirshhorn in January to become deputy
director and curator of modern and contemporary art at the Art
Institute of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   SUBTRACT ONE AT SOTHEBY'S
</P>
<P>
   The number of veterans leaving Sotheby's keeps growing. The
latest is Katherine Ross, who has been at the auction house for 16
years, most recently as a senior vice president and director of
museum services in New York. She has been named senior vice
president for public relations and communications at Prada, the
fashion company, where she will oversee publicity and special
events.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
