<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH IS MUM ON CHOOSING RUNNING MATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas said Thursday that his
campaign had begun ``serious vetting'' of the financial and medical
records of the top candidates to be his running mate, and he said
he did not intend to run the finalists through a public interview
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something I can do to bring some order and privacy to
the process,'' Bush told reporters on his campaign plane. ``It
doesn't suit my style to say, `Hey, so and so's coming in,' and
have the person have to walk through a bunch of reporters to have
the discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said only his wife and Dick Cheney, the former congressman
at the head of his search process, knew his thinking on the issue.
He said he had learned the dangers of being too public from
watching his father select Dan Quayle. He said that since
``everybody knew'' who was on George Bush's short list, it was easy
for Quayle's selection to leak out.
</P>
<P>
   With the Republican National Convention little more than two
weeks away, speculation has been mounting and Bush received a
barrage of questions at a news conference here on whether he would
select Gov. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania, who was at his side. ``I'm
not telling you,'' he replied. Many Republicans believe Ridge's
choice is unlikely because his support for abortion rights would
create a storm among conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had some rare praise for his opponent, Vice President Al
Gore, naming him, along with Walter Mondale, Quayle and his own
father as recent vice presidents who had all served their
presidents well.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of them have been very good vice presidents,'' he said.
``All of them were assigned specific tasks. All of them gave
counsel to their presidents and all of them did a very good job at
keeping their counsel private.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor also said that Gore was a forceful debater.
But Bush was soon back to jabbing at Gore over his campaign style
and fighting with him over the state of the Texas budget.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also unveiled a proposal for a $75 million five-year
program of grants to community groups to use veterans as mentors
and role models in programs for children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 2042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
