<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1449 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-YORUBA-AMERICAS-ART-N     07-13 1279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YORUBA-AMERICAS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: THE SOUL OF A CULTURE GLEAMS FROM COUNTLESS BEADS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Exhibition notes at end of review.) 
 By ROBERTA SMITH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A diaspora is a many-leveled thing, for the simple
reason that people never travel light. No matter how meager their
physical possessions, they carry beliefs, traditions,
sensibilities, ways of talking, thinking, seeing and doing, all in
their heads. Wherever they arrive, things are never the same:
Sooner or later there are modulations, great or small, in local
habits of clothing, religion, diet and art and much else. Something
new has been added.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, one of the world's great beneficiaries of
diasporas, this process is everywhere visible. We move through it
daily in a diffuse, taken-for-granted, way. In a subway ride, a
change of blocks or boroughs, even a walk around a corner, it is
possible to dip into another culture, a different way of life.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it never hurts to see the rhythms of this process in
isolation, especially when they are traced through the migration of
an entrancing, universally loved artistic form and presented in
visually dazzling terms. This is the achievement of ``Beads, Body
and Soul: Art and Light in the Yoruba Universe.''
</P>
<P>
   The show, as opulent as it is edifying, follows the migration of
one people's beading tradition, and the religious beliefs it
reflects, from Africa to various parts of the Americas. Originally
organized by the Fowler Museum of Cultural History at UCLA, this
effort is now split between two of New York's smaller, more
innovative arts institutions: The Museum for African Art in SoHo
and the Studio Museum in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   The Yoruba people are not alone in attributing spiritual power
and religious meaning to beads or in grasping their visual and
decorative potential. But they may be somewhat unusual in doing
both at the same time. And this double intensity helps explain why
their use of beads, and the immense faith they have in them,
survived the devastations and dispersals of the slave trade to
flourish in the Americas, especially in Brazil and Cuba, where
Yoruba descendants are most plentiful, and in New York, which has
sizable populations of Afro-Cubans and Afro-Brazilians as well as
African-Americans of Yoruba descent.
</P>
<P>
   Yoruba beading, its sources, techniques, meanings and
permutations in this hemisphere, form a rich, complex subject, as
this show's lavishly illustrated, multischolar catalog suggests. It
is an implicitly hybrid art. An indigenous bead language using
oil-palm seeds and kernels, carved wood beads and especially cowrie
shells (still the aristocrat of Yoruba beads) was irrevocably
expanded when Europeans began taking tiny pierced bits of glass and
ceramic to Africa as early as the 15th century.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a pervasive art: Yorubans have made necklaces,
bracelets and bead-covered objects central to both religious and
daily life, to expressions of faith and social rank. The beads'
pure colors heightened the chromatic symbolism of the Yoruba
religious cosmos with its hierarchies of spirits, ancestors and
gods, or orisa, each distinguished by specific hues. Beads adorn
the ritual objects and regalia of those gods' earthly
representatives: Kings and queens, priests, diviners and healers.
The one-by-one equality of stringed beads is seen as a reflecting
the consensus-oriented Yoruba social structure. The word for bead
reoccurs in their language, in metaphors for riches of all kinds:
Children, wealth, solidarity and wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   The journey plotted by this exhibition begins at the Museum for
African Art, with displays of necklaces and objects using
indigenous beads: Necklaces of palm-oil seeds, a small shrine
dangling heavy strands of cowrie shells. Especially notable are
three small wood figures of Esu-Elegba, the god who mediates the
threshold between the mortal and the spirit worlds, festooned with
strands of lustrous kernels, cowries and carved wood amulets.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition first proceeds by deity. There are beaded sword
sheaths associated with Ogun, god of iron and warfare; a staff for
Orisa Oko, the god of agriculture, its tall beaded sheath decorated
with sculptures of women; a wonderful fat puppet for Sanyin, the
god of healing.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear that the introduction of brighter color made
possible what might be called portable mosaics, objects whose
colored images and rich patterns radiate joy, order and reverence
as surely as anything at Ravenna. It also seems to have made
possible the development of a pictorial, two-dimensional language
equal to but different from the sculptural tradition already in
place. Among the exhibition's most engaging objects are several
pairs of Ibeji, or sacred twins, small carved wood figures whose
little beaded tunics gleam with geometric patterns and images.
These are grouped near an extraordinary full-sized tunic, whose
surfaces, worked and reworked with beads and cowries, resembles a
lovingly tended shrine.
</P>
<P>
   One sees the mingling of cultures on all sides. A king's regalia
include a beaded chair whose floral patterns might be English and a
gown beaded in gold, white and blue whose spiraling forms can also
be found on Islamic tiles. (The surface includes the date of
coronation date, 1934). Across the way, some beaded crowns and
coronets borrow the forms of a bishop's miter and an British
barrister's wig. Others, more indigenous, are dramatically
sculptural conical crowns whose beaded surfaces are decorated with
schematic faces and topped with beaded birds and other animals. A
group of ``House of the Head'' shrines, containing the small beaded
personal pyramids, or ``inner heads,'' which Yoruba people receive
at birth, bristle majestically with cowrie shells.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition at the Museum for African Art ends with a display
of the diviner's regalia: beaded tapers, chains, bags and
necklaces, as well as two stunning examples of the elaborate
head-to-toe ensembles worn during Egungun ceremonies, which honor
ancestors. Suggesting a cross between a Muslim chador and something
suitable for a Venetian masked ball, they combine layers of dark
rich fabric with glittering panels and veils of beads.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition at the Studio Museum in Harlem, which is
relatively sparse, examines the Yoruba beading and religious
practices in the Americas, where orisa permutated into Santeria in
Cuba and Candomble in Brazil while retaining the same gods. The
show is arranged in a series of altars containing objects made by
contemporary artists, many of whom are also priests.
</P>
<P>
   The altars seem a bit flimsy, partly because, once again, the
objects themselves exude such concentrated power. Nonetheless, Jose
Rodriguez's crown for Oblata, a god of ancient wisdom, which is
rendered in white, silver and blue beading and topped with a bird
riding an elephant, has the radiant perfection of anything in the
downtown show. And one sees new variations on older themes and
forms. In Shona Sloan-Shango Ni Ohun's paintinglike ``Beaded
Portrait Portrait of a Devotee of Orisa Shango,'' includes
depictions of a rattle and conical crown like those displayed
downtown; they belong to a figure who resembles the bead-garbed
twins at the SoHo museum.
</P>
<P>
   Works like these suggest that the beading tradition the Yoruba
people set forth is alive, well and in good hands. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Beads, Body and Soul: Art and Light in the Yoruba Universe''
is at the Museum for African Art, 593 Broadway, near Houston
Street, SoHo, (212) 966-1313, through Aug. 27, and at the Studio
Museum in Harlem, 145 West 125th Street, (212) 864-4500, through
Sept. 17.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 2046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
