<HEADER>
A1450 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-VETS-HNS &LR;      07-13 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-VETS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SAYS VP PICK MUST BE WILLING TO PLAY 2ND FIDDLE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ A vice president must be qualified to assume the
nation's top job if necessary, but Republican presidential
candidate George W. Bush indicated Thursday that his running mate
also must be a loyal confidant willing to live in the chief
executive's shadow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make certain the person I pick is somebody with whom
I can get along and don't have to be looking over my shoulder or
worrying about my back if I become the president,'' Bush said
Thursday at a news conference in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking earlier in the day with reporters on his campaign
airplane, Bush praised the past four vice presidents _ including
his Democratic rival, Al Gore _ as men who had fulfilled that role.
He said Democrats Walter Mondale and Gore as well as fellow
Republicans Dan Quayle and Bush's own father, former Vice President
and President George Bush, had served loyally.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of them were assigned specific tasks, all of them gave
their counsel to the president and all of them did a very good job
of keeping their counsel private,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to have a vice president who brings a lot of added
value,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush denied a published report that he had narrowed his list to
New York Gov. George Patatki, former GOP presidential candidate
Elizabeth Dole and Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge. But he told
reporters in Pennsylvania that Ridge is still under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Others known still to be in the running include U.S. Rep. John
Kasich of Ohio and Oklahoma Gov. Frank Keating.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he feels sorry for political reporters who are under
pressure from their editors to break the story on his running mate
choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not want to be in your position where your job
performance is somehow measured on your ability to be first to
figure out what's on my mind,'' said Bush, who said he wants to
announce his choice to the news media and the nation at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaigned in Pennsylvania and New Jersey on Thursday,
laying out a $75 million proposed program to help pay for military
veterans to serve as mentors and tutors for youth. The money would
be distributed as federal grants to community programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Pennsylvania Democratic Party used the visit as an
opportunity to renew questions about whether Bush received
favorable treatment when he was on temporary duty with the Alabama
Air National Guard in 1972 and 1973 while working on a U.S. Senate
campaign. There is no record of Bush actually pulling duty while in
the Alabama guard on a transfer from his Texas guard unit.
</P>
<P>
   Bush defended his service, saying the proof is in the fact that
he was discharged honorably after serving as an F-102 pilot in
Texas. Bush said he served with the Alabama guard but did not fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done what I said I did,'' Bush said. ``I fulfilled my
obligation. I proudly served.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
