<SLUG> BC-GORE-INTERVIEW-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE GETS LONG-AWAITED ENDORSEMENT FROM BRADLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHARLES POPE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREEN BAY, Wis. _ Bill Bradley, once a bitter rival of Al Gore
for the Democratic presidential nomination, enthusiastically
endorsed the vice president Thursday, providing a shot of momentum
that Gore believes will pay rich dividends in tossup states like
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In only his second public appearance since dropping out of the
Democratic race in March and his first with Gore, Bradley gave Gore
his biggest wish _ a strong, unequivocal endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect his judgement and have an interest in his thoughts
and recommendations,'' Gore said in an interview after the rally at
an amusement park on the shore of Green Bay. ``This is a very big
endorsement that will help quite a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore touched on a variety of issues in the interview, ranging
from patients' bill of rights legislation to the fate of Northwest
salmon. Among his comments:
</P>
<P>
   _On salmon and the possible breaching of Snake River dams: He
believes it is possible to bring various factions together to work
out a solution based on the best science available. ``Extinction is
not an option, nor is economic dislocation.''
</P>
<P>
   _On patients' bill of rights: ``You deserve the best health
care, not just the cheapest,'' he said, repeating a theme made
earlier in his speech. ``I am tired of life and death decisions
being made by HMO accountants and insurance company clerks _ people
at the other end of a telephone line who have no license to
practice medicine, and no right to play God.''
</P>
<P>
   _On entitlement programs: Gore said he would not privatize
Social Security. ``Let's put both Social Security and Medicare in
an off-budget, iron-clad lockbox where politicians can't touch
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he believes his campaign is finally hitting its stride
after months of spotty performances. The turnaround began more than
a month ago, he said, ``but I think it's been especially noticeable
the past three weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons, he said can be found in changing public attitudes
as well as in a change in him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that people are beginning to look at the importance of
prosperity and progress and why it makes sense to continue it,'' he
said. ``I think I'm doing a little bit better job of communicating
personally. And I think there's a groundswell in the country for
the kind of continued positive change that I represent.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president was obviously pleased by Bradley's comments
and his vigorous defense of Gore's policies, even though long
delayed. Bradley's support is important to Gore because it could
keep voters from defecting to Green Party candidate Ralph Nader.
Gore aides have become increasingly worried that Nader's appeal
could be particularly strong in states like Washington and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley, in his comments, left nothing to doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here in Green Bay ... because I believe what Vince
Lombardi once said is true. `Winning is a team sport,'''said
Bradley, standing with Gore at the same amusement park pavilion
that Franklin Roosevelt visited in 1934 to promote the New Deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make it clear that I endorse Al Gore for president
of the United States,'' Bradley said to rising applause. ``I
believe that under his leadership we will come closer to solving
the problems I mentioned earlier than under the leadership of Gov.
George Bush. And it's not even a close call.''
</P>
<P>
   In accepting Bradley's endorsement, Gore effusively praised the
former senator from New Jersey, a stark contrast to the lacerating
attacks he launched during the primaries. The lingering anger over
that treatment is one reason Bradley did not come out sooner for
Gore, Bradley aides said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I treasure Bill Bradley's support,'' Gore told a crowd of
several hundred supporters on a sunny, hot day. ``He is a good
Democrat who speaks and stands for principles we all believe in.
And Bill Bradley will be an important part of this campaign _ and
an important part of America's future.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, however, called Gore's appearance with Bradley an
act of desperation that underscored how wobbly his campaign is.
Like Washington state, Wisconsin has been a reliable state for
Democrats in recent elections but is up for grabs this year. Like
Washington state, Wisconsin has five Democrats in the U.S. House
and four Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have a lot of good to say about Al Gore,'' Bush
spokesman Dan Bartlett said. ``Al Gore still struggles to bring his
party together.''
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts in the Northwest, however, said Bradley's
support will help Gore. ``Being seen with Bradley is the most
dramatic move he could make,'' said Don Balmer, who teaches
political science at Lewis &AMP; Clark College in Portland. ``There is
no other dominant personality out there. Clinton carried the area,
the economy is good. It's more or less his to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim McDermott, D-Wash., who supported Bradley during the
primaries, agreed. ``I don't think there will be any question but
it will be helpful to him.''
</P>
<P>
   The joint appearance, McDermott said, draws attention to Gore at
a time when the campaigns ``are in the doldrums. There's not much
happening anyplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from acknowledging Bradley's support, Gore stuck to the
same themes he's been focusing on for the past two weeks,
attempting to link Bush to special interests such as the gun lobby
and ``big oil'' while touting the economic boom that has occurred
under the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Gore also pointed out budget problems now afflicting
Bush's home state.
</P>
<P>
   Texas officials reported Wednesday that the state's budget is
$610 million out of balance. Democrats blamed the shortfall on $1.7
billion in tax cuts pushed by Bush. Bush, however, said the deficit
was caused by unexpected high costs in programs such as Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   The news about Texas' budget woes capped one of the Gore
campaign's best weeks in months.
</P>
<P>
   The event in Green Bay marked the next step in a weeklong effort
to link Bush to a Congress controlled by Republicans and beholden
to special interests. In a standard speech delivered throughout the
week, Gore targeted the issues that polls say voters find most
important: education, health care, Social Security and the economy.
</P>
<P>
   And in an indication of how rocky Gore's campaign has been, his
aides were openly pleased that they were able to go an entire week
without being sidetracked by problems.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Gore said he is unfazed by many recent polls,
including one in Washington state, that show him trailing Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't particularly focus on polls, whether they go up down
or sideways,'' he said. ``The level of real support for the choices
the country has to make will, I think, be affected by Senator
Bradley, by his endorsement, by his presence. I think it will have
an effect on the election. The polls, I don't know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
