<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR FRIDAY, JULY 14
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Friday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-NYT (moved Tuesday, July 11)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, July 11
about efforts by Mexico's governing party to regroup after losing
the presidential election misstated the name of a faction leader,
the governor of Tabasco state. He is Roberto Madrazo Pintado;
Tabasco is not part of the name.
</P>
<P>
   BC-JEWISH-PRESS-MEDIA-NYT (moved Sunday, July 9) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, July 9
about pressures on The Jewish Week after its report on accusations
of abuse of teen-agers by a rabbi in Paramus, N.J., gave an
outdated name for a Jewish organization to which the paper has
ties. It is the United Jewish Communities; the United Jewish Appeal
was one element of a merger that created the new group last year,
with the Council of Jewish Federations and the United Israel
Appeal.
</P>
<P>
   BC-NY-COWS-NYT (moved Tuesday, July 11)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, July 11
about fiberglass cows on exhibition in the New York area
misidentified the building where Fresco, a cow reclining in an
inner tube, is displayed. The building (formerly named for Exxon)
is now known by its address, 1251 Avenue of the Americas. (The
McGraw-Hill Building is at 1221 Avenue of the Americas.)
</P>
</TEXT>
