<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WorldCom and Sprint End Their Agreement to Merge
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom and Sprint officially abandoned their $115 billion
merger, bowing to pressure from regulators, who were concerned that
the creation of such a large telecommunications company would
stifle competition. Far from dampening the outlook for ever-larger
communications concerns, the dissolution of the agreement fueled
speculation about consolidation among large telecommunications
companies, with both WorldCom and Sprint being mentioned as
potential takeover targets for foreign companies. Shares in
WorldCom rose $3.4375, to $47.9375, while shares of Sprint
increased 68.75 cents, to $48.
</P>
<P>
   Two Insurers Face Bias Lawsuits
</P>
<P>
   MetLife and Prudential Insurance have been accused in two
class-action lawsuits of charging their black customers higher
premiums for life insurance than white customers. The companies
said that they stopped using race as a factor about 50 years ago
but that some of these remained in effect. They said they stopped
collecting premiums on the policies in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Outpaces Dow and S&AMP;P
</P>
<P>
   Strong quarterly reports touched off new buying in technology
stocks, lifting the Nasdaq composite index 75.27 points, or 1.8
percent, to 4,174.86. The rest of the market mostly languished as
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 2.92 points, or 0.2
percent, to 1,495.84, and the Dow Jones industrial average edged up
5.30 points, or 0.05 percent, to 10,788.71.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Rejects Hold on Gas Tax
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted against suspending the federal gasoline tax
through the November election, calling the measure a calibrated
attempt to cozy up to voters at the expense of the nation's roads
and highways.
</P>
<P>
   Tyco Says SEC Inquiry Is Over
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission has ended its
investigation of Tyco International's accounting practices without
taking action against the company, Tyco said. The news helped lift
shares of Tyco $3, to $51.50.
</P>
<P>
   GE Earnings Increase by 20 Percent
</P>
<P>
   General Electric, benefiting from a robust economy and its
aggressive push into selling products online, said that its
second-quarter earnings rose 20 percent, beating Wall Street
projections by a penny.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising Bursts Into Song
</P>
<P>
   Television commercials that feature elaborate musical production
numbers, long out of favor on Madison Avenue, are making a
comeback. Big advertisers, like the Gap, are offering viewers
minimusicals with maxi-casts for products as disparate as books,
shampoo, apparel, soft drinks, cleaners and credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   Price of Imported Goods Up 0.8 Percent
</P>
<P>
   The price of goods imported to the United States rose 0.8
percent last month, the fastest pace since February, driven by a
jump in oil costs, government figures showed.
</P>
<P>
   Ford to Take a $3.3 Billion Charge
</P>
<P>
   Ford will take $3.3 billion in charges for costs of spinning off
its Visteon parts unit and reorganizing its European business,
resulting in its first quarterly loss since the end of 1992.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
