<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STALLED SUMMIT COULD TAKE LONGER THAN PLANNED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT AND ANN SCALES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ President Clinton returned to Camp David
Thursday night as Israeli and Palestinian envoys ended their third
day of negotiations, rejoining a summit that has not yet reported
progress and could continue longer than initially planned.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials refused to describe the substance of
the talks, but said that Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat held their first face-to-face
meeting without Clinton the night before. Flanked by aides, the two
leaders met for about an hour in Arafat's lodging, then joined
Clinton at a Mediterranean barbecue dinner that lasted late into
Wednesday night, an official said.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton left Thursday morning to give a speech in Baltimore
and attend a White House news conference, a senior Israeli official
described the mood at the summit as ``carefully optimistic.'' Rabbi
Michael Melchior, a member of Barak's Cabinet who serves as
minister of diaspora affairs, flew to Washington with Barak earlier
in the week and had spoken to members of the delegation three or
four times since the talks began, said he was left with the
impression the talks were going reasonably well. But he suggested
the most critical discussions were still ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have certain limitations,'' Melchior said of coming weekend
and the Jewish Sabbath, during which observant Jews are not
permitted to engage in any work. ``But these will be very crucial
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Melchior, along with other Israeli officials, did not rule out
the possibility that the talks might continue well into next week,
perhaps even after Clinton's scheduled departure next Wednesday for
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are prepared to remain as long as necessary. We could
continue while the president is away,'' said Barak spokesman Gadi
Baltiansky.
</P>
<P>
   But a State Department official indicated that Clinton would
stick to his original schedule, which calls for the talks to end by
Wednesday. ``We remain on the same schedule that we started with,''
spokesman Richard Boucher said. Boucher said that both Clinton and
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright other plans after Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, an Israeli official who is not participating
in the talks indicated that Barak might take the difficult step of
agreeing to swap tracts of land with the Palestinian Authority in
order to reach an agreement during this negotiating session _ an
idea that has been debated since 1995 but was injected into the
debate anew Thursday on Israeli radio. The notion was that Israel
might give up areas of undeveloped land bordering the
Palestinian-controlled Gaza Strip in return for keeping areas on
the West Bank where Israeli settlements have been built.
</P>
<P>
   Yossi Beilin, the Israeli justice minister who is considered a
chief architect of the Oslo Accords that paved the way for the
current talks, said Barak and Arafat ``will talk about swapping
land.'' Other analysts said they believed a swap would be a
necessity for a peace deal, allowing Arafat to return home with an
agreement under which Israel makes concessions, not just the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Melchior, who did not attend the negotiations but met with
reporters about 15 miles away from Camp David, said a land swap,
like many other options, remained a possibility. ``I'm sure
everything is being discussed,'' Melchior said.
</P>
<P>
   Three members of the Palestinian Liberation Organization's
executive committee arrived in Washington Thursday and indicated
they hoped to meet with Clinton and the negotiators at Camp David.
US officials, after first claiming not to have known about their
intentions, seemed to soften their opposition to allowing them at
the presidential retreat.
</P>
<P>
   The three PLO members _ identified as Tayseer Khaled of the
radical Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine, Suleiman
al-Najab of the Marxist Palestinian People's Party, and Sameer
Ghosheh of the Popular Struggle Front _ had opposed the Oslo
accord. But their support would be necessary now for Arafat to cut
a workable deal that would be acceptable to most Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a request, it will be for the US, by agreement of
the parties, to make a judgment about where these people should
come to the camp,'' one US official said. A decision, the official
said, would be based ``on their overall value to the
negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department continued its blanket of secrecy on the
substance of the talks. Boucher, beginning his daily press
briefing, welcomed reporters to the ``daily press blackout.'' And
Clinton, before returning to Camp David after spending the day at
an NAACP convention and meetings at the White House, told reporters
a peace agreement could well be predicated on silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The less I say, the greater our chances of success,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
