<DOCNO> NYT20000713.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1464 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AIRBUS-NEW-JET-ART-2T     07-13 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRBUS-NEW-JET-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUEEN OF THE SKIES OR ALBATROSS? AIRBUS' $10 BILLION GAMBLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT7 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) By JOHN
TAGLIABUE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOULOUSE, France _ Another white elephant like the Concorde? An
extravagance like the English Channel tunnel? Or a bet-the-company
gamble that will prove just as successful as the Boeing 747 it
hopes to succeed?
</P>
<P>
   Europe has a couple of gigantic transportation debacles to its
credit. The supersonic Concorde jetliner sounded promising, yet
never got beyond a production run of about 20 airplanes, and has
been confined for the past quarter of a century to a single
trans-Atlantic route connecting New York with London and Paris. The
Channel tunnel, though an operating success since it opened in
1994, cost $15 billion to build, double the original estimate, and
accumulated a $14 billion mountain of debt.
</P>
<P>
   Yet now the European Airbus Industrie group is close to
introducing another transportation behemoth, a gigantic
double-decker jumbo jet, known for now as the A3XX, for use on long
distance routes like those between Asia and Europe or the United
States. With a capacity of between 555 and 800 passengers, it would
carry at least 140 passengers more than the largest Boeing 747. And
its development cost is expected to exceed $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing remains skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think there is a market for this kind of aircraft, but a
very, very limited market,'' said John Dern, a Boeing spokesman in
Seattle. Boeing calculates that demand over the next 20 years for
jetliners in the 400 passenger and up category will amount to
``fewer than 400,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing itself is ``actively discussing'' with potential
customers its own alternative _ a stretched version of the 747 _
but a final decision on whether to build it has not been reached,
he added.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Airbus remains adamant that Europe's experience will be
different this time. Unlike the Concorde, its proposed A3XX is
encountering strong interest among airlines, Airbus officials say.
Unlike the channel tunnel, they insist, it would be financed in a
way that would avoid a financial debacle.
</P>
<P>
   To get ready for the project, Airbus _ a loose consortium of
four big European aerospace companies, Aerospatiale of France;
DaimlerChrysler Aerospace of Germany; BAE Systems of Britain,
formerly known as British Aerospace; and Construcciones
Aeronauticas of Spain _ is recasting its corporate structure. Its
French, German and Spanish partners are in the process of merging
to form the European Aeronautics Defense and Space Co.
</P>
<P>
   EADS, as the company is known, will be the world's third-largest
aerospace group after Boeing and Lockheed Martin, both U.S.
companies, and its shares _ a 30 percent stake _ began trading on
European stock exchanges on Monday. Originally, the company had
hoped to raise $3.5 billion offering shares for 22-24 euros each,
but underwriters lowered that price to 19 euros to bring in about
$3 billion before public trading began. In the first day of
trading, the stock dropped about 10 percent in Frankfurt, Germany;
Madrid, Spain, and Paris to about 17 euros. Since then, shares have
climbed back to close Thursday on the German Bourse in Frankfurt at
18.10 euros.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus itself will become a unified, more easily manageable
corporation owned 80 percent by EADS and 20 percent by BAE Systems.
In return, European governments have pledged development aid for
the A3XX in the form of refundable loans.
</P>
<P>
   From the European perspective, the motivation for the A3XX is
clear. By all estimates, civilian air travel will continue to grow
into the new century at a rate of about 5 percent a year. Yet
Boeing, with its 747, has a monopoly on the largest aircraft, those
with more than 400 seats, which are expected to account for about
one-quarter of all civilian aircraft sales. The A3XX is in fact
only part of a broader effort by Airbus to challenge Boeing in
every sector above the 100-seat jetliner.
</P>
<P>
   For Boeing, the consequences are potentially devastating. For
years the 747, the uncontested queen of the skies and the flagship
of most of the world's major airlines, has been Boeing's cash cow,
accounting in good years for roughly half of Boeing's profits.
``It's a huge, huge item for Boeing,'' said Joseph Campbell Jr., an
analyst who follows Boeing at Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the new Airbus jumbo jet threatens Boeing's dominance
in Japan, where the 747 is king, and where Boeing enjoys cozy
relations with both carriers and industrial suppliers of parts for
its planes. To respond, Boeing is studying the possibility of
investing $3 billion to $4 billion in a stretch version of the 747,
for 500 passengers, that would compete head-to-head with the A3XX.
</P>
<P>
   For Airbus, the stakes are perhaps even greater. Airbus
jetliners account for 70 percent of the revenue of EADS, its
biggest shareholder, and failure of the A3XX would be a serious
burden as the new aerospace giant seeks to lift off the ground.
Moreover, as the first project in which Airbus is relying
principally on capital markets rather than government aid, a
debacle would sour relations with investors.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of this year, Airbus will have to decide whether
sufficient demand for the new aircraft exists to justify starting
construction. Assuming it decides to go ahead, as most experts
expect it will, the first test flights will be in mid-2004, and the
first aircraft will be delivered in the fall of 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Still, big obstacles remain. For one thing, Washington is eyeing
suspiciously the intention of European governments to help finance
the A3XX, and the project affords the potential for a major
trans-Atlantic trade war. Since Airbus got started in the early
1970s, successive White Houses have objected to its financing
through government loans. The Europeans counter that Pentagon
spending is tantamount to a hidden subsidy to big U.S. aerospace
contractors, including Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, a compromise agreement was reached regulating aid to
the industry, but both Boeing and the next president face tough
decisions on whether to challenge, or perhaps even discard, the
1992 agreement if the A3XX project proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest question is whether Airbus can get enough orders
to make the project ultimately profitable. Airbus executives have
told analysts that they must sell about 240 of the planes before
turning a profit, though they will not say within what time frame.
Campbell of Lehman Brothers calculates Airbus will have to sell at
least 150 A3XX jetliners by 2010 for it to succeed. With Boeing
offering a less expensive alternative, that is a tall order to
fill.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Still, many say the project makes sense. Nine key customers have
said they are interested, six publicly, including Emirates
Airlines, Air France, Singapore Airlines, the International Lease
Finance Corp., Qantas, and Virgin Group's Virgin Atlantic. And the
A3XX, while more expensive initially, would be cheaper to operate
on a per-seat basis than a 747, Airbus officials say.
</P>
<P>
   As much as Boeing dreads the prospect, airline companies, like
car buyers entering a showroom, relish the idea of having more
bargaining clout. When airlines go to Boeing headquarters, said
Daniel Solon, managing director of Avmark International Ltd., a
London airline consultant, ``at every other category you can say,
`The other guy has such and such. What can you do for us?'''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Airbus, as much as it looks forward to making itself
Boeing's equal up and down the line, cannot make the decision
lightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a case of betting the company,'' said Chris Partridge, an
analyst at Deutsche Bank Securities in London. ``But then, isn't
that what Boeing did with the 747?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, such a huge project seems almost a natural to a
Continent that brought forth the Concorde and the channel tunnel.
But at a time when governments in Europe are constrained by the
fiscal requirements for the euro, the single currency introduced
last year, and companies like Airbus and its shareholders rely
increasingly on capital markets, it will not be easy.
</P>
<P>
   Noel Forgeard, the Airbus chief executive, insists the A3XX is
not the huge gamble it has been portrayed. ``It's a figurehead, but
it's certainly not the only project we have,'' he said in an
interview at Airbus headquarters outside this southern French city.
Indeed, he added, relative to the size of the company, which last
year generated sales of 15.7 billion euros, or $15 billion, it is
not even as ambitious as the 1990s project to develop the A320
family of wide-bodied jets.
</P>
<P>
   Gamble or not, the A3XX is daunting. At 239 feet, it is not much
longer than the biggest 747s, but it would boast two full passenger
decks, one above the other, plus a windowless third deck below that
could be used for cargo or passenger services. Since the plane
would be flown mostly on long-haul routes, like London to Australia
or Hong Kong to Los Angeles, Airbus officials fancifully describe
the possibility of installing fitness rooms, a duty free shop, even
a McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   They describe first-class amenities that could include sleeping
berths, roomy lounges and cocktail bars _ evoking a cruise liner
more than a jetliner. Some experts are skeptical, believing the
temptation to squeeze in large numbers of passengers will prevail.
``In the end, it could be more steerage,'' said Avmark's Solon,
``than Queen Mary.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its size, Airbus boasts that the A3XX will not tax
airports more than a 747. Though weighing 590 metric tons, 150 tons
more than the biggest 747, an innovative design for the wheel
carriage would spread the weight over the tarmac. Most airports
will disembark passengers from one level, though newer airports
like Hong Kong will be able to link passenger gangways at both
upper and lower levels. At any rate, Airbus has assured airlines
that the turnaround of the A3XX _ the time needed to unload
passengers, cargo and baggage, and be refitted for flight _ would
be no longer than the scheduled 90 minutes for the 747.
</P>
<P>
   For financial planners, of course, the monster is the aircraft's
costs. Forgeard estimates total development costs of 10.7 billion
euros, about $10.2 billion, though some experts believe they could
run as much as $20 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Forgeard said about 4 billion euros will be raised by
risk-sharing partners who will supply parts in exchange for
providing financing. Another 2 billion euros will be raised with
government loans, and the rest through the bond market and by
selling stock.
</P>
<P>
   To persuade airlines of its cost effectiveness, Airbus argues
that to break even, the A3XX must fill just 323 of its 555 seats,
or only 33 more than the 747 must fill to be profitable, yet offers
232 more seats for additional ticket sales, against the 747's 123.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the Clinton administration or its successor may
be tempted to bring Airbus before the World Trade Organization if
American officials believe they can make the case that European
governements are providing improper subsidies. But Boeing, worrying
about a backlash among its airline customers and suppliers who
build for both airline makers, could be reluctant to encourage such
an action. And if Washington presses the case, Airbus pledges to
fight back.
</P>
<P>
   American companies stand to profit by supplying parts like
engine supports, landing gear, evacuation systems and much of the
electronics for the A3XX. If airlines choose engines from a
consortium of General Electric and United Technologies' Pratt &AMP;
Whitney, one of two engine suppliers, American-made equipment could
account for roughly one-third the value.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of this year the EADS board plans to decide whether
to begin construction. Forgeard, a board member, said the decision
would hinge as much on the quality of the orders as on their
quantity. Some airlines, he said, because of their sway within the
industry, `'will have more influence in terms of a domino effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Forgeard, clearly hinting he favors a go-ahead, says the biggest
risk for Airbus would be not to gamble.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would be a real bet,'' he said, ``would be to neglect an
important part of the market, or address it with programs not
compatible with our resources.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
