<HEADLINE>
CLINTON HOPES TO REINVIGORATE MIDEAST SUMMIT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Editors: In 2nd graf, ``today'' refers to Friday. Includes trim
indicator.) 
 
By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ Buoyed by a new U.S.-Vietnam trade agreement,
President Clinton returned to Camp David late Thursday saying he
intends to bring fresh energy to peace talks between Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton took an eight-hour break from the negotiations _ which
today enter their fourth day _ to address the NAACP convention in
Baltimore and appear at a Capitol Hill awards ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   During his absence, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright met
with Barak and members of the Israeli delegation, but a similar
session with Arafat was put off. Officials declined to say who
postponed the meeting or why.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Barak and Arafat held their first meeting without
U.S. officials present. Except to say the two leaders seriously
discussed the core issues that must be resolved as part of the
peace terms, officials declined to say whether there was any
breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   These include the status of Jerusalem, the nature and borders of
a Palestinian state, the future of Jewish settlers in the West Bank
and Gaza Strip, and whether more than 2 million Palestinian
refugees will be allowed to return to their homes in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Before flying back to Camp David on Thursday afternoon, Clinton
praised the U.S.-Vietnam trade agreement, saying it will provide an
example for Arafat and Barak.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agreement is one more reminder that former adversaries
can come together to find common ground in a way that benefits all
their people, to let go of the past and embrace the future, to
forgive and reconcile,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take the energy I feel here from all these people back to
Camp David and make the argument that they should follow suit,''
Clinton said. Standing with him in the White House Rose Garden were
representatives of the Vietnamese government and former Vietnamese
prisoners of war now serving in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Before setting out for the remote presidential retreat in
Maryland's Catoctin Mountains, Clinton declined to answer questions
about the peace talks, which are being carried out under a rigid
secrecy rule imposed by the U.S. hosts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I should say nothing about what's going on at Camp
David,'' the president said. ``The less I say, the greater our
chances of success.''
</P>
<P>
   While U.S. officials tried to keep a lid on details of the
negotiations, some purported details emerged, mostly from Middle
East sources.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, Cabinet minister Haim Ramon, a Barak confidant, said
a proposed land swap _ unpopulated land inside Israel's borders in
exchange for West Bank land currently occupied by Jewish settlers _
was on the table. It was the first time an Israeli official had
publicly acknowledged willingness to consider such a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Arab legislator Ahmed Tibi, a former adviser to
Arafat, said the two sides had agreed that Jewish settlements in
the Gaza Strip would be abandoned as part of a peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher declined comment.
``We're going to hear a lot of stories _ some of them could turn
out to be true, some of them may not be true,'' he said.
``Statements that are made halfway around the world, we can't spend
all our time dealing with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat and Barak are working against a self-imposed deadline of
Sept. 13 to try to strike a final peace agreement settling the most
intractable issues in their nations' 52-year conflict.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some officials have speculated privately that, if progress is
made on the core issues, the Camp David talks could be adjourned,
then reopened sometime in August.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Barak indicated talks might continue
uninterrupted until a final deal is reached, even if Clinton is
away. The president and Albright are scheduled to leave Wednesday
for Okinawa, site of the annual meeting of leaders of the Group of
Seven industrialized nations and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are prepared to remain as long as necessary. We could
continue while the president is away,'' said Gadi Baltiansky,
Israeli government spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Stressing that the Clinton's agenda still includes next week's
meeting in Okinawa, Boucher left open the possibility that Albright
might remain behind to keep the Arafat-Barak talks on track.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, she does have things on her schedule'' other
than the Camp David negotiations, Boucher said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
