u s BC-OLY-TRACK0714-COX     07-13 0492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TRACK0714-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dash for Sydney starts
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ The U.S. Olympic Track and Field Trials
come down to basic math: Finish in the top three in your event or
go home and watch the Sydney Games on television.
</P>
<P>
   The Trials give no special passes for world-record holders, no
exemptions for past Olympians.
</P>
<P>
   For eight days starting today, the Trials will have a 200-meter
showdown between the world's fastest men, the outspoken Maurice
Greene and the all-business Michael Johnson. They will feature
Marion Jones as she finallybegins her bid for five Olympic gold
medals.
</P>
<P>
   But those stars and everyone else _ from old favorites Jackie
Joyner-Kersee and Gail Devers to the sport's rising stars, pole
vaulter Stacy Dragila and hurdler Angelo Taylor _ must play the
survival game at Hornet Stadium on the campus of California State
University-Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get one of those top three places is what's important now
for every American track-and-field athlete,'' Jones said. ``Once
that is done, you can relax a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The trials hold no guarantees even for Jones, star of Nike's
``Me &AMP; Mrs. Jones'' summer ad campaign. If she comes down with an
injury, as she did before the Atlanta trials, tough luck.
</P>
<P>
   Reebok learned a painful lesson in 1992, when decathlon favorite
and pitchman Dan O'Brien failed to clear a pole-vault height in the
trials.
</P>
<P>
   It is what makes the trials special. The participants book their
tickets knowing the chance of heartbreak, knowing that athletes who
have run like champions since the Atlanta Games may never see
Sydney, because of a tweaked hamstring muscle or a bad day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably the most pressure any athlete is ever going to
feel,''Johnson said. ``People have been training for this, and you
got one shot. And for some reason, the trials are always in a hot
place, too, and that adds to the whole deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnsons, who opens with a first-round race tonight in the 400
in his bid to double Down Under later this summer, at least has his
Olympic fame. Others, including Greene and Jones don't.
</P>
<P>
   Since Atlanta, the 25-year-old Greene has been burning up the
track, smashing the 100-meter world record and challenging
Johnson's supremacy in the 200. But Greene knows he needs to make a
statement here and then to follow it up in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Short of a catastrophe, Greene is a cinch for the U.S. team
selected by the close of the meet. At these trials, ultimately, it
doesn't matter if you win, as long as you don't come home a dreaded
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't get an Olympic gold medal, my career would be
nothing,'' he said. ``I need to get the gold medal to feel
complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, this is the biggest meet of my life,'' Greene said. ``I've
put my body through a whole lot the last few weeks, and I'm sure
it'll pay off.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
