<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1470 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-PHILADELPHIA-POLICE-N     07-13 1306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILADELPHIA-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE BEATING TAINTS BURNISHED IMAGE FOR GOP CONVENTION HOST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)   By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ All decked out in bunting and civic pride for the
forthcoming Republican National Convention, this city Thursday
suffered the ignominy of seeing its police on national television
beating and kicking a suspect who had allegedly stolen a police car
and shot at an officer in a running gun battle through the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome, America!'' the Philadelphia Daily News proclaimed to
the approaching conventioneers on its front page, above a
photograph of the fugitive being pummeled by a group of eight or
nine police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for city leaders who have been preparing a
showcase venue for GOP delegates arriving at the end of the month,
the arrest and beating were recorded by a hovering TV news
helicopter. The tape was replayed endlessly across America as an
image of this city that threatened to be more definitive than any
red, white and blue balloon drop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the videotape doesn't look good, any fool will admit
that,'' said Police Commissioner John F. Timoney who resented as
``inflammatory'' any comparison with the videotaped 1991 clubbing
of Rodney King that traumatized the nation and scandalized the Los
Angeles Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   Timoney, a former deputy commissioner in the New York Police
Department, warned against a ``rush to judgment,'' noting that the
fugitive had allegedly stolen a police officer's gun and shot at
him and repeatedly resisted being brought to ground in a mile-long
chase.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department announced that it would review the tape
for evidence of excessive police force. The image on the tape
dampened civic pride in a city that has been hailing its own
renaissance, and revived old images of a tough city where police
behavior had to be federally monitored.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's vibrant renewal as a convention city has been
widely acclaimed as a triumph over some dark history where a past
mayor, Frank Rizzo, personally packed a club in his law-and-order
photo ops and another, Wilson Goode, ordered the police bombing of
barricaded protesters, with fatal results and disastrous notoriety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately this incident may be used by some elements of
the protest movement to look at our police department as much more
brutal than it actually is,'' said Stefan Presser, legal director
of the state American Civil Liberties Union, referring to the
anticipated thousands of protesters who plan to demonstrate here
during the convention, which runs from July 31 through Aug. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw the situation in Seattle where people with legal
protest permits had their march hijacked by others intent on
violence, and that's where there's a certain edginess growing right
now,'' said Presser, who in the past decade engaged in various
legal challenges to the police and said he found their behavior
clearly improving.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Black leaders, noting that white and black police were taped in
the beating, contended that the case was one of brutality more than
racism toward the suspect, who is black.
</P>
<P>
   ``This comes out of a history of violence and brutality in this
department for 30 years,'' said J. Whyatt Mondesire, president of
the Philadelphia National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief comment while campaigning in Pittsburgh, Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas, who is to be formally nominated at the
Philadelphia convention, said, ``Obviously we've got to take these
incidents very seriously.'' But he reserved further comment, as did
Republican convention officials who had eagerly selected this
overwhelmingly Democratic city after seeing firsthand the evidence
of its downtown renewal.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania, who had urged his fellow
Republicans to ``go into nontraditional constituencies'' for the
Philadelphia convention, said that while the 20-second tape was ``a
pretty horrible sight,'' it was important to study all of the
earlier parts of the chase for a full understanding of the police
officers' intensity.
</P>
<P>
   David L. Cohen, the co-chairman of the city's convention host
committee, said a full investigation would show that the police
were dealing with a shifting, dangerous situation and that the
city's chief officials would tolerate ``no whitewash'' of any
excesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this something we think is going to put a stain on
Philadelphia? No,'' Cohen said. ``It's not a blight on the city at
the dawn of the convention.''
</P>
<P>
   A bit of preconvention edginess was discernible even before the
beating. The City Council, prompted by the violent street
demonstrations during sessions of the World Trade Organization
meeting in Seattle in December, recently passed an ordinance making
it illegal for protesters to wear masks and bandanas with the
intent of intimidating the public. And, amid media speculation
about the potential for mass arrests, police said that, if
necessary for processing detainees, they would consider reopening
the notorious Holmesburg prison, a century-old bastion that was
closed five years ago as unusable.
</P>
<P>
   The edginess grew as planners of protest demonstrations
complained that law enforcement surveillance agents had been
snooping about routine meetings and photographing them on the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so silly,'' said Jody Dodd, an organizer with the Women's
International League for Peace and Freedom, who said the group's
plans for strictly nonviolent street protest were already public
knowledge on the Internet. Dodd said the tape of the police beating
``can't help but have a lingering effect in the back of people's
minds,'' quite possibly for the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``It behooves the police now to act with great restraint and
conduct themselves in the best light,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor John Street emphasized there was much more to the chase
than the final scene. ``As inflammatory as this tape might be, we
have to keep in mind that the police were in the process of
apprehending a criminal suspect who had resisted a number of
attempts to arrest him and who had shot a police officer,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the Thomas Jones, 30, sped off through north
Philadelphia after being stopped for driving a stolen car. He then
crashed his car and fled on foot, according to witnesses, before
being tackled by police. In a scuffle, the 6-foot-tall, 240-pound
suspect grabbed an officer's gun and began shooting, according to
witnesses and police. Then, they said, he jumped into a nearby
empty patrol car.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Michael Livewell was shot in the hand, police said, in
trying to stop the suspect, who was wounded but managed to flee in
the patrol car. Dozens of shots were fired in the ensuing chase
before the suspect was finally cornered at 26th and Oxford streets.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the tape shows the car down below, its windows
blown out, as police warily approach with drawn guns then finally
seize Jones as he emerges and is instantly surrounded and wrestled
down in a flurry of kicks and punches. Jones was in fair condition
Thursday, handcuffed to a hospital bed after being treated for five
bullet wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Police said records showed that Jones had earlier convictions
include robbery, assault and an attempt to run over a police
officer while fleeing arrest. Unofficially, police contended
through local media sources that the group beating occurred as the
suspect, whose behavior is not entirely clear on the tape,
continued to resist, biting one officer's finger and gripping a
cell phone that could have been mistaken as a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ``At what point did the resistance cease and was unnecessary
force used?'' asked Police Commissioner Timoney. ``That's the
critical question here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
