u f BC-LOCKHEED-BAE-BOS &LR;      07-13 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKHEED-BAE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOCKHEED SETS $1.67 BILLION DEFENSE DEAL WITH BAE SYSTEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin Corp. said it will sell its Sanders electronic
warfare division in New Hampshire and other units to BAE Systems
for $1.67 billion in cash, in a deal that would give the British
company control of Sanders and its roughly 4,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   BAE's interest had raised concerns about foreign access to the
advanced weaponry made by Sanders. Thursday, the Pentagon said it
has only begun to review the transaction's security implications,
in what could become a key test of its efforts to encourage closer
ties between American and European defense contractors.
</P>
<P>
   In choosing BAE, Lockheed Martin seemed to be betting it would
prevail over whatever objections might be raised that could benefit
the runner-up in the bidding contest, Northrop Grumman Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the sale supports US Department of Defense
objectives and trans-Atlatic cooperation,'' said Lockheed Martin
chief executive Vance D. Coffman.
</P>
<P>
   BAE's top North America executive, Mark Ronald, said the deal
poses no risk to US security, adding BAE is ``proud of our security
record, which I believe is among the best in the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   If BAE completes the purchase by the end of the year, as it
hopes, it will gain access to whiz-bang Sanders products. Among
them are ``countermeasure'' devices used to fool enemy missiles,
either by jamming radio frequencies or by firing flares.
</P>
<P>
   BAE will also acquire an infrared-sensors unit in Lexington,
Mass., with about 400 employees, and other parts of Lockheed
Martin's Aerospace Electronics Systems division. Altogether, the
deal would add 5,300 Lockheed Martin employees to BAE's current
North American work force of 18,300.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders president Walter P. Havenstein Thursday said he hopes to
remain as head of the company, which would retain its autonomy with
BAE.
</P>
<P>
   People close to BAE said the firm doesn't plan layoffs after the
purchase. That message may bring support for the deal from New
Hampshire's congressional delegation, including Senator Bob Smith,
a Republican member of the Armed Services Committee. But their
opinions are still unclear: Smith has declined to discuss the deal.
A staff member said he couldn't be reached to comment Thursday.
Havenstein said he doesn't expect layoffs following the deal but
hasn't been told for sure.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin said last fall it would auction off Sanders and
other units to raise cash and pay down debt. Like Raytheon Co.,
Lockheed Martin has struggled after a wave of consolidation in the
defense industry. Meanwhile, the Clinton administration has tried
to encourage closer ties between American and European defense
contractors.
</P>
<P>
   But those efforts were dealt a blow in May when BAE and other
contractors beat out Raytheon, based in Lexington, Mass., for a
much-contested $1.2 billion British missile order.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon had given BAE permission to bid on Sanders, but
hasn't indicated whether it would grant BAE final approval for the
sale or when the companies can expect a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The capabilities included in this transaction represent
important areas of modern technology,'' Pentagon spokeswoman Cheryl
Irwin said Thursday. The review is ``focused on ensuring that our
industrial partners are responsive to, and capable of meeting,
current and emerging (Defense Department) requirements,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   John Hamre, who was deputy secretary of Defense until March,
said he expects the BAE purchase would eventually be approved.
</P>
<P>
   Hamre, now president of the Center for Strategic and
International Studies in Washington, wrote in a recent e-mail that
``I suspect that there will be concerns, but that they can be
worked out.'' He added ``there are security procedures in place or
adaptable to cover any problem that might emerge.''
</P>
<P>
   BAE was formed last November through the merger of British
Aerospace and Marconi Electronic Systems, and has annual revenue of
about $20 billion. Based in Farnborough, England, BAE has become
one of the largest US defense contractors through service
agreements with the Pentagon and units like Tracor Inc. in San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders represents the bulk of the assets Lockheed said it would
sell Thursday, which altogether include about 5,300 employees and
1999 revenue of $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The units are valued on Lockheed Martin's books at around $2.6
billion. The seller said it would take a third-quarter charge of
about $1 billion, or $2.50 cents per share, to account for the
transaction.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was announced after the close of trading. In New York
Stock Exchange trading Thursday, Lockheed Martin shares fell 6.25
cents to close at $25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
