<HEADER>
A1477 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-FLU-VACCINE0714-COX     07-13 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLU-VACCINE0714-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flu vaccine expected to be late, in short supply
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The arrival of the influenza vaccine will be
significantly delayed for next winter's flu season, and a shortage
is possible, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
confirmed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a month after the possibility of lower-than-expected
influenza vaccine supplies surfaced in an advisory panel meeting in
Atlanta, the agency said all four manufacturers of flu vaccine have
experienced problems growing one of the three strains of virus that
make up the flu shot.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturers, who produced 85 million doses of vaccine last
year, have told the CDC a strain newly added to the vaccine this
year has reproduced more slowly than strains used in years past,
frustrating attempts to accelerate the process.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Food and Drug Administration has said two
manufacturers have additional production problems, though it has
not disclosed what those problems are.
</P>
<P>
   The result will be at least a month's delay in the start of mass
flu-shot campaigns, which usually run from October to mid-November
to allow recipients to develop immunity before the height of flu
season in late December and early January.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that is clear is that there is going to be a
delay,'' said Dr. Keiji Fukuda chief of the epidemiology section in
CDC's influenza branch. ``It is clearly possible there may be a
shortage, and also possible there may not be one, which makes
planning difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   The shortfall, which first became public in a June 23 meeting of
the CDC's Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices, comes in a
year when more people than ever have been asked to get flu shots.
Last April, the advisory panel published new guidelines urging
routine flu vaccination begin at age 50. Previously, shots were
recommended primarily for people older than 64.
</P>
<P>
   That change added a potential 4 million new recipients to the 76
million for whom the shot was already recommended, including 35
million Americans 65 and older, 2 million pregnant women, and 39
million people younger than 65 who have underlying health problems
that put them at higher risk.
</P>
<P>
   In an average year, influenza causes approximately 20,000 deaths
and 110,000 hospitalizations in the United States. The past five
flu seasons have had above-average rates of illness and death; last
winter's was the worst of the five.
</P>
<P>
   In a typical year, flu accounts for more than 7 percent of
deaths per week during the flu season; at the peak of last year's
flu season, the proportion was more than 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Flu vaccinations are mostly distributed through health care
providers, businesses and churches. In Georgia, county and local
health departments buy and administer about 20 percent of the
shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The vaccine) is going to be late and there is very likely to
be a shortage,'' said Mike Chaney, immunization program manager
with the Georgia Division of Public Health, which advises the local
departments but does not buy or distribute flu vaccine. ``It's not
going to be an easy task trying to have folks understand that,
because they are used to just lining up in September and getting
that shot.''
</P>
<P>
   The CDC issued guidelines Thursday for managing the delay and
the potential shortage:
</P>
<P>
   Organizations that sponsor vaccination campaigns should delay
them until November. ``We have a pretty good chance then that
people will receive the vaccine in time to be prepared for the
upcoming flu season,'' Fukuda said.
</P>
<P>
   Health care workers, many of whom are offered flu vaccinations
by their employers, should seek to get the shot on their usual
schedule. ``They work most closely with lots of high-risk people,
when those people are particularly vulnerable,'' Fukuda said. ``We
want to make sure they aren't inadvertently transmitting the flu.''
</P>
<P>
   Patients who are at potentially high risk of serious illness
from the flu, many of whom routinely receive flu shots from their
health care providers or when discharged from hospitals, should
also seek to have the shot on the usual schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Those considered at risk include people 65 and older; those with
underlying medical conditions such as chronic heart and lung
conditions, diabetes, kidney failure and suppressed immune systems
as a result of infection or medication; children younger than 18
who are on long-term aspirin therapy; and women who will be in the
second or third trimester of pregnancy during flu season.
</P>
<P>
   The new recommendation to give shots to all adults 50 and older,
Fukuda said, was mostly aimed at capturing additional high-risk
patients: One-third of those over 50 have an underlying condition
that might put them at additional risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to have a clearer idea of what is going on by the end
of the summer,'' he said. ``We expect some vaccine will be moving
out from the manufacturers by the end of July, but we won't have a
good handle on what to ultimately expect for another couple of
months.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
