<SLUG> BC-ESTATE-TAX14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATE MOVES TOWARD VOTE TO REPEAL ESTATE TAX
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Republican-sponsored measure to phase out the
federal estate tax over the next decade appears headed for Senate
approval, despite veto threats from President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Senators spent much of Thursday debating and voting on competing
partisan plans to eliminate or modify the tax on assets left by the
deceased.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans offered the same bill which overwhelmingly passed
the House last month. It would lower the estate tax rate, which
tops out at 55 percent, gradually and eliminate it after 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The death tax ... is unfair, it's un-American and it's
immoral,'' said Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, claiming repeal would
help preserve small businesses and family farms.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats argued that the Republican bill would mainly help the
richest people in America first and would offer little help to
small businesses and family farms for a decade. They offered a bill
that would increase the threshold on estates subject to taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the first $675,000 of a person's estate _ $1.35
million per couple _ is exempt from tax. In most cases, small
businesses and family farms valued at less than $1.3 million _ $2.6
million for a couple _ also are exempt.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic alternative would have raised the personal
exemption to $2 million per couple next year and $4 million by
2010. It would have raised the exemption for family-owned
businesses and farms to $4 million per couple next year and $8
million by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic alternative was rejected, 53-46, on a largely
party-line vote.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of votes, senators:
</P>
<P>
   _ Approved elimination of the 3 percent telephone excise tax,
which dates from the Spanish-American War, and agreed to make the
business research and development tax credit permanent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Agreed to roll back, from 85 percent to 50 percent, the amount
of Social Security benefits subject to federal income taxes. That
was the level of benefits subject to taxation prior to 1993.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rejected an amendment that would have suspended the 18.3-cent
federal gasoline tax for 150 days.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rejected an amendment to double, from $40 billion to $80
billion, the amount budgeted for a Medicare prescription drug
benefit.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Senate: www.senate.gov/
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is lrryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
