A1480 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-NAACP-IMPACT-TEX     07-13 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-IMPACT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAACP MEMBERS HOPE MFUME'S SUCCESS AT THE NATIONAL LEVEL WILL
TRICKLE DOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By BECHETTA JACKSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Mention the name Kweisi Mfume and most
African-Americans will praise the former Maryland congressman for
the strong national image of the NAACP, the country's oldest and
largest civil rights organization.
</P>
<P>
   Mfume, whose name means ``conquering son of kings,'' brought the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People from a
$4 million deficit to a $2 million surplus, led an economic boycott
of South Carolina over the state's flying of the Confederate battle
flag and persuaded networks to increase the number of blacks on
television.
</P>
<P>
   Under his leadership, the NAACP has gained a renewed sense of
energy and purpose. Now, as thousands of delegates return home from
the 91st annual convention, many face the daunting task of
breathing new life into the 1,700 branches nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Strengthening the effectiveness of sluggish chapters is vital if
the venerable organization is to be a powerful force in the 21st
Century, national leaders say.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, some branches have been criticized for lacking
visibility in the community and failing to take on issues of
importance to African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Area chapters also struggle to attract new members _
particularly young people _ and too often rely on a core group to
carry out the work, members said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our branches are like any other volunteer group,'' said Julian
Bond, the NAACP's chairman, who helped Mfume rejuvenate the
organization. ``We have various levels of engagement and activity.
Certainly, some of them are not as effective as others.''
</P>
<P>
   In Fort Worth, Texas, membership has declined by about half
since the annual fee to join jumped from $10 to $30 about a year
ago, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing membership remains the biggest challenge facing the
chapter, said Fort Worth City Councilman Frank Moss, the branch
treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of visibility is another obstacle for Fort Worth members.
Earlier this year, a group of ministers urged members to boost
their presence in the community. Fort Worth residents too often
fail to see how their lives are enhanced by the work of the local
branch, the ministers said at a round-table discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Moss agreed with the ministers. ``That's one of our problems,''
he said. ``We have not done a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss described the Fort Worth branch as a stable organization
whose members have been involved for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really need younger people to come in and help out,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The branch in nearby Arlington, Texas, faces similar hurdles.
The organization has several dormant committees because there are
too few members to steer them, leaders said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a shot in the arm just like a number of other
branches,'' said Arlington NAACP Branch President Rick L. Harris,
who started the organization in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said his chapter is struggling with membership at a time
of unprecedented prosperity because ``we have a lot of black folk
who think they have arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless something hurts them, or they are hit financially,''
Harris said, ``they don't seem to be motivated to join.''
</P>
<P>
   In Dallas, turmoil has plagued the chapter during the past
decade. Chapter president Lee Alcorn has been suspended by the
national office three times for rule violations. Alcorn says most
people assume that local chapters are not doing anything
substantial.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas branch has held numerous protests without approval of
the national office, causing Alcorn's suspension.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't take a laid-back approach to social change,'' he
said. ``We have to be out there on the front lines so people can
see what we're doing. That's the only way we can attract new
members.''
</P>
<P>
   When Mfume took over the organization, he urged local affiliates
to agitate for social change, not to just be another social club.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas State NAACP Branch won a small victory recently when
Gov. George W. Bush removed a controversial plaque of the
Confederate flag from state Supreme Court building.
</P>
<P>
   And earlier this week the branch in Dallas suburb Grand Prairie
was recognized by the national office for doubling its youth
membership, president Ollie Dailey said. The Grand Prairie NAACP
has about 150 members on its youth council, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The branch also mounted a petition drive to get a police officer
fired after the officer fatally shot a mentally ill man in the city
a few years ago, and has fought against housing discrimination,
Dailey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to be visible in the community,'' he said. ``But people
have to understand that any organization is only as strong as its
supporters.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson B. Rivers III, national field director of the NAACP, said
the organization has never had as many members as it should, but
continues to make significant progress.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 140 college chapters at universities such as
Harvard, Princeton and Stanford, he said. Approximately 68,000 of
the organization's members are college and high school students.
And there are 450 youth councils around the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mfume urged branch leaders during the convention to implement a
bold plan in a few key areas and pursue them publicly and
effectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``The struggle in every community is different,'' he said.
``Whether it's voter registration, political education or job
discrimination, we have to be out there fighting for the betterment
of people of color. If all of our branches are addressing these and
other very vital issues, we can only grow stronger and more
powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 2129EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
