<DOCNO> NYT20000713.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1481 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CARS-COLLECTING-NYT &LR;      07-13 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-COLLECTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUNT EMILY, A VINTAGE LIMOUSINE, STILL DAZZLES AT 81 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Idaho, Minn., Wash. Mass.)   By PAUL DUCHENE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ When people ask Michael Whitesel about his Aunt
Emily at the Pebble Beach Concours d'Elegance next month, he'll
have all the answers. She has been part of his family for four
generations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aunt Emily'' is a concours judge's term to describe huge,
stately conveyances that are sensible rather than sexy. Whitesel's
imposing aunt is a 1919 Cunningham limousine that his
great-grandfather bought new in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The Cunningham certainly was sensible, in an imposing way. The
black-and-maroon giant is nearly 7 feet tall and 20 feet long. It
has survived more than 100,000 miles on mountainous gravel roads in
the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   But it is especially noteworthy for having been in the same
family for nearly 81 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what makes this car such an interesting story,'' said
Glenn Mounger, co-chairman of the Pebble Beach concours, an annual
event in California that is widely considered the most important
collector-car show in the world. ``We get one-family cars presented
from the 1950s and occasionally the '40s, but to get a car out of
the teens from the same family is very rare.''
</P>
<P>
   Mounger brought the car to the attention of the Pebble Beach
selection committee, which invited Whitesel to this year's
50th-anniversary concours, set for Aug. 20.
</P>
<P>
   The opulent oceanfront Lodge at Pebble Beach is far removed from
the Cunningham's rough-and-tumble domain in Wallace, Idaho, a
mining town that was the backdrop for the film ``Dante's Peak.''
</P>
<P>
   When Model T Fords sold for $525, Whitesel's great-grandfather,
Harry L. Day, paid cash for a car that cost 14 times as much: a
Cunningham Model 64 limousine with a separate, covered driver's
compartment. Whitesel still has the canceled check for $7,468.75,
dated Jan. 26, 1920.
</P>
<P>
   Day could afford it. His family owned the Hercules and Tamarack
silver mines, Idaho's biggest. From 1901 to 1925, the Hercules
alone yielded dividends estimated at nearly $20 million and at one
point produced 6 percent of the nation's lead.
</P>
<P>
   Day Mines reported wartime dividends of $2.9 million in 1916 and
$3.6 million in 1917, and although they dipped to $500,000 at the
war's end, the future must have seemed bright _ bright enough that
when he decided to buy a new automobile, he chose one of the most
handsome and expensive brands in America.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in 1907, Cunningham, of Rochester, N.Y., assembled
vehicles with Buffalo or Continental engines and then, in 1911, its
own four-cylinder units. But the company vaulted into the luxury
class with its V-8 of 1916, the same year it ceased making
horse-drawn carriages. Initially rated at 45 horsepower, the
442-cubic-inch flathead engine (twice the displacement of Ford's
famous V-8 of 1932) was tweaked by the late 1920s to produce 110
horsepower. Customers could choose two sizes of cars, with
wheelbases of either 132 or, like Whitesel's car, 142 inches.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Cunningham made cars from 1907 to 1936 (though the last
few years involved supplying custom bodies for Ford chassis).
Production ran as high as 200 cars a year, and at least 38 are
known to have survived. Cunningham did not bother with a dealer
network. If you wanted a car, you ordered it from the factory.
Harry Day, who had joined the exclusive Bohemian Club in San
Francisco, ordered his through the company's agent in that city.
</P>
<P>
   Cunninghams changed little from year to year, which suited their
conservative customers. If the buyers were finicky, the company was
more so, urging owners not to allow local garages to work on the
cars. If necessary, the factory would send a mechanic by train to
make repairs.
</P>
<P>
   When silver and lead prices plummeted with the Depression and
mining was halted, the car's 1932 license plates were not renewed.
The car was parked in a warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Henry L. Day, Harry's son, took over Day Mines Inc., and
capitalized on his analysis of the family empire, the subject of
his thesis for a degree at Harvard. He consolidated the company
holdings, buying less successful competitors, and by the end of
World War II owned 719 mining claims.
</P>
<P>
   The Cunningham was forgotten until the early 1970s, when a local
newspaper article led to a stream of interested buyers. Henry, by
then 71, decided to have the car restored. He contacted Bob
Larrabee in Clarkston, Wash., and a lively correspondence followed.
The work began in 1974 at Larrabee's shop rate of $9 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Larrabee, 65, recently recalled the job. ``It had been sitting
in a damp building since 1932,'' he said. ``Everything was rusted
and gummed up. The wheels wouldn't turn; the motor wouldn't turn.
The tires were flat and falling apart.''
</P>
<P>
   The project turned into a total ``frame off'' restoration. The
shop replaced woodwork and completely rebuilt the engine,
transmission and rear axle. The interior was usable after minor
repairs were made.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no parts for Cunninghams,'' Larrabee said.
``Everything was a challenge. We recast door handles, machined
everything ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   His original estimate for the job was $5,300; Day's records show
that the final figure was $20,027.69. But the men's relations
remained cordial even as the bill soared, and Larrabee kept a
detailed record book with photographs of each stage of the work.
Day wrote to tell the restorer how proud he was of the finished
product.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry approved everything,'' Larrabee recalled. ``He came down
three or four times that year and sometimes brought relatives with
him. When the car was completed, he had me deliver it to Spokane,
and I rode with him to Coeur d'Alene.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the Cunningham was finished, Whitesel, who is
Henry Day's grandson, fell in love with the huge old car _ proving
the adage that a collectible car can be defined as something you
rode in between the ages of 5 and 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 8 or 9 years old,'' said Whitesel, who is now 32 and
lives here. ``I remember he took us all for rides. Then, in 1983, I
rode with him in the Wallace centennial parade.'' Henry Day died in
1985 and Whitesel's mother had the car appraised, planning to sell
it. Its value was estimated at $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 17,'' Whitesel recalled. ``I begged her not to sell it.
I said, `I'll do anything!' Mom agreed that if I arranged insurance
and storage, she wouldn't sell the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept it in a parking garage for a year, then in a museum in
Coeur d'Alene, then in an airplane hangar, then two and a half
years ago I shipped it to Portland.''
</P>
<P>
   He plans to keep the car and share it with the public when
possible, at events like Pebble Beach. ``I'm not much of a
knuckle-basher, but I have a fascination with it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For his wedding, in April 1997, he hired a chauffeur. He and his
bride left the church in the back of the maroon-and-black
Cunningham.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 2132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000713.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1482 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-CHURCH-BURNINGS-AZR &LR;      07-13 1672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCH-BURNINGS-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-CHURCH-BURNINGS-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    MEDIA IGNORED, THEN OVERSIMPLIFIED, BLACK CHURCH ARSONS (a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: Moving in ``A'' and ``K'' categories) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By Sharon Bramlett-Solomon (a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although the national crisis over the burning of Black churches
has abated
</P>
<P>
   and the attention of the media is no longer focused on it, the
retreat of this
</P>
<P>
   news story from the spotlight may be a blessing. For the truth
is, an analysis
</P>
<P>
   of the nationwide phenomenon shows that newspapers did a
disturbingly poor job
</P>
<P>
   of explaining the church-burning ``conspiracy,'' reporting it
opaquely and
</P>
<P>
   strewing the issue with highly volatile implications,
particularly when it
</P>
<P>
   came to race.
</P>
<P>
   In short, news coverage of the idea of a conspiracy was unclear,
undefined,
</P>
<P>
   unenlightening, and it may have helped to escalate racial
tension.
</P>
<P>
   The evolution of the story shows how easy it was for the
conspiracy idea to
</P>
<P>
   be picked up by the press. From January 1995 to December 1997,
at least 142
</P>
<P>
   largely Southern Black churches were set on fire by arsonists.
Federal law
</P>
<P>
   enforcement officials and the U.S. national media began to focus
on these
</P>
<P>
   arson-caused fires in the spring 1996, after their swelling
numbers became too
</P>
<P>
   difficult (and too regional) to ignore. Pressure on federal
officials to
</P>
<P>
   investigate the church burnings came from community leaders,
politicians and
</P>
<P>
   ministers, both Black and White, across the country. The
torching of almost 40
</P>
<P>
   Black churches in 11 Southern states over this 18-month period
signaled a
</P>
<P>
   crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The series of Black church burnings in the south has special
historical
</P>
<P>
   resonance. Many Americans saw the fires not only as racially
driven, but also
</P>
<P>
   as a stark reminder of America's dark era of racial strife in
the 1950s and
</P>
<P>
   1960s, when church burnings were a major form of White terrorism
against Black
</P>
<P>
   Americans. During the civil rights movement, scores of Black
churches that
</P>
<P>
   were rallying points for civil rights demonstrations were bombed
or set on
</P>
<P>
   fire. Black Americans tended to see church burnings as a symbol
and reminder
</P>
<P>
   of racist America as well as a sign of deteriorating race
relations.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Frances Berry, chairwoman of the U.S. Commission on Civil
Rights,
</P>
<P>
   labeled the Black church fires ``a wake-up call'' for Americans
to deal with
</P>
<P>
   the nation's race-relations issue. Berry reported that federal
investigations
</P>
<P>
   revealed 70 percent of the Southern Black church fires were
racially
</P>
<P>
   motivated.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to growing outrage over the church fires, President
Clinton in
</P>
<P>
   June 1996 created the National Church Arson Task Force,
including 200 members
</P>
<P>
   from the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, the FBI and
the U.S. Justice
</P>
<P>
   Department. It was the largest federal task force in history. A
major question
</P>
<P>
   federal officials explored was whether the Black church arsons
were set by
</P>
<P>
   racists, conspirators, copycats or others.
</P>
<P>
   Deval Patrick, U.S. assistant attorney general for civil rights,
who headed
</P>
<P>
   the church task force, said investigations revealed that race
was only one of
</P>
<P>
   several causes. He said some fires had been set by church
members trying
</P>
<P>
   fraudulently to collect insurance money, others by burglars and
some by
</P>
<P>
   pyromaniacs. In a handful of cases, he said, the arsonists
involved were in
</P>
<P>
   hate groups.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick said investigation over a 15-month period found nothing
to show
</P>
<P>
   there was a national conspiracy targeting Black churches. Arsons
at White
</P>
<P>
   churches, he said, approached the number at Black churches, with
both taking
</P>
<P>
   place at record numbers.
</P>
<P>
   However, Patrick said although no organized conspiracy was
found, ``an
</P>
<P>
   intense climate of racism behind the church fires'' did exist.
Profiles of
</P>
<P>
   those arrested, Patrick said, revealed they were generally
White, male and
</P>
<P>
   young, low-income, poorly educated, frequently drunk or high on
drugs, rarely
</P>
<P>
   affiliated with hate groups, but often deeply driven by racism.
In other
</P>
<P>
   words, although conspiracy theories were largely debunked by the
task force,
</P>
<P>
   racist motives were not.
</P>
<P>
   Two prominent figures increased national press coverage. Clinton
drew media
</P>
<P>
   attention with a speech given at the site of a burned church in
June 1996 in
</P>
<P>
   Greelyville, S.C. He vowed that the church burnings would not be
tolerated and
</P>
<P>
   would be intensely investigated by federal officials.
</P>
<P>
   An unprecedented victory
</P>
<P>
   By the end of 1997, with increased national press attention,
stiffer
</P>
<P>
   punishments and a louder public outcry, the arson-caused fires
at Black
</P>
<P>
   churches began to decline after about 15 months of National
Church Arsons Task
</P>
<P>
   Force investigations.
</P>
<P>
   In an unprecedented victory for burned Black churches, a South
Carolina
</P>
<P>
   jury of nine Blacks and three Whites in July 1998 ordered the
Klu Klux Klan to
</P>
<P>
   pay $12.6 million to Macedonia Baptist Church. The jury deemed
the Klan's
</P>
<P>
   rhetoric of hate had motivated four Klansmen to set the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, several journalists questioned the media coverage's
accuracy and
</P>
<P>
   fairness, charging the press with initial indifference to the
burnings,
</P>
<P>
   simplistic treatment of a complex story, stereotyping the
arsonists as largely
</P>
<P>
   White racists, and escalating public hysteria by hyping the
story as a return
</P>
<P>
   to the tactics of the segregation era.
</P>
<P>
   Despite critics, at least one press defender addressed the
topic. American
</P>
<P>
   Journalism Review writer Joe Holley noted that over a
seven-month period,
</P>
<P>
   journalists prudently ``connected the dots'' in the fires. They
tended to take
</P>
<P>
   place at Southern Black churches in isolated or rural areas with
most of the
</P>
<P>
   arsonists being White. ``It's an example of how the media can be
distracted,
</P>
<P>
   even misled for a while, but given time, are able to right
themselves, regain
</P>
<P>
   their balance, and tease out the complex truth,'' Holley wrote.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, Birmingham Post Herald reporter Ted Bryant
criticized
</P>
<P>
   the press for moving from ``indifference'' to ``hysteria'' and
charged that
</P>
<P>
   reporters inaccurately promoted stereotypes of the arsonists as
White
</P>
<P>
   hate-mongers. Michael Kelly, New Yorker magazine writer, also
noted coverage
</P>
<P>
   problems. He said that at first, reporters paid little attention
to the fires
</P>
<P>
   but later went overboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a case of overreaction that seems to have been inspired in
roughly
</P>
<P>
   equal measure by genuine concern, guilt and self-interests, they
leaped on the
</P>
<P>
   bandwagon with near-hysteria as misplaced as their previous
indifference,''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly wrote. Detroit Free Press religion writer David Crumm also
took the
</P>
<P>
   press to task, charging that reporters ignored motives other
than racism and
</P>
<P>
   ``often relied heavily on stereotypes supporting the idea that a
pack of
</P>
<P>
   church-burning racists could be on the loose.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, none of these critics addressed the fact that one of the
most
</P>
<P>
   confusing aspects of the reporting was the focus on whether they
were part of
</P>
<P>
   a national conspiracy. Although federal investigators say they
found no
</P>
<P>
   national conspiracy at work (such as KKK or militia groups),
coverage of the
</P>
<P>
   issue was confounding rather than informative. This writer's
research study of
</P>
<P>
   newspaper editorials from the Nexis Lexis database and
Editorials on File
</P>
<P>
   showed that only a third of the 109 editorials published on the
burnings
</P>
<P>
   addressed the conspiracy issue and that what was written was
poorly explained
</P>
<P>
   and highly ambiguous.
</P>
<P>
   Making an unclear point
</P>
<P>
   For example, a St. Louis Post Dispatch June 12, 1996, editorial
stated that
</P>
<P>
   church fire investigations ``turned up no interstate
conspiracy'' even though
</P>
<P>
   ``several fires have been linked to people with KKK ties.'' But
the editorial
</P>
<P>
   writer's point about the conspiracy issue was unclear. Because
the KKK has
</P>
<P>
   members in chapters across the nation, why would KKK or Aryan
Nation member
</P>
<P>
   involvement not constitute a local (if not a national)
conspiracy? This
</P>
<P>
   unanswered question should have been addressed to help readers
put facts into
</P>
<P>
   perspective.
</P>
<P>
   In a more radical perspective, Noah Chandler of the Center for
Democratic
</P>
<P>
   Renewal in Atlanta, a civil rights watchdog group, called media
focus on the
</P>
<P>
   conspiracy question ``racist conspiracy itself.'' Other
conspiracy labels also
</P>
<P>
   were noted in the press, including what the Houston Chronicle
called a
</P>
<P>
   ``conspiracy of silence'' and the Bergen Record called
``conspiracy of
</P>
<P>
   hatred.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the press conspiracy discussion was short on clarity
and showed
</P>
<P>
   that, though well-intentioned, American journalists were unable
to deal with
</P>
<P>
   racial motivations that lie deep in the culture; so deep, in
fact, that they
</P>
<P>
   can be expressed spontaneously, without coordination and over an
extended
</P>
<P>
   period of time. Such coverage shows journalists have difficulty
handling
</P>
<P>
   subtle events and reporting on complex social events without
jumping to sudden
</P>
<P>
   conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Although current reports from the Church Arson Task Force reveal
the Black
</P>
<P>
   church fires have greatly declined, Assistant Attorney General
Patrick says
</P>
<P>
   investigations of the arson cases and vigorous pursuit of the
arsonists
</P>
<P>
   continue. But it may be blissful that national news headlines on
the fires
</P>
<P>
   have ceased. For although press perspectives on the rates,
arrests and
</P>
<P>
   deep-seated and complex racial motivations behind the arsons are
warranted,
</P>
<P>
   what is not are poorly explained ideas and speculation of a
national
</P>
<P>
   conspiracy targeting Black churches that may help to incite the
very racism it
</P>
<P>
   seeks to expose.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sharon Bramlett-Solomon is a professor of journalism in the
Walter
</P>
<P>
   Cronkite School of Journalism &AMP; Telecommunication at Arizona
State University.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
