<SLUG> BC-OLY-AUSTIN0714-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Decision time for track and field athletesBy John Maher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ The first thing you notice as you dip down
out of a cloudless sky to land in Sacramento are the fields of
emerald near the city, their lush green a stark contrast to the
brown and crisp landscape of a Texas summer.
</P>
<P>
   That, however, is mostly illusion. Just some irrigated rice
fields. Anything that isn't watered here is just so much refried
straw.
</P>
<P>
   It's hot here. Not Texas-style,
sear-your-hands-on-the-steering-wheel hot, but hot for California.
And that's just the 90-degree weather. Tickets for the U.S. Olympic
Track and Field Trials at the jazzed-up Sacramento State field are
hotter than that. And the competition, particularly between Michael
Johnson and Maurice Greene, could be downright scorching.
</P>
<P>
   Only once every four years do American sports fans pay the
attention they should to track and field, and that time is now.
With the Olympics a scant two months away, these trials will decide
who gets a chance to shine in Sydney and who's consigned to four
more years of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   It's a virtual mini-series of Olympic drama. The most
anticipated event figures to be the showdown between world
record-holder and former Baylor star Michael Johnson and ``world's
fastest human'' Maurice Greene in the 200 meters. That should be
the showstopper a week from Sunday, but there's going to be a lot
of other compelling dramas along the way.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest theme for the competition comes on the women's side,
where Marion Jones is trying to set herself up to win five gold
medals and make some serious Olympic history. In the long jump
competition, which begins today, one of her opponents is scheduled
to be the legendary Jackie Joyner-Kersee, who suddenly popped out
of retirement. The present vs. the past. And don't forget about the
future. Ychlindria Spears was also on the list of entrants. She's
not ready to beat the top names, but if you look at her high school
marks and theirs . . . well, UT, which figures to have the inside
track on Spears, could have quite a catch.
</P>
<P>
   The the high schooler who is drawing the most attention is
400-meter runner Monique Henderson, who clocked a 50.74 to torch
the California high school record. She's got a shot at being the
first high schooler to make the U.S. Olympic track team since 1976,
when Johnny ``Lam'' Jones of Lampasas ended up getting a gold in
the 400 relay.
</P>
<P>
   In the women's 100 meters, contested this weekend, Jones' main
competition figures to be Inger Miller. But there's also a strong
Texas contingent headed by Carlette Guidry, whose been battling
another Texan, Chryste Gaines, since their high school showdown in
Memorial Stadium some 15 years ago. UT connections in the field
include Nanceen Perry and LaKeisha Backus.
</P>
<P>
   In all there's some three dozen athletes in the field who either
attended UT, went to high school in Austin or who at least train
part time in Austin. There's a lot more, including Johnson, with
connections to the state. They'll like it hot and that's exactly
what it is here for the U.S. Olympic Trials. In all, there are more
than 1,000 athletes battling for 117 potential slots on the U.S.
team.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
