<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1489 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-NYT &LR;      07-13 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK AND ARAFAT HOLD IMPROMPTU MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MIDEAST-CLINTON) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ It appears that not everything happens as
scripted at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   Unknown to their American hosts, Prime Minister Ehud Barak of
Israel and Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, held an impromptu
meeting at Arafat's cabin on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton was not present, nor was Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, or any other American negotiator. The two
leaders, who have met each other on a number of occasions back
home, talked for about an hour before dinner, accompanied by some
of their negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   The substance of what was said was not described in the brief
account given by the State Department spokesman, Richard Boucher,
who was scrambling on Thursday morning to find out details of what
went on.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that such an encounter took place was taken as a
sign that a serious effort was being made by the two sides to deal
with the issues.
</P>
<P>
   The encounter was also in contrast to the first Middle East
summit meeting at Camp David 22 years ago, when President Jimmy
Carter negotiated between the Egyptian president, Anwar Sadat, and
the Israeli prime minister, Menachem Begin. Then, Begin and Sadat
met in Carter's presence only, and after the third day refused to
even do that until the final treaty was signed.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday morning, Clinton was confident enough to leave Camp
David for some previously scheduled events. He left the conference
in the hands of Albright until his return Thursday night in time
for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   At the annual conference of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People in Baltimore, Clinton asked for
prayers for a ``full, final and fair peace.'' He cited Dr. Martin
Luther King Jr. as saying peace was more than the absence of war
but also the presence of justice and brotherhood.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, apparently trying to broaden his seven-member delegation,
was joined in negotiations by Dan Meridor, the chairman of the
foreign affairs and defense committee in the Israeli Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Meridor, a former member of the Likud party, lent more
conservative credentials to the Israeli team at a time when Barak
faces opposition at home from conservative and religious political
parties.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Camp David, three Palestinian leaders from the radical
wing of the Palestine Liberation Organization said they wanted to
meet with Arafat during the summit talks. Such an encounter would
break the rules of seclusion set down by the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Their request appeared to be an attempt to warn Arafat that his
domestic constituency was not unified behind the goal of a peace
agreement with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department did not rule out such a meeting, saying
``provisions can be made to bring a limited group of people for a
brief time'' to the summit meeting. But so far, Boucher said, no
request had been received from the three Palestinians, who
represent the Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine, the
Marxist Palestinian People's Party and the Popular Struggle Front.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton was away, Albright met for an hour with Barak on
Thursday afternoon and then with the delegations of both sides.
Boucher studiously avoided any reference to what they talked about,
relying on the familiar vocabulary of the delegates ``grappling''
with the ``tough issues'' that need to be resolved for a peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The actual content of those issues _ the borders of a
Palestinian state, the number of Israeli settlers on the West Bank,
the status of Palestinian refugees and the future status of
Jerusalem _ have not been mentioned at any of the briefings in the
last three days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 2137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000713.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1490 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-JOHNSON0714-COX     07-13 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-JOHNSON0714-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's all down hill for Johnson
 &HT;    By Dave George
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Double gold, twice as nice as any other
sprinter's fastest fantasy, belonged to Michael Johnson in 1996. As
the U.S. Track and Field Trials begin today in Sacramento, the
question is whether the five-ring Olympic circus has lost any of
its magic for him.
</P>
<P>
   Funny thing is, Johnson already gave the answer to that in May
to a group of reporters who were peppering him for information on
his newborn son, Sebastian. Are you getting enough sleep, Michael,
between running the track by day and walking the floors by night?
Yes. Has your life changed greatly, Michael, now that you and your
wife Kerry are parents? Yes, but only for the better. Will you make
a gift to the baby of your two Olympic gold medals from Atlanta?
</P>
<P>
   Only here did Johnson stop and give genuine thought to his
response. Only here did he seek out the eyes of the questioner in
the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can go get his own medals,'' Johnson said flatly, eliciting
great gales of laughter with a perfectly serious answer.
</P>
<P>
   Serious. Perfect. These are words that fit a man who gets more
done with seemingly less anxiety or fuss than any superstar athlete
in any sport at any time on any planet. Superman, that's what
people were calling him four years ago, when Johnson won the
Olympic 400-meter race with ease and followed that up with a
stunning world-record of 19.32 seconds in the 200. Easy to forget
how this legend began, though, with a shy teenager coming out for
his high school track team in Texas in a pair of black horn-rimmed
glasses better suited to Clark Kent.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 33, has earned global admiration one stride at a time,
slowly at first, certainly at last.
</P>
<P>
   For all the disappointments of previous Olympic cycles _ he
broke a leg prior to the 1988 Trials and was floored by food
poisoning at the 1992 Barcelona Games _ the 1996 Atlanta Olympics
were a celebration of what can happen with a gifted athlete finally
hits his stride. Tonight Johnson helps open the Trials with an easy
cruise though the 400-meter heats. On July 23, the final day of the
meet, he'll close things down with a spark and a crackle in the
200-meter showcase. A top-three finish in the Sacramento races is
all Johnson needs to advance to September's Sydney Olympics and a
defense of his double gold. Ridiculous, though, to imagine that he
won't keep right on winning, no matter the setting, no matter the
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   At Atlanta four years ago, Frankie Fredericks of Namibia ran 200
meters in 19.68 seconds, bettering the previous Olympic record.
With Johnson out front, however, raising both arms at the finish
line in salute to his own world-record effort, the spectacular
silver medalist could have stopped short of the tape and still gone
unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised,'' Johnson said recently of his immediate
reaction to running a 19.32, a full four-tenths of a second faster
than a world record that had stood for 17 years. ``I also was
elated. There was a lot of emotion. I thought, 'OK, I've completed
the double. I've made history.' ``
</P>
<P>
   And now, four summers later, there are two unimaginable concepts
to consider. First, that Johnson is favored to pull a
double-double, winning the 200 and the 400 for a second consecutive
Olympics when no other man has won both events in a lifetime.
Second, that there are people who wish he wouldn't make it look so
easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like they're looking for somebody to beat me,'' said
Johnson, who once went eight years without losing at 400 meters.
``They're looking for great competition. They want to see a race.''
</P>
<P>
   Will Johnson get one at Sacramento? Well, anything is possible
in the pressurized environment of the U.S. Trials, but Johnson is
supremely confident. He set the world record in the 400 at the 1999
World Championships in Spain with a run of 43.18 and is talking now
about dropping it into the 42's. What's more, Johnson ran a 19.71
in his first 200 of the season, a March meet in South Africa. From
1979 until 1996, Pietro Mennea's 19.72 was the world record.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Greene, who earned the title of world's fastest man last
summer with a world record 100-meter run of 9.79 seconds, expects
to give Johnson a challenge in the 200 at the Trials. Greene won
the 200 at the 1999 World Championships, a race that Johnson
skipped while concentrating on the 400.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, I don't really have to do anything extra,''
Johnson said in a preview of the Trials. ``With my experience, I
know exactly what to do, just go out and don't make mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   You might even say it's all downhill from here for Johnson, who
described for reporters the sensation of charging around the final
curve to win the 200 at Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a kid,'' he said, ``my dad made me a go-cart and I
could make it go really fast. There was a hill by my house and I
knew if I went downhill on the go-cart, I could go faster. So go
put a go-cart on top of a hill if you want to know how it feels.''
</P>
<P>
   Like you've got a gear no one else has discovered, one would
think, and all that matters is keeping things steered in the right
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
