<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1494 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-GUIDRY0714-COX     07-13 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-GUIDRY0714-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Guidry running well, but a long shot to win medal
 &HT;    By Randy Riggs
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Her resume includes two Olympic gold medals, a
World Championship gold medal, two U.S. Championship golds, an
American indoor record in the 200-meter dash and more NCAA titles
and All-America honors than anyone in the proud history of the
University of Texas women's track program.
</P>
<P>
   But does sprinter Carlette Guidry truly think her career has
been an unqualified success?
</P>
<P>
   Guidry says yes.
</P>
<P>
   Bev Kearney isn't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   Kearney, the Texas women's track coach, has been Guidry's
personal coach since 1994. How much longer Guidry will compete is
uncertain, because the powerfully built Houstonian _ she was known
as ``Turbo'' when she arrived at UT in 1988 _ will turn 32 on Sept.
4, just 17 days before the start of the track competition at the
Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   If this is, indeed, Guidry's ``last big hurrah,'' in Kearney's
words, then Guidry seems determined to make it memorable. Kearney
believes the veteran sprinter is motivated to finish strong to make
up for a career that hasn't quite met her expectations, although
that's an opinion not necessarily shared by Guidry _ ``I've had a
great career. I'm really pleased with what I've done so far,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kearney is skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly believe Carlette feels she hasn't achieved all her
goals in athletics and is trying to redeem herself,'' she said.
``She's really disappointed with the outcome of things in 1996, but
it's also her whole career overall.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's been lacking?
</P>
<P>
   According to Kearney, individual Olympic gold medals. The two
Guidry has earned, in 1992 and 1996, came for her role on the U.S.
400-meter relay teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Games in '96 were especially bittersweet. Guidry won
the U.S. trials in the 200 in a career-best 22.14 seconds and was a
favorite in the Games, but was injured at a relay camp before the
Olympics. She finished eighth in the 200 finals in Atlanta, and ran
only in the prelims of the relay. That got her a medal when the
U.S. quartet crossed first in the finals, but she wasn't on the
awards stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really bothered her, watching them on the podium and
thinking it could have been her,'' Kearney said. ``She got a medal,
but it wasn't the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite an encouraging early summer, Guidry seems a long shot to
finally grab an Olympic individual gold. In her best event, the
100, her season-best time of 11.13 ranks 18th in the world and is
tied for eighth on the list of entries for the trials. In the 200,
she recorded a 22.90 indoors that ranks 13th among the trial
entries.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Track &AMP; Field News has predicted Guidry will finish second
in the 100 at the trials. That would get her to Sydney because the
top three finishers in each event advance, providing they meet the
Olympic qualifying standard.
</P>
<P>
   The trials open today in Sacramento, Calif. The first round of
the 100 prelims are on tap, with the semifinals and finals on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   If Guidry wins an individual Olympic gold, it would represent a
tremendous upset. American Marion Jones, the world leader in both
short sprints, is the overwhelming favorite in the sprints in her
bid for five golds (100, 200, both relays and long jump). Also
expected to challenge for the gold is American Inger Miller.
</P>
<P>
   But Guidry is running with confidence, and it's been reflected
in her last two outings. She ran her 11.13 in winning the Oregon
Classic in Portland, then blazed to a wind-aided 11.06 winning time
at a meet in Palo Alto, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel real confident,'' she said ``This year I was able to
let a lot of stuff go and be receptive to Bev's teaching. I'm so
much better now than I was when I was young and just running on
athleticism.''
</P>
<P>
   The main lesson Kearney has taught Guidry is to break down her
races into phases. Guidry doesn't have a hair-trigger start, but
Kearney has taught her not to panic if she gets behind early in a
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm not a great starter, but I'm OK,'' Guidry said.
``I've learned I can get back in a race real fast if I don't panic.
In the past, I'd panic when I got behind early, and lose
everything. Staying composed is something Bev has really drilled
into my head.''
</P>
<P>
   Noted Kearney: ``I've built in safeguards for her all along her
race. When you have only one strategy and it doesn't go as planned,
it creates more opportunities for failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Guidry also has toned up physically through better eating
habits. Her weight, about 145 pounds on a 5-foot-7-inch frame, is
not substantially lower than the 152 pounds she maxed out at during
her college career (1988-92) at UT. But she's much more fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first year I've had Carlette with no weight
problems,'' Kearney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really know how big I was until I looked at pictures
from when I ran for UT,'' Guidry added. ``Weight-wise, it's not all
that much different than now, but it wasn't all muscle back then.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, much has changed for Guidry since she came out of
Houston as one of the nation's top young prospects 12 years ago.
She doesn't want to contemplate her future in track until after the
Olympics, but she admits the possible finality of her career is
always lurking in her subconscious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think about it a little bit,'' she said. ``I don't feel
old, though. I just feel I've matured a lot, and I know what to do
now, finally, to take care of myself.''
</P>
<P>
   But will that be enough for Guidry to supply the missing
ingredient of her career. Kearney, for one, isn't betting against
her despite the odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``She believes in herself more than she's worried about anyone
else,'' Kearney said. ``She's at her best physically, and she's a
lot more intense and focused than I've ever seen her. That can make
someone like Carlette Guidry very, very dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
