u f BC-BLACKS-INSURE-NYT &LR;      07-13 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKS-INSURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSURERS DEFENDING SUITS CHARGING DISCRIMINATION IN PRICING
PRACTICES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ MetLife and Prudential Insurance have been accused in
two class action lawsuits of charging their black customers higher
premiums for life insurance coverage than they charged white
customers.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits were filed recently in federal District Courts in
New York and Newark, where the companies have their headquarters.
The companies said they stopped using race as a factor in life
insurance sales about 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies said some of the discriminatory policies remained
in effect, but that they had stopped collecting premiums on them in
the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is in no way reflective of MetLife's business today,''
said Kevin Foley, a spokesman for the New York company.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential said through a spokesman, Robert DeFillippo, that
while race had once been a factor in his company's sales, it was
now ``completely unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than three weeks ago, American General, the fourth-largest
life insurer, agreed to pay restitution of $206 million to settle a
class action lawsuit and claims from insurance regulators that for
decades the company charged black customers higher premiums than
whites, and that it often collected premiums from customers of all
races that exceeded the value of their insurance policies.
</P>
<P>
   Florida is investigating four other companies for similar
practices.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of the lawsuits and investigation has been on policies
sold to poor people and designed to cover burial expenses. Premiums
of as little as a few cents or a few dollars were paid weekly or
monthly and death benefits were in the range of a few hundred or a
few thousand dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators around the country believe that more than 30
companies sold these policies and they suspect that many of them
discriminated against black customers. For years, actuarial tables
used by insurance companies were based on the assumption that
blacks had shorter life spans than whites. Now actuaries and
sociologists say that poverty rather than race led to shorter lives
for many of those against whom the companies discriminated.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential said that over several decades it had been increasing
the death benefits on policies for black customers who had paid
higher premiums or refunding the higher premiums. MetLife insisted
that it never had separate rates for blacks and whites, but that
being black was regarded as an additional risk factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were rated a high risk, white or black, you paid the
same price and got the same benefits,'' Foley, the MetLife
spokesman, said. He said he did not know whether the high risk
category was made up of more blacks than whites.
</P>
<P>
   John Stoia, a partner in the firm of Milberg Weiss Bershad Hynes
&AMP; Lerach, who has been working on both lawsuits with lawyers at
several other firms, said he hoped to get refunds or increased
death benefits for customers who paid higher rates for coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Foley of MetLife said his company would ``defend itself against
the idea that MetLife was deceitful, that it defrauded
African-American policyholders or hid from them any facts necessary
for them to make their purchases.'' He added: ``There was no
economic loss on the part of any African-American policyholder who
bought a policy from us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
