<HEADER>
A1498 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-BRADLEY-1010(2TA     07-13 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BRADLEY-1010(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETURNING FROM SECLUSION, BRADLEY ENDORSES GORE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., N.Y., N.J., Texas, Pa.)   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE with ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREEN BAY, Wis. _ Bill Bradley emerged from months of political
seclusion Thursday to endorse Vice President Al Gore, his erstwhile
primary foe, and to help Gore appeal to independent voters here in
the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, whose bitter primary battle with Gore ended without his
winning a single state, used the words of Vince Lombardi, the
former coach of the Green Bay Packers, to say that he would work
for a Democratic president and a Democratic Congress. ``Winning is
a team sport,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today I want to make it clear that I endorse Al Gore for
president of the United States,'' Bradley told a crowd at an
old-fashioned amusement park on the shore of Lake Michigan. He
cited the vice president's leadership and his understanding of
technology, saying that that understanding would allow Gore to keep
the nation steady in an era of rapid change.
</P>
<P>
   Gore effusively praised Bradley for his ``high ideals,'' adding:
``There is no more passionate voice for justice and equality in all
of America.''
</P>
<P>
   As the two Democrats were making up on stage, Gore's campaign
was engaged in the kind of political pounding of Gov. George W.
Bush's policies that Gore had employed so effectively against
Bradley in the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign seized on news of a $750 million state budget
shortfall in Texas as evidence that Bush's proposal for a
$1.3-trillion tax cut for the nation over 10 years would derail the
roaring economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Bush wants to do for America what he's done for Texas _
go to Washington and spend our surplus and then more for
budget-busting tax cuts, and hope then that somehow it will all add
up,'' Gore declared. ``The last thing this country needs is an era
of Bush economics that brings us back to deficits, high interest
rates and high unemployment.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush responded with a sharp attack on Gore, saying that the vice
president did not understand the budget process in Texas and that
his state's budget shortfall would be covered by surplus tax
revenues. ``If Al Gore suggests a state with a surplus shouldn't
cut taxes then how can the American people count on Al Gore to cut
taxes when our nation has a surplus?'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   But the main task of the day, at least for Gore, was to present
Bradley as an ally and win over the independent voters that
Bradley, a former New Jersey senator, appealed to in his own
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday was the first time that Bradley and Gore had met since
debating in Los Angeles on March 1. Bradley, who last fall
surprised the Gore campaign by gaining strong support in New
Hampshire and other critical states, was ultimately trounced by
Gore in every state in which they competed. Bradley dropped out of
the race on March 9, retaining his handful of delegates and not
issuing an explicit endorsement of Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But the Gore campaign has had trouble attracting the kind of
voters to whom Bradley appealed, particularly white men and
independents. And as the mid-August Democratic convention
approaches, officials said, the Gore camp has been ever more eager
to knit up the raveled Bradley relationship and aggressively court
the swing voters who are up for grabs in the Midwest battleground
states. ``I really appreciated Sen. Bradley's support,'' Gore told
supporters at the airport here after the event. ``This is one of
the most important days in the election.'' He added: ``He has a big
following and an even larger number that respect his judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign chose this quaint set piece of Americana for
the long-awaited reunion for its picturesqueness and the chance to
reach swing voters. The crowd, which local police officials
estimated at about 3,500 people, was bolstered by Gore supporters
from organized labor, including the National Education Association
and the International Association of Fire Fighters. They have been
among Gore's most ardent supporters, and their presence reflected a
concern in the Gore camp that the event, given the animosity that
characterized their primary battle, could have gone awry.
</P>
<P>
   As it happened, the event appeared to go smoothly, even if there
was little warmth between the candidates and their staffs. None of
the Bradley aides is joining the Gore campaign, and the two
candidates did not make themselves available to reporters for
questioning after their speeches. Democratic officials said that
Bradley could not be available because he had to catch a plane
Thursday night to Italy, but there also was some grumbling among
Bradley backers that Gore had held the event in Wisconsin instead
of a state like New Jersey or New York, where Bradley is better
known and more popular.
</P>
<P>
   The two met privately at the airport here for 40 minutes, with
no aides present, before they appeared together and clasped hands
for the cameras. Gore aides said that Bradley would have a
prime-time speaking slot on the second night of the four-day
nominating convention and they expected Bradley to campaign on
behalf of Gore, but nothing had been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Bradley alluded to the ``big'' issues he had
raised in the campaign _ racial strife, poverty, globalization _
and said that under Gore's leadership, ``we will come closer to
solving the problems I mentioned earlier than under the leadership
of Gov. George W. Bush. And it's not even a close call.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he was endorsing Gore because the vice president
understood technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more of our future will depend on forces and
scientific breakthroughs that many Americans don't fully
understand,'' Bradley said. Putting in his own words an idea that
the Gore staff often asks its supporters to say in public, Bradley
added: ``It takes leadership to see the future as it could be and
then to set a direction and move our country toward it.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Vice President Gore has a deep understanding of
those technological forces changing America. I know he will strive
to keep America ahead of those forces so that they maximize our
future for the greatest number of Americans.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Whether Bradley was quite ready to step out seemed arguable.
Famously contemplative and reluctant to follow the traditional
norms of politics, he acknowledged somewhat wistfully in his speech
that his loss to Gore had been a deep disappointment, one that he
was chalking up to experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Experience is what you get when you don't get what you really
wanted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to their effort to present the Bradley endorsement
in the best possible light, the Gore team went to great lengths to
focus attention on the Texas budget, delivering reams of documents
and flying a policy aide from Washington and a state legislator
from Texas to Green Bay to brief reporters on it.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that his own proposals for balancing the budget and
paying down the debt, would maintain the current economic boom. He
added: ``Gov. Bush has a different priority _ massive tax breaks
for those who don't need them. Let's give Gov. Bush credit. He
practices what he preaches, in that his top priority for Texas'
budget surpluses was a big tax cut.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Pittsburgh, Bush responded to the
criticism by pointing out that President Clinton was planning to
sign a $15 billion supplemental appropriation for extra expenses in
the current budget year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why Vice President Al Gore has got no credibility on an
issue like this,'' he said. ``On one hand he wants to launch an
attack. On the other hand President Clinton is doing the same
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush added that the shortfall resulted from unanticipated
Medicaid expenses and criminal justice costs, but he said the state
had plenty of money to cover those expenses. ``We still have a
surplus and we're going to have a surplus,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Later asked why Bush had made such a point of aggressively
rebutting Gore, Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for the governor,
pointed to the man who lost so badly to Gore in the primaries.
``Bush is not Bradley,'' Fleischer said. ``Bush will
counterpunch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
