<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1500 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-RECORD-BOOK-ADVANCE-N     07-13 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECORD-BOOK-ADVANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME WARNER WINS BIDDING WAR FOR JACK WELCH BOOK WITH $7.1 MILLION
ADVANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo.)   By DAVID D. KIRKPATRICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Time Warner Trade Publishing Thursday acquired the
right to publish a book by Jack Welch, the widely-admired chairman
of General Electric Co., for a record advance of $7.1 million, more
than advances previously paid for books by Gen. Colin Powell or the
pope.
</P>
<P>
   Publishers involved in the bidding war for the proposal said the
extraordinarily high level of interest in the book reflected the
country's growing obsession with business and the stock market.
American are working more hours and, in an overheated job market,
seeking more rewarding work, said Carolyn Reidy, president of the
trade division at Simon &AMP; Schuster. Meanwhile the baby boom's
interest in saving for retirement has spread a new fascination with
the investing. The eye-popping sum also testified, they said, to a
masterful sales job by Welch himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a book that many of us have wanted to publish for
years _ a one of a kind book, by the kind of person who comes along
once in a century,'' said Maureen Egen, president of Time Warner
Trade Publishing, a unit of Time Warner Inc., who met with Welch
and bought the book. ``He is an amazing teacher _ just in the time
we spent with him we learned so much.''
</P>
<P>
   The news of the price _ believed to be a record for a one-time
work of nonfiction _ immediately drew skepticism from the people in
the book business. An executive at the Tattered Cover, a large
bookstore in Denver, and other editors in New York said they had
never heard of Welch. Others questioned the magnitude of the
advance. The contract includes only rights to sell the book in
North America, leaving Welch and his agent the right to sell
foreign rights and first-excerpt rights to others. Foreign rights
are expected to be very lucrative because Welch has attracted a
cult following among businessmen in some other countries, notably
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   To pay off a $7.1 million advance on royalties would require
sales in North America of about 1.6 million hardcover books. Only
one or two titles a year sell more than one million copies. A
recent bestseller by Bill Gates, chairman of Microsoft Corp.,
recently sold about half million copies.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is this the first book to trade on Welch's reputation as a
business savant. A half dozen books have already tapped that
market, including ``Jack Welch and the GE Way'' and three other
books written by the author Mark Slater with Welch's extensive
cooperation. Their editor, Jeffrey Krames at McGraw Hill Companies,
said the titles of the Jack Welch library are among the company's
best sellers, with a total of about half a million copies in print
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The long shelf of Welch books has even drawn an anti-Welch
backlash _ ``At Any Cost: Jack Welch, General Electric,'' and ``The
Pursuit of Profit'' by Thomas F. Boyle.
</P>
<P>
   Welch wanted to leave posterity his own account of his business
philosophy. At 64 years old, he will retire next year after a 20-
year stint at the helm of General Electric, after lifting the
company from a motley conglomerate with a market value of about $12
billion to one of the world's largest and most widely admired
companies with a market value of over $280 billion. As Welch
reminded prospective publishers in meetings last week, the company
has delivered shareholders a stunning average annual return over 20
percent during his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Welch has teamed up to write the book with John A. Byrne, a
writer for Business Week magazine and the author of a critical book
about another hard-charging executive, Al Dunlop. Byrne two years
ago spent six months researching a profile of Welch for the
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   To sell the project, Welch tapped Mark Reiter, 48, a literary
agent with the predominantly sports marketing firm International
Management Group. Reiter is not a big name agent in the literary
world world but whose boss, Mark McCormack, IMG's founder, is a
friend of Welch.
</P>
<P>
   Reiter wasted no time in closing a deal, in part to keep the
pressure on the bidders. He sent out a brief proposal for the book
along with Byrne's profile of his subject shortly before the fourth
of July. Immediately several publishers called in to try to make
pre-emptive bids. ``I didn't even need to read the proposal to know
I wanted to buy the book,'' said Stephen Ruben, who heads the
Doubleday-Currency business book imprint at Bertelsmann Group.
</P>
<P>
   On July 5, Reiter called the long list of publishers to set a
minimum bid of $4 million. Four publishers made the cut and each
met for an hour Friday morning with Welch, his agent and writer at
the GE executive's New York office in Rockefeller Center office _
beginning with Warner, followed by HarperCollins, Doubleday and
finally Simon &AMP; Schuster. Welch's secretary concealed the list of
appointments so that none of the publishers knew the names of their
rivals. Each sent teams of about a half a dozen top executives.
Executives of Doubleday prepared a complete book jacket and
marketing plan to pitch to Welch.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his shirt sleeves at a conference table, Welch, who
has bright blue eyes and speaks with a slight stutter, preferred
talking about his ideas about management over marketing details,
publishers said. Executives said Welch interrupted prepared
presentations. He caught them off guard by candidly challenging
them to top the other publishers' ideas. He took out a notepad to
draw diagrams illustrating such subjects as the challenges facing
Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   At the one point, the conversation turned to Lee Iacocca, the
legendary chairman of Chrysler Motors whose autobiography sold 2.6
million copies in hardcover and 3.5 million in paperback in North
America. Welch told them that he would consider a book like
Iacocca's a failure, because it was about a personality rather than
ideas. Welch said he preferred the model of Alfred P. Sloan's ``My
Years With General Motors,'' which lives on as a business school
perennial.
</P>
<P>
   Bidding started Monday morning in flurry of phone calls to
Reiter's office. Bids rose through the day from $4.1 million to
$4.5 million, and from $4.5 million to $5.5 million. When the
bidding reached $6.5 _ the level of Colin Powell's advance for
worldwide rights _ - Doubleday and Simon &AMP; Schuster dropped out. At
$7.1 million, Welch and Reiter halted bidding to evaluate the two
finalists' marketing plans and get acquainted with their
executives.
</P>
<P>
   Welch will give his share of the advance to educational
charities. At a typical agent's commission of 15 percent, Reiter
will net about $1 million. But, of course, that does include the
foreign rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
