<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIVIL-UNION-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTSIDERS FLOCK TO VERMONT FOR CIVIL-UNION WEDDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Edits, corrections thruout)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAPHAEL LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PUTNEY, Vt. _ Three hours after landing at Logan International
Airport Thursday morning, John Ferrari and Henry Lloyd of Atlanta
clasped hands on a stranger's back lawn in this bucolic town,
looked each other in the eye, and pledged to remain united for
life.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after a few pleasantries with a justice of the peace they
had met five minutes earlier, the two men, wearing tennis shirts
and jeans, got into their rented SUV and whooshed back to the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   Like the typical Las Vegas wedding, it was just a couple of
out-of-staters getting hitched, with no cake, caterers or weeping
in-laws looking on. But unlike heterosexual newlyweds in Nevada,
when Ferrari and Lloyd's four-minute ceremony ended Thursday, they
knew their bond would not be legally recognized in their distant
home.
</P>
<P>
   So go civil unions in Vermont these days, two weeks after the
state implemented its landmark, controversial law allowing gay and
lesbian couples to live in a state of near-matrimony. According to
town clerks, justices of the peace, and those watching the novel
process unfold, the ``CU'' of Ferrari and Lloyd is the norm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flatlanders,'' as outsiders are called here, constitute the
vast majority of couples who have so far entered into civil unions.
Vermont is the only state that recognizes them as legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the ceremonies tend to be minutes-long, bare-bones
affairs, nearly all of which lack the now cliched images Americans
have come to expect when two people come together for life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a societal model for this,'' said Ferrari, 39.
``We have to think through every little step and talk about whether
we want to do things the straight way or something totally
different. The only thing we knew was that we wanted to do this as
soon as possible. If a state comes along and says, `We're going to
legally acknowledge you,' you don't wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Since July 1, when civil unions became law, town clerks have
notified the Vermont Department of Health that they have issued 19
civil union licenses, 11 of which went to out-of-state couples,
said Linda Davis, who manages the department's vital records
division. Since small towns are required to notify the state only
once a month, some here believe that perhaps three or four times
more civil unions have actually taken place. Most of those have
been to out-of-staters as well.
</P>
<P>
   Clerks from across Vermont are saying the same thing: It may be
Vermont's law, but those taking quick advantage tend to come from
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think about the nationwide population of gay and
lesbian people, and you think about the fact that Vermont is the
only place it's available, I can see why out-of-state people would
be the majority,'' said Dorothy Mammen, coordinator of the Vermont
Freedom to Marry Task Force, which campaigned strongly for civil
unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of them who are doing it quickly may well have done a
commitment ceremony at home and yet whenever they do one of those,
there's no official recognition, so they're coming here to finish
what they have started.''
</P>
<P>
   If out-of-staters are making up the majority of couples entering
into civil unions, that does not necessarily mean Vermont's gay and
lesbian couples are uninterested, many here say. Some speculate
that many of Vermont's committed lesbian and gay partners are busy
planning more involved ceremonies, deciding which caterer to hire,
which band will play, and who will be invited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally don't think the law is in any jeopardy and I
think a lot of Vermonters know that,'' said Marc Awodey, a
Burlington justice of the peace who will have performed 11 civil
unions by the end of this weekend. But the fear that the law will
someday be revoked is ``something that prompted some (out-of-state
couples) to go ahead more quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet if some couples hope to get hitched while the hitching's
good, others hope to use their civil unions like a seed that they
will plant in their home states. Ferrari and Lloyd, who plan to
move to Southern California in the next few weeks, say they are
quite serious about using their union as a ``test case'' in their
new state, or joining other California couples already doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Westing, the Putney justice of the peace who performed
their ceremony, said other couples have told her the same thing.
``I don't get the sense that a lot of these couples are content to
accept that their civil union is only good in a state where they
don't even live.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite such high-minded arguments, some observers here believe
much of what they're seeing is plain old spontaneity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's vacation time, and let's face it, this is a really
popular state for gay, lesbian, bisexual, and transgendered couples
anyway,'' said Barbara Dozetos, editor of Out in the Mountains, a
monthly newspaper that caters to the state's gay and lesbian
community. ``Don't think some couples aren't just saying, `Let's do
it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ferrari, a retired cabaret dancer and sales executive, and
Lloyd, a corporate executive, say they began discussing the
ceremony months ago, when it looked as though Vermont would succeed
in legalizing such unions. When July 1 finally arrived, Ferrari
said, they decided their time had come.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Vermont was brave enough to accept us, we had to show
support for Vermont as soon as possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the couple spent countless hours contemplating
whether to enter into civil union, their simple ceremony Thursday
seemed to pack more emotional power than they expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``You realize, of course, that this means you can't get rid of
me now,'' Lloyd, 45, said moments after the men were CU'd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that what this means?'' Ferrari said, laughing. ``Gee,
maybe this was a bad idea after all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
