<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFEREES KEEP GUN-CONTROL BILL HOLSTERED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LETITIA STEIN 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two months after moms marched in Washington and
across the nation for stricter gun laws, legislation that would
curb access to weapons is stalled on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   It has been over a year since the Columbine High School shooting
prompted Congress to enact measures to tighten federal gun laws.
Since then, additional legislation, which is attached to a juvenile
justice spending bill, has stagnated in a judiciary conference
committee charged with resolving differences between bills passed
in the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The conference committee has met only once, last August, without
breakthroughs, despite recent congressional resolutions instructing
the committee to move quickly to iron out differences in the bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason to believe that that conference committee is
going to meet for the rest of the session,'' said a House
Democratic staff member. ``My impression is that the Republicans
are just trying to run out the clock for the rest of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Gun-control advocates suggest frustration over the inaction will
show up in the voting booth in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're bitterly disappointed by the inaction of Congress,''
said Nina Butts, an organizer of the Million Mom March in Austin
and lobbyist for Texans Against Gun Violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to change the faces at the Texas capitol and in
Congress,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Butts and other gun-control advocates think the issue could
prove decisive in voting decisions this fall among the thousands of
largely professional, suburban women who joined rallies in
Washington and 67 other cities in May.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, those voices and continued pressure from the Clinton
administration have failed to break the congressional deadlock.
Both the House and Senate have urged the committee to address
discrepancies in the two bills in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nation is waiting for Congress to act to close the
gun-show loophole that lets criminals and young people buy guns at
gun shows, no questions asked,'' said Attorney General Janet Reno
at an event held this past week &UR;  &LR; to encourage college students to
rally against gun violence on campuses.
</P>
<P>
   A month after the shootings at Columbine High School in
Littleton, Co., in April 1999, Vice President Al Gore placed a
tie-breaking vote to pass a Senate measure that would require
gun-show background checks, child safety locks on firearms and ban
the importation of large capacity ammunition clips.
</P>
<P>
   The House approved a scaled-down version of the legislation that
also would require background checks to be conducted at gun shows _
closing a loophole that allowed unregulated firearms purchases at
gun shows _ but shortened the deadline for completing background
checks at gun shows from the Senate's deadline of three business
days to 24 hours. Additionally, the House measure more narrowly
defined gun shows as events where guns alone are sold, which
critics claimed would allow unregulated gun purchases at smaller
venues.
</P>
<P>
   Both Democratic and Republican strategists say the gun issue
could determine who wins the elections in such battleground states
as Illinois, Michigan, Ohio and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conventional wisdom is that this cuts in the suburbs and that
it cuts with women and so on. The reality is that it cuts beyond
just the suburbs, and it cuts with men too, '' said Democratic
pollster Mark Mellman, who thinks the issue could play a decisive
role in the battle for control of the House.
</P>
<P>
   But some Republicans contend the polls show that only those who
want greater enforcement of existing gun laws, not new
restrictions, will actually base their voting decisions on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``History has shown that when it comes to actual voting
behavior, the people who support gun rights always out-vote the
people who support more gun control,'' said Bill Pascoe, press
secretary at Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Pascoe said anti-control voters will bring their message to the
polls in November, which he anticipates will help Republicans in
the fall elections.
</P>
<P>
   But not all Republicans agree with the leadership view.
Congresswoman Constance Morella, R-Md., said the issue will draw
attention in the election, especially among suburban voters in the
northeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not asking that guns be taken away from people. They can
still use them for hunting,'' she said, referring to the gun
lobby's concern that the legislation would restrict the
constitutional right of citizens to own a gun. ``We're asking for
appropriate restrictions that everyone can believe in,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control advocacy groups hope to redirect the momentum from
the Million Mom March into voters education drives and other
grass-roots activities centered on the fall election. The
Washington-based Handgun Control political action committee also
plans to spend $2 million on the 2000 elections, and Texans Against
Gun Violence is seeking to raise $30,000 to spend on campaigns this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think they're putting their eggs in the electoral
basket, and they're going to say voters don't care about this,''
said David Bernstein, a spokesperson for Handgun Control. ``We
think that's a big mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of more gun control also are mobilizing in local and
national campaigns. National Rifle Association Spokeman Bill Powers
said the 3.8 million members of the gun owners' rights organization
are sending record amounts of money to the group's political action
committee and signing up to get involved in campaign activities.
</P>
<P>
   Powers said it is still to early to discuss what actions the NRA
will take this fall, but ``members are very aware that this is a
very critical election year, and we're looking forward to
November.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
