<P>
   (NYT12) EL SALADO, Colombia -- July 13, 2000 --
COLOMBIA-MILITARY -- Armed men, more than 300 of them, marched into
the tiny village of El Salado, Colombia early on a Friday, went
straight to the basketball court that doubles as the main square,
announced themselves as members of Colombia's most feared
paramilitary group and with a list of names began summoning residents
for judgment. By the time they left late Sunday afternoon, they had
killed at least 36 people whom they accused of collaborating with the
enemy, left-wing guerrillas who have long been a presence in the
area. With most villagers having fled to nearby towns, a lone
resident remained in El Salado. (Larry Rohter/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) HINGHAM, Mass. -- July 13, 2000 -- RETAIL-TALBOTS-BOS
-- Since 1947, Talbots Inc. has provided sensible wardrobes for women
between 35 and 55. In 1997, looking to broaden its appeal to include
women in their late 20s and early 30s, Talbots began flirting with
trendier styles and shorter hemlines. The result was a marketing
flop. Not only did new styles fail to win over younger customers, but
they also alienated women who had been intensely loyal to Talbots for
years. Since 1997, Talbot's has returned to its classic roots and
have become one of the hottest apparel retailers in the business
according to Wall Street analysts. Talbot's, chief executive officer,
Arnold B. Zetcher, at a Talbot's store in Hingham, Mass. (Tom
Landers/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- July 13, 2000 -- CARRACCI-BAROQUE-2 -- In
the 1580s, Annibale Carracci, unhappy with the Mannerist preciosity
that dominated the art of his time, helped start an art academy that
pushed for a return to nature and the classical heritage of the great
Italian masters who preceded him, in particular Correggio, Veronese
and Titian. Carracci was considered one of the greatest draftsmen of
his age. He created a highly influential fresco cycle for the ceiling
of the Farnese Palace in Rome, that was lauded as the equal of
Raphael's work in the Vatican. "A Domestic Scene," probably from the
early 1580's by Carracci is featured in the exhibit, "The Birth of
Baroque: The Carracci at the Metropolitan," at the Metropolitan
Museum of Art. (The Metropolitan Museum of Art/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- July 13, 2000 -- CARRACCI-BAROQUE-1 -- In
the 1580s, unhappy with the Mannerist preciosity that dominated the
art of his time, Ludovico Carracci helped start an art academy that
pushed for a return to nature and the classical heritage of the great
Italian masters who preceded him, in particular Correggio, Veronese
and Titian. The academy developed a style which eventually became
known as Baroque. "The Lamentation," circa1582, by Carracci is
featured in the exhibit, "The Birth of Baroque: The Carracci at the
Metropolitan," at the Metropolitan Museum of Art. (The Metropolitan
Museum of Art/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) DENVER -- July 13, 2000 -- EPISCOPAL-GAYS -- Members
of the House of Deputies at the Episcopal Church's convention in
Denver Wednesday debated a plan to set up a task force to "assist"
three dioceses in complying with church law by ordaining women as
priests. Delegates from the three Episcopal dioceses gather to pray
after the resolution requiring the dioceses to ordain women passed.
(Kevin Moloney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- July 13, 2000 -- AIRBUS-NEW-JET -- The
European Airbus Industrie group is close to introducing another
transportation behemoth, a gigantic double-decker jumbo jet, known
for now as the A3XX, for use on long distance routes like those
between Asia and Europe or the United States. With a capacity of
between 555 and 800 passengers, it would carry at least 140
passengers more than the largest Boeing 747. And its development cost
is expected to exceed $10 billion. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- July 13, 2000 -- HKN-MESSIER-RANGERS -- At
age 39, and after enduring three playoff-less seasons of his own in
Vancouver, once retired New York Rangers captain Mark Messier now
returns to the same Broadway stage that he once owned like no other
hockey player before or since. This time, it is for a
long-anticipated second act with a two-year contract for a base total
of $11 million to guarantee his return. Messier talking with
reporters during an emotional press conference announcing his return
to the Rangers. (G. Paul Burnett/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- JULY 13, 2000 -- COMPUTERS-NAVY-BOS --
There was a time when sailors would be out of touch with home for
weeks or months. The youngsters aboard the USS McFaul, one of the
Navy's newest ships, will never know such a world. These days, the
Navy depends on an intricate system of global communications that
ensures that a ship is never out of touch. Neither are its sailors.
Providing e-mail access for its 320-person crew is a trivial matter
for the McFaul, a floating showpiece of advanced technology. First
Class Petty Officer, Shawn Turek, a cryptologic technician, online
while aboard the USS McFaul during a recent stop in New York.
(Jonathan Wiggs/The Boston Globe) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) KENNEBUNKPORT, Me. -- July 13, 2000 -- BUSH-BROTHER --
Former President George Bush with his son Jeb in Kennebunkport, Me.
Rather than capitalize on his brother's fame, Jeb Bush has receded
into the shadows far more than is typical for a new governor of a big
state. Resisting entreaties from other governors and Republican
officials, Bush rarely ventures beyond Florida to take part in party
functions. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ST. PETERSBURG, Russia -- July 13, 2000 -- ADV. FOR
SUN. JULY 16 -- GERGIEV-BALLET-2 -- A scene from the Maryinsky Opera
production of "Das Rheingold," produced by Valery Gergiev. For a
theater that until a decade ago was entirely dependent on the
government for money, the Maryinsky's success at collecting private
sponsors is remarkable, not only by Russian but also by European
standards. And it is owed entirely to Gergiev himself, whose
near-demonic energy and magnetic charm are now legendary, both here
and abroad. (James Hill/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) ST. PETERSBURG, Russia -- July 13, 2000 -- ADV. FOR
SUN. JULY 16 -- GERGIEV-BALLET-1 -- A poster for the Stars of the
White Nights festival, showing Valery Gergiev in action, in front of
the Church of the Savior on the Blood in St. Petersburg. Every June,
Gergiev, one of the world's most sought-after conductors and the
theater's artistic director, brings glamour to this gritty city with
a pretty face, where czarist palaces share streets with Dickensian
squalor, a city of giant potholes and columned facades, of high
culture and low wages. (James Hill/The New York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- July 13, 2000 --  HARRY-POTTER-VOICE --
Jim Dale, 64, an actor and the voice for the Harry Potter audiobooks
is a blithe spirit who wishes that the books were available during
his childhood. Dale, cast to narrate "Harry Potter and the Goblet of
Fire," J.K. Rowling's latest book, created 125 speaking voices for
the audio, and needed guidance from the author for the
phantasmagorical names. Dale, who was a pop music and television star
in Britain before he ventured into narration, in his apartment in New
York. (Librado Romero/The New York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
