<DOCNO> NYT20000713.0341 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1512 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-JOYNER-KERSEE-NYT     07-13 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-JOYNER-KERSEE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOYNER-KERSEE TRIES TO MAKE U.S. OLYMPIC TEAM A 5TH TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mo., Calif., Ga., N.C.)   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ The lasting image is of Jackie
Joyner-Kersee standing on the runway at the 1996 Atlanta Olympics,
mired in sixth place in the long jump, one attempt remaining, her
right upper leg heavily bandaged from a hamstring injury. At one
point, she had even whacked the leg with the small mallet used to
set her mark on the runway, as if hammering the dent out of a
fender, trying to will the strained muscle into explosive
compliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there is more there,'' she told herself on the infield
of the filled Olympic Stadium. ``Forget about the leg. This is it,
Jackie. You either attack the board or don't jump at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Attack she did, sailing from sixth place to third on what was to
be her farewell jump in the Summer Games, her valedictory
performance as the greatest athlete of her generation. Later,
Joyner-Kersee said the bronze medal was special, nearly as
rewarding as the two gold medals she had previously won in the
heptathlon and the gold she had won in 1988 in the long jump.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really had to work for this one,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1998, Joyner-Kersee retired, giving
professional basketball a short try, becoming a sports marketing
agent and running a foundation dedicated to providing sports
opportunities for youngsters in her hometown of East St. Louis,
Ill.
</P>
<P>
   But she could not stay away from track and field. Joyner-Kersee
will come out of retirement at age 38 to jump again at the Olympic
trials Friday night. She is seeking to make her fifth Olympic team.
Her presence could also throw up an impediment to Marion Jones'
attempt to win five gold medals at the 2000 Summer Games in Sydney,
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a Jackie-Marion duel,'' said Bob Kersee, who is
Joyner-Kersee's coach and husband. ``Competing against Marion,
frankly even going after the gold medal, we've been there, done
that. What we haven't done is been on five Olympic teams. That's
the challenge. That's what we're excited about. The first thing is
to make the team, then you start worrying about trying to win a
medal.''
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to know what to make of this comeback. The
qualifying round is Friday night; the final is Sunday.
Joyner-Kersee still holds the American record at 24 feet 7 inches.
In fact, she has delivered the top seven jumps by an American
woman. Yet, she has not jumped in two years, and her last attempt
was a mediocre 20-11}. She has been training seriously since late
March, Kersee said, but has not taken any full jumps, working
instead on the speed to her approach and her technique.
</P>
<P>
   One of two things will most likely happen. Either retirement has
healed her injuries and fresh legs will carry her sufficiently to
gain one of three spots on the Olympic team, or she will jump
poorly and pay for a moment of hubris. In either case, nothing has
happened this season to discourage Joyner-Kersee from believing
that she can make the American team and win another Olympic medal.
</P>
<P>
   Fiona May of Italy, the 1996 Olympic silver medalist, has the
world's top jump at 23-3\. Jones is fifth on the world list with a
seasonal best of 22-10{, assured now that her unmatched sprinter's
speed can overcome the many inadequacies in her form. Her personal
best is 23-11}, and on any given attempt Jones is capable of
jumping breathtakingly far or frustratingly short.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I see in the long jump, between 22 and 23 feet is
capable of making the team,'' Kersee said. ``I feel a Jackie who is
healthy and on the mark still has that ability. I think we couldn't
sit home wondering whether we had a chance to make five Olympic
teams. As usual, we've got to go out and accept the challenge. From
what I see in terms of trajectory, I still think Jackie is a
23-foot jumper. I don't know that for sure. This is a new
experience for me as well. But Jackie has always set all the
standards.''
</P>
<P>
   She has jumped once against Jones at the national championships,
three years ago in Indianapolis, where Jones prevailed with a leap
of 22-9. Jones is the type of athlete who seems to thrive in the
cauldron of competition. Friday night, in addition to the long-jump
qualifying, she must run her first round of the 100 meters. While
Joyner-Kersee's presence could unnerve Jones, it could just as
easily propel her. The two are friends, and Jones has consulted
Joyner-Kersee for suggestions about smoothing the kinks in her own
awkward technique.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be wonderful if Jackie's going to be in the mix,''
Jones said recently. ``Jackie's going to be ready. She's not going
to come out here and jump 18 feet. I think one of the highlights of
my career was competing against her in '97. When the competition
starts, it'll be a free-for-all. I'm OK with it.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Joyner-Kersee, whose grandmother named her after Jacqueline
Kennedy Onassis in hopes that she would grow up ``to be the first
lady of something,'' returns to the event that helped make her the
first lady of track and field. She first learned to long jump on
her front porch back in East St. Louis. She and her two sisters
would leap into a pit fashioned from sand carried from a nearby
park in discarded bags of potato chips.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be great to see if I could do it,'' Joyner-Kersee
said. ``I've always admired Willye White, knowing that she was able
to do it. It would be an honor and would put me in a pretty
exclusive class of people.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she did not consider herself to be a rival of Jones'.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider her a friend. I'll be out there critiquing her,
seeing if there's anyway I can help her out, but she's the best we
have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
