<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1519 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-EPISCOPALIANS-TEX     07-13 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPISCOPALIANS-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Episcopalians put more pressure on Thursday on the conservative
Diocese of Fort Worth and two other dioceses nationwide to accept
women as priests.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth delegation walked out in protest at the national
convention in
Denver after the House of Deputies overwhelmingly approved a
resolution for an action plan by Sept. 1, 2002, to make sure that
Fort Worth and dioceses in Illinois and California comply with
church law making it mandatory to accept female priests.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution will be voted on Friday by the House of Bishops,
who must concur for it to go into effect.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the nearly 30-year-old church law on acceptance of
female priests, Fort Worth and the diocese of Quincy, Ill., still
have none. San Joaquin in northern California recently began
accepting women.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of clergy and lay representatives at the convention
passed a resolution that would set up a task force to ``assist''
the three dioceses in complying with the church law. If a diocese
is ruled to be out of compliance, congregants may seek to oust the
bishop _ a long and complicated process.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution was heartily opposed by the Rev. Canon Charles
Hough, clergy leader of the Fort Worth House of Deputies
delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Hough, who led Fort Worth's walkout, said at a news conference,
``We are disappointed by what has transpired here today. We are not
surprised. We've been fighting this battle for as long as this
diocese has been in existence _ 17 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Explaining the walkout, Hough declared: ``We weren't walking out
of the church. ... We're not leaving the Episcopal Church. ... We
went back to pray because that's what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hough said that some Episcopalians in Fort Worth and other
dioceses believe that appointing female priests is contrary to the
Bible and against church tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're being singled out, and now we're being persecuted for
matters of conscience,'' he said. ``What we are pleading for in
this convention is tolerance and toleration.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Rehill, a delegate from Newark, N.J., was among those
urging the House of Deputies to force compliance of laws on
acceptance of female priests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recall that three years ago there were four dioceses who
would not accept the ordination of women,'' Rehill said. ``Now
there are three. Progress has been made. There should be none.''
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth Episcopal Bishop Jack Iker, one of the church's last
holdouts in accepting female priests, is expected to strongly
oppose the resolution when it is brought up in the House of Bishops
on Friday. He oversees a 23-county diocese with about 19,000
members.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be one more step to enforce the canon requiring
women's ordination,'' church spokesman Jim Solheim said.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution noted the ``lack of progress'' in acceptance of
female priests in the Fort Worth diocese, as well as in Quincy,
Ill., where the bishop is Keith Ackerman, a former Arlington
priest.
</P>
<P>
   The Diocese of San Joaquin is making ``progress,'' the
resolution acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Iker contends that the Fort Worth diocese is in reasonable
compliance with church laws on female priests under an unusual
cooperative agreement with the Episcopal Diocese of Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   If a woman in the Fort Worth diocese feels called to the
priesthood, she is put under the direction of Dallas Episcopal
Bishop Jack Stanton.
</P>
<P>
   Iker's plan also allows any church in the Fort Worth diocese to
accept a female priest. To do so, however, that church would have
to become a part of the Dallas Diocese.
</P>
<P>
   Female deacons who are preparing to become full-fledged priests
have been allowed to work in churches in the Fort Worth diocese,
Hough noted.
</P>
<P>
   But Katie Sherrod, a Fort Worth resident and member of the
Episcopal Women's Caucus, a group that supports women's ordination,
said that the diocese's stand has led some couples to be married in
other denominations and some families to refuse to have their
daughters confirmed in the Episcopal Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do feel we need the ministry of female priests in our
diocese,'' said Sherrod, a former Star-Telegram columnist.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 2212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
