<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1520 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-TAXIS-CREDIT-CARDS     07-13 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TAXIS-CREDIT-CARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TESTS CREDIT CARDS IN CABS 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Cash transactions could soon become optional at of
one of their few remaining strongholds: yellow cabs.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the New York City Taxi and Limousine Commission
said Thursday that 50 yellow cabs have been cruising the city for
the last three weeks with devices that allow riders to pay their
fares with credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   A pilot program is likely to introduce hundreds more
credit-card-friendly cabs to the streets in the next six months,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is something we've been thinking about for a while,'' the
Taxi and Limousine commissioner, Diane McGrath-McKechnie, said at a
news conference. ``The technology is available and we're able to do
it now.''
</P>
<P>
   The technology, developed by a company in Queens, links a
credit-card reader to a modified taximeter. Riders can slide their
Visa, Mastercard or American Express cards through a reader near
the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   The card reader is also connected to a modem that operates on a
cell phone frequency. The apparatus can get an approval of the
passenger's card during the trip.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the ride, the meter prints a receipt with the fare
amount and blank lines for tolls and tip. Riders fill those out and
hand the receipt back to the driver, who enters the total into the
meter.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers who work for fleets can get cash for their credit-card
fares whenever they return to their garages. Nevertheless, some
cabbies seemed hesitant about the new system.
</P>
<P>
   One, Zahoor Ahmed, said he goes into his Brooklyn garage only
once a week, and he could not wait that long to be paid.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Taxi Workers Alliance, which represents more than
2,000 drivers, is also opposed to the credit system. It fears that
the cost of the technology will be passed along to the drivers
through higher cab-leasing fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no benefit in this for the drivers, said Bhairavi
Desai, a leader of the drivers' group.''
</P>
<P>
   But supporters of the technology say fleet drivers do not incur
any costs by accepting credit cards. Instead, taxi owners and
owner-drivers who choose to adopt the system have to pay $550 to
$950 per cab for installation. The cab owner also pays a monthly
fee for the modem's cellular connection and a fee for each
transaction _ 25 cents plus 1.53 percent of the amount charged on
Visa and Mastercard. A spokesman for American Express declined to
disclose that company's fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a win-win all around,'' said Bruce Schaller, an
independent taxi industry consultant based in Brooklyn. ``It's good
for the customer, it's good for the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Half of the 50 yellow cabs in New York that now take credit
cards are owned by Ronart Leasing Corp. in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Levine, vice president of Ronart, said he believes that
many people going to and from airports are using radio-dispatched
limousines instead of yellow cabs because they want to pay with
credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   But Levine, whose fleet has 246 cabs, said reaction to the
technology is mixed among fleet owners. Smaller fleets probably
cannot afford the devices, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Several cities, including San Diego and Los Angeles, have used
similar credit card systems in many cabs for years, Schaller said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
