<P>
   (NYT12) EL SALADO, Colombia -- July 13, 2000 --
COLOMBIA-MILITARY -- Armed men, more than 300 of them, marched into
the tiny village of El Salado, Colombia early on a Friday, went
straight to the basketball court that doubles as the main square,
announced themselves as members of Colombia's most feared
paramilitary group and with a list of names began summoning residents
for judgment. By the time they left late Sunday afternoon, they had
killed at least 36 people whom they accused of collaborating with the
enemy, left-wing guerrillas who have long been a presence in the
area. With most villagers having fled to nearby towns, a lone
resident remained in El Salado. (Larry Rohter/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) HINGHAM, Mass. -- July 13, 2000 -- RETAIL-TALBOTS-BOS
-- Since 1947, Talbots Inc. has provided sensible wardrobes for women
between 35 and 55. In 1997, looking to broaden its appeal to include
women in their late 20s and early 30s, Talbots began flirting with
trendier styles and shorter hemlines. The result was a marketing
flop. Not only did new styles fail to win over younger customers, but
they also alienated women who had been intensely loyal to Talbots for
years. Since 1997, Talbot's has returned to its classic roots and
have become one of the hottest apparel retailers in the business
according to Wall Street analysts. Talbot's, chief executive officer,
Arnold B. Zetcher, at a Talbot's store in Hingham, Mass. (Tom
Landers/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- July 13, 2000 -- CARRACCI-BAROQUE-2 -- In
the 1580s, Annibale Carracci, unhappy with the Mannerist preciosity
that dominated the art of his time, helped start an art academy that
pushed for a return to nature and the classical heritage of the great
Italian masters who preceded him, in particular Correggio, Veronese
and Titian. Carracci was considered one of the greatest draftsmen of
his age. He created a highly influential fresco cycle for the ceiling
of the Farnese Palace in Rome, that was lauded as the equal of
Raphael's work in the Vatican. "A Domestic Scene," probably from the
early 1580's by Carracci is featured in the exhibit, "The Birth of
Baroque: The Carracci at the Metropolitan," at the Metropolitan
Museum of Art. (The Metropolitan Museum of Art/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- July 13, 2000 -- CARRACCI-BAROQUE-1 -- In
