<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-U.S.-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIETNAM AND THE U.S. SIGN `HISTORIC' TRADE AGREEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In what President Clinton described Thursday as a
``historic step in normalization, reconciliation and healing,'' the
United States and Vietnam signed a lengthy trade agreement that, if
put into effect fully, would transform America's onetime enemy from
a quasi-socialist redoubt into Asia's newest capitalist recruit.
</P>
<P>
   The 150-page accord covers bank branches, customs fees,
publication of laws and regulations, and tariffs on onions, garlic,
potatoes and cheese among many other goods, services and investment
protections _ a prescription for economic overhaul that
substantially curtails the power of Vietnam's Communist Party over
its economy.
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam, with its small, troubled and highly protected economy,
risks much more than the United States. But the agreement requires
the United States to reduce its tariffs on Vietnamese imports
substantially, a concession that has often proved a tough sell in
Congress. It is unlikely that Congress will vote on the measure
during Clinton's term, however.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. trade representative, Charlene Barshefsky, and
Vietnam's trade minister, Vu Khoan, signed the agreement Thursday
afternoon. At a Rose Garden ceremony shortly after the signing,
Clinton, flanked by several Vietnam War veterans who now serve in
Congress, hailed the trade deal as a vital step in resuming full
ties. Clinton normalized diplomatic relations in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the bitter past, we plant the seeds of a better future,''
Clinton said. ``This agreement is one more reminder that former
adversaries can come together to find common ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington and Hanoi have been trying to seal their first
postwar trade accord for nearly five years, about as much time as
it took them to sign the Paris Peace Agreement of 1973, which led
to the withdrawal of American troops from Vietnam. Hanoi balked at
American demands several times and walked away from a completed
agreement last year, Clinton administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But Vietnamese officials became far more flexible in June, just
after the House voted to grant China, Vietnam's neighbor, rival and
fellow communist reformer, coveted trading rights in the American
market.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said that China's pending
accession to the World Trade Organization and signs that Vietnam's
economy had stagnated convinced Vietnamese leaders that the time
had come to inject some capitalist energy into the economy akin to
the initial wave of reforms that began in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a confluence of factors, and China was clearly an
important one,'' Barshefsky said Thursday. ``This will deepen and
accelerate economic reforms, strengthen the rule of law, and help
Vietnam integrate itself into the world economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement shows that Vietnam insisted on a comfortable grace
period to allow its companies to adjust to foreign competition.
Though American retailers can enter the market there for the first
time, they will be limited to a single retail store indefinitely.
Vietnam would allow American financial companies to issue credit
cards, but only eight years after the agreement takes effect.
</P>
<P>
   In businesses that might affect Vietnam's ability to exercise
political control, including phone and Internet services, foreign
companies will have to wait at least three years before they can
begin to enter joint-venture agreements with local partners, and
then they will be allowed to take only minority equity stakes.
</P>
<P>
   The changes Vietnam has agreed to undertake are similar to those
China pledged to make, but the pace is often slower. There are a
few exceptions: Vietnam has agreed to allow foreign banks to take
deposits and make loans in local currency, the dong, relatively
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Carlyle A. Thayer, an expert on Vietnam at the Asia-Pacific
Center for Security Studies in Honolulu, said top leaders clearly
decided to mimic Chinese-style market-openings, gambling that they
can maintain party control just as their northern counterparts
have. But he said the agreement takes away much of the flexibility
the leaders have to dictate the scope and the speed of change.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they drag their feet this time, they are going to be facing
legal guerrilla warfare,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement will not take effect at all unless Congress
approves the measure and awards Vietnam so-called normal trade
relations, subject to annual review. Though Clinton administration
officials predicted that Congress would embrace the idea of
normalizing economic ties, labor unions quickly disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   Unions have long demanded that developing countries accept
international labor standards as part of market-opening trade
agreements. This accord, like others negotiated by the Clinton
administration, does not contain language to that effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very disappointed that they did not even attempt to
address worker rights,'' said Thea Lee, a top official at the
AFL-CIO. ``This is just another agreement that encourages American
companies to move their jobs overseas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 2215EDT &QL; 
