<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1538 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-DEMOCRATS-NYT &LR;      07-13 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DEMOCRATS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DEMOCRATIC HARMONY 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, July 14:
</P>
<P>
   The formal endorsement of Vice President Al Gore by former Sen.
Bill Bradley of New Jersey on Thursday was predictable, but Gore
had reason to savor it. Although the vice president defeated
Bradley in every state primary early this year, his campaign since
then has been strangely lethargic. The polls show Gore with only 70
percent support among Democrats, while Gov. George W. Bush has 90
percent support among Republicans. Though he did poorly in the
primary season, Bradley might give Gore a lift among young people
and independents.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's endorsement also marks a shift toward the convention
season and the vice-presidential selections. As political theater,
Bradley's performance at a boisterous rally in Wisconsin was far
different from the awkward endorsement of Bush in May by Sen. John
McCain, who jokingly compared the exercise to taking medicine. In
both cases, how McCain and Bradley handle themselves for the rest
of the year will be watched by party professionals as a sign of
whether either will be able to pick up the pieces and run again if
their nominees are defeated in November.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign was quick to try to recycle the former New
Jersey senator's earlier criticism of Gore, particularly the
charges that Gore was not telling the truth about his record. But
there is a long history of challengers having to eat their words at
convention time with little ill effect. It was Bush's father, after
all, who had to live down his description of Ronald Reagan's
tax-cut plans as ``voodoo economics.'' Both Bradley and McCain have
ruled themselves out for the vice-presidential nominations of their
parties, and there does not seem to be a rush to make them change
their minds.
</P>
<P>
   Only two weeks before the opening of the Republican National
Convention in Philadelphia, speculation is rampant over Bush's
choices. The governor said on Thursday he had a short list. The
guessing has centered on three governors _ Frank Keating of
Oklahoma, George Pataki of New York and Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania _
as well as Elizabeth Dole and Sen. Chuck Hagel of Nebraska. Pataki
and Ridge are pro-choice Catholics who might stir up an unwelcome
furor among anti-abortion forces at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, Gore is said to be looking closely at
Sens. Evan Bayh of Indiana and Bob Graham of Florida, as well as
Gov. James Hunt of North Carolina. But because of the vice
president's weak standing among the Democratic faithful, he is said
to be considering the House minority leader, Rep. Dick Gephardt of
Missouri. Some party insiders say Gephardt, more than anyone else,
would put Missouri in the Democratic column and expand Gore's
support generally within the Democratic base, especially in the
industrial Midwest. But such thinking also highlights one of Gore's
problems. At this point, he should be thinking of strategies for
reaching beyond Democrats to independents and Republicans and not
have to worry about support among Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   This has been a slow season for the campaign. But it is worth
remembering that the primary elections were a time of unusually
intense public interest. Our guess is that the conventions will
reawaken the public's appetite for a combative fall campaign. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
