<HEADER>
A1539 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BAKALY-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      07-13 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAKALY-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTORS CITE DECEPTION IN TRIAL FOR STARR SPOKESMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Justice Department lawyers and witnesses Thursday
accused Charles G. Bakaly III, the former spokesman for Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr, of obstructing justice by misleading
colleagues and a federal court about what he told The New York
Times about a possible indictment of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening day of Bakaly's trial for criminal contempt of
court, a prosecutor charged that his untrue statements had caused
Starr's office to file a false statement to the court in which it
denied discussing the case with a reporter for The Times.
</P>
<P>
   John Griffith, the prosecutor, said that Bakaly made a false
statement when he claimed that a Times reporter had assured him
that his sources were outside the independent counsel's office.
That was ``false,'' Griffith said, because ``Bakaly knew he had
been the source or a source'' of the Jan. 31, 1999, article at
issue in the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The false statement began to unravel, Griffith said, through
Bakaly's gradual admissions, which came only after he had led
Starr's lawyers to file untrue information with U.S. District Judge
Norma Holloway Johnson. That, in turn, caused an obstruction of
justice by delaying court proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Bakaly's lawyers argued that he had struggled to
make his statement truthful and complete, but had been thwarted by
a passion for secrecy among those lawyers for the independent
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Michele A. Roberts, a lawyer for Bakaly, said that if the Starr
lawyers had accurately reflected in their court filings what he had
told them, they would have made it clear that Bakaly sought to
steer Don Van Natta, the Times reporter, ``away from writing the
article he ultimately wrote.'' That article embarrassed the
independent counsel's office by making it appear the office was
trying to prejudice the Senate impeachment trial of President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The defense has also argued that even if Bakaly's statements
were judged false, no serious harm was done. But Johnson has
rejected that argument.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who is hearing the case without a jury, ruled Wednesday
that obstruction could be shown if the government proved the claim
that Bakaly's conduct ``required the court to hold two in-chambers
conferences with outside counsel for the Office of Independent
Counsel and imposed unnecessary work and costs on the OIC.''
</P>
<P>
   In a city where leaks are as common as broken campaign promises,
the rare spectacle of someone actually on trial for being a source
proceeded with little drama and less revelation Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Several hours were devoted to questioning Donald Bucklin, a
lawyer who represented Starr's office in many cases concerning
allegations that the office had improperly disclosed information to
reporters. Bucklin was asked mainly about the preparation of
Bakaly's sworn statement.
</P>
<P>
   In that statement, which was presented to Johnson, Bakaly denied
discussing ``nonpublic'' matters with Van Natta. The January
article quoted ``associates of Mr. Starr'' as saying that he had
decided he had the authority to indict a sitting president and that
Starr was being pressed by lawyers in his office to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors hoped to use Bucklin's testimony to show that Bakaly
edited and changed the statement and was responsible for what it
said. Efforts to prove that the statement was false are expected to
come in Friday's proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Bucklin quoted Bakaly as saying that in the course of three
meetings with Van Natta, the reporter had said he knew that lawyers
were pressing Starr to indict the president, that he also knew
about a meeting to discuss four options concerning an indictment,
and various other matters as well. Bucklin said that Bakaly told
him the reporter said all the information had come from sources
outside the counsel's office.
</P>
<P>
   But later, after he saw a statement by Bakaly to FBI agents,
Bucklin testified, he believed the original sworn statement had
been false, and formally withdrew it.
</P>
<P>
   Another witness Thursday, Solomon Wisenberg, recalled reading in
the FBI interview report that Bakaly said he was the ``associate''
quoted in Van Natta's article.
</P>
<P>
   Wisenberg then demanded to know why Bakaly had told him he was
not one of the associates cited in the article. He said Bakaly
denied ever saying that.
</P>
<P>
   On reflection, Wisenberg testified, Bakaly had in fact told him,
speaking of lawyers in the office, ``Van Natta says we are not the
associates referred to in the article.''
</P>
<P>
   Wisenberg also described the meeting reported by the Times as an
all-day session on Jan. 27, 1999. It had been called by Starr to
determine how the office would decide whether to indict the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Wisenberg said there had been a ``stronger than usual
admonition'' to keep the points of discussion secret. He said when
he read the Jan. 31 article he was dismayed that obviously someone
among the 20 or so lawyers present had leaked details of the
meeting. He said he feared the article would make the counsel's
office look as if it was engaged in a ``ham-handed'' effort to
affect the Senate impeachment trial of President Clinton, which was
under way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
