<SLUG> BC-DEM-CONVENTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE WEIGHS TIMING NO. 2 PICK TO UPSET RIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore is strongly considering
plans to announce his running mate the day after the Republican
National Convention ends early next month, as a way of siphoning
media attention from the Republican candidate, Gov. George W. Bush,
Democratic officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   National conventions have traditionally afforded presidential
nominees a triumphal moment in the spotlight. Sometimes the
post-convention ``bounce'' has been fleeting, but other times it
has provided real momentum going into the fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned that the Republicans could use that bounce to expand
the marginal lead they already hold in many national polls, the
Democrats are assessing whether to try to reduce Bush's
post-convention coverage with the announcement of their
vice-presidential pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a tactical option, it's attractive and under serious
consideration,'' one top adviser to Gore said of the plan, which
was first reported Thursday morning in USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   But the adviser said that Gore had not agreed yet, for several
reasons. Gore may want to allow some time to pass after the
Republican convention ends to gauge the public's response to the
Republican ticket. And he may also need extra time to determine
whether he wants to counter the Republican choice in terms of
gender or geography.
</P>
<P>
   Another variable would be the timing of Bush's announcement of
his running mate. If it is well before the Republican convention,
Gore will be more likely to make his announcement shortly after the
end of that convention, the adviser said.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of when Bush announces his pick, Gore is likely to
announce his choice of running mate well before the Democratic
National Convention begins on Aug. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials said Thursday that they had tentatively
scheduled President Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton to address
the convention on its first night, a Monday, allowing Gore to
command the spotlight for most of the following three nights.
</P>
<P>
   There had been some discussion of having Mrs. Clinton, who is
running for the Senate from New York, speak on Tuesday, when the
Democrats plan to focus on women candidates. But Gore's advisers
wanted both Clintons to speak on the first evening, to ensure that
the vice president would dominate subsequent media coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials said Clinton might introduce a biographical
video of her husband on Monday night. But they said she would also
probably give a speech focusing on her own campaign themes.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Bill Bradley, who formally endorsed Gore on
Thursday, is scheduled to be among the featured speakers Tuesday,
Democratic officials said. On Wednesday, the convention will begin
focusing more on Gore's biography, with testimonials and, possibly,
video clips.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will accept the nomination on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   There has been one hitch to having the Clintons speak Monday
night: no network is planning to cover the convention live that
night. But Democratic officials said they were hoping ABC would
broadcast a halftime report during Monday Night Football in which
Clinton would speak live.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 2310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
