<HEADER>
A1645 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-COLUMBIA-DRUG-TRIAL-N     07-13 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMBIA-DRUG-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE SENTENCES ARMY COLONEL TO PRISON FOR WITHHOLDING SMUGGLING
INFORMATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN FEUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After being chided by a federal judge for not
apologizing for his crimes, a U.S. Army colonel who once ran the
government's antidrug operations in Colombia was sentenced Thursday
to five months in prison for never reporting that he knew his wife
was smuggling heroin through diplomatic mail from Bogota to New
York City.
</P>
<P>
   The colonel, James Hiett, stood with his hands clasped tightly
before him in federal District Court in Brooklyn as U.S. District
Judge Edward Korman pronounced sentence in a weary, troubled
whisper.
</P>
<P>
   Moments before the sentence was handed down, Korman asked the
colonel if he had anything to say on his own behalf.
</P>
<P>
   His lips set and his chin held high, Col. Hiett said that he did
not.
</P>
<P>
   ``How is it you have nothing to say?'' Korman then asked,
slapping his hand on the desk in what seemed like inadvertent
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think I could speak at this point to tell you what I
really feel, sir,'' Hiett answered crisply, his jaw muscles
quivering with restrained emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that I did _ that I consciously did _ was try
to protect my wife after the fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Hiett admitted in April to paying his household bills with
thousands of dollars he knew his wife had earned from shipping
heroin from the U.S. Embassy in Bogota to accomplices in Manhattan
and Queens.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Laurie Anne Hiett, pleaded guilty in January to drug
trafficking charges and is serving a five-year prison term.
</P>
<P>
   The case of Hiett, who oversaw about 200 American troops charged
with training Colombian security forces in drug enforcement
operations, has been an embarrassment for the Army, which cleared
him of all involvement in the smuggling scheme last year after a
three-month investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Army's findings, Korman excoriated the colonel
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone in a position of trust engages in conduct like
this, it undermines confidence in the military,'' Korman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It undermines confidence in the country's drug program. And
that's what abuse of trust is about.''
</P>
<P>
   Hiett, 48, has already filed for his retirement, which is to
take effect in November.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors have said that he could face a reduced
pension, even court-martial.
</P>
<P>
   But Army officials did not return phone calls Thursday seeking
comment on the colonel's case.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual emotional twist to the sentencing hearing
Thursday, Korman allowed the mother of an Army captain who died in
a military plane crash last year while serving under Hiett's
command to address the court before the sentence was issued.
</P>
<P>
   The mother, Janie Shafer, of Brunswick, Md., has accused Hiett
of causing the death of her daughter, Capt. Jennifer Shafer Odom,
by revealing secret information about military surveillance flights
to Colombian drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   Although Korman allowed Shafer to speak, he acknowledged that
there was no evidence to support her allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Standing at the lectern with a photograph of her dead daughter
pressed to her chest, Shafer begged Korman to investigate the plane
crash, which the Army ruled an accident.
</P>
<P>
   Korman said he had no power to investigate the crash, but he
consoled Shafer with gentle words from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking at the picture of your daughter and I'm holding
back tears myself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can just imagine your suffering as a parent myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
