<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON EXPLAINS ARAFAT KISS 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a campaign swing Thursday through Queens, Hillary
Rodham Clinton offered her most detailed explanation yet about why
she kissed Suha Arafat, the wife of Yasser Arafat, after Arafat
made scathing remarks about Israel during a joint appearance in
November.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if any of you have been to the Middle East,''
Clinton said. ``But if you have, you know that a kiss is a
handshake.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, appearing at the Bell Park Jewish Center in Queens
Village, made the remarks in response to a woman's question on the
encounter with Arafat, and on her stand on the issue of Palestinian
statehood.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not offer her opinion on whether there should be a
Palestinian state, but said that her political opponents would
``keep raising and keep raising'' the encounter with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   The incident, which provoked harsh criticism at the time from
Jewish organizations in the United States, involved a joint
appearance by the two women on the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in a very difficult position, and I am the first to
admit that,'' Clinton said to a largely supportive group of more
the 300 people at the Queens Village center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did what I was expected to do,'' she said, adding that she
had ``responded appropriately as the first lady of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   During the November joint appearance in Ramallah, Arafat,
speaking in Arabic, accused the Israeli government of poisoning
Palestinian women and children with toxic gas.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton showed clear signs of discomfort during the remarks but
gave Arafat a polite, salutatory kiss when she left.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Clinton offered an explanation that was similar to
one she gave reporters in November, but it was her first expansive
discussion on the episode before a large group of voters. She said
the translation of Arafat's remarks that she was given in earphones
during the West Bank event was different, and far less offensive,
than the more accurate version she learned of after leaving Israel
for Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was great debate over what was the right translation,
the one I heard in my ears or the one that was put out after I left
Israel,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, she said, ``immediately when I found out about the
alternative translation I condemned it,'' adding that Arafat's
remarks had been ``inflammatory and outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who was asked by another member of the audience in
Queens Village if she had changed her ``pro-Arab'' views, responded
by saying that she and President Clinton had been supporters of
Israel throughout their political careers and that ``all my
comments and work I have done had been premised on what would be in
the best interest of Israel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 2312EDT &QL; 
