<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PHILLY-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A CRUEL AND UNUSUAL ARREST 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, July 14:
</P>
<P>
   The sickening sight of Philadelphia police officers caught on
videotape punching, kicking and stomping on a man who had already
been shot five times brings to mind the vicious beating of Rodney
King by Los Angeles police officers in 1991. Philadelphia's police
commissioner, John Timoney, says such comparisons are unfair. There
are clear differences in the two cases. But they both show officers
out of control and using excessive force to settle a score with a
suspect.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia man, Thomas Jones, allegedly resisted arrest,
fired on the police, stole a patrol car and led police on a chase
before he was pulled out of the cruiser. The officers obviously
were enraged by such resistance and by the shootout, which left one
officer wounded in the hand. But that does not excuse the ferocious
beating that took place after Jones was wounded, surrounded and
lying on the ground. The tape showed a mob attack rather than an
orderly arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Since several of the officers involved are black, as is Jones,
there are fewer racial overtones in this case than in the assault
on Rodney King, in which all four of the officers in the beating
were white. That difference, however, offers no comfort to civil
rights groups that have been working for years to end notorious
patterns of abuse in the Philadelphia Police Department. There have
been positive strides in police-community relations in recent
years. But the fact that the officers showed no restraint suggests
that the police culture has not changed enough in Philadelphia,
which will soon play host to the Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor John Street and Timoney have said they will conduct
vigorous investigations into the officers' actions. The Justice
Department announced on Thursday that it would begin a civil rights
inquiry to determine whether excessive force had been used. The
videotape records a scene that will be hard to justify.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
