<HEADLINE>
IPO SUCCESSES COULD LAUNCH NEW BREAKOUT PHASE FOR TECH STOCKS 
 &HT;     BY KATHLEEN PENDER
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a saying on Wall Street that when the initial public
offering window is almost closed, only the best deals squeak
through.
</P>
<P>
   If that's true, then now should be a good time to consider
buying IPOs. But is it?
</P>
<P>
   William Smith, president of the IPO Plus Aftermarket Fund,
thinks the answer is yes.
</P>
<P>
   On May 30, an article in the Wall Street Journal predicted the
IPO market would remain moribund through the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since that article came out, our fund is up 40 percent,'' he
says. That gain erased half of a huge loss in the March-to-May
period, leaving the fund up 10 percent year to date.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, whose fund invests in IPOs at the offering, and later, in
the so-called aftermarket, explains: ``We've been doing research
since 1991. Since then, the IPO market has been officially declared
dead six times. During those times, only good deals were able to
get out, and there was less competition in the aftermarket.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, he says, ``we're in the sweet spot _ the early part
of a breakout phase.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, IPOs had one of their best days in months yesterday.
Investors are feeling more optimistic after two Internet
bellwethers _ Santa Clara's Yahoo and Mountain View's Ariba _
announced better-than-expected earnings earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in three companies that make telecommunications or
computer hardware soared in their first day of trading yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose's Sunrise Telecom, which makes equipment for testing
telecommunications networks, premiered at $15 per share and closed
at $40.31, for a 169 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
   Triton Networks of Fresh Meadows, N.Y., which makes broadband
wireless equipment, went public at $15 (up from an initial range of
$10 to $12) and finished the day at $38.44, up 156 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Network Engines of Canton, Mass., raised the size and price of
its deal, from 5.5 million shares at $13 to $15 per share to 6.5
million shares at $15 to $17. It went public at $17 and closed at
$29, for a first-day gain of 71 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company makes computer servers that are a cheaper
alternative to those from Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   The laggard of the day was I-Many of Portland, Maine, which
makes software for companies doing business on the Internet. Its
stock was up only 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hardware is a much easier sell than software these days,''
says Ross Sakamoto, manager of the H&AMP;Q IPO and Emerging Companies
fund. ``Demand is insatiable for hardware.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some investors were surprised that yesterday's hardware
deals did so well.
</P>
<P>
   Sunrise's $25 gain ``threw me for a loop,'' says Jeff
Hirschkorn, a senior market analyst for IPO.com.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the company is making money, about 90 percent of its
sales are for testing digital-subscriber lines, and he says DSL is
past its prime as an investment fad. Another risk: 40 percent of
sales are to a single customer, SBC Communications, the parent
company of Pacific Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Tuen, director of research with IPO Value Monitor, says
Sunrise ``overshot on the upper end. I probably wouldn't buy it
where it's trading now.''
</P>
<P>
   Sakamoto was also surprised by Triton's performance. The company
makes ``fixed-wireless'' equipment, which beams high-speed data to
rooftop antennas over radio waves. It's a cheaper alternative to
laying fiber the ``last mile'' to homes and offices, but the
technology is still unproven, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Sakamoto says this is a sign that the market is becoming more
selective.
</P>
<P>
   ``A mediocre company might be treated really, really badly. A
really good company will get undue reward,'' he says. ``Everybody's
going to want to have the good name. Nobody wants a neutral or bad
name.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Divine Interventures, a Lisle, Ill., Internet
incubator similar to CMGI, finally got its problem-plagued IPO off
the ground this week. Its shares hit the market at $9, much lower
than planned, and finished their first day at $8.78. They rose
yesterday to $10.56.
</P>
<P>
   Another ho-hum deal was Sohu.com, which operates an Internet
portal in China. It originally hoped to sell shares at $16 to $19
but had to settle for $13. It closed yesterday at the inauspicious
price (at least in the United States) of $13.13.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a positive development when you see a company like Divine
that has to cut its price to get out,'' says Smith. ``It's the sign
of a discriminating marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   PICKS OF THE LITTER: I asked the experts to name which IPOs they
think will get the most attention in the weeks ahead.
Unfortunately, some of these stocks may go so high on the first day
you won't want to touch them, unless you can get in at the offering
price.
</P>
<P>
   - &UR; Blue Martini Software. &LR;  Smith and Hirschkorn think investors
might get legally intoxicated on this San Mateo company, which
makes software that helps companies improve their relationship with
customers on the Web and through traditional channels like call
centers. Its customers include Levi Strauss, Harley Davidson and
Deluxe, the check-printing company.
</P>
<P>
   - &UR; America Online Latin America. &LR;  This IPO was shelved awhile
back, but now it's back on the runway. Hirschkorn says it's a joint
venture between AOL and and Cisneros Group, a big telecom player
south of the border.
</P>
<P>
   - &UR; Corvis. &LR;  This Columbia, Md., company isn't making any money,
but it does make fiber-optic equipment, so of course it will
``probably be overvalued,'' says Sakamoto.
</P>
<P>
   - &UR; Embarcadero Technologies. &LR;  Sakamoto also likes this San
Francisco maker of software that helps programmers design databases
from many different vendors.
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Almost any biotech IPO. &LR;  ``Across the board, these companies
are being snapped up because even if you are extremely
knowledgeable about biotech (which most people aren't), it's hard
to distinguish who the winners will be three to five years from
now,'' says Linda Killian, a portfolio manager on the IPO Plus
Aftermarket fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``So institutional investors are buying portfolios of these
companies. If you don't know which ones are going to be the
winners, you pick a bunch of them and hold them.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, she thinks Discovery Partners, which is developing
compound libraries for drug discovery, may get more attention than
some others.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kathleen Pender at kpenderATsfgate.com
</P>
<P>
