u k BC-EDITORIAL-VIETNAM-NYT     07-13 0367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-VIETNAM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CAPITALISM IN VIETNAM 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, July 14:
</P>
<P>
   More than 25 years after the fall of Saigon, the United States
signed a broad trade agreement on Thursday with Vietnam. The accord
pledges further opening of the Vietnamese economy and permits
American companies there to compete on a more equal footing with
other foreign businesses. Its signing marks another welcome step
toward healing the wounds of a bitter and divisive war.
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam has been opening its markets for more than a decade. But
foreign companies operating there have been discouraged by
burdensome and costly bureaucratic interference. American companies
entered the Vietnamese market after the two countries established
normal diplomatic relations in 1995. But with their late start and
the absence, until now, of a trade agreement, American concerns
have been at a disadvantage. The United States ranks only ninth
among countries investing in Vietnam, and trade between the two
countries is a disappointingly small $1 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   The new trade agreement, which still must be approved by
Congress, could change that picture significantly. High-growth
industries like telecommunications will be opened to freer
competition. American tariffs on goods manufactured in Vietnam will
be sharply reduced, permitting American companies there to produce
for export to the United States market. From the Vietnamese side,
the agreement represents a recognition that market reforms must go
forward if Vietnam is to compete effectively with China for foreign
investment.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, Vietnam remains a repressive Communist
dictatorship. Intellectuals calling for more democracy face
isolation and house arrest, Buddhist leaders are harassed, senior
Communists pressing for faster reforms face persecution. Washington
rightly made progress on refugee issues and finding the remains of
missing American combatants conditions for signing the trade
agreement. With America now likely to play a larger economic role
in Vietnam, Washington should raise its voice on behalf of
persecuted Vietnamese democrats. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-13-00 2338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
