<DOCNO> NYT20000713.0367 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-13 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1664 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PACIFIC--CYBERLAUNCH-     07-13 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PACIFIC--CYBERLAUNCH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCHIPELAGO LIFTS PACIFIC EXCHANGE INTO CYBERSPACE 
 &HT;     BY SAM ZUCKERMAN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
San Francisco's Pacific Exchange stepped into a brave, new world
Thursday, completing the previously announced merger of its stock
trading business with an all-electronic rival.
<P>
   The combination of Pacific's stock operation with Archipelago, a
new-generation computerized trading system that competes with
conventional exchanges, will create the nation's first fully
automated equity exchange.
</P>
<P>
   As previously disclosed, Pacific will shut its San Francisco and
Los Angeles stock trading floors sometime late this year or early
next year, replacing them with the Archipelago system, which
operates entirely in cyberspace. Pending Securities and Exchange
Commission approval, the new operation will have the full status of
an exchange, allowing it to trade a complete range of stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the market has been divided between conventional
exchanges, such as the New York Stock Exchange, and electronic
networks operating under a variety of restrictions that have
limited their ability to function as stock marketplaces.
</P>
<P>
   The Archipelago Exchange, as the operation will be called,
``will be the first of its kind,'' said Pacific Exchange Chairman
and Chief Executive Officer Philip DeFeo. ``It will be a real
competitor to the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq.''
</P>
<P>
   Archipelago, based in Chicago, is the fifth-largest electronic
communications network, or ECN, as the new-generation stock trading
systems are called.
</P>
<P>
   ECNs directly link buy and sell orders without using middlemen.
They mainly trade Nasdaq stocks, where they command about 30
percent of the market. New York Stock Exchange rules hamper their
ability to trade shares listed on that market.
</P>
<P>
   Under New York rules, however, Pacific and other regional
exchanges are able to trade shares of the companies it lists.
Archipelago agreed to combine with Pacific to get access to those
New York stocks, including such blue-chip names as IBM,
Hewlett-Packard and General Motors.
</P>
<P>
   As compensation, Archipelago is paying Pacific an undisclosed
sum, giving it an equity stake and a seat on the Archipelago board.
</P>
<P>
   For Pacific, a deal with Archipelago removes a millstone from
its neck.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Pacific's business of trading stock options has
grown rapidly and profitably. But in the stock-market business, the
exchange has lost market share and millions of dollars annually.
</P>
<P>
   Combining with Archipelago and eliminating the expense of a
trading floor will ``solve the burden of the equity drag on us,''
allowing the exchange to concentrate on its options business, DeFeo
said.
</P>
<P>
   The new operation faces tough hurdles to establish itself. One
of its most difficult tasks will be to carve out a role for
Pacific's dozens of wholesale brokers, known as specialists, who
serve as middlemen in stock trades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't know how (the Archipelago Exchange is) going to
work with the specialists,'' said Chase H&AMP;Q analyst Greg Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Once Pacific adopts the Archipelago system, directly linking buy
and sell orders, the specialists will be squeezed out of many
stocks. They might still play a vital function by ``making a
market,'' that is, by guaranteeing to buy or sell shares when
investors don't specify a trading price or when no other orders are
available.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Sam Zuckerman at szuckermanATsfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
